<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY AND CHARLIE ROSE: COOKING, BREVITY AND BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For nearly an hour in an auditorium at the 92nd
Street Y on Wenesday night, Hillary Rodham Clinton answered
questions about her politics and her husband, about her failures as
first lady and as a candidate for office, about Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and about her kitchen skills (or lack thereof).
</P>
<P>
   But even Charlie Rose, who interviewed her, could not prompt the
first lady to respond to a question that has dogged her since she
started traveling through New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want is for you take some stands here: Are you a
Yankees fan or a Mets fan?'' Rose inquired, grinning as he leaned
way forward in his arm chair. ``You can't be both. It's not
allowable in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've actually given up trying to talk about that, because I
can't convince anyone that I cared about the Yankees,'' Clinton
responded as she smiled back at her interviewer. ``So I don't want
to go there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a notable moment in a session that marked a new stage in
Clinton's gradual emergence as the unguarded candidate: A
full-fledged interview, in front of a paying audience, albeit in
what for Clinton should be friendly territory, Manhattan's Upper
East Side.
</P>
<P>
   For much of it, Clinton was more revealing than usual. Still,
her instinct for caution exasperated Rose, whether it was in was
talking about the Yankees (who are her preferred team, an aide
later explained), her roundabout attacks on Giuliani or an attempt
to offer a sunny account of her years in the White House, an
assertion that led Rose to cut off his guest in mid-sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was good about the impeachment?'' Rose demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I have a very interesting take on that,'' she said,
referring to the impeachment in the House, and subsequent acquittal
in the Senate, of President Clinton. ``What was good about it was
that we protected and saved the Constitution. And that was a very
good outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, in recounting her unsuccessful campaign for
national health insurance in 1994, Clinton suggested that she had
come under less criticism once she faded back from public view.
``You know, Charlie, it was so interesting for me to learn that it
was more acceptable for me to work behind the scenes than
publicly,'' she said. ``It says that we have a real problem with. .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Rose finished her sentence: ``Strong women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you say that,'' Clinton retorted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on,'' prodded her host.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not budge. ``I think it's a problem with the role of
a first lady. Because it's not a job. It's a role.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose did have some success, though. For much of the campaign,
Clinton has declined to reveal any details of private conversations
with President Clinton. She let on Wednesday night that the
president had advised his wife to be less verbose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is incredibly helpful, because I have a tendency when I
talk to issues to go on and on,'' Clinton said. ``I say, `These
issues are complex,''' said Clinton, who is running for office for
the first time. ``And he says, `You've got to get it down to 10 or
15 seconds.'''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Clinton said her discussion of her kitchen skills in
the speech when she announced her candidacy, when she boasted of
making a ``mean tossed salad'' and a good omelette, had been
misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was a clear way of saying, `I can't cook,'''
she said. ``I thought it was a funny way of saying I can tear up
lettuce and break eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Break eggs?'' Rose repeated back to her. ``You just gave it
away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
