<SLUG> BC-BROWN-DAVIS-SCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIZARRE TIFF ENDS AS GOV. DAVIS APPOINTS S.F. MAYOR BROWN TO 
 RETIREMENT BOARD
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ Ending a bizarre tiff between two powerful
California Democrats, Gov. Gray Davis Wednesday appointed San
Francisco Mayor Willie Brown to the state retirement board _ a post
the mayor says he already held.
<P>
   In what Davis officials say was an embarrassing mixup, an aide
to the governor mistakenly sent Brown the paperwork necessary for
appointment to the board several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   A Davis spokesman said the appointment was not made until after
Davis and Brown met Wednesday afternoon for 45 minutes in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``All appointees of the governor represent his views _ not
theirs _ on the boards which they serve,'' said Davis spokesman
Michael Bustamante. ``They are not free agents. Appointments are
not made until the governor has a chance to talk personally with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brown was clear Wednesday morning, telling the Chronicle
that he had already taken the oath of office for the job, which
made him a member of the Public Employees Retirement Board, whether
Davis liked it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the oath of office and I am on the board,'' Brown said
in an interview before his meeting with Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' trip to see Brown in San Francisco Wednesday was not
originally on either man's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said Davis, who had been considering Brown for the
post for some time, is now ``confident Brown will fairly reflect
his views on CalPERS.''
</P>
<P>
   The appointment comes at an awkward time for the media-sensitive
Davis. On Tuesday, a federal grand jury issued a subpoena demanding
information on Brown's dealings with the city's minority
contracting program.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment incident started last month when a Davis aide
called the CalPERS board seeking a telephone number for Tom Clark,
the board member Brown replaced, to tell Clark he was no longer on
the board.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Brown's appointment seeped out. A press release
announcing Brown's appointment was prepared by Davis' staff but not
released.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted by reporters, Davis said through a spokesman he
had not yet appointed Brown, a declaration they continued to make
throughout the day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Davis speak personally about it to Brown until Tuesday,
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called to say some staff person had inadvertently got in
front of him,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   But several legal sources contacted by The Chronicle said it was
too late for Davis to do anything but agree to the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's Feb. 9 oath of office as member of the Public Employees
Retirement System board is on file in the secretary of state's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a dynamic addition to the 13-member board that manages
the largest public pension fund in the country, with assets
totaling more than $171 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the members are elected, four are set by law and three
are appointed. Brown is one of the governor's two appointments.
</P>
<P>
   One of the board members who likely will be least happy with
Brown's appointment is State Controller Kathleen Connell.
</P>
<P>
   Davis dislikes Connell, and acting at Davis' behest, the crafty
and persuasive Brown could undercut her influence on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Connell said she was ``glad'' to see Brown on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Brown would be carrying out Davis' wishes, Connell
said, ``I would hope we all implement a common vision here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown also has ties to State Treasurer Phil Angelides, a board
member and former head of the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who skipped Wednesday's meeting of the retirement board,
could forge a bridge between Angelides and Davis that has not
existed before.
</P>
<P>
   Board members do not receive a salary.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Brown, whose job on the board is to represent local
governments, presides over a city that has its own retirement
system.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 2,000 of the city's employees are members of CalPERS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
