A9506 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     02-17 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IN THE MARKET FOR A RICH SPOUSE?  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ My taste in TV viewing has risen to new depths.
</P>
<P>
   I watched ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' Tuesday
night, and I give it three thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty women competed, beauty-contest style, to be chosen to
marry an anonymous man. Mr. X made his pick, then the happy couple
was married onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers, I'm sure, were offended. They think the justice of
the peace should have said, ``I now pronounce you creep and
desperado.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``You may now kiss the bride, tell her your name and give
her a platinum card.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Till sanity do you part.''
</P>
<P>
   It was beyond weird. Who would think a show this educational
would be on anything but PBS?
</P>
<P>
   I'm kind of proud, because I'm indirectly responsible for the
show. Several years ago, a writer named Michael Silver and I did a
one-shot pilot radio show here in San Francisco, and Mike Fleiss,
the executive producer and co-inventor of ``Who Wants to Marry,''
was our producer /co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   The show bombed like the Enola Gay, whereupon Fleiss fled to Los
Angeles and got into TV work and became rich and famous. He owes me
big.
</P>
<P>
   OBVIOUSLY, ``Who Wants to Marry'' will not be a one-shot wonder.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Fleiss if he would do a flip-flop show, with a
super-rich woman sorting through a field of hunky dudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already had three women come forward and offer to do
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, there was a prenup to Tuesday night's wedding. Or as
Fleiss said, ``There was paperwork in place for the protection of
both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Was the bride required to commit to a minimum length of
marriage? Nope. No cover, no minimum.
</P>
<P>
   And Fleiss says Mr. X didn't do this for a goof.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sincere in his desire to meet the right woman, and he
really felt it was his destiny to do it this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it beats hanging out in the Safeway produce aisle and
asking babes for tips on squeezing cantaloupes.
</P>
<P>
   SOMEBODY keep an eye on the cable cars and Coit Tower.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of America's home office in Charlotte, N.C., is
functioning as a black hole, sucking in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   BofA President Ken Lewis told the Charlotte Observer, ``We have
some very complicated businesses across America and I always
(would) rather have people closer to me than not. So every chance I
get to bring more things into Charlotte, I'm going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And most BofA things that are not in Charlotte are here in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is the bank's No. 2 exec and designated heir to the throne
of Hugh McColl.
</P>
<P>
   Hey Ken, feel free to take the Banker's Heart sculpture at
Kearny and California. You could use it as a paperweight.
</P>
<P>
   Or will you be needing it in S.F. as a wrecking ball?
</P>
<P>
   BELT-CINCHING, the BofA has a new travel policy that has caught
the attention of flying execs.
</P>
<P>
   Business fliers are reimbursed for airline tickets, but only the
amount of the lowest fare on any airline flying that route. So if
you pay $500 and the bank's computer finds a $300 fare on Acme Air,
you eat $200, even if you spent last weekend pruning the bonsai
plants around your neighborhood's Versateller ATM.
</P>
<P>
   I THOUGHT that was a wine rack: J.P. Murphy heard the traffic
reporter on KGO advise, ``If you're going on a ski trip, make sure
that your rental car has a ski rack.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy plans to give it a try, figures maybe it will work better
than just tossing the skis onto the top of the car and hoping for
the best.
</P>
<P>
   TO CLARIFY stuff you may have read here:
</P>
<P>
   I wrote that Michael Jordan could give trash-talking lessons to
Bill Bradley. Readers said, ``What? That well-mannered gentleman
Jordan?''
</P>
<P>
   Fact: Jordan was the NBA's foremost trash talker. Taunts, digs,
insults, challenges. Devastating, because he could back up his
words.
</P>
<P>
   And ... While the Coolidge did sink in WWII after the captain
steered his liner into a friendly minefield in the S. Pacific, the
captain was following the routing given him by our own Navy, a
reader points out.
</P>
<P>
   ALL YOU HEAR about the stock market whizzes is that they're
making money by the trunkful. What you don't hear about is the
pressure and tension involved.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning on the floor of the Pacific Exchange,
44-year-old John Lawson dropped dead of a heart attack. In a
cutthroat biz, Lawson was, I'm told, a sweetheart of a guy. Also a
devoted dad and an avid runner.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH isn't the only candidate who takes liberties with
the language. One reader has noticed that Al Gore always talks
about ``nuculur'' weapons and energy.
</P>
<P>
   And here come the judge: Harriet Hultquist found in her Solano
County sample ballot this statement from a candidate for Superior
Court judge: ``My wife and me have three daughters/ ...''
</P>
<P>
   The proper wording, of course, would be: ``My wife and me/have
daughters three.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
