<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9509 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      02-17 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The Rockets still have quite a ways to go in their push to be a
.500 team, but they got a little closer Wednesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost seven feet closer, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rogers, the 6-11 forward who has been recovering from
surgery to repair torn ligaments in his right thumb, practiced with
the team Wednesday, his first workout since being put on the
injured list Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
   For Rogers, it was a welcome break from the tedium of watching
games from the sidelines, wishing he could get out and run with his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me it would take six weeks (to return), but to me,
whenever I feel like I can do something with it, I want to be out
there on the floor,'' Rogers said. ``I hate it. I hate watching
basketball games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like sitting on the bench. I've been out of the game
for a long time, so the first time a doctor says it looks good (to
return), I'm going to get out there on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Not soon enough for the Rockets, who have spent much of the
season adding bodies _ mostly large bodies _ to the injured list.
And with back-to-back games against the Spurs _ at San Antonio on
Friday and Compaq Center on Sunday _ and their twin towers of Tim
Duncan and David Robinson, having a long body like Rogers back
would certainly help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy with him being here,'' said Rockets coach
Rudy Tomjanovich. ``I just talked to Keith Jones, our trainer, and
he feels right now that it isn't a physical deal as far as the
injury (keeping Rogers off the court), but it's just basketball,
when he can get ready. Possibly by Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, but not positively, everyone is quick to caution.
While Rogers is antsy about returning, the last thing he wants to
do is reinjure the thumb, causing yet another prolonged stay on the
injured list.
</P>
<P>
   But Rogers is still waging an internal war, doing everything
possible to hasten his return to the lineup, including a few things
he shouldn't have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut casts off (his wrist and thumb),'' said Rogers,
laughing. ``You do whatever it takes to give you something to hold
on to. When I had that cast on, my hand started going dead and I
couldn't feel anything. That's not how I wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that in order for me to be effective, I have to be able
to do something with that ball in my hand, so I did a couple of
things I wasn't supposed to do, but it worked out for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rogers was right where he wanted to be Wednesday, back on
the court with the Rockets, he still is far away from where he
wants to be as far as his conditioning is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' said Rogers of his first day back at practice.
``My timing is OK, but I know I have to get my conditioning back.
That's NBA condition. You always think you're in pretty good shape
because you run up and down and you're not really tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once you're banging, pushing and running, that's a whole
different game. That's what I'm working on now, trying to get back
in shape. But my timing is good compared to what I thought it would
be (after) not being able to use this hand at all. That's a plus
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   A minus for Rogers, however, has been the big-man rotation the
Rockets have employed _ one that has been working quite well of
late.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Cato starts at center and Matt Bullard at power forward,
with Hakeem Olajuwon and Kenny Thomas coming in off the bench.
Rogers, who was averaging 9.1 points before the injury, knows he's
going to have to work his way back into the game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the hardest thing in the NBA is trying to get back
into the rotation,'' Rogers said. ``I think that's going to be my
biggest fight right now, trying to get back in and fit in well with
what they're trying to do. They're out there, you're learning new
plays, so this is like starting all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A plus for me is that none of the plays were really run for
me. I got most of my points by feeding off somebody else, so I
think I can still bring that to the table as well as run the floor.
I'm not really threatened by any of this. I'm not worried about it
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich doesn't anticipate any problems in trying to get
playing time for the versatile Rogers, who can play any of the
three frontcourt positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``(When Rogers returns) we'll have an athletic, all-around
player that I thought was playing consistently for our team,''
Tomjanovich said. ``He had a lot of highs but not a whole bunch of
lows. I think he fits in our style of play and our system real
well.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
