<SLUG> BC-DEMO-CONVENTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR NAMES CEO FOR KEY CONVENTION COMMITTEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Frustrated at his lack of control in planning for
the upcoming Democratic National Convention, Mayor Richard Riordan
named one of his top aides Wednesday to serve as chief executive
officer for the Host Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Noelia Rodriguez, who has been Riordan's chief
spokeswoman since 1994, will replace Lucy McCoy, who is stepping
down as president of the group after more than a year of work that
included winning the bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for the mayor to increase his involvement and
he wants to be involved in day to day planning,'' McCoy said. ``And
it's appropriate for him to bring someone from his own staff in to
make that happen. The committee is in the final phase of its work
and the mayor wants to be involved. This is good overall for the
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's decision to install Rodriguez in the post came only
this week after more than a month of concern over the Host
Committee's work both in fund-raising _ it is still about $8
million short of its $33.5 million goal _ and in planning for the
mid-August convention.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor apparently also was concerned that he and the city not
be embarrassed during the event, as they were at the millennium
celebration on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 40, who came to work for Riordan from Southern
California Edison Co., is taking a leave of absence from her city
post to take on the DNC work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for me and, as we move from
planning to implementation, the mayor wanted somebody he has
confidence in to take it to the next stage,'' Rodriguez said. ``The
Host Committee is in good shape and the all the components are
there. It's just putting it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   She is to make the transition into the job over the next week,
and said she will continue to consult with the mayor on city
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``As one of my trusted advisers for six years, I know Noelia
possesses the strategic skills, public relations expertise and
tenacity to get things done,'' Riordan said. ``As CEO of L.A.
Convention 2000, she will serve me and Los Angeles well as we
finalize preparations to host the best convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Host Committee is separate from the group that is planning
the convention itself. The Host Committee is responsible for
bringing together the various city services that will be required _
police and traffic control, primarily _ as well as coordinate other
events related to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors of cities that host such conventions normally play a very
active role. Los Angeles' situation is different in that the Host
Committee is a private organization; the city is to provide
services, but no funding. All the money is to be raised privately.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion is that Riordan is a Republican serving
as host to the opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is a registered Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy said she will be working with Rodriguez on the transition
and will then return to her public affairs company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
