<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMBLED DODGERS START OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ In 47 days, the Dodgers can begin shedding
last season's disaster. Forty-seven days and the Dodgers, still
without a playoff win since 1988, open the season at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The path of optimism that leads to the start of the season
begins today as pitchers and catchers voluntarily report to
Dodgertown.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike a year ago when folks around here were pushing out
their chests and tempting the rest of the baseball world to take
their best shots, a humility has taken over. A 77-85 record and
third-place finish has that effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be more reserved,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone said. ``Last year we had a very talented group, but we found
out we weren't quite as good a team as we hoped to be. We don't
feel the pressure of expectations and high hopes that were created
by everyone last year.''
</P>
<P>
   After adding more than $120 million in free-agent contracts last
offseason only to fall flat, very little is expected of the Dodgers
this season. They traded Raul Mondesi for Shawn Green and shipped
Eric Young and Ismael Valdes to the Chicago Cubs for reliever Terry
Adams.
</P>
<P>
   After making big free-agent signings in 1998, the Dodgers were
less visible this time around when they signed reliever Gregg
Olson, veteran pitcher and Dodger favorite Orel Hershiser and
utility outfielder F.P. Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some things that we needed, and I think you're going
to get a chance to see that,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``I think we have a chance to be a very good ballclub. How good? It
depends on the players. I wouldn't say we're as flush as the
Yankees or Cleveland (with talent and balance), but we've made
strides.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers went heavy on getting ``character players''
during the offseason, there are still plenty of questions that need
answers if they're going to compete for a postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, can Mark Grudzielanek play second base? For
the second straight winter Grudzielanek worked with former big
leaguer Bucky Dent in Florida. But unlike a year ago when he
re-trained his brain to play shortstop, Grudzielanek had to learn
the basics of a new position.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also need to know if Alex Cora can hit enough to be
the everyday shortstop. Or will Juan Castro or Jose Vizcaino
surprise and win the job?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably going to live with Grud to make sure he can turn
a double play,'' Johnson said. ``I'm going to be breathing down on
Cora and Castro and Vizcaino. I'm going to be watching them closely
with my glasses on.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Grudzielanek have a new position in the field, but
he's also the favorite to replace Young at the top of the batting
order. It's a crucial spot to set up the trio of Gary Sheffield,
Green and Eric Karros, who combined to drive in 336 runs last
season.
</P>
<P>
   While second base and shortstop are question marks, third base
also could be a troubling situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers could still lose Adrian Beltre if an arbitrator
reverses commissioner Bud Selig's decision and grants the
20-year-old third baseman free agency. At that point, it may only
be a few weeks until the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers lose Beltre, Vizcaino and Kevin Orie would most
likely platoon at third.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how you plan for it, if we were unfortunate in
regards to keeping Adrian, you just can't replace a young,
athletic, talented player like that,'' Malone said. ``To me, you
can prepare all you want, but being prepared and replacing Adrian
Beltre are two different things. Being prepared doesn't mean we
have a suitable replacement.''
</P>
<P>
   While the corner positions in the outfield are set with Green
and Gary Sheffield, there's a battle looming in center field. Devon
White is on the trading block, and if he doesn't play well could
lose his job to Todd Hollandsworth, or find himself in a platoon
system. Either way, Johnson is eyeing his center fielder as the
Dodgers' all-important No. 2 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of important, catcher Todd Hundley is healthy after
struggling last year while recovering from shoulder surgery late in
the '98 season. After the fiasco that swirled around him for much
of last season, that should be welcome news for the Dodgers. And
Hundley won't have to spend a spring answering questions about when
he's going to finally get behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Like the position players, there are spots on the pitching staff
that have to be settled. The Dodgers traded Mondesi because he was
unhappy and Young to dump $9 million of salary and end a feud with
Johnson, but Malone and Johnson both said trading Valdes became an
option because of Eric Gagne's emergence last season.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen whether Gagne, a 24-year-old rookie
right-hander with five major league starts, can be the fourth
starter the Dodgers envision. There are also questions about the
fifth starter, a battle between long-forgotten Carlos Perez and
Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the team would like to see more development from Chan
Ho Park and Darren Dreifort. They combined to go 26-24 last season,
but neither pitched well until the Dodgers were well out of
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we recognized it's a lot harder to win than people
think because you can have a lot of talent, but you don't win for a
lot of different reasons,'' Malone said. ``We addressed that and
put together a team that will enable us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the Dodgers rate positionally heading into spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   Position Comment Rating
</P>
<P>
   First base Eric Karros can deliver 30 homers, 100 RBI in his
sleep. Settled
</P>
<P>
   Second base Mark Grudzielanek was fine at short, but can he
pivot on the double play. Suspect
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Alex Cora can field, but batting is the question. A
.143 average in 60 games. Suspect
</P>
<P>
   Third base If Adrian Beltre remains with club, all is fine.
Otherwise, Kevin Orie and Jose Vizcaino platoon. Unsettled
</P>
<P>
   Catching Todd Hundley worked on conditioning in the offseason.
How much did he improve? Unsettled
</P>
<P>
   Left field With transition to left field complete, Gary
Sheffield should flourish. Settled
</P>
<P>
   Center field GM Kevin Malone talked with Devon White about
expectations. White missed three weeks of `99 without going on
disabled list. Suspect
</P>
<P>
   Right field Shawn Green brings his 42 homers and 123 RBI into
the middle of the lineup. Settled
</P>
<P>
   Starters Kevin Brown, Chan Ho Park and Darren Dreifort are the
top three, but can rookie Eric Gagne be No.4? Unsettled
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Closer is Jeff Shaw, but how will trio of Alan Mills,
Gregg Olson and Terry Adams co-exist? Can Onan Masaoka be
situational lefty? Unsettled
</P>
<P>
   Bench Dave Hansen is premier pinch-hitter. Players are versatile
at plate and in field. Settled
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
