<HEADLINE>
SCALABRINE CAUGHT IN DILEMMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC forward Brian Scalabrine admitted he has been
caught in a dilemma lately, worried about whether he should focus
on grabbing rebounds or blocking out the other team's top
rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine grabbed just three rebounds last week against UCLA
but said he was concentrating on trying to keep Bruins forward
Jerome Moiso away from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to make a decision,'' Scalabrine said. ``I can block
out and let (my teammates) go for a rebound, or I can go for the
ball. If I block out, I get chewed out for not getting rebounds,
but you have to make a decision. It's a Catch-22.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine said if he just tries to block out, it allows forward
David Bluthenthal to grab more rebounds. Bluthenthal is averaging
10.6 rebounds in Pacific-10 Conference games, the best mark in the
conference. As for Scalabrine, he is averaging 6.1 rebounds in
conference games.
</P>
<P>
   No redshirt: If he doesn't return from his broken ankle, it
appears forward Jarvis Turner will be unable to redshirt. According
to NCAA rules, Turner would be allowed to play in six games, and
the senior appeared in seven games before his injury.
</P>
<P>
   Road test: Scalabrine said he did as little as possible over the
Trojans' eight-day break but is still unsure if he has regained the
bounce in his legs. After the loss to UCLA, he complained that he
could not drive to the basket, because he had trouble getting out
of ``first gear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually can't find out until the game starts,'' Scalabrine
said. ``They feel the same as before. In games, I can't get into
second gear. I'll find out (today).''
</P>
<P>
   In search of a win: USC has tried to keep a ``one-
game-at-a-time'' philosophy, even in the midst of its three-game
losing streak, but the Trojans (13-9, 6-4) realize the odds for a
victory this weekend are much greater against Arizona State than
No. 4 Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're preparing for Arizona, and we don't want to look ahead,
but I'll say this, the only thing is, I'm trying to get a split,''
Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   USC probably needs to win one more road game and its final four
home games to earn an NCAA berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just four more wins is really shady to get into the
tournament,'' freshman guard Nate Hair said.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep shooting: Hair is coming off one of his worst games of
the season, a 1-for-9 shooting effort against UCLA, but said he
hasn't lost any confidence in his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't shoot too well, but I don't anticipate doing that
again soon,'' Hair said. ``Coach Bibby tells everybody I'm going to
pull you out if you pass up an open shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hair said he is still recovering from the stress fracture he
suffered in his knee before the season, and it affects his ability
to drive to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have good days and bad days. Slowly, but surely, I'm coming
back,'' Hair said. ``I can't go to the hole and dunk like I used
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Added to list: Scalabrine is among 11 players that have been
added to the original list of 30 finalists for the Wooden Award and
Wooden All-American team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
