<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEERS AMAZED BY TIGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rain permitting, the Nissan Open will begin t oday
at Riviera Country Club, where, again, most of the buzz regards Tig
er Woods.
</P>
<P>
   The world's No. 1-ranked player captured the attention of
golfers everyw here -- and plenty of non-golfers as well -- by
winning six consecutive PGA Tour starts before Phil Mickelson
prevailed in last week's Buick Inv itational to end the tour's
longest win streak in 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   Woods fell five wins shy of Byron Nelson's PGA Tour-record
streak of 11 but not at all in the estimation of some distinguished
touring brethren who will join him this week at Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited that another friend of mine won last week,''
said David Duval, the world's No. 3-ranked golfer. ``But I was kind
of hoping to se e Tiger win again - I wanted to see him run that
record down.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have necessitated Woods running over Duval this week
as well, but that's the kind of interest Woods, 24, has created
after winning 17 times in less than five full seasons. ``You have
to see for your own eyes how good this guy is,'' said Ernie E ls,
the defending Nissan Open champion and a two-time U.S. Open winner
` `I look at him for motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   The motivation increased the last time he went head to head with
Woods. Els played his last three holes in 3 under par, only to have
Woods go 4- under in the same stretch and win the Mercedes
Championships for his fou rth win of the streak.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Open and Riviera record-holder Ted Tryba (61 last year)
offered t his during a rain break on the practice range Wednesday:
``As far as his winning the tournaments he's winning and how he's
winnin g, I think it's unbelievable. But then when I go watch him
play and I wa tch him hit balls and I watch him putt, it seems
pretty believable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now he's the best player in the world, and the question
we need to answer as players out here is, is going to get better or
is he going to come back to us? It's hard to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is hardly the only player of note at the Nissan , which
includes F red Couples, Justin Leonard, Mark O'Meara, Jesper
Parnevik, Steve Pate a nd Hal Sutton and many others who will play
in next week's Anderson Cons ulting Match Play Championship at La
Costa.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval, for one, doesn't tire of the talk of Woods: ``No, I
don't,'' said the man who was No.1 in the world before being rep
laced by Woods last year. ``Just because it's what needs to be
talked ab out at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest about this - he's doing some things all of us
wish we were doing, and it's neat stuff The buzz it's created and
was creating and does create is something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval got another feel for that Wednesday, while slogging up
Riviera's ninth fairway during a rainstorm. ``I looked over at No.
18. it's 11 o'clock, it's raining, it's cold and there's several
hundred people watching him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact he's had and is continuing to have - you see how
he's viewe d outside our game now. It's hard for me, a friend of
his, to grasp who he is and what he represents because he's become
such a big star, but I don't look at him that way. So it's just
kind of a weird deal for me, in a good way It's weird, but it's
cool to see.''
</P>
<P>
   If Duval feels conflicted about the larger-than-life persona of
his frie nd and rival, the ormer No. 1 feels absolutely certain he
and the rest o f the current PGA Tour participants are playing in
this league at the ri ght time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're very lucky to be a part of it right now, to be a
part of the game . I feel like I'm very lucky to be out here
playing against hi m and to be given the opportunity to compete
with him and to give him a good beating now and then. It's a neat
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
