<HEADLINE>
BRUINS RUNNING OUT OF TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The math gets simpler, the nerves get tighter and the margin for
error gets smaller with each defeat. The UCLA Bruins, losers of
four of their last five, are running out of time to secure an NCAA
Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   At 13-9 overall and 4-6 in the Pac-10, the Bruins must win five
of their last eight games to reach the 18-victory plateau that
should secure an at-large bid.
</P>
<P>
   A breakdown of the remaining games makes tonight's matchup at
Arizona State critical to UCLA's postseason path:
</P>
<P>
   - Give the Bruins three home victories over Pac-10
bottom-feeders Oregon State, Washington and Washigton State, making
them 16-9 overall and 7-6 in conference.
</P>
<P>
   - Give them two losses at against heavyweights Stanford and
Arizona, both on the road, dropping their record to 16-11 and 7-8.
</P>
<P>
   - That means the Bruins must win two of three games against
Oregon (home), Arizona State (road) and Cal (road). If they fail
tonight, the pressure will be enormous against the Ducks and Bears,
and both beat the Bruins in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to try to get two wins back because of our earlier
losses,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``If we have the
Washington and Cal (defeats) back, then we're 15-7 and it's a
typical UCLA season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But because we lost to Cal and Washington, we're 13-9 and we
have a smaller margin for error. Our backs are to the wall a little
more. ''
</P>
<P>
   The players are aware of their predicament; they can't escape it
. But they refuse to play the numbers game or term individual games
``must wins.'' They claim to have Arizona State in the crosshairs,
nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get ahead of ourselves, that's when we tend to mess up
,'' guard Rico Hines said. ``When we think about North Carolina, we
lose to USC. We've got to get everybody on the same page and take
care of ASU.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie's, err, house: The Bruins held high-scoring ASU guard
Eddie House to 18 points last month in Pauley Pavilion. But they
're bracing for a huge game from House tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll come with more fire than last time,'' said UCLA guard
Ray Young, who played against House in high school in the Bay Area.
``He'll probably try for a 30- or 40-point game, and he's probably
due for a 3 0- or 40-point game.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU is 9-2 when House scores at least 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   A clarification: UCLA did not submit JaRon Rush's ap peal to the
NCAA last week, as previously reported. Instead, the Bruins filed a
supplemental report that answered lingering questions the NCAA h ad
about UCLA's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins expect to file the appeal of Rush's 29-game
suspension this week and hope to have a response next week.
</P>
<P>
   Giving back: UCLA assistant coach Michael Holton will give a
motivational speech Tuesday morning at Stephens Middle School i n
Long Beach. Holton, who attended Stephens as an eighth grader, will
address over 100 student-athletes. His theme: don't stop believing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 0033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
