<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9518 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GOP-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON &LR;      02-17 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN PICKS UP ENDORSEMENTS FROM TWO WHO HAD OPPOSED HIM
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW and JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Arizona Senator John McCain flashed his
conservative credentials in the heart of Republican South Carolina
Wednesday, touting his military background and the endorsements of
two party stalwarts who had opposed his candidacy prior to his New
Hampshire triumph.
<P>
   Former rival Gary Bauer, the Reagan administration official who
had championed socially conservative causes, and California
Secretary of State Bill Jones, who had previously endorsed Texas
Governor George W. Bush, both said that McCain now represented the
GOP's best chances of capturing the White House.
</P>
<P>
   That contention was buoyed by a New York Times/CBS poll that
found that voters' impressions of Bush had diminished so
substantially that after months of favorable ratings, as many
people now dislike him as like him.
</P>
<P>
   The developments came as McCain made a final push for votes just
three days before a primary that is critical to his uphill quest to
win the GOP nomination. McCain _ a former Navy Pilot and POW _
draped himself in patriotic themes, seeking a bond with residents
of the state with the highest number of veterans per capita.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bones of South Carolinians lie in quiet groves that once
were killing fields all over the world, where they sacrificed
usually in defense of somebody else's freedom,'' McCain told
students at Furman University. ``There is no more patriotic state
in America than South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in Saturday's primary _ in a state with fewer
residents than the Bay Area _ were evident in the frenetic pace of
Wednesday's campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   A big McCain victory, coupled with wins Tuesday in Michigan and
Arizona _ where he is ahead in polls _ could make the Arizona
senator hard to stop.
</P>
<P>
   But a victory by Texas Gov. George W. Bush could be enough for
the GOP front-runner to turn back McCain's insurgent bid. Bush led
the polls by huge margins as recently as last month. But McCain's
victory in New Hampshire on February 1 has given him a surge of
support, and a poll released Wednesday showed the South Carolina
race in a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where gospel music dominates the radio waves, the
Confederate flag flies over the Capitol dome, and Republican Strom
Thurmond has been elected to the Senate every six years since the
days when segregation was the norm, it is not surprising that
candidates are vying for the mantle of being the true conservative
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigned Wednesday on the other side of the state,
emphasizing his experience as a chief executive in contrast with
McCain's legislative career. He cited his success reforming Texas'
schools, welfare system, tort laws, tax code and juvenile justice
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person who's coming with a record of reform,'' Bush told
supporters in the low-country town of Beaufort.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has allowed surrogates to suggest that McCain is stained
with traces of liberalism, while national conservative icons like
Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson and radio talk show host
Rush Limbaugh have begun to take up a crusade against McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain's voting record in Washington puts him squarely
in the GOP mainstream, some conservatives are angered by his zeal
for campaign finance reform and financial penalties against tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   McCain hopes Bauer's support will help him with social
conservatives, who have rallied behind Bush and former State
Department official Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, the former president of the Family Research Council, made
a ban on abortion and an emphasis on Christian values the central
part of his campaign, which he abandoned after coming in last place
in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Joining McCain onstage at Furman University outside Greenville,
Bauer declared McCain ``the best shot we have to end the era of
Bill and Hillary and Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour later in Los Angeles, Jones _ California's top elected
Republican _ reversed his early endorsement Bush, saying that he
now believes McCain is the best choice for California and the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain can beat (Democratic Vice President) Al Gore in
November,'' Jones said. ``I hope George Bush can beat Gore, but I
know McCain can.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' defection is more bad news for the Bush campaign, which
has seen its huge lead in California cut in half since McCain's
18-point victory in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush still has the overwhelming support of California's
Republican establishment including the backing of Insurance
Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush, the GOP's only other state
officeholder, 28 of the 32 Republican assembly members and 14 of
the 15 GOP state senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bill wants to be on the winning team, he ought to stay
here,'' Bush said while campaigning in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush campaign has spent $50 million trying to kill this
man (politically), but (McCain) won't go away because of the
message and the messenger,'' Jones said at a Los Angeles news
conference. ``I can understand why there are hard feelings (among
Bush supporters), but I didn't want this opportunity to pass me
by.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush once enjoyed an aura of invincibility, the New York
Times poll suggests that it has been greatly diminished by McCain's
success in New Hampshire. Nationwide, Bush is favored by 53 percent
of Republican primary voters as compared to 33 percent for McCain.
Just three months ago, Bush held a 68 percent to 8 percent lead.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 1225 adults also found that McCain's message of
reforming campaign finance laws was far more popular than Bush's
plan to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bush's advantages is his huge campaign treasury, though
the Texas Governor was forced to respond yesterday to concerns that
he has already spent $50 million of the record $70 million he has
raised. Bush said the campaign was  &LR; is ``on plan.'' His aides
dismissed reports that he has hastily arranged fund-raisers next
week to buck up the treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bush's expenses was a 30-minute television commercial
featuring conversations with South Carolinians; it ran on three
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also has been all over radio and television _
and even the telephone lines _ with a spot featuring conservative
Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill, who praises Bush's ``strong pro-life record
in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain has been demonized by advocates of legal
abortions for casting 82 votes against a women's right to choose
during his 17 years in Congress, the National Right to Life
Committee is sending a mass mailing to South Carolina voters
warning about McCain's support for using tax dollars for fetal
research.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has dismissed the attacks from the anti-abortion group as
being motivated by his proposal for laws to govern campaign
spending, which the group fears would limit its influence.
</P>
<P>
   A poll conducted for Reuters by the Zogby Group shows Bush with
43 percent support, McCain with 40 percent and Keyes with 4
percent. The poll has a statistical margin of error of 4 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 607 likely voters shows Bush with a 2-to-1
advantage among Republicans, but McCain with a far larger advantage
among independents and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   All voters are eligible to participate in Saturday's Republican
primary, and the outcome will hinge on the number of independents
and Democrats who participate. In the 1996 GOP primary, 276,000
voters were cast. Officials expect 300,000 to 400,000 votes
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's hope that he can repeat his come from behind victory in
New Hampshire is evident in every speech he gives. At a morning
stop in Newberry, McCain mentioned New Hampshire 10 times in the
first nine minutes of his address.
</P>
<P>
   (Washington Bureau Chief Marc Sandalow reported from South
Carolina. Political Writer John Wildermuth reported from San
Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
