<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAW DELIVERS OFF THE BENCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE -- It takes a slump, foul trouble or injury to get
Brian Shaw into a game, but lately his play alone has been enough
to warrant more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly true Wednesday night, as Shaw contributed a
season-h igh-tying 10 points in 17 minutes off the bench in the
Lakers' 92-85 victory over the Charlotte Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really pleased with Brian Shaw's effort off the bench,''
coach Phil Jackson said after playing him the entire fourth
quarter. ``Our bench has been able to help us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's philosophy in such situations?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking to not make (Jackson) nervous, as he says I
always do when I'm on the court,'' he said. ``I just play solid
defensively and keep the ball moving. We have a tendency at times
to get stagnant and just kind of stand around and watch Kobe
(Bryant) do his thing or watch Shaq (O'Neal) do his thing. When I
come in I just try to make sure everybody touches the ball, it gets
from side-to-side in our offense, and pick up the tempo a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jackson favorite Ron Harper, slowed by any number of things
related to age, playing just 20 minutes, Shaw carried the load. In
a tight fourth quarter, he hit 2 of 3 shots for four points, adding
three rebounds, two assists and a blocked shot.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers up by just a point late in the game, Shaw hit a
20-foot jumper to make it 86-83 with 2:39 to go. Then he made a key
defensive rebound that led to an A.C. Green bucket that helped seal
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to have the opportunity to be out there in that
situation and for it to work out the way it did for us tonight,''
Shaw said. ``Hopefully it's somethign that I can build on, and
coach will have more confidence that I can come through in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   No L.A. Toni: Jackson wasn't surprised at the news Wednesday
that Toni Kukoc had been traded by the Bulls to the Philadelphia
76ers . In fact, when Jackson spoke to his former pupil while the
Lakers were in Chicago, Kukoc said he felt something would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knew that it was imminent, that it was happening,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has previously been outspoken about his desire to
acquire Kukoc , but with warnings of tampering charges, he declined
to admit to any disappointment over the trade. Kukoc cannot be
traded again before the Feb . 24 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really guess I can't comment on that,'' Jackson said. ``I
just have to say that it was an interesting trade. I think it's
going to strengthen a couple teams. And Chicago's got some ducks in
a row. They want to hold all the balls (in the NBA draft
lottery).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
