<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORTS-CRIME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 U.S. PORTS AWASH IN CRIMINAL ACTIVITY  &HT;     By BILL WALLACE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ U.S. seaports are under siege by smugglers, drug
traffickers and other criminals, yet law enforcement agencies that
regulate them are understaffed and outgunned, U.S. Sen. Dianne
Feinstein told federal officials meeting here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drug trafficking, alien smuggling, export of stolen
automobiles and international cargo theft are rampant,'' the
California Democrat told members of a federal task force
investigating seaport security issues during a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet, in spite of the fact that the major problems besetting
seaports all fall within the traditional jurisdiction of U.S. law
enforcement, no federal agency currently has comprehensive
authority to regulate activity at seaports.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein was one of a host of speakers who turned out for a
day-long hearing held by the Interagency Commission on Crime and
Security in U.S. Seaports, a special working group made up of
representatives of 20 different federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's session was the second of three public forums to be
held by the commission. The panel, which was appointed by President
Clinton, began a detailed inquiry into law enforcement issues at
U.S. ports last summer and is scheduled to deliver a report
containing its findings and recommendations for reform to the
President in April.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks that kicked off the session, Feinstein said a series
of recent incidents at West Coast ports underscore the
vulnerability of U.S. ports in an age of transnational crime and
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Customs Service inspectors had seized 132 kilograms of
opium last summer at the Port of Oakland, the largest opium seizure
in U.S. history, she noted. In addition, drug traffickers are
increasingly using regular freight cargo containers to ship cocaine
and other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There also has been an increase of alien smuggling in the last
few months at West Coast ports, including those at Los Angeles,
Long Beach, Seattle, Vancouver and Tacoma,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement sources tell her that such incidents are just
``the tip of the iceberg,'' said Feinstein, who is running for
re-election this year.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein noted that American ports have too few Customs agents
for adequately monitoring incoming and outgoing shipments and often
lack modern crime fighting equipment such as scanners capable of
X-raying the contents of entire containers and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   She also said there is a lack of coordination of law enforcement
efforts by the organizations responsible for port facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after Wednesday's hearing, U.S. Commissioner of
Customs Raymond Kelly, one of the three co-chairs of the
commission, acknowledged that stemming the tide of contraband and
human smuggling is a daunting task, but that the 201-year old
Customs Service is trying to figure out new and better ways to do
the job.
</P>
<P>
   He said the service had commissioned a Price Waterhouse audit of
its resources and functions in an effort to find ways to make the
agency more efficient, and is trying to find ways to finance new
technology it needs to improve its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need better information and we need better intelligence,''
he said. ``We need technology ... We need additional resources _
additional people to do the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
