<HEADLINE>
STORR OWNS CHICAGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- Kings goaltender Jamie Storr continued his mastery of
the Chicago Blackhawks in Wednesday's 4-1 victory at the United
Center .
</P>
<P>
   Storr raised his record to 5-1 lifetime against the Blackhawks
with a 1.25 goals against average. He defeated Chicago 3-2 on Nov.
16 even though the Hawks scored two goals in the final period and
outshot the Kings 23-1.
</P>
<P>
   Storr was sidelined with a concussion Dec. 18 when Chicago won 8
-4 in the middle of the Kings six-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it like it's me who won the game,'' said Storr
, who set a career high with his 13th victory. ``We play Chicago
well. They are physical, but we take it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Nov. 16 game, the Blackhawks came on in the third
period. Tony Amonte scored on a breakaway after the puck bounced
off the skat e of defenseman Rob Blake. Chicago later had several
excellent scoring c hances, but Storr, who made 25 saves, turned
them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lead and we held on to it,'' Storr said. ``This is
the first game of a big trip and we wanted to keep the momentum
going.
</P>
<P>
   Berg Sits: Defenseman Aki Berg, whose up and down season has
resulted in several benchings, was a healthy scratch against the
Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   Berg did not play well last Monday against Calgary. Defenseman
Jaroslav Modry, whose only action the past month has come for minor
league Long Beach, played in place of Berg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he did it, but I'm not going to make too much
out of it,'' Berg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through the same thing when I played in New York,''
veteran Mattias Norstrom said. ``The most important thing when you
are sitting in the stands is not to sulk but to think how well you
will do when you get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Out: Third-line winger Craig Johnson missed Wednesday's
game due to a fluke injury that forced him to receive four stitches
to the middle finger on his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was cut when trying to open the window of his hotel room
. The window was broken and fell out of the sash, slicing his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray also elected to rest third-line winger
Marko Tuomainen, who is bother by a sore left foot. Donald Audette,
activated from injured reserve before the game after missing more
than a month with an left ankle sprain, took Johnson's spot in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to be back after six weeks,'' Audette said. ``I've
stayed in good shape and I know that helped me tonight. I wanted to
be ready when I finally got back and I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Any Questions? Colin Campbell, NHL director of Hockey
Operations, and his assistant Mike Murphy will address the players
this afternoon at the team hotel in Detroit for an update on this
year's rul es changes.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial rules has involved goaltender
interference. Until this season, goals were disallowed when
offensive players were in the crease. But with scoring down, the
rules were relaxed and teams are complaining their goaltenders have
become easy targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
