<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS UP TO THE CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. -- The Lakers snuffed out the hot-at-home
Charlotte Hornets on Wednesday, but it wasn't so much
team-versus-team as it was a series of personal challenges:
</P>
<P>
   Kobe vs. Eddie. Rice vs. the ghosts of past and future. Shaq vs.
himself.
</P>
<P>
   It was a clean sweep for the Lakers' three amigos as they used a
late defensive charge to grab a 92-85 victory at the soldout
Charlotte Coliseum. It was the Lakers' second fourth-quarter
comeback in as many nights, and fifth straight win.
</P>
<P>
   They got it when Kobe Bryant bested close friend and former
Laker Eddie Jones, outscoring him 26 to 18 in their first
head-to-head matchup.
</P>
<P>
   They got it when Glen Rice, who was buckling under the weight of
trade rumors and decreasing playing time, snapped out of his funk
to score 21 points against his old team.
</P>
<P>
   And they got it when Shaquille O'Neal, suddenly an ace
free-throw shooter, hit a pair of clutch shots from the line with
22.7 seconds left to seal the win.
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing special about beating ex-teammates or
ex-teams, Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just special to come here and win. It's a tough place to
play,'' he said. ``The guys have lost like three games here all
season long. So it was a big game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest play came from O'Neal, though not by design. With
the Lakers leading by 3 points, and 23.5 seconds left, they were
supposed to run down the clock before shooting. But they muffed the
inbounds play, O'Neal ended up with the ball and was instantly
fouled by ex-Laker Elden Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Swish. Swoosh. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal even left his hand dangling in the air after the second
shot for emphasis, then ran back to the bench for too many high
fives to count.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a gripping moment when Shaq has to go to the foul
line the last minute,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``We came back to
the bench, we said, `Don't worry about it, just go out there and
shoot them the way you've been shooting.' He did.''
</P>
<P>
   It capped a 26-point, 14-rebound night for O'Neal, who was
better from the line (6 for 9) than from the field (6 for 17). His
foul-shooting groove is now 32 for 41 (78 percent) over the last
three games.
</P>
<P>
   He's even enjoying such moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure did,'' he said. ``You see how I left my hand up there?
I ain't missing no more. I'm at a point in my life where it's time
to start concentrating now. So I've been concentrating these last
couple games and just developed more concentration, more confidence
and just keep going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been easy, it's just that I never cared before. I
never cared about shooting 80 percent,'' he said. And now? ``I
still don't care . I'm just taking my time, focusing.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing 90 minutes over two nights, O'Neal struggled from the
field but said it was due more to the Hornets' tactics than
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illegal defense, holding, fouling. The same (things) everyody
else does,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers trailed by six early in the fourth quarter, but
Robert Horry blocked Jones to spark a Bryant dunk at the other end
and the Lakers grabbed the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Hornets coach Paul Silas then rested Jones (who was 6 for 20),
and Bryant took advantage -- hitting three straight jumpers over
David Wesley for an 80-76 Laker lead, which they never
relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Rice, playing in Charlotte for the first time since
forcing the Hornets to trade him last year, sent word through a
Lakers spokesman that he would not speak to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's starting to get his focus back,'' O'Neal said. ``I think
he's not bothered by whatever's going on outside of basketball,''
presumably constant trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Salley was constantly in his ear,'' Brian Shaw said. ``He
talked to him a lot on the plane last night. He knew he was going
to have a lot of emotion coming back and playing here. He just
wanted him to put all the trade rumor stuff aside and just go out
and do what he does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
