<SLUG> BC-MARS-LANDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO SIGNALS FROM MARS NOT FROM LANDER, NASA SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long radio search for messages from the lost Mars Polar
Lander ended Wednesday when NASA officials announced that the faint
radio signals they have tried to track apparently came from some
unknown source on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   One brief signal last month ``had all the earmarks'' of a
message from the spacecraft, said Richard Cook, the mission's
project manager at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, ``and we felt
we had to check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   But weeks of detailed analysis showed that the signal didn't
come from Mars, and ``it is unlikely that we will attempt to listen
again,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   The $165 million spacecraft was radioing steadily from space
December 3 as it flew on course toward its target near the Martian
south pole, but its signal vanished barely minutes before its
scheduled landing.
</P>
<P>
   The 150-foot radio telescope managed by SRI International on the
Stanford University campus picked up weak signals December 18 and
again January 4, and NASA officials called for help from scientists
and engineers at three radio telescope arrays in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the huge telescopes at Jodrell Bank in England, Westerbork
in the Netherlands and Bologna in Italy all failed to hear
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point I'm mystified,'' said Ivan R. Linscott, a senior
research engineer at Stanford who has led the effort at the big
Stanford dish-shaped antenna that is a familiar landmark above
Interstate 280 on the edge of the university campus.
</P>
<P>
   What finally convinced the experts that the mysterious signals
must have come from transmitters on Earth rather than from the
spacecraft was the continued stability of their radio frequencies,
Linscott said.
</P>
<P>
   If the signals had come from Mars, he said, their frequencies
would have varied wildly as they were buffeted by turbulence in the
electrically charged particles that stream from the sun in the
unending ``solar wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent experts named by NASA to a failure review board will
continue trying to determine what might have been the fate of the
lost spacecraft, but they can probably do little more than propose
speculative scenarios when they report next month, Linscott said.
</P>
<P>
   When the reports are in, NASA will have to decide whether
another orbiter and lander similar to the ones lost in December
should be launched in 2001, or whether new technology is needed and
the next Mars mission should be delayed until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The lost Mars lander was to have propelled two tiny
``microprobes'' into the soil of the target area in a search for
evidence of frozen water, and the lander itself would have
monitored weather in the south polar region, dig soil samples for
chemical analysis and photograph the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing series of Mars missions is designed to scout out
places on the planet where NASA hopes to send spacecraft to collect
samples of soil and small rocks and return them to laboratories on
Earth over the next decade.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 0045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
