<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1ST     02-17 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WARD'S INJURY SWINGS THE MOOD FOR KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs for rewriting throughout) 
(sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the new, new National Basketball Association, you
really don't know exactly what is going to emerge from the runway _
the A effort or the B effort. The players themselves usually don't
know. They are just trying to keep healthy for the long march from
autumn to spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are inconsistent enough on their own, but now they
have external pressure on them. Charlie Ward fractured his right
pinkie in Wednesday night's game, which means the Knicks have to
replace 28 minutes a game at point guard for the next three or four
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   They got the word minutes after they outlasted Minnesota, 93-89,
in a game that was more or less representative of the midwinter
trek to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had flown in from other cities on Tuesday night.
Minnesota had merely lost to Denver at home, but the Knicks had
been downright ghastly in Toronto. The Madison Square Garden factor
normally tends to energize both the Knicks and their visitors, but
Wednesday night's game was long on fouls and short on finesse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we would play hard tonight,'' the Knicks' coach, Jeff
Van Gundy, said with heavy emphasis on the word ``tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy added: ``But it's not about tonight. It's about
consistency. After good wins, how do we come back?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Van Gundy went out and got the news that his starting point
guard was hurt, which surely threatens any potential consistency
the Knicks have within them.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the Knicks. On Tuesday, Minnesota's young
star, Kevin Garnett, described the loop-the-loop logistics of the
league: there is always another game. Good grief, is there always
another game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these last few games show that when you relax and when
you don't come out with that focus or edge, you get beat up pretty
bad,'' Garnett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA's crazy like that,'' added the young sage from a
Chicago high school. ``You have one night when you're great and one
night when you're terrible. The best thing is that tomorrow is
another day.''
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistency in the league _ we are not talking here about
losing; we are talking about apathy _ is yet another symptom the
NBA is floundering right now. The television rating for the
All-Star Game last Sunday was the lowest since the game went on the
networks, down 35 percent from the last one, two years ago, when a
certain Michael Jordan still roamed the land. People are avoiding
pro hoops on Sunday afternoon in favor of Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night it was a distinct pleasure to push the clicker
and get away from Patrick Ewing's bemused scowl in search of George
W. Bush's characteristic smirk.
</P>
<P>
   The eminently clickable Knicks seem unable to put a few strong
games together, and Van Gundy does not want to blame road games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can lose the fight on the road, but when you have no
fight, that's a problem,'' Van Gundy said. ``Different guys take a
possession off. There is not a priority to set a tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Ward was hurt, Van Gundy was forced to take stock of
his team on Wednesday as the 76ers seemed to improve themselves by
trading for Toni Kukoc. If the Knicks have many more walkabouts
with Ward missing, they could be in jeopardy of losing the
home-court advantage in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Knicks had enough talent, Van Gundy screwed up his
face and remained silent long enough to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't separate talent from commitment,'' he said.
``Hustling is part of talent. It's all part of the same package.''
</P>
<P>
   He criticized his players for not being physical enough, despite
their reputation for aggression, most of which went north with
Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are going in unimpeded,'' Van Gundy said, adding that his
players ``sort of got out of the way'' on layups Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The players seem mildly embarrassed but not to the point of
losing their cool or throwing themselves around on the floor after
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the Knicks who give off the stale aroma. The
new ownership of the Dallas Mavericks set a new low by renting the
definitive tired old act, Dennis Rodman, for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Although he can still rebound, Rodman basically stinks up the
league. He sat on the court, tossed his shirt, blustered, and later
suggested that he and Commissioner David Stern duke it out. On
Wednesday, he was fined $10,000 and suspended a game. It's really
the fault of the new owner, Joe Cuban, who hasn't been around long
enough to be embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   But hang in there. The playoffs are in two months. Charlie Ward
will be back by then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
