<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9533 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-RODMAN-TEX     02-17 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN SUSPENDED ONE GAME, FINED $10,000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It didn't take long for forward Dennis Rodman to draw
the wrath of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   A week after playing his first game with the Mavericks, Rodman
has been fined $10,000 and suspended for one game. The penalties
stem from Tuesday's home game against the Milwaukee Bucks, when
Rodman verbally abused the officials and failed to leave the court
in a timely fashion after he was ejected with 7:13 remaining in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, who has 29 rebounds in two games with the Mavericks,
will sit out tonight's 7:30 tilt against the Detroit Pistons at
Reunion Arena. The one-game suspension costs Rodman a game check of
$5,032, in addition to the fine.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, who has been heavily fined throughout his NBA career,
said he expected a fine or suspension after he used disparaging
remarks about NBA commissioner David Stern and the referees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fine, a heavy fine, I don't give a damn,'' Rodman said. ``Me
and David Stern need to clear our differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said \RTuesday\S night, let's get into a ring, and he
get naked and I get naked, and let's go on and get it on,
brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach Don Nelson said Rodman should have used better
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the commissioner will put on the boxing gloves
and box Dennis Rodman,'' Nelson said. ``I don't think that's going
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, he is in charge of Dennis' future, and a wise man
probably wouldn't jeopardize that. It's not a good idea to
challenge the commissioner. The commissioner will win every time.
Not in the ring; outside the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's suspension comes at a critical time. The Mavericks
trail Minnesota by seven games in the race for the eighth and final
playoff spot in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Mavericks were rolling along with 10 wins in 13
games before Rodman came on board. Since Rodman's arrival, some of
the players' minutes have been reduced, team chemistry has been
tampered with, and, more importantly, the Mavericks are 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Rodman thrusting the Mavericks into the national
spotlight in a negative light, the Mavericks must be privately
asking themselves if signing him was worth the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's a marked man,'' forward Cedric Ceballos
said. ``But in any given situation he does draw a lot of attention,
and they take that as a negative and don't want to see that
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's latest run-in started when he argued that the Bucks
should have been whistled for illegal defense. That drew a
technical from referee Ken Mauer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while Bucks guard Sam Cassell was preparing to shoot the
free throw as a result of Rodman's first technical, Rodman decided
to take a seat on the floor at the opposite end, near the
free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Referee David Jones noticed Rodman sitting down, then
immediately ejected him. Rodman proceeded to verbally abuse Jones
before leaving the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with the ejection if he sat in the middle of
the floor,'' Nelson said. ``I didn't see it. I was talking to one
of the referees at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, who will be 39 in May, had five days off because of
All-Star weekend between his first and second games. Now, because
of his suspension, he'll have four days off before his third game,
Sunday in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play, and I want to help this team,'' Rodman said.
``It's a big challenge for me.''
</P>
<P>
   So is staying out of trouble with the NBA office. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
