<HEADLINE>
STARS KILL OFF PENALTIES, PREDATORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In 47 seconds, the Stars saved 60 minutes. Their 3-0
victory against the Nashville Predators last night was won in the
span between the one-minute and 1:47 mark of the third period. The
Predators had a five-on-three power play in that time that the
Stars didn't just kill, but suffocated. ``I thought the kill at the
start of the third period brought it right back again,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said of the momentum that had been drained out
of the team in the second period. ``I thought our penalty killing
pretty much won the hockey game for us tonight.'' The Stars killed
off seven Nashville power plays. They've killed 71 of the past 74
they've faced. The crew of defenseman Richard Matvichuk, et al., is
doing what they do best, sucking the offense out of other teams.
``The Dallas Stars organization has proclaimed ourselves as the
defensive team of the NHL,'' Matvichuk said. ``And we've proven it
the last few years.'' A healthy dose of penalty kill along with
just enough of captain Mike Modano and backup goalie Manny
Fernandez proved it last night, putting them four points ahead of
the Phoenix Coyotes in the Pacific Division. They have a chance to
turn that into a six-point lead with a victory in tomorrow night's
showdown between the two division heavyweights. Modano scored two
of the Stars' goals, including a salty, back-breaking goal at 4:22
remaining in the third period. The goal was Gretzky and Jagr and
Lemieux all rolled into a three-second frame. Predators defenseman
Drake Berehowsky didn't have a chance as Modano danced around him
like Fred Astaire to get a wide look at the goal. ``I was just kind
of guessing,'' Berehowsky admitted. ``He had a lot of speed built
up, and I was just sitting back. I was trying to guess.
Unfortunately, he got off a good shot.'' He has been the Stars'
most-productive player since missing a game Jan. 15 with a mild
concussion. He has 16 points (eight goals and eight assists) in his
past 12 games. The statistic is even more impressive considering
the Stars have only 31 goals in that span, meaning he has been
involved in more than half of them. ``He's a dominant player right
now,'' Hitchcock said. ``He's a dominant player in a lot of
aspects. ... He's a dominant player in the full 200 feet of ice.''
It wasn't their best game, but it didn't have to be because once
again Modano was their best player. The good news for the Stars is
the last time the Stars played less than their best and won, they
came out the next game and took it out on Phoenix, kicking them
around, 2-0. The previous game against Atlanta, ironically, was the
closest Fernandez had ever been to a shutout; the Thrashers scored
with two minutes left. Last night Fernandez stopped 18 shots for
the first shutout of his NHL career.
``I think the guys felt a little bad about the last one. They kept
saying `I'm sorry,' '' Fernandez said. ``The first one is always
special when it's the first one. You get the first one out of the
way, and then you don't think so much about it and get reminded
every time about it. So now I'm just a regular goaltender now.''
The performance certainly wasn't anything new for Fernandez. He has
stopped 250 of the 263 shots he has faced in his past 10 starts.
His biggest saves last night were seconds apart midway through the
second period. Predators center Sebastien Bordeleau, with his feet
just on the edge of the crease, had two cracks at it. But Fernandez
stopped both, swallowing the second beneath his pads. Fernandez
said the key for him was Modano's goal 77 seconds into last night's
game on a play he created. He was bumping and grinding behind the
Predators' net before leaving the puck along the boards for winger
Brenden Morrow. Morrow dropped it to winger Jamie Langenbrunner,
who sent a no-look pass through the crease to Modano. He deked down
Nashville goalie Tomas Vokoun and then stuck it in for a 1-0 Stars
lead. Modano flashed this feisty style all night, including looking
like he might drop the gloves at one point in the third period. ``I
doubt it,'' Modano said with a chuckle. ``At times in the past, I
would try to hide and get away from the game. That's something I've
had to learn to deal with. It gets me in the game, challenges me.
When you get pushed like that into a corner, you fight back.'' The
game was the Stars' first of a string of seven games in 12 days, a
string that Hitchcock told him team before the game would be a
measuring stick. ``I still feel that way,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's
going to tell us a lot where we stand in this conference.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
