<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-COUNCIL-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. POLICE CHIEF CALLS FOR REBUILDING COMMAND STAFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a dramatic presentation to the City Council,
LAPD officials outlined a series of reforms Wednesday to prevent
the ``monstrous'' situation at the Rampart Division _ where
warnings were ignored or overlooked _ from occurring again.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Bernard C. Parks and his top deputies told the
council that the scandal already has led to implementing several
reforms in management and supervision. He pointedly noted that the
budget cuts imposed by the mayor and council over 20 years reduced
the number of command-level supervisors, a problem that became
critical in the patrol officer buildup in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The command staff needs to be rebuilt to previous levels and
internal affairs operations expanded sharply, he said. Changes in
state law and the City Charter are needed to use sting operations
and other methods to closely monitor officer conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could this go on?'' Parks asked. ``It's generally a lack
of oversight by command supervision all the way up through the
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Confronting pressure for an outside investigation of the LAPD,
Parks repeatedly reminded officials that it was the department
itself that began the investigation in 1998 as a result of cocaine
missing from evidence lockers.
</P>
<P>
   That led to the arrest of former Officer Rafael Perez, who has
since sought to reduce a projected 14-year prison sentence by
detailing a seemingly out-of-control anti-gang Community Resources
Against Street Hoodlums unit at the Rampart Division that assaulted
and shot gang members, planted evidence on them and lied in court
to win convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 1 priority is to make sure that those folks who were
imprisoned or are in jail because of this are set free,'' Parks
said, adding that criminal investigators have begun to move beyond
the investigation of Perez and are looking at other officers.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said officials were also looking at other CRASH teams and
all specialized units in the city to determine whether there are
other problems, as well as making changes to ensure there is
increased supervision of the units and that their roles are
clarified.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Chief Mike Bostic, who has been in charge of a massive
Board of Inquiry project to be completed by March 1, said the
problems at Rampart should have been seen earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The systems were in place, but they were either overlooked or
ignored,'' Bostic said. ``This was a monstrous investigation.' As
part of the inquiry, profiles were conducted of Perez and 11 other
officers who have been fired or relieved of duty.
</P>
<P>
   In looking at their records from the time they applied to the
LAPD through their years on the force, Bostic said at least four of
them should not have been hired because of problems, particularly
involving debts, that should have been discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said the department plans to administer polygraph tests to
all applicants to uncover these and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said he wants to see the department get the power to
periodically review the financial situation of officers as well as
stage periodic sting operations to uncover those who might have
gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the chief said he wants to expand the Internal
Affairs Group to the levels recommended by the Christopher
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems at Rampart was that the CRASH unit was in a
separate office with no direct supervision from anyone outside the
sergeant in charge of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Parks has already sent out an order changing that to require
that all CRASH units as well as specialized units such as narcotics
and vice report to a watch commander daily and also be involved in
roll calls.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue that needs to be addressed is the level of
supervision, Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   When the department began its massive buildup in 1994, the ratio
of officers to sergeants was seven to one. In 1994-95, the ratio
was lowered to eight to one, meaning less supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said the total number of supervisors dropped
dramatically after the 1978 passage of Proposition 13 and a series
of budget cuts in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we hired all these new officers, we never replaced the
supervisors,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a $9million package of reforming the department,
Parks said he wants to begin to replace those administrators to get
tighter controls.
</P>
<P>
   Council members, who had received the briefing in a closed
session two weeks ago, agreed under public pressure to Wednesday's
open meeting to review the state of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   They said they remained concerned about eliminating criminals
from the department and restoring public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Parks was asked whether a code of silence exists
within the Police Department in which officers refused to inform on
one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no different in this organization than in any other
organization,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Several council members expressed concern about public
perceptions of the scandal and efforts to fix the department.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg, who is campaigning for a state
Assembly seat, said she is constantly questioned about the Rampart
scandal and the fear people have of police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public wants to know how this was missed,'' Goldberg said.
``You had officers with tattoos, officers with gang initiations,
awarding plaques for shootings. I get told by people that they
don't trust the police anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying to me that they believe the presumption of
innocence is not there anymore. And it's not just the police. It's
the courts and the public defender and the District Attorney's
Office. They don't trust the entire justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski, who chairs the council's Public
Safety Committee overseeing the LAPD, said the city cannot tolerate
criminals within the police force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deal with the criminality first,'' Miscikowski
said. ``We have to get rid of the corruption in these elite
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Laura Chick said she had raised questions at the
start of the LAPD personnel buildup over the need for greater
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiring all these officers meant more than just getting them
the equipment,'' Chick said. ``We were hiring officers and didn't
have the supervisors in place to train them.''
</P>
<P>
   The full Board of Inquiry report is to be released March 1 to
the Police Commission, which will then conduct its own analysis of
it. The City Council on Tuesday authorized providing whatever funds
are needed by the commission to conduct its review.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
