 STATE-TEXAS-TEX 
VICTORY KEEPS TEXAS ALIVE IN Big 12 RACE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas forward Gabe Muoneke justifiably was having a
hard time breathing as last night's pivotal match with Oklahoma
State moved into the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My asthma was acting up, but I wasn't about to tell coach
\RRick\S Barnes to let me sit,'' Muoneke said.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing. Muoneke breathed life into the Longhorns' continuing
hopes for a repeat Big 12 championship, leading the way to a 68-57
victory over the No. 8 Cowboys before an Erwin Center crowd of
15,525. The Longhorns avenged an earlier 73-65 loss in Stillwater.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off the bench for the third consecutive game, Muoneke
scored a game-high 17 points and passed out three assists to pace
No. 17 Texas (18-6) to a record fourth victory over a Top 10
opponent this season and their 10th consecutive victory at home.
The Longhorns are 6-0 at home in conference games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to protect your home court if you're going to win the
title,'' pointed out Texas center Chris Mihm, who recorded his 15th
double-double of the season with 15 points and 16 rebounds. ``This
is a huge game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns pumped their Big 12 record to 9-2 in pulling even
with OSU and staying a game behind leader Iowa State (22-3, 10-1),
which pulled off a big victory at Kansas last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised Iowa State won in Lawrence,'' OSU coach Eddie
Sutton said. ``I guess that means both of us better go up to Ames
and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas is at Iowa State Tuesday; OSU follows on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And as much as his offense was key, Muoneke also contributed to
a defensive effort that held OSU forward Desmond Mason to 12 points
after he had drilled Texas for 30 in the Cowboys' victory last
month. Texas also got another productive game from guard Darren
Kelly, who followed his clutch performance at Missouri Saturday
with a 14-point performance and a good defensive effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas was more aggressive this time,'' said Mason, who hit
four of 13 shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns broke from a 29-27 halftime lead to a 48-35
advantage with a 12-2 run, during which Muoneke scored eight of his
13 second-half points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took what the defense gave me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason singlehandedly brought OSU back by scoring seven points in
a 9-0 run with Muoneke and Kelly on the bench catching a breather.
Muoneke ended the run with a baseline slam and UT inched back up by
10.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton put the Cowboys into a zone to clog the middle after a
timeout with 6:58 to play. Texas scored only three more field
goals, but forward Chris Owens _ a 50 percent free-throw shooter _
hit six of seven from the line to help keep OSU at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Key was Mihm's rebound and follow layup after Owens' only miss
after six in a row with 1:57 left. That gave Texas a 64-55 edge and
OSU could not hit another shot from the floor, scoring only two
more points on a pair from the line by Glendon Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was really good,'' Barnes said of the 41.2 percent
defensive effort. ``It was a great college game. Both teams played
their hearts out and there were no easy baskets at any time.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
