<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-17 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUSTIN _ As basketball arenas go, the Frank Erwin Center has always
been a great place to stage a boat show.
</P>
<P>
   While Duke's Cameron has always had its Crazies, the Drum has
been known to have its Doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   It has seen some good basketball teams, sure _ even championship
teams. But as often as the Longhorns have put together squads that
could threaten anyone in the land, the home floor hasn't exactly
been Cameron Indoor Stadium, or even Phog Allen Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more like a sort of Gracie Allen Fieldhouse, with
all its soft lighting, soothing surroundings, polite applause and
Geritol Generation season-ticket holders hollering at students to
sit down.
</P>
<P>
   But in barreled the No. 8-ranked Oklahoma State Cowboys on
Wednesday night, with old nemesis Eddie Sutton scowling and
prowling along the sideline, first place in the Big 12 potentially
on the line and emotions bubbling over.
</P>
<P>
   The Horns found themselves in the midst of their first truly
large home game in probably two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to tell our guys,'' Texas coach Rick Barnes
said. ``We lose this, we have no chance (at winning the conference
title).''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona game earlier this year? Most Texas fans remember
that day _ Dec. 4 _ for the football loss the Longhorns took from
Nebraska in the Big 12 Championship Game. The wins over DePaul,
Michigan State and Massachusetts? The first two came in Puerto
Rico, the last one on the road. And they were non-conference games
at that.
</P>
<P>
   This one was at home, and the Horns desperately needed it. This
one brought back memories of the Southwest Conference, of Abe
Lemons and Eddie Sutton. Of the kinds of games that fans used to
break down the doors hoping to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel the electricity when both teams walked into the
building tonight,'' Barnes said. ``It was a great college
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   It was two Top 25 teams and a potential payback game for a loss
Texas took in Stillwater last month. It was the league's best big
man, Texas' Chris Mihm, and a truly great scorer, OSU's Desmond
Mason.
</P>
<P>
   And it proved to be just what the Longhorns needed, a tense
68-57 affair, but a win that kept Texas in the conference race and
was the best basketball show Austin has seen in quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was unbelievable tonight,'' said Texas forward Gabe
Muoneke, who came off the bench to be the hero of the night with 17
points on 8-of-12 shooting. ``They picked us up, and we played at a
higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns needed every bit of emotional surge, and if
they're going to have a legitimate shot at winning another Big 12
title, they're going to have to take this energy on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke clearly was the man Wednesday with an eight-point
explosion midway through the second half that broke open the game
and crippled the Cowboys' hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm, doing a sort of Shaq Diesel kind of thing to the middle of
the lane, did the rest. The two Texas big men combined for 32
points and 21 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chance for us to move right back up top and show what
we could do,'' Mihm said. ``In this conference, if you're going to
expect to win the title, you're going to have to win all your games
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a night for Barnes to circle and perhaps remember
if this season gets even better, which it just might. The old place
showed it still has some rattle left in the rafters.
</P>
<P>
   And the Longhorns showed a 20-2 team that the conference title
remains theirs until someone takes it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'm going to find something wrong about this game
when I look at it on tape,'' Barnes said, ``but when we needed to
make plays, we made plays. It was obviously a big win.''
</P>
<P>
   There remains quite a tough road for the Longhorns in their
title quest, especially next week when they travel to Ames, Iowa,
to take on Iowa State in another showdown.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a team that continues to show it can get the job
done at home and on the road. This is a team that seems to have all
the right ingredients to make a run in the conference and NCAA
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The further we go down the road,'' Muoneke said, ``we're going
to have to keep doing the things we've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
