<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ROOKIES-H     02-17 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ROOKIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Tony Stewart won three events and finished
fourth in the Winston Cup points championship last season, things
no rookie had done before.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The one thing Stewart didn't have much of was competition from
other rookies, but don't expect a runaway winner this year. Stewart
and many other Winston Cup drivers believe the 2000 rookie class is
the best ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, I could be going to some of these guys for advice,''
Stewart said. ``So yeah, I would rate them pretty high. They have
quite a batch of credentials, and they're all here because they
deserve to be here. These guys have been quick in whatever type of
car they were driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven talented rookies are planning to compete in every Winston
Cup event this season, and all hope to be in the field for Sunday's
Daytona 500. They have little in common except for driving skill
and confidence in their ability.
</P>
<P>
   The group includes Dale Earnhardt Jr., Matt Kenseth, Mike Bliss,
Scott Pruett, Dave Blaney, Jeff Fuller and Stacy Compton. All seven
have been winners at other levels of racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be the toughest year ever to be the best rookie,''
said Kenseth, who is driving the DeWalt Ford. ``There's always a
lot of pressure being a rookie in Winston Cup, but we have pressure
this year just competing with the other rookies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth and Earnhardt have received most of the attention among
the rookie class. They battled all last season for the Busch Grand
National championship before Earnhardt clinched his second
consecutive title.
</P>
<P>
   Both are in their mid-20s, and both have famous mentors helping
them. Kenseth is being guided by Mark Martin, who is the co-owner
of Kenseth's car with Jack Roush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be with Roush Racing if it wasn't for Mark
Martin,'' Kenseth said. ``He put this whole thing together. I'm
going to rely on him a lot this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt can rely on his father. Junior is seen as the heir to
his famous dad's racing legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a lot to learn,'' Junior said. ``And my dad tells
me I still have some straightening up to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Earnhardt, ``Little E'' to many people in the garage
area, has everything a rookie could hope for in a new team.
Budweiser will put up $50 million over five years to sponsor the
team owned by Earnhardt's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done pretty well for himself,'' Dale Earnhardt said of
his son. ``I try to advise him a little bit, but as far as telling
him to do this or don't do that, the biggest thing I've told him is
don't mess with Daddy out on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior's success the last two years has drastically changed his
life, making him almost as popular with the fans as his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain things I used to do that I just can't do
anymore,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``You learn to stick around your
real friends.''
</P>
<P>
   It might surprise some people to learn that Earnhardt's best
friend is Kenseth. When they are off the track, they don't talk
about racing.
</P>
<P>
   They are more concerned with the rest of the rookie field than
they are with each other. The group includes drivers with a lot
more racing experience than Kenseth or Junior has.
</P>
<P>
   Blaney, 37, is a former World of Outlaws series champion who has
been a Busch driver the previous two years, winning four poles last
season and finishing seventh in the points standings. He joins Bill
Davis Racing as Ward Burton's teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to be a contender in the rookie race,'' Blaney said.
``I don't know if anybody else expects it, but I do. We have the
team to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he thinks Blaney, like Stewart last year, will prove
he is better suited to the higher horsepower of the Winston Cup
cars than the less powerful Busch cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dave is going to surprise some people,'' Davis said.
``I think we are going to see three, four or maybe even five
drivers in contention for the rookie title.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss and Compton, two drivers making the transitions from the
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series, also hope to be contenders. A lot of
NASCAR fans in Houston will be rooting for Bliss, who is the driver
of the Conseco Pontiac for A.J. Foyt's new team. Compton is driving
the Kodiak Ford for Melling Racing.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, a veteran Busch driver and the oldest rookie at 42, is
getting more attention these days for his sponsor _ Viagra _ than
his driving skills, but he hopes that will change.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett, 40, is making the transition from CART with new Winston
Cup team owner Cal Wells III. Pruett was the fastest rookie
qualifier at Daytona last weekend with the 10th-best speed overall
at 189.470 mph in the Tide Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems strange to be called a rookie,'' Pruett said. ``I've
raced a long time in a lot of different series and have a lot of
experience, but there is certainly a lot to learn here. And this is
a tough rookie group, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the veteran Winston Cup drivers feel the same way. Jeff
Gordon, the 1993 Rookie of the Year, calls it ``a pretty impressive
class.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bobby Labonte: ``It's an incredible class of rookies.''
</P>
<P>
   The rookie class of 1979 included Dale Earnhardt and Terry
Labonte, but defending series champion Dale Jarrett thinks this one
is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is probably the best rookie class we've ever seen
come into Winston Cup,'' Jarrett said. ``They will be in contention
in a lot of races.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
