<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9547 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-OKLAST-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      02-17 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OKLAST-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ There is one thing about defending a conference
championship.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title is yours until someone takes it away from you.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State has looked like it was capable of winning the Big
12 crown, even looked like the favorite to do so, but the title
still belongs to the Texas Longhorns _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a resounding effort from forward Gabe Muoneke, Texas
got a measure of revenge for an earlier loss in Stillwater with a
68-57 win over Oklahoma State on Wednesday before a season-best
crowd of 15,525 at the Erwin Center.
</P>
<P>
   No. 17 Texas improved to 18-6 overall and 9-2 in Big 12 play to
pull into a second-place tie with the eighth-ranked Cowboys (20-3).
Iowa State, which hosts Texas next week, leads the league with a
10-1 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at them being ranked No. 8 in the country, and we
don't think they were overrated, we just think that if they're No.
8, then we must be No. 7 or No. 9, because the two teams are that
close to each other,'' Muoneke said. ``We think they are one of the
best teams in the nation, and we feel we must be as well. We knew
if we could beat them, we could establish ourselves as one of the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to show you can win games like this if you want to
make it to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke finished with 17 points on 8-of-12 shooting to lead
Texas. Chris Mihm added 15 points and 16 rebounds and Darren Kelly
chipped in 14 points for the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke, who has come off the bench the past three games after a
run-in at practice with coach Rick Barnes, took over for a
2{-minute stretch of the second half to lead the Longhorns to the
win.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke had a steal and a long pass downcourt for an assist on a
Kelly dunk, then scored eight consecutive points in a 12-2 run that
gave the Longhorns a commanding 48-35 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got aggressive, and he was getting the ball really
deep, and when he gets the ball down that low you can't really stop
him,'' Oklahoma State's Desmond Mason said of Muoneke.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke said coming off the bench is a challenge for him in his
senior year, but his concern for what is best for the team is more
important than any selfish desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that I love it, but he (Barnes) has been doing
this for a long time and I'm not going to question his decision,''
Muoneke said. ``We're winning, and we won last year. He's come
through for me in every situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said it is Muoneke who is coming through for the
Longhorns in the most important stretch of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was great tonight,'' Barnes said. ``I like him coming off
the bench. I know what we're going to get from him. He changes the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that bothers me is people thinking he's not
starting because of some discipline problem from three games ago,
and that's not the case. People make too much about who's starting,
I think. Gabe's been great _ not good, but great about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who finished with just 12 points, answered the
Muoneke-led run by scoring seven points in a 9-0 blitz to get the
Cowboys back into the game, but Oklahoma State never got closer
than five points the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys pulled within 55-50, Muoneke drove the lane
against a 2-3 zone for a scoop layup to make it a seven-point game
with five minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Owens, a 50.5 percent foul shooter entering the game, hit
five of six from the line in the final four minutes to help thwart
the Cowboys' comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Little was decided in the first half, as the two teams slugged
it out with neither taking charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys biggest lead was five points at 17-12, while the
Longhorns' best advantage was a three-point edge of 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Texas took a two-point advantage into the break on Ivan Wagner's
3-pointer with less than 10 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who had 30 points against Texas earlier this season, had
trouble getting free against the Longhorns' pressuring man-to-man
defense. With a variety of Longhorns chasing him, Mason took just
three shots in the first half and finished only 4-for-13 overall
from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desmond didn't play very well, and it's hard for us to win if
he doesn't play well,'' Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton said.
``When your top two scorers, (Joe) Adkins and Mason, go 7-for-25 on
shots, it's going to take you out of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
