<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO HANDICAP SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA MADNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Which Southern California team has the easiest
path to the NCAA Tournament? That's easy: Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to their record, schedule and power ratings, the Waves
are close to securing an at-large bid. If only UCLA and USC had it
so easy...
</P>
<P>
   With 3 weeks until Selection Sunday, here's a look at the local
contenders:
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine: The Waves are 19-6 overall and 9-1 in the WCC (tied
with Gonzaga). In itself, the record won't excite members of the
NCAA Tournament Selection committee. But the Waves will get bonus
points for a bold nonconference schedule (Kansas, Auburn, UCLA).
They are 26th in the Ratings Percentage Index, which closely
approximates the NCAA's power ratings ahead of Michigan State, Ohio
State, Utah, UCLA and Gonzaga and they're 33rd in the latest
Sagarin power ratings. (Teams in the 30s are usually good bets for
at-large bids.)
</P>
<P>
   The Waves can't afford a late-season collapse; a loss to Loyola
Marymount, San Diego or St. Mary's would crush their power rating.
But if they take care of regular-season business and finish 23-6,
they probably won't need to win the WCC tournament to get a bid.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA chances: Very good.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge: Despite victories over Oregon and Fresno
State, the Matadors have one path to the NCAA Tournament: They must
win the Big Sky tournament. With power ratings of 114th (Sagarin)
and 125th (RPI), they have no chance for an at-large bid.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, they're running out of time. At 14-7 overall and 6-4
in the Big Sky (third place), they trail first-place Eastern
Washington by two games with six to play. Don't forget: The
regular- season champ hosts the postseason tournament.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA chances: Slim.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State: The Beach might be the best team in Southern
California right now, but it has one of the toughest paths to the
tournament. The 49ers are 16-4 overall and 8-1 in the Big West.
They beat USC early in the season and had won 15 in a row until
last week's loss to Utah State.
</P>
<P>
   But because of a weak nonconference schedule (two non-Division I
wins: Cal State Dominguez Hills and Cal State Monterey Bay) the
49ers are 74th in the RPI and 46th in Sagarin. That's too low for
an at-large invitation, so they'll need the automatic bid that goes
to the winner of the Big West Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA chances: Solid.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA: Remember how soft the schedule seemed after early-season
victories over Iona, Fairfield and Morgan State? As expected, it
got tougher so much tougher, in fact, that it now stands as the
best in the Pac-10 and one of the top 10 in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins win five of their last eight to reach the 18-win
plateau, they're in the tournament, no questions asked. If they
finish 17-13 overall and 8-10 in the conference, the schedule just
might get them one of the last at-large bids. Their power ratings
are solid (32nd in the RPI and 39th in the Sagarin), and they have
three good wins (DePaul, Purdue and North Carolina).
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why the Bruins are in this predicament. The
losses to Colorado State and Washington are as inexcusable now as
they were at the time.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA chances: Decent.
</P>
<P>
   USC: Based solely on what they've done since Jan.1, the Trojans
(13-9, 6-4) would be in good shape. They've beaten Arizona and UCLA
in conference play, and they're one game out of third place.
</P>
<P>
   But their 7-5 nonconference record with no quality wins
</P>
<P>
   could keep them out of the tournament. They're 35th in the
Sagarin but 63rd in the RPI. In order to reach the magic 18-win
plateau, the Trojans must finish 11-7 in conference.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA chances: Decent.
</P>
<P>
   Selection Sunday preview: Cincinnati, Stanford, Arizona, Duke
and Michigan State are competing for the four No.1 seeds. Michigan
State has the least-impressive record, but the Spartans played a
brutal schedule and have the Big Ten tournament for a last-second
power-ratings boost.
</P>
<P>
   Teams competing for the No.2 and 3 seeds are Tennessee, Auburn,
Florida, Kentucky, Indiana, Ohio State, Texas, Oklahoma State and
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Western Athletic Conference nor the newly formed
Mountain West have automatic bids. That's one less at-large berth
to go around.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the ACC, Big Ten, Big 12, Big East and SEC will fill
most of the at-large slots, but it doesn't appear any of them will
get more than six bids. The Atlantic-10 and Conference USA could
get just two or three bids each.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa is for real. So are Iowa State and Louisiana State. All
three could be fourth- or fifth-seeds.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 definitely will get three bids (Arizona, Stanford and
Oregon). It should get four, and it might get five.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: Commissioner Tom Hansen, working on behalf of
seven constituents, continues to push for a postseason tournament.
Problem is, his marquee schools, Arizona, Stanford and UCLA, are
opposed for academic, financial and competitive reasons. The
postseason tournament is a constitutional issue, so eight schools
must be in favor....
</P>
<P>
   Arizona beat Washington State last weekend for the 30th
consecutive game, a streak that dates to Jan. 1986. It's the
longest intraconference streak in the nation. The longest
nonconference streak belongs to Marquette, which has defeated
Wisconsin-Milwaukee 34 consecutive times.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has as many canceled flights this season (four) as
losses....
</P>
<P>
   Stanford power forward Mark Madsen on his rebounding: ``I'm
trying to be more aggressive going to the glass.'' That's like
Vince Carter saying he wants to jump higher....
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for the stretch run, Oregon gets David Jackson, a
transfer from Utah, back from knee surgery. Jackson was expected to
be the Ducks' sixth man when the season began....
</P>
<P>
   Trying to make his team tougher, Washington coach Bob Bender
ordered a 6 a.m. practice Monday....
</P>
<P>
   And finally: Stanford's field-goal percentage defense (33.8) is
on an NCAA-record pace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
