r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     02-17 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WIN IN OT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Guy Hebert has won more than his share of games for
the Mighty Ducks. For seven years the diminutive goalie has been a
tower of strength for a team that hasn't always provided him with
quality support.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night before 12,956 at The Pond it was the Ducks
who were forced to try and win one for their goalie. And thanks to
Oleg Tverdovsky that is just what they did. The Anaheim defenseman
combined with Paul Kariya for a breathtaking goal at 3:20 of
overtime to give the Ducks a 6-5 victory over the Calgary Flames.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrik Olausson's power play goal at 14:00 of the third period
tied the game, 5-5, setting the stage for Kariya and Tverdovsky to
work their magic.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya made several nifty moves in the neutral zone and left a
drop pass for Tverdovsky, who used a brilliant inside-out move to
get around Daryl Shannon and easily beat goalie Fred Brathwaite who
didn't know where Tverdovsky was heading.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible goal ... I've never seen a goal like
that,'' said Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg, a man not given
exagerations. ``Paul made about eight moves, Oleg made about eight
moves. Two great players made a play to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oleg came off the bench like he was shot out of a rocket, I
figured it was going in one net or another,'' said Hartsburg with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was Tverdovsky's eighth of the season, gave the Ducks
their second overtime win of the season and moved Anaheim
(25-26-8-1) within four points of seventh-place Colorado and kept
it five back of Edmonton, San Jose and the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably my best goal ever,'' said Tverdovsky. ``I
scored some like that in juniors ... but not on this level.''
</P>
<P>
   But the defensemen seemed more impressed by the way the Ducks
kept fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every point is crucial, we need every point,'' he said.
``Tonight we never gave up and we got rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks did their best to make things comfortable for Hebert,
giving him three leads to work with. But each time the crowd or
team looked like they might be able breath easy he let another
questionable goal in.
</P>
<P>
   One bounced off his glove, another off his stick and a third
went off his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim took a 4-3 lead into the third period only to have Jason
Wiemer bounce a shot off Hebert's shoulder into the net 33 seconds
after play began.
</P>
<P>
   Weimer then put the Flames on top with a power play goal at 9:28
. The shot bounced off Hebert's leg pad, but he really had little
chance on the play after two quick passes by Phil Housley and Marc
Savard got the puck to Weimer in prime scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   tainly wasn't Hebert's best night, but nobody was ready to
point fingers, especially after such an emotional victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't Guy's strongest game, but we on the game and that's
all that matters,'' said Kariya, who had a goal and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   Weimer's second goal looked like it might doom Anaheim's
chances, but after several close calls on goal-mouth scrambles, the
Ducks got just what they needed -- a power play of their own and
Olausson converted with the help of a Matt Cullen screen.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second power play goal of the game for the Ducks who
have scored power play goals in nine consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   The power play had given them a 4-3 lead with 28.5 seconds left
in the second period when Olausson's point shot bounced off Steve
Rucchin in the slot.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks won the battle of the bounces in the first period even
though it was Calgary that opened the scoring on Clarke Wilm's goal
at 8:26.
</P>
<P>
   Just 15 seconds after the Flames had taken the lead the Ducks
tied the game when Kevin Haller scored his second goal of the
season and first since the Ducks' home opener on Oct. 8. The
defenseman's shot from the left point went through traffic and
appeared to deflected off a Calgary defender and through
Brathwaite's pads at 8:41.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames recorded nine of the game's first 11 shots, but the
Ducks took the lead at 13:54 thanks to a good bounce and some
hustle by Paul Kariya. The Anaheim captain just barely held the
puck in the Ducks zone before he spun and flipped it toward the
net. The puck hit Housley's skate and bounced right to Rucchin, who
beat Brathwaite from the left circle for his 12th goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Teemu Selanne also assisted on the play, extending his scoring
streak to 12 games and recording the 700th in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning from a staph infection in his left ankle Rucchin
has scored in nine of 11 games, recording five goals and 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his best game of the year,'' said Hartsburg. ''He
played with the passion we need and he was a force each time he was
on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilm's goal began the strange series of the goals, when his
deflection hit the post. The center raised his arms thinking he had
scored and everybody seemed to pause just a moment. That split
second hestation was all that Wilm needed to knock home the rebound
for his ninth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary's second and third goals weren't so much strange as they
were downright discouraging. Anaheim dominated most of the second
period and nearly took a 3-1 lead on an early power play. Even the
Ducks much-maligned penalty killing unit, ranked 26th in the NHL,
easily killed off Calgary's 43-second two-man advantage and was
within five seconds of killing off the rest of the penalty time
when Hebert whiffed on Robyn Regeher's soft shot from the right
circle at 5:04.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's No. 1 line combined to give the Ducks a 3-2 lead at
10:15 when Rucchin did the dirty work along the boards, Selanne
provided the centering pass and Kariya the lightning-fast finish
from the slot for his 35th goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   After another good penalty killing effort Braithwaite stopped
Jeff Nielsen and Kariya on breakaways -- the Ducks' momentum
stalled again when Hebert let a soft shot by Cale Hulse bounce off
his stick and Jarome Iginla scored at 17:02.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
