<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-COUNTDOWN-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans John McCain and George W. Bush face off in South
Carolina, where the primary is only two days away, the Campaign
Countdown is in full swing. Laura Ingraham checks in this week with
a candid look at front-runner Bush's strategy _ or lack of same _
in pursuit of the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' Ingraham writes, ``Bush is where Bill Clinton was
in 1992, when he decided to appear on `60 Minutes' to face
persistent questions about his marital infidelity. He's where his
dad was in 1988, after he lost the Iowa caucuses and Bob Dole was
threatening to win the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, this is his moment of crisis, when he will either
rise to the challenge or fall into the heap of past would-be
nominees who simply weren't ready for political prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush is to recapture the mantle of the hard-charging,
principled, top-of-his-game front-runner,'' the author and MSNBC
host continues, ``he'll need to look inward. The Washington
Establishment, campaign consultants, his parents and Christian
conservatives are useless at this stage. Money and endorsements
can't help him now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person who can stabilize this suddenly shaky campaign
is that dynamic scrapper who dared to take on popular Democratic
Gov. Anne Richards of Texas and won, a committed, no-holds-barred
campaigner named George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingraham joins former Democratic vice-presidential nominee
Geraldine Ferraro _ her counterpart on Campaign Countdown, The New
York Times Syndicate's rotating weekly campaign-commentary column _
in calling it the way she sees it, telling it like it is about
liberals and conservatives alike.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro and Ingraham offer the kind of timely, hard-hitting
insider insights that your readers will want in the upcoming
election season, just in time for what is shaping up as the most
exciting presidential election in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   For a look at this timely feature, visit The New York Times
Syndicate Website at www.nytimes.com/syndicate. Or to see this
week's column and/or subscribe to Campaign Countdown, call Bob
Farnell at (800) 535-4425 or e-mail him at farnellb &LR; nytimes.com. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
