A9664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN20-COX     02-17 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Seeking alternatives to reparations
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it is because affirmative action is being dismantled by
the Reaganized and Bushified federal courts that an old idea _
compensation for the damage done to African-Americans over the 350
years of slavery and segregation _ is stirring again.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action opened long-blocked opportunities to a
shunned people who had been wounded and burdened uniquely. But
affirmative action is being called off before it can complete and
secure its ends, victim of a phony ``colorblindness'' whose real
blindness is to the manifest persistence of racism and its harms.
America the Good has never been much of a match for America the
Easily Distracted.
</P>
<P>
   So the case for reparations is being made anew not only but
chiefly by Randall Robinson, whose TransAfrica led a reluctant U.S.
government into policies that honorably helped to end apartheid in
South Africa. Robinson argues powerfully that black America remains
undermined by the inherited consequences of economic deprivation,
social dislocation and persistent racial abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a debt compounded over centuries that should,
Randall says, literally be paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't gonna happen. That's simply too big a can of worms for the
nation to dare open. Even to pry at it credibly would risk a
political recoil whose likely effects would further damage the
claimants.
</P>
<P>
   But the untenability of the idea does not mean that it isn't a
useful lens through which to view and understand _ and
understanding, to mitigate _ the debilities our tormented racial
history has left us.
</P>
<P>
   Since black America was finally freed by the Voting Rights Act
of 1965 _ the real emancipation _ it has narrowed gaps with white
America in education and income. But the gaps are not near being
closed and as long as they linger the disparities rack up
continuing social costs all Americans pay.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways, if we will have them, to hurry the lines
together.
</P>
<P>
   We could, for instance, rebuild the devastating criminal justice
system from the ground up to remove systemic racial inequities that
are producing black convicts in grotesque disproportion to black
crime. Education, much invoked but little honored as a remedy,
really could be a big part of the solution if we would treat its
failures as catastrophes like floods and tornadoes _ that is, with
emergency crews and aid, and cost be damned.
</P>
<P>
   And if not with broad reparations, then where direct harm can be
shown, financial compensation should be due. Fisk University's Race
Relations Institute, in an intriguing new project, is looking for
black families that can document they were forced from land or
property by threats or other illegal means, going back to the
1870s. Lawyers can't be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   The real Martin Luther King Jr. _ not the sappy version we have
now for rote and easy admiration _ was toying in his last years
with schemes for a major redistribution of wealth. America, 135
years after the Civil War, is still holding out on those 40 acres
and a mule.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
