<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN20-CO     02-17 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Oil cartels again pillage little guy's wallet
 &HT;    (For release Feb. 20, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The motorist tooling around in a 5,000-pound Lincoln Navigator
probably will not be fazed much by the breakneck increase in fuel
prices. After all, if you can afford a $46,000 vehicle, what's
another couple of bucks for gas?
</P>
<P>
   The American economy is good, the experts say; everyone
supposedly is rolling in money. Yeah? How about the little guy who
drives 20 miles to a factory job and back every day? How about what
he's having to pay for gasoline these days _ as opposed to his
income and current financial obligations?
</P>
<P>
   There are several types of motoring public in this country.
There are those in the gas-guzzling Navigators, Expeditions and
Broncos who can afford it. There are those who heeded the warnings
of President Carter a quarter-century ago and purchased more
fuel-efficient autos (example: Navigator, 12 mpg; Honda Civic, 25
mpg.) And there are those in the lower economic strata, driving 6-
or 10-year-old cars that drain gasoline quicker than you can say
OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   While the president is well-intending when he seeks to release
some of the U.S. emergency fuel supply, and to financially assist
people in parts of the country where the price of heating oil has
ascended beyond all reason, he is not addressing the issue.
</P>
<P>
   That issue is U.S. dependence on foreign oil. It is the same
issue Richard Nixon faced with the 1973 Arab oil embargo and it is
the same issue each succeeding president has encountered without
success.
</P>
<P>
   It may well be that fortunes are being made on E-trading and in
technology stocks, but people with fortunes _ or close to it _
really wouldn't be expected to pout much over a rise of about 30
cents a gallon in a short period. For the salaried, for those on
fixed income, this is very much a huge increase in the cost of
living.
</P>
<P>
   How we allowed ourselves to fall victim again to the oil cartels
is beyond me. Too much of what I hear from the men who would be
president is about abortion. Nothing they say or don't say is going
to change anyone else's mind on abortion; they ought to move on to
a new subject: What are we going to do about oil prices? Who did
this to us? And why? Can't we force their hands back to normality?
</P>
<P>
   An international boat show is taking place in Miami this
weekend. The front page of the local newspaper showed a full-color
aerial photo of a waterway crammed with luxury boats. The story
talked about a 60-foot sport fisherman costing $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, elsewhere in largely immigrant Miami, motorists are
seeking gas stations that might be charging a penny less than the
one down the street, the total difference in a 15-gallon tank being
less than a half-buck.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines, rather than cutting back on the peanuts and tuna salad
sandwiches, have added fuel surcharges to their ticket prices.
Mobile street peddlers are charging more for tomatoes today because
they are paying more for gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   This is the stuff of which inflation is made. I don't need Alan
Greenspan to tell me that.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has to get a handle on energy, particularly
renewable energy. It has been too long since we were told that this
country needed to be less dependent upon foreign interests for our
energy, and to be more fuel efficient in our transportation modes.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has happened. In fact, we've drifted from a trend toward
fuel-efficient vehicles to one of gas-guzzling SUVs and minivans.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we're paying the price. Tomorrow, we'll be paying more.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
