<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-POKER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Howls at the dog tracks
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHORTER, Ala. _ Virginia Fannin sells her share of Lance peanut
bars, fan belts, cigars and Cokes from the small, rural grocery
that bears her family's name.
</P>
<P>
   Like many in Macon County, however, Fannin knows that the
business that really puts food on the table sits down the road. In
other counties, breadwinners work at car factories. In Huntsville,
they make rockets. Here, they build dreams for $2 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   VictoryLand Greyhound Park rises from the dirt and asphalt less
than five minutes from the Fannin Grocery on a two-lane country
highway next to Interstate 85. In 1986, VictoryLand was the top
track in the nation, handling $188 million in wagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there. No use in lying about it,'' said Fannin,
echoing a truism of life for many in this county 15 miles east of
Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   For years, though, VictoryLand has been off track financially.
Casinos in Mississippi have drained business for a decade.
Lotteries in Georgia and Florida have siphoned off patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Video gambling is the stopper, track officials claim. They want
to add poker, blackjack and similar games to keep the tour buses
from rolling to the Gulf Coast. Dog tracks in Rhode Island, Iowa
and West Virginia added video gambling machines after they faced
similar competition.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents claim the instant games are so addictive that they
call them the ``crack cocaine'' of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, former Gov. David Beasley called the games a
``cancer'' on society and vowed to eliminate them, then lost
re-election in 1998 after video poker supporters donated millions
to his opponent. Ironically, legislators have voted to ban the
games starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Alabama Tourism and Marketing Committee will conducted a
public hearing Wednesday in Montgomery on a bill that would allow
Macon County residents to vote on whether they want video gambling
at their dog track.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a version of the bill passed a Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation would let residents in Mobile, Birmingham
and Greene County decide whether to allow video gambling at dog
tracks there.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Johnny Ford introduced the bill as local legislation for
Macon County. Traditionally, laws proposed for specific communities
have passed without debate from lawmakers in unaffected parts of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   But gambling opponents _ whose pressure led to the overwhelming
defeat of a statewide referendum last year that would have created
an Alabama lottery _ might not let the video gaming bills pass
without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by The Associated Press showed 49 percent in the
House and 45 percent of the Senate opposed the video gambling
bills. After the lottery's autumn defeat, pro-lottery lawmakers
want to rack up some anti-gambling votes before the 2002 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Steve Windom, who fought the lottery, says tracks are
exaggerating their financial plights. ``Any senator who votes for
gambling after the people rejected gambling last October is going
to do so at his or her risk,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   For VictoryLand, the issue is survival, said Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The track is the largest private employer in the county. It has
cut back to about 400 workers after hitting a high of 800 in the
late 1980s, including 500 full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, this is our Mercedes. This is our Honda,'' said Ford,
referring to automakers Alabama lured to other counties.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when you couldn't get a weekend room at the
Days Inn next to VictoryLand without a reservation. Up to 30
charter buses, many from Atlanta, would jam the parking lot. Even
during the week, matinee races would pack 'em in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you had the machines there, you wouldn't have to go to
Mississippi, would you?'' Fannin said from behind her grocery
counter. ``I'd vote for it.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million people wagered $176 million in 1990 at
VictoryLand. Last year, just 305,000 customers bet $85 million,
according to industry spokesman Rick Heartstill.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the industry's slump nationwide, VictoryLand and
the Birmingham Race Course _ both owned by a Montgomery businessman
_ still ranked among the country's top 10 in wagering in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The track provides a big wad of cash for Macon County. Just
23,000 people live there. Per capita income is $14,300 _ among the
lowest in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   When the state Senate rejected a similar video gambling bill
last year, employees in the VictoryLand break room shook their
heads in resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no real industry here,'' said Charles Johnson, head of
the Macon County Racing Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Since the track opened in 1984, its revenue has helped generate
$37 million for the county school board, $6 million for the county
commission and $7 million for the city of Tuskegee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would hurt if they closed,'' said Vijay Patel, who runs the
Days Inn outside the track's gate. ``They pay a lot of taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   During a recent midweek matinee, a bus from East Point, Ga.,
pulled into the parking lot. Inside, the infield scoreboard
encouraged bettors: ``Avoid the last minute rush. Please wager
early.'' Down on the track, dog grooms dressed in navy blue
jumpsuits walk the greyhounds to eight metal starting boxes. They
slide shut metal doors behind the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   There's a slight pause. Then: Bing, bing, bing, bing.
</P>
<P>
   Like the gentle tone on an airplane alerting you the ``fasten
seatbelt'' light has been turned off, a bing tells you the
motorized lure the dogs will chase has started whipping around the
track. Race time is almost here. It will be over in less than 32
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pari-mutuel racing is suffering basically due to the new
competition because it's so quick. There's instant gratification,''
said Roy Berger, president of the American Greyhound Track Owners
Association, a group that represents all 49 of the nation's dog
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horses run about every 30 minutes,'' Berger said. ``One of the
reasons that dog tracks became so popular in the '70s and '80s was
because we could run two or three races in 30 minutes. Now, people
can pull the handle on a slot machine every 20 or 25 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
