<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    C'mon Regis, I want to be a millionaire
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I have an addiction. Actually, I have
several, but let's not go there. I have become obsessed with ``Who
Wants to be a Millionaire.'' I rarely miss an episode. One of my
proudest moments came when the million-dollar question popped up a
few weeks back, and I knew the answer before the four choices were
displayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far is the Earth from the sun?'' asked Regis Philbin, the
man with the solid-silk ties and gangster suits, finally free from
Kathy Lee Gifford, at least in prime time. He's bound to be doing
the happy dance every night.
</P>
<P>
   Easy, it's 93 million miles, I thought, while running a piece of
oak through the jointer-planer in my shop. Bingo. The actual
contestant and I got it right. I have no idea why I remembered that
piece of trivia, but I did. Thus the germ of an idea began to form.
</P>
<P>
   Playing at home, I am the king, impressing wife and children
with my alleged acumen. Being in the newspaper business gives you
is a treasure trove of useless information. ``You should try to get
on the show,'' the people with whom I live implore.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I say. I am a firm believer in the American way, which is
trying to beat long odds to become rich overnight. I still buy
lotto tickets, even though I know I have a better chance of being
killed by a falling buzzard. My brother says the lottery is
gambling for the mathematically challenged. So? I am mathematically
challenged. That's why I'm in journalism and not engineering. And,
by gosh, somebody has to win eventually. For $2 a week, I can dream
of being the next instant millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   I know enough about probability theory to never bet more than a
buck, at most two, on a 1-in-16 million chance of winning big
money. There is not a lot of difference between having those odds
or increasing them to 20-in-16-million by betting $20. But I can
lose a buck twice a week and not worry about it. Twenty bucks
starts cutting into the fluff money, the spare change spent on soft
drinks, video rentals and other non-essentials.
</P>
<P>
   So I made an effort to get on the show. The first night, I
dialed in for two hours, hitting the redial button while reading.
Busy, busy, busy. I never got through. The next night, I started
earlier and got connected after about five tries. Here we go, I
thought. I'm on the road to winning a million bucks before taxes,
which won't be enough to retire but ought to keep the wolves from
the door as I send a herd of children through college.
</P>
<P>
   It's all done by voice-mail. No live humans are involved at the
entry level. I entered my birth date and the last four digits of my
Social Security number. The object is to answer three questions,
which gets you to the next level. If you've watched the show, the
format is like the ``fast finger'' challenge by which Regis picks a
new contestant for the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   My question: Put the following words that form the title of a
famous children's book in the correct order, in 10 seconds: Mother.
Are. My. You.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. ``You Are My Mother.'' I punched the keypad on the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   I was wrong. It's ``Are You My Mother?'' Y'all probably knew
that. I didn't. The rules banned me from playing until the next
day. Depression and embarrassment kept me away for about three
days. Then I tried again, getting through on the first try. It must
be a sign, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put the following words in the correct order: Bay, Bengal,
The, Of.'' Tough, huh?
</P>
<P>
   I got it wrong again, when I hit the wrong key on the phone pad.
I am notoriously bad at phone pads, which is one reason I despise
phone numbers that use letters, such as 1-800-The-Body. I am
keypad-challenged. Regis hung up on me again. I'm thinking that a
round of therapy may be in my immediate future, and then made the
mistake of telling my wife of my miscues. She laughed and made
large fun of me. I deserve this. Too much strutting in the living
room while popping off answers under absolutely no pressure. Call
it karma.
</P>
<P>
   Then it happened the third time. Once again, I knew the answer,
and once again messed up on the keypad. Regis said goodbye. I'm
hoping the computer doesn't keep a record of the mistakes, or I'll
never get on the show. Too dumb to live, the computer would say,
let alone be on ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not giving up hope. I will call back, once I've gotten over
the pain of earlier rejection. Easy money has a powerful allure.
But I bought an extra lotto ticket this week to hedge my bets.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
