A9690 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GOTTLIEB-COLUMN18-COX     02-17 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTTLIEB-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Political rules reassert themselves
 &HT;    By Martin Gottlieb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For a while there, this political season was
upsetting the best _ and one of most unknown _ rules of
presidential politics. To wit, presidential nomination fights are
about credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about money, standing in the polls, personality, campaign
ability, the quality of a campaign organization, issues and
ideology. Ask only who is the closest thing to a president, the
most acknowledged national leader. If one person stands out, that
person will get the nomination. If not, there will be a scramble.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, presidents always get presidential nominations they
pursue. So do vice presidents: Richard Nixon, 1960; Hubert
Humphrey, 1968; George Bush, 1988. Even former vice presidents
always get nominations they pursue _ Richard Nixon, 1968; Walter
Mondale, 1984 _ unless extraordinary circumstances prevail.
Humphrey lost in 1972, but only because he didn't enter the race
until his chosen candidate, Edmund Muskie, self-destructed. And Dan
Quayle was so lacking in support in 1996 that he decided to not
even make the race; he tried in 2000, but only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   So Al Gore couldn't fail in 2000 without falling into the same
category as Quayle, where he really didn't seem to fit. And yet for
a while there it looked dicey. Bill Bradley took a good lead in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed to hit a wall. The best bet is that the reason is
not that Gore finally got his act together, but that a sitting vice
president simply has a large, locked-in corps of
benefit-of-the-doubt support from the public on the basis of his
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a vice president or former vice president in
the field, a guy like the Bob Dole of 1996 has a great advantage.
He had been a leader of his party for many years in Washington, a
genuine national figure. He had once been the GOP nominee for vice
president and had been talked about for the presidency for years.
Some of his opponents had hardly been thought of as presidential
timber by anybody but themselves (Steve Forbes, Pat Buchanan, Lamar
Alexander).
</P>
<P>
   Dole pretty much breezed to the nomination, much like Ronald
Reagan in 1980, another year when there was no vice president in
the field. Reagan was the two-term governor of the largest state,
acknowledged leader of the then-soaring conservative movement, a
man who had almost been nominated for president in 1976. It was
simply his turn.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there's simply nobody like that in the race. In such
cases _ the Democrats in 1976, 1988 and 1992 _ there is a scramble.
The Republicans faced such a year in 2000 and decided they didn't
want a scramble.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP politicians and financial contributors decided that if
nobody in the field had national standing _ if nobody had the
respect of the American people that results from being nationally
visible for a long time without making a jerk of oneself _ they
would pick the guy who looked strongest in the polls and pretend he
did.
</P>
<P>
   In metaphorical smoke-filled rooms _ supposedly marginalized in
presidential politics with the modern advent of primaries _ they
invented George W. Bush as a national figure.
</P>
<P>
   But they couldn't quite make their support substitute for his
lack of pre-existing national standing. He isn't coasting, money or
no money, endorsements or no endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   If the John McCain phenomenon were happening in the Democratic
Party, it would be running up against the vice presidency and
having a lot more trouble. In the Republican Party, it is running
up against nothing in particular in the realm of presidential
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's credentials in the realm of national leadership aren't
exceptional, either. So there's a fight. But at least it's not in a
smoke-filled room.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Gottlieb is a member of the editorial board of the Dayton
Daily News. He may be reached at (225) 2288 or by e-mail at
martingottlieb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
