<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9692 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RESTAURANTS-BDAY18-CO     02-17 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANTS-BDAY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Happy birthday: Many restaurants singing different tune
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you've ever eaten out, you know the drill: Right in
the middle of your surf-and-turf, some hapless diner is surrounded
by waiters belting out a happy birthday song.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the ``Happy Birthday'' song. Many restaurants have
replaced the century-old original with their own versions, which
have waiters singing a different tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any idea where it came from, but it's official
company policy for us to sing our own birthday song,'' said Janice
Dehnkamp, manager of an Atlanta-area Folks restaurant. ``I think
it's more fun. We sing it off-key on purpose, and then give away a
dessert.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning the company's birthday song is also part of the
training ritual for employees of the Texas-based Metromedia
Restaurant Group, parent company for Bennigan's, Bonanza, Steak and
Ale and Ponderosa.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Chris Barnes said the song was created by employees in
the late '70s, and goes a little something like this: ``Happy,
happy birthday, on this your special day! Happy, happy birthday is
what we're here to say!''
</P>
<P>
   Though it can't be verified, Barnes claims the Bennigan's
version launched a smorgasbord of half-baked imitators at other
restaurant chains. ``I wouldn't say the other restaurants ripped us
off, but we invented it,'' Barnes asserted.
</P>
<P>
   At Macaroni Grill restaurants, classically trained servers
serenade customers with an operatic version called ``Buon
Compleanno'' _ in Italian. The Longhorn Steakhouse version is less
high-falutin'. In keeping with its countrified ambience, Longhorn's
birthday song ends with the poetic lyrics ``hot damn!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our customers wrote it on a napkin, and it just caught
on,'' said Longhorn spokeswoman Pam Davis. ``It fits our concept
and is user-friendly for servers who are too embarrassed to sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally conceptual is Red Lobster's birthday anthem, which ends
with a cheery invitation to: ``Come back soon and eat more fish.''
</P>
<P>
   The story behind the traditional birthday song, penned by
Mildred Hill and her sister Patty Smith Hill in 1893, is a
well-documented piece of American folklore.
</P>
<P>
   The song's longevity is a no-brainer: Everybody has a birthday.
Figuring out why so many pretenders to the throne have surfaced is
a little trickier.
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurateurs say the songs are simply an effective
marketing gimmick that leaves customers with a catchy jingle
ringing in their ears long after they've dined on their
complimentary cupcakes. There's another possible reason, however,
and it involves copyright lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its age, the Hill sisters' original song is still under
copyright, which means if it is performed in a public place _ like
a restaurant _ the owner must pay royalties.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is taken seriously by the American Society of
Composers, Authors and Publishers. The New York licensing agency
collects fees on behalf of Warner/Chappell Music, a Los Angeles
company that holds the song's copyright.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't sue based on one song. But we could,'' said
Vincent Candeloria, licensing director for ASCAP in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Howard, senior lobbyist for the National Restaurant
Association, said most restaurateurs understand they might be on
the hook if ASCAP took them to court for improper use of a song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restaurants that don't want to violate the law have avoided
the whole issue by just coming up with their own songs,'' Howard
said. ``It makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
