<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9693 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV20-C     02-17 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: HOW LONELY IS IT OUT THERE IN CYBERSPACE?
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Feb. 20. By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A half-century-ago, David Riesman, a Yale
sociologist, found in ``The Lonely Crowd'' that Americans had
shifted from lives guided by internal gyroscopes to ones steered by
the currents of peer pressure and the mass media.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Norman Nie, a Stanford political scientist,
released a study that found the Internet fostered social isolation
among Americans, auguring an online society drained of genuine
human relationships and meaningful emotions. Some reports viewed
his findings as a cyber-age update of ``The Lonely Crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Nie sees the Internet as but the latest in a series of
technological upheavals that have served to disconnect people,
allowing them to drift away into the amorphous world of cyberspace.
Such views are at odds with champions of change, who see
information technology as a tool that begets wider democracy,
greater freedoms, improved societal links and better financial
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The recent spate of hacker attacks against the Web proved
traumatic to Internet insiders because they fear people may turn
away from what they perceive to be a blighted medium at the very
point when it appears poised to make a great leaps forward.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Renaissance society never disavowed books, even when
they found them packed with lies and chewed by rats. In our own
times, nearly everybody has a phone, even if it spawns unwanted
calls, and a TV set, even if the fare is often bland.
</P>
<P>
   A more nuanced view of the Web is voiced by Jakob Nielsen, a
transplanted Silicon Valley guru. The mild-mannered Dane came by to
tout his newly published 420-page book, ``Designing Web Usability:
The Practice of Simplicity'' (New Riders), as a tool for making
``the world safe for humans again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a newspaper man who started out in this business not long
after ``The Lonely Crowd'' came out, it wasn't pleasant to hear
Nielsen assert that our ``legacy media'' are doomed when new
hardware arrives, within the decade, that supports full media
integration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why,'' Nielsen asks, ``do you have to choose among (1) seeing
moving images of an event on TV, (2) reading the full story in the
newspaper, or (3) reading a reflective analysis of the underlying
issues in a magazine?''
</P>
<P>
   But Nielsen sees a ``glorious future'' for most folks working in
current formats. ``I believe,'' he writes, ``that this may easily
happen because interactive media are more engaging than passive
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Nie study finds online activity to be essentially
anti-social and, therefore, alienating in nature. By contrast,
Nielsen predicts that an easier-to use Web will usher in a golden
age of communication through its unprecedented many-to-many
approach. ``The current Web,'' he concludes, ``just scratches the
surface relative to what's possible once everybody in the rich
world is connected through a single network.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, it's safe to predict that, on the Web of the
future, both ``The Lonely Crowd'' and the worried Nie update will
be available for most anyone to download or to read on line.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
