<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-CRYSTALRIVER18     02-17 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRYSTALRIVER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crystal River: A home where the manatee roam
 &HT;    By Louis Hillary Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRYSTAL RIVER, Fla. _ With its colonial pillars guarding the
main entrance, the Plantation Inn fights to maintain a certain Old
South dignity, even as ugly strip malls proliferate along nearby
U.S. 19. For the most part, the folks at the inn are succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the lawns and golf villas looked a bit worn and
faded, the public spaces inside the inn are elegant. There are
leather and plush fabrics and two cozy bars _ the sports-oriented
Den and the Library, a more formal watering hole between the
hotel's restaurant and lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The lobby staircase is of the sort that Scarlett O'Hara might
have favored. But fiddle-dee-dee, that's not all. More than a
million dollars' worth of renovations have added freshness to the
large, comfortable rooms. In my room, an armoire (housing a TV) and
multipaned windows gave the feeling of being in a friend's guest
room rather than an inn with 126 rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Located on the Crystal River, the Plantation Inn is not so much
rooms, as it is a base for exploring outdoor activities on what's
called the ``Nature Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a guided fishing tour along the Crystal River or head out
into the Gulf of Mexico for saltwater fishing. You can pack your
own picnic or let your guide prepare lunch for you on one of the
secluded islands.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer swimming with fish to catching them, there's a
full-service dive shop on the grounds that offers instruction and
equipment rental.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular dive trips is to swim or snorkel with
the manatees in the Crystal River. The inn's brochure points out
that the river is home to more manatees than any other spot in
Florida. If you want to see manatees but not be in the water with
them, bring your camera as you walk along the river as it wraps
around the inn.
</P>
<P>
   The sea cows often can be seen meandering in the clear water.
Sit near the gazebo at sunset, and you'll find that the changing
light makes the reflection of each cloud a possible manatee
sighting.
</P>
<P>
   Is that one?
</P>
<P>
   I spotted three, maybe four. Or maybe none.
</P>
<P>
   Boat rentals and guided tours are available at the inn's marina,
allowing you to explore the extensive river system for an hour or a
day. Screw a telephoto lens onto your camera or take along
binoculars and enjoy the enormous variety of birds in the area.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer to stay close to the inn, there are all-weather,
lighted tennis courts, volleyball courts, croquet, shuffleboard and
an 18-hole championship golf course. I favored the golf, which is
within walking distance of the main building even when carrying
your bag. The pro shop is large and well-stocked, and features a
restaurant with decent clubhouse food and a friendly bar.
</P>
<P>
   For more formal dining, try the Plantation Room restaurant in
the main building. It overlooks the river, pool and the poolside
bar _ Alligator Annie's. The service was slow even though only a
few tables were occupied, but the food was worth the quiet wait. My
steak was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   What: The Plantation Inn, 9301 West Fort Island Trail, P.O. Box
1116, Crystal River, FL 34423. Phone: (352) 795-4211 or (800)
632-6262. Web site:
</P>
<P>
   www.plantationinn.com
</P>
<P>
   Basic room rates range from $90-$165; golf packages start at
$186.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
