<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-CLUBS-LIST18-COX     02-17 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CLUBS-LIST1 </SLUG>
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Book club favorites
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' by Arthur Golden: The fictional life
story of Sayuri, a famed geisha, following her childhood in a poor
Japanese fishing village to her rise as Japan's most important
geisha.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Midwives'' by Chris Bohjalian: Follows the life of Vermont
midwife Sybil Danforth through the eyes of her daughter, from
Sybil's life as a hippie through the trial in which she is accused
of killing a mother during an emergency Caesarean delivery.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cold Mountain'' by Charles Frazier: The story of a wounded
Civil War soldier, Inman, who walks away from the war, through the
devastated and soon-to-be-defeated South, and returns home to Ada,
his pre-war sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Reader'' by Bernhard Schlink: A post-World War II novel
about Michael Berg, who as a 15-year-old had an affair with Hanna,
a woman twice his age. Hanna disappears one day and Michael doesn't
see her again until he is a law student observing a trial in
Germany and sees Hanna on the stand being accused of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' by David Guterson: Set in 1954 on
an island near Seattle, this novel follows the trial of a
Japanese-American fisherman accused of murdering a white colleague,
told through the eyes of a journalist covering the trial who is in
love with a Japanese woman.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood'' by Rebecca Wells: A
story about four fiery Louisiana women who, as lifelong friends,
support each other through various situations, particularly the
reverberations on Ya-Ya Vivi Walker after her daughter, Siddalee,
calls Vivi a ``tap-dancing child abuser'' in a New York Times
interview.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Shipping News'' by E. Annie Proulx: A novel about
Quoyle, who returns to Newfoundland with his two daughters after
his wife is killed in a car accident with her lover. He goes to
work for the local newspaper covering shipping news and learns
about his forebears.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Stones from the River'' by Ursula Hegi: The story of Trudi
Montag, a dwarf born to an unstable mother and gentle father in a
tiny Rheinish town before World War I, following her life during
the Weimar Republic and World War II, and her work as
free-spirited, nonconforming town librarian and historian.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``American Pastoral'' by Philip Roth: Narrated by Nathan
Zuckerman, this novel, set in New Jersey during post-World War II
to the mid-1970s, tells the story of Seymour ``The Swede'' Levov
and how his life is affected when his beloved daughter, Merry,
blows up the town post office to protest the Vietnam War, killing a
physician, then disappears deeper into her cause.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Crossing to Safety'' by Wallace Stegner: A novel about two
couples _ Larry and Sally Morgan and Sid and Charity Lang _ who
meet during the Depression in Madison, Wis., following them through
decades of success, devastation and friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9697 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-FORWARD18-COX     02-17 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FORWARD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What if you tried to change the world - and did?
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Simon &AMP; Schuster is betting a lot on
``Pay It Forward,'' and so far the book is living up to their
expectations. The Book of the Month Club has taken it, and Kevin
Spacey, Helen Hunt and Haley Joel Osment are making the movie for
Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   And you can see why, for this is a powerful narrative with an
idealistic idea grounded in familiar characters.
</P>
<P>
   The story: A schoolteacher in a small California town gives his
class an extra-credit project: Come up with an idea that can change
the world.
</P>
<P>
   A boy named Trevor actually does. He devises a chain letter of
deeds _ one person does a nice thing for, say, three people, with
the proviso that they pay it forward, not back _ that is, those
first three each have to do a nice thing for three other people,
those nine each do something nice for another three apiece, and so
forth.
</P>
<P>
   The geometrical implications are obvious; at the 16th level,
about 43 million people are suddenly basking in random acts of
kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor's project doesn't start out well _ the first recipient of
Trevor's goodwill is a con on parole who collapses into recidivism;
the second is an old lady who dies. But just when Trevor is ready
to give up, his idea takes hold, is smelled out by an inquiring
reporter, and a worldwide movememt leads him to the White House and
a beaming Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those modern fables that seek to recapture the
messianic message of Frank Capra, circa ``Meet John Doe'' _ to
convince us that, beneath the vast panoply of avarice and cunning
on daily display, a single human being can make a difference, that
heaven can be right here on Earth. Catherine Ryan Hyde believes the
same thing Anne Frank did: that people are basically good at heart.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with most of these books _ ``The Christmas Box,''
``The Celestine Prophecy'' et al. _ is that they never quite get
where they're going. The ideas may be Capraesque, but the execution
isn't, and neither are the times. They're like Capra, but they're
not Capra.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your own emotional equation and vulnerabilities,
the reader either buys into them or not; questions of literary
quality seldom enter into such decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The characters of ``Pay It Forward'' are all overly familiar
types _ the Vietnam vet whose internal scars are even more horrific
than the external; the harried but well-meaning blue-collar mother;
the cynical, busted journalist _ but what Hyde does with them is
less familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay It Forward'' is much more subtly written than other
inspirational books, with believable dialogue and shadings that
make the characters seem more lifelike than they have any right to
be:
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't sure if he was asleep. She allowed herself to drift
into a feeling, a sense, that she somehow watched all this from
above. Not so much physically, but more in a sense of perspective
... She wondered if she would remember this feeling next time
something seemed, in the short run, to be going wrong. She knew she
probably would not. She knew people transcended that line of
knowledge all the time, but damned if they didn't tend to cross
right back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Until an ending that strikes me as an error in judgment _ let's
just say that Trevor is too rarified for this dirty world, just
like his most illustriously selfless predecessor _ Catherine Ryan
Hyde accomplishes a very difficult job, with an easy, benificent
wisdom about the ways of the world:
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't get,'' one character thinks, ``we see everywhere
we look. What we won't let ourselves do, be, we refuse to tolerate
in any other living soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9698 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-NOMAD18-COX     02-17 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NOMAD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biography follows life on an intrepid traveler
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``One life is an absurdly small
allowance,'' wrote Freya Stark in a letter to a friend in 1929, and
the woman who emerges from this quick-paced biography seems to have
lived hers like a whirling dervish.
</P>
<P>
   Stark was a fascinating, fearless, homely woman, made homelier
by a ghastly accident suffered at age 12, when her long hair was
caught in large, rapidly spinning power wheel in a mill owned by
her stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   Before she could be freed, the remorseless wheel tore off half
her scalp, one of her eyelids and her right ear. She had to wear
her hair brushed over one side of her head for the rest of her
life, to hide the horrible scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I should really have liked, is to be very pretty,'' Stark
confided to a friend. She was ashamed of her plainness, yet it
proved a blessing in disguise: It drove her to excel in the
wilderness, far from domesticity.
</P>
<P>
   She learned Arabic, learned how to use a compass and sextant,
read and wrote voluminously, lived to be 100 and left behind 22
books and eight volumes of letters detailing her journeys to such
places as Luristan, Hadhramaut, Yemen, the Elburz mountains,
Ctesiphon, Baghdad and Oman. Some are still in print, and their
titles are stirring: ``The Valleys of the Assassins,'' ``Dust in
the Lion's Paw,'' ``The Minaret of Djam,'' ``Riding to the Tigris''
and ``The Southern Gates of Arabia.''
</P>
<P>
   She traveled intrepidly, openly, as a woman, often alone,
through Muslim countries where women were little more than
property. She rubbed shoulders with bandits and devil-worshipers
out of the pages of Kipling. She was honored with the gold medal of
the Royal Geographic Society, performed valuable intelligence work
during World War II and championed the rights of Arabs in Palestine
_ views that made her extremely unpopular in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Biographer Jane Geniesse brings Stark thrillingly to life, yet
does not idolize or soft-focus her subject. She peers deeply into
Stark's personal life, bringing out shortcomings as well as
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Stark could be manipulative, jealous, mean-spirited, devious.
She tended to use people as long as they were useful, then drop
them. She was a self-promoter who often overdramatized her
achievements. She was almost never the first explorer to visit a
place, and often she wasn't even the first woman to get there.
Twice, she had to be ingloriously airlifted by the Royal Air Force
out of tight spots she'd gotten herself into.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evacuate! Evacuate! A maiden most immaculate!'' British
officials gibed behind her back.
</P>
<P>
   What Stark was, was a gifted gleaner. She came along in the late
afternoon of the British Empire and vacuumed up the last, rich
crumbs of discovery from regions of the world that had been poorly
mapped, or poorly understood, then made them come brilliantly alive
in trenchant, descriptive prose for armchair travelers back home.
</P>
<P>
   She reminds you, at times, of a female Richard Halliburton or
Lowell Thomas, though smarter and more complex. She was brave,
imaginative, fiercely competitive. Above all she possessed the gift
of firing the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Men found her fascinating, despite her looks. She attracted a
series of older men, scholars, aesthetes, authors, explorers and
businessmen, to act as her patrons and protectors, though when she
finally married, late in life, she chose as her husband a former
diplomat, Stewart Perowne, an agonized, guilt-ridden, closet
homosexual. The marriage lasted only a few months, and Geniesse
describes it with great feeling and understanding for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to feel,'' Stark wrote to a friend after her first few
successful journeys, ``that I had missed the real reason of life by
not marrying, and was out of the stream in a backwater, as it were.
But now I feel this is not so. I think that the human being is just
coming to that point where we are just stepping along into a wider
world, and need not fear being lonely, except in the way that
pioneers are lonely. Life is easier for married people: but I think
it ought to be if anything richer for us, as long as we take it
with full hands and not with the inferiority sense which has often
ruined the lives of spinsters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Though personally,'' she added, ``I would like to be
married.''
</P>
<P>
   If the book has a flaw, it is that it doesn't quote its subject
enough. Geniesse's excerpts from Stark's writings are tantalizing,
enough to make you greedy for more, but too few to satisfy
completely. Rather, she wings through the closing decades of
Stark's life in too great a hurry, disposing of whole journeys and
books in a few lines. The book is very smartly paced throughout,
never a dull moment, but at the end, the pace escalates from smart
to breakneck.
</P>
<P>
   Aged and laden with honors, Stark summed up the rewards and
penalties of longevity in a single, brilliant simile:
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting for death, my dear, is very much like being in an
old-fashioned steam train, setting out on a journey. You let down
the window by a leather strap, and your friends are on the platform
waving goodbye. And then the blasted train doesn't move.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
