A9699 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MILNER18-COX     02-17 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turow providing competition to other `lawyer fiction'
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most authors of popular suspense and mystery novels seem to be
written by lawyers these days. Some are better than others, and of
course, some are worse. But they both seem to be selling well, so
it's no surprise that lawyers from coast to coast are trying their
wits and self-discipline at fiction.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about it, this should come as no surprise.
Lawyers are closely related to fiction writers as well as actors in
temperament and inclinations. In other words they're full of B.S.
and, if an audience gathers, can turn into extroverts regardless of
their private personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most widely known and maybe most popular
lawyer/novelist today is John Grisham, despite the fact that many
critics denounce his work as unworthy of serious consideration. I'm
not one of those. His stories keep me reading and that's one way to
judge good writing, in my opinion. Not the only way by any means,
but one of several to measure what someone has managed to put on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   But my favorite lawyer/novelists are Scott Turow and Robert K.
Tanenbaum. Both are head and shoulders above Grisham in most every
way you should judge a writer.
</P>
<P>
   Turow has recently come out with a new novel titled ``Personal
Injuries'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux). It's his fifth and, at
least at the present time (having just finished reading it), I rate
it as his best, although ``Burden of Proof'' and ``Presumed
Innocent'' are excellent, too. Well, heck, they're all excellent.
</P>
<P>
   As are all Turow's stories (and most of the other stories by
lawyer/writers), ``Personal Injuries'' is about the practice of law
and those who do it for a living. Probably the one thing, if there
is only one thing, that sets Turow's books apart from the others by
his fellow lawyer/writers are his characters. His books, that is to
say, are character-driven rather than plot-driven _ not that the
plots are weak. They aren't, but they usually have more to do with
the strengths and weaknesses of the characters than such stuff as
action and physical suspense. There's plenty of suspense, but most
of it, almost all of it in fact, is psychological and moral
suspense. How will the people you've come to know so well and care
for so much react when the chips are really down? How will they
respond to this or that temptation or action?
</P>
<P>
   In ``Personal Injuries'', Robbie Feaver (pronounced ``favor'')
is a highly successful personal injury lawyer. He is a womanizer
with a wife who has an incurable illness and grows weaker by the
day. He has a secret bank account where he sometimes deposits money
that makes its way to the pockets of judges who decide Robbie's
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie is busted by a special government task force and, in
exchange for a promise of leniency, agrees to wear a wire as he
goes about the business of fixing his upcoming court decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a jerk and crook? The truth is the reader and FBI
agent, female, assigned to stick close to him to make certain he
does what he's supposed to do and doesn't blow his cover, slowly
learns to love the guy. Like the characters in the old Kris
Kristofferson song, he's a walking contradiction, partly truth and
partly fiction.
</P>
<P>
   This book is primarily Robbie's story, but it's almost equally
the story of Evon, the FBI agent whose life is changed forever by
her association with Robbie, but not in the way you'll assume in
the earlier stages of the story.
</P>
<P>
   I recommend this one without hesitation or reservations. If you
love finely tuned provocative writing, this one's for you.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
