r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN18-COX     02-17 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush prefers big picture, delegating the details
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When he first ran for governor in 1994, George
W. Bush made the campaign appearances. But most of the campaign
nuts and bolts were delegated to key aides: political guru Karl
Rove, campaign manager Joe Allbaugh, press aide Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush became governor, Allbaugh became chief of staff and
Hughes, communications director. Rove directed Bush's political
operation as a consultant but spent a lot of time at the Capitol.
The trio became known as ``The Iron Triangle.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was the big-picture guy, his staffers say, sitting in on
policy meetings. But he delegated most details of pet issues, such
as tax cuts, and all of the details of smaller ones not on his
priority list. Meanwhile, the governor pursued ``retail''
one-on-one politicking with legislators, using his prominence and
engaging personality to push his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has the same approach and same people in charge in his
presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, there's not any difference,'' said Allbaugh.
``Basically, he still sets the agenda and figures out the broad
goal that he's trying to achieve and directs staff to implement it.
That hasn't changed one bit, and it's been very successful for the
past six years that I've been lucky enough to be with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas at Austin government
professor and presidential scholar, wonders how much is Bush and
how much is his handlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the evidence that I can see seems to be that he delegates
to a degree that it's hard for me to see where his advisers end and
he begins,'' Buchanan said. ``It looks like a group project, and
it's hard to find evidence of his guiding hand. ... Other people
put words in his mouth all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's defeat by Arizona Sen. John McCain in New Hampshire's GOP
primary Feb. 1 shocked people inside and outside government who had
endorsed Bush The Inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were suggesting that what he should do when he got
whipped in New Hampshire was to fire a bunch of people,'' Buchanan
said. ``And he didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush, who believes in loyalty, consulted with the same
trusted staffers _ plus Mark McKinnon, who did TV ads in his 1998
re-election and is back for the big race. They retooled his
campaign to make him The Reformer With Results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hires people that he believes in and trusts, and then he
delegates,'' said McKinnon. ``He doesn't micro-manage. He invests a
lot of trust and faith in people to do their job, but he expects
them to do it well, and he expects results.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he very much empowers people, and there is also not a lot
of second-guessing,'' McKinnon said. Bush is personally secure, so
``when things don't go well, there's not a lot of finger-pointing
and blame.''
</P>
<P>
   And so now the cautious campaign that had tried to keep the Bush
message focused on a few issues like tax cuts and compassionate
conservatism has decided it has no choice but to copy McCain's more
open-ended town-hall approach.
</P>
<P>
   Now the nation will see if Bush the Delegator can show enough
substance to compare well to Senate veteran McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he's taking more questions, he's not as free-floating
by any means as John McCain,'' said Buchanan. ``He doesn't wing it
that much.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush was combative in Tuesday's CNN debate, at times
he looked frantic and desperate against McCain's seasoned debate
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Allbaugh insists Bush's delegative style isn't a campaign
defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's a very quick study,'' Allbaugh said. ``And the
volume of material he riffles through is just so large that I don't
believe that's a hindrance at all. The American public wants a
president to be as widely versed in as many issues as possible, but
I think they also understand that a president can't be an expert on
every issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're mainly interested in an individual who can
make good decisions based on sound judgment. And I would point to
the governor's last five years as Texas' chief executive officer as
the best preparation to become the president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The retooled Bush will find in the next few days whether he can
convince enough voters of that.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
