<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-AGING-PLAYER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Better late than never: Man plays college basketball at 32
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Baldwin was in Kitzinger, Germany, serving his
country as a member of the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   Future Lincoln County High basketball star Antonio Henderson was
a first-grader whose travel experiences had not yet included the
big city of Atlanta, some 120 miles west of his Lincolnton
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a decade and a half later, Henderson and Baldwin _
separated by 12 years and distinctive mindsets _ are together as
peers on the basketball team at Atlanta Metropolitan College.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Henderson, 20, one of the nation's leading
junior-college scorers with a 26-point average, who is the veteran
in organized basketball experience.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Henderson, a sophomore guard, says about Baldwin, ``He
brings a lot of maturity and continuity to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played the game in the high school because back then I
wasn't interested,'' Baldwin said. ``I was not the player type, but
I could talk the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Since those days at Tuskegee (Ala.) Institute High in the
mid-1980s, the son of a career military man has gone through many
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin, 32, is married and the father of three. He is studying
computer engineering while he continues his military connection
through the Army Reserve. He hopes to reap full retirement benefits
in six or seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I joined the Army in November of '85,'' said Baldwin, who was
following the lead of his father, Melvin, a missile expert. ``I got
interested in basketball after I got to Germany in June of '86. I
was a tank mechanic and when I wasn't fixing tanks, I was in the
gym. There was nothing else to do at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 5 and 190 pounds, Baldwin, still a teen-ager, found
that he had ``game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pickup basketball, then company league and
tournaments,'' he said. ``I found out that I pretty much had what
it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin continued to play frequently, even after marrying a
former Texas-El Paso track star in October 1991 while stationed at
Fort Bliss in Texas. And when daughters DeJonee, now 8, and Renee,
4, and son Michael Jr., 3, came along, Baldwin's interest in
basketball waned only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my experience in Germany, I began to wonder if I could
play at a college, any college,'' Baldwin said. ``To me, it really
didn't matter who I'd play for. I just wanted to be able to say
that at least I got a chance to play college ball for one year.''
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of wife Demetrice, who assured him that she
would give him full support, Baldwin decided in the fall to try out
for the team at Atlanta Metropolitan College. He already was taking
courses there, hoping to enroll later at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hesitant at first, but I told him to go for it, because
if he didn't he might regret it the rest of his life,'' said
Demetrice, who competed in the 400 meters, long jump and triple
jump at UTEP.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really encouraging,'' said Baldwin, who moved his
family to Atlanta three years ago. ``She told me to just go out and
do what I had been doing on the court for the last 10 or 11
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin, competing for a spot against players years younger, was
impressive enough to make the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lively body and he's extremely quick on his feet _
really talented for a guy who is 32 years old,'' Atlanta Metro
coach Robert Pritchett said. ``But what impressed me most was his
intensity. At his age, it's got to be his love for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said, ``We look at him, and we know when to stop
kidding around and get serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin acknowledges that, 20 games into his first and perhaps
last season as a college player, he is still trying to find his
place. Never mind that he has averaged seven rebounds and six
points while playing 25 minutes per game. A comfort zone on the
court has been elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't found my niche yet,'' he said. ``So I really
try to do the little things _ like take the charge, dive for the
loose ball and battle for every rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be construed as the downside of Baldwin's college
basketball experience. Part of the upside is the Baldwin cheering
section.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three of the children can't wait to get to the gym on game
nights,'' Demetrice said. ``The most excited is Michael Jr., who
makes sure that everybody knows that that's his daddy on the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin said, ``I really thought it would be tough juggling
athletics, class work, fatherhood and wifehood. But it's been a lot
of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And inspiration, Pritchett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see a young family with that kind of togetherness and
commitment is quite refreshing,'' Pritchett said. ``It really
doesn't matter whether or not Michael plays after this season. The
kind of person he is, especially with his family, will probably
have a big impact on the rest of the players on the team a long way
down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
