r t BC-FLA-GOLF18-COX     02-17 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-GOLF18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appealing options to swing (the clubs) on Nature Coast
 &HT;    By Louis Hillary Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CITRUS SPRINGS, Fla. _ If you want to play a devil of a golf
course, El Diablo is the place to go.
</P>
<P>
   Recently chosen by Golf Digest magazine as the No. 1 New
(Affordable) Course in America, El Diablo is 7,045 yards of
perfectly manicured fairways that undulate through the piney woods
like a rattlesnake on the prowl. Smooth and deliberate. And silent.
Situated in this tiny Central Florida hamlet with almost no
development around the course, El Diablo is as pristine and
beautiful as it is challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely critical as to what people see when they come
in here,'' says course superintendent and assistant manager Don
Maidlow, who built the first 27 holes at the ultra-exclusive Black
Diamond Ranch in nearby Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   But El Diablo is not the only quality course vacationers can
play in the area. Golden Ocala, just northwest of its namesake
city, has plenty of challenges of its own, plus borrows a few from
other, more famous courses including Augusta National, St. Andrews
and Baltusrol.
</P>
<P>
   Both courses are within an hour's drive of Crystal River and the
Plantation Inn. If you don't want to drive, the inn has a
well-staffed and maintained par 72 championship course that plays
host annually to the Florida Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a nine-hole executive course used by the teaching
pros at The Original Golf School, which makes its winter home at
the inn. Led by Jay Morelli, named the New England PGA Teacher of
the Year, the school prides itself on a 4-to-1 pro to student
ratio.
</P>
<P>
   While the pros at the Plantation Inn may teach weekend golfers a
better swing, El Diablo can teach humility to even
low-handicappers, but with six tees, the course can be a
comfortable fit for almost any level of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cater to the ladies,'' says Maidlow, who has planted 26,000
azaleas among the high rolling hills that give depth to some holes
and hilltop views to others.
</P>
<P>
   From the red tees, El Diablo plays at 5,144 yards, almost 2,000
yards shorter than from the gold. I played from the whites (6,232
yards) and it still was plenty of golf course, but a fair one.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Jim Fazio, older brother of the more famous Tom, the
course does not blind you with doglegs or force you to carry acres
of water to reach fairways. In fact, there is water on only one
hole, the signature 11th _ a 392-yard, uphill par 4. Instead,
Fazio, who also designed the new Trump International course in West
Palm Beach, used the natural contours of the rolling land and
well-placed native-sand waste bunkers to make this a thinker's
course.
</P>
<P>
   More of a rear-back-and-hit-it course, Golden Ocala has a layout
that can be overpowered by big hitters. With fairways that leave
room for error, the attraction of the 6,735-yard course is a chance
to play some holes the average golfer likely will never lay eyes on
except on television.
</P>
<P>
   Hole 6 replicates Augusta's 16th, and 11 and 12 are copies of 12
and 13 _ the Amen Corner of the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest hole on the course is No. 15, a copy of the fourth
hole at Baltusrol _ a 209-yard par 3. Hitting from an elevated tee,
you must carry a wide pond then hold the ball on a narrow green.
</P>
<P>
   After playing El Diablo or Golden Ocala, give yourself a break
and tee off at the Plantation Inn course.
</P>
<P>
   While beautifully maintained, it is typical of older Florida
coastal courses _ flat, short (6,161 yards from the white tees),
with tightly grouped fairways and greens. Water is the course's
biggest challenge, with hazards guarding 14 holes.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   El Diablo Golf &AMP; Country Club: 10405 N. Sherman Drive, Citrus
Springs, Fla. 34434 (just off U.S. 41 south of Dunnellon). Phone:
(352) 465-0986. Current rates: $29-$49
</P>
<P>
   Golden Ocala: Off U.S. 27, approximately 4 miles west of
Interstate 75 in Ocala. Phone: (352) 622-2245. Current rates:
$29-$49
</P>
<P>
   Plantation Inn Golf Shop: 9301 W. Fort Island Trail, P.O. Box
1116, Crystal River, Fla. 34423. Phone: (800) 632-6262. Web site:
www.plantationinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Current rates: $24-$42.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
