<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9703 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MODELS-FAVORITES18-CO     02-17 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODELS-FAVORITES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gisele a favorite, but new crop of models set fashion runways
aflame
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the fall fashion shows wrapped up in Bryant Park
last week, we polled a dozen front-row habitues about which models
they favored and why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gisele, Gisele, Gisele. Who doesn't love Gisele?'' said
Glamour's Suzanne Yalof. (After a week of watching, editors get to
know models on a first-name basis _ that's how they're referred to
in the designer's program note.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Who couldn't be in love with Gisele?'' echoed Andre Leon
Talley of Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-brainer _ Gisele by far,'' said Linda Wells of
Allure. ``Aren't you going to get the same answer from everyone?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no. While the tanned, curvy cover girl, also the
hands-down favorite of photographers, topped almost everyone's
list, her skyrocketing fees meant she was seen far less this season
than last.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers reported that she stormed out of the Helmut Lang show
when the designer downgraded her number of appearances. Stephanie
Seymour and Claudia Schiffer, in rare runway showings, had to pick
up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   At other shows, lesser-known models stepped in her place.
``Gisele is amazing,'' said Evyan Metzner of Mademoiselle. ``But
she's everywhere, so it's nice to see new girls.''
</P>
<P>
   While they're all super-tall, downright skinny and blessed with
perfectly symmetrical features, what the models-with-the-mostest
share is their individuality. A trademark expression. A quirk of
personality that's communicated without a word. Simple stage
presence that never upstages the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   A look that says, again and again, ``Look at me.... And love
what I'm wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BOMBSHELL
</P>
<P>
   With a voluptuous figure that makes her stand out as a
well-nourished woman in a field of anemic-looking little girls,
Gisele Bundchen comes across as pure force of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``She radiates a light and optimism and sexuality,'' says
Vogue's Talley. ``And her body is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Ralph Lauren tapped her to wear a gold mesh bikini
top and gold leather skirt for Fashion Week. And Donna Karan
dressed her in a stretchy red halter dress. She's stayed busy the
rest of the year with back-to-back covers for Vogue, W and Harper's
Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   It's her curvaceous body, though, that sends designers
scurrying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designers tend to save their va-va-va-voom looks for her,''
says Cindy Weber Cleary of InStyle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   THE GROUNDBREAKER
</P>
<P>
   When she debuted several seasons ago, Sudan-born Alek Wek
changed standards of what was considered beautiful. Her distinctly
African features _ cherubic cheeks, broad nose and full lips _ and
coal-black skin stood out in a field of WASP-y American models. And
Alek's hair is cropped so short she almost appears bald.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dumbfounded at BCBG when she came out with hair,'' says
trend forecaster Tom Julian, who chose her as a favorite (Wek wore
a wig for the show). ``The clothes work for her, and she works for
the clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Talley says, ``She's broken barriers not only of color but of
beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Alek has worked for Gucci, Fendi, Galliano and Chanel, and has
inked contracts with Clinique and Moschino.
</P>
<P>
   (The scuttlebutt during Fashion Week was whether Alek has had
liposuction. Her formerly prominent behind is flatter now, but some
think it's just hard work at the gym.)
</P>
<P>
   THE NEXT BIG THING
</P>
<P>
   Like Gisele, Caroline Ribiero hails from Brazil, and she is
being heralded as the new face to watch. She's 5-foot-11,
swizzle-stick thin and with a face that can look sultry in one
show, regal in the next, and girl-next-door in the third.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike some mannequins, it's impossible to mistake Caroline
for anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her kind of exotic looks,'' says celebrity stylist
Phillip Bloch.
</P>
<P>
   She has a face that resists easy categorization, he says.
``She's undefinable, and that's what I think is so beautiful about
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
