<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9704 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-SPACE18-COX     02-17 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SPACE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Competition rocketing in Hollywood as studios seek galactic
blockbusters
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Forget the United States and Russia. The space
race is between Disney and Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   More than three decades after the Cold War contest to put the
first man on the moon, the rival studios are battling to land the
first of two big Mars movies in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The dueling dramas _ Disney's ``Mission to Mars'' and Warners'
``Red Planet'' _ follow a tradition that in recent years has seen
competing films about asteroids (``Armageddon,'' ``Sudden
Impact''), volcanos (``Dante's Peak,'' ``Volcano''), Olympic runner
Steve Prefontaine (``Prefontaine,'' ``Without Limits'') and
computer-animated insects (``A Bug's Life,'' ``Antz'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission to Mars'' and ``Red Planet'' are just the first two
Mars-related movie projects cleared by Hollywood mission control.
Directors James Cameron (``Titanic'') and John Carpenter
(``Halloween'') also have Mars films in the works.
</P>
<P>
   A host of other space-themed films are also set to blast into
theaters this year, as studios attempt to cash in on the public's
fascination with the 1997 Mars Sojourner mission and the success of
blockbusters such as ``Apollo 13'' and ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch Black,'' a sci-fi horror movie about nasty nocturnal
aliens, opens today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' will star Clint Eastwood and Tommy Lee Jones
as retired astronauts called back into service, a la John Glenn.
John Travolta and Garry Shandling will play extraterrestrials in
``Battlefield Earth'' and ``What Planet Are You From?'',
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Disney-Warners race, ``Mission to Mars'' will touch
down first on March 10. Director Brian De Palma reportedly
delivered the sci-fi adventure, which stars Tim Robbins and Gary
Sinise, two months ahead of schedule. It was originally slated for
summer release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Planet,'' starring Val Kilmer and Tom Sizemore, was
rumored to be rocketing to an even earlier launch date. Instead,
its release was recently pushed back to Nov. 10 from June 16.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mars movies deal with the first manned missions to Earth's
nearest neighboring planet and subsequent rescue attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Like NASA's real-life Mars missions, both have faced their share
of setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   De Palma stepped in when ``Mission to Mars''' original director,
Gore Verbinski (``Mouse Hunt''), departed over budget concerns.
Actress Connie Nielsen (``The Devil's Advocate'') replaced Monica
Potter (``Patch Adams''), who abandoned her astronaut suit for the
lead role in a romantic comedy, ``Head Over Heels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Planet,'' the feature debut of commercial director Antony
Hoffman, lost the NASA approval it shared with ``Mission to Mars''
in a dispute over a murder scene. Prickly stars Kilmer and Sizemore
have been feuding, according to set reports posted by Survive Mars,
a Web site devoted to the production of both films, as well as
Cameron's.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy Award-winning ``Titanic'' director is producing a
television miniseries and a short IMAX 3-D movie, which he will
direct, for 2001. Both of Cameron's projects deal with the first
manned mission to Mars _ and a subsequent rescue attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter is in pre-production on ``Ghosts of Mars,'' also due
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick countdown of this year's space movies. As with
NASA missions, launch dates are subject to change.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pitch Black''
</P>
<P>
   Director: David Twohy
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Vin Diesel, Radha Mitchell, Cole Hauser, Keith David.
</P>
<P>
   Having learned nothing from ``Alien'' and ``Starship Troopers,''
space pilot Fry (Mitchell) crash-lands her vessel on a seemingly
uninhabited planet. The survivors include a lawman (Hauser) and his
murderous prisoner (Diesel). They must all band together once the
planet's sun goes down and its nocturnal inhabitants emerge. (Opens
today.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What Planet Are You From?''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Mike Nichols
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Garry Shandling, Annette Bening, John Goodman, Greg
Kinnear.
</P>
<P>
   Shandling (HBO's ``The Larry Sanders Show'') co-wrote this
battle-of-the-sexes comedy, in which he stars as an alien sent to
Earth to impregnate a woman (Bening) to perpetuate his all-male
race. His E.T. proves to be as inept at human courting and mating
as the typical earthling. (March 3)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mission to Mars''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Brian De Palma
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Tim Robbins, Gary Sinise, Don Cheadle, Connie Nielsen,
Jerry O'Connell.
</P>
<P>
   When the first manned mission to Mars meets with a mysterious
disaster, a rescue mission is launched to investigate the tragedy
and bring back any survivors. As the Toronto Star put it, ``It's
pretty clear De Palma has decided to stop ripping off Hitchcock for
once so that he can remake Kubrick's `2001: A Space Odyssey.'''
(March 10)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Battlefield Earth''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Roger Christian
</P>
<P>
   Cast: John Travolta, Barry Pepper, Forest Whitaker, Kim Coates,
Kelly Preston.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta, a noted Scientologist, stars as the leader of an evil
alien race on a quest for global domination in this sci-fi thriller
based on a novel by Church of Scientology founder L. Ron Hubbard.
Pepper (``Saving Private Ryan'') plays a young man who leaves his
desolate home high in the Rocky Mountains to take a final,
courageous stand. (May 5)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Space Cowboys''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Clint Eastwood
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Clint Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, Donald Sutherland, James
Garner, James Cromwell.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood and Jones spike their Tang with Geritol and blast off
for adventure as two aging NASA veterans recommissioned for one
last mission. Eastwood reportedly rejected the film's premise
before John Glenn's 1998 return to space at age 77, fearing that no
one would believe the notion of a senior citizen going into space.
(Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Red Planet''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Antony Hoffman
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Val Kilmer, Carrie-Anne Moss, Tom Sizemore, Benjamin
Bratt, Simon Baker, Terence Stamp.
</P>
<P>
   A team of U.S. astronauts, not sporting the NASA logo, makes the
first manned expedition to Mars in an attempt to colonize the
planet. When their equipment suffers life-threatening damage, the
crew struggles for survival on the hostile surface of Mars,
reportedly fighting each other _ and killer space worms. (Nov. 16)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
