<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I have an addiction.
Actually, I have several, but let's not go there. I have become
obsessed with ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire.'' I rarely miss an
episode. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches
Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ George W. Bush is the big-picture guy as Texas
governor, his staffers say, sitting in on policy meetings. But he
delegated most details of pet issues. Meanwhile, the governor
pursued ``retail'' one-on-one politicking with legislators, using
his prominence and engaging personality to push his priorities.
Bush has the same approach and same people in charge in his
presidential run. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Bush can still win in South
Carolina. The abdication of the hunt by Steve Forbes may be his
saving grace. Should Bush win the nomination, however, he has some
groveling to do to get back to the center. (John Young is opinion
page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GOTTLIEB-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ For a while there, this
political season was upsetting the best _ and one of most unknown _
rules of presidential politics. To wit, presidential nomination
fights are about credentials. (Gottlieb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
