<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, February
18, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANTS-BDAY _ Restaurants love to celebrate patrons'
birthdays. Oddly, though, many don't like to sing ``Happy
Birthday.'' One reason is that the venerable song is still
copyrighted, and restaurants could be sued. Another is that they
like to come up with theme songs for their own chains; Longhorn
Steakhouse's song ends with ``hot damn!'' and Red Lobster's
finishes with ``come back soon and eat more fish.'' (Harris,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 26. WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CROATIA _ DUBROVNIK, Croatia _ Dubrovnik's claim to fame
and its ``crowning jewel'' are the city walls. Old Dubrovnik is
surrounded by 1,940-meter-long walls built between the 11th and
17th centuries. Today the main purpose of the walls is to provide
visitors a glimpse of a history. (Keller, Dayton Daily News
freelancer; not for use outside Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Part of Lindsay Keller's ``Semester at Sea'' reports.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0215 -- Even an aunt's warning wasn't enough to
keep two slick pickpockets from victimizing an American tourist on
holiday. (Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes one
4-column color illustration of a tourist being pickpocketed in Rome
and a 1-column color photo of the author showing what he was
wearing when he was robbed.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TIPS BOX -- How to prevent being victimized by theft while
on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MARDI GRAS PREVIEW -- New Orleans' annual bash is all set
for the hardiest partyers. (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
Art includes a 2-column color photo from Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- The Windy City is acknowledging Black
History Month with exhibitions, performances and other events.
(N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   JSO-ANNIVERSARY _ For the Jacksonville Symphony Orchestra, a
golden anniversary means a golden opportunity. Between Tuesday and
March 5, travelers to the city can partake of a banquet of concerts
by the JSO and visiting ensembles, including the Minnesota
Orchestra (Thursday-Friday) in a first-ever stop by a major
symphony to the area. Those same days, on street corners and in
workplaces and schools throughout the city, JSO musicians in small
ensembles will offer a series of informal chamber concerts called
``Art Attacks.''(Green, Atlanta Journal-Constitutution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRYSTALRIVER _ CRYSTAL RIVER, Fla. _ With its colonial
pillars guarding the main entrance, the Plantation Inn fights to
maintain a certain Old South dignity, even as ugly strip malls
proliferate along nearby U.S. 19. For the most part, the folks at
the inn are succeeding. (Park, Palm Beach Post). 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLA-GOLF _ A tour of excellent and affordable golf course on
Florida's Nature Coast. (Park, Palm Beach Post). 18. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-CENTERPIECE
</P>
<P>
   MODELS-FAVORITES _ NEW YORK _ As the fall fashion shows wrapped
up in Bryant Park last week, we polled a dozen front-row habitues
about which models they favored and why. ``Gisele, Gisele, Gisele.
Who doesn't love Gisele?'' said Glamour's Suzanne Yalof. (After a
week of watching, editors get to know models on a first-name basis
_ that's how they're referred to in the designer's program note.)
``Who couldn't be in love with Gisele?'' echoed Andre Leon Talley
of Vogue. (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-TV _ A look at the flap over ABC, NBC, CBS and Fox's
agreement with the minority coalition led by the NAACP. If the
formula holds, the NBC agreement could mean as few as 5 minorities
added to the staffs of second season shows. I'll do a reality check
on this half-assed attempt at affirmative action and see what some
minority writer-producers think about the situation in Hollywood.
(Holloway, Austin American-Statesman). 50.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   BACKSTREETBOYS _ A look at the Backstreet Boys and how modern
rock got in its current state. How did a manufactured group like BB
get so popular? (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   FILMTRILOGY-SOUTHERNLIT _ In some ways, the premiere of Ross
Spears' documentary trilogy ``Tell About the South: Voices in Black
and White'' may be the most significant film event in Atlanta since
``Gone With the Wind.'' Narrated by former U.S. Poet Laureate Rita
Dove, the series tells the story of Southern literature from its
revival in 1915 to the present. Featured are never-before-seen
interviews with Eudora Welty, Alice Walker, Shelby Foote, Reynolds
Price, Pat Conroy, William Styron, C. Vann Woodward and others. The
films will be shown at Georgia State University on Feb. 26 and are
free and open to the public. We preview the films and talk with
filmmaker Spears about this ambitious project. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 36.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Feb. 20.
</P>
