<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE (San Francisco) _ Opponents of a ballot initiative
to ban gay marriages in California launch their TV ad campaign by
taking on state Sen. Pete Knight, whose name the measure bears.
``Pete Knight, the California politician behind Prop. 22, may not
like it that his son is gay. But he shouldn't make us vote on his
private problem,'' says the ad. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-DIVERSITY (San Francisco) _ Student leaders at the
University of California at Berkeley have joined student body
presidents at other Pacific-10 Conference schools to urge their
campus administrators to increase minority enrollment. By ANNIE
NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-N.Y.-REPUBLICANS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Frustrated by what he
calls a ``pattern of pandering'' by George W. Bush, Rep. Peter King
(R-N.Y.), says he is ``seriously reconsidering'' his support for
the GOP presidential front-runner. Moreover, a ``significant''
number of New York Republicans also are quietly questioning Bush's
viability in the presidential race, says King. By LARA JAKES
</P>
<P>
   NEW-BUSH (San Francisco) _ He offers campaign finance reform. He
does town hall meetings to get close to voters. He comes off as a
political pugilist. He says he's a reformer and an outsider who
challenges the status quo. Is this U.S. Sen. John McCain? No, it's
the newly revamped Texas Gov. George W. Bush preparing for the big
Republican primaries in California and other major states March 7.
By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NICARAGUA-DEMOCRACY (Managua, Nicaragua) _ Daniel Ortega, the
unrepentant Marxist and nemesis of President Ronald Reagan, is
getting his nose powdered as a Canadian film crew prepares to
interview him. But the former Nicaraguan revolutionary leader and
president is fidgety and uncomfortable. For him, the revolution
that he lost in a democratic election in 1990 is all too recent. By
SUSANA HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   NICARAGUA-ENVOY (Managua, Nicaragua) _ Oliver P. Garza, a former
drug enforcement agent and veteran diplomat, was named U.S.
ambassador to Nicaragua last fall. The native Texan quickly delved
into the subtle _ and not-so-subtle _ predicaments and complex
politics of this emerging democracy mired in poverty. By SUSANA
HAYWARD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-STEPSISTER (Undated) _ Gregpru Maguire's new book,
``Confessions of an Ugly Stepsister,'' offers a retelling of the
Cinderella story. The tale, set against a backdrop of Holland in
the 17th century, is one of deception, beauty, enchantment and luck
as an impoverished widow and her two daughters are taken in by a
Flemish painter. By GLORIA MAZURE.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-JUDDS (Undated) _ The Judds _ mom Naomi and daughter
Wynona _ have reunited and are on the road once again. By MICHAEL
C. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MISS-JULIE (Los Angeles) _ Director Mike Figgis and the
actors of ``Miss Julie,'' which opens Friday, discuss turning the
play into a movie. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Reviews of ``The Story of Us'' and
``The Muse,'' which are being released on videotape. By BRUCE
WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-LONELINESS (San Francisco) _ The Internet ``has the
potential to become our tyranny of loneliness,'' says Norman Nie, a
Stanford University political scientist who helped conduct the
study that shows that the computer revolution could be turning us
into workaholic shut-ins. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-LAPTOP (San Francisco) _ Apple Computer Co. Chief
Executive Officer Steve Jobs has unveiled some tweaks to the
Cupertino-based computer maker's product line at a Tokyo
conference, including the debut of a new, gray-hued, beefier iBook
consumer laptop. This iBook has double the memory and hard-drive
size of the previous model. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   LEARNLINK (North Greenbush, N.Y.) _ LearnLinc Corp., a North
Greenbush distance-learning software company, has announced that it
is being acquired by Gilat Communications for about $39 million in
stock. LearnLinc, one of the fastest growing software companies in
the Albany region, is the third company to be acquired in as many
months by the Israel-based company. By DANIELLE T. FURFARO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ We are watching ``Ally McBeal''
and trying (as we always do) not to talk to the TV screen. We watch
``Ally'' now and then because it is a phenomenon. Its characters,
plot lines, special effects and peculiar buzzwords have become a
major part of the national cultural fabric. We do not watch it
because it resonates for us personally. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
