<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKI-VACATION-ART-BOS &LR;      02-17 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-VACATION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THERE'S LOTS MORE THAN SKIING AROUND THOSE SLOPES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WENDY FOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who says a ski vacation is only about skiing? Or about skiing at
all?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in the old days folks headed north just to strap on the
boards and point downhill, but that was before fitness clubs, hot
tubs, snowshoeing, and, yes, computerized indoor golf courses.
(Read on.)
</P>
<P>
   With the right planning, there's no need to ski at all on a ski
vacation, unless you really want to. Put another way, if you're
taking several days to ski with the family next week during school
vacation, there's plenty to do for all ages besides actually skiing
downhill.
</P>
<P>
   For example, virtually all major ski areas in New England, and
many minor ones as well, offer cross-country skiing. Killington,
Okemo, and Sugarbush in Vermont, Waterville Valley and Sunapee in
New Hampshire, Sunday River in Maine, and Wachusett in
Massachusetts, to name only a few, all have cross-country trails
and equipment rentals, if not right at the slopes, then nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Trail fees range up to about $15, with another $15 or so for
daily equipment rental.
</P>
<P>
   Most areas also have snowshoes for rent, and for that, one
doesn't even need a trail. Often, you can find little headlamps to
light the way through fields and woods during night snowshoe treks.
Rentals are usually about the same price as cross-country skis.
</P>
<P>
   Ice rinks abound, and fitness clubs are everywhere with workout
rooms, pools, hot tubs and daily membership fees. Sugarbush Health
and Racket Club, for example, (802-583-6300) charges $13 a day for
use of the pool, weight room, indoor and outdoor hot tubs, steam
and sauna rooms. Court time for tennis, racquetball, and squash is
$20 an hour, but then they knock the daily fee down to $9.
</P>
<P>
   Tubing on the slopes after the lifts close (free some places, as
much as $5 at others) is gaining ground as well, and nearly every
place has horse-drawn sleigh rides and hayrides. At Waterville
Valley, for example, sleigh rides leaving from the village square
are $10 for those 13 and older, $5 for younger children, and free
for the youngest children sitting on a parent's lap. (603-236-8175)
</P>
<P>
   At Stratton, weekend sleigh rides (adults, $17; children, $12;
under 2, free) include a bonfire with hot chocolate and s'mores.
(802-297-9210).
</P>
<P>
   Then there's golf. Really. Okemo just opened an astoundingly
high-tech Winter Indoor Golf Academy (802-228-1396) with an array
of virtual-reality gizmos, including a 700-square-foot indoor
putting green complete with undulations and breaks; a computerized,
full-swing simulator so you can pretend to play all the fancy
courses (try matching Tiger Woods's 31 on the back nine at Pebble
Beach); and a three-dimensional, computerized system to analyze,
and correct, your swing.
</P>
<P>
   According to Okemo spokeswoman Pam Cruickshank, the Vermont
resort joins Arizona, Florida, and Puerto Rico as the only spots in
the country with a setup like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many people are crossovers,'' says
Cruickshank. ``They're skiers and they're golfers, too. A lot of
people ski during the day, and then go to the golf course, play a
round of golf, and go out to dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   The simulator rents for $50 an hour, which can be split among
several golfers. Private lessons and clinics also are available.
All ages welcome.
</P>
<P>
   At the Balsams Wilderness resort, way up in New Hampshire near
the Canadian border, you could spend an entire ski vacation
indoors. (603-255-3400).
</P>
<P>
   Most people stay at the Balsams hotel, as there aren't many
options nearby. First-run movies show nightly in the hotel's
250-seat theater. Wine tastings and cooking demonstrations are
regular affairs. Several furnished fireplace areas provide what
Balsams spokeswoman Bonnie Clymer calls ``cozy nooks'' for reading
or playing board games. Ping-Pong and billiards are popular in the
game room.
</P>
<P>
   All the indoor activities, plus ice skating on a lighted rink
and snowshoeing, are included for those paying the $150-$170 per
person, per night, double occupancy room rate. (Children are $9 per
night, multiplied by their age.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We find half our guests come here and don't ski,'' says
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   Killington opened an indoor climbing wall this year at Snowshed
lodge for all ages. Designed by Josh Bruckstein, co-owner of Green
Mountain Rock Climbing Center in nearby Rutland, the wall is 26
feet high and takes up the entire end of a large lunch room.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Bruckstein and Chris Borodenko, also a climber
and an artist who painted the wall to look like wintry New England
countryside, helped several people climb with ropes and harnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skiing is a lot more physical and requires coordination,''
said Heather Mellen, 25, a lawyer in the New York office of Boston
law firm Goodwin, Proctor &AMP; Hoar. ``This is more mind over matter.
So if you're getting too banged up as I was, this is a good
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Five-year-old Bryan Raiche's mother works at Killington, and
he'd been up the wall a couple of times before. Still, he said,
eyes wide after a brief climb, it felt ``pretty dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see me?'' he asked, full of pride. ``I didn't go all
the way up 'cause my feet couldn't reach the other ledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The wall costs $10 for three climbs.
</P>
<P>
   If that all seems a little much, though, for what is supposed to
be a week of crisp mountain air and winter sports, how about a
snowy hike through the state park at Wachusett (Visitors Center,
978-464-2879), a guided night snowshoe trek to the stone cottage in
which author Pearl Buck stayed near Stratton (802-297-2200), or
horseback rides through frozen woods from Edson Hill Manor
(802-253-7371) near Stowe, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Stowe, in fact, has among the most varied activities. In
addition to the horseback riding (all ability levels, 10 years and
older), the Helen Day Art Center off School Street is open
Tuesday-Saturday, noon-5 p.m. (802-253-8358) For the next several
weeks, a photo exhibit includes Eugene Atget's photographs of
Paris, Berenice Abbott's photos of New York City, and Jules
Backus's pictures of the stencil art of Paris. A $2 donation is
requested.
</P>
<P>
   From 8 a.m.-6 p.m. seven days a week, visitors to the Cold
Hollow Cider Mill in nearby Waterbury (802-244-8771) watch cider
being made while munching fresh donuts made on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest draw, however, and conceivably the most popular
tourist attraction in all of Vermont, according to Stowe's Kirt
Zimmer, is the Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice cream factory, also in Waterbury
on the Waterbury Stowe Road. Take the $2 tour weekdays, 10 a.m.-5
p.m., every hour and the half-hour, and get free ice cream samples
at the end. (802-244-5641)
</P>
<P>
   At Stratton, after the lifts close Tuesday and Saturday night,
ride up the mountain in a car towed by a snowcat to dinner at the
midpoint restaurant (802-297-2200). Watch the groomers, take in the
view, and learn what goes on at the slopes after the lifts close.
</P>
<P>
   Waterville Valley offers moonlit tours (or at least nighttime
tours) of the countryside on snowshoes or cross-country skis
(603-236-4666), and tubing from 5:30-9:30 p.m. at the main ski
area.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if skiing really is what you like, there's plenty of
that, even for spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Stratton, for example, has what they call a ``border cross
competition'' Saturday nights. Skiers, snowboarders, and ski
boarders (those people with a tiny snowboard strapped to each foot)
compete over an all-terrain course. You can watch from the
slopeside restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Or, any day in any lodge at any ski area, just find a window
seat and watch the crowd outside: the fashion, the falls, the
grace, the technique. It's terrific theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
