<HEADLINE>
SKOCPOL ON MAKING THE SYSTEM WORK FOR WORKING FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALYSSA HAYWOODE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MISSING MIDDLE 
Working Families and the Future of American Social Policy 
By Theda Skocpol 
Norton, 207 pp., $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a teenager struggling into baby clothes, America is making
do with undersized political ideas. Take the popular debates:
Welfare reform looks at a sliver of the population; promises of tax
cuts often focus on another small group, the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Those left out are described in the title of Theda Skocpol's new
book, ``The Missing Middle: Working Families and the Future of
American Social Policy.'' These people, Skocpol writes, ``are
working men and women of modest economic means . . . who do most of
the providing and caring for the children who represent the future
of American society, while paying the taxes that sustain
retirees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Missing Middle'' is a straightforward policy read. But
between the lines is a rousing warning: Don't settle for
``restricted politics,'' the circus train of stereotypes, quick
fixes, and shortsighted moralizing. Skocpol blames liberals,
conservatives, progressives, and politicians alike for their
political tunnel vision, and criticizes the stylish but sometimes
hollow rhetoric of the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The book's strength is its mix of analysis, journalism, and
common sense. Skocpol, a professor of government and sociology,
makes the social-scientific case to back up parents' experiences:
Government policies haven't caught up with today's challenge of
raising children and earning a living.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there's a ``historic formula for success in
American social policy.'' We just have to remember what worked and
why. Skocpol's examples include Civil War benefits, public
education, and the Social Security Act.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time in what sounds like a Tom Hanks movie, the
American Legion pushed for the historic and successful GI Bill. The
Legion was ``instrumental in persuading Congressional
representatives, including skeptical Southern conservatives, to
enact the very generous and comprehensive 1944 legislation.'' In
the 1910s and 1920s, organizations like the National Congress of
Mothers and the General Federation of Women's Clubs won programs
for mothers and children.
</P>
<P>
   These programs, Skocpol says, shared four traits: reliable
sources of public revenues; constituents from different social
classes; the backing of voluntary organizations that worked with
government; and the perception that they rewarded service or helped
people prepare for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Current events are analyzed in a chapter that dissects
stereotypes _ not of minorities but of the elderly. Skocpol
punctures the myth of fat cats cruising on golf courses while
Social Security checks fill their bank accounts and the American
Association of Retired Persons bullies Congress. This chapter could
stand alone as an invaluable example of how a kernel of truth _
that these days, benefits are skewed toward the retired elderly _
can explode into fabrications.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Skocpol briefly laments what might have been.
After the civil rights efforts of 1955 to 1965, there might have
been full-employment programs or universal health coverage _
dignified government support for all citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Her larger goal, however, is to expand the debate over what
might be; hence the appeal of her final chapter. Its list of
proposals presents political and logistical challenges. But even
those who disagree with Skocpol should be impressed by her breadth.
Her sweeping proposals expose a vast, largely ignored continent of
ideas. These include an AARP-type organization for parents;
universal access to paid family leave financed by employer
contributions and general tax revenues; and using the Social
Security Trust Fund to finance ``GI Bill-style loans'' to college
students that would be paid back through automatic payroll
deductions. Instead of being solely the art of the possible,
politics, Skocpol shows, can be the art of great possibilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
