<HEADLINE>
DIRECTORY PUTTING ITS SWITCH TO THE IPO TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet investors have no problems thinking outside the box.
But can they think outside the book?
</P>
<P>
   Switchboard Inc. of Westborough, Mass., the big telephone
directory service on the Internet, will be pitching its initial
public stock offering in a road show next week, with plans to hit
the market by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Switchboard, which urges its customers to ``think outside the
book,'' is looking to raise as much as $60 million in an IPO that
would value the company at about $284 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a believer,'' said analyst Suzanne Chase of Burnham
Securities, who follows Banyan Systems Inc. of Westborough, a
majority owner of Switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   By Internet standards, Switchboard is an old-timer, with a track
record that dates back to 1996. Hopes for an earlier public debut
were dealt a setback when Switchboard lost a critical Web
relationship in fall 1998 and dramatically redirected its business
last year.
</P>
<P>
   America Online killed a marketing agreement that had referred
AOL customers to Switchboard's directory and signed on with
competitor Infospace Inc. instead.
</P>
<P>
   About 45 percent of Switchboard's 1998 revenues were tied to
agreements with America Online. Traffic to the phone directory site
plunged when the relationship ended. Switchboard, which attracted
5.5 million unique vistors in October 1988, pulled in slightly less
than half that audience in December 1999, according to Media
Metrix, the Internet traffic tracking firm.
</P>
<P>
   Switchboard ranked a distant second to Infospace and its 6.9
million unique visitors among Web directory sites in December. But
fans believe the company did the right thing for its long-term
prospects by not paying up to keep the America Online pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of pie-in-the-sky out there, and when
everything shakes out, those who have build real business models
will survive _ and there's a phenomenal opportunity,'' Chase said.
``I believe Switchboard will be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the idea the Switchboard stock offering is any IPO
stick-in-the-mud. It is still contemplating a beginning stock
market value more than 30 times its total 1999 revenues of $8.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Switchboard redirected its business last year through two key
deals. Banyan sold a big piece of the company to CBS Inc. in June,
in return for $95 million worth of ads and promotion and $5 million
in cash. CBS now owns a 41 percent interest in Switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   The company also moved into the local advertising market in a
big way, lining up with Discover Financial Services to identify and
pitch merchant advertising accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Switchboard's directory to pull up all the hotels in a city
and a series of display advertisements appear on your computer
screen, along with all the listings.
</P>
<P>
   It's a way to dig deep down into the economy for new Internet
advertising, but Switchboard's strategy involves thousands of small
clients spending relatively short money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local (Internet) commerce and advertising have not developed
as quickly as many have liked,'' said Chris Charron, research
director of media and entertainment at Forrester Research in
Cambridge. ``Local marketers don't spend a lot of money on online
advertising, and they are slow to embrance online commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Charron said the slow growth of local advertising and the niche
nature of the Internet are two serious problems facing so-called
big-book telephone directories on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   He said companies like Switchboard will do well to repackage
pieces of their databases over and over to reach many small
targeted audiences on the Internet, ``slicing and dicing'' the
information it has already collected.
</P>
<P>
   Another key development for directory companies: wireless
communications. Infospace has respun its entire business as a
technical infrastructure for wireless Web services that most
experts believe will take off like a rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your cell phone for the Chinese restaurants in the area, and
a list pops up on the handset. Push a button, and the phone dials
you through.
</P>
<P>
   Switchboard doesn't describe any grand wireless plans in its
stock-offering documents, but analysts say it's still early in the
wireless game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this race for the wireless space is really just
beginning,'' Charron said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The New Economy, Part I: Sycamore Networks Inc. of Chelmsford,
Mass., the fiber-optic networking company that went public last
fall and reported revenues of less than $20 million in the most
recent quarter, now commands a greater stock market value than the
slumping FleetBoston Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore was worth $27.4 billion Wednesday, while the market
capital of Fleet, the nation's eighth-largest bank holding company,
was $26.2 billion, according to Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   --The New Economy, Part II: John Hancock Financial Services Inc.
has told all employees except senior officers that they would each
receive 200 stock options in the newly public company. Happily for
employees, the exercise price will not be the same $17 per share of
Hancock's initial public offering last month. Hancock shares
finished at 14 11/16. The exercise price of employee options will
be based on the closing price of Hancock shares March 13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1256EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
