<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9789 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HARVARD-DORMS-ART-BOS     02-17 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-DORMS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HARVARD STUDENTS TRYING TO LIVE IN BILL GATES' SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Business calls are muffled or routed to his
cell phone. E-mail messages to his partners can only be sent via
special accounts. And letters and packages go directly to his
anonymous mailbox at a nearby post office.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Tseng is not a drug dealer or political dissident, but, for
much of the past year, the 20-year-old Harvard Internet
entrepreneur has been forced to act like one.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many schools throughout the country, the nation's oldest
university has long maintained, if not always enforced, stringent
rules against students running businesses in dorms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something they impress on us from the very
beginning,'' said Tseng, a cofounder of an online textbook sales
company. ``A lot of people here are pretty paranoid about the
rules, but it's hard to absolutely follow them.''
</P>
<P>
   Student-run businesses at Harvard are nothing new. The most
notable is Bill Gates's launching of Microsoft in the mid-1970s, an
endeavor that provoked administrators to reprimand Gates for using
university resources for personal profit.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter century after the billionaire's pioneering days at
Harvard, a mushrooming number of student-founded computer companies
on campus is forcing the university to reconsider its policy.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent student-faculty meeting, the Harvard College dean,
Harry Lewis, proposed rewording the severe language in the
university's student handbook to permit undergraduates to engage in
``modest'' business activities from their dorm rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become aware of the fact that a number of successful
businesses started when their founders were undergraduates and
posed no problems,'' said Lewis, referring to such
multimillion-dollar startups as Chipshot.com, a site selling golf
equipment. ``So we decided that a blanket prohibition was no longer
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rules, however, won't be a blanket endorsement for free
enterprise on school grounds. If the faculty approves Lewis's
proposal in a meeting later this spring, students will still have
to abide by a list of regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The young capitalists will have to get permission before doing
business in their dorms and avoid using their dorm addresses,
university e-mail accounts, or Web sites for business, and they
will still be prohibited from disbursing goods from their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``When business-related activities are permitted, care must be
taken to avoid excessive use of university resources, misuse of
university facilities and information provided primarily for
Harvard's teaching and research missions, and activities that might
jeopardize the tax-exempt status of the university or its
property,'' the proposal states.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said there are at least three other lingering concerns
about revising the policy: Harvard's name could be expropriated or
entangled with student businesses; students might lose sight of
their primary goal of getting an education; and computer servers
and other resources could be bogged down by increased use.
</P>
<P>
   Student entrepreneurs discount the importance of such concerns
and say they doubt whether new rules will make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any changes will have little to no effect on student
startups,'' said Peter Weed, a senior who founded The Crimson
Business Group, a company that helps students launch new
businesses. ``Most of us already ignore the rules anyway. That's
part of the reason they're talking about changing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, in fact, has rarely taken disciplinary action against
students running business from their dorms. ``Typically, we notice
something, tell the student to stop, and the student stops,'' Lewis
said. ``So the problem goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Baker, a junior who runs Datesite.com, which boasted of
matching 175 couples only two weeks after launching last February,
said the proposed rules won't really affect him, since his company
is already established.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a bit worried about it last year,'' Baker said. ``But
we're settled now, and we have little need to use university
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Andrew Chung and Matthew Ebbel, whose Web business,
Collegebeans.com, undercuts university bookstores, say new rules
would help those in the early stages of a business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not that there are cameras or anything in the
room,'' Chung said. ``It's that You're always worrying you might do
something wrong that will jeopardize your degree. This should make
it easier on new startups.''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining why the university is considering relaxing its
rules after so many years, Lewis said that 70 percent of Harvard
students now hold jobs because of their financial aid requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those students, he said, work out of their dorm rooms,
designing or monitoring company Web sites. Those jobs, Lewis said,
``can't be distinguished'' from those of students who are
proprietors of their own Web-based companies.
</P>
<P>
   For Greg Tseng, the administration's change of heart is good
news.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his tiny dorm room, Tseng, a Harvard junior, clicks
on his Web site, Limespot.com. Just by pulling up his site's bright
orange opening page, he wonders whether he's violating university
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the problem now,'' he says. ``There's a lot of fear
you're going to do something that's going to get you in big
trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
