<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9790 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-FIREPLACES-2ND &LR;  &UR;      02-17 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-FIREPLACES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... vent-free units.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wright advises going to a specialty retail hearth store for
installation and service and, of course, purchase. ``You may pay a
little bit more, but they'll be able to give you a greater range of
options and what is most suitable for your square footage and
decor.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Wright says, with homes now so airtight, negative pressure
can build up and cause back-drafting down a traditional brick
chimney, introducing harmful exhaust into the home. Therefore, the
sealed gas-combustion units prevent such drafts and reduce concern
about air quality in a home.
</P>
<P>
   Another boost to the increasing popularity of gas fireplaces is
improvement in log technology. The first ``pretend'' logs only
glowed and had an odd, bluish flame. Today, logs have a more
authentic yellow, flickering flame with burning red embers
underneath that send off from 20,000 to 40,000 BTUs of heat an hour
(35,000 BTUs heat 1,500 square feet).
</P>
<P>
   To put gas logs, which are ceramic or glass, in an existing
wood-burning fireplace, you must by law disable the damper so the
flue remains open. There is loss of heat up the chimney, but this
can be lessened by installing glass doors when the logs are not
being used. To install the log unit, a plumber must drill into the
basement and hook up the gas logs to the existing gas line, says
Black Magic's Gignoux. The flames from these logs will be larger
and more realistic, but this is offset by the loss of heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``People buy these for effect rather than for heat,'' says
Gignoux.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remote-control comfort
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cormack, a salesman at Affordable Windows and Doors in
Newton, Mass., says he bought a home nine years ago that had no
fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we added a family room, we really wanted a fireplace, but
couldn't afford the expense,'' says Cormack. ``I stumbled on a
direct-vent gas unit at the August West store in Hingham, Mass. It
would cost me one-third of what it was going to cost me to put in a
masonry fireplace. I put in a black granite hearth and surround and
it ended up costing me about $2,300 compared to $6,000 to $8,000
for a brick fireplace. We used it all the time. It was a great
source of heat and so easy to operate. I had a remote, so I just
clicked it on from my chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormack has recently moved to another home where there is no gas
line on the street. He has decided to install an electric
fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Gas stoves are also enjoying a new popularity, according to
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are wonderful space heaters because the heat radiates
from six sides, they now have a wide expanse of glass in front, and
they're attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   And like fireplace units, they vent directly thereby avoiding
those tall, ugly pipes reaching up through the ceiling out to the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in New England aren't wild about putting a stove in the
living area,'' says Gignoux. ``But there are pluses _ a stove is
free standing with no mantel, hearth, or tile surround.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looks are important
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, he says, it's looks that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stove is like a piece of furniture,'' says Gignoux. ``Looks
are very important, and it is the woman who usually makes the
decision about what type of unit to buy. We have this very
efficient stove that just isn't selling well because people don't
like the look, even though it's a workhorse, very efficient, and
the cleanest burning.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright says that not enough attention has been paid to the
aesthetics of these units and that the industry must give the
consumer more options _ that manufacturers must offer five, six, or
seven choices instead of the present two or three.
</P>
<P>
   And for folks who must have wood burning in their fireplace,
there is also a solution that avoids the expense of brick and
mortar.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hanna, partner in S. &AMP; H. Construction, lives on the second
floor of a two-family house in Cambridge where there was no
existing fireplace. He built out a wall, put in a zero-clearance,
metal firebox, framed around it, and then snaked a stovepipe up
through the third floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't like the idea of piping in gas,'' says Hanna.
``There's something real primal about a wood fire. It's warm and
hypnotic. We like hanging out in front of it. I order a cord and
have the kids carry the logs up from the basement. At night, I pull
the wire-mesh screen across, pull back the rug, and go to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Wright sees continuing improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A microchip will be placed in the gas log units to regulate
the flame and more closely mimic real fire,'' says Wright. ``Plus
the new fires will begin slowly like a wood fire, roar when it
catches, and smolder in the end. These chip products will be on the
market within the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, there'll be fireplaces that are installed on an
outside wall that are glass on both the inside and outside _
thereby allowing people to enjoy a fire while sitting on a deck on
a cool summer evening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
