<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PRIESTESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S HIGH PRIESTESS OF THE HOUSE-PROUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ &UR;  &LR; As soon as she saw the galley proofs of ``Home
Comforts: The Art and Science of Keeping House,'' trend-sensitive
domestic titan Martha Stewart invited author Cheryl Mendelson onto
her TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mendelson writes that good homemakers are good list
makers, Stewart asked for her lists. ``So I grabbed some from the
refrigerator. They were written on torn envelopes and whatever. But
when we started filming, they had copied out every item on my lists
in round handwriting on the nice type of yellow legal paper!''
</P>
<P>
   Mendelson is laughing as we sit at the small round kitchen table
in her Upper West Side apartment. A thoughtful and precise woman of
53 with cinnamon-colored hair and a passing resemblance to Susan
Sarandon, she is respectful of Stewart but offers an alternative
vision of homemaking, focused on making things work well, rather
than look good. In fact, Mendelson could be called the anti-Martha.
</P>
<P>
   The author, whose housekeeping encylopedia has been a surprise
bestseller (it's now in its seventh printing, with 160,000 copies
in print), gets her ``home comforts'' from a clean kitchen and
crisp linens on a freshly made bed rather than from fashioning wine
coasters from twigs and color coordinating candles with the
dinnerware. She even suspects that such craft and decorating
projects are often seized on as substitutes for housekeeping skills
by people who are trying to make their domiciles more homey, but
don't know how.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of generations, Mendelson believes, the
very real know-how required for housekeeping has been devalued and,
to a large extent, lost, like a language people stopped speaking
and nobody wrote down. So she herself wrote it down. She spent
eight years researching and writing about subjects most people
avoid even thinking about. The results are more than 800
comprehensive pages on neatening, serving meals, laundering,
ironing, and cleaning, a kind of ``Joy of Cooking'' for housework.
It sounds dull, but actually makes almost hypnotic reading.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing many people want to know about Mendelson is
whether she's obsessive-compulsive. They assume she must be. In
fact, she says, a tad combatively, ``that's who they want me to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely manifesto
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In promoting her book, the author has found herself leading a
charge against the common cultural assumption that a person who
enjoys housework must be crazy. And ``Home Comforts'' has become an
unlikely manifesto.
</P>
<P>
   Her apartment kitchen is old-fashioned and cozy. It's bitterly
cold out, and she moves my chair next to one of the radiators so I
can warm up. (She believes a home should be, above all, welcoming.)
She makes a pot of good coffee, using a vacuum pot coffee maker.
(``Home Comforts'' has a section evaluating coffee-making
techniques.)
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen tablecloth is patterned with cheerful cherries.
Almost everything else is white. But the refrigerator casually
plastered with those lists and family photos in full view is
reassuring. A decorator recently told me it was tacky to put
anything on my own refrigerator, and I have been struggling with
this injunction ever since. Now I can't wait to get my magnets back
out.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Mendelson, a Harvard-trained lawyer with a PhD in
philosophy; her husband, a Columbia English professor; and their
8-year-old son share a large university-owned apartment with a
dining room, living room, kitchen, laundry room, two home-offices,
two cozy bedrooms, three bathrooms, and a long hallway.
</P>
<P>
   There is so little clutter the place looks almost
underfurnished. I'm aware of spaciousness and light, rather than
objects.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the apartment holds enough books to stock a library.
There are, by my count, 24 white floor-to-ceiling bookcases, all
installed by the Mendelsons. There are also about two dozen white
overhead cabinets in the kitchen, and half of these were added by
the family.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is everything in its place, but there's a place for
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost. There are three bikes in the dining room. ``We
have no place to put them,'' she shrugs. ``They flit around from
hallway to dining room to office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most housing was built when people owned many fewer things,''
says Mendelson. ``They just don't have the storage space that
people need today.'' My house was built in 1829, and I immediately
make a mental note to engage the services of a cabinetmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Mendelson learned housekeeping from her grandmothers when she
was growing up on a farm in the Appalachian corner of Pennsylvania,
where 19th-century ways survived into her 1950s' childhood.
</P>
<P>
   One grandmother was Italian, the other Scots-Anglo-Irish, and
they differed mightily on whether beds should be made up
immediately each morning or aired out, whether ironing was a waste
of time or the queen of household arts, whether sunlight should be
invited in or sealed out, and whether red-eye gravy or garlic
belonged in a healthful meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were always asking, very casually, as if it were
unimportant to them, `How does your other grandmother do it?' ''
recalls Mendelson with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   This rivalry launched Mendelson on the road to evaluating
varying homemaking techniques, and also to setting them in a
cultural context.
</P>
<P>
   After her family moved to the Florida suburbs, Mendelson focused
on academic achievement and tried to abandon, or at least hide, her
interest in domestic matters to fit in with her new world. It
seemed bourgeois and politically incorrect, especially to her first
husband. But after a period of ``antidomestic posturing,'' her true
nature reemerged. She recalls the nadir as the time she came home
to find their wet muddy dog and two belonging to friends romping on
their bed to her husband's complete indifference. She cried. ``It
was probably our only pair of sheets and I couldn't stand the
thought that I had no bed to sleep in.''
</P>
<P>
   What she has written, after divorce, practicing law (which she
found true drudgery), and remarriage, is partly a philosophical and
lawyerly argument in favor of good housekeeping, as well as a
how-to book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A range of responses
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hot potato. I don't get an indifferent response. The
most excited readers are young, well-educated women who don't know
how to keep house. But some politically based women see it as
regressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendelson says her book is aimed at both genders and advises
couples fighting the chore wars to negotiate for maintenance jobs
that each enjoys. (According to a recent study, though men still do
much less housework than women, men now average 10 hours a week
compared with five in the prefeminist era of the early 1960s.)
</P>
<P>
   The Mendelsons split homemaking 50-50, each doing about 10 hours
a week, not including cooking time. (Her husband tells me he
especially enjoys neatening closets when putting off grading
students' papers.)
</P>
<P>
   The Mendelsons also have a weekly housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   They see no inconsistency in this.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does the basics, like dusting and vacuuming. But I do the
harder stuff. It's my house. I wouldn't ask any paid employee to
clean my kitchen floor on their hands and knees, but I'll do it
twice a month,'' says Mendelson. ``I do the tops of the
bookshelves, the corners, the backboards. But not every week! I do
one room a week, in depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Mendelson may not be obsessive-compulsive, but she has no
doubt that bad housekeeping can kill you. ``Home Comforts'' devotes
many pages to deadly bacteria, electrical safety, slips and falls,
proper disposal of hazardous household wastes, tap-water
temperature, and potentially lethal garage doors. This is a book
that tells you what to do if someone's clothing catches on fire.
Slightly unnerved after reading the dates on her food storage
chart, I realized I should toss every condiment I own, most of the
frozen food, and all of the jelly. Those pathogens are sending
their tentacles straight for the bottom of the jars.
</P>
<P>
   Mendelson is particularly focused on child safety. Her son's
room is probably the cleanest in the house. Many of her son's
classmates are ``little wheezers,'' she says, referring to the
increase in childhood asthma. ``It's important to reduce exposure
to allergens in children's rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   History of housekeeping
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She got the idea for her book from the antique homemaking
manuals she collects. ``Housekeeping changed tremendously between
1900 and 1950! People got electric lights, hot water,'' she says.
The biggest improvement was in laundry day, which actually used to
use up two days a week, one for washing, one for ironing.
</P>
<P>
   But except for the microwave, there was remarkably little real
improvement in homemaking between 1950 and 2000, she says. ``My
grandmothers would be completely comfortable here. The biggest
change has been the phenomenal growth of consumer goods. Those
great big houses won't make people happy. They'll need a lot of
help to take care of 10,000 square feet. People are better off with
2,000 to 3,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Homemakers used to follow a standard weekly routine. Monday was
washday, and when Mendelson walked to school in rural Pennsylvania
on Monday mornings, ``every woman would be hanging out her first
load.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of cleaning as crisis management, Mendelson advises
easing into such a schedule: ``Habitual things don't feel hard.''
Her current routine is:
</P>
<P>
   Monday: washing and ironing.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: odd jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Friday: minicleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday and Sunday: all done.
</P>
<P>
   She and her family also do morning and evening neatening
``blitzes,'' and she has boxes and drawers sanctioned as ``holding
stations'' for mail, school papers, and other objects waiting to be
sorted and shelved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of superficial neatness,'' Mendelson says.
``It's utilizing organizational systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The doorbell rings. As she strides down the front hall to
welcome another guest, Mendelson scoops up a visiting child's
backpack without slowing, tosses it against the wall, then sends a
wayward umbrella in the same direction with a quick, efficient
little kick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1301EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9793 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-17 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MAGAZINES AIMING AT YOUNG GUYS, IT'S FLESH WARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the flesh wars raging on America's newsstands, score one for
Gear magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff magazine poses actress Alicia Witt in her underwear while
Maxim magazine uses barely bikini-clad model Kim Smith to front for
its swimsuit issue. Details goes with undressed actress Virginie
Ledoyen while the inaugural cover for FHM (For Him Magazine) opts
for actress Rachael Leigh Cook in a microscopic two-piece outfit.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the new issue of Gear with its career-altering
seminude shots of Jessica Biel _ teen star of the popular WB
family-values show ``7th Heaven _ that generated a buzz that
bounced from the New York tabloids to Newsweek. (On Tuesday, ``7th
Heaven'' executive producer Aaron Spelling filed a $100 million
lawsuit against Gear in connection with the photo spread and
accompanying article.)
</P>
<P>
   This glossy battle of pulchritude is not about the models and
actresses who adorn the magazines' pages, however. It's about the
young men who stare at them. In April 1997, a British import called
Maxim came ashore here, changing the face of both publishing and
pop culture. A philosophical descendant of the early Playboy
magazine, tamer than skin magazines, and less literary than GQ or
Esquire, Maxim became a magnet for 20-something professional males
who wanted frothier and fleshier lifestyle journalism. (The
magazine's unrepentent motto is ``sex, sports, beer, gadgets,
clothes, fitness.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tapping into the downscale side of an upscale urban
male,'' says Tony Silber, editorial director of Folio, the magazine
for magazine management. ``Nobody had ever tapped into that market
until Maxim.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then everyone's jumped into the fray. Last year, Maxim
unveiled sister publication Stuff and this past week, the US
version of the British magazine FHM was launched. A year-and-a-half
ago, Bob Guccione Jr., son of the Penthouse magazine publisher,
rolled out Gear. Conde Nast's Details _ which has tinkered with
different formulas over the years _ is now trying to evolve from
what its editor calls a ``Maxim look-alike mode.'' Such
high-mindedness, however, entails risk. When P.O.V. magazine
recently folded, some observers blamed it on a failure to compete
vigorously enough on the sex-and-suds front.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been some P.O.V.-like casualties, the new
wave of men's magazines still seems to be building. Three of the
entries are less than two years old, Gear just upped its
publication schedule from bimonthly to monthly, and Stuff is poised
to do the same. The magazines' combined rate base _ the circulation
figure they cite for their advertisers _ is closing in on 4
million, not counting FHM. According to figures at the end of 1999,
Maxim's 1.66 million circulation _ which more than doubled in a
year _ is greater than GQ's and Esquire's combined. And Brill's
Content magazine recently named Felix Dennis, the chairman of the
company that publishes Maxim and Stuff, to its list of 25
influential media movers and shakers.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, all these magazines are trying to answer the same
age-old question. What do (young) men really want?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be adults,'' says Steve Douglas, the general
partner of the Douglas Jones magazine consulting group. These are
``the men's magazines for the guys who don't want to grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its fluff, the ``lad magazine'' genre that originated in
the '90s in Britain is attempting to fill a genuine niche in the
male reading market. The once powerful Playboy and Penthouse
magazines were waning, a victim of Internet porn sites and X-rated
videos. And the more highbrow men's publications _ what FHM editor
in chief Ed Needham likes to refer to as the ``cardigan and
slippers titles'' _ have never exactly taken that demographic group
by storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point (of the Maxim trend) is to . . . try to
determine the market for young men'' outside of sports or skin
magazines, says Douglas. They're ``trying to put the `guy culture'
into a printed version.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the temptation to lump all these magazines together,
there are differences of degree if not emphasis. Maxim, Stuff, and
FHM are largely viewed as the lighter fare while Details and Gear
are more likely to dabble in more serious journalism. The
scandalous Biel issue of Gear, for example, includes a lengthy
piece examining the murder charge against pro football player Rae
Carruth and a hard look at AIDS therapies.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines are willing to parse the distinctions even finer.
Steve Colvin, president of the firm that publishes Maxim and Stuff,
says Maxim's ``editorial turn is humorous, irreverent, knowing, and
succinct.'' Stuff editor in chief Andy Clerkson says his magazine
skews a bit younger and ``is more grounded in pop culture than
Maxim.''
</P>
<P>
   Details editor Mark Golin, who formerly toiled at Maxim,
dismisses that publication as ``a few jokes and some babes leaning
over.'' Details, he says, is now interested in producing a ``young
men's magazine that offers a little more substance,'' such as
``pursuing a guy's inner emotional life.'' Guccione calls Gear
``first and foremost an entertainment magazine'' with ``another
level of more solid investigative journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard not to notice some of the staples of this style
of journalism. There are a lot of features involving young women
who gather in a room, imbibe alcohol, and then discuss the do's and
don'ts of sex. Memorable sports brawls and tragedies are a favored
topic as are stories about escaping avalanches. There is plenty of
light service journalism with an emphasis on gadgets, gizmos, and
male fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nothing unites these competitors like the pages of
photographs of nubile and nearly nude women. One is tempted to say
the magazines are simply selling sex. But that's a harder sell when
every post-adolescent male is a few mouse clicks away from
no-holds-barred Internet porn and when their photos are no racier
than those in the Sports Illustrated swimsuit issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about sex,'' says Needham. ``Sex is an ancient
physical act that various civilizations have struggled to come to
terms with. It's about sexiness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggests sex without showing it,'' adds Steven Cohn, editor
in chief of the Media Industry Newsletter. ``In the old sex talk,
it maybe goes to third base and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Colvin espouses the idea _ certain to be disputed in some
quarters _ that these pictorials are more worshipful than
exploitive. ``The attitude of Maxim is `Hey, women are great,' ''
he says. ``We love women. They're better than us really.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the popularity of these publications, Guccione puts
it in terms that are more sociopolitical than sexual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the nerve the genre has touched is the death of
political correctness,'' he says. ``It was seen for what it was,
empty rhetoric. It was a faux social movement. I think what
happened is men were made to feel dirty for having natural,
instinctive interest in sex.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one other subtle marketing mechanism embedded alongside
all the sexy pictures. In their own breezy fashion, these magazines
do dispense advice _ on relationships, fashion, and finance _ to
their readers. But they studiously avoid the preachier ``build
better abs'' or ``be a better lover'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   These magazines are ``about how to make relationships more
fulfilling (but) without the `honey, read this,' '' approach, says
Douglas. ``It's been very hard to write for the guys on lifestyle
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the latest British invasion here to stay, redefining once
and for all the men's magazine? The verdicts are mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The category is hot as hell,'' says Douglas. ``The attempt to
break this category open . . . will be a breakthrough. It's been a
. . . project ever since Esquire launched.''
</P>
<P>
   Many estimates are bullish, suggesting the genre may have an
upside of 10 million-plus readers. Others aren't so sure. ``I've
been a little skeptical of it overall,'' says Cohn. ``The men's
advertising market is much weaker than women's.''
</P>
<P>
   The record in England _ where the ``lad mags'' are beginning to
level off _ may foretell its future here. The Maxim wave worked in
that ``suddenly, there was a magazine for guys who weren't looking
for journalism,'' but ``looking for a laugh,'' says Golin. ``Over
here, it's a larger country. It'll take them a little longer to
plateau.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
