<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-2000-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT WHEELS OUT WINDOWS 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Microsoft Corp. is launching Windows 2000, its
most ambitious and complex software ever, a project that has taken
nearly four years and cost an estimated $1 billion in development
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   And if all goes well, users won't notice a thing.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Redmond, Wash., company's $200 million
marketing blitz, Windows 2000 is its most reliable operating system
to date, allowing users to run computers smoothly for months, even
years, at a time without crashing.
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft, it is supposed to be a crowning achievement, one
that is expected to bring the company $1 billion in revenue this
year, according to some Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of popping champagne corks, the company has been
busy this week putting out fires and trying to assure a skeptical
public of the worthiness of its latest product, aimed at business
users.
</P>
<P>
   Looming over Microsoft's parade are several clouds _ ranging
from competition from the upstart Linux operating system to reports
that the software may contain tens of thousands of bugs in its
massive program code.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has been dismissing these clouds, but their presence
has nevertheless dampened the company's stock price. Since last
Thursday, Microsoft shares have fallen 7.9 percent, closing Tuesday
at 97 5/8, down 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   The slide began Friday, when Gartner Group, an influential
research organization in Stamford, Conn., reportedly warned that
companies will be slow to adopt Windows 2000 because more than 10
percent of existing software may not be compatible with the new
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks came a day after Michael Dell, head of Dell Computer
Corp., told analysts he did not expect a ``massive immediate
acceleration'' in computer sales from Windows 2000. Gartner Group
analysts and Dell have since tried to clarify their statements,
insisting their comments were taken out of context. The market
reaction to Gartner's warning ``was way off the map,'' said Tom
Bittman, a research director at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   But the damage had been done. Microsoft shares tumbled nearly 6
percent to $99.94 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More bad news came over the weekend. Reports surfaced about an
internal Microsoft memo that counted 63,000 potential bugs in
Windows 2000. The memo, unearthed by online publisher Sm(at)art
Reseller, set off a flurry of debate over what constitutes a bug.
Microsoft, acknowleging the memo, insists the 63,000 count included
thousands of minor comments or suggestions made by its automatic
bug-finder, a software tool called Prefix.
</P>
<P>
   ``That account was completely inaccurate,'' said Craig
Beilenson, Microsoft's lead product manager for Windows 2000.
``Prefix is so sensitive that it finds thousands of false
positives. It flags things that aren't really problems. It's
ironic, because hundreds of independent analysts have been saying
that Windows 2000 is a rock-solid product.''
</P>
<P>
   Beilenson pointed out that Microsoft sent out 750,000 test
copies of Windows 2000, its largest testing effort ever. Then
again, analysts say that's not surprising, given that Windows 2000
is the company's most complex software, with close to 30 million
lines of programming code.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to dispel doubts, Microsoft chairman Bill Gates is
expected to announce that Windows 2000 has been running on
thousands of its customers' computers for months, without major
glitches. Other issues remain, though.
</P>
<P>
   In the desktop arena, sellers of the upstart Linux operating
system have been making a small but noticeable dent in Microsoft's
share of the market, capturing just under 4 percent _ making it the
third most widely used operating system, after Microsoft's Windows
and Apple Computer's Macintosh OS, according to International Data
Corp. of Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   The rate at which businesses will leap to buy Windows 2000 is
expected to be fairly slow in the beginning, not only because of
the expense but because companies are loath to abandon their
existing computer systems and learn new ones.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly true of the market Microsoft is targetting
with two of the three versions of Windows 2000 being released: for
the larger, more complex, and more expensive computer systems
called servers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft dominates the market for desktop operating systems,
with an 87 percent share. But it captured just 30 percent of the
dollars spent on server software last year, according to
preliminary estimates by IDC.
</P>
<P>
   Unix-based operating systems (sold by Sun Microsystems Inc., IBM
Corp., and Hewlett-Packard Co.) accounted for 53 percent of the
amount spent on server software last year, said Dan Kusnetzky, a
program director at IDC.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Microsoft is expected to take longer to make
headway in a market that already has significant competitors.
Gartner Group estimates 3 percent to 6 percent of servers will be
swtiched to Windows 2000 by the end of this year, but that the
figure will leap to nearly 50 percent by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are just going to be more cautious and take their
time,'' Bittman said, especially since Unix is widely viewed as
being more reliable than Windows 2000. ``Without a doubt, Unix is
far more stable. But it also costs more.''
</P>
<P>
   Systems running on Windows 2000, he said, can be 25 percent to
75 percent less expensive, primarily because Windows 2000 can run
on less expensive computers that use Intel microprocessors _
so-called Wintel machines _ rather than costly proprietary hardware
sold by Sun, IBM, and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is likely to try to exploit that cost difference in
its marketing of Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The cost message is resonating with Cormac O'Reilly, chief
technology officer for Getronics, an Amsterdam-based computer
services company wuth offices in Boston, where O'Reilly works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wintel is an extremely cost-effective platform when compared
with other architectures,'' said O'Reilly, whose company is
converting to an all-Windows system over the next two years. ``For
us, it's almost a 60 percent savings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
