u a BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     02-17 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB HACKERS MIGHT BE TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who's been hacking into eBay and Yahoo and other popular Web
sites? So far, nobody knows for sure: The technology required for
such denial-of-service attacks has been in the public domain for
months, easily accessible to any malcontent with a working
knowledge of computers. But experts in the Internet underground are
betting that the culprits are adolescent misfits looking for cheap
thrills and bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   They call them ``script kiddies,'' ``code kiddies,'' or ``packet
monkeys,'' brazen teen-agers who use other people's programs to
wreak havoc in cyberspace. To the lay Web user, these ``kiddies''
are mysterious and even dangerous figures. But in the hierarchy of
the hacking subculture, they're at the bottom of the food chain,
vermin who thrive on other people's skills. They're disdained by
serious hackers who view themselves as security vigilantes or
activists who hack with a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably kids in high school who aren't the tough
guys, the quiet shy kids who aren't in the `in' group,'' says Bronc
Buster, a well-known California hacker who broke into a Chinese
government site in 1998 to protest human rights violations. ``They
go home and get on the computer, and they can be the tough guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Such contempt is in the hacking world, where sharp divisions
exist between older and younger generations of self-described
computer geeks. In the realm of hackers, there are three types of
people. The ``black hats'' are criminals who break into computer
systems for malicious reasons, while the ``white hats'' are purists
who will not have anything to do with illegal activity. The ``gray
hats'' exist in the murky area between good and evil: These mature
hackers write programs that reveal security holes in computer
systems and post them publicly on the Internet, allegedly to draw
attention to the flaws.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``script kiddies'' then use those programs to
conduct attacks with no political or professional aim. ``Whoever is
doing this is unsophisticated,'' says Weld Pond, a research
scientist and a member of the veteran hacking group LOpht, which
recently merged with security firm (at)Stake Inc. of Cambridge,
Mass. ``They haven't had to figure out anything new. The guy who
designs the gun has to understand ballistics and internal
combustion; he has to be an engineer. But the person who goes to
the bank and uses the gun is just a hoodlum.''
</P>
<P>
   So why write the programs in the first place? Why put the
weapons in the hands of potential hoodlums? Seasoned scientists
like Pond contend that the only way to demonstrate a security flaw
is to write a program that shows how to crack it. ``It's like the
best way to build an alarm system may be to actually go to jail and
talk with the people who rob houses,'' he says. ``We're trying to
solve problems, not have a religious discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who call themselves ``hacktivists'' claim they write
programs to practice a sort of civil disobedience in cyberspace.
Carmin Karasic, a Quincy, Mass. digital artist, wrote a program
called Floodnet, a tool somewhat similar to the technology used
this week to disrupt Yahoo and the other sites. Floodnet enables
users to request a Web page repeatedly; if it is run simultaneously
by hundreds of users, it can flood a system, making it impossible
for other users to access the site. Karasic and her group, the
Electronic Disturbance Theatre, used the program last year to
target the Mexican government and protest the ongoing war in
Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a place for civil disobedience on line,'' says
Karasic. ``But I don't think you should do this sort of thing
unless there is some clear purpose, like attacking a Ku Klux Klan
site or something. But (the Yahoo attack) makes no sense. It sounds
like script kiddies who are doing it for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, these miscreants act to get attention, but so far, no
one has claimed credit for the recent disruption, which is arguably
the biggest attack in the history of the Internet. Several members
of the hacker underground said a few individuals claimed to know
the identity of the culprits on Internet Relay Chat, an underground
discussion system on the Internet frequented by hackers. But so far
no one has stepped forward; in past incidents when hackers defiled
Web sites, the perpetrators left their signatures on the sites, as
a sort of digital graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   But the people responsible for the attacks would not have gained
praise within their own community. They are being maligned not only
on Internet Relay Chat channels, but also in such on-line forums as
www.slashdot.org, where they were dismissed as ``lame'' people who
``have no life.'' The Internet underground has been trying to
dispel stereotypes of the hackers as something straight out of
central casting, the pasty-faced uber-geek, or the Lone Gunman in
``The X-Files.'' But this week's attacks perpetuated that image,
even within the clubby hacker subculture. ``The stereotypes are
kinda true,'' said Pond. ``We do sit behind the computer 25 hours a
day, getting up only to go to the bathroom and that kind of
thing.'' In this underground world, it can be difficult to tell the
good guys from the bad guys, the black hats from the gray hats.
``If you saw us walking down the street, you wouldn't be able to
tell who we are,'' Pond says. ``If you had a lineup of black hats
and gray hats, you wouldn't be able to tell them apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
