<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9800 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-FIREPLACES-2TAKE     02-17 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-FIREPLACES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HOMEOWNERS TURNING TO GAS FIREPLACES FOR CONVENIENCE, EFFICIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say the word ``fireplace'' and people get a dreamy, faraway look
in their eyes. Not so faraway that images of cavemen huddled before
a pile of burning sticks spring to mind. But back to festive family
holidays, midday warmups after sledding or ice skating, quiet
weekend mornings reading a novel, or intimate evenings with a loved
one sipping wine _ all before a fire crackling in a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   A fire warms us. Pleases the eye. Smells good. Sounds great. The
connection between hearth and home is so powerfully primal that all
negatives seem to go, well, right up the chimney. People forget
long afternoons chopping and stacking; frigid trips to the
woodpile; tedious lighting and relighting; and the telltale black
holes burned into the living room rug from errant embers.
</P>
<P>
   But times are changing. Even king hearth, the reigning icon of
home, is no longer safe from technological attack. Fireplaces will
continue to be the focal point in a room, but they'll wear
different clothes and operate from a different source. And they
will not disappear _ even in hot and humid Florida, 90 percent of
home shoppers want a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Hearth Product Association based in Arlington,
Va., the sale of gas fireplaces, stoves, and inserts has increased
dramatically in the past decade from 149,000 in 1992 to almost
800,000 in 1998, a jump of 417 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening in this industry can be summed up in one word
_ convenience,'' says Richard Wright, publisher and editor of
Hearth &AMP; Home magazine. ``It's similar, for example, to what's
happened to FedEx. Everyone was delighted when they came on the
scene and you could get a letter to its destination overnight. Then
along came the Internet. Now people use e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gas fireplaces are so easy and clean,'' says Wright. ``You can
come home, settle into your La-Z-Boy chair, and just flick a switch
on the wall or on your remote, and you've got a fire. Immediately
you have a fire. No fuss, no mess.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he says, ``70 to 80 percent of the population doesn't even
know these fireplaces exist.''
</P>
<P>
   They will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cheaper than a brick chimney
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeannie Wahlberg, 35, says she had two criteria when she and her
husband, Bobby, a pipe fitter, moved to a new home with their four
young children _ a fireplace and a view of the ocean. She got the
ocean view in Quincy, Mass., but not the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never considered a gas fireplace until my brother put one
in, and then a girlfriend did,'' says Wahlberg, a part-time
secretary in a law firm. ``I suppose we could have gone the brick
chimney route, but it would have been so expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our gas unit gives us extra warmth and is the focal point of
our living room,'' says Walhberg. ``It really is as beautiful as a
regular fireplace, and so much cleaner and easier to use. With four
kids, there's no way my husband and I can sit up at night and wait
for a fire to burn out.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more contractors say they are installing gas fireplaces
in new homes. More homeowners are converting their wood-burning
fireplaces to gas by putting in inserts or gas logs. And, because
these direct-vent fire machines are less expensive to install and
more economical than the brick-and-mortar fireplace, more and more
people are installing not one but multiple gas fireplaces in their
homes _ in bathrooms, home offices, bedrooms, and dens.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Dutton, interviewed before he left his position as service
manager of Architectural Fireplaces in New England, says he's seen
the switch to gas skyrocket in the past five years. Of the 40 to 50
fireplaces the company installs per week, 75 percent are now gas.
And these installations are not just in condos or inexpensive
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one site, the homes range from $800,000 to $1 million,''
says Dutton. ``Of the 30 homes at this particular site, only one
has a wood-burning fireplace. Two-income families just don't have
the time for chopping wood, storing it, maintaining a fire, and
cleaning up afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Efficient and versatile
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he adds, there is no heat loss up a chimney because gas
inserts and fireplaces are sealed. And they cost less to install
because there is no $5,000 to $6,000 brick chimney involved. Gas
units can be directly vented to the outside.
</P>
<P>
   They can also be placed virtually anywhere in a home or
apartment and can be finished with surrounds and mantels in keeping
with the traditional appeal of a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``A gas fireplace still remains the focal point in a room,''
says Dutton. ``In higher-end homes, contractors are putting in
granite hearths, specialized tile and marble surrounds, and
beautifully carved mantels around gas units.''
</P>
<P>
   Gas fireplaces without ducting or trim are priced from around
$750 to $1,500 (this includes the unit and the logs), according to
Perry Gignoux of Black Magic Chimney and Fireplace in Cambridge,
Mass., whose installations are running 67 percent gas to 44 percent
wood. Gas inserts start at $800 and up. A licensed plumber is
required to do the venting and gas work, which can add another $700
or more. And if there's no preexisting fireplace, carpentry work
may include sheetrock and plastering, decorative masonry or tile,
and a mantel.
</P>
<P>
   Direct vent units work at 70-plus percent efficiency compared to
25 percent for wood-burning fireplaces (heat escaping up the
chimney), according to area retailers and suppliers. And because
gas units can be hooked up to a room's thermostat, they act as room
heaters and can be regulated. Depending on the size, the cost runs
from 20 to 40 cents an hour.
</P>
<P>
   And they are safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a ton of safety devices on these units,'' says Paul
Bichun, acount executive for Fireplace Products Inc., which sells
top-of-the-line fireplaces and stoves. ``Massachusetts is one of
the strictest states in the nation as far as codes. Gas units shut
off if they are venting incorrectly or the wind blows out the
pilot. It's really safer to have one of these in your home than to
pump gas at a gas station.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus if the electricity goes off during a storm, a gas fireplace
will continue to work just like the gas stove in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   As for direct venting, Michael Dorion of Fireplace and Patio
Concepts by August West in Boston explains that the vent for these
fireplaces is made up of a tube within a tube. The air comes into
the outer liner for combustion and goes out through the inner tube.
There's no air from the house involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely sealed unit,'' says Dorion. ``You elbow the
vent up and directly out the wall and terminate it outside the
house. It looks very much like a dryer vent from the outside. But
most important, always hire a plumber who is familiar with these
units.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts does not allow vent-free units.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
