u i BC-ZIMBABWE-SURVIVOR-BOS     02-17 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-SURVIVOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPASSION COUNTS, OCEANS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAFARA, Zimbabwe _ Dwarfed by a smoke-gray concrete factory
behind it, House No. 11130 sits on the edge of a cornfield, one of
many nondescript brick-and-mortar dwellings in this township
outside Zimbabwe's capital.
</P>
<P>
   But this house is different. The new home of Esther Daiton and
her nine children _ some hers, some those of adult relatives who
died of AIDS, some friends of the orphaned children _ is evidence
that Africa's tragic AIDS crisis is not beyond compassion's reach.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Esther, who has AIDS herself, was told in a
four-part Globe series last October. It prompted an outpouring of
generosity from people in Boston and beyond that fundamentally
changed the lives of her family.
</P>
<P>
   Barely two months ago they huddled against flooding rains in a
dingy wooden shack. Today they share four rooms, each larger than
the shanty they once called home.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, they ate butter sandwiches once a day; now they
have fresh food and meat and go to bed with their bellies full.
</P>
<P>
   The children used to spend their days scrounging for pennies and
waiting for death. Now they go to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never lived in a place like this before,'' Daiton said.
``We have running water and a flush toilet, food and medicine,
blankets, and $1,000 in a bank account.''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet 27 years old, Esther has already experienced a lifetime
of loss. In the story of her family lies the devastation of a
continent: whole families lost to AIDS, millions of children
orphaned, governments in denial. Africa is the global epicenter of
the AIDS epidemic. More than 2 millions Africans die each year of
AIDS. One in four adults in Zimbabwe, Botswana, Namibia, and
Swaziland carries the virus that causes the disease. By the end of
2001, 13 million children will be left parentless. Too many more
won't reach their first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Esther had three children of her own. The youngest died in 1998
at 19 months. Two of her sisters, Naipiri and Maria, also died of
AIDS. So did Esther's third husband. And her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as she herself was sliding into the advanced stages
of AIDS, Esther traveled several hundred miles north to Malawi to
find her orphaned nephews and nieces. She walked, hitched rides
with truckers, and sometimes literally crawled. She had very little
money and almost no food. Not only did she find her sisters'
children, but she also took in three other AIDS orphans.
</P>
<P>
   Once back in Zimbabwe, they lived in a tiny room in a row of
shacks wrapping around the back side of her house. Esther and the
children had to sleep head to toe on a cold floor. They had no
electricity and no money. When she wasn't too sick to stand up, she
sold popsicles to buy bread.
</P>
<P>
   The response to her story was immediate. People sent checks,
letters with $10 notes, and care packages. Island Hospice, an
outreach program in Harare, the capital, helped Esther set up a
bank account and find a new place to live. She still has no
electricity, and the children still sleep on the floor. But the
roof doesn't leak, and Esther has already planted a vegetable
garden out front.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in Esther's life, however, are tenuous. She and the
children look strong and healthy. The money in her bank account may
be enough to pay rent and school fees for a year. But the
government has cut her from its social welfare program, and Esther
has no work. She's searching for an old, nonelectric sewing machine
so she can sew clothes and bedspreads to earn enough for the
family.
</P>
<P>
   And people in the community prey upon her new position. Last
month a woman dropped two children at the house and asked Esther to
look after them for a hour. The woman never returned, and Esther
had to track her down. Last week, two other women and a child were
evicted from a neighboring house, and moved in with Esther.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the longer term, everything is still very uncertain for
Esther and the children,'' said Colletta Peta, a social worker at
Island Hospice. ``But then, they have never lived like this before.
People can be so kind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
