<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD, CHEAP CLEANER FOR LAMINATE FLOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have installed two laminate, faux-wood floors: one Pergo,
one WilsonArt. The spray cleaner sold by Pergo smells and appears
to be a solution of vinegar, alcohol, and water. Can you recommend
a homemade formula for cleaning these floors?
</P>
<P>
   DAVID SCHWOEGLER, &UR;  &LR; San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   A. Any heavy-duty cleaner such as Spic and Span will work well
with all laminate floors. Make a standard solution (for floors) of
Spic and Span and water, and wash the floors with this. Rinsing may
not be necessary (it seldom is with Spic and Span), but certainly
won't hurt. Almost any finish will dull from washing, but polishing
with a dry cloth will restore the gloss. There is nothing wrong
with the vinegar, alcohol, and water solution, except maybe odor,
which will dissipate quickly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to enclose an attached carport with full foundation. I
want to keep the gable roof, which runs into the roof of my ranch
house, to make the project less expensive. But contractors say they
can't dig the foundation hole with the roof in place. In other
words, they say the roof must go. My husband operates digging
equipment; could he shore up the roof and dig the foundation holes
himself?
</P>
<P>
   F.F., Everywhere
</P>
<P>
   A. It is not that the contractors can't, they don't want to. It
would be slow, fussy work _ and that costs money. Your husband, who
works with digging equipment, is a natural for the job. His first
assignment is to contact an architect or engineer to tell him how
to shore up the roof. That gabled roof is structural, a part of the
main house, and any structural work requires the approval of an
architect or engineer. It's the law. And, when digging out the
foundation, be mighty careful not to nudge any of the shoring posts
holding up the roof.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having a fence built with pressure-treated posts and
cedar rails and pickets. The fence man wants to put the posts in
concrete. Is that correct?
</P>
<P>
   ALBERT COMMITO, Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is not correct, in my opinion. In the old days, posts were
put in concrete for stability, but there was no way to keep water
from between the concrete and the post, so the posts rotted out
there in 10 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   Later, wooden posts _ be they pressure-treated, cedar, or any
wood _ were set in earth with several inches of gravel at the
bottom for drainage; the crushed stone helps keep water from
staying around the posts. And that is what your fence man should
do. Try to put the posts 3 feet into the ground; 2 feet is OK, but
not ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Since pressure-treated posts will not decay, there is no reason
to bury them in concrete.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a house full of radiators, and four nice radiator
covers. Is it still a good idea to put aluminum at the back of the
radiator? How about on the sides and under the top?
</P>
<P>
   PHIL NACHMAN, Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Any time you put reflecting metal such as those aluminum
sheets, you will get reflection of heat and light. Even shiny
aluminum foil will work. If you have a full enclosure, you can put
the metal on the back, sides, and under the cover. If you have only
a cover, then the metal goes behind the radiator and under the
cover. Dust the aluminum and keep it polished. A dirty and dull
metal will not do much good at all. The handyman has received a few
brickbats on this subject; one caller said that enclosures tend to
restrict the heat.
</P>
<P>
   They don't, if they have ample front openings. The right design
will increase the radiator's efficiency by distributing heat more
completely, without drafts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My back porch has teak floorboards and steps. The contractor
sealed the wood. Is that acceptable? And should I paint the deck
and steps?
</P>
<P>
   RICH LALLY, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, sealing is acceptable. No, do not paint; you will be
asking for a constant maintenance problem and ugly peeling.
</P>
<P>
   The sealer will make the wood water-resistant, which teak
already is to a great extent. To continue the sealing, it must be
done once a year, but at least there will be no peeling. You can
continue the sealing or simpy do nothing; the teak will turn gray
from weathering whether it is sealed or not. If you want a color,
use a semitransparent stain; one coat will do, and will last for
three to five years. The semitransparent stain will also seal the
wood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I noticed in a recent column you responded to a query about
the need to protect cedar decking from the elements. Do the same
principles apply to redwood decking? Can I leave it year after
year?
</P>
<P>
   KATHLEEN SMALL, San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think I said that cedar deck boards need protection;
the idea was that you could seal them if you wish. Sealing might
make them more weather-resistant, but would have to be repeated
annually. The same applies to redwood. You can leave it or seal it;
it will make little difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
