<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTOBER SLIGHT STILL SMARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ It was just after noon and, by that time, the
temperature was well into the 80s. Tim Wakefield, his blue T-shirt
flecked with sweat, had finished his workout. He sat on a bench and
began to speak. You immediately noticed the contrast.
</P>
<P>
   Body language: Calm. Relaxed. At ease.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken language: Hurt. Underappreciated. Still sorting things
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to come to camp bitter over something that
happened four months ago,'' the Red Sox pitcher said.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about the strange experience he had in October.
Red Sox manager Jimy Williams told him he wanted to meet with him
in private. ``I thought he was going to tell me I was starting Game
1 (of the American League Championship Series),'' Wakefield said.
Instead, the manager told him that he would not pitch against the
Yankees; he was being left off the ALCS roster. The words surprised
him and stuck with him.
</P>
<P>
   He began the season as a starter. Tom Gordon was injured and
Derek Lowe was not ready to be a closer, so Wakefield became a
stopper. When Ramon Martinez could pitch only three innings in
early September, Wakefield became a long reliever (six innings of
scoreless relief). He never guessed that he would become a
spectator, too.
</P>
<P>
   A month and a half after the season ended, he was still trying
to understand why he wasn't asked to help during the season's most
important series. Williams called him at home so Wakefield would
know where to direct his displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said if I wanted to blame someone, to blame him,''
Wakefield said. But he isn't sure who made the playoff decision.
``I don't know,'' he said with a shrug. ``I just work here.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was precisely the problem in October: work. All men who
throw knuckleballs are used to the work. Lots of it. There are only
two knuckleballers in the Hall of Fame (Phil Niekro and Hoyt
Wilhelm). Niekro pitched until he was 48, threw more than 5,400
innings and had 19 seasons in which he lasted 200 innings or more.
So, no, you can't call these guys slackers. But they are certainly
among the most misunderstood athletes in sports.
</P>
<P>
   They grip baseballs with finely manicured fingernails. They
deliver the ball so slowly and smoothly that they look like
synchronized swimmers in their follow-throughs. They can pitch on
five days' rest, four days' rest or two days' rest. They can save a
tired staff. Unfortunately for them, they also happen to be the
masters of the most underrated pitching category: innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Wins are supreme and strikeouts are sexy, but 200-plus-inning
guys are necessary. You know what 200-inning guys are? The
fullbacks of baseball. You don't realize how important they are
until you don't have one.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have already acknowledged the importance of Wakefield.
He is expected to be part of the rotation this year. Exclusively.
The Martinez brothers will lead the rotation, followed either by
Wakefield or Jeff Fassero. Wakefield said staying in a starter's
routine will be more pleasant than flopping between the bullpen and
rotation. He will also be helped by Niekro, who is expected to come
to City of Palms Park next week and be his tutor.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the first time that has happened. In 1995, his first
season with the Sox, Wakefield would phone the Hall of Famer for
Knuckler Pointers. Phil and Joe Niekro also worked with Wakefield
after he was released by the Pirates. Phil Niekro briefly worked
with him in '98, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (Phil) over the winter and saw him at his
brother's golf tournament,'' Wakefield said. ``I called him once.
He was a very busy person'' because of shows and appearances. It's
clear Wakefield is anticipating a nice knucklers' retreat when
Niekro arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he was talking about goals of 15-20 wins and 200-plus
innings. A lot of pitchers can't mention that number of innings so
casually, he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 20 years ago, guys threw 300 innings and it was no big
deal,'' he said. Later, he joked that his goal was to have 30
starts and 30 relief appearances in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   (Aren't you glad that we are even discussing baseball at this
point? I am thrilled to be here and, I promise, the 83-degree
temperature _ mostly sunny, 5 percent chance of rain _ only has a
little to do with it.)
</P>
<P>
   Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan bounced from pitcher to pitcher
and hitter to hitter Tuesday. He saw Williams's son, Brady, talking
with a few other players and shouted, ``You guys hitting?''
</P>
<P>
   Before they could answer, Kerrigan volunteered, ``I'll throw to
you.'' So they dragged out a batting cage and went to work.
Kerrigan watched young pitchers throw. He long-tossed with Brian
Rose and was so impressed with one pitch that he paused, shook his
head and said, ``Now that's beautiful.'' Eventually, he moved on to
Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   They were in the field together for a long while. Wakefield said
there was no ``clearing of the air'' over the October incident, but
you got the feeling something was said. By the end of the day,
things were back to normal. Someone asked Wakefield if he could
throw nine innings right now, on the spot. He smiled and said,
``Sure could.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
