<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING AT MARRIAGE . . . WITH CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, Mom and Dad, how was your Valentine's Day?
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 18-month-old twins, the last thing I wanted to do was
light candles and break out the china,'' says Megan Dupes of
Plymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romance is at the bottom of the heap,'' says Barbara
Lynn-Davis of Cambridge, Mass., whose daughter just turned 1.
</P>
<P>
   That probably sums it up for most couples who are also parents.
Who has the time for romance? Who has the energy?
</P>
<P>
   Just because we are busy married people with children, however,
does not mean we are doomed to a romance-free marriage that grows
more distant or eventually fails. While studies show that having
children speeds the decline of marital satisfaction, it's not as if
not having children keeps a marriage alive: On average, all
relationships deteriorate over time.
</P>
<P>
   But there are 10 to 15 percent of parents who report an increase
in satisfaction in all aspects of their marriage after their
children arrive, says psychologist Kristin Lindahl of the
University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, what do we have to do to be among them?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, these are partners who know better than to hope
that having a baby will salvage a bad marriage, says Lindahl. To
the contrary, these couples already have a strong marriage. They
face parenthood with realistic expectations, including knowing
their relationship will continue to change throughout the active
parenting years; function as a team and support each other; and
place a priority on working on their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   It's this last piece that gets most couples in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking time for each other is probably the most important
thing you can do,'' says researcher Pam Jordan, a nurse and
associate professor at the University of Washington in Seattle who
counsels couples as they become parents.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, putting marriage before children is not part of
the American culture. ``It feels selfish,'' she says. Parents
typically tell her, ``How can we get a sitter when we've both been
working all week and the kids have been in day care and we haven't
had any quality time as a family?''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's answer is that time spent focused on each other is time
invested in your children. ``It's your relationship together that
creates a context for the family,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   There is such a high correlation between the quality of the
parents' relationship and children's well-being that researcher
Carolyn Pape Cowan can predict how young children will do in school
by looking at their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couples who take time to nurture each other are more able to
nurture their children. Couples who nurture each other also have
children who are less preoccupied with worry about family
dynamics,'' says Cowan. She and her husband, Philip, are in the
vanguard of research on how marriages thrive after parenthood and
have followed more than 200 couples for eight years, since the
birth of their first child. They are co-authors of ``When Partners
Become Parents,'' revised edition (Erlbaum), and co-directors of
Becoming a Parent Project at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the strain parenthood puts on partners doesn't
disappear once a baby sleeps through the night, or starts to talk,
or uses the potty. Pass one hurdle and new ones appear: which day
care, which preschool, what bedtime, what sport?
</P>
<P>
   How you cope with each new issue depends, to a large extent, on
the history partners have for dealing with conflict, says Jay
Belsky, who is also known for his research on the transition to
parenthood. He says couples whose marriage remains strong tend to
have:
</P>
<P>
   --Realistic expectations. ``In the old days, the wife expected
to do everything, and she did,'' he says. ``Today, she expects her
partner to do more, but she hasn't relinquished control
proportionate to her expectation.'' At the same time, Father is
happy to no longer have the pressure to always know best, but still
frequently wants to be able to exert that authority. ``Both sides
have given up territory,'' says Belsky, but they haven't
necessarily figured out how to work within the new landscape.
Resentment and anger build not only because there are different
expectations, but because the expectations don't get verbalized. In
the most typical scenario, it's the wife who feels put upon. ``She
thought they would be sharing equally,'' says Cowan. ``Most couples
can't and don't.''
</P>
<P>
   --A division of labor that feels equitable, even if it doesn't
look that way. Alan Dupes, for instance, doesn't pull much of his
share during the week: He works full time and goes to school three
nights. But he tries hard to take the twins on an evening or on
Saturday morning so Megan has time to herself. That may not seem
like much of a trade-off, but it means a lot to Megan, who handles
her frustrations by making sure she has emotional support (she's
active in the parenting programs at nearby Jordan Hospital, where
Alan has also attended dads' classes) and by telling herself he
won't be in school forever. ``We're a team,'' she says, ``and this
happens to be what we need to do right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That would draw kudos from Jordan. ``If you don't think of
yourselves as a team, it's a setup for blaming your partner for
things not being the way you want them to be,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   --Rose-colored glasses. ``Imagine you're the wife,'' says
Belsky. ``Your husband lets you sleep in, but you awake to discover
he dressed the baby in the same chocolate-stained top she wore
yesterday. You can say, `She can't wear that top, it's filthy!' or,
`Thank goodness she's dressed.' '' The difference, he says, is
between having a partner and a helper, between sharing and
micromanaging. To Belsky, this is the single most important trait a
couple can have. Megan Dupes agrees. ``Since Day 1, my theory has
been that whatever my husband does, it isn't wrong, it's just
different,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when these differences can be huge, of course,
because men and women look at parenting at least partly based on
the role models they were raised with.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a man looks at what he's doing, he's comparing himself to
his father, who didn't do anything with the kids,'' says Belsky.
``He's saying to himself, `Wow, what a great dad I am!' '' The
mother, meanwhile, is comparing what he does to what she does and
concluding, ``You don't do anything around here!''
</P>
<P>
   If couples could freeze-frame the moment and talk _ What made
you say that? What were you thinking? _ they might better
understand each other's perspective and defuse tension. Often,
that's all you need to do, says Belsky. He is the author of ``The
Transition to Parenthood'' (Delacourt) and a professor at
Pennsylvania State University, on leave at Birkbeck College in
London.
</P>
<P>
   As simplistic as it sounds, making time to talk is the antidote
every researcher recommends, beginning with the birth of the first
baby and never letting up.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan recommends formal, weekly dates. ``The idea is to not
lose touch as friends,'' she says. Otherwise, says Cowan, ``You
find yourselves on opposite sides of an issue with no idea of how
you got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because you make time to communicate doesn't mean it always
has to be heavy-duty or nonbaby conversation. Barbara Lynn-Davis
says that more often than not these days, she and husband Michael
Davis relate to each other through the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Alan and Megan Dupes haven't left the house as a couple in four
months, but they do have dinner alone four nights a week. Although
they purposefully set this up as a time to talk and reconnect,
they're often too exhausted even for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll eat in front of the TV,'' says Alan. ``But even that's
nice. Just to sit and be peaceful together.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Talk on the phone from work, send e-mail, find other small
gestures to express your love. Researcher Pam Jordan's favorite
anecdote is of a woman who would pack her husband's lunch each day,
then take a bite out of his sandwich. ``It was her way of saying,
`I'm with you even though I'm not with you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   --Don't wait for your partner to do something extraordinary to
praise him or her. Find something kind and supportive to say each
day.
</P>
<P>
   --A good way to get time together, especially an overnight, is
to trade babysitting with a neighbor or friend.
</P>
<P>
   --It's not unusual for many months to go by before some couples
resume sex after a baby is born. That typically doesn't create
lasting damage as long as you find other ways to be close, like
hugging and snuggling, and sharing how you feel emotionally,
researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Is your child's car seat used correctly? Ninety
percent aren't. During National Child and Passenger Safety Week,
it's a good time to check out tips from the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration's Web site, www.nhtsa.dot.gov. Safe
Kids is another resource at www.safekids.com. Also check out your
Governor's Highway Safety Bureau for child safety seat check points
this week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
