<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-17 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE BELIEVE IN MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our family's just wild about Harry. Potter, that is.
</P>
<P>
   I spend an afternoon a week with each of my grandchildren.
Jessie, 8, and I are in the middle of building a dollhouse while
Danny, 5, and I are exploding volcanoes, but after a while we set
aside our projects and head upstairs to curl up on my bed and enter
Harry Potter's world together.
</P>
<P>
   All of J. K. Rowling's books about the magic in our midst are on
the bestseller list. Is there anyone who hasn't heard about the
Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, where Harry and his
friends study charms and spells while fighting off the evil forces
around them? The appeal of these books has been spread far and wide
by word of mouth, but the words out of my mouth are spoken aloud.
</P>
<P>
   These books are better shared than savored alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie and I are working on vocabulary, although she doesn't
know it. The story's so engrossing that she doesn't want to miss a
single nuance. Professor Binns, who teaches History of Magic, bores
his students into a ``stupor.'' Jessie wants to know what that is,
the difference between ``mortal danger'' and ``peril,'' and what it
means when Uncle Vernon shows no signs of ``relenting.'' Rowling's
vocabulary is challenging; ``valiant,'' ``demonic,'' ``artifacts,''
``slouched,'' ``torpor,'' ``spawn,'' ``jaunty,'' and ``dumbstruck''
all show up before Page 40, but these thrilling words not only
enhance Harry's adventures, but increase our pleasure in them. It's
as if Rowling has dipped her language in a tincture of magic. Each
meaning I disclose to Jessie adds to its enchantment.
</P>
<P>
   I simplify for Danny, skipping or switching to an easier
vocabulary. He'll hear them in context when his family listens to
the books on tape. Danny's interested in motivation, which often
baffles him. Why would Uncle Vernon, saddled with an unwanted
nephew for the summer, get meaner when he found out Harry wasn't
allowed to use magic outside school? Why would anyone think
children from old wizard families were better than those born to
Muggles, or ordinary folk? Danny wants to know why the kids try to
solve their own problems instead of going to adults for help. The
story can be dark and disturbing. He needs to be reassured
frequently that good will triumph over bad.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of Rowling's success is that she's dealing with real
life. Gussied up in outlandish costumes, it's still recognizable.
What does it do to some people when they have power over you? What
is snobbery all about? Why are people mean? Jessie and I are racing
through while Danny and I move more slowly. He wants to figure out
why Harry's friend Ron is ashamed of being poor and why Harry
hasn't given him some of the gold he's inherited from his parents.
As Danny comes to understand Harry's world, he's making sense of
his own. He's solving mysteries other than those of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, reading together isn't only preparing Jessie for the
verbal part of the SATs, or helping Danny come to grips with the
complex and scary world of the 21st century. We laugh a lot. And
we're starting to notice more and more magic in our world.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Danny showed up one afternoon with a lasso tied to
his belt. Why? He had no idea, but the chapter we read that day had
to do with Harry and his friend Ron having to de-gnome a garden, a
task similar to weeding. The technique involved catching the gnomes
and swinging them by their feet in great circles ``like a lasso,''
until they were too dizzy to find their way back to their
gnomeholes. Danny and I agreed it was no coincidence that he was
prepared to practice swinging imaginary gnomes in my living room.
Magic was clearly at work.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie and her mom, meanwhile, visited an antique dollhouse shop
in search of furniture. The old woman behind the counter sniffed
that Jessie was much too young to touch a single object in her
shop, but when Jessie turned on her charm, the old crone suddenly
smiled, shuffled into the back room, and located a small box of
dollhouse treasures she actually gave Jessie as a gift, including
three miniature books, one crystal goblet, and an ice cream cone on
a china plate. Surely, this was a witch who recognized a kindred
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``All kinds of strange things are happening to us these days,''
I confided to Jessie the other day. ``Our family may not be Muggles
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessie gave me a look halfway between faith and skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   She almost believes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
