<HEADER>
A9812 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-17 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING VANDALS OUT OF YOUR PC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The message on the computer at my church wouldn't have meant
much to the ladies in the next room sorting canned goods for the
weekly food giveaway. But to me, it was like stumbling across a
serpent in a garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system's silent NetBIOS over TCP/IP (NBT) Internet Server
is actively advertising its existence across the Internet and thus
inviting equally silent connection and intrusion into your
system,'' the message read.
</P>
<P>
   A fancy way of saying ``Busted!''
</P>
<P>
   I'd just used Shields Up, a fascinating free Internet service
run by programmer Steve Gibson that tests the security of
Internet-connected computers like the one at my church.
</P>
<P>
   I'd visited Shields Up at grc.com. A few seconds later, I got
the worrisome results. There on the screen was my name and the name
of the church's internal computer network, both available to any
cunning scavenger on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, our church computer is connected to the Internet
through a high-speed DSL line that can remain connected around the
clock, and thus constantly exposed to computer vandals. Good thing
I'm in the habit of switching it off when it's unattended.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, some cracker might have tried a bit of nastiness,
like installing a ``denial-of-service'' program and using it to
attack some other Web site. That's the trick used by the vandals
who made front-page news last week.
</P>
<P>
   So far, their planted programs have been found in the computers
of some major universities, rather than at Baptist churches. But as
millions of us start using DSL and cable modem connections to the
Internet _ leving our machines powered up and dialed in all the
time _ we too will become targets.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. makes it all too easy. The Windows 95 and 98
operating systems found on most home computers have a feature
called NetBIOS that's designed to let several machines at the same
location talk to each other. The trouble is that once you log onto
the Internet, NetBIOS exposes the contents of your computer to a
world of nosy people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the other major operating systems, like Unix, Linux, and
Apple Computer Inc.'s Mac OS, have flaws of their own. None of the
popular operating systems are ``hardened'' _ designed from top to
bottom to be extremely difficult to subvert. Hardened systems are
harder to use. So faced with this choice, software makers generally
opt for simplicity over security.
</P>
<P>
   The security holes can be plugged, though, with a piece of
software called a firewall. All the communications between your
computer and the Net travel through software settings called ports.
Each port has a number, and there are over 65,000 of them. But the
standard Internet services almost always use the same ports. Web
pages come through over port 80, for instance, while Usenet
bulletin board messages use port 119. A firewall basically opens
the ports for permissible types of data, like Web pages, and closes
the others.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, a gross oversimplification. Many a thick
book has been written on the finer points of firewall
configuration. Besides, a firewall won't do any good if someone has
already loaded a hostile Internet program on your computer, using
it to hammer some other server on the Net. Firewalls target bad
data coming in, not going out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a start. And there are some reasonably simple and
cheap firewalls for amateurs. The antivirus company Symantec Inc.
offers Norton Internet Security 2000, a $60 Windows program that
throws in antivirus protection and privacy defenses, such as cookie
blocking. Not only does it block the usual ports, but it can also
be used to detect programs on your machine that are making
unauthorized attempts to send data over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Zone Labs Inc.'s ZoneAlarm does the same, and it's downright
ruthless about it. The software is available at www.zonelabs.com.
The first time you run it, ZoneAlarm won't even let your browser
access the Web without permission. And yet ZoneAlarm is fairly
simple to use and has the advantage of being free for home and
nonprofit users.
</P>
<P>
   Just the thing to protect an innocent Baptist computer from the
wickedness of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can contact me at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
