<HEADLINE>
FOR CAR SELLERS, IT'S SHOOTOUT TIME IN DOT.COM CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The inquiries come in an inexorable flow over the electronic
transoms of fax and e-mail. They are not about ABS, SUVs,
transmissions, tires, engines, nuts, bolts, child restraint seats,
or road rage.
</P>
<P>
   They are each, instead, the same question from some PR person
somewhere: Wouldn't you like to write a story about some new auto
Web site (kicktires.com, bounceonseats.com, snakeoil.com,
feelyoungagain.com, buycars.com)? They are so numerous I feel like
an armadillo on a Texas highway filled with roaring, 10-wheeled
dot-coms. I scuttle out of the way and let the traffic pass.
</P>
<P>
   It's shootout time in Dot-Com City, and customers, automobile
manufacturers, and dealers are either targets or caught in the
crossfire. It is the dealers feeling the heat the most right now.
They've got to have individual dot-com capabilities but they fear
what widespread dot-com trade could do to their business.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from this year's annual convention of the National Auto
Dealers Association indicate that, for the second year in a row,
dot-com business was the talk of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintive wail from dealers: Don't let us get dot-commed by
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Your local auto dealership is a tangible Web site that you visit
in person. You browse. Click onto a car by kicking the tires. Open
a window by pulling on a door handle and climbing inside. For FAQs,
turn to a salesman. If you like the answers, you click on OK. If
you don't, you are the curser. It has long been thus.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   And that has dealers trembling. There are now third parties,
many with virtually no retail auto sales experience, trying to get
into the business of selling cars directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   You would think that NADA, with nearly 20,000 new car and truck
dealers holding 40,000 separate franchises, would have met the
challenge head-on and immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a lag. First, they had to fight off a potential
threat from another flank _ the manufacturers, who as of last
year's convention were still threatening to take their cars to
consumers directly over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That threat arose even as dealerships were setting up their own
Web sites showing inventory, financing plans, prices for parts,
service specials, and other offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers, meanwhile, were giving potential consumers such
information as suggested retail price, options, vehicle specs, and
consumer advice.
</P>
<P>
   Some independent sites, operating with dealer cooperation,
became ``brokers'' for dealers who cooperated with them.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, consumer service sites _ such as Kelley Blue
Book _ made it possible for potential buyers to walk onto any
showroom better informed than ever and ready to move on at click
speed if they didn't like what they heard.
</P>
<P>
   It all had to make dealers nervous.
</P>
<P>
   They got some relief: Several states passed laws protecting
franchised dealers. And by the time this year's NADA convention
rolled around, big automakers such as GM and Ford were vowing to
stand by their dealers and not sell cars directly to consumers on
line nor to sell franchises to Web site operators. How long the
latter can last, I'm not sure.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, according to the Automotive News, many potential
e-dealers and many millions of dollars were in play at this year's
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the threat, the magazine posed, of a computer
billionaire buying up dealerships across the country and using his
own electronic engine to drive sales, ``selling vehicles nationwide
via flatbed truck.''
</P>
<P>
   It could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of convention participant Brain Stafford who
came to town representing Trilogy Inc., a Texas software provider
that already has jumped into appliances, employee recruitment, and
gift registration.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford has no auto retailing experience, Automotive News said,
but he did arrive ready for a shootout: He had $100 million stuffed
into his holsters, looking to corral automobile franchises, mostly
of the small, rural (read inexpensive) herd.
</P>
<P>
   This would provide a platform for sales that would at least
mimic manufacturer-to-dealer-to-customer.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure how long the manufacturers' promises to not let the
franchises be sold to these dot-com providers would hold up in
court.
</P>
<P>
   After all, once the practice of established franchises selling
directly over the Internet has become commonplace _ and it is
happening already _ how can it be possible to keep out legitimate
business people who want to buy into the action and do the same
thing?
</P>
<P>
   Would it be fair to tell franchise holders that they cannot sell
the businesses they have bought and built to someone who will
operate them in many similar ways?
</P>
<P>
   And, once the ball is rolling, how long will manufacturers be
able to stick to a vow of no direct Internet sales as they watch
third parties doing what they could be doing themselves?
</P>
<P>
   It's a scary time for dealerships, no doubt. But it is not a
time for anybody to even blink, let alone bury their heads in the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   The dot-com shootout is under way and dealerships and
manufacturers, if they want to continue to be players, need to play
with their strengths.
</P>
<P>
   I see a parallel here with my business, newspapers. Information
is the foundation of this business. No matter how it gets
delivered, folks who can gather, organize, and cogently present
information are valuable. That's why combinations of print media
and Internet sites are valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Now look at auto dealerships _ the bricks, glass, repair shops,
showroom floors _ as the foundation of that business. True, the
manufacturers roll out the product, but once it leaves their hands,
it is doubtful that, even in a high-tech future, many people will
buy new models of autos based only on photos. They're still going
to want to at least go kick the tires _ even if they return home
and do the purchase on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the manufacturers are still going to need places that
will service and repair the products they sell.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no reason, even though it means monumental change,
that dealerships can't remain players in all these areas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
