r e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-STEPSISTE     02-17 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-STEPSISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETELLING OF CINDERELLA STORY TANTALIZES THE IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GLORIA MAZURE  
 c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hobbling home under a mackerel sky, I came upon a group of
children. They were tossing their toys in the air by turns telling
a story and acting it too.''
</P>
<P>
   The passerby, an old woman, pauses to rest, unnoticed by the
youngsters, and hears a play about a pretty girl _ scorned by her
two plain stepsisters _ who goes to a ball and meets a prince who
adores and romances her.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story that resembles her own. ``I can peer at it as if
at a painting, through the rheumy apparatus of the mind. ...''
</P>
<P>
   As the aged lady continues to listen, she is carried back on the
tale's threads to a corner of her memory. There, her own family
tale begins _ in a time without the magic of pumpkins and glass
slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus opens ``Confessions of an Ugly Stepsister'' (Regan Books,
368 pages, $24), a new book by Gregory Maguire that offers a
retelling of the Cinderella story.
</P>
<P>
   The tale, set against a backdrop of Holland in the 17th century,
is one of deception, beauty, enchantment and luck as an
impoverished widow and her two daughters are taken in by a Flemish
painter.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire quickly serves up a helping of adventures mixed with
fanciful situations and wry observations. ``In fairy tales, rats
turn into human beings. In reality,'' the author observes, ``it's
far more common for human beings to turn into rats.''
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a journey, tempest tossed on the shores of
imagined history, in which the reader bobs along in the wake of the
unexpected. The story's path, strewn with divergent whimsy, is
dappled throughout by a contrast of opposites. Calm becomes stormy,
plagues replace placid times, fabulous balls transform bad times.
We are drawn to anticipate one thing, and another comes to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The tale opens upon a weary trio _ Margarethe and her daughters,
Iris and Ruth _ as they arrive in a small town in the Netherlands
after escaping trouble in England. Their hopes of finding rescue
with a relative are quickly dashed and the abandoned trio turns to
village residents for help.
</P>
<P>
   They face slammed shutters and unhearing ears until the village
artist, Master Schoonmaker, offers them lodging in exchange for
errands and housekeeping. Among the artist's penchants are
recording the religious dictates of the times and portraits of the
wealthy, and documenting ``the gallery of God's mistakes.'' He also
does his part in sheltering and helping lost souls.
</P>
<P>
   After a time, Iris poses for the artist and gains, through an
artist's eye, new views on life. As the reader is drawn along, Iris
learns much about herself, art's hidden values and life's unwritten
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The story's scenes are all painted with a tincture of the times
_ settings, social structures, ways of life _ even the philosophies
of the day. We become privy to the ways and needs of the locale and
its inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   An engaging array of people is depicted in bright, lively
descriptions, including those with shriveled arms, or humped backs,
or elderly moving like a ``splay-leg bug skittering over the
surface of a pond.'' This is a book for lovers of words.
</P>
<P>
   And also for lovers of high spirits. A wonderful tangle of human
foibles and weaknesses is wound in with the strengths and wonders
of the characters we meet.
</P>
<P>
   Fate swirls its cape over the story's vivid landscape of events.
When the town roads ice over, all the residents turn out _ boys and
men playing games, skaters twirling, oldsters falling, fieldmen
fishing. ``As far as the eye can see along the curve of the river,
tiny pegs of people, in black and gray and red.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the festivities, Iris greets an old woman she has dubbed
the Queen of the Hairy-Chinned Gypsies, who appears throughout the
book to sprinkle about her oblique wisdom. Iris teases the old
woman about her blustery fierceness and the idleness of the threats
she makes. In the book's cryptic mix of humor and counsel, the old
crone off handedly retorts, ``It's your job to change yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Fate also changes lives. Iris uses her ability to speak English
and Dutch to befriend and tutor a merchant's beautiful daughter,
Clara. Later, through a tumbling of time, Clara becomes Iris'
stepsister.
</P>
<P>
   Margarethe sums up her change in social situation in becoming
betrothed to the well-off father of Clara as knowing ``when to
jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Maguire has a wonderful knack of turning the tables on
well-known fables _ and shifting our comfortably seated
expectations. He managed a similar sleight of mind two years ago in
his debut novel, ``Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch
of the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Maguire beckons readers to leave the familiar niche of fancy and
fantasy and enter his realm of reality, where events alive with
village ways and new vantage points blend with history, religion
and, in this story, an artist's brush mirroring the human state.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of skimming the surface of a story to yield a bare-bones
philosophy, readers must look deeper into the times, traveling
through layers and a larger bite of history, its causes and
controversies. Nestling the stories in their era's events adds a
sense of reality and dimension to the characters, making it
possible to ponder the past as well as the characters' travails.
</P>
<P>
   But where does the familiar Cinderella story come in? During a
time of economic catastrophe, preparations for a grand ball
surround a visit by the famed, though aging, Marie de Medici. She
is coming to town to sit for a portrait and, perhaps, to procure a
bride for her nephew.
</P>
<P>
   The stirrings of the village gossip mill reach even the
beautiful Clara, always reclusive, who has taken refuge in the
kitchen as she grows up, finding comfort among the cinders. Iris
urges her stepsister, Clara, to venture out to the ball. When Clara
says she is not ready to be seen, Iris counters, ``Like me, you are
ready to look.''
</P>
<P>
   And, from there, the rest of the story is just a coach ride
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
