<HEADER>
A9823 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      02-17 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ECHO _ A SOUND CAR FOR A NEW GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's this? A brand new subcompact in an age of behemoths. A
stingy sucker of fuel in a time of massive swilling? A small
four-seater in a day when if you're not hauling eight or nine
people, you're just not in the flow?
</P>
<P>
   Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   They call it the Echo _ as in Echo Boomers, the children of Baby
Boomers _ and Toyota has this car aimed squarely at them. When
Toyota killed the Tercel a couple of years back, some wondered if
the car maker would be out of the subcompact arena. Since then,
Toyota obviously realized that as its Camry generation aged and
remained loyal, they'd need a subcompact to haul in younger
loyalists. This is it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wedge of a car that looks much like the Prius, the
soon-to-the-market electric/gasoline hybrid. Like the Prius, it's
got economy and environment written all over it. They should paint
them all one color: green.
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, it is remarkable to see the cab-forward design
so common to big Chryslers featured in a subcompact. There's a
reason for this (more on that later). Its hood slopes up steeply as
the lines carry very high over the roof and drop down to a high,
chopped trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Climb inside, and the first thing you notice is the instrument
cluster: a crushed oval, slanted toward the driver, at center dash.
It's a simple, elegant little thing holding the speedometer, gas
gauge, and a ring of warning lights. The gauges are black-on-white
and wonderfully retro _ think Porsche or Chrysler 300M.
</P>
<P>
   The legroom up front is deceptively good, given that the dash
seems to rise straight up from the floor. There is surprising
legroom in the rear, as well, for the two passengers it holds back
there.
</P>
<P>
   The seats look low and flat as you gaze at them through an open
door, but when you climb into the driver's seat, you feel as if
you're sitting high, almost like in a van. This is where that
cab-forward treatment adds to the feel; you have to rise a bit to
even see the hood, giving that snub-nosed van aura.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to it is remarkable headroom _ think Ford Focus _ that
continues all the way back.
</P>
<P>
   You're dealing with an inexpensive car here, so don't expect
automatic windows. And in the two-door model tested, even the door
locks were manual, baffling my young friend and
mornings-to-the-school-bus passenger Diane Romano, all of 12, who
had to be shown that in some cars, you need to pull up the lock, as
opposed to clicking an automatic button.
</P>
<P>
   The seats were flat, firm, and wide enough to be supportive and
comfortable. The 60/40 split rear seat folds and gives entry to the
trunk, which is virtually cavernous for a subcompact car.
</P>
<P>
   It's powered by a 1.5-liter, DOHC, 16-valve, 4-cylinder engine _
all aluminum with steel liners _ that delivers 108 horsepower, 15
more than the old Tercel. Going green, it gave me just over 36
miles per gallon in a mix of highway, city, and country driving.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed manual transmission was tight and smooth, and the
engine, small as it is, handled upshifts with grace.
</P>
<P>
   Suspension has struts and an antiroll bar up front, with a
torsion beam axle at the rear. This is not an advanced system, but
we're looking to save some money here. You'd expect a car with this
setup and a high roofline to give you body roll when cornering at
speed, and that's what you get. But this was not meant to be a
sports car, not designed to be blasting through turns or weaving in
and out of traffic at high speed.
</P>
<P>
   It is meant to be reliable, comfortable, and utilitarian. The
Echo is all of these.
</P>
<P>
   It was remarkably smooth on my pitted country road, took frost
heaves with noticeable thumping sounds but no real jolts inside,
and moved in and out of highway traffic at good commuter speed.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the middle of what was a very windy week, it held its
own against the icy blasts thrown at it, keeping on line when you'd
expect a car this size to get tossed about some.
</P>
<P>
   It's got disc brakes up front, drums in the rear, and they are
plenty to bring this lightweight to easy stops. Antilock brakes are
an option, and I'd go with them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with a base price of $9,995, there are a lot of options
worth looking at (and I'm not sure you'll find one Echo out there
offered at $9,995). Good marketing starting point, but probably not
rooted in reality.
</P>
<P>
   The two-door I tested had among its options power steering, air
conditioning, an upgraded sound system, a sports package, an
all-weather package with heavy-duty battery, and intermittent
windshield wipers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these options you'd want anyway, which means you're up
over $12,000 _ still cheap in a day when $30,000 cars are
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   This car will compete with the Chevrolet Metro, Hyundai Accent,
and other subcompacts. But if you like comparison shopping, I'd run
this against the Ford Focus and then make my decision.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The porthole air vents at the sides and center of the dash.
Rotate them in any direction and you change air flow. Simple and
easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The front door on the two-door is a bit narrow so it's not as
easy as it should be getting into the front seat and downright
tricky getting into the rear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $9,995 &QL; 
Price as tested: $12,946 &QL; 
Horsepower 108 /Torque: 105 lb-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 93.4 inches / 163.2 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 65.4 inches/ 59.1 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 2,128 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 4 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
