<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CENSUS-PROMO-$ADV20-C     02-17 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-PROMO-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENSUS GOING ALL-OUT TO PROMOTE PARTICIPATION
 &HT;    920&AMP;add. For release Sunday, Feb. 20.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How do you get millions of Americans to do
something they are not inclined to do?
</P>
<P>
   Begin with an advertising blitz, including precious TV air time
during the Super Bowl. Then call on the help of an even higher
authority, the kind who wear priestly robes and preach fire and
brimstone.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the U.S. Census Bureau wants all the help it can get,
even prayers.
</P>
<P>
   From the neighborhood church pulpit to network prime time,
chances are good that over the next month you are going to hear
about the importance of responding to the Census 2000
questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   This year's once-a-decade tally is the most complex and costly
ever. The bureau will spend $4.5 billion as it seeks to count some
275 million citizens and millions of undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high: Census data are used to determine how
congressional seats are apportioned and how billions of dollars in
federal money are distributed among the states.
</P>
<P>
   The count has become more difficult in rapidly changing America,
with a booming immigrant population unfamiliar with the census and
traditionally mistrustful of government. There's also a large
segment of middle America too busy and too easily distracted, who
are likely to allow their census forms to languish among the junk
mail before they get around to filling them out.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Census Bureau is using paid advertising
to get the message out after a disturbing drop in the mail-in
response rate. Only 65 percent of households responded in 1990 down
from 75 percent in 1980 and 78 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is on to avoid a repeat of 1990, when an estimated
8.4 million people were missed, most of them minorities and
children. That cost some states additional congressional seats and
badly needed money for school, roads, parks and other social
services.
</P>
<P>
   Targeted, multi-lingual ads, aimed mainly at minorities who are
less likely to fill out the form, began airing last fall. The
prime-time push to reach them and a broader TV and radio audience
begins later this month. By March, the agency will become the
nation's third largest advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   Among the spots: a teacher conducts her class from a broom
closet, the result of undercounted children and thus the lack of
new and needed classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't be able to get away from us,'' said Terry Dukes,
executive vice president of the ad giant Young &AMP; Rubicam, which is
managing the $167 million campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Census also is relying on the volunteered services of
clergy, schools, politicians, civic leaders, professional athletes
and others to spread the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a profoundly important issue. If we want to make good
decisions about where we're going, we first have to know exactly
who we are,'' President Clinton said from the White House last week
during an orchestrated Census event.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Patrick Flores of Texas, a leading spokesman for
Hispanic Catholics, will dedicate Mass on Sunday (Feb. 20) in San
Antonio to the census, a service broadcast weekly to some 8 million
Spanish-speaking viewers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Census Director Kenneth Prewitt will attend the service, and
address brief remarks to the two central themes: The count is
important to deliver tax dollars to your neighborhood, and
confidentiality is assured _ in other words, the Census Bureau will
not be sharing your identity with any other government agency.
</P>
<P>
   As the bedrock of community life, particularly in black and
Hispanic neighborhoods, churches across America will help deliver
the message. The Census Bureau has even provided ministers, priests
and rabbis with suggested announcements _ essentially talking
points from the pulpit _ on how to remind parishioners in March and
April of the need to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's join together in this important effort,'' the Census
Bureau recommends that the clergy tell their congregations on
Sunday, March 26. ``And make sure our community is represented in
the census.''
</P>
<P>
   The census has used churches, schools and community centers in
the past to promote its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Census in the Schools'' programs will reach some 1 million
classrooms in an effort to enlist children, particularly those in
immigrant and low-income families, to convince their parents to
fill out and return their Census forms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, other paid advertising and promotions are coming
from a variety of special-interest and minority groups with a stake
in seeing a better count.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of messages from myriad sources has the ad
professionals fretting that the result could be mind-numbing
overload. ``That is something that we're going to be watching
closely. ...That risk of: Will we get turned off? That's a good
question,'' said Dukes.
</P>
<P>
   But better too much than not enough, Census officials say. Among
the problems in 1990 was the Census Bureau's reliance upon donated
time for public service announcements, which mostly aired late at
night or at other periods of slim audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the agency's task was a decision by the U.S. Supreme
Court last year that raised the stakes by forbidding the Census
Bureau from using statistical models to fill the projected gaps in
the undercount for the purposes of reapportioning congressional
districts.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no guessing, however scientific it may be. The
Census Bureau must make every effort to count every man, woman and
child.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In October, the Census Bureau awarded its advertising contract
to Young &AMP; Rubicam, whose corporate clients include Ford and AT&AMP;T.
The ad agency set about formulating a campaign unlike any other it
has ever done.
</P>
<P>
   While most companies seek to sell their products to people who
are inclined to buy them, the Census Bureau needed to tailor its
message to people who are reluctant or uninterested in filling out
the questionnaire. Thus, the Census Bureau needed a different sales
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that kept coming back to us again and again in
our research is that being counted means absolutely nothing to
people. Of the people who think about it at all, only a very small
percentage of mainly older Americans consider it as a patriotic
duty. What motivates most people is: What's in it for me?'' said
Dukes.
</P>
<P>
   To build a demographic model of their target audience, the ad
agency turned to existing data on the types of people who do and
don't participate in their local PTA, those who try to avoid jury
duty and those who do it but don't necessarily want to.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they identified three distinct groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ The largest, 43 percent of the population, are dubbed
``undecided passives.'' They may fill it out or not, but feel no
compelling reason to do so.
</P>
<P>
   _ The second group, at 40 percent, are those most likely to
respond. These are mainly white-collar, middle- and
upper-middle-class homeowners familiar with the census.
</P>
<P>
   _ The third group, at 17 percent, are those unlikely to fill out
the form at all, including immigrants, Native Americans and others
highly distrustful of government.
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam took the lead in producing the themes for its
campaign to reach broad and reluctant middle America. It also
coordinated the effort among four subcontractors, ad agencies which
specialize in reaching African Americans, Hispanics, Asian
Americans and Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   By late March, chances are that most Americans will have been
exposed to at least 50 census ads on TV, radio or in print. Among
minorities, the exposure rate is at least twice that.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the census campaign is like a election campaign.
The Census Bureau and its ad agency won't be able to fully gauge
its effectiveness until the returns are in.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of putting this campaign together was inventing it for
the first time, which is why research played such a big role. We
really don't have an opportunity to get it wrong. It's a big
number, and a big public number,'' said Dukes. ``We had to be very,
very smart about how we handled this.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
