<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9826 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-NICARAGUA-DEMOCRACY-2     02-17 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICARAGUA-DEMOCRACY-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER DECADE OF DEMOCRACY, NICARAGUA STILL STRUGGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: For photos to accompany this story, call the San Antonio
Express-News at 210-250-3297.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ How times have changed. Daniel Ortega, the
unrepentant Marxist and nemesis of President Ronald Reagan, is
getting his nose powdered.
</P>
<P>
   A film crew from Canada is doing a documentary on the Nicaraguan
Revolution. Ortega is wearing his favorite colors _ khaki pants and
a crisp T-shirt with the United Colors of Benetton printed across
his chest. But the former Nicaraguan revolutionary leader is
fidgety and uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long is this going to last?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers want the mustachioed, legendary bad boy of the
1970s Cuban-style revolution to look, well, not so revolutionary.
Speak from the heart, they urge him.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega, however, can barely crack a smile. For him, the
revolution is too recent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great challenge of the Sandinistas is to regain power. In
1990, we lost the revolution,'' Ortega, 54, said in an interview
after he finished with the film crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still looking to destroy us, but we are still in the
ring fighting to mend the course of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely the course will change. At the end of the Cold
War, after the crumbling of the Soviet Union and the Berlin Wall,
Fidel Castro's Cuba is the only Communist holdout in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Nicaragua, once the flashpoint of Reagan's anti-Communist
agenda, has slipped from the world stage. The Contras _ the
U.S.-backed militants fighting Ortega and his revolutionaries _ and
other players of the long, messy war are but fading memories.
</P>
<P>
   But change comes slowly in this lush land of lakes and
volcanoes, of sweet rum and strong coffee, where decades of civil
war, dictatorships, earthquakes and hurricanes have conspired to
starve the masses _ and enrich a few.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the 21st century, transformation is creeping in
on Nicaragua, a nascent democracy of 4.7 million people, struggling
to rise above crippling poverty, the autocratic habits of its
political elite, a long history of U.S. intervention and the
devastation of Hurricane Mitch in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For Ortega and his Sandinista National Liberation Front, the
second-largest political party in the country, it has been a long
haul from guerrilla to legislator.
</P>
<P>
   The middle-aged Sandinistas, now wielding cellular phones
instead of machine guns, are not really in vogue. And Ortega has
lost much of his personal magic.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas land reform and literacy drives were among his goals,
Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman, of the center-right Liberal
Constitutional Party, has embarked on a free-trade course to
attract foreign investors and beef up the nation's primitive
infrastructure since taking office in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a firsthand look as the country makes the transition is
Oliver P. Garza, who was named U.S. ambassador to Nicaragua in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, this country was almost a Cuban-model state,''
Garza said. ``Look how long it took the United States to become a
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All these countries are in a state of evolution. They need
time to grow,'' said Garza, a Texan who has been a diplomat in
Mexico, Colombia and Panama. ``We should not rush to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Second to Haiti as the poorest country in the Western
Hemisphere, Nicaragua has $6 billion in foreign debt, made harder
to pay since Hurricane Mitch, which caused $1.7 billion in damage
to roads and crops, not to mention lives and memories. About 18,000
people were left homeless, and 3,000 were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman, calling his country's external debt ``eternal debt,''
says it is going to take 60 years to repay it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to demonstrate is that we are a serious
government,'' Aleman, 53, said in an interview. ``We are trying to
take care of rural poverty, create incentives for production,
investment, a basic market economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a caravan of speeding vehicles, sirens wailing and a cloud of
dust behind them, Aleman and a government entourage comb the rocky
countryside virtually every day, opening new schools, housing for
hurricane victims, electrical power plants and potable water
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Banners with his slogan, ``Works, Not Words,'' are up all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the fanfare is to ensure his party's victory in the
next election. Others disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he zipped through the community of El Tanque, 60 miles
northwest of Managua, and dedicated 167 cement-block homes for
hurricane victims.
</P>
<P>
   In this flat land, the cornfields are the only relief from the
sun. In the background is the San Cristobal volcano, which has been
spewing ash for two months. Next to it is the Casitas volcano,
where a white barren scar runs down the middle, evidence of the
mudslide that buried 2,000 when Hurricane Mitch blew into Nicaragua
and neighboring Honduras in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big tomb. Hundreds are still buried there,'' said
Red Cross worker Orlando Abellan.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of El Tanque are happy after Aleman's visit. They like
the new two-room homes, painted bright yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Alonso Rueda and his wife, Mariana Centeno, lost more than 50
family members when a river of mud swept down the volcano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost everything: parents, children, cousins, nephews,''
said Rueda, 72. ``We rescued only two adults and four of our
children's children.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them is 10-year-old grandson Marvin, his body slashed with
inch-thick scars carved by debris.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Aleman makes routine rounds, he now is in Sandinista
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that boy Daniel (Ortega) cared more for the poor,''
said Mariana Centeno. ``We had more work. There were more jobs. Now
we have nothing, just what we can grow.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby town of Posoltega, several hundred people, mostly
farmers, are living in plastic tents donated by the Red Cross and
the U.S. government. They have been waiting for new homes for more
than a year. They watch the volcano with wariness and fear the
month of April, when rains begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't gotten even a grain of rice,'' said 36-year-old
Justa Flores, who lives in a tiny tent with her husband and nine
children. ``I planted marigolds, so I wouldn't be surrounded by so
much misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever they can, families get odd jobs. They even return to
the volcano, where land is fertile, to plant maize, beans and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aid has been slow going. A lot of countries are
contributing aid, but the damage is such that it's going to take
time,'' said Ambassador Garza.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend among the poor is to occupy land anywhere they can.
I talked to one person who lost all his family except one. And he
still farms the land where his house was. Because it's theirs,''
Garza said. ``It's hard to get people out of flood plain areas.
Moving a whole town, it's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. government policy toward Nicaragua is to strengthen its
democratic institutions, and Garza has said there needs to be
``transparency'' in government _ that is, no corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan supported by the International Monetary Fund,
Nicaragua is a candidate for debt relief, a project under which
developed nations write off money owed _ albeit with strict
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The United States forgave most of Nicaragua's $248 million debt
after the 1990 election ousted the Sandinistas. Since 1998,
Washington has provided about $200 million for debt and hurricane
relief.
</P>
<P>
   But as democracy takes root, accusations of sleaze and illicit
enrichment abound.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
