<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-NICARAGUA-DEMOCRACY-2     02-17 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICARAGUA-DEMOCRACY-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 MANAGUA, Nicaragua: x x x illicit enrichment abound.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing has raised more suspicion than the recent deal Aleman
made with Ortega, once bitter enemies, to change 17 articles of the
constitution. Among them are immunity from prosecution for outgoing
presidents and vice presidents and a permanent seat in parliament.
The agreement also nudged aside so-called ``microparties'' that
received government funding, even if they weren't formal parties.
</P>
<P>
   The pact also reduced the percentage vote needed to win the
presidency, from 45 percent to 40 percent, which could give the
Sandinistas a better shot in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the deal creates a formidable two-party system that
an outsider could have a hard time ousting.
</P>
<P>
   Without the pact, Aleman said, he had no peace from the
boisterous Sandinistas, who were forever staging demonstrations
against capitalist changes, including the privatization of
government businesses. Since 1991, more than 350 state institutions
have gone public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were strikes, protests. So we called our opponents to
sit at the table and not at the barricades,'' Aleman said. ``That's
the way to act with the opposition _ civilized. Don't the
Republicans and Democrats make agreements all the time? Nicaraguan
people want to live in peace. Our only enemy is misery, poverty and
unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Aleman said, the pact does not mean there is new-found
love with Ortega, who jailed Aleman during the Sandinista
government. Aleman's wife died of cancer while he was imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sandinistas now appear to be good, nice, more saintly than
Ghandi,'' the president said. ``But they will never again return to
power. I would rather die.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amid the controversy is a scandal involving Aleman himself, who
is accused by Comptroller General Agustin Jarquin of
influence-peddling and enriching himself.
</P>
<P>
   Jarquin filed charges in the National Assembly in January
accusing Aleman of using the presidency to buy thousands of
state-owned coffee plants and fruit trees at radically reduced
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm accused of buying property? It wasn't a gift. I didn't
steal it. I bought it. Is the president not a citizen?'' Aleman
said. ``My grandfather was a coffee grower. My father was a coffee
grower. I'm a coffee grower. If they are so ready to accuse me, let
them prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding irony to scandal is the fact that Jarquin, believed to
have political ambitions as well as popularity, just got out of
jail himself. He was placed under temporary arrest for allegedly
paying a reporter to investigate corruption under Aleman.
</P>
<P>
   Nicaraguans don't know what to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The economy and polls so far favor Aleman. Under his
administration the economy has grown 5 percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Managua, virtually destroyed by a 1972 earthquake and ignored by
years of civil war, is seeing a bit of a boom. Roads are being
paved, avenues widened and luxury hotels are going up.
</P>
<P>
   For Ortega, however, the capitalist road leads to corruption of
the rich and destitution for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   He admits mistakes. He's sorry he controlled agricultural prices
and did not allow a free market, and he said he failed in
consolidating land reform.
</P>
<P>
   As happened during Cuba's revolution, the Sandinistas
confiscated hundreds of properties from the wealthy and distributed
them among the poor _ and among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are about 800 cases in court, with Nicaraguans and
American citizens demanding the return of their properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not able to establish a socialist state, but we
started a liberal democracy, with all its negative elements,''
Ortega said. ``I'm not satisfied, but Nicaragua will never again
resort to arms to change a government. And we did that. We also
made the United States look differently at Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After overthrowing in 1979 the U.S.-backed regime of Anastasio
Somoza, the patriarch of a family dynasty that ruled despotically
since 1937, the Sandinistas faced a more formidable enemy _ Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   He froze aid to Nicaragua in 1981, imposed a trade embargo and
forces in his administration embarked on the relentless Contra war,
financed by selling arms to Iran, to topple Ortega.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega won the presidency with 64 percent of the vote in 1984.
But the Contra war took its toll.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Sandinistas held new elections, which they lost to
a U.S.-funded coalition headed by Violeta Chamorro de Barrios,
widow of popular la Prensa newspaper publisher Pedro Joaquin
Chamorro, who had been killed by Somoza.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega said he lost for two reasons: the economic hardship of
the Contra war and the 1989 U.S. invasion of Panama, which put the
fear of an almighty ``American empire'' into Nicaraguans. He said
his popularity dropped afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Sandinistas lost again to the center-right Liberal
Constitutional Party, a conservative group led by Aleman, the
former mayor of Managua, who won with 52 percent of the vote. The
Sandinistas came in second with 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Sandanistas have 36 seats in the National Assembly,
while Aleman's Liberals the presidency and 46 seats in the 90-seat
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sandinistas were organized to be in power, but not to be
an opposition party. They had no democratic training,'' said Sergio
Ramirez, a lawyer and former vice president under Ortega who broke
with the Sandinistas in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't understand the situation. They lost in 1990, lost
even bigger in 1996 and will lose again a fourth and fifth time,''
said Ramirez, now an author.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are now a traditional party,'' said Ramirez, who also
teaches literature at the University of Maryland. ``They don't have
the mythical sheen of the revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides a new political climate, Ortega was hurt by allegations
by his stepdaughter, Zoilamerica Ortega Murillo, now in her 30s,
that he had sexually abused her since she was 11.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega denies the accusation, calling it ``slander and infamy''
to hurt him politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been so hard on my family. Because she is not only
the daughter of my wife, she is the sister of my children,'' he
said. ``But I'm used to being accused of things all the time. I can
still give much to the country, with a lot of enthusiasm, vitality
and hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
