<HEADER>
A9833 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i BC-NICARAGUA-ENVOY-HNS &LR;      02-17 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICARAGUA-ENVOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ENVOY WIELDS INFLUENCE IN IMPOVERISHED NICARAGUA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: For photos to accompany this story, call the San Antonio
Express-News at 210-250-3297.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ He's our man in Nicaragua, no stranger to
political intrigue, drug violence and international disputes.
</P>
<P>
   He is Oliver P. Garza, who was named U.S. ambassador last
September in one of the most troubled and poorest nations in the
Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taken aback at what I saw from the ride to this
residence, at how much poverty you could see,'' Garza said from his
home. ``More in comparison to anywhere else I've been.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been to many places, having served as a diplomat in
Mexico, Colombia, the Dominican Republic, South Korea and Uruguay,
among others. A graduate of St. Mary's University in San Antonio,
ex-drug enforcement agent and veteran diplomat with a plenty of
experience in strife-torn countries, Garza hasn't wasted any time
in getting to know Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately delved into the subtle _ and not-so-subtle _
predicaments and complex politics of this emerging democracy mired
in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly meets with the president, with would-be presidents,
ex-presidents and players from all ideologies. He has visited
practically every corner of this New York state-sized nation,
talking to farmers, construction workers, housewives and hurricane
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Garza is one of the highest profile personalities in Nicaragua,
where the American government has been vilified or beloved,
depending on events of the times and who is in power.
</P>
<P>
   It is said there are two people here one visits to get things
done: Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, historically beyond
ethical reproach, and the U.S. ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know now how the cardinal feels,'' said Garza, referring to
the long list of people who daily request an audience to complain
about this or that or to ask for help.
</P>
<P>
   One moment he is having a private lunch with President Arnoldo
Aleman, and the next he is receiving a shipment of U.S. aid for
victims of a devastating hurricane in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first. His morning routine: up before 6 a.m., a
walk through the grounds _ hoping for a peek at the residential
peacock and giant lizard. Then he hits the newspapers and makes
coffee with his wife, Yolanda.
</P>
<P>
   He stunned the help by insisting on grinding and brewing his own
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   He comes to the post at a crucial time for Nicaragua, a
democracy only since 1990, when elections ousted the left-wing
government of the Sandinista National Liberation Front headed by
Daniel Ortega, who still aspires to regain power.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first people Garza went to meet was Ortega, a bitter
enemy of the United States since he was a teen-ager opposed to
American involvement in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandinista talk is still colored by revolutionary talk from
the Socialist line. They are looking to get back to power, but they
are going to have to adjust their words and economic outlook,''
Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sandinistas have changed, but you continue to see Daniel
Ortega going back to the same rhetoric, traveling to the old Soviet
block countries,'' Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Garza, the son of a farm laborer, has found an
admirer in Ortega, from humble roots himself.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the new ambassador, Ortega, who rarely smiles, got a
big grin across his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good meeting with Mr. Garza. I'm glad that we have
someone with Latin-American roots, a Hispanic, as ambassador,''
Ortega said. ``It will facilitate communication with the United
States, my country and the Sandinistas. We hope to maintain and
develop this relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sandinistas, once a large army of 80,000, have dwindled to
about 14,000. Garza said they pose no threat and have evolved
mostly as a police force, similar to what happened to Panama's
National Guard after the 1989 U.S. invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider the numbers that existed, Nicaragua has gone
far,'' the ambassador said. ``The army has been responsive to
democracy and civilian rule.''
</P>
<P>
   In a fledgling democracy, public bickering, accusations of
corruption and political maneuverings are all too common. They are
rampant now in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, 57, writes much of it off to growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them: `You elected them. You don't like it? Vote them
out! That's what a democratic process is all about.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
