<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-PEET-FEATURE-LAD     02-17 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PEET-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, AMANDA PEET IS WEARING A GUN (AND THAT'S ABOUT IT)
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's about half an hour into ``The Whole Nine Yards.'' Matthew
Perry, who plays a neurotic Montreal dentist, has been waving his
arms and pratfalling all over the screen. Bruce Willis has been
striking terse, insinuating tough-guy poses as the hit man next
door. Michael Clarke Duncan, ``The Green Mile's'' gentle giant,
plays another professional criminal and has been filling up much
empty space.
</P>
<P>
   But just as you're about to write the film off as a desperate
``Analyze This'' wanna-be, an unexpected presence suddenly raises
it to an hilarious new level. Willis gets interesting. Duncan gets
interesting. Perry's slapstick becomes funny.
</P>
<P>
   It appears as if the whole movie has been lifted on the slender
shoulders of Amanda Peet. The self-effacing, 28-year-old actress
says no, of course not; she's working with comic masters here, and
she's just a stage-trained dramatic actress from one of those WB
network youth soaps.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the movie's writing and timing does get sharper right
around the time that Peet's perky character comes into her own. But
there's no discounting her contribution to that process, either.
Not since Samuel L. Jackson and John Travolta debated the merits of
French fast food has so delightfully distinctive a contract killer
appeared on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonathan Lynn kept telling me that, if Jill weren't aspiring
to the profession that she is, she would be a cheerleader,'' says
Peet. ``Just bubbly and enthusiastic and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran British farce director Lynn (the BBC's ``Yes,
Minister,'' ``My Cousin Vinny'') knew that the part _ which, in
``Nine Yards''' ethically upside-down universe, is also the closest
thing to the movie's conscience _ required adroit presentation.
</P>
<P>
   And an extra something special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key to someone who is so fundamentally amoral is
that they must be played by an actress who you automatically
like,'' Lynn says. ``It's a beautifully written role, of course,
but Amanda brought what was there on the page to life with her own,
unique, quirky personality. And she has such charm.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, the actress says that she was just striving not to
look ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to do but scary, because I had to figure out a way
not to show how silly I thought she was,'' explains Peet, whose
training included a stint with the legendarily serious acting
teacher Uta Hagen. ``I learned from Bruce and Matthew and Jonathan
about how important it was to bring precision to comedy
performance, building gags bit by bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Peet is hesitant to make a spectacle of herself. In
fact, while Jill's cheerful personality and oddball sense of right
and wrong make the performance memorable, audiences aren't likely
to forget the scenes Peet plays wearing nothing but a .38 and a
megawatt smile either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did full-frontal nudity on stage before,'' Peet reveals,
``and, really, I was the least nervous in that scene, the most
grounded. It's kind of like a counter-phobia feeling that I brought
to this. When the camera rolls, and you're with someone the
magnitude of Bruce Willis, you're already scared. But then, when
you do something that's even worse, it belittles the original fear.
In a way, that's very liberating.''
</P>
<P>
   And that registers fully on screen, despite obvious
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amanda was very relaxed about it,'' says Lynn. ``She must be
one of the very few people in the world who could play a nude scene
and be funny at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing ``Nine Yards''' uninhibited Jill was a behavioral 180
from Peet's day job on TV's ``Jack and Jill'' _ in which, as if to
prove the point, she plays Jack. And Jack, essentially, is a dull
girl, an uptight, aspiring New York journalist who, at midseason
anyway, is involved with someone but in love with someone else, an
upstairs neighbor played by Ivan Sergei (his character's last name
is Jillefsky _ get it?).
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack's sort of a control freak, a la Meg Ryan in `When Harry
Met Sally...,'' Peet says, invoking another idol in her vast
pantheon of role models. ``I try to be really anal, have a lot of
Post-It notes around and stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to play,'' she says. ``But no more or less so than
the woman in `Nine Yards.' What's fun is having a hook, a thing
that you can commit to. I want the opportunity to play characters
with doubts and flaws. There's a weird thing with actors, maybe
especially with women, that's all about being appealing. But I
think that's the biggest trap. Anything that gets you away from
that kind of vanity can only be good for your work.''
</P>
<P>
   Peet is well aware that there's irony in a statement like that
coming from one of network TV's pretty young faces. In fact, she's
too smart to miss the absurdities that are part and parcel of an
actor's life. The daughter of a Manhattan lawyer and a social
worker, she studied American history at Columbia University before
sharpening her focus on acting, which she'd been dabbling in since
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of rejection eventually led to stage work, appearances on
``Seinfeld,'' ``Law and Order'' and ``Spin City,'' and parts in
such films as ``One Fine Day,'' ``She's the One,'' ``Body Shots''
and last month's ``Isn't She Great.'' Although set in her hometown,
``Jack and Jill'' is the first job that's prompted cross-country
relocation.
</P>
<P>
   And Peet is seriously homesick. Although, typically, she takes
an absurdist view of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all like a suburb,'' she says of L.A. ``And when I see
palm trees, it's very strange, especially during Christmas and New
Year's. The cotton snow everywhere ...''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the weather's better.
</P>
<P>
   ``No!'' she huffs with comic exaggeration. ``It's like a weird,
bad dream!''
</P>
<P>
   All right then. Peet does the petulant thing funny, too, and
we're likely to see more of that in her next movie, ``Whipped.'' A
comedy about three con men who all fall in love with the same
woman. The picture is currently rated NC-17 solely for its frank,
sexually charged language.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bizarre that they're taking seriously the impact of
language in a movie that, tonally, verges on spoof,'' Peet says.
``The movie overtly does not condone or hero-ify what is being said
but rather makes buffoons out of the people who say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And because it also involves women talking very graphically
about sexual matters, that's probably particularly offensive to the
ratings board,'' she adds. ``We're not supposed to be discussing
those things _ or having any of those preoccupations.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the ``Whipped'' controversy's final outcome may be, the
movie is a hit with Peet. She met her boyfriend, actor Brian Van
Holt (CBS' ``Love &AMP; Money''), on the production.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Peet hopes to develop her obviously natural
gift for comedy while nurturing and deepening her dramatic
abilities. She'll always be serious about acting, but she's
discovering that the only way to get better at it is to have
serious fun with the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comedy is so hard, but I'm learning more and more that so much
of it is about relaxation,'' Peet explains. ``For a long time, I
think I thought I was really good, but really I was terrible
because I was trying to orchestrate things. You can't do that,
because the camera sees it, and the audience sees it _ it takes you
out of the moment, and it's not fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell when an actor's really reveling in something and
when they're just planning and indicating what's happening. It's an
ongoing struggle to get that right, but I genuinely find it
fascinating.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
