   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIVER-DISEASE (Undated) _ After successful experiments with
mice, scientists say they have found what could be a promising way
to treat cirrhosis of the liver, an intractable condition that is
the seventh-leading cause of death in the United States. Reporting
in the journal Science, the researchers say they reversed symptoms
of liver failure in mice by activating production of telomeres, the
appendages on chromosomes that act as a kind of aging clock for the
cell. By Nicholas Wade. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTEROID (Washington) _ NASA gets the first data back from
the NEAR satellite, which this week became the first spacecraft to
orbit an asteroid. By Warren E. Leary. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-LONGEVITY (Undated) _ A gene known to govern the rate
of aging in yeast cells has been found to be active in mice,
yielding a new insight into why mice and people age and into
possible ways of enhancing life span. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-AVALANCHES () _ At least 33 major avalanches have struck
south central Alaska in recent weeks, bringing a cycle of fury and
danger that, even by the Last-Frontier standards of a state where
awesome natural power is continually on display, has been
extraordinary. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RAIL-MERGER (Montreal) _ For much of the last century, the
Canadian National railroad helped define Canada. But now Canadian
National plans to merge with a giant American railroad, the
Burlington Northern and Santa Fe, and its focus has shifted to the
south. The merger underscores how far the formation of a true North
American economy has developed in the six years since the North
American Free Trade Agreement went into effect. Although they may
be less visible, the auto, banking, and telecommunications
industries already operate on a north-south axis and pay hardly any
attention to borders. Not everyone accepts the vision of the new
railroad or the changes it represents. In the United States,
shippers and unions want to derail the deal. In Canada, shippers
and farmers are concerned, while nationalists see the proposed
merger as the loss of a revered national symbol. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FED-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the
Federal Reserve, warns that the economy is in danger of overheating
even after the central bank has raised interest rates. In comments
that are certain to bolster expectations that the Fed will continue
a series of quarter-point rate increases this year, Greenspan said
that there was ``little evidence'' that the economy is slowing and
that the prices of stocks, homes and other assets were being pushed
ever-higher and raising consumer demand beyond the economy's
ability to produce goods and services. Stocks, which had risen
sharply before his testimony on the back of a weaker-than-expected
producer prices report, reversed course after Greenspan's testimony
before the House Banking Committee. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-STOCK (Undated) _ Looking at the recent decline in America
Online's stock price. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were mixed in mid-afternoon. At 2:20
p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was down 13 points, but the
NASDAQ composite was up 95 points. Treasury prices were mixed, with
the long bond up a bit in price but the shorter maturities lower.
European markets were higher: London up 0.13 percent and Frankfurt
up 1.46 percent. The Nikkei closed up 0.98 percent and the Hang
Seng ended down 0.36 percent. Crude oil slipped below $30 a barrel,
at $29.38. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FTC-MERGERS (Undated) _ Robert Pitofsky, head of the FTC, is
expected to announce a tightening of how the commission reviews
mergers because companies are increasingly proposing more elaborate
and troublesome schemes to win approval for blockbuster deals. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
