<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-JUDDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDDS REUNITE AND ARE ON THE ROAD AGAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional trim included) 
 
By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A quick check of the answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael, it's Naomi Judd and I'm calling earlier because I'm
excited. It's quarter after 10 a.m. I'll call you back.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to describe Naomi Judd isn't easy because she is a woman
who has lived many lives. A few identities can be tried on for
size, and all of them would fit well.
</P>
<P>
   _ Survivor: As a divorced mother of two in the mid-'70s who
broke free of an abusive relationship and took care of her
children, she could be said to have survived a rough single
motherhood. It's also a description fitting to her winning battle
with hepatitis C, which sidelined her from performing in 1991. Her
body is now rid of the affliction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Entrepreneur: After she and daughter Wynonna started singing
country lullabies as the Judds to anybody who would listen, the duo
landed a recording contract in 1983. Their first single, ``Had a
Dream'' (For the Heart), went Top 20 on the country-music charts.
Soon after, they had a string of eight consecutive No. 1 hits and
became the most successful female country-music duo in history.
</P>
<P>
   _ Proud: As in proud mama. Following Naomi's retirement from
performing, Wynonna continued with a successful solo career that
has included several platinum albums and three No. 1 singles from
her self-titled debut. She just released ``New Day Dawning.''
Naomi's other daughter, Ashley, has become a big-ticket movie star,
appearing in the movies ``A Time to Kill,'' ``Double Jeopardy'' and
the recently released ``Eye of the Beholder.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Plucky: After an eight-year hiatus, a healthy Naomi Judd
reunited with Wynonna in the studio, and the Judds recorded four
songs. The tracks _ including the Naomi-penned barn-dance romp
``Big Bang Boogie'' and a cover of Jesse Winchester's ``That's What
Makes You Strong'' _ are included as a bonus CD with Wynonna's
``New Day Dawning.''
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, on New Year's Eve, the Judds performed together for
the first time since 1991's farewell tour. They have extended the
tour through March. and included a date at the Houston Livestock
Show and Rodeo, where they will perform Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   All are apt descriptions, but none suit Naomi Judd as well as
``personable'' does. Her rags-to-riches-to-sickness-to-health story
is the stuff miniseries are made of and has given her a
spirituality and day-to-day joyfulness that most take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Another check of the answering machine 10 minutes after the
first message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael, have you seen `Eye of the Beholder' yet? It's really
good. This is Ashley Judd's mother _ sometimes known as Wynonna's
mother, too. So take your wife or poopsie-woopsie to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did I mention that she is market-savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Answering the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael, I finally found you ... ''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many situations that Naomi Judd can't relate to
because, at some time in her life, she has dealt with them all.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, she wears lavish designer gowns on stage now, but she
recalls living in Marin County in the San Francisco Bay area on
deloused mattresses while studying to be a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get back (to the Bay area), sometimes I'll rent a
hunk-a-junk car, go out with my hair up and no makeup on and visit
that old apartment,'' Naomi says. ``When I put on a $6,000 gown
now, I cackle because I remember when I had three dresses to my
name.''
</P>
<P>
   When she finally made it to the top of country music and had
wealth and all of life's comforts, she contracted hepatitis C,
sometimes referred to as chronic liver disease. There was no amount
of money that could help her because fewer than 10 percent of
hepatitis C cases make a complete recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Riches and celebrity couldn't save Naomi, but they were
certainly going to do all they could. After traveling the country
looking for cures, she now counts some of the leading surgeons and
hepatologists in the United States as friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very grim disease,'' says Naomi, who is now the
spokesperson for the National Liver Foundation. ``I think I've
become somewhat of an inspiration _ not to the patients, but to the
doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first to help Judd was a psychologist, Dr. Blair
Justice, who is based at the University of Texas Health Science
Center in Houston and the author of the book ``Who Gets Sick.''
Naomi met with him following a Houston concert on the Judds'
farewell tour.
</P>
<P>
   Justice had never heard of Naomi or the Judds, but he couldn't
believe that she was touring with hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to meet me after the show and he said, `You're not
going to put on pantyhose, brush your hair and perform,''' recalls
Naomi, who says she was fatigued at nearly every stop.
</P>
<P>
   She continues, ``Afterward he shook his finger at me and said,
`You little stinker. I know what you're doing. You are using this
support to keep you going.' And he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judd has other ties to Houston _ memories that make playing the
rodeo a joy even though the Judds won't have the time to perform
their whole show on their own stage.
</P>
<P>
   While she is now happily married to former Elvis Presley sideman
Larry Strickland, during a separation years ago, she went on a
blind date with ZZ Top's Billy Gibbons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we had in common was a love of old cars,'' Judd
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Touring in 2000 is different for the Judds from what it was in
the old days. The women no longer move from town to town in the
``Judd-Mobile'' eating pinto beans and corn bread at truck stops.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi and Wynonna each have their own bus, and now Wynonna is
the single mom traveling with her two toddlers, Elijah and Grace.
She divorced her husband, Arch Kelley, last June.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi describes Wynonna's bus as a day-care center, while hers
is a peaceful valley of candles and aromatherapy. She's ecstatic to
be on the road again, happily married and enjoying the careers of
her daughters.
</P>
<P>
   At the New Year's Eve show in Phoenix, Naomi even joked with
Ashley about her roles in movies in which she plays murderers or
bares skin.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, it appeared that a rift was forming among the Judds
about morality, but on stage in Pheonix as 2000 rolled near, she
just shook her finger at special guest Ashley and said, ``You're
grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   After being broke and a single mom, after superstardom, after
critical illness, Naomi is just happy to be and is making no
promises about what the future might hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just keep putting one foot right in front of the other,''
she said. ``Right now I feel fab-u-lous.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the best word to describe her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
