<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NY-REPUBLICANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK CONSERVATIVE RECONSIDERS SUPPORT FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Frustrated by what he called a ``pattern of
pandering'' by George W. Bush, one New York congressman says he is
``seriously reconsidering'' his support for the Republican
presidential hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Rep. Peter T. King said, a ``significant'' number of
Republicans in the state also are quietly questioning Bush's
viability in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing discontent,'' King, a conservative Republican from
Nassau County, said from his Washington office on Wednesday. But he
added: ``How far they're going to go, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   King's announcement came as Bush, the governor of Texas, faces a
hard-fought primary race in South Carolina after suffering a
19-point loss to GOP rival John McCain in New Hampshire two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, Bush and McCain are locked in a statistical
dead heat, according to a Zogby International poll released
Wednesday. In New York, the Texas governor holds a 44-37 percent
edge over McCain, who was behind by 19 points last month, according
to a Quinnipiac survey.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican Party spokesman Dan Allen said he knew of no
New York Republicans who are backing away from Bush. ``I'm
surprised to hear that,'' Allen said of King's comments,
``especially considering how much support at the grass-roots level
that George Bush has. ... If anything, we've been getting even more
calls that people are gung-ho for him.''
</P>
<P>
   King said he was troubled by several recent Bush comments and
appearances _ most notably his visit to Bob Jones University, a
Christian institution in South Carolina that bars interracial
dating and has harshly criticized the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this whole pattern here of pandering to anti-Catholic
elements,'' said King, who is Catholic. Bush was also wrong, King
said, to align the Nation of Islam with faith-based organizations
during a television interview and to describe the Northern Ireland
peace process as ``falling apart'' in Tuesday night's GOP debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am seriously reconsidering my support,'' King said. ``I try
to have a sense of loyalty, but the loyalty is really being
stretched right now.''
</P>
<P>
   However, King said he was neither prepared to immediately break
ranks with Bush or to back McCain, the senior senator from Arizona.
King first came out for Bush for president in May as part of an
elaborate endorsement ceremony staged by New York Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor probably did the right thing at the right
time,'' King said. Asked if he thought Pataki still should support
Bush, King said only: ``The governor can think for himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
