<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `ALLY': JUST ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ We are watching ``Ally McBeal'' and trying (as
we always do) not to talk to the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   We watch ``Ally'' now and then because it is a phenomenon. Its
characters, plot lines, special effects and peculiar buzzwords have
become a major part of the national cultural fabric.
</P>
<P>
   We do not watch ``Ally'' because it resonates for us personally.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this failure to connect is due to an age gap. Ally and her
eccentric pals are in their early 30s at most; we are 50.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe we don't connect because we have this quaint
idea that even a semi-comic show about a young, supposedly
intelligent woman lawyer ought to have more than just trace
elements of female input on its creative team of producer, director
and writer.
</P>
<P>
   We know that Ally's creator and Svengali, the prolific David
Kelley, has long insisted that his title character is not meant to
be anybody's symbol of new womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   But, as ``Ally McBeal'' has insinuated itself into the
collective consciousness _ and amassed a warehouse of Emmy, Golden
Globe and People's Choice awards _ we also know that SOMEHOW the
big-eyed, elfin Ally and other female characters on the show have
come to symbolize a brand of new womanhood: They are all fabulous
looking and as capable in their professional lives as they are
desperate, bumbling or coldly manipulative in their personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ally is such a part of the national Zeitgeist, we do
something different when we watch it: We keep our finger off the
remote control mute button and make ourselves listen to the
commercials. (We think you can tell almost as much about the makeup
of a hit show's audience from its ads as you can from the show
itself.) On this night, we are struck most by a light-beer
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not the one that features a pair of idiot, bar-camping
babes on the perpetual make. Neither is it one of a series in which
non-speaking (but always large-breasted), bar-camping babes simply
decorate the scene of ``Preppie Dudes Just Want To Have Fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this light beer commercial opens with a babe _ all
clingy dress, long legs and mounds of luxurious hair _ sitting next
to a good-looking man on a train.
</P>
<P>
   The man peruses the babe with a smarmy, arrogant glance that
immediately labels him as ``Loser.`` Then, with the assured aplomb
of James Bond, another good-looking man, sitting across the aisle
from the babe, orders a specific brand of light beer.
</P>
<P>
   The train enters a tunnel and the screen goes dark for a few
seconds. When the lights come on, the now-beaming babe has moved
across the aisle and has her arm linked through the arm of the man
who is drinking his light beer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite our best intentions, we begin to talk to the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect,'' we groan. ``This is not only woman-as-trophy, it's
trophy that can be had for the price of a watery domestic beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not even the price of a beer! The woman has no beer. She's
starry-eyed and all-his just because HE'S drinking the watery
domestic beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, we remember reading a magazine article about what is
and is not intended by today's cooler-than-thou young advertising
wizzes. Most campaigns are meant as ``jokes, exaggerations,'' said
one successful wiz. Their primary aim is merely ``to grab
eyeballs.''
</P>
<P>
   That reminds us of something else Kelley told Goodman in 1998:
``It's not our intent that everyone is supporting Ally every week.
But at the end of the week ... you're still involved with her. You
may be frustrated for being so, but we hope the audience comes
back.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they have.
</P>
<P>
   After all, like the babes-and-beer ads, ``Ally McBeal'' isn't
about role models, aspirations or inspiration. It's just
entertainment. An exaggeration. All in harmless fun. Right? We must
remember not to take it so seriously.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0136 </DOCNO>
