<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-APPLE-LAPTOP-HNS &LR;      02-17 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-LAPTOP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     APPLE PLANS HEFTIER iBOOK IN SHADES OF GRAY  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT BEER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apple Computer Inc. has announced improvements
to the company's product line, including a beefier iBook laptop
that has double the memory and hard-drive size of the previous
model.
</P>
<P>
   The new machine's gray-hued color theme runs counter to the
existing two orange and blue portables. The ``tangerine'' model has
been less popular than the ``blueberry'' version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers have been cringing at the orange model,'' said Louis
Mazzucchelli, an Apple analyst at Gerard Klauer Mattison &AMP; Co. in
New York. ``This should get rid of those concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The new iBook (graphite in color) will sport 64 MB of RAM, a 6GB
hard drive and a 366 MHz processor. It is on shelves this week at a
cost of $1,800.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jobs, the company's chief executive, said Apple would
double the memory and disk size of the existing $1,599 tangerine
and blueberry iBook models without raising the price. The 300 MHz
processor also remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, who made the announcement in at a conference in Tokyo,
also introduced an upgraded Powerbook, the company's business-grade
laptop. The new machines will sport 500MHz and 400MHz processors at
$3,499 and $2,499, respectively. They will include high-speed
``firewire'' ports, with which users can transfer
professional-quality digital video to and from digital camcorders
or external hard drives, and built-in ``airport'' capability, with
which they can connect to the Internet wirelessly.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs also announced a speed boost to its Power Mac G4 line. The
500MHz, 450MHz and 400MHz systems will be priced at $1,600 to
$3,500. Apple had bragged that the G4 had these speeds last year,
then had to trim the claims back by 50 MHz across the line because
of technical difficulties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
