<HEADER>
A9906 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-LEARNLINC-ACQUIRED-HN     02-17 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNLINC-ACQUIRED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ISRAELI COMPANY ACQUIRES DISTANCE-LEARNING SOFTWARE DEVELOPER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Stands for LEARNLINK)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DANIELLE T. FURFARO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH GREENBUSH, N.Y. _ LearnLinc Corp., a North Greenbush
distance-learning software company, has announced that it is being
acquired by Gilat Communications for about $39 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   LearnLinc, one of the fastest growing software companies in the
Albany area, is the third company to be acquired in as many months
by the Israel-based company.
</P>
<P>
   When LearnLinc began negotiations with Gilat last month, the
local software company was only looking for venture capital,
according to Degerhan Usluel, the company's chief executive.
However, both sides quickly decided the companies should join
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that it made a lot of sense,'' Usluel said. ``It
will make us the strongest firm in the e-learning market in terms
of products, services and infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the acquisition, Gilat gains LearnLinc's learning
software, which enables an instructor and students to work together
on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw in LearnLinc an excellent group of product developers
who fit nicely into our overall strategic development,'' said Todd
Miller, vice president of business development at Gilat.
</P>
<P>
   The other companies acquired recently by Gilat were Utah-based
Allen Communications and Israel-based John Bryce Training, both of
which specialize in areas of distance-learning technology. Gilat
itself has pioneered distance learning by remote satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Gilat moved boldly in acquiring three companies in
such a short time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be an easy thing to digest,'' said Victor
Halpert, who analyzes Gilat for Salomon Smith Barney. ``But with
the proper management, it can be successful. Lots of traditional
CEOs wouldn't have made such a bold move.''
</P>
<P>
   LearnLinc will operate as a fully owned subsidiary of Gilat and
will remain in its North Greenbush office. It also plans to add
between 30 and 50 employees to its current base of 40 by the end of
the year. Companywide, Gilat has about 660 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1994, LearnLinc has facilitated on-line training for
many large U.S. corporations, including Aetna US Health Care,
Lucent Technologies and MCI WorldCom. Many colleges and
universities also use LearnLinc software.
</P>
<P>
   ``LearnLinc has been growing like crazy and were finding it hard
to keep up in terms of hiring people,'' said Jack Wilson,
LearnLinc's chairman and founder. ``This way, they will be able to
combine sales and marketing forces with the other divisions. It
will be one-stop shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger is expected to be finalized on Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Gilat Communications trades on the Nasdaq under the symbol
GICOF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1448EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
