 ART ADV.: Photos with HARVARD-DORMS, HOME-FIREPLACES and
SKI-VACATION are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service
subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ OK, so maybe raising the price of vodka
in a land where people on average drink 28 bottles of the stuff a
year but have little money to spare was not the smartest thing for
a presidential candidate. 1580 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PROSECUTOR (Moscow) _ As Russia's federal prosecutor,
Yury Skuratov knew the Kremlin's deepest darkest secrets. Now, as a
besieged outsider running for president, he is threatening to tell
all. 740 words.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-SURVIVOR (Tafara, Zimbabwe) _ Esther Daiton is raising
her extended family after the other grown-ups died of AIDS. She's
got it, too. By Kurt Shillinger. 725 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DIFFERENCE (Charleston, S.C.) _ After a N.H. GOP
primary that featured relatively few attack ads, the contest here
is as different as North and South. To hear some South Carolinians
tell it, this has become the political equivalent of Sherman's
March. By Michael Kranish. 1250 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-DORMS (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Three decades after
billionaire Bill Gates's pioneering days at Harvard University, a
mushrooming number of student-founded computer companies on campus
is forcing the university to reconsider its policy banning
commercial enterprise in the dormitory. By David Abel. 1000 words.
PHOTO
</P>
