<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9916 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-$ADV20-COX     02-17 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAGA OF ELIAN MOVES INTO U.S. COURTS, EXPERTS AGREE RETURN JUST
A MATTER OF TIME
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Feb. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After three months of protests, political posturing and
nasty family squabbling, the case of 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian
Gonzalez heads to the hushed confines of a federal court here on
Tuesday(2/22).
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler will take up the question
of whether his court has jurisdiction over the boy and whether
Elian's Miami relatives _ who want him to remain in the United
States _ have any right to make claims on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the court hearing _ which could clear the way for
the boy to be returned to his father in Cuba _ comes none too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boy has faced layer upon layer of stress,'' said Alan
Delamater, a child psychologist at the University of Miami. ``While
kids can be remarkably resilient, all in all I'd say there's a
significant toll on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian was found floating in an inner tube off the coast of Fort
Lauderdale on Thanksgiving Day. His mother and 10 other people
drowned after their small boat capsized on an ill-fated trip from
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Since his rescue, the boy has become the center of an
international tug-of-war, with the government Cuban President Fidel
Castro organizing massive rallies almost daily calling for the
boy's return to Cuba. In Miami, Cuban exiles _ not swayed by polls
showing most Americans favoring Elian's return _ have protested,
saying he should be kept here rather than sent back to an
impoverished future on the Communist island.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno upheld a decision
by federal immigration officials that Elian should be returned to
his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, in Cuba. But Reno stopped short
of forcibly removing the boy from the Miami home of his
great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, who has cared for him since his
rescue from the Florida Straits.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami family then filed a federal lawsuit aimed at blocking
Reno's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's long-awaited hearing will take up a motion by
government lawyers to dismiss the case. Their primary argument is
that immigration decisions are a matter for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, and not the courts. They also contend the
Miami family has no legal standing because immigration officials
correctly ruled that Elian's father is the only one with the legal
right to speak for him.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the law is squarely behind the government's
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no question,'' said David Abraham, a
University of Miami law professor who specializes in immigration
matters. ``Immigration admissions decisions are not reviewable by
the courts. The law is clear and has been clear from the outset.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Miami family, however, argue that the boy should
be given the chance to apply for asylum in this country, and that
failing to do so denies him of his constitutional rights. They also
asked Hoeveler to honor a ruling by a Miami-Dade County family
court giving custody of Elian to Lazaro Gonzalez, or to appoint an
independent guardian to care for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has ignored the family court ruling, saying that
immigration matters are solely a federal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   If Hoeveler decides he has no jurisdiction in the case or the
Miami family has no legal standing, the family could appeal to the
11th Circuit Court in Atlanta. That process could take days, if not
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hoeveler decides he has jurisdiction and the family has a
right to pursue the lawsuit, he would hold another hearing on the
merits of the case during the week of March 6.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the sparring over the boy has continued. Cuban
officials have charged that two of the great-uncles now caring for
Elian have been arrested for drunken driving, demonstrating their
lack of suitability to care for him.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father, Juan Miguel, has also written two letters to
Reno in recent weeks decrying the delays in the case, and asking
that the boy be moved to live with other Miami relatives who favor
sending him back to Cuba and allowing Cuban officials to visit the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has also repeatedly said he will not come to this
country to claim his son, and in his second letter to Reno said he
refuses to recognize the jurisdiction of U.S. courts over the
matter, dashing speculation that he might travel to Miami for the
court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives, meanwhile, have constructed a privacy
fence around their Little Havana home and asked that the media
scale back its constant coverage of the case. They have also
expressed outrage that one of Elian's grandmothers teased the boy
by biting him and unzipping his pants during a much-publicized
visit in early February.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, psychologists say Elian has suffered
enough trauma _ the loss of his mother, being left alone in the
ocean, the swarm of media following his every move _ to upset even
the most stable person.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface he may be doing well, but as far as the long
term, it's clear he will have a lot to deal with,'' said Wade Horn,
a child psychologist and founder of the National Fatherhood
Initiative, which promotes responsible fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern for him is what happens afterwards,'' Horn added.
``If he stays here, he could grow up with a tremendous sense of
guilt about not going back to his father. But if he goes, he may
come to resent losing the life he could've had here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
