<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9935 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT18-COX     02-17 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS DEADLINE LOOMS, U.S. AND MICROSOFT SEEK DEAL
 &HT;    670&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates signaled Thursday
that bargaining on a settlement of the federal antitrust case
against the company had reached a crucial phase.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said on NBC's ``Today'' show that he had joined Steve
Ballmer, the company's newly named chief executive officer, in
``spending considerable time'' on seeking an accord ``because we
think it would be in everyone's interest if we could put this
behind us and get it settled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting all of our creativity into that,'' Gates said.
``We've got to make sure that consumers are still going to have the
benefits of our innovation,'' he added, but ``we're very
open-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have begun meeting face to face in settlement
talks at the Lawyer's Club in Chicago, and the negotiations now
include chief government litigator David Boies.
</P>
<P>
   The developments come just days before both sides are to appear
before U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson on Tuesday for
arguments on whether Microsoft broke antitrust laws by misusing its
Windows operating system to increase its share of other personal
computer software markets, particularly Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson already has issued ``findings of fact'' that Microsoft
does have an operating system monopoly, and has leveraged that
monopoly to stifle competition and harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   If he finds those actions broke the law, Microsoft would be
subject to penalties, possibly including a breakup of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's newfound open-mindedness toward accepting a solution
that falls short of a full breakup is also evident in recent
e-mails to congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the company said it was willing to accept
``common-sense'' curbs on its business practices as the price of a
settlement. But any remedy that splits up the world's most valued
company would be ``extreme and unwarranted ...a regulatory death
sentence while the high-tech economy whizzes by on Internet time,''
one message argued.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after handing down his findings of fact, Jackson tapped
Judge Richard Posner, chief of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
7th Circuit, to informally broker a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Posner had been meeting with the government team each Monday and
Microsoft lawyers each Tuesday, but face-to-face talks began in
earnest this week, a sure sign that progress was being made.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers think a settlement might be imminent, or at least
that enough progress can be made for Jackson to postpone Tuesday's
oral arguments on the conclusions of law, which would lead directly
to a final ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there really is a delay due to the mediation by Judge
Posner, it must mean that they are very close to a settlement,''
University of Baltimore School of Law professor Bob Lande, who has
followed the case closely, said. ``If they are just talking,
putting forth the same old far-apart positions, they would just go
ahead with the oral arguments on the 22nd.''
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances, the government holds the high cards and need
not accept a weak settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Jackson's earlier findings, Gates and Ballmer face the
prospect that the flow of innovation, Microsoft professed stock in
trade, could be disrupted by the company's continuing legal woes,
including the prospect of widespread private civil suits.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department remains under considerable pressure
to settle as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than offering his backing, President Clinton has declared
his neutrality in the landmark suit, even though the officials in
charge of the prosecution _ Attorney General Janet Reno and Joel
Klein, who heads the Justice Department's antitrust division _ are
his appointees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without expressing an opinion on that case one way or the
other, I think what I favor is an American economy where people who
have good ideas and new messages they want to get out ought to have
some way to do that, if they can generate a following,'' Clinton
said in a CNN interview this week.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Klein has zealously sought to create an anti-Microsoft consensus
among technology industry leaders. But he has found few, if any,
top-level takers.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-December, Klein secretly assembled a blue-chip roster of
Microsoft critics at the Silicon Valley headquarters of Intuit.
They included such luminaries as Intuit's Bill Campbell, Sun
Microsystems' Scott McNealy, Oracle's Ray Lane, Netscape's Jim
Barksdale and Novell's Eric Schmidt, who joined by speakerphone
from his Utah home.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting failed to produce a joint statement. Moreover,
several other firms that have been stung by Microsoft's past
practices _ notably IBM, Intel and Gateway _ have also kept their
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Klein and Boies have been striving to keep the 19
states and the District of Columbia _ who, by Jackson's order, are
tightly joined to the case _ walking down the same settlement path.
</P>
<P>
   Several of these state attorneys general take only a scant
interest in the proceedings. But others _ notably Connecticut's
Richard Blumenthal, Iowa's Tom Miller and New York's Eliot Spitzer,
all Democrats _ have taken a harsh line.
</P>
<P>
   One possible defector is Ohio Attorney General Betty Montgomery,
a Republican. Writing recently in the Columbus Dispatch, David
Mayer, a professor of law at local Capital University, reported
that Montgomery ``is said to have serious qualms about the Justice
Department's plan to break up Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   But Klein's nuanced approach also has gained a fair share of
academic defenders. One of them is Robert Litan, director of the
economic studies at the Brookings Institution and a former deputy
assistant attorney general in the antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
   As Litan sees it, the sole reasonable objection to the various
breakup options is that they could fracture the de facto global
Windows standard for personal computers powered by Intel
processors.
</P>
<P>
   Litan adds: ``In the short run, this is highly doubtful.''
Multiple ``operating systems companies would have strong incentives
to use the common (programming hooks) of the current Windows _ and
the new Windows 2000 _ so that each would have a full range of
applications programs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the longer run,'' Litan concedes, ``standards might
diverge, but it is through that competitive process that innovation
occurs _ the major theme of Jackson's opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
