<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH BORROWS FROM RIVAL IN TRYING TO BOLSTER CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ He offers campaign finance reform. He does town
hall meetings to get close to voters. He comes off as a political
pugilist. He says he is a reformer who challenges the establishment
and the status quo. And he is an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Is this Arizona Sen. John McCain, candidate for the Republican
presidential nomination? No, it is Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who
has tried to transform his campaign into the same bus-riding
insurgency movement that has propelled McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the ``compassionate conservative?'' Now Bush is a
``reformer with a record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than emphasize his own strengths, he's trying to copy
McCain,'' said Jack Pitney, a government professor at Claremont
McKenna College in California. ``Next thing you know, he'll be
talking about his days as a prisoner of war.'' (Bush wasn't, McCain
was during the Vietnam conflict.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain face each other Saturday in South Carolina's
Republican primary, where the two candidates have about an equal
amount of support among GOP voters, according to recent polls. A
McCain win in South Carolina, combined with his 19-point victory in
New Hampshire on Feb. 1, could weaken nationwide support for Bush
and produce a wild and even nastier fight for delegates in
California and New York _ two voter-rich states that hold primaries
on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign says its message has been consistent
throughout the primary, although it acknowledges that Bush recently
has changed tactics and is getting closer to voters through a
series of town hall meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Governor Bush is trying to do is just hammer away at the
substantive issues and talk about his record and talk about his
results,'' said campaign spokeswoman Alixe Mattingly.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been a change in Bush over the past two weeks,
political analysts and campaign strategists say. While Bush and
McCain agree with each other on many issues, McCain's message of
challenging the Washington elite is hitting a responsive cord with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Tuesday's debate with McCain and former State
Department official Alan Keyes, Bush announced his own plan to
overhaul the way national campaigns are financed, perhaps trying to
capture the one issue most closely associated with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has followed up with an advertisement saying his plan is
``real reform'' compared with McCain's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   During the New Hampshire primary, McCain boasted he attended 114
town hall meetings, sometimes talking into the evening on any
subject that came up. Bush, however, was criticized for coming to
the state too late and not paying closer attention to rank-and-file
voters.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Bush campaign is touting one-on-one meetings with
voters in Florence, Conway and Litchfield, S.C. In the past, Bush
has confined his public appearances to orchestrated rallies and
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush hasn't abandoned his plan to cut taxes by $483
billion _ nearly double McCain's proposal _ Bush is no longer
exclusively pushing the cut in his advertising. In polls across the
country, voters are saying they believe using the federal surplus
to protect Social Security and Medicare are more important than
giving taxpayers a break.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign has highlighted protecting Social Security and
Medicare in promoting its tax cut, and now Bush has shifted to a
more balanced message in his advertising and during debates. The
Bush campaign may be taking a cue from the recent polls and from
the failed 1996 campaign of Bob Dole, who offered a large tax cut
to little avail.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is punctuating these tactical moves with a more aggressive
personal attitude. During the debate Tuesday in South Carolina, he
jabbed his finger, interrupted McCain and Keyes, scoffed, and tried
to dominate the conversation about as much as Keyes did. McCain,
who is trying to soften his image a bit, was more passive.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have noticed Bush's change in tone and message over the
past few weeks, and it looks a lot like McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush campaign has for at least a year been on cruise
control, with every indication he was going to get the
nomination,'' said Dennis W. Johnson, associate dean of the
graduate school of political management at George Washington
University in Washington, D.C. ``It just looked like everything was
clear sailing and the need to have a really clear, sharp message
wasn't there until McCain came along. I think what you've seen is a
redefinition to make Bush seem more like McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Since South Carolina has an open primary, meaning that Democrats
can vote in the Republican election, McCain could benefit from
appealing to the outsiders. It has been his strategy all along:
Appeal to the independent-minded voters in New Hampshire and do the
same in South Carolina. Then use the momentum to win California.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   California Secretary of State Bill Jones, the state's highest
ranking Republican officeholder, cited McCain's ability to attract
Democrats and independents when he defected from the Bush camp this
week and endorsed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to tell if McCain's message will sell in
California. Unlike South Carolina, only votes from registered
Republicans count in the selection of delegates for the national
convention. That favors Bush, although McCain claims to have
convinced 30,000 supporters to register as Republicans and vote on
March 7.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign, meanwhile, continues to paint the Arizona
senator as an outsider, despite his 17 years in Congress and his
chairmanship of the Senate Commerce Committee. McCain doesn't mind
so much when U.S. senators and others speak ill of him, or when
Bush talks about being against the establishment and then touts
endorsements from the nation's governors and lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the worst thing the establishment can say about John McCain
is the establishment doesn't like John McCain,'' said
communications director Dan Schnur, ``then we'll do OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
