<P>
   &UR; TOM HANKS WALKS `THE GREEN MILE' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) Includes a color slide of Tom Hanks in a scene from
``The Green Mile.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN SPELLING &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It was almost inevitable that Tom Hanks' new movie earn an Oscar
nomination as Best Picture _ it's a Stephen King adaptation by
writer/director Frank Darabont, the team that created the classic
``The Shawshank Redemption,'' and, well, it stars Hanks, winner of
two Best Actor Oscars in the 1990s. Hanks talks with New York-based
free-lance writer Ian Spelling about the new film, his reaction to
the Oscar talk, the challenges of creating distinct characters when
he himself has become so well-known and what lies ahead for an
actor who, at 43, has already reached the peak of his profession.
(slugged: BC-TOM-HANKS-IN-THE-GREEN-MILE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF,
priority code w, category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACE VALUE: `MILE' HIGH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By VANCE LEHMKUHL &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In this color cartoon feature from The New York Times Syndicate,
artist Vance Lehmkuhl offers an intriguing take on Tom Hanks as he
appears in the upcoming film, ``The Green Mile,'' depicting Hanks
sitting on a ``Forrest Gump''-style bench with his ``Green Mile''
co-star, the hulking Michael Clarke Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `INSIDE' STRAIGHT: AL PACINO ENTERS THE TOBACCO WARS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,300 words) Includes a color slide of Al Pacino in a scene from
``The Insider.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By CINDY PEARLMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; World rights except Chicago &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Al Pacino has made a career of playing roles torn from the
headlines of the day, from ``Dog Day Afternoon'' and ``The
Godfather'' to ``Serpico'' and ``City Hall.'' Now he's tackling
what may be his most explosive subject ever _ a real-life look at
the tobacco controversy _ in the Oscar-nominated ``The Insider.''
Pacino talks with Chicago-based free-lance writer Cindy Pearlman
about the new film, his role as a real-life ``60 Minutes''
producer, the challenges of approaching a subject on which his
audience is likely to have strong, preconceived ideas and why it
doesn't bother him that ``60 Minutes'' stalwart Mike Wallace has
denounced the film. (slugged:
BC-AL-PACINO-IN-THE-INSIDER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF, priority code w,
category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DENZEL WASHINGTON FIGHTS THE GOOD FIGHT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of
Denzel Washington in a scene from ``The Hurricane.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By IVOR DAVIS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Nominated for an Oscar as Best Actor for his performance as
imprisoned boxer Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter in ``The Hurricane,''
Denzel Washington makes no apologies for taking his work seriously.
Whether it was training relentlessly to make himself convincing as
a professional boxer or immersing himself in the history of
Carter's case, Washington went the extra mile to hone his
performance. The actor talks with Hollywood-based writer Ivor Davis
about the movie, the challenge of playing a real-life person who
remains alive and active, what he thinks Carter's story has to say
to Americans of all colors today and why he believes that he
himself only narrowly escaped a life of crime and prison. (slugged:
BC-DENZEL-WASHINGTON-IN-THE-HURRICANE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF, priority
code w, category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JULIANNE MOORE AND ONE HOT `AFFAIR' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,300 words) Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of
Julianne Moore with Ralph Fiennes in ``The End of the Affair.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By IVOR DAVIS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Her performance in ``The End of the Affair'' has won Julianne
Moore an Oscar nomination as Best Actress, capping a busy year
which also saw her co-starring in ``An Ideal Husband,'' ``A Map of
the World'' and ``Magnolia.'' Moore talks with Hollywood-based
writer Ivor Davis about the movie, the challenge she faced, as an
American, playing an Englishwoman opposite British star Ralph
Fiennes and how she approached the movie's torrid sex scenes.
(slugged:
BC-JULIANNE-MOORE-IN-THE-END-OF-THE-AFFAIR-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF,
priority code w, category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOT JUST ONE OF THE BOYS: HILARY SWANK AND `BOYS DON'T CRY' &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) Includes a color slide of Hilary Swank with Chloe
Sevigny in a scene from ``Boys Don't Cry.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN SPELLING &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Swank has done soap opera in ``Beverly Hills 90210,''
shown her athletic prowess in the feature film ``The Next Karate
Kid'' and faced evil in the original film version of ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer,'' but her latest film is easily her most
challenging _ and has earned her first Oscar nomination. ``Boys
Don't Cry'' casts her as Brandon Teena, nee Teena Brandon, a woman
who disguised herself as a man and began a new life for herself in
small-town Nebraska, until hatred and intolerance brought this
real-life story to a tragic ending. Swank talks with New York-based
free-lance writer Ian Spelling about the film, the unique
challenges of playing a woman playing a man, her own experiences
with intolerance and why she thinks Brandon Teena's story had to be
told. (slugged:
BC-HILARY-SWANK-IN-BOYS-DONT-CRY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF, priority code
w, category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MICHAEL CAINE, AMERICAN-STYLE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) Includes a color slide of Michael Caine with Tobey
Maguire in a scene from ``The Cider House Rules.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By CINDY PEARLMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; World rights except Chicago &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caine has never played an American before _ the accent
took him weeks of coaching to master _ but it was worth it to make
``The Cider House Rules,'' he says. The film casts him as a kindly
doctor who runs an orphanage, and also performs abortions on the
side to prevent unwanted children from being born. Caine talks with
Chicago-based free-lance writer Cindy Pearlman about the new film,
the horrendous experiences from his own childhood which drew him to
the role, why he's happier as an actor now that he's aged out of
leading-man roles and why he doesn't want to talk about the Oscar
chances for his performance in ``Cider House Rules.'' (slugged:
BC-MICHAEL-CAINE-IN-THE-CIDER-HOUSE-RULES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF,
priority code w, category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACE VALUE: RISING CAINE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By RICARDO CASTANEDA &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In this color cartoon feature from The New York Times Syndicate,
artist Ricardo Castaneda offers an intriguing take on Michael Caine
playing the sympathetic doctor in the upcoming film, ``The Cider
House Rules.''
</P>
