<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9951 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COLLEGE-DIVERSITY-HNS     02-17 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-DIVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDENTS CALL FOR DIVERSITY IN ADMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANNIE NAKAO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Student leaders at the University of
California at Berkeley have joined student body presidents at other
Pac-10 Conference schools to urge their campuses to increase
minority enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a resolution passed by the Pac-10 Student Body
President's Conference at UC-Berkeley two weeks ago, student
leaders on Wednesday called a ``day of action'' to make diversity a
priority for campus administrators.
</P>
<P>
   At a cold and wet Sproul Plaza, Patrick Campbell, president of
the campus' Associated Students governing body, addressed barely a
score of students and supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But he said no other campus held more significant meaning for
the affirmative action movement than Berkeley, flagship of the
University of California, which in 1995 banned the use of race and
ethnicity in admissions, and some say, triggered a nationwide
affirmative action rollback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a second-generation Bear and I love this university very
much,'' Campbell, 22, said, referring to Berkeley by its mascot.
``I believe in this university's motto, 'Let there be light,' and
its creed, 'Excellence through diversity,' and I will fight to keep
this university in line with its mission, motto and creed.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind him were rows and rows of empty plastic chairs _
symbolic, Campbell said, of the minorities who are n0t enrolled at
Berkeley because of the policy against admissions based on race.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1999, blacks, Hispanics and American Indians made
up 13.6 percent of new freshmen, up from 11.2 percent the previous
year, but well below the 21.5 percent in 1997 _ the last year for
which race and ethnicity were used as a factor in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   UC-Berkeley Chancellor Robert Berdahl has expressed support for
repealing the university's affirmative action ban, but UC regents
have thus far not considered such action.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley news conference coincided with similar activities
at the University of Washington, Washington State University, the
University of Arizona, Arizona State University, the University of
Southern California and the University of Oregon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1544EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0155 </DOCNO>
