<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MILITARY-ANTRAX-NYT &LR;      02-17 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-ANTRAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SUBCOMMITTEE SEEKS HALT IN ANTHRAX VACCINATIONS FOR MILITARY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (rk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House subcommittee Thursday released a scalding
critique on the Pentagon's effort to vaccinate American troops
against the biological agent anthrax, saying the program relies on
incomplete, outdated science and suffers from poor planning.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing its report, the subcommittee called on the Pentagon
to suspend the vaccination program until questions about its
effectiveness and adverse side effects are answered. Acknowledging
intelligence warnings of the possibility of an attack with anthrax,
it also recommended the Pentagon speed up research for a safer
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by the naticEP{ security subcommittee of the House's
Committee on Government Reform, represents another blow to the
Pentagon's anthrax program, which has faced delays, cost overruns
and occasional resistance from service members.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have repeatedly defended the vaccinations as
a safe, effective way to protect American troops from a biological
weapons attack using the deadly bacteria. In December, however, the
Pentagon was forced to halt new vaccinations because of problems at
the vaccine's manufacturer, causing further delays.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has said only a few hundred people in the military
have balked at the shots, but the instances have sometimes been
embarrassing. Only this week, the Air Force backed off its plans to
court-martial a major for refusing to take the shots and decided to
handle the case by an administrative hearing instead. And early in
1999, an airman with an untarnished record left the service under
``other than honorable conditions'' for refusing to take the
anthrax vaccination.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-page report released Thursday, the product of a year-long
review, could give momentum to efforts in Congress to force a halt
to the vaccinations. In the wake of growing protests from service
members, several House members have proposed separate bills that
would make the program voluntary or suspend it entirely until the
National Institutes of Health completed a study.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's development was the latest in a controversy that had
its beginnings in 1997, when Secretary of Defense William Cohen,
alarmed by reports that at least 10 countries have the ability to
make anthrax weapons, announced that he was ordering all 2.4
million active-duty and reserve troops to have the vaccinations.
They began a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax is a naturally occurring bacterium that infects cattle
and sheep. When produced as dry spores, it can be incorporated into
one of the deadliest biological agents, capable of causing death
within days of being inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Although no country has ever used anthrax in battle, the
Pentagon says that 10 countries, including Iraq and North Korea,
have the ability to make biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked early on that this might actually be a solution,''
said Rep. Mark Souder, R-Ind., who joined three other Republicans
in releasing the report. ``But the more you dig into this the more
you realize this is more of a political solution than a substantive
medical solution to the question of chemical and biological
technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
