<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9960 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS &LR;      02-17 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OPPONENTS OF PROPOSED BAN ON GAY MARRIAGES LAUNCH TV ATTACK ON
THE MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Opponents of a ballot initiative to ban gay
marriages in California launched a TV ad campaign this week taking
on state Sen. Pete Knight, whose name the measure bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete Knight, the California politician behind Proposition 22,
may not like it that his son is gay. But he shouldn't make us vote
on his private problem ,'' says the ad. It began airing in
Sacramento Tuesday and in Los Angeles Wednesday and will hit the
San Francisco Bay area next week.
</P>
<P>
   Another 30-second ad by the No on Knight campaign takes a softer
approach, showing a photo montage of children and their parents and
asking, ``What if your child, or the child of someone you know,
turns out to be gay? Do you still want the best for them?'' The two
ads are the No on Knight campaign's answer to pro-Prop. 22 ads that
have been airing for almost four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, sponsored by Knight, a Palmdale, Calif.,
Republican, and conservative religious forces, would define
marriage as a relationship between a man and a woman - as
California law already does - and deny recognition of same-sex
marriages from any state that might legalize them in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Prop. 22 campaign also unveiled two new ads this week
that reinforce its message that voters must approve the measure if
they want to show their support for family and marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The backers' first ad weeks ago was a direct appeal to Latino
voters, who may make up 16 percent of the electorate in the March 7
primary.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new ads depicts an African-American elementary school
teacher and appeals directly to parents and teachers about what
they want for their children. The second shows an elderly woman
going through mementos in her attic while she reminisces about her
own wedding day and talks about ``the way marriage has always
been.''
</P>
<P>
   The No on Knight campaign noted that state Superintendent of
Schools Delaine Eastin, the California Teachers Association and the
California Federation of Teachers have come out against Prop. 22.
</P>
<P>
   No on Knight campaign aides say they hope their TV ads will turn
public sentiment against the initiative, which polls have
consistently shown to be ahead with a majority of California voters
just three weeks before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the ads attempt to take the focus off the question of
whether gays should marry and to redefine the issue as one of
fairness, safety and non-discrimination, according to Ann Crigler,
director of the Unruh Institute of Politics at the University of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the highly charged, emotional feelings surrounding gay
marriage, I think it's probably wise for them not to take it on
directly,'' said Crigler, a professor with a specialty in political
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to shift the debate away from the way the Yes
on 22 people have framed it, which is to protect marriage, and
toward a question of treating people equally and fairly and
protecting people so there won't be acts of violence against
them,'' Crigler added.
</P>
<P>
   The No on Knight ad featuring the children says Prop. 22 ``could
increase anti-gay violence and (would) be used by extremists in the
Legislature to discriminate against gay people.'' The one that
takes on Pete Knight acknowledges that ``most people don't support
gay marriage'' but calls the initiative ``just more government
interference'' in people's private lives.
</P>
<P>
   Targeting Knight directly could prove to be a risky move,
Crigler said. Knight, the conservative senator whose son David is
gay and opposes his father's initiative, failed three times to get
the Legislature to pass a gay marriage ban before taking it to
state voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bringing a very personal family matter into the public
domain _ and in some ways they (the measure's opponents) are asking
that people not do that,'' Crigler said. ``So it could potentially
backfire on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Yes on 22 ads keep their agenda very narrowly focused,
she said. And using children and an elderly woman to deliver their
message is a shrewd move, she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
