<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9973 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-HANGINGUP-TEX     02-17 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HANGINGUP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANE KEATON'S MOVIE COMES CLOSE TO INSULTING ITS TARGET AUDIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the past couple of weeks, female writers have published
pieces in The New York Times Magazine and the Web 'zine Slate
bemoaning the state of ``women's'' entertainment. Neither seems too
happy with Oprah Winfrey's new Oxygen cable network, and Francine
Prose, in her Times piece, inveighs against the TV show
``Providence'' and the Meg Ryan et. al. movie ``Hanging Up.'' To
paraphrase Prose, the movie is condescending to and contemptuous of
its target audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably a little more well-meaning than that, but that
doesn't make it a better movie. ``Hanging Up'' was written and
directed by women, and stars three women, who are prominently
displayed on the movie poster in character-development shorthand:
Diane Keaton, in power suit and glasses, is the workaholic
overachiever; Lisa Kudrow, staring off into oblivion, is the
sorta-spacey one; and Ryan, bemused smile in place, is stuck in the
middle of a tangled life.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan is Eve Marks, a party planner whose father (Walter Matthau)
is dying and is suffering the lapses in lucidity that often follow
strokes. Sometimes he's charming and poignant, sometimes he's
amusingly irascible, and sometimes he's just plain cruel, although
he doesn't mean to be. He's a handful, and Eve, who is the only one
who sees him in the hospital, can't get her sisters to visit, much
less help out. She and her siblings communicate so much by
cellphone _ hence the title _ that it's amazing some cell provider
didn't offer to sponsor the movie.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for Ryan, whose likability makes us root for her
characters almost instinctively, we'd realize a lot faster that
someone needs to shake Eve and tell her to get a grip.
</P>
<P>
   Every time a phone rings, she freaks out and cries ``He's
dead!'' as if her father's illness were the only reason anyone
would call in her cell-happy life. She runs her own business, but
she's such a mess it's amazing that she can even find time to
shower, much less to keep her amazing house immaculate and her hair
so perkily disheveled. She has a husband (Adam Arkin) whose
moral-support method is to sternly make decisions for her; when he
leaves town, Eve nearly dissolves into a pile of Jell-O. She also
has an elementary-school-age son who shows up to do something cute,
then virtually disappears from the movie. Eve barely has a
conversation with the poor kid; maybe he's the one who's keeping
the house clean, just to get her attention.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan acts her heart out trying to make us like Eve, but she's
straining against the increasing cloyingness of screenwriters Nora
and Delia Ephron, whose own sibling rivalries had to be more
realistic than what we see here. Everyone in Eve's family has _ or
had _ a glamour job: older sister Georgia (Keaton) is a Grace
Mirabella-esque magazine publisher, younger sister Maddie (Kudrow)
is a self-absorbed and flaky soap-opera actress, and dad was part
of a screenwriting team _ and the Ephrons appear to believe that
dying parents affect only this class level. They also throw in a
divorce, represented in the form of a mom (Cloris Leachman, seen
far too briefly) who walked out on their dad and his shenanigans
long before he was sick.
</P>
<P>
   Not a trick is missed in the manipulation department _ ``Hanging
Up'' should have been called ``Pushing Buttons.'' But it's strange
to think that, with so much feminine talent involved, the
filmmakers couldn't see that they're delivering an anti-feminist
product and forcing their points about female solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   This is a real letdown from Keaton, who directs with the
nervousness and frenetic tics that are a hallmark of her acting
style; in performance, it can be beguiling, but as presentation,
it's maddening. It's as if she's always interrupting herself
because she can't decide what insight she wants to present next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanging Up'' is easier to take than two other current movies
directed by women, Jane Campion's bizarrely entertaining screed
``Holy Smoke!'' and Kimberly Peirce's dark and brutal ``Boys Don't
Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's only because it has less to say, and what it has to
say has been said before. You can give it points for not being
totally offensive, along the lines of the Fox show ``Who Wants to
Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' But at least ``Millionaire'' was
honest about its offensiveness; ``Hanging Up'' dresses its
offensiveness up in glamorous black and winsomeness and even fools
itself. Look closely, though, and you'll see that the empresses are
wearing no clothes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Hanging Up''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Diane Keaton
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Meg Ryan, Walter Matthau
</P>
<P>
   Length: 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ profanity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
