<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-MISS-JULIE-HNS &LR;      02-17 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MISS-JULIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISS JULIE' A MIX OF STAGE AND SCREEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Miss Julie'' is an intriguing cross between the
disciplines of theater and film. Directed by Mike Figgis (``Leaving
Las Vegas''), it has some of the most cutting dialogue since 1966's
``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?''
</P>
<P>
   Although infrequently staged in the United States, ``Miss
Julie'' is a classic play often studied in drama classes and
performed in Europe. Written in 1888 by August Strindberg, it is a
one-act work, a three-person drama that dissects issues of class
and gender through a highly personal conflict.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of what Figgis calls ``political propaganda'' relevant to
the time and original location _ Sweden _ has been dropped. That
leavesa battle of wills, emotions and sexuality between the two
main characters.
</P>
<P>
   The title character is the immature and rebellious daughter of a
wealthy count. Jean is the count's calculating, cynical footman.
The third character, less seen, is Christine, the count's cook and
Jean's secret lover and fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Miss Julie'' is being released by United Artists, a
major Hollywood studio, it is a low-budget picture aimed at viewers
who enjoy live theater, where conversation dominates scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Julie is played by talented English actress Saffron
Burrows, who appeared in ``Circle of Friends'' and ``In the Name of
the Father.'' She's also the scientist about to be chomped on the
poster for ``Deep Blue Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean is Scottish actor Peter Mullan (``Braveheart,''
``Trainspotting'') who gave a fantastic performance in 1998's
little-seen Scottish drama ``My Name Is Joe,'' for which he won a
best-actor award at the Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The story takes place one evening after a party, in and around
the castle's huge kitchen. Miss Julie has taken a fancy to Jean and
brazenly comes into servant territory looking for him.
</P>
<P>
   The result is about 100 minutes of emotional dynamite as each
character tries to get the upper hand, either through seduction or
belittlement. Sometimes it's hard to tell which is which.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their language to each other, at its core, is really
shocking,'' Figgis said.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis, who was nominated for Academy Awards as both director
and writer of ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' also wrote the adaptation of
the play for this film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the contradictions in the male-female characters
were really interesting _ the way (one) turned left when the other
turned right,'' Figgis said.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a roller coaster in which, at first, one character
is on top and the other at the bottom. Then the sides are reversed.
Words and class are used as deadly blades to cut deep.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship spirals increasingly out of control. Jean, who
is smart, angry and opportunistic _ not to mention snobbishly
class-conscious _ alternately rejects, manipulates, mocks and
encourages Miss Julie. An easy judgment would be that Jean is
cruel. But Mullan finds that far too simplistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a million ways to play this character,'' Mullan
said, his Glasgow accent so thick it demands close attention,
especially since he speaks quickly. ``Cruel is the least
interesting side to me. Sad? Bitter? Lonely? Arrogant? Stupid? I
would apply those terms. I don't know if he's cruel. He's too sad
for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a mask he puts on whenever he thinks he's vulnerable.
He knows if he really opens up his soul, it leaves one option only,
and that's rebellion. Rebel against the class system ...rebel
against his own feelings of inferiority ... and he's not up to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time he looks at Miss Julie, she is so beautiful, so
privileged, so articulate, so above him that he feels like
Quasimodo. He feels ugly in her presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when he sees a little avenue _ `Ah, for some bizarre
reason you find me attractive' _ he uses that.''
</P>
<P>
   To maintain the theatricality of the piece, Figgis applied an
unusual cinematic approach to filming. Most of the movie was shot
in long takes, with two cameras _ one operated by Figgis _ to
achieve a playlike feel and ensure the best material in the least
time. The film was shot in 16 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire set is in soft light so there is no shadow,''
Figgis said of his approach, which allowed the actors to roam with
relative freedom, not trying to hit prearranged marks to be in the
right light. ``The actors can go anywhere they want.''
</P>
<P>
   But the style also created some unexpected humor for the actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two (sound) booms going whoosh and two boom
operators who haven't a clue where the other one is going _ whoosh,
whoom, swoosh _ and you see cameramen crashing into a wall and
pretending absolutely nothing has happened, and you are doing this
serious love scene or being all angst-ridden, it's riotously
funny,'' Mullan said.
</P>
<P>
   The technique paid off in unexpected ways. For instance, there
is an intense love scene in the middle of the movie. Figgis shows
it in split screen, from two cameras at once. It's an unusual and
somehow shockingly personal approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the scene to be really erotic, but I didn't want any
nudity; I didn't want it to be explicit,'' Figgis said. ``But I did
want it to be something very intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Both actors and director insist the technique came about by
accident. To save time and money, Figgis would play back scenes
from both cameras at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day they were looking at the love-making in this fashion
and they thought it was very powerful,'' Burrows said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised when I saw it. It's hard to imagine until
you see it what it will do to the eye. I find it very erotic. It
seems it's more than two images. It seems to multiply into more
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgis was delighted with the unexpected result.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw it on play-back, I was completely blown away. Maybe
it's that, in a sex scene, we are always put in the perverse
position of the uninvited voyeur. Maybe if you put two cameras in
there, it allows us to escape the awkwardness of watching something
we really shouldn't be watching.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
