<HEADER>
A9979 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS18-     02-17 3470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``All About My Mother'' R (profanity, sexuality, drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Cecilia Roth,
</P>
<P>
   Marisa Paredes
</P>
<P>
   and Penelope Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   1 Oscar nomination: foreign film. Spain's bad-boy filmmaker
Pedro Almodovar grows up with this humane celebration of nurturing
women. It's a virtually male-free fable with a title inspired by
that backstage classic ``All About Eve.'' ``Mother'' can wink at
its own campy sensibility while still grabbing you by the gut. Dark
and tender, the movie beautifully balances humor and heartache. In
Spanish with subtitles. (SM) 1 hour, 41 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' R (strong sexuality, profanity,
</P>
<P>
   violence and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Spacey
</P>
<P>
   and Annette Bening.
</P>
<P>
   8 Oscar nominations: picture, actor (Kevin Spacey), actress
(Annette Bening), director, original screenplay, cinematography,
film editing, original score. The ever-more-remarkable Spacey plays
a man caught in a midlife limbo in this scarily disturbing,
daringly hilarious, well-written and well-acted comedy-drama. It's
a hauntingly optimistic elegy for America the Beautifully Screwed
Up. (ERG) 1 hour, 58 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``American Movie'' R (profanity and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   A documentary
</P>
<P>
   featuring Mark Borchardt.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Smith's documentary is alternately hilarious and
horrifying as it chronicles Mark Borchardt's attempts to make his
autobiographical magnum opus, ``Northwestern.'' The 30-ish
Borchardt _ a high-school drop-out with three kids who still lives
with his mother _ is a not-so-young, incredibly selfish film geek.
``American Movie'' is funny, scary and as compulsively watchable as
a train wreck. (ERG) 1 hour, 44 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela's Ashes'' R (profanity and sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Emily Watson
</P>
<P>
   and Robert Carlyle.
</P>
<P>
   1 Oscar nomination: original score. A finely made adaptation of
Frank McCourt's popular memoir of growing up in poverty and death
in Ireland. Fans of the book will enjoy seeing their favorite parts
re-created onscreen. Others, who don't have the memory of McCourt's
lyrical prose whispering in their heads, might wonder what the fuss
is all about. (SM) 2 hours, 26 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Anna and the King'' PG-13 (violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jodie Foster
</P>
<P>
   and Chow Yun-Fat.
</P>
<P>
   2 Oscar nominations: art direction, costumes. Maybe we didn't
need another version, but this one is handsome and engaging. Jodie
Foster and Chow Yun-Fat star in this lavish, songless costume drama
that holds its own against the beloved 1956 musical ``The King and
I.'' (SM)2 hours, 20 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Given Sunday'' R (profanity, sexuality and nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Al Pacino,
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Foxx and Cameron Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stone takes on pro football's dark side _ pills, booze,
prostitutes, shady back-office deals _ and almost fumbles. The
jarring game visuals come at you nonstop. Al Pacino plays the coach
of the fictional Miami Sharks and argues constantly with young team
co-owner Cameron Diaz. Jamie Foxx plays a rising quarterback and
emerges as the best actor in the large cast. (Bob Longino) 2 hours,
50 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beach'' R (violence, profanity, sexuality,
</P>
<P>
   drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Leonardo DiCaprio
</P>
<P>
   and Virginie Ledoyen
</P>
<P>
   A secondhand plot. Leonardo DiCaprio plays a restless young man
who travels with other aimless, privileged young people to a hidden
paradise _ then screws it up. It's hard to get attached to
characters who care about only one thing: their next moment of
pleasure. The cinematography makes the most of exotic locations.
But all the beauty in the world can't camouflage the film's
gorgeous emptiness. (SM)1 hour, 59 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Being John Malkovich'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack
</P>
<P>
   and Cameron Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   3 Oscar nominations: director, supporting actress (Catherine
Keener), original screenplay. It's a loopy original. John Cusack
plays a quirky file clerk who discovers a door that leads into the
noggin of actor John Malkovich. Toying with big concepts _ the
nature of identity, the lust for celebrity, sexual desire, the
illusion of free will, it's playfully profound one moment, gonzo
the next. And often hysterically funny. (SM) 1 hour, 52 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Boiler Room'' R (profanity and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Giovanni Ribisi,
</P>
<P>
   Vin Diesel and Ron Rifkin.
</P>
<P>
   A high-powered descendant of ``Wall Street'' and ``Glengarry
Glen Ross,'' this study of muscle-mouthed stockbrokers aiming to
make their first million before getting their first wrinkle pays
onscreen tribute to those two movies. It's a bracing reminder that
greed is still good _ so long as you don't get caught when you
pretzel the rules. (SM) 1 hour, 59 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bone Collector'' R (profanity, violence and grisly images)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Denzel Washington
</P>
<P>
   and Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Double Jeopardy,'' this crime drama is, at its core, pure
pulp filmmaking. It delivers plenty of sucker punches. But thanks
to the film's two talented stars _ Denzel Washington as a brainy
quadriplegic detective and Angelina Jolie as his equally brainy
forensics cop _ this thriller's got enough electricity to make it
watchable. (Bob Longino)
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 58 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'' PG-13 (nudity,
</P>
<P>
   substance abuse, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Caine
</P>
<P>
   and Tobey Maguire.
</P>
<P>
   7 Oscar nominations: picture, director, adapted screenplay,
supporting actor (Michael Caine), art direction, original score,
film editing. John Irving adapted his own novel. In the first half,
Dr. Larch (Caine) delivers babies and performs illegal abortions in
his Maine orphanage. In the second, less-engaging half, Larch's
protege, Homer Wells (Tobey Maguire), runs off to learn about the
world. (ERG) 2 hours, 5 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamonds'' PG-13 (profanity and sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kirk Douglas,
</P>
<P>
   Dan Aykroyd and Lauren Bacall.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is, Kirk Douglas is back on screen after a serious
stroke. The bad news is, he's back in this. He plays an aging boxer
who convinces his estranged son (Dan Aykroyd) and loving grandson
to drive to Reno where he stashed some diamonds 60 years ago. The
bonding road-trip is excruciating and a visit to a brothel (run by
a very professional Lauren Bacall) is almost unwatchable. (ERG)1
hour, 37 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``The End of the Affair'' R (scenes of strong sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ralph Fiennes,
</P>
<P>
   Julianne Moore
</P>
<P>
   and Stephen Rea.
</P>
<P>
   2 Oscar nominations: actress (Julianne Moore), cinematography.
Neil Jordan's somber, velvety and often sensual adaptation of
Graham Greene's novel explores love both physical and spiritual.
While the movie doesn't skimp on humid clinches and bared skin, it
also summons up the intangible mysteries of sacrifice and devotion
to a higher power. (SM)1 hour, 49 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Eye of the Beholder'' R (language, sex, nudity, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ewan McGregor
</P>
<P>
   and Ashley Judd.
</P>
<P>
   Boredom, like beauty is in the eye of the beholder. What begins
as a hypnotic riff on the old surveillance classic, ``The
Conversation,'' ultimately veers off into nowhere. Too bad because
the picture is as stylishly acted as it is directed. An isolated
British surveillance agent (Ewan McGregor) becomes more involved
than he intends in the case of a diplomat's son and a mysterious
femme fatale (Ashley Judd). (ERG)1 hour, 50 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasia/2000'' G
</P>
<P>
   Animated. Music from Beethoven
</P>
<P>
   and Stravinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The entirety of this new ``Fantasia'' isn't worth one whirling
mushroom from the 1940 original. The movie lacks the wit, charm,
warmth, humor and awe of its predecessor, underscored by the
inclusion of one old segment, ``The Sorcerer's Apprentice.'' Our
advice: Drop off the kids, shop the mall, then go rent the
original. (ERG) 1 hour, 30 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Galaxy Quest'' PG (mild violence and sensuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver
</P>
<P>
   and Alan Rickman.
</P>
<P>
   It'll beam you up, up and away. Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver and
Alan Rickman lead a small band of has-been sci-fi TV show actors
lured by misguided aliens into helping them save their far, far
away galaxy from an invasion of evil bug-lizards. Though it starts
slowly, ``Quest's'' completely cornball humor sometimes scores
direct hits. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 42 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, Interrupted'' R (profanity and drug content,
</P>
<P>
   sexuality and suicide)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Winona Ryder
</P>
<P>
   and Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   1 Oscar nomination: supporting actress (Angelina Jolie). Two
fine actresses, two fine performances. Based on Susanna Kaysen's
memoir about the two years she spent in the '60s at a mental
hospital, the movie goes for a rip-roaring tone reminiscent of
``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.'' Winona Ryder steadies the
movie, but Jolie provides the fireworks as a charismatic sociopath.
(ERG) 2 hours, 5 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile'' R (profanity, violence, sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tom Hanks
</P>
<P>
   and Michael Clarke Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   4 Oscar nominations: picture, supporting actor (Michael Clarke
Duncan), adapted screenplay, sound. A manipulative but meticulously
crafted, absorbing and beautifully acted adaptation of Stephen
King's prison novel. Tom Hanks plays a 1930s death row guard whose
latest prisoner, a mysterious hulk played by Duncan, has mystical
powers of healing. (SM) 3 hours, 2 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun Shy'' R (profanity, violence and brief nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liam Neeson,
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Bullock and Oliver Platt.
</P>
<P>
   Stressed-out undercover drug cop Liam Neeson matches ulcers with
stressed-out junior Mafioso Oliver Platt in a deeply funky New York
comedy about murder, stomach disorders and male anxiety. It's
scattershot, but it scores a few surprising satirical bull's-eyes.
Love interest Sandra Bullock's screen time is unwisely minimized by
producer Sandra Bullock. (Bob Campbell, Newhouse News Service)1
hour, 42 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Hanging Up'' PG (profanity and mild sexual themes)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Diane Keaton,
</P>
<P>
   Meg Ryan and Lisa Kudrow.
</P>
<P>
   Breezily written by the Ephron sisters and briskly directed by
Diane Keaton, the movie's ads want you to believe it's a
side-splitting sibling comedy about three sisters (Keaton, Meg
Ryan, Lisa Kudrow) trying to connect. However, it's really an aging
parent-confused adult child story in which Ryan tries to be all
things to her dying dad (Walter Matthau). (ERG) 1 hour, 32 minutes.
C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy Smoke'' R (sexuality and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kate Winslet
</P>
<P>
   and Harvey Keitel.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Campion's movie is about how we blow smoke at each other
emotionally, spiritually and sexually. An Australian girl (Kate
Winslet) who's joined a cult in India is lured home by her family,
who hire a professional deprogrammer (Harvey Keitel). As the two
face off, the question becomes who will deprogram who. It's a
brutally primal battle of the sexes that makes Sam Shepard look
tame. (ERG)1 hour, 44 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hurricane'' R (profanity and some violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Denzel Washington
</P>
<P>
   and Vicellous Reon Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   1 Oscar nomination: actor (Denzel Washington). Washington
delivers his best performance in years as pugilist Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter, the middleweight contender wrongly imprisoned
for nearly 20 years in a triple murder. Though ably directed, the
film contains some fabrications to tell this otherwise compelling
true story. (Bob Longino)
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 5 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolia'' R (profanity, drug use, sexuality,
</P>
<P>
   violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julianne Moore
</P>
<P>
   and Tom Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   3 Oscar nominations: supporting actor (Tom Cruise), original
screenplay, song. A mesmerizing tapestry about broken families,
love and forgiveness. Unfolding at fever pitch and studded with
small miracles of acting, writer-director Paul Thomas Anderson's
movie is exhilarating and exhausting, the sort of thing you live
through as much as watch. The payoff is well worth it. (SM)2 hours,
59 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Mysteries of Egypt'' Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring Omar Sharif
</P>
<P>
   and Kate Maberly.
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic's bigger-than-life Imax film offers many
breathtaking views of Egypt's natural and man-made wonders. There
is ample footage of giant pyramids, huge statues and redwood-tall
columns, all frequently displayed from ground view with a seemingly
you-are-there feel. Warning: Some of the narration is pure hokum.
(Bob Longino) 40 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Friday'' R (profanity, drug use, sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ice Cube
</P>
<P>
   and Mike Epps.
</P>
<P>
   A dumb comedy. The best that can be said for this sequel to
``Friday'' is that, unlike the first flick, the characters don't
spend most of the movie sitting on the front steps yacking and
getting stoned. They go elsewhere to get stoned. Lamely written,
it's a reminder that, while complex, mature and funny
African-American comedies are being made, there's always a market
for flatulence and dog poop jokes. (SM)1 hour, 33 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch Black'' R (profanity and sci-fi violence and gore)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vin Diesel
</P>
<P>
   and Radha Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry aliens, stupid humans: the usual. ``Pitch Black'' is just
the latest sci-fi ripoff of ``Aliens,'' packed with caricatures. In
the movie's last hour, writer-director David Towhy pretends to
explore his stick figures' moral choices, and he forgets to deliver
the thrills. (SM) 1 hour, 47 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Play It to the Bone'' R (violence, sexuality, drug content,
</P>
<P>
   profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Antonio Banderas,
</P>
<P>
   Woody Harrelson and Lolita Davidovich.
</P>
<P>
   An entertaining take on boxing. Antonio Banderas' Cesar, a
Madrid-born boxer, now lives in Los Angeles and has become best
pals with Woody Harrelson's Vince, a Texas-born fighter. The first
half of the film is a road movie, with Grace (Lolita Davidovich),
Vince's former girlfriend and Cesar's current lady, driving them to
Las Vegas; it soon becomes a love story. (Kevin Thomas, From Los
Angeles Times.) 2 hours, 5 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Scream 3'' R (profanity and strong horror violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Arquette, Courteney Cox Arquette and Neve
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a scream any more, but it's a decent wrapup of the
series. Neve Campbell, Courteney Cox Arquette and David Arquette
are all back and on the Hollywood set of ``Stab 3,'' ducking the
knife-swings of a killer clad in the familiar Halloween getup. The
new movie isn't as clever with its clues as the others, but it
manages to wheeze its way across the finish line, wrapping up the
trilogy in satisfying fashion. (SM)1 hour, 56 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Simpatico'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jeff Bridges, Nick Nolte,
</P>
<P>
   Albert Finney and Sharon Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the world of horse-racing, this movie reminds you that
you can have the best bloodlines imaginable and sometimes the nag
still won't run. A blue-ribbon cast is wasted on a tale of old pals
with a shared shady past that still haunts them 20 years later.
Jeff Bridges is a wealthy Kentucky breeder; Sharon Stone his
doped-up, depressed wife; Nick Nolte a crumpled alcoholic
blackmailing Bridges. (ERG)1 hour, 40 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'' PG-13 (violent images)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bruce Willis,
</P>
<P>
   Haley Joel Osment
</P>
<P>
   and Toni Collette.
</P>
<P>
   6 Oscar nominations: picture, director, supporting actor (Haley
Joel Osment), supporting actress (Toni Collette), original
screenplay, film editing. A surprising, spine-tingling gem.
Eight-year-old Cole (Osment) can see restless phantoms with their
skulls blown open. It's a fascinating, odd film that speculates on
what the relationship between the restless dead and a liaison to
the living world might be. (SM) 1 hour, 47 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleepy Hollow'' R (violence and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Johnny Depp,
</P>
<P>
   Christina Ricci.
</P>
<P>
   3 Oscar nominations: cinematography, art direction, costumes.
Tim Burton's latest is a blend of scary swordplay, witchcraft and
self-spoofing humor. Johnny Depp is effective as Ichabod Crane, who
investigates a series of beheadings in 1799 Sleepy Hollow. The
movie's comic relief balances the Headless Horseman's single-minded
attacks, which spare neither men, women nor children. (SM) 1 hour,
45 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Day'' PG (mild peril and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Chevy Chase.
</P>
<P>
   A lame kids movie about Syracuse schoolkids trying to extend one
out-of-school snow day into two. Chevy Chase plays a TV weatherman
suffering all kinds of humiliation and Chris Elliott appears as the
ominous Snow Plow Man with bad teeth. (Robert Denerstein, Denver
Rocky Mountain News)1 hour, 30 minutes. D-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Straight Story'' G
</P>
<P>
   Starring Richard Farnsworth
</P>
<P>
   and Sissy Spacek.
</P>
<P>
   1 Oscar nomination: actor (Richard Farnsworth). David Lynch
shifts gears in this lyrically simple little film based on the true
story of 70-plus Alvin Straight (Farnsworth), who drove his John
Deere riding mower more than 300 miles to reconcile with his
brother. It's a sublime celebration of America at its most
beautiful: kind, welcoming, gloriously eccentric. (ERG) 1 hour, 41
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuart Little'' PG (brief profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Geena Davis,
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Lipnicki and
</P>
<P>
   the voice of Michael J. Fox.
</P>
<P>
   1 Oscar nomination: visual effects. Based loosely on E.B.
White's 1945 children's book, Stuart is a 3-inch-tall
computer-animated wonder voiced by Michael J. Fox. He brushes his
teeth, gargles and aw-shucks smiles with such convincing visuals
you'll swear he's the next best critter since ``Babe.'' But his
movie, at first charming and angelic, turns into slapstick. (Bob
Longino) 1 hour, 33 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet and Lowdown'' R (profanity, sexuality and alcohol abuse)
</P>
<P>
   Starring
</P>
<P>
   Sean Penn and
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Morton
</P>
<P>
   2 Oscar nominations: actor (Sean Penn), supporting actress
(Samantha Morton). This jazzy little doodle of a mockumentary is
middling Woody Allen and, as such, mildly likable once you get past
the insistent whiff of self-justification. Penn is superb as a
legendary (and fictional) jazz guitarist in the 1930s who's an
angel with a guitar in his hands and a louse the rest of the time.
(ERG) 1 hour, 35 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented ...'' R (violence, profanity, brief nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matt Damon,
</P>
<P>
   Jude Law and
</P>
<P>
   Gwyneth Paltrow
</P>
<P>
   5 Oscar nominations: supporting actor (Jude Law), adapted
screenplay, art direction, original score, costumes. A handsome but
flawed adaptation of novelist Patricia Highsmith's twisty thriller.
Matt Damon plays the title character, who travels to Italy to bring
back a rich man's son but ends up adopting his lifestyle and
committing murder. (SM) 2 hours, 18 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tigger Movie'' G
</P>
<P>
   Animated feature with
</P>
<P>
   Tigger, Pooh, Baby Roo, Piglet, etc.
</P>
<P>
   This charming animated feature clearly knows its intended tot
audience and takes care of them. The irrepressible, ever-bouncing
Tigger goes searching for his family and discovers his real family
isn't necessarily other Tiggers. Pooh, Piglet, Baby Roo and the
whole A.A. Milne gang are back, as are the Sherman brothers (``Mary
Poppins''), who wrote the sprightly songs. As Tigger himself would
say, it's tiggerific. (ERG) 1 hour, 16 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Topsy-Turvy'' R (for a scene of risque nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jim Broadbent
</P>
<P>
   and Allan Corduner.
</P>
<P>
   4 Oscar nominations: original screenplay, art direction,
costumes, makeup. You don't have to be a fan of Gilbert and
Sullivan's operettas to enjoy it. But a love of the theater can
help you appreciate Mike Leigh's meticulously detailed valentine to
performers of the 19th century. (SM)2 hours, 39 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2'' G
</P>
<P>
   Computer animation
</P>
<P>
   featuring the voices of
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hanks, Tim Allen and Joan Cusack.
</P>
<P>
   1 Oscar nomination: song. More rock 'em, sock 'em fun than
families have seen in years. Woody (Tom Hanks), Buzz Lightyear (Tim
Allen) and old and new characters are locked in a delightful story
of toy rustling and what it means to love a child. It sports an
inspired, hilarious script and stunning visuals. (Bob Longino) 1
hour, 25 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whole Nine Yards'' R (sexuality, nudity, and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Perry
</P>
<P>
   and Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   A comedy with a body count and familiar mafioso premise, but
with enough twists to eventually overcome its familiarity. Bruce
Willis stars as a hit man. As in ``The Sixth Sense,'' he doesn't
seem to mind playing genial straight man to his funnier cast mates:
Matthew Perry, Patricia Arquette and Kevin Pollack. (SM)1 hour, 43
minutes. B
</P>
