<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-NINEYARDS18-CO     02-17 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-NINEYARDS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comedy keeps rolling as `Whole Nine Yards' goes the distance
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this age of mafiosi hiring shrinks on screens big and small,
Jimmy ``the Tulip'' Tudeski (Bruce Willis) is an old-fashioned hit
man: He doesn't sweat rubbing someone out, and he sleeps just fine
at night.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody who stops sleeping well is sad-sack dentist Nicholas
``Oz'' Oseransky (Matthew Perry). That's because Jimmy has moved in
next door in Oz's Montreal neighborhood, sporting an alias. When Oz
susses the killer's true identity, his shrew of a wife, Sophie
(Rosanna Arquette, working an amusingly grating Quebecois accent),
insists that he fly to Chicago, Jimmy's old stomping ground. Maybe
he can get a ``finder's fee'' for ratting Jimmy out to the guy's
mortal enemy, Hungarian crime lord Janni Gogolak (Kevin Pollak,
making the most of his accent, too).
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention that this is a comedy? The movie takes care of
laughs in its first half-hour by letting Perry do a bunch of
pratfalls (which he does expertly), but the script seems too
familiar. Luckily, as the plot kicks in, ``Yards'' gets better and
funnier, delivering enough twists (in plot and character
revelations) to overcome its tired premise.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes the statuesque Natasha Henstridge as Willis'
estranged wife, Cynthia; Oscar nominee Michael Clarke Duncan (``The
Green Mile'') as one of Janni's strongmen; and, in the movie's
funniest example of derailing our expectations, Amanda Peet as Oz's
perky dental assistant, who turns out to have an unexpected hobby.
They all get involved in a complex series of moves and
countermoves, centered on possession of a $10 million fortune that
Jimmy, Cynthia and Janni all have claim to. Each of them, natch,
wants to nab the full amount, the whole nine yards of the title.
Oh, and they each want to get rich without getting whacked.
Screenwriter Mitchell Kapner provides a witty touch by having Oz's
profession be not only a running joke, but a crucial plot point.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jonathan Lynn (``My Cousin Vinny'') keeps the comedy
rolling smoothly, pulling off the difficult task of keeping things
funny even as the movie starts racking up a sizable body count. (By
contrast, look at the way ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' turns into a mess in
its final reel.)
</P>
<P>
   As in ``The Sixth Sense,'' Willis doesn't seem to mind playing
genial straight man to his funnier cast mates. Perry strikes the
right balance between verbal and physical comedy. Henstridge
doesn't get a chance to be much more than the Girl, but Arquette
makes the most of an opportunity to mock her own sexy image. The
movie's nicest surprise is Peet, but if I spoiled it by telling you
why, you'd want to whack me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whole Nine Yards''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Perry and Bruce Willis. Rated R for sexuality,
nudity and violence. At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 43 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A comedy with a body count and a familiar premise,
but with enough twists to overcome its familiarity.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
