<HEADER>
A9982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      02-17 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BLISS IN MARITAL `STORY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THE STORY OF US'
</P>
<P>
   This movie's married couple seems to have big problems. But the
real problems are with the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   Director Rob Reiner tries to meld drama and comedy but misfires
on both counts. His look at love on the rocks mixes crude humor
with the tone of television's ``Once and Again,'' with weepy
sensitivity intercut by the stars' confessionals to an unseen
listener.
</P>
<P>
   If only Katie (Michelle Pfeiffer) and Ben (Bruce Willis)
confided more in each other. They don't try hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   He's a clownish slob, and she's a dutiful neatnick, but they
seem to be deeply in love. As Rocky might say, they fill each
other's gaps.
</P>
<P>
   But for some reason, they allow trifles to come between them and
let stubbornness turn molehills into mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In short, you grow impatient with them as much as you pull for
them to pull it together.
</P>
<P>
   Overly anecdotal, the yarn zaps around in time, and its earliest
flashbacks are shaky. Pfeiffer can pass for younger than her 41
years, but Willis, when playing a comb-over 20-something, looks
exactly his age of 44.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reiner is poking us in the ribs with strained
sitcom-style moments that are too crude for the serious context.
</P>
<P>
   Most offensive are the uniformly blunt and irritating co-stars _
Paul Reiser, Rita Wilson and Reiner himself _ who overact badly as
the couple's unlikely friends. (You wouldn't want any of these
people in your face.).
</P>
<P>
   Yet the most awkward element is at the end, when the film's
theatrical trailer suddenly appears, almost in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   The clip is an effective funny-sad montage set against Mason
Williams' urgent ``Classical Gas.'' But to put the trailer in the
movie? Like Ben and Katie's split, it just doesn't feel right.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Universal, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE MUSE'
</P>
<P>
   Albert Brooks is like the child you want to encourage, even when
he keeps falling on his face. He once aced tests and won football
games, but now he keeps fumbling the ball.
</P>
<P>
   As writer, director and star, Brooks has created charmingly
offbeat comedies with a real-life edge, from ``Real Life'' to
``Lost in America'' to ``Defending Your Life.''
</P>
<P>
   But his last film, 1996's ``Mother,'' was a poor relation, and
this one isn't much better.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is fun: A zestful woman (Sharon Stone) who claims to
be a goddess serves as muse for frantic Hollywood types seen in
cameos (Martin Scorsese, James Cameron).
</P>
<P>
   But Brooks simply takes that premise into a mundane comedy of
misery. He portrays a once-respected but now struggling
screenwriter who hooks up with Stone as a last resort. She moves
into his house, becoming absurdly high-maintenance while dispensing
common-sense advice that he interprets as brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   The pathetic, desperate Brooks bows to Stone's every whim, and
the nonsense goes on and on _ and on.
</P>
<P>
   Like his character, Brooks just isn't delivering the goods
anymore. Perhaps he needs to study this film and its failure and
think real hard _ unless he knows a true muse who can help.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1/2 star.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, USA, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.95
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
