<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN18-COX     02-17 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush has gone from free agent to religious-right mouthpiece
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Phil Gramm, I was missing you so.
</P>
<P>
   For a Texas pundit, Gramm is like a mountain spring, always
there when the canteen rattles.
</P>
<P>
   When most of us were at a word loss for what happened on the way
to George W. Bush's inauguration, Gramm gurgled this:
</P>
<P>
   ``No Texan has ever done well in New Hampshire. Those people
expect candidates to grovel. Texans have many skills. Groveling
isn't one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grovel'' is a good Gramm word. Very guttural.
</P>
<P>
   And what a man to bring up the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Texans too proud to grovel? In 1996 Gramm prostrated himself
before the religious right in a quest for the GOP presidential
nomination. His gain? After a staggering defeat in Louisiana, Gramm
was out of the race before he was off his knees.
</P>
<P>
   And now, who's hugging the floor in deference to the Christian
Coalition but George Bush?
</P>
<P>
   No one was in a better position, as a well-endowed,
well-endorsed candidate, to tell Coalition founder Pat Robertson to
go to hell, figuratively speaking.
</P>
<P>
   The last person you'd expect Bush to cozy up to would be the
airwaves kingmaker who sees a king in the mirror. Bush has openly
warred with the Christian Coalition for control of the Texas
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas isn't South Carolina after a stunning primary loss.
What disbelieving eyes are seeing, as the anointed GOP front-runner
struggles to right his vessel, is Bush in Robertson's servitude.
</P>
<P>
   Here we had Bush defending the character of the organization
against the criticisms of John McCain. McCain has ample reason to
criticize. Robertson effectively has called McCain a stalking horse
for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   This is fascinating because on the key social issues for the
religious right, particularly on abortion, they show scant
difference. One difference: McCain hasn't groveled.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference: McCain appears to be consistent, while Bush
is posing for voters in fuzz focus.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's debate, McCain pointed out that he and Bush both
support exceptions to a ban on abortion including cases of rape,
incest and the threat to a mother's life. Yet, McCain pointed out,
Bush supports the GOP platform, which would require a woman
impregnated by a rapist to bear the rapist's child.
</P>
<P>
   Either his rival hasn't read the platform, as McCain implied, or
Bush is just trying to play off as many sides as he can while
hoping that no one pays too close attention.
</P>
<P>
   As the religious right insists, the abortion issue has turned a
lot of GOP candidates once torn about abortion into springtime
zealots.
</P>
<P>
   No better example exists than Gramm. I remember asking him to
express a position _ any position _ on abortion a few years ago,
without success. Then Gramm ran for president and became, with the
Christian Coalition holding his coat, the most fervent
anti-abortion crusader imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is clear. Agents of zeal are crucial to winning
primaries and caucuses, be they Christian evangelicals or labor
unions. They are so crucial, apparently, that someone who won
distinction as a centrist and a consensus-seeker, like Bush, feels
he must abandon the middle and embrace extremists when the going
gets tough.
</P>
<P>
   What does the middle say about abortion? In the 1996 primaries,
exit poll after exit poll found a Republican majority opposing a
constitutional ban on abortion. This even as GOP candidates, with
an eye to the religious right, called for exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Democrats of the 1980s were the party in the throes
of ideological extremes when it came to electing presidents, so
today are the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can still win in South Carolina. The abdication of the hunt
by Steve Forbes may be his saving grace.
</P>
<P>
   Should Bush win the nomination, however, he has some groveling
to do to get back to the center.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
