<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-BUSH (Greenville, S.C.) _ John McCain, likening himself
to Ronald Reagan, appeals to Democrats and independents to join
Republicans to deliver him a victory in Saturday's crucial GOP
primary. Meanwhile, George W. Bush, campaigning in Florence, S.C.,
accuses McCain of riding a ``high horse on a low road'' by
continuing to distribute a flyer that says Bush's tax cut plan
would damage the future of Social Security. The latest polls show
the two in a statistical dead heat with turnout the likely
determining factor. By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-REFORM (Columbia, S.C.) _ John McCain's ``national
crusade,'' as he grandly styles his campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination, is a multifront battle that seeks more
than just capturing the White House. McCain is fighting not only
George W. Bush but also the whole Republican establishment,
including the party hierarchy and GOP leadership in Congress. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SPEECH (Myrtle Beach, S.C.) _ We analyze George W. Bush's
basic stump speech. It's partly personal and partly laced with
applause lines on taxes, national security and education calculated
to appeal to core conservative Republican voters. The unstated
agenda is drawing distinctions between him and John McCain. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-VIETNAM (Columbia, S.C.) _ John McCain once said of his
wartime captors in Vietnam: ``I hate those gooks and I always
will.'' The Republican presidential hopeful says he was only
referring to those individuals who held him captive and tortured
him _ not the Vietnamese people. Also, McCain says he is
``unstoppable'' if he wins South Carolina. By CLAY ROBISON and R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MISTAKES (Washington) _ Saying she was ``shocked'' to
learn that as many 98,000 Americans die each year from mistakes
made by hospitals and doctors, Rep. Constance Morella, R-Md.,
introduces legislation aimed at encouraging hospitals to share
information about their errors. She says the aim is to help prevent
other institutions from making the same mistakes. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-EROS (Undated) _ Scientists say Eros, the Valentine's Day
asteroid, appears to be a fragment from a planet. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-UH (Houston) _ For the first time in 32 years, the
University of Houston will play host to the nation's No. 1 college
basketball team tonight when the Cougars face top-ranked Cincinnati
at Hofheinz Pavilion. By JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN (Dallas) _ Column on the memorial service
held in Dallas for former Cowboys coach Tom Landry. By MICKEY
HERSKOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ Advance on the opening of spring
training for the Houston Astros as they begin their quest for a
fourth consecutive National League Central Division championship.
By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Animal-rights zealots opposed to the
wearing of fur recently disrupted the annual New York fashion show
by shouting, waving placards and throwing red paint on people.
After years of such stunts, however, it is clear the zealots have
already lost that battle. Women still like fur coats. So People for
the Ethical Treatment of Animals is about to shift tactics,
attacking the wearing of leather instead. Wooden shoes, anyone? By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ A major paradox in the current
presidential campaign is that the contenders are spending millions
of dollars to win the White House while, in their political
demagoguery, they describe Washington as a synonym for evil. By
ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
