<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HANGING-FILM-REVIEW-N     02-17 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANGING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANGING UP': CELL PHONE FROLICS, AND DEAR, DITSY DAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's clear that Eve Marks (Meg Ryan), a harried professional
party planner, has reached the end of her rope when she arrives
home one day to find a big shaggy dog munching on the telephone and
doesn't have an instant conniption. Eve, who practically lives on
the phone, hastily retrieves the instrument, then thinks twice and
tosses it back to the insatiable pooch, who resumes his meal while
she dashes around her fancy Los Angeles house ripping every phone
and fax connection out of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The doggie with the telephone is one of many desperately
lighthearted Hallmark moments in ``Hanging Up,'' a chilly
machine-tooled comedy adapted from Delia Ephron's 1995 novel and
directed by Diane Keaton. Frustrated cell phone communication among
the major characters is such a naggingly unfunny recurrent gag in
the film that by the time it's over, you wish that dog had devoured
every telephone on the set ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   With a screenplay by the author and her sister Nora Ephron (who
produced the movie), ``Hanging Up'' tackles the touchiest of
subjects, the decline and death of a parent, and efficiently
Ephronizes it into a series of cute, easy-to-swallow
pseudo-epiphanies. By the end of the story, the three daughters who
come together over the death of their irascible, alcoholic father
have transcended their simmering mutual resentments long enough to
indulge in a cheery Thanksgiving Day food fight where they
laughingly pour flour over one another's expensive outfits.
Liberation, in this ready-for-Lifetime movie, apparently means not
having to fret about your laundry bills.
</P>
<P>
   Eve ( Ryan) is the married middle daughter of a triumvirate that
includes Georgia ( Keaton), a high-powered magazine editor who
resembles a younger, softer-edged Gloria Steinem, and Maddy (Lisa
Kudrow), an insecure, budding soap opera actress. Their father, Lou
(Walter Matthau), a once successful screenwriter, is a crusty,
wisecracking old geezer who is rapidly losing his marbles from
drinking and age but still has plenty of fighting spirit. In other
words, he is Matthau as a grumpy older man.
</P>
<P>
   As Lou, whose biggest claim to fame was writing movies for John
Wayne, slips from absent-minded senescence into a coma, the movie
cooks up assorted tepid dramas to keep his three daughters in a
tizzy. Eve is arranging a big bash for a women's commerce
organization at the Richard M. Nixon Memorial Library, a sure-fire
comic site that the movie woefully underexploits for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   She is less than pleased when the organization's leaders
unanimously decide Georgia should be the party's keynote speaker
and miffed when Georgia's speech turns out to be a spontaneous,
weepy reflection on their father's death. Since Eve has been his
primary caretaker, she feels Georgia has appropriated and exploited
her grief in the same way that many years earlier she stole her
recipe for stuffing and published it in The New York Times. Of such
mountains are the movie's emotional molehills built.
</P>
<P>
   Eve is that familiar Meg Ryan alter ego, an officiously perky
wonder woman whose take-charge attitude masks a daddy's-little-girl
vulnerability. Georgia is that comforting cliche, the professional
dynamo with an empathetic heart palpitating under a gregarious but
steely surface. Maddy is the slightly lost baby of the family who
feels ignored and underappreciated. Ryan, Keaton and Kudrow do
their best to give these one-dimensional women some depth, but
they're struggling against a screenplay that reduces deep emotions
into low-cal, risk-free hissy fits that can be settled with a
misty-eyed hug.
</P>
<P>
   Using extended flashbacks and reveries, the movie tries to pack
as much biographical information as possible into 92 minutes, but
its very busyness ensures that the characters' feelings stay on the
surface. The closest the movie comes to real drama is a flashback
in which Lou drunkenly disrupts a children's birthday party. Its
primary indication of the passage of time is that Ryan's blond hair
keeps getting shorter.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows, few events in life are more emotionally loaded
than the death of a parent. As sugarcoated and joke-encrusted as it
may have been, ``One True Thing,'' sparked by Meryl Streep's
astonishing portrayal of a dying cancer patient, stirred up enough
genuine human drama to qualify as a triple-hankie movie.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hanging Up,'' with its squalling cell phones and deathbed
Hollywood jokes about John Wayne and June Allyson, meeting your
maker is just another way of meeting cute. Give the movie half a
hankie.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Hanging Up'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It has some off-color humor and profanity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HANGING UP'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Diane Keaton; written by Delia Ephron and Nora
Ephron, based on the book by Delia Ephron; director of photography,
Howard Atherton; edited by Julie Monroe; music by David
Hirschfelder; production designer, Waldemar Kalinowski; produced by
Laurence Mark and Nora Ephron; released by Columbia Pictures.
Running time: 92 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Meg Ryan (Eve), Diane Keaton (Georgia), Lisa Kudrow
(Maddy), Walter Matthau (Lou), Adam Arkin (Joe), Cloris Leachman
(Pat), Jesse James (Jesse) and Edie McClurg (Esther).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1624EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
