<SLUG> BC-FILM-PITCHBLACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COLOR OF EMPTINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The science-fiction thriller ``Pitch Black'' may be about a
planet that's immersed in darkness, but director David Twohy always
makes sure you have something to look at. Twohy and his crew put a
lot of thought into the visuals of this movie, half of which
actually takes place in daylight _ the harshest, whitest daylight
Twohy and cinematographer David Eggby can manage. Colors leach out,
faces distort, and at night, alien creatures become
glow-in-the-dark blurs.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't look like too many other movies. But it sure feels
like you've seen it before.
</P>
<P>
   Twohy, who delivered a nifty little science-fiction cult film
with 1996's ``The Arrival,'' gets ``Pitch Black'' off to a rousing
start with a spaceship crash punctuated with nerve-rattling
strobe-light flashes and furiously hyperactive editing. After the
dust settles, we're left with a motley crew of characters stranded
on a desert planet with three suns, and it's only a matter of time
before something starts making their stay unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   The key characters are a docking pilot named Fry (Radha
Mitchell), a macho lawman named Johns (Cole Hauser) and a convicted
murderer named Riddick (Vin Diesel, also on view this week in
``Boiler Room'').
</P>
<P>
   There are others _ most notably a Muslim cleric (Keith David)
and a fey antiques dealer (Lewis Fitz-Gerald) _ but Fry, Riddick
and Johns provide most of the bickering ... er, ``tension.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are bad enough already when the survivors discover that
the planet is inhabited by some nasty batlike creatures and some
even nastier ``Alien''-like creatures, each of which has a nose for
blood, a taste for human flesh and an inability to withstand light.
So everything is OK for our heroes as long as they stay in the sun,
right? Whaddaya think the odds are that they crashed hours before a
rare solar eclipse?
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Blair Witch Project,'' ``Pitch Black'' is meant to
play upon our childhood fear of the dark, not to mention our adult
fear of handheld shaky-cams. And Twohy's skewed visuals are
unnerving _ at first. But once you focus in on the characters, and
realize that you'd rather see (and maybe even root for) the
monsters, it becomes tough to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell plays spunky while modeling the latest in
midriff-bearing spacewear. Diesel, Hauser and Fitz-Gerald get their
share of macho and/or dry one-liners. Other characters wait to be
plucked off like secondary ``Star Trek'' guest stars. And everybody
gets a piece of dialogue along the lines of ``We've got to get off
of this rock!''
</P>
<P>
   It's passably entertaining, and genre fans who thought the
previews were cool probably won't be disappointed with Twohy's
warped imagery. But the script lifts from so many other sources
that it quickly becomes apparent ``Pitch Black'' was a good idea
with no other good ideas to back it up. It just doesn't stand up in
the cold light of day.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Pitch Black''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 1-5
</P>
<P>
   Director: David Twohy
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Radha Mitchell, Vin Diesel
</P>
<P>
   Length: 107 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ profanity and gory violence.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
