<SLUG> BC-TVMOVIE-2GETHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING FUN OF BOY BANDS SHOULD BE MORE FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have seen my share of bad movies but few, if any, prepared me
for the utter, complete, sometimes cringe-inducing mess that is
``2gether,'' MTV's parody of the boy-band phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   And what is so disappointing is that the idea and the timing are
so right.
</P>
<P>
   The Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync have sold, between them, more
than 20 million CDs in less than two years, almost exclusively to
little girls who love their fresh-scrubbed good looks and endless
stream of bland, first-makeout-session-friendly, faux-soulful tunes
about the vagaries of teen romance.
</P>
<P>
   This music is, for the most part, dreck: hollow, dumbed-down and
marketed with ruthless efficiency, which is certainly a winning
formula for much of what is successful in pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Point being, the current crop of cutie-pie boy bands is ripe for
the picking; they practically beg to be made fun of, as did heavy
metal in the '80s and hip-hop in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for ``2gether,'' the first film from MTV's
Original TV Movies division, parodies of both of those genres _
``Spinal Tap'' and ``Fear of a Black Hat'' _ have set a standard
that director Nigel Dick and ``writers'' Brian and Mark Gunn never
come close to reaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spinal'' and ``Fear'' were gleefully vicious in their
disassembling of bloated metal bands a la Uriah Heep and the
mechanizations behind flash-in-the-pan hip-hop acts. They pulled no
punches and got the details right _ and seeing just how close they
could come to the real thing was at least half the fun, if not
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``2gether'' can't decide whether it wants to be sweet or nasty
and mainly chooses the former, dumbing down its subject matter and
undercutting whatever glib knowingness (which is to say, value as a
parody) it might have had as a result. Dick and the Gunn brothers
want to make us laugh at boy bands, but they refuse to go in for
the kill (or to get a lot of details right) and end up oozing as
much vanilla as the wussy music they're trying to thumb their
collective nose at.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins with music manager Bob Buss (Alan Blumenfeld)
getting fired from his job with chart-topping boy band Whoa! on the
eve of a big show in Boston. And it is only here, as
Buss/Blumenfeld explains the makeup of boy bands (you have to have
the rebel, the cutie, the shy one, the older brother and the
heartthrob) that the film works.
</P>
<P>
   This takes approximately five minutes, and the next 77 are a
wash. The plot, such as it is, involves Buss wanting to assemble a
boy-band within a week so he can open for Whoa! in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   So we're treated to a road trip, a trip to a karaoke bar, a
jealous girlfriend, coming up with the band name _ 2gether, of
course _ a disastrous first gig, a defection among the ranks, a
chance meeting in an all-night truck stop with the guys in Whoa!
(gosh, they're jerks _ ``can you believe it?!?!?)'' and
(ohmygoshnoWAY!) a triumphant show.
</P>
<P>
   Please. The dialogue is dreadful, the acting more so. Only Alex
Solowitz as the Kid Rock-ish ``rebel'' Mickey Parke seems to really
commit himself to his role _ which is, basically, being a
pseudo-playa moron. How hard could this have been?
</P>
<P>
   There are more holes in the plot than in the Dallas Cowboys'
offensive line. How, for example, would a fat, balding guy such as
Doug Linus (Kevin Farley; yep, Chris' brother) even be
``considered'' for such a group? There are more ridiculous gaffes _
one near the end involving the girlfriend and a tape of 2gether
songs that made me laugh out loud _ but you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Also undercutting the film's premise is that almost all of the
major characters stop what they're doing and explain what's going
on TO THE CAMERA. This is a huge parody no-no; we're never told who
this camera crew is or why they would following around an
unemployed former manager as he tries desperately to rebuild his
career. The film would have been much better _ and far, far more
believable _ without this treatment. As it is, it's just something
else that takes away from the believability of the entire project.
</P>
<P>
   The film does have one might-have-been-redeeming quality: The
music itself. Songs such as ``Say It (Don't Spray It)'' and
2gether's big hit ``U + Me Us (Calculus).'' Both are just about
perfect in their cookie-cutter blandness but both, unfortunately,
underscore just how unrealized the film around them is.
</P>
<P>
   MTV is obviously trying to show us how hip it is for parodying
the very acts it has helped to become enormously wealthy, but it
drops the ball early and often. ``2gether'' just isn't convincing
and smartly snarky enough to do what it sets out to do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``2gether''
</P>
<P>
   Monday: 7 p.m. on MTV. The film will run commercial-free. A
soundtrack album of 10 original songs is available now.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
