<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOST OF NPR'S `MARKETPLACE' FUMBLES ON DOCUMENTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm a big fan of ``Marketplace,'' National Public Radio's
business news show.
</P>
<P>
   The award-winning show is informative, snappy, humorous and
human, and after listening to it for a half-hour, you pretty much
know all the big business news of the day and have probably picked
up a few smaller gems to share with your spouse at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   So I was looking forward to reading the new book by David
Brancaccio, the host and senior editor of ``Marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Brancaccio makes his show lively, entertaining and informative.
He takes what many consider dry, boring news and gives it an
``Entertainment Tonight'' spin.
</P>
<P>
   And he is a seasoned newsman with a master's degree in
journalism from Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   So I am disappointed to confess that I wasn't bowled over with
``Squandering Aimlessly: My Adventures in the American
Marketplace,'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 283 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   His premise was good. Brancaccio tells readers that the book
idea came about because in his high-profile job, (''Marketplace''
has 3.7 million listeners), people constantly ask him what they
should do with their extra money.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a time of great surplus for some, this is an acute
occupational hazard, like that of the chiropractor at a convention
of contortionists,'' he writes. ``I need to answer the question for
myself before I could have anything meaningful to say about other
people's money.''
</P>
<P>
   So Brancaccio took off, literally, to find his financial
``street smarts.'' He took 10 trips over 16 months to discover what
to do with that bonus, severance check, inheritance, lottery win,
tax refund or other capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   He chose 10 categories on which to base his trips: taking a
shopping spree, doing good, starting a business, gambling, giving
it away, investing in the markets, buying a house, going back to
school, retiring early and saving for a rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   His trips included a day of shopping at Minnesota's Mall of
America; a talk with socially responsible investors in Jackson
Hole, Wyo.; gambling and talking with two former professional
gamblers in Las Vegas; visiting Wall Street; attending classes at a
country music school in Levelland, Texas; and hanging out at the
Biosphere in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The travelogue is interesting to a point, but the book lacks
basic research to bolster its premise. Brancaccio goes to the mall,
for example, but doesn't tell readers how big it is or how much
consumers are spending annually at malls or how much square footage
of retail space there is per person in this country (an
astronomical number, by the way, compared with 20 years ago).
</P>
<P>
   At the country music school in Levelland, he found many
interesting characters who abandoned solid careers for an almost
whimsical lifestyle. Yet Brancaccio doesn't mention how many people
nationally have returned to school for a career change or even how
many are enrolled in South Plains College, one of the few places
that offers a degree in country music.
</P>
<P>
   Without much work, you can find statistics and analyses on just
about anything. If Brancaccio had backed his stories with numbers,
his book would have been far more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   A classic example of how an author can engrossingly entwine
travel with big-picture analysis is Bill Bryson's ``A Walk in the
Woods,'' about his experience walking the Appalachian Trail.
Besides the fascinating, detailed account of his walking
experience, Bryson crams the book with more historic,
environmental, social and scientific information than anyone can
remember but that adds eye-widening appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Brancaccio has not provided much of a big picture, and that
leaves the reader wanting much more.
</P>
<P>
   Next time you go on the road, Brancaccio, take a researcher with
you, and don't forget to plug in the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Age Works: What Corporate America Must Do to Survive the
Graying of the Workforce''
</P>
<P>
   By Beverly Goldberg
</P>
<P>
   Free Press, $25
</P>
<P>
   Smart companies, think tank Vice President Beverly Goldberg
says, are installing recruiting programs that target senior
citizens. With the labor shortage continuing and baby boomers
aging, this is becoming a necessity, he says. ``Age Works''
discusses the employment numbers crunch and how farsighted
companies are thinking up ways to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``1001 Ways to Take Initiative at Work''
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Nelson
</P>
<P>
   Workman, $10.95
</P>
<P>
   This book was written by the author of the bestselling ``1001
Ways to Reward Employees'' and ``1001 Ways to Energize Employees.''
Bob Nelson is also founder of a motivational company in San Diego.
In his newest book, Nelson suggests that readers work for
themselves, not a company, thereby controlling their own destiny.
That, in turn, means people can inspire themselves with tools and
advice provided in his book.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentals of Venture Capital''
</P>
<P>
   By Joseph W. Barlett
</P>
<P>
   Madison Books, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   It's surprising to see a 165-page book as costly as one that is
two or three times bigger, but capitalist Joseph Barlett appears to
knows his subject very well. From angel investors to joint
ventures, Barlett succinctly but thoroughly discusses the types of
venture capital and how and where to find them. With 35 years in
the business, Barlett has been one of the leading practitioners in
U.S. venture capital, and his insights are all here.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
