<HEADER>
A9996 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     02-17 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROODING `SUICIDE PACT' A BRIGHT SPOT IN HARD ROCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question surrounding Therapy? and its latest CD, the
just-released ``Suicide Pact _ You First,'' is not whether it's one
of the best hard-rock records of the past five years (it surely
is), but whether it will get the airing it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   For those who remember, the band _ born 10 years ago in Belfast,
Northern Ireland _ was briefly on the cusp of stardom in the United
States, thanks to the success of 1992's ``Nurse'' and 1994's
``Troublegum'' CDs, tours with the Rollins Band, Helmet, Jesus
Lizard and Swervedriver, and a growing horde of fans who loved the
nasty, snarling, compact songs of vocalist/guitarist/lyricist Andy
Cairns.
</P>
<P>
   Therapy? was that rare combination of intelligent lyrics,
vicious metallic attack and pop smarts, born of the same sort of
lust for The Big Riff and the confessional anger and sadness that
fueled Husker Du, Joy Division and Big Black. For one brief moment
_ amid the buzz that surrounded ``Troublegum,'' still one of my top
five hard-rock records _ they grasped the brass ring.
</P>
<P>
   And then it all went _ well, if not south, then certainly
sideways. According to Cairns, that CD was a ``one-off'' pop record
_ if pop records can include songs about knife wounds, paralyzing
frustration, murder fantasies and utter, black despair.
</P>
<P>
   Their label, A&AMP;M, wanted hits, but they wanted to make darker,
more interesting records. As a result, the next CD, ``Infernal
Love,'' got no push at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know how to market us; Green Day and Offspring
were big at the time,'' Cairns says by phone from London. ``And
they wanted us to compete with Metallica and Aerosmith! We were
treading water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Infernal Love'' bombed in the United States, and its
follow-up, 1998's ``Semi-Detached,'' was released just as A&AMP;M was
being absorbed into Polygram via its merger with Seagram's.
</P>
<P>
   It was never released in the United States and didn't fare that
well in Europe, where the band has always been more popular.
Therapy? found itself without a label, and with a not-so-great CD
in the racks and no profile in the States. Cairns had been a very
hard partier, but he eased back, cut down and fell in love with a
woman named Kristina. The band made ready to record again _ it just
didn't know for whom.
</P>
<P>
   But the day they began recording ``Suicide'' in England, they
signed a worldwide deal with Ark 21, a wide-ranging label that's
also home to Austin's Wayne ``The Train'' Hancock. A new lease on
life beckoned, and they banged out ``Suicide'' in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just decided we might as well just wipe the slate clean and
do what we wanted to do,'' Cairns says. ``We made a very noisy,
garage-y, underground record, and it was great fun. We just worked
on instinct, tossed about some lyrics, and didn't try to steer the
songs somewhere they weren't meant to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suicide'' is an expansive, articulate, roaring beast of a CD,
hard rock for people who think and prefer real life to fantasy.
Martin McCarrick's cello and second guitar are integrated into the
songs better than on ``Infernal Love'' or ``Semi-Detached,'' and
the songs have a dark, brooding tone; it's easily their best work
since ``Troublegum,'' although far different, and will probably end
up on my top 10 list for the best CDs of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal with Ark 21 means that the band will once again
tour the United States with an intensity not seen since 1995.
Cairns, married for more than a year, just celebrated the birth of
his first child, Jonah, in October, and says he's put the days of
``just going from one party to another'' behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a single man, I'd worry 24 hours a day about music. Now
that I have other things in life, I make the most of my creative
time,'' he says. ``I've sorted myself out, and I've totally gotten
back into music.''
</P>
<P>
   The first signs of Therapy?'s rebirth are the release of
``Suicide'' and a showcase set at South by Southwest in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to start from scratch in America,'' he says.
``What I'd like to do is establish a true fan base, have small
places rammed full of fans, make a lot of friends, do it the honest
way. All of our favorite bands are American _ we're not trying to
resell you something you've already got.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
