<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0001 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TEXASQUARTER-TEXWEASK WEGOT'EM:THOSEREADERIDEA   02-17 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASQUARTER-TEX </SLUG>
 WE ASKED FOR 'EM, WE GOT 'EM: THOSE READER
IDEAS CAME ROLLING IN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By
KATHY HARRIS c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   The readers have spoken, and they feel strongly about the design
of the Texas quarter, to be introduced in 2004. In a previous
article, we offered some wacky ideas about the upcoming Texas
quarter just for fun, but it's time to get down to business, before
a posse is formed. As promised, here is the top vote-getter from
readers, along with some other ideas (we're impressed!):
</P>
<P>
   1. A longhorn in some form or fashion was the top pick. Caleb
Miller, 13, of Fort Worth even suggested a longhorn standing in a
field of bluebonnets. A perfect combo, Caleb. If only we could get
Lady Bird Johnson to campaign for this one. We also liked the
design turned in by Rick Pinner of Whitney, which combines stars
and a longhorn. It's clean, it's classy, it's TEXAS. Runner-up
artist honors go to Robert Barnes of Fort Worth, who packed more
things on a quarter than seemed humanly possible, including
bluebonnets, a cattle skull, prairie cactus, a lone star, and the
words ``prosperity,'' ``diversity,'' ``industrialization,'' ``Sam
Houston'' and ``Stephen F. Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Sure, we remember the Alamo, and so do you, because it came
in a close second among readers. It's not that we have anything
against the Alamo. We're just not sure there are enough Daughters
of the Republic to guard each quarter if the Alamo makes it onto
the coin. Runner-up to the Alamo was a lone star. OK. It is the
Lone Star State, but do we really want to start a trend of state
quarters reflecting the state nickname? Imagine how obnoxious those
Missouri folks would be, always saying, ``Show me the money.''
</P>
<P>
   3. The Dallas Cowboys may be ``America's Team,'' but several
readers made the case for the real thing on an American quarter.
Mary Anne Miller of Fort Worth conjures up a nice image of a cowboy
on his horse, overlooking a valley full of longhorns. Too bad we
can't capture the Texas sunset or a wide-open blue sky in the
background. No matter. They'll just have to make the Texas
half-dollar, instead. After all, if everything is bigger in Texas,
its coin should be, too.
</P>
<P>
   4. Thinking about cowboys gets us thinking about chuck wagons,
which gets us thinking about corn bread, which gets us thinking
about ... ribs. Sonny Norrell of Fort Worth thought of a plate of
ribs, too. And what better way to wash them down than with a frosty
Big Red? Our state quarter would be the only mouth-watering money
out there!
</P>
<P>
   5. Willard H. Jordan of Mineral Wells points out that one of
America's biggest heroes is from Texas. Audie Murphy, the most
decorated combat soldier at the time of his death in 1971, was born
near Kingston. What better way to remind Americans that they owe
their freedom to servicemen and servicewomen like Murphy than by
putting his face on the Texas quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1633EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
