<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KIRIKOU-FILM-REVIEW-N     02-17 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIRIKOU-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KIRIKOU AND THE SORCERESS': CAN-DO AFRICAN BOY WINS AND EVIL
SORCERESS LOSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mother, bring me into the world,'' demands Kirikou, the infant
protagonist of the animated fable ``Kirikou and the Sorceress.''
Like its tiny hero, ``Kirikou'' proceeds at its own pace, and that
pace is a more willful and slower piece of storytelling than
children are accustomed to getting from American animated films, in
which emotional crises are worked out like story problems (if Buzz
and Woody need to get to point A ...).
</P>
<P>
   The director Michel Ocelot's belief in his film is as winning as
his title character's confidence, even though ``Kirikou'' is
probably a story more suitable for younger children than for older
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Kirikou tells his mother when he's ready to be born and then
pops out, a rambunctious can-do charmer who's constitutionally
incapable of being defeated. This fairy tale, based on a West
African legend, sends its indomitable little-boy hero with a ridge
of sculptured hair atop his head on his way to outwit the evil
sorceress Karaba and her minions: grim, obedient fetish objects and
a thirsty beast that consumes all the water in sight.
</P>
<P>
   It's wonderful and rare to see an African landscape rendered for
an animated film and not have any of the characters voiced by white
mainstream American movie stars, or hear any Broadway
approximations of African music. The rhythms of ``Kirikou'' are
aided by the lyric pulse of Youssou N'Dour's score, which lends the
story an airy exuberance. The music does some of Ocelot's work for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Ocelot's style of illustration often uses a regal rigidity. His
characters are frequently captured in profile, rendered as if they
were pictograms created by the artist Romare Bearden. It's a
full-scale delivery of animation with its own cultural imperative.
</P>
<P>
   This gives the movie an odd delicacy, especially in scenes when
``Kirikou'' is most effective, as when Karaba's fetish figures _
blockish and frightening _ charge onto the screen. This scene and
shots of Karaba _ her burning amber eyes match the gold jewelry she
wears, tribute she has forced villagers into surrendering _ have a
haunted serenity, instead of the anarchic pop-pop-pop that even the
most tepid American feature-length cartoons provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kirikou and the Sorceress'' has a modesty of scale that limits
its power, even with the occasional glimpses of fairy-tale horror
(with a primal earthiness reminiscent of ``Princess Mononoke'')
that peek through. The formality of both the dialogue and the
visuals also vaguely suggests the earliest Japanese anime to reach
America, stuff like ``Astro Boy'' or ``Gigantor,'' though stripped
of the action.
</P>
<P>
   It's more a piece to admire than to be involved by, yet it's
easy to imagine children hypnotized by a hero tinier than they are
when ``Kirikou'' is continually loaded into the VCR. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `KIRIKOU AND THE SORCERESS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michel Ocelot; written by Ocelot (in French, dubbed
into English), based on a West African tale; director of
photography, Daniel Borenstein; edited by Dominique Lefever; music
by Youssou N'Dour; produced by Didier Brunner, Jacques Vercruyssen
and Paul Thiltges; released by ArtMattan Productions. Running time:
74 minutes. With the voices of: Theo Sebeko (Kirikou), Antoinette
Kellermann (Karaba), Kombisile Sangweni (The Mother), Mabuto
Sithole (The Old Man/Viellard) and Fezele Mpeka (Uncle). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1634EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PARISH-FILM-REVIEW-NY     02-17 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARISH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PARIAH': ENTERING THE RANKS OF RACISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pariah,'' which begins a weeklong engagement at the Screening
Room in New York Friday night, opens with the voice of the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. warning that ``racism is a sickness unto
death.'' But this new film by Randolph Kret mistakes the study of a
particularly virulent set of symptoms for a diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that the Southern California skinheads who
rampage through the movie are sick people. When they are not
spewing obscenities at blacks, gays and one another or committing
acts of wanton brutality against blacks, gays and one another, they
are apt to be recalling lives of loneliness and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But having discovered these pathologically angry souls, Kret,
who directed ``Pariah'' from his own script, seems unsure about
what to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   What he tries to do is send an outsider into their ugly little
world. Steve (Damon Jones) is a quiet white grad student type whose
world is shattered when the skinheads attack him and his
African-American girlfriend, Sam (Elexa Williams).
</P>
<P>
   Sam, gang-raped while Steve is forced to look on helplessly,
goes home, cuts her wrists and dies. Steve decides to take revenge.
But first he shaves his head, dons red suspenders and an angry
scowl and decorates his arms with Nazi tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of an ordinary, tolerant white person going undercover
into a world of extreme race-hatred is a promising one. (It was the
subject of Costa-Gravas' interesting 1988 film ``Betrayed,''
starring Debra Winger and Tom Berenger.) But to bring the idea to
life requires a script and an actor capable of conveying the
psychological complications such a journey must entail.
</P>
<P>
   Steve's motives are never made very clear. Why didn't he call
the police? (The answer seems to be that Los Angeles, despite being
overrun by gangs of marauding youths who carry out their attacks in
broad daylight, doesn't have any.)
</P>
<P>
   And why, if he's so inclined, doesn't Steve just track his
assailants down and kill them? Why would he want to make friends
with them first? His decision is presented as if it were the most
natural response to what has befallen him and yet on reflection it
seems completely absurd.
</P>
<P>
   For his part Jones, a slow-moving, passive screen presence,
doesn't adequately register the nuances of guilt, rage and
curiosity his character needs to hold our interest or elicit our
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Nuance is not something Kret has much use for. The lives of the
skinheads are so nasty and brutish that it seems hard to imagine
that any young person, however alienated or ideologically zealous,
would want to go near them.
</P>
<P>
   And in a misguided attempt to give the film some political
balance and complexity, Kret conjures up a group of hyped-up,
violent young black men (the only black male characters in the
movie), who drive around the city terrorizing whites and who
introduce gunfire where before there had been bats, fists and
knives. This gang and the mob of vengeful gays who later lay waste
to the skinheads' crash pad are on hand to make the point that the
world is trapped in a cycle of retributive violence.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that ``Pariah'' is a relentlessly violent
film. It is also simplistic, repetitive and morally confused. Kret
clearly wants to generate an atmosphere of assaultive intensity,
but after a while the raised voices and pounding fists induce a
kind of weary numbness.
</P>
<P>
   The only real charge comes from the soundtrack, which features
some terrific songs by antiracist hardcore bands like Minor Threat,
Social Unrest and the Wives.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the attack on Steve and Sam, the scenes of
violence tend to be sloppily filmed and loosely edited, and the
sheer number of them further dilutes their effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Matters are not helped by the acting, which ranges from almost
credible (Aimee Chaffin as the chief skinhead's moll; David Lee
Wilson as his sociopathic sidekick) to unwatchable (Ann Zupa as a
neurotic fat girl; Anna Padgett as a skittish junkie; Brandon
Slater as the gang's mentally retarded mascot).
</P>
<P>
   Racist extremism is a problem. We need movies that address it.
Chances are you already agree with these propositions. All
``Pariah'' succeeds in doing is screaming them at you, at maximum
volume, over and over and over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `PARIAH' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Randolph Kret; director of photography,
Nils Erickson; edited by Bill Deronde; music by Scott Grusin; Joint
Effort, production design; produced by Shaun Hill and Vince
Rotonda; released by Indican Pictures. Running time: 105 minutes.
With: Damon Jones (Steve), David Oren Ward (Crew), David Lee Wilson
(David Lee), Elexa Willams (Sam), Aimee Chaffin (Sissy), Angela
Jones (Angela), Anna Padgett (Lex) and Brandon Slater (Doughboy). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
