<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-IVINS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     02-17 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVINS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHRUB': A TEXAS-STYLE BASHING: DOUBLE-TEAMING `DUBYA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Shrub,'' the title of this new book about George W. Bush, says
it all: the dismissive nickname, first coined by former Gov. Ann
Richards of Texas, is a tip-off that this isn't going to be a
nonpartisan assessment of this Republican presidential candidate;
it's going to a sassy, sarcastic indictment of Bush and his
policies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the book reads like a long, editorial rant against
Bush's political record, a rant that's sometimes persuasive,
sometimes unfair, if almost always entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Ivins, a columnist for The Fort Worth Star-Telegram, and
Lou Dubose, editor of The Texas Observer, make no secret of their
liberal bias in the pages of this book. ``The dirty secret of Texas
government,'' they write, ``is that we keep our `low tax, low
services' tradition going by cheating the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   They depict Bush as a ``wholly owned subsidiary of corporate
America'': ``We don't think this is a consequence of political
calculation; it is more a consequence of his life experience,
political thinking and party affiliation. We can find no evidence
that it has ever occurred to him to question whether it is wise to
do what big business wants. He is perfectly comfortable, perfectly
at home, doing the bidding of big bidness.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the legwork of other reporters from both the national and
Texas press as a springboard for their commentary, Ivins and Dubose
argue that as a candidate Bush benefited, at crucial points in his
career, from family influence and the largess of corporate
interests. They observe that most of the money for his failed oil
business ventures was raised during the years when his father ``was
either running for president or serving as Ronald Reagan's vice
president,'' and contend that he sold his stock in one of those
companies shortly ``before news of the company's precarious health
was made public.''
</P>
<P>
   He ``walked away from the whole mess,'' they coyly add, ``with
more money than Bill Clinton ever dreamed of making on a little
real-estate deal now known as Whitewater.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush's foray into baseball, which enabled him to turn a
$600,000 investment in the Texas Rangers into a $15 million profit,
Ivins and Dubose write that ``the team increased its book value
from $83 million to $138 million by convincing the city of
Arlington there would be no more baseball unless local taxpayers
sprang for a new stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, they observe, this anti-tax politician personally
benefited when residents of Arlington, worried about losing their
franchise to another city, voted ``to add a half-cent to one of the
highest sales taxes in the nation in order to raise the $191
million needed to build the Ballpark at Arlington.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the view of Ivins and Dubose that George W. Bush _ or
``Dubya,'' as they call him _ has successfully straddled ``the
divide between the Christian right and the economic conservatives
in the Republican Party'' by giving the members of the Christian
right ``just enough to keep them in line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks the talk but rarely walks the walk,'' they write, and
still gets the support of the Christian right because it wants to
be on the side of a winner. These observations, needless to say,
went to press before Bush's loss to John McCain in the New
Hampshire primary, a loss that has not only put Dubya's
front-runner status in question but has also heightened his tilt
toward his party's right wing.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Ivins and Dubose argue, Dubya's real concerns have
less to do with ``God, guns and gays'' than with the issues
``dearest to the business community,'' namely ``tort reform, lax
regulation of industrial polluters, tax cuts for the oil and gas
industry, electricity rates that place the interests of industry
far above the interests of consumers, and privatizing welfare for
huge profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of business, they argue, is Dubya's No. 1 priority,
a position that has had particularly serious consequences, they
contend, in the area of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   As governor of ``the state with the highest volume of air
pollution in the nation,'' Ivins and Dubose write, Bush
``accommodated the state's biggest polluters'' by implementing a
program of ``voluntary compliance.'' The companies that helped to
design that voluntary program, they add, showed their support for
Bush by contributing $260,648 to his 1998 gubernatorial campaign,
and $243,900 to his presidential campaign within a month of the
opening of his exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that even more financial support (as much as $4.5
million by one estimate) has come to Bush from business, medical
and real estate groups intent on promoting tort reform that would
help insulate ``corporate interests from lawsuits filed by
consumers, workers, injured parties and the survivors of those
killed through malice or negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   In depicting Bush as a friend of big business, who is ``blind to
the difficulties of life in the nation's underclass,'' Ivins and
Dubose rely upon a blend of sarcasm and down-home Texas invective
to make their points. Though this makes for a highly readable
narrative, it can also backfire on the authors when they overstate
their points.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing Bush's reported distaste for reading policy books,
for instance, it seems quite gratuitous to add that ``people who
have read only one book can be quite dangerous _ witness Timothy
McVeigh and all those poor citizens who read Ayn Rand and are stuck
like Saul of Tarsus on the road to Damascus.''
</P>
<P>
   The one area in which Ivins and Dubose give Bush high points is
education, writing that ``he has been attentive, consistent, and a
hard worker to make public schools a higher priority for the
state.'' But they add that the weakness of the Texas governorship _
the office, they write, ranks ``behind lieutenant governor,
attorney general, comptroller and land commissioner'' in terms of
actual power _ means that ``it is impossible to give him the lion's
share of the credit for any single initiative _ too much of the
heavy lifting has been done by others.''
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, they argue, Bush's record as governor indicates
that ``he doesn't know much, doesn't do much, and doesn't care much
about governing.'' So much so, they conclude, that ``it's kind of
hard to figure out why he wants a job where he's expected to
govern.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SHRUB: THE SHORT BUT HAPPY POLITICAL LIFE OF GEORGE W. BUSH' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Molly Ivins and Lou Dubose &QL;
</P>
<P>
   179 pages. Random House. $19.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
