<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PITCH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     02-17 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITCH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PITCH BLACK': DARK AND DISMAL DOINGS ON A PLANET WITH THREE SUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his elephantine glare and trapezius muscles that could
support a Mack truck, Vin Diesel, who appears in two films opening
Friday, is definitely the flavor of the movie weekend. In ``The
Boiler Room'' he is a hulking illegal stock trader who would be
right at home in the world of ``The Sopranos.'' And in the snazzily
atmospheric sci-fi horror film ``Pitch Black'' he is Riddick, a
fiendishly grinning murderer with a nose for menstrual blood. In
the movie's opening scenes, in which Riddick tears off his
manacles, he suggests a bone-crushing hybrid of Hannibal Lecter,
Harry Houdini and Hulk Hogan stomping out of a leather fetishist's
private dungeon.
</P>
<P>
   But in both roles Diesel finds ways to insinuate glints of
humor, intelligence and even a grudging sweetness. As styles of
macho, shaved-headed antihero go, he is a new variation on
something familiar. Think of Telly Savalas as a hip-hop thug, and
you'll get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, of course, no one's trapezius muscles could
actually handle a Mack truck. But the combination of Diesel's
massive shoulders and good-natured sarcasm go a long way toward
carrying ``Pitch Black'' above the muscle-bound fray. Narratively
speaking, the movie isn't much more than a flickering montage of
scary action sequences set in the nightmarish murk of a remote
planet after the crash landing of a spacecraft that kills most of
the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But in evoking a fear of darkness and of shrieking batlike
things slicing at you when the lights go out, the movie shrewdly
taps into the lurking primal terrors of anyone who ever had to
sleep with a night light. If ``Pitch Black'' goes where ``The Blair
Witch Project'' has gone before, it has millions of dollars at its
disposal to give that unnamable menace a shape as well as a sound.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the list of survivors besides Riddick, who is being
transported from one prison to another, are his sullenly handsome
guard, Johns (Cole Hauser), and the spacecraft's attractive docking
pilot, Fry (Radha Mitchell), who become the quarreling de facto
leaders of an escape plan. The remaining survivors, a loose rainbow
coalition, range from a Muslim cleric to a fussy English
antiquities dealer whose stash of fine wine comes in handy as
lighting fuel when a solar eclipse (the planet has three suns)
plunges the wasteland into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch Black,'' directed by David Twohy, from a screenplay he
wrote with Jim and Ken Wheat, tweaks this formulaic
escape-from-hell story with just enough original touches to give it
a lift. Hauser's Johns may look heroic, but he turns out to be no
Luke Skywalker when he is discovered injecting morphine into his
eyeball. And while Mitchell's Fry fits the image of a Little Fixit
Superwoman who will lead everyone to safety, she turns out to be a
bit of a bungler.
</P>
<P>
   One of the movie's most ingenious touches is to make the
carnivorous monsters, who come out only at night, all things to all
fantasies. When first encountered, they are wriggling subterranean
octopuses that shoot shiny tubular tentacles out of holes in the
desert and pull their prey underground. Once the planet's sulfurous
yellow daylight ends, they swarm above the desolate desert-scape in
chattering armies. When deprived of human prey, they begin to
attack and devour one another while in the air, raining down bluish
blood and entrails on those below. But the clearest glimpses of
them come through Riddick's surgically improved, radarlike night
vision, in which they resemble shark-toothed flying starfish. The
movie also shows the humans through the creatures' eyes as shadowy
line drawings.
</P>
<P>
   One thing ``Pitch Black'' can't do is begin to create the
engulfing sense of total darkness that its title promises. Even
when the survivors' lights begin to fail (among the unforeseen
meteorological events on this supposedly parched planet is an
unexpected cloudburst), the humans are clearly visible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as their lights begin to flicker, and the ravenous
creatures gather on the edge of darkness, you have an ominous sense
of what the world must have been like before electric light gave us
the illusion of rationality, a time when our demons couldn't be
instantly banished with the flick of a switch.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Pitch Black'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has profanity and some
gory violence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PITCH BLACK'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Twohy; written by Jim and Ken Wheat and Twohy,
based on a story by the Wheat brothers; director of photography,
David Eggby; edited by Rick Shaine; music by Graeme Revell;
production designer, Graham Walker; creatures designed by Patrick
Tatopoulos; produced by Tom Engelman; released by USA Films.
Running time: 107 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Vin Diesel (Riddick), Radha Mitchell (Fry), Cole Hauser
(Johns), Keith David (Imam), Lewis Fitz-Gerald (Paris), Claudia
Black (Shazza) and Rhiana Griffith (Jack/Jackie).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
