<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-CAVEDWELLERS-$     02-17 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CAVEDWELLERS-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PALESTINIAN CAVEDWELLERS OUSTED IN MIDEAST BATTLE FOR 'FACTS ON
THE GROUND'
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Feb. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A-TWANI, West Bank _ Life in a cave was good for Ibrahim Abu
Jundiyeh, but his family lost even that meager existence in the
fight for the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were happy. We were joyous in the cave. We had our land,''
Abu Jundiyeh said. They had rugs on the dirt floor, an entrance of
stone blocks and a few hundred square yards for his wife, 11
children and their livestock to spread out.
</P>
<P>
   But they were among about 450 people, according to the Israeli
human rights group B'Tselem, that the Israeli army has evicted from
caves in the rocky Hebron hills since October.
</P>
<P>
   The families say they had been in the caves for generations.
Now, many have gone to tents and borrowed homes in the villages
nearby, some of the poorest in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   They complain that many of their goats and sheep, which shared
their large caves at night, have died from cold. The children have
coughs too, after months of winter rain and a snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather die than live like this,'' said Abu Jundiyeh,
50.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Army officials said Abu Jundiyeh and the others had to
be moved because they were in a military zone set aside for
light-weapons target practice. Palestinians say they never hear
weapons firing and claim such military zones are just excuses for
land confiscation.
</P>
<P>
   The cave dwellers appear to be caught amid the jostling of the
Oslo peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Under Oslo, Israel is withdrawing from land in the West Bank
captured in 1967. But there are about 150 Jewish settlements,
really housing developments, spread throughout the area.
</P>
<P>
   The settlements are part of the battle for ``facts on the
ground'' in the West Bank. The idea is that final rulings about who
gets land will be determined by who is living there at the time.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say the settlements create obstacles to a peace
agreement. Under pressure to stop their growth, the Israeli
government last fall evicted militant settlers from about a dozen
new outposts they had established.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Jundiyeh's eviction _ and subsequent arrest for eight days
when he refused to move _ came Nov. 16, just a few days after
Jewish settlers were evicted from the Ma'on Farm settlement nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The army told the settlers they could not stay in a firing
range, and the leaders of the 170,000-strong settler movement
pointed to the several hundred cave dwellers, demanding they be
cleared out too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a war going on for my country,'' said Yehudit Tayar,
spokeswoman for the settlers leadership council. ``The decisions
that are going to be made are going to be very dependent on where
everybody is.''
</P>
<P>
   Shlomo Dror, spokesman for the Israel's military administration
of the West Bank, said that other cave dwellers in firing ranges
have been evicted over the last several years. They are regularly
allowed back to tend their fields.
</P>
<P>
   He says the cave families have other homes and are only in the
tents because Palestinian leaders want to use them as facts on the
ground against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But, some of the army's harshest critics come from Israel
itself. Israeli peace groups, for example, have helped Palestinian
groups provide tents and medical care to the cave dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, seven Israeli writers signed a public plea for
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak to let the cave dwellers go home.
The list included literary notables as Amos Oz and A.B. Yehoshua.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel ashamed about what we are doing, for what our army
is doing,'' said author David Grossman, who signed the letter. ``I
have seen a lot of injustice in the last 15 years, but it is very
rare that you see such an injustice so clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said that even if the cave dwellers have other homes _
and many deny that they do _ cave life has been their chosen way
for generations.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Mahmoud Hussein Hamamdeh, lost two caves where his
family and livestock lived. Now, he is borrowing a dirt-floor,
stone house here in A-Twani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will wait to return to my land,'' he said, ``Or, I will die
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
