<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN18-CO     02-17 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN18-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Confederate flags for everybody
 &HT;    (Fixes grammar and clarity in 3rd and 7th grafs.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ People ask what I think about the Confederate
flag flap. I tell them not much.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the truth. I don't spend much time thinking about the
Confederate flag, or what it represents then and now. It neither
inspires nor inflames me. I could say the same about the Lone Star
flag.
</P>
<P>
   The American flag, however, is something else again. I can
become teary-eyed when we're singing ``The Star-Spangled Banner''
as I watch Old Glory waving in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   The more I travel in other parts of the world, the more America
means to me, and the flag for which it stands, indivisible.
</P>
<P>
   What the Confederate flag stands for is what's currently
dividing this nation's people _ meaning as it does, for some, the
heritage of the Old South; for others, the racism of neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Same flag, same flagpole, diverse reactions _ and you ain't just
whistling ``Dixie.''
</P>
<P>
   Which sort of brings me to my point. As you may or may not know,
the song of the Old South, ``Dixie,'' was appropriated by Union
forces during the Civil War, such were its stirring strains.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, even today, you'll find these alternative lyrics in
the archives of patriotic songs, the way the North sang it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Way down South in the land of traitors,
</P>
<P>
   ``Rattlesnakes and alligators,
</P>
<P>
   ``Come away, come away, stay away, Dixieland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where cotton's king and men are chattel,
</P>
<P>
   ``Yankee boys must win the battle,
</P>
<P>
   ``Come away, come away, stay away, Dixieland.''
</P>
<P>
   If I had been a Union soldier in the time of the Civil War,
that's the version I would have sung.
</P>
<P>
   And if I were an African-American in these times, I think I
would appropriate the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   Certain modifications, of course, would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Picture the battle flag of the Confederacy _ blue bars of white
stars crossed on a blood-red field _ which speaks volumes of the
heritage of the Old South.
</P>
<P>
   Now picture the battle flag of the Confederacy _ the same blue
bars, the same white stars, the same blood-red field, but
surrounded by a huge black circle with a slash through it. That
would speak volumes as well.
</P>
<P>
   If I were an African-American, I'd probably fly that flag over
the headquarters of the NAACP, on the grilles of 18-wheelers driven
by black truckers, on the walls of black-owned restaurants and
other private businesses _ all the places where you see the
traditional Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   And even on a separate but equally prominent flagstaff over the
Capitol building of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Would it outrage white Southerners who revere the flag of the
Old South?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. That's the whole idea.
</P>
<P>
   Because if nothing else, it would accomplish this much:
</P>
<P>
   Those white Southerners, who say they can't understand the rage
of African-Americans when the Confederate flag is displayed in
public places, would now know exactly how it feels.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of The Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers and proudly displays in the
privacy of his own home a Civil War photograph of his
great-great-grandfather wearing the uniform of the Confederacy.
Mailing address is P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75904; e-mail,
jmurray(AT)txucom.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-YARDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     02-17 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YARDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WHOLE NINE YARDS': A SCHLUMPY DENTIST AND HIS WISE-GUY
NEIGHBOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Whole Nine Yards,'' Matthew Perry can be seen in the
kind of role Bruce Willis used to get in the beginning of his film
career (in movies like ``Blind Date''): the likable loser who just
wants to do what's right. And Willis has graduated, if that's the
word, to playing the kind of grinning tough guy he used to mock on
the old ``Moonlighting'' television series.
</P>
<P>
   Perry is Oz, a nice-guy dentist so beaten down by his bored,
pouty harridan of a wife, Sophie (Rosanna Arquette), and his
mother-in-law, who ridicules him mercilessly, that he's given to
fits of anger. After he pulls out of his driveway, Oz just starts
pounding the interior of his car with his fists, or his forehead.
Collecting himself, he drives off and a few yards later begins
flailing away at the steering wheel again.
</P>
<P>
   When the confident Jimmy ( Willis) breezes into the house next
door, decked out in ensembles from the Danny Aiello collection _
open two-toned sport shirts exposing fresh white undershirts _ Oz's
anxieties are ratcheted up several points on the Richter scale. It
turns out Jimmy is Jimmy (the Tulip) Tudeski, a former Chicago
organized crime figure who ratted out his associates. Sophie
coerces Oz into giving Jimmy's location away to Jimmy's old mob
boss, the peculiarly accented Janni (Kevin Pollak).
</P>
<P>
   Oz is scrambling to dig himself out of a financial crater his
father-in-law left behind; he sighs, ``I'm worth more dead than
alive.'' Sophie, playing both sides, wants a hit on him. And Jimmy,
with his bark of a laugh, sets Oz's knees to knocking whenever he
turns up.
</P>
<P>
   It's an intricate sprawl of a plot, ``The Whole Nine Yards,''
with hit men, love interests (Jimmy's ex-wife, played by Natasha
Henstridge, is part of the story, too), large sums of money and
allegiances constantly in motion. The mountainous Michael Clarke
Duncan plays a hit man so big he's like a ZIP code with a pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, who resembles a puppy that benefits from rather chic hair
care products, shows the knack for slapstick that he employs on the
sitcom ``Friends,'' flinging himself about as if trying to take a
bullet for his president. His real talent is verbal finesse, which
he doesn't get to exploit; some of his line readings on ``Friends''
are so precise that it takes a moment for them to register. (He can
do almost as much with a nervous pause or stammer as Woody Allen.)
Wrapping a tanned arm around Perry as he prepares to take him for a
drive, Willis coos, ``It won't kill you.'' Perry mutters,
``Promise?''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is another Jonathan Lynn identity-crisis comedy; he
directed ``My Cousin Vinny'' and ``Trial and Error,'' with Michael
Richards, which may have been the biggest misuse of the wide screen
in the history of big lenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yards'' is minus the verve of someone who can take a simple
idea to the extreme; it must have been directed by a sleepwalker.
Despite Perry's plucky slapstick and the treacherous gunplay that
accounts for the second half of the movie, ``Yards'' is
underwhelming, amusing only in fits and starts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few things in the film's favor is that it's actually
set in Montreal instead of pretending to take place in an American
city. (For once, the Canadians don't try to hide their fluted
vowels.)
</P>
<P>
   The real star of ``Yards'' is Amanda Peet, playing Jill, Oz's
receptionist, a young woman with a keen affinity for the mechanics
of murder. Her smile has the warm wattage of Julia Roberts, with a
grin so prominent and appealing that you almost expect a joke to be
played off of it, since this is a movie about a dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Jill has the same sunny, eager interest in her boss as in
Jimmy's career as a hit man; she doesn't make distinctions about
anything she likes. She comes to represent an ideal _ loyalty _ but
does so with such blithe commitment that she's like grapefruit
sorbet: she cleanses the palate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Whole Nine Yards' is rated R (under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes nudity,
violence and language particular to gangsters. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE WHOLE NINE YARDS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jonathan Lynn; written by Mitchell Kapner; director
of photography, David Franco; edited by Tom Lewis; music by Randy
Edelman; production designer, David L. Snyder; produced by David
Willis and Allan Kaufman; released by Warner Brothers. Running
time: 100 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With: Bruce Willis (Jimmy Tudeski), Matthew Perry (Oz
Oseransky), Rosanna Arquette (Sophie), Michael Clarke Duncan
(Frankie Figs), Natasha Henstridge (Cynthia), Amanda Peet (Jill)
and Kevin Pollak (Janni Gogolak). &QL;
</P>
