<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-N     02-17 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAILS COUNT   IN   RENOVATION OF THE WHITE HOUSE BLUE ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Mass., Ark. ,  Ireland, France ) (ART ADV: A photo, NYT20, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By   WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year is the 200th anniversary of Abigail and John Adams'
move into the White House. As its first residents, they had very
little furniture, and Adams complained about the spartan
surroundings. The current White House curator, Betty C. Monkman,
said that at the top of her wish list for future acquisitions would
be ``something _ anything _ associated with the Adams family, be it
silver, furniture or a portrait of Mrs. Adams.''
</P>
<P>
   Monkman knows what she needs. She has just completed a book on
the historic furnishings of the White House, which Abbeville Press
and the White House Historical Association will publish in
September.
</P>
<P>
   It is the antiques in the White House that determine its
decoration. Take the Blue Room, which was recently renovated at a
cost of $358,358. (The money was raised by the White House
Endowment Fund, a nonprofit charity and subsidiary of the
historical association.) The entire project was driven by the
design of a suite of French furniture that President James Monroe
ordered in 1817.
</P>
<P>
   History buffs will recall that the White House was designed in
1792 by James Hoban, an Irish architect turned Southerner who won a
design contest advertised in newspapers. (The ad was written by
Thomas Jefferson, then secretary of state, who also entered the
contest but lost.) The oval Blue Room was placed on the State
Floor, where public receptions are held.
</P>
<P>
   The British sacked and burned the White House in 1814, but it
was rebuilt in 1817. James Monroe, a Virginian, and his New
York-born wife, Elizabeth, were the first residents of the rebuilt
mansion. As American minister to France, Monroe had lived in Paris
for years. As president he ordered 2 sofas, 2 screens, 6 footstools
and 38 chairs from Pierre-Antoine Bellange (1758-1827), a master
Paris cabinetmaker patronized by Napoleon, Louis XVIII and Charles
X.
</P>
<P>
   He also ordered a marble-top table and a pier table, the only
two pieces of furniture that have remained in the White House
continuously since 1817, according to Betty Boyd Caroli, author of
``Inside the White House.'' He specified mahogany, but Bellange
delivered gilded beechwood, decorated with carved sprigs of olives,
telling Monroe that mahogany was not appropriate for a presidential
palace. Cynics think the French were unable to obtain mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   When the Monroes left the White House, they took some of the
Bellange suite with them. Presidents were allowed to remove
furnishings until 1961, when Congress made all objects belonging to
the White House ``inalienable'' parts of its permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   President James Buchanan sold the rest of the Bellange chairs at
auction in 1860, when Empire furniture went out of style, and
replaced them with a Victorian Rococo Revival suite.
</P>
<P>
   Kaki Hockersmith, the Little Rock, Ark., decorator commissioned
by Hillary Rodham Clinton to help redo the White House in 1992,
said three of the original Bellange chairs were acquired in 1961
and 1962. One of the original bergeres and three more chairs were
bought in 1972, during the presidency of Richard M. Nixon. (Nixon
sponsored the largest program of antiques acquisition for the White
House, guided by Clement E. Conger, the curator who assembled the
fine collection of American antiques that grace the diplomatic
reception rooms at the State Department.)
</P>
<P>
   With several of the Bellange pieces in hand, Hockersmith went
about redoing the Blue Room, which had last been refurbished in
1972 and was quite shabby from the onslaught of 1.5 million
sightseers a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were considerations of style, color, paint finishes,
wallpaper and carpets,'' said Hockersmith, who was required to
consult regularly with the Committee for the Preservation of the
White House. The first lady is chairwoman of the committee, which
also includes the director of the National Trust for Historic
Preservation; Jonathan Fairbanks, a former curator of decorative
arts at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston; curators from the
Winterthur Museum, Garden and Library in Delaware; and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge was to decorate around the French furniture,''
said Monkman, who is also on the committee. ``We wanted a sense of
how French decor would have been done in a ceremonial house in
1817.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Thomas Savage Jr., a committee member who runs Sotheby's
educational programs, added: ``We tried to create a room that would
speak eloquently to the Bellange furniture. We wanted the room to
be evocative of the high-style taste of the Monroe era.''
</P>
<P>
   The first consideration was color, as the room had been many
shades over the years, including robin's-egg blue. ``Mrs. Clinton
wanted a more vibrant blue,'' said Hockersmith, who is also
decorating the Clintons' new home in Chappaqua, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked a blue that was known on the Continent at that
time,'' Savage said. ``But we also had to consider how the color
would look on camera, which is very tricky. Receptions in the Blue
Room are often televised, so we had to make some concessions for
modern living.''
</P>
<P>
   After long deliberations Hockersmith ordered $112,000 worth of
sapphire-blue silk with gold medallions for the Bellange chairs and
blue and gold silk for the draperies from Scalamandre.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the wallpaper. Wendy Cooper, a curator at Winterthur,
and Richard Nylander, director of the Society for the Preservation
of New England Antiquities, joined Hockersmith for a day at the
Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum in Manhattan, looking at
period wallpapers and documents. For the side walls they chose a
document from an 1820 New England house belonging to the society
and a swag border and dado from original French wallpapers of 1815.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton said the swag border didn't look quite right,''
Hockersmith recalled. ``So we took away part of the brown shadow,
and it suddenly looked like real fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   The wallpaper had been done originally as a block print.
Brunschwig et Fils had to transfer it to silk-screen, a process
that took weeks. Hockersmith ordered $24,215 worth of the
wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   The blue rug with the center medallion is a copy of a period
carpet from England that was French-inspired. ``It's an 1820s
design,'' Nylander said. ``We chose it to coordinate with the
furniture.'' Hackersmith ordered a copy from Stark Carpet, at an
estimated cost of $48,500.
</P>
<P>
   So it went. Decision after decision. It took years to complete
the Blue Room. ``It looks spectacular now,'' said Stuart Feld,
president of Hirschl &AMP; Adler, who sold the White House two pairs of
French sinumbra lamps from the 1820s and is a frequent visitor.
``I've known a succession of curators there,'' he said. ``They are
less likely to spring for an antique unless it has a direct
connection to the White House. But they are always interested in
anything that was there once.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1725EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0039 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LESS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-17 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LESS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOT ONE LESS': A SUBSTITUTE TEACHER IS PUT TO THE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By A.O SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zhang Yimou's ``Not One Less'' enlarges the possibilities of
filmmaking even as it grounds itself in one of cinema's oldest,
most basic principles: the camera's ability to document reality.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang is best known for heart-wrenching, visually stunning
period dramas like ``Raise the Red Lantern'' and ``Shanghai
Triad,'' and for his association with Gong Li, one of the
outstanding film actresses of our time.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Not One Less,'' he has chosen to work with a cast of
ordinary villagers and city dwellers _ schoolchildren, shopkeepers
and minor functionaries _ most of whom play themselves. And he has
restrained his painterly temperament _ the sense of color and
composition he used to magnificent effect in movies like ``Ju Dou''
and ``Red Sorghum'' _ preferring simply to observe the ragged
textures and jerky rhythms of daily life in a poor, dusty corner of
modern China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not One Less'' is, among other things, about scarcity. In one
early scene, an elderly teacher painstakingly counts out 26 pieces
of chalk, one for each day of the month he will be absent. When the
chalk is broken and trampled because of the carelessness of his
temporary replacement, you feel an almost sickening sense of waste.
And later you feel something like awe at the sight of 27 children
sharing their reward for a hot day's Sisyphean labor in a
brickyard: two lukewarm cans of Coca-Cola, which is all they can
afford.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its deliberate austerity, ``Not One Less'' is
extraordinarily rich. And despite the look and pace of raw
documentary film, the movie is a splendid, assured piece of
storytelling. Its narrative emerges slowly and organically from a
mass of observed detail so that it feels like a series of events
the camera has discovered out in the world, rather than like the
realization of a scheme the filmmaker has devised beforehand in his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of ``Not One Less'' is Wei (Wei Minzhi), 13, a
primary school graduate who has been pressed into service as a
substitute teacher in the Shuiquan Primary School. She stands a few
inches taller than her charges, and it is hard not to hear more
than a trace of irony in their voices when they address her,
according to the dictates of courtesy and custom, as ``Teacher
Wei.''
</P>
<P>
   Her main qualifications, other than the fact that no one else
wants the job, are an innate, unsmiling bossiness, neat handwriting
and her ability to perform, in a tentative, quavering voice, one
song about Chairman Mao.
</P>
<P>
   The film's first half is like a cinema-verite debunking of every
uplifting heroic-teacher melodrama from ``The Corn Is Green'' to
``Dangerous Minds.'' Teacher Wei writes lessons on the blackboard,
her students copy them into notebooks and everybody seems pretty
miserable. Pedagogical rapport is out of the question: either Wei
succeeds in browbeating her pupils or they succeed in humiliating
her. (The impulse to abuse substitute teachers seems to transcend
cultures.)
</P>
<P>
   Especially successful is Zhang Huike, who drives Wei to
paroxysms of frustration. (The class clown is also, apparently, a
universal archetype, unless young Zhang Huike has access to pirated
satellite broadcasts of ``The Simpsons.'')
</P>
<P>
   But then Zhang Huike is sent to the city to work off his
parents' debts. Wei, who has been promised a bonus if she can keep
her class intact (this is the source of the film's title), sets out
to bring him home. And the movie, which has so far been a slow,
touching study of village life, becomes something else: a work of
lyrical realism that has some of the shattering, redemptive power
of Vittorio De Sica's ``Bicycle Thief.''
</P>
<P>
   Wei Minzhi's performance, if that is the word for it, slowly
takes on a heroic cast. Her character is composed of equal parts
pigheadedness and cluelessness, which is to say that she's 13 in a
way that anyone who knows a real 13-year-old, or has been one, will
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Her sense of how the world works is based on instinct, wishful
thinking and second-hand information, and is almost entirely at
odds with the way the world works.
</P>
<P>
   The long second half of the film, in which Wei fruitlessly hunts
for Zhang Huike on the bewildering streets of the provincial
metropolis of Jiangjiakou City, is almost unbearable. Why doesn't
she just give up and go home? Only an infernally stubborn,
hopelessly ignorant child would persevere in the face of a world so
huge, so unyielding and so casual in its cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Wei might be the younger sister of the title character in ``The
Story of Qiu Ju,'' Zhang's 1992 film, which starred an almost
unrecognizable Gong Li as a pregnant farmer's wife pursuing an
apparently hopeless cause through China's implacable legal
bureaucracy. Like Qiu Ju, Teacher Wei will not take no for an
answer, and the force of her will transports this movie beyond
naturalism into the realm of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not One Less'' earns its emotional payoff the hard way. It may
be the greatest film ever made about obstinacy, which it reveals to
be not only a virtue, but also a species of grace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `NOT ONE LESS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Zhang Yimou; written (in Mandarin, with English
subtitles) by Shi Xiangsheng, based on his novel; director of
photography, Hou Yong; edited by Zhai Ru; music by San Bao;
produced by Zhao Yu; released by Sony Pictures Classics. Running
time: 106 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Wei Minzhi (Herself), Zhang Huike (Himself), Tian Zhenda
(Mayor Tian), Gao Enman (Teacher Gao), Sun Zhimei (Sun Zhimei),
Feng Yuying (Television Station Receptionist) and Li Fanfan
(Television Host). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
