<P>
   DOW _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan removed any doubt
on Thursday that interest rates on business and consumer loans _
the kind that sustain economic growth _ are headed higher. In his
Humphrey-Hawkins testimony, Greenspan said the U.S. economy is
still growing too fast even after four short-tern rate hikes since
last June. He added that the Fed will stick to a policy of
``incremental interest-rate increases'' this year to avert
inflation _ even though he added that, at the moment, ``inflation
has remained largely contained.'' The prospect of higher interest
rates sent financial and other interest-sensitive stocks lower,
dragging down the Dow Jones industrial average. But technology
stocks advanced on profit gains. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ASTA-TRAVEL _The nation's largest travel agent group wants the
government to block creation of a travel web site owned jointly by
several airlines, including Atlanta-based Delta. In a filing to the
Justice Department, the group says the web site would lead to
price-fixing and ``end, once and for all, the hope for a vigorous
competitive industry that was the promise of airline
deregulation.'' The airlines say the site would be independently
managed to ensure neutrality. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
