<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News has moved the following feature
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients. For questions
about stories, please contact Steven Rosenberg at the Daily News,
(818) 713-3752.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MEG-RYAN-INTERVIEW _ She's Megnetic _ at least that's kind
how Meg Ryan is described by her ``Hanging Up'' co-star Lisa
Kudrow. While Ryan is still making movies, it's motherhood and
coffee-drinking, in that order, that take priority most days. By
Glenn Whipp (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PEET-FEATURE _ Amanda Peet is the bright (and occasionally
naked) spot in ``The Whole Nine Yards.'' She's also got a day job
as the Jack in ``Jack and Jill'' on the WB. By Bob Strauss (moved
on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   TV-PICKS _ Daily News TV critic David Kronke picks the ``Law &AMP;
Order''-meets-``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit'' crossover and
an ``X-Files''-meets-``Cops'' blend as two shows to look out for
this weekend (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PITCH-BLACK-REVIEW - Down-on-their-luck space humans
crash-land on a desert planet populated by strange, dangerous
things. You've seen it before. ``Pitch Black'' doesn't do it
particularly worse or better than the median ``Alien''-attrition
norm. By Bob Strauss (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BOILER-ROOM-REVIEW - ``Boiler Room,'' a high-energy look at
a group of Generation-X stock swindlers, is a modestly entertaining
film that's mostly derivative of other, better movies like ``Wall
Street'' and ``Glengarry Glen Ross.'' But at least first-time
writer-director Ben Younger is smart enough to acknowledge those
sources, while simultaneously bidding to become part of the greed
canon. By Glenn Whipp (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NINE-YARDS-REVIEW - ``The Whole Nine Yards'' isn't as funny
as ``Analyze This,'' but after a slow start it develops into its
own kind of farcical good time. And its extreme nature actually
adds to the laughs _ what you're expected to buy into here is often
so dark, the only honest response to it is in gasping chuckles. By
Bob Strauss (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   FILM-NOT-ONE-LESS-REVIEW _ A sweet and winning tale of an
innocent girl's fierce determination, ``Not One Less'' finds
Chinese director Zhang Yimou embracing the very same themes he did
eight years ago in ``The Story of Qiu Ju.'' Only here, Yimou has
cast the film entirely with non-professionals, with all
participants roughly playing the same roles they have in life. By
Glenn Whipp (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HANGING-UP-REVIEW _ The unsurprising news that families can
drive you nuts is unnecessarily emphasized by the shrill clan
depicted in ``Hanging Up.'' By Bob Strauss (moved on the ``e''
entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ASLEEP-AT-THE-WHEEL _ Already the recipient of six Grammy
Awards, Asleep at the Wheel could be forgiven for being at bit
jaded about the chance to double that number with its half-dozen
nominations for Wednesday's awards ceremony. By Fred Shuster (moved
on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-DISCS-REVIEWS _ CD reviews by Daily News staff (moved on
the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-COLUMN _ ``Double Jeopardy,'' with Ashley Judd and Tommy
Lee Jones,'' and a re-release of the Truffaut's ``Jules and Jim''
are two highlights of this week's upcoming VHS and DVD releases. By
Rob Lowman (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-SONGS _ Hap Palmer takes traditional kids' favorites like
``Old McDonald,'' ``Itsy Bitsy Spider'' and ``Bingo,'' and updates
them with new verses to help young ones learn their numbers,
letters and colors. By Nancy Hewitt (moved on the ``e''
entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   TV-SUNDAY-REVIEWS _ Sweeps brings us ``Little Richard,''
starring Leon as the flamboyant rocker, ``The Wishing Tree,'' with
Blair Underwood as a magical, mute forest-dweller, and ``Flowers
for Algernon,'' with Matthew Modine updating the role that earned
Cliff Robertson an Oscar in 1968's ``Charly.'' By David Kronke.
EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, FEB. 20. (moved on the ``e'' entertainment
wire).
</P>
<P>
   GAME-ZOBMONDO _ You don't really have to swallow worms or eat
boogers anymore now that you're grown. But you can still take these
and other such dares (in spirit, anyway) with a new board game,
Zobmondo, created by a former business student at UCLA. By Phil
Davis (moved on the ``e'' entertainment wire).
</P>
<P>
   BREAD-MADE-BY-HAND _ Suzanne Dunaway shares her secrets for
making Italian-style breads by hand in her new cookbook, ``No Need
to Knead: Handmade Italian Breads in 90 Minutes.'' Story with
recipes. By Natalie Haughton (moved on the ``d'' food wire).
</P>
<P>
   BREAD-SIDE _ A profile of bakery owner and cookbook author
Suzanne Dunaway. By Natalie Haughton (moved on the ``d'' food
wire).
</P>
