<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT     02-17 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEVIDEO NOTES AND NEWS
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AND BARDOT CREATED SIZZLE
</P>
<P>
   It has become a flood: Brigitte Bardot videos. By the end of
April there will be 10 Bardot films in recent release, an absolute
outpouring for a figure who, though she more than made a mark for
herself in the 1950s as the liberating ``sex kitten'' of French
film, hardly has the retrospective potential of, say, Humphrey
Bogart (the subject of an 18-film video reissue next month).
</P>
<P>
   Movies by the bunch are often linked to commemorative occasions,
and in this case the death last week of Roger Vadim, the French
director who helped make Bardot famous, might have served the
purpose. But the Bardot video wave had already begun in October
with ``Une Parisienne'' (1957), a bedroom farce with Charles Boyer,
and ``Plucking the Daisy'' (1956), with Bardot as a frisky romance
novelist who is shipped off to a convent, both released by Home
Vision.
</P>
<P>
   In November came ``The Night Heaven Fell'' (1958), directed by
Vadim, in which Bardot makes a long sexual getaway with a
good-for-nothing (Stephen Boyd) who has murdered her uncle and
seduced her aunt.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Home Vision will release Vadim's ``Don Juan''
(1973), with Bardot as a MademoiselleDon Juan, and his film ``And
God Created Woman'' (1956), in which Bardot's wild dancing and
frank sexuality electrified French film and helped make it
something of a sensation in the United States. In that film, in
garb ranging from scanty to nothing, the young Juliette (``pouty''
and ``saucy'' being two favorite adjectives applied to Bardot
characters) keeps a rich old womanizer (Curt Jurgens) dangling
while having an affair with the brother (Christian Marquand) of her
brooding, long-suffering husband (Jean-Louis Trintignant). ``And
the devil created Bardot,'' someone wrote in the French press.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly, although Bardot never made apologies for cutting a wide
sexual swath. In April, Anchor Bay will release a documentary,
``Brigitte Bardot: Take One,'' in which the actress, now 65, takes
a guileless and pleasantly offhand view of her celebrity. Vadim
calls her a ``royal personality, with her very direct humorous
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Bardot, who came from eccentric but strait-laced parents, was
married to Vadim when they made ``And God Created Woman.'' But
earlier the very notion of the director had upset her father. ``Dad
had a gun in his office, and he showed it to Vadim and said, `If
you touch her, I'll use it,''' she recalls in the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with Vadim, a legendary lover and husband of
one screen goddess after another, ended during the filming,
although they continued to work together. Other Bardot films coming
from Anchor Bay include Vadim's ``Please Not Now!'' (1961), a
comedy; ``Come Dance With Me'' (1959); and ``Naughty Girl'' (1956).
</P>
<P>
   Jay Douglas, Anchor Bay's chief movie buyer, said there was no
special occasion for the Bardot titles. Last year he and some
associates had been discussing the greatest of the century in
various categories, and the topic of sexiest women came up. ``And
Bardot has been underexposed on home video,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE JEOPARDY
</P>
<P>
   In the pretty Northwest, a pretty art dealer (Bruce Greenwood)
with a pretty wife named Libby and a cute son hatches an insurance
scheme that makes it appear that Libby murdered him on their nice
new sailboat. The jury buys it, but this being the movies, Libby
walks free in six years and into the custody of a parole officer
named Travis (Tommy Lee Jones).
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that her supposedly dead husband took off with her
best friend (Annabeth Gish), Libby gives Travis the slip and takes
off to locate the fellow and reclaim her son. But all the
Hitchcockian games are ``more memorable for their settings, like an
elaborate New Orleans cemetery, than for their sense,'' Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Paramount. $107.37; DVD, $29.95. 106 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKFAST OF CHAMPIONS
</P>
<P>
   Full of early-'70s irreverence, Alan Rudolph's film plunges into
1950s greed with the wild exuberance of Kurt Vonnegut's 1973 novel.
A model of grotesque self-promotion, the suburban car dealer Dwayne
Hoover (Bruce Willis) has an alienated neurotic for a wife (Barbara
Hershey), a would-be lounge singer for a son (Lukas Hoss) and a
closet transvestite for a partner (Nick Nolte). But while a
sterling cast pumps a lot of adrenaline into the caricatures, the
satire now seems overheated in a movie that ``looks and feels like
a frantic, live-action psychedelic cartoon'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Hollywood. $104.16. 110 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   BEST LAID PLANS &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Barker's thriller mixes two friends (Alessandro Nivola and
Josh Brolin) and an available young woman (Reese Witherspoon) who
has a sexual encounter with one of them but turns out to have been
the girlfriend of the other. In any event, she ends up gagged and
handcuffed in a visually ambitious but exasperatingly written film
that aspires to the chilly moral ambiguity of ``The Usual
Suspects'' but too often ``seems to be playing ethical dress-up
with film noir crises it can't fully embrace'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Fox. $104.16; DVD, $34.98. 90 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   JOE THE KING
</P>
<P>
   Frank Whaley's sincere but wobbly first film does a good enough
job of conveying the embarrassment, panic and despair of a young
boy (Noah Fleiss) growing up dirt poor in a strife-torn household
in upstate New York in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Val Kilmer and Karen Young are the embattled parents who
alternately take out their frustrations on each other and the boy,
who is left to skulk miserably and take up petty crime. Whaley
elicits fine performances.
</P>
<P>
   But individual monologues seem oddly disconnected in a movie
that ``feels unglued, as if crucial sequences had been left on the
cutting-room floor'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Trimark. $79.99; DVD, $24.99. 100 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   IT HAPPENED HERE and WINSTANLEY. This week two acclaimed films
by Kevin Brownlow and Andrew Mollo are available at reduced prices.
What would have happened if the Nazis had overrun Britain? ``It
Happened Here'' (1966, 96 minutes) vividly imagines such an
occupation. In ``Winstanley'' (1975, 96 minutes), an English
Reformation-era religious sect tries to establish itself on land
coveted by neighboring villagers. In both films, Lawrence Van
Gelder wrote in The New York Times, `` Brownlow and Mollo recreate
a convincing milieu, disdain simplistic reasoning and heroics, and
demonstrate that the riches of a film reside not in its budget but
in the talent and dedication of those who make it.'' Milestone.
$29.95 each. Information: (800) 603-1104.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS RAMS SUPER BOWL XXXIV CHAMPIONS. Anyone with the
slightest interest has already been exposed to every replay a dozen
times or more, but here, from the vantage point of no fewer than 20
cameras, is the Rams' inarguably exciting victory over the
Tennessee Titans. Embellishments include interviews and coverage of
the Rams' progress through the NFL season. USA. $19.95. 60 minutes.
Release date: Feb. 21.
</P>
