<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT DELAYED?: WHAT THE AIRLINE OWES YOU AND WHAT MIGHT YOU GET
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by STRANDED-TIPS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was trying to get home from Europe, which required changing
planes in Philadelphia. Which was OK, because it was better than
one of the other options, which involved a stop in Tunisia. (Don't
ask.)
</P>
<P>
   It was even OK when the flight from Philadelphia to Fort
Worth-Dallas got canceled because of airline snafus after a
snowstorm. I spent the night at a comfortable airport Sheraton, at
the airline's expense; they also gave me a dinner voucher and a
long-distance phone card and booked me on their first flight to
Fort Worth the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But that was just the beginning. Almost 24 hours later, I did
end up in Texas _ in Houston. (Again, don't ask.) Which was better
than the alternative: spending another night, this time at my own
expense, in Charlotte, N.C. (stop asking), and taking my chances on
getting onto one of the next day's Fort Worth flights.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I got all the way home _ you really don't want to
hear that part _ I was more confused than ever about this: When
your flight is canceled, just exactly what does the airline owe
you? Meals, phone calls, an overnight stay in a plush airport
hotel, a flight somewhere else _ or nothing?
</P>
<P>
   A review of the policies of 10 major U.S.-based airlines reveals
that you might get all of the above. Or some of it. Or maybe zip.
</P>
<P>
   And possibly during the same trip.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, what you get depends on the reason your flight was
scratched. (The airline's fault, you win. The weather, you lose.)
</P>
<P>
   But unofficially, it may also depend on which airline you're
flying, how much you spent on your ticket, whether you fly the
airline frequently, whether you have special needs or are traveling
with children or older people _ and, possibly, the mood of the
people making the decisions that day at that airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you find, when you start looking at it, is that they're
pretty vague promises,'' says Ed Perkins, a consumer advocate for
the American Society of Travel Agents. He is also the former editor
of the Consumer Reports Travel Letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody comes out and says, we will give you a
hotel room. What they say is, we will do whatever is appropriate,
which is simply a way of getting off the hook. ... What you get is
pretty much up to the airline.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the major airlines _ American, Southwest, United,
Delta, TWA, US Airways and the like _ voluntarily adopted plans
aimed at improving customer service. The plans were a kind of
compromise after months of discussion among airline leaders,
legislators and the federal Department of Transportation, and they
cover such topics as the airlines' plans to improve the
availability of airfare and delays information to passengers, calls
for a government review of liability limits for lost luggage, and
improving airline responsiveness to complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are supposed to make this information available to
the public; you can download the plans on each airline's Web site.
These plans also detail what can happen in the case of a flight
being canceled or delayed.
</P>
<P>
   But the only situation that is covered by law is when you lose
your seat on a domestic airline flight because of overbooking.
(Fewer than one in 10,000 domestic passengers is involuntarily
bumped, according to 1999 statistics from the federal Department of
Transportation.)
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, the rules are pretty cut-and-dried: If you get
involuntarily bumped from an overcrowded flight and get to your
final destination more than an hour late, you are paid the cost of
the one-way fare or $200, whichever is less. If the delay is more
than two hours, that amount is doubled.
</P>
<P>
   (This deal applies only if you hold up your end of the bargain.
For instance, if you showed up at the gate late, even if the flight
hadn't departed, you'll likely be out of luck.)
</P>
<P>
   But all other cases are, to some degree, open to interpretation.
Most airlines follow a policy roughly similar to this:
</P>
<P>
   When a flight is canceled or delayed, the airline first tries to
reroute you on their next available flight. If the delay is the
airline's fault, and you can't get to your destination that day,
they'll put you up at a hotel for the night, provided a room is
available. They'll also try to help with meals or other
incidentals. Sometimes, that means they might hand out free
sandwiches and soft drinks in the boarding area; sometimes they'll
give you vouchers to take to airport restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   If the airline doesn't consider the delay to be within their
control _ for instance, if an airport is closed because of ice or
there is a problem at the air-traffic control tower _ you're on
your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do whatever we need to do to take care of the passenger
if it's something within our control,'' says Mark Kienzel, a
spokesman at Fort Worth-based American Airlines. But ``when it
snows 4 feet in Buffalo there's not much we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   That said, what actually happens can be much murkier _ depending
on who's traveling.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent traveler Judy Goldschmidt, a tourism worker in
Philadelphia, recalls that about a year ago, thunderstorms caused
her to miss a connection between St. Thomas and Philadelphia; she
spent the night in Puerto Rico at her own expense. But she met a
group, which included a passenger using a wheelchair, that received
hotel accommodations, dinner and breakfast, all paid for by the
same airline that had declined to help her.
</P>
<P>
   On a different trip last month, Goldschmidt had to pay for her
room when she got stuck in Florida because of a blizzard on the
East Coast. However, she met other passengers stranded by the same
snowstorm _ but traveling from international destinations _ who
received rooms and meals from the same airline.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the airlines don't agree that some passengers get
preferential treatment _ ``We view all of our customers the same,''
says Beth Harbin of Dallas-based Southwest, famous for its
all-coach policy.
</P>
<P>
   But others say it does happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do try to reward the loyalty of our best customers, those
who have shown they will fly on us often, and we do try to reward
the customers who are spending the most,'' says Kurt Ebenhoch, a
spokesman at Chicago-based United Airlines. Though the airline has
policies on what's given out when, gate agents are given more
leeway with first-class passengers and frequent fliers, among
others, he says.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the airlines say their goal is to minimize the
number of cancellations in the first place _ and to deal with
stranded or delayed passengers more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past year, for instance, United has introduced
portable checkout units that are brought into the gate area during
delays or cancellations. They allow more gate agents to work at the
same time, moving lines along faster, Ebenhoch says. The airline
also has introduced a paging system for Internet-enabled
passengers; go to their Web site before your flight, and you can
arrange to be paged in case of gate changes, delays or
cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines point out that the percent of delayed and canceled
flights has hovered at about the same rate for years, somewhere
around 20 to 25 percent. Only a small percent of those flights are
actually canceled.
</P>
<P>
   That does not take into account, however, that airlines are much
busier than a decade ago. About 10 years ago, the flight load, or
average passenger level, was about 60 percent. Today, it's 70
percent or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Cancellations ``may not happen more often (today), but it
probably takes the airlines longer to work out all the kinks,''
says Perkins. ``There aren't as many empty seats, so if your flight
is delayed or canceled, it takes longer to get everybody home.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   So when you run into delays, what other outs do you have?
</P>
<P>
   For one, you can try to get there on another airline. Most major
airlines have interline agreements with other carriers, which means
they will accept each other's tickets if the airline authorizes
such a transfer.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't work with everybody. Southwest, for one, doesn't
have such arrangements with other airlines; if they can't get you
to your destination, they won't send you to another airline, and
other airlines won't accept your Southwest ticket. Southwest counts
on being able to get passengers there through its large number of
daily flights to most of its destinations, says spokeswoman Harbin.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents say your best bet is often pre-planning. Try to
avoid the last flight of the day, avoid connecting flights in
airports with a tendency toward weather problems, and be ready to
negotiate with gate agents if there's a delay, says Steve Loucks,
director of public relations for the Carlson Wagonlit Travel chain.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, an airline ticket is a contract, points out consumer
advocate Perkins. So, if you don't get the service you contracted
for, you have the right to sue. Don't expect to recover damages _
``You can't really say, `I missed the flight and lost a
million-dollar business deal, so you owe me a million dollars,' ''
Perkins says.
</P>
<P>
   But if you file in small claims court, you stand a fair chance
of recovering costs directly related to the canceled flight,
Perkins says. This might include the cost of a hotel room, meals,
transportation, long-distance phone calls and/or an additional
higher-priced airline ticket.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Perkins says he has heard of few travelers who
actually go to all that trouble. Which is easy to understand. If
you've ever had to spend an extra 30 or 40 hours on the road, like
I just did, by the time you get home, you'd rather just forget the
whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FYI: The Department of Transportation publishes a booklet
containing more information about your rights when flying. You can
read it at www.dot.gov//airconsumer//flyrights.htm, or you can
order a copy for $1.75 (postage included) by writing Consumer
Information Center, Pueblo, CO 81009
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
