<HEADLINE>
`FLOWERS FOR ALGERNON': GETTING SMARTER ISN'T NECESSARILY GETTING
HAPPIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Program notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New York
area. Check local listings.) 
(af) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlie Gordon is a tough role for any actor. Oscar voters
recognized that and gave Cliff Robertson the best actor award for
the 1968 film ``Charly.'' (Spelling consistency has never been the
entertainment industry's strong suit.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Matthew Modine takes on the challenge in a CBS movie,
``Flowers for Algernon'' (the title of the Daniel Keyes novel on
which both films are based), and while he does an admirable job,
the resulting film makes Robertson's achievement seem all the more
astonishing in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie is a mentally retarded man who is asked to participate
in an experiment. He undergoes surgery that gradually increases his
IQ, not to make him normal but to turn him into a genius. The
experiment works, and it changes his life in innumerable ways, some
of them unwelcome. And, it turns out, there's a catch.
</P>
<P>
   In the new film, which has its premiere on CBS on Sunday night,
Charlie's first glimmer of recognition comes when his fellow bakery
employees make fun of him, as they always have, and he realizes he
doesn't think the idea of ``pulling a Charlie Gordon'' is so funny
anymore. He is feeling the first taste of dignity, born of new
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   When the transformation results in a romance with his teacher,
Alice (Kelli Williams of ABC's legal drama ``The Practice''),
Modine's Charlie remains childlike and gentle. In the same
situation, Robertson's character took on a more traditional
masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years later, what is remembered about Charly is his
subtle but excruciating emotional evolution.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations and reactions of today's Charlie seem
one-layered, and his brilliance often comes across as just
obnoxious. That's especially true when he turns film critic after
seeing ``Anna Karenina'' with Alice. ``They reduced the novel _
excuse the cinematic reference _ to black and white,'' he
pronounces.
</P>
<P>
   Some attitudes in ``Flowers for Algernon'' seem dated and
offensive now. Ron Rifkin, as the doctor conducting the experiment,
refers to Charlie as ``one of nature's mistakes.'' But the film has
its charms. The love scene between Charlie and Alice is discreet,
tender and very touching, and the story succeeds in being a
tearjerker.
</P>
<P>
   Algernon, incidentally, is the lab mouse who undergoes the same
surgery as Charlie. He has problems, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FLOWERS FOR ALGERNON' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Sunday at 9 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written by John Pielmeier; based on the novel by Daniel Keyes.
Jeff Bleckner, director; Taavo Soodor, production designer; Linda
Muir, costume designer; Michael Fash, director of photography;
Geoffrey Rowland, editor; Mark Adler, music. Craig Zadan, Neil
Meron and David R. Ginsburg, executive producers; Mark Winemaker,
producer; Bleckner, co-producer. Produced by Citadel Entertainment
and Storyline Entertainment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Matthew Modine (Charlie Gordon), Kelli Williams (Alice),
Richard Chevolleau (Burt), Jeff Pustil (Gimpy), Ken James (
Donner), Richard Fitzpatrick (Frank), Bonnie Bedelia (Rose) and Ron
Rifkin (Dr. Strauss). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC has been shameless in recent seasons about exploiting
viewers' musical memories in order to boost ratings. ``Little
Richard,'' the network's latest effort in that area, may be uneven
and at times lazy, but at least it conveys a frank, joyous love of
its subject. Or maybe the credit for that should go to the film's
star.
</P>
<P>
   The actor known as Leon plays Ricardo Wayne Penniman, who in the
early 1950s (as he will enthusiastically remind you) may have
invented rock 'n' roll. He captures Little Richard's enthusiastic
narcissism as well as his magnetic stage presence.
</P>
<P>
   The story follows the singer from Macon, Ga., to New Orleans to
international fame. It begins as a father-and-son drama, focusing
on the parent's reaction of horror to the child's effeminacy, and
makes strong points about racism before turning into a traditional
rags-to-riches story. (He presents his mother with a big pink
mansion and buys lots of clothes.)
</P>
<P>
   But ``Little Richard'' does a good job of celebrating the energy
and excitement of early rock 'n' roll. Even if the crosscutting
between Richard's and Pat Boone's versions of ``Long Tall Sally''
goes on a little too long, it's priceless. In the end, Leon and
Little Richard have something crucial in common: just a little
touch of star quality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `LITTLE RICHARD' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Sunday night at 9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 4 in New York) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
