<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Feb. 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A winter storm will bring a potpourri of precipitation to the
Northeast and Great Lakes on Friday as low pressure tracks
northeastward from the Ohio Valley. At daybreak, snow will be
falling at a fast rate from northern Pennsylvania to northern
Illinois. During the day, warmer air will stream up and over a
layer of subfreezing air, causing the snow to change to sleet in
portions of the interior Northeast. Precipitation will commence as
snow Friday morning along the Northeast seaboard but will change to
rain near the coast. Total snow accumulations of 4 to 10 inches are
expected during Friday and Friday night from near Chicago to near
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, humid air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico
will fuel numerous showers and thunderstorms from the Tennessee
Valley to the middle Ohio Valley on Friday. Some of the storms may
be severe, replete with damaging winds and hail. A few of the
showers and storms will reach the Carolina coast by evening.
Unseasonably warm air will continue to cover Texas and the
Southeastern states. Amid plentiful sunshine, afternoon
temperatures will reach well into the '70s across the region with
80-degree readings across most of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Sinking currents of air associated with high pressure will
promote sunshine and seasonable temperatures from the Northwest to
the northern Plains. Generally dry weather will also prevail
farther south across California and the Southwest though spotty
snow showers will pepper many of the west-facing mountain slopes of
the central Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Caboose Storm
</P>
<P>
   The storm system that will produce wintry precipitation across
the Northeast on Friday marks the last in a series of Pacific
disturbances to streak across the nation in the speedy southern
branch of the jet stream. Typically, such a ``caboose'' jet stream
disturbance marks the end of the existing weather pattern and a
switch to a new regime. Indeed, instead of the current pattern of
two swift tributaries of the jet stream, the southern branch will
weaken, slowing the eastward progress of Pacific disturbances,
while the northern branch recedes northward, virtually locking cold
air in Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
