<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0070 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-17 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GO FUR IT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When animal rights zealots opposed to the wearing
of fur disrupted the recent spring New York fashion extravaganza
with their familiar scare tactics, they were figuratively beating a
dead horse _ or rather a dead mink.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators leapt up, waved banners reading ``fur shame,'' and
tossed a tofu pie at the runway. But the rude antics didn't stop
the parade of fur-trimmed clothes, which were wildly applauded as
they came down the runways.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward a resigned spokesperson for People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals (PETA) called it ``our last hurrah.'' It was a
graceless and overdue retreat from a socially worthless enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a decade ago, however, PETA and its allies sent the
fur industry into a slump with a brash crusade to persuade or
frighten women into dumping their elegant and warm fox, raccoon,
sable and mink coats in favor of wrapping up in wool. (Sheep are
politically correct, being luckier than other animals prized for
their coats. After they are sheared, they live on to be sheared
again.)
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive campaign, marked by sneak attacks that spattered
paint on women wearing fur coats on the streets, intimidated
individuals and the industry for awhile. But gradually the feminine
desire for beautiful outer garments has overcome feelings of guilt
about wearing the pelts of murdered animals.
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost a half-century since Richard Nixon saved his
own political skin by immortalizing his wife's preference for a
``good Republican cloth coat.'' He was sending a message of false
humility, not one of outrage over animal assassination. In any
case, Patricia Nixon promptly donned a mink after they finally made
it to the White House in 1968 and cloth coats have not been
identified with Republicans since.
</P>
<P>
   The last straw for PETA was a referendum last year to force
fancy Beverly Hills shops to attach labels to fur coats describing
the POSSIBLE (not necessarily actual) murderous methods by which
pelts meet their fate. The idea was that if purchasers saw tags
describing cruelty to animals, the fur industry would go out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Hills may be full of spoiled rich folks, but they are
not fools. They rejected the nuttiness and with that elite
endorsement fur has soared again.
</P>
<P>
   Coat sales have rebounded. One industry report says sales are up
25 percent over last year. Supermodels who used to pose nude in
anti-fur advertisements are now seen shamelessly flaunting mink.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the economy. Maybe it's resentment against the
moralizing of single-minded zealots. Maybe it's just the sheer joy
of wearing a nice fur.
</P>
<P>
   So PETA is shifting its energies to a new target. Now PETA has
announced it is going after leather, also the product of skinning
dead animals. Leather, by this logic, is just hairless fur.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is particularly upset about the apparently
brutal methods in India of slaughtering cattle, whose processed
hides are shipped to the United States and Europe. A video of
alleged Indian cattle torture is circulating in Britain to try to
arouse animal lovers. Cattle in the United States are killed in a
more humane way.
</P>
<P>
   This may also be the beginning of a broader campaign against
eating meat; how can you oppose the use of an animal's outside
while enjoying its cooked insides? These PETA people really think
big.
</P>
<P>
   But tackling leather, let alone meat-eating, is going to be a
tough sell. A really tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   Fur is a luxury. We can do without it, even if we fantasize
looking gorgeous in a fluffy Russian red fox hood, just like Julie
Christie in the classic film ``Doctor Zhivago.''
</P>
<P>
   But leather is an accessory necessity and is more versatile than
cotton, canvas, rubber or tree leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Think purses, belts, shoes, watch straps, luggage, billfolds,
vests.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone for wooden shoes? Plastic handbags? Rope belts? Ugh. For
kindergarten kids, maybe. Not for adults.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion industry is currently in love with leather jackets,
coats, pants and boots. Suits with pockets and cuffs trimmed in
leather are hot. Very handsome they are, too.
</P>
<P>
   But the shoe problem is the real stickler here. Going barefoot
is not a culturally acceptable alternative in boardrooms or most
places outside the beach. Sneakers also have their social
limitations. Comfortable, yes. Appropriate everywhere, no.
</P>
<P>
   Both the clunky shoes and stiletto heels now favored by
fashionable women require leather soles, no matter what strange
nonsense dictates the design of the rest of the shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Enforcement of PETA's new campaign would seem a tad awkward.
Will this lead to a rash of purse-grabbing, with the culprits
explaining that they were merely doing research into the question
of leather vs. plastic _ not stealing the money inside?
</P>
<P>
   Will advocates creep along the floor of movie theaters peering
at the soles of feet stretched out along the aisles, to nab those
violators who aren't decked out in canvas and rubber-soled Dockers?
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean anyone approves of cruelty to animals. But a
wholesale assault upon legitimate industries that provide a product
people have liked and used for centuries is not a productive way to
advance a cause. It is only a maddening nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
