<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0073 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-BUSH-HNS &LR;      02-17 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; POLLS SHOW BUSH AND McCAIN IN CLOSE S.C. RACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C.2000 _ Hearst Newspapers &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   FLORENCE, S.C. _ With polls showing Texas Gov. George W. Bush
slightly ahead two days before South Carolina's Republican
presidential primary, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. urged Democrats and
independents Thursday to join Republicans to help him win.
</P>
<P>
   Launching a final 48-hour cross-state dash from the piedmont to
the seashore and back again, McCain asked for the support of
conservative Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a party that welcomes the Reagan Democrats of old''
McCain told a rally in Greenville, in northwestern South Carolina.
``I want a party that says, `Come on in, come on in, there's room
for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused McCain of continuing negative ads despite McCain's
promise not to do so. Bush described as `factually untrue'' a
McCain campaign flyer that says Bush's tax plan would fail to put
`one red cent'' into saving Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted that his plan would funnel $2 trillion of the
projected $4 trillion federal budget surplus into debt relief and
restoring the financial health of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Greenville, McCain defended his advertising as
`an accurate representation'' of Bush's tax plan.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days before the Saturday primary, polls showed Bush
with a slight lead in a close race race. The latest Palmetto Poll,
released Thursday, showed Bush leading McCain by two percentage
points, 49 percent to 47 percent, with a 3.3. percentage-point
margin of error. Former Reagan administration official Alan Keyes
trailed far behind with four percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll _ directed by David Woodard, a political scientist at
Clemson University _ also projects turnout of between 350,000 and
370,000, which would be a record. In 1996 when former Senate
Majority Leader Bob Dole beat conservative commentator Patrick
Buchanan, 276,000 ballots were cast.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard said turnout would be the key. Bush is running way ahead
in most polls among Republicans and if turnout stays in the 350,000
range, `Bush should be OK,'' Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   But if turnout goes over 400,000 with independents and Democrats
turning out in large numbers to participate in the open primary,
`Bush could be in trouble,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Charleston Post and Courier and WCBD-TV showed
Bush with 45 percent and McCain with 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters `I feel like we have a good chance. I'm
taking nothing for granted, however.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, `I actually thought I'd win New Hampshire. I
guess I'm not a good forecaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that, win or lose in South Carolina, he intends to
continue his campaign in upcoming primaries in Michigan and Arizona
next week.
</P>
<P>
   With polls give Bush a big edge among Republican voters, McCain
is banking on support from independents and Democrats, the same
kind of voters who propelled McCain to a landslide victory over
Bush in New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been sort of criticized by the fact that we are
attracting independents and Democrats,'' McCain told an
enthusiastic audience of veterans in Spartanburg, S.C. ``I'm proud
that anyone would flock to our banner. This is about the future of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain told reporters later: ``We used to proudly call them
Reagan Democrats and I'd like to reassemble that coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator has started making more frequent off-hand
references to his distinguished 22-year Navy career in the final
days of a campaign in a state with the highest proportion of
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a Navy pilot shot down over North Vietnam and imprisoned
for five years, is being accompanied by fellow POWs. ``If you see
any really old guys, you'll know I was in prison with them,''
McCain told the rally in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   McCain tells audiences of incidents at book signings for his
autobiography, ``Faith of My Fathers,'' where ordinary veterans
come forward with mementos of their service to the nation. He jokes
that his wife Cindy believes he may be running for president
because of the ``knocks on the head'' he suffered during torture by
North Vietnamese guards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at
202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
