<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NIGHT-THEATER-REVIEW-     02-17 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGHT-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SATURDAY NIGHT': FLATBUSH ROOTS, MANHATTAN DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They look as if they're waiting to be immortalized by
Norman Rockwell, these open-faced Brooklyn lads, but it's clear
that they've got the itch, and bad. Restless, randy, hungry for
action: you've seen their kind before in American musicals, ready
to erupt into violent dance and show-stopping anthems of youth.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, when this quartet sings, in the opening minutes of
``Saturday Night,'' a 40-some-year-old show that is just now having
its official New York premiere, the voices are often soft and
reflective, and the melody they carry keeps sliding away from
forthright buoyancy, as if retreating from hope.
</P>
<P>
   It's a charming, even funny number about nothing more serious
than being single and not having a date. But its wistful quality is
bottomless. When the singers observe that ``alive and alone on a
Saturday night is dead,'' the hyperbole is sincerely felt.
</P>
<P>
   That mood tinges all of ``Saturday Night,'' which opened
Thursday night at the Second Stage Theater here, lending a gentle
power to a show with a slight, contrived book and a decidedly dated
air. It also sets off echoes sure to stir the hearts of aficionados
of the American musical.
</P>
<P>
   The title song of ``Saturday Night,'' written for characters on
the cusp of adulthood, was created by a young composer on the edge
of maturity. Stephen Sondheim, then in his mid-20s, had been given
his first chance to write the complete score and lyrics for a
Broadway show. The musical, which was tabled after the death of its
40-year-old producer, Lemuel Ayers, would remain unproduced for
four decades, itself a story of hopes brightening and dimming.
</P>
<P>
   During its long consignment to limbo, Sondheim quickly graduated
into shiny success. He also continued to write about the pain of
hoping to connect. ``Alone is alone, not alive,'' goes a lyric from
``Company,'' the show that established his reputation as the bard
of urban anxieties. Look closely and you'll see the same yearning
face in ``Saturday Night.''
</P>
<P>
   The startling, expressive talent that gives voice to that
yearning may still be embryonic in ``Saturday Night,'' but it is
definitely there. Kathleen Marshall, the inventive choreographer
(``Kiss Me, Kate'') and the artistic director of the Encores!
musical concert series, has staged ``Saturday Night'' with an
understanding that it has to be treated delicately for its
particular and prophetic charms to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   This tale of coming of age in Flatbush on the eve of the 1929
stock market crash is burdened with a sluggish book by Julius J.
Epstein and characters who suggest a middle-class answer to the
Bowery Boys. It is not made for slam-bang showmanship. Overselling
its tame-seeming streetwise comedy and tentative love story would
sink it.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, Marshall has encouraged her fresh-faced cast, led by the
Australian cabaret star David Campbell and Lauren Ward (``Violet,''
``1776''), to shimmer instead of dazzle. Marshall's choreography
correspondingly emphasizes imaginative wit over calisthenic flash.
It is as if the production were introducing a shy but very talented
child, who must be coaxed instead of pushed into the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Like Derek McLane's sets, which present a vision of New York as
storybook-innocent in its way as that of the movie ``Stuart
Little,'' the overall production has an aura of nostalgia that's
knowing without being snide. Based on ``Front Porch in Flatbush,''
an autobiographical play by the brothers Julius J. and Philip G.
Epstein (screenwriters on ``Casablanca''), ``Saturday Night''
follows the fortunes of a group of Brooklyn chums eager to get
lucky, both financially and sexually.
</P>
<P>
   At their center is the charismatic Gene ( Campbell), at the
house of whose conveniently absent father much of the action takes
place. An order clerk on Wall Street, Gene has been infected with
get-rich fever and a taste for glamour. Trying to crash a dance at
the Plaza Hotel, he meets a fancy Southern debutante type who turns
out to be Helen ( Ward), just another pretender from Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The central, oddly gnarled plot is about how Gene's aspirations
to grandeur get him into trouble. It is not, to tell the truth, a
gripping or believable story, and its adult version of adolescent
humor, wide-eyed with the hint of a leer, must have seemed stale
even in the 1950's.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the show's message _ abandon ambition, be yourself
and stay at home _ is a downer, given the subliminal ache of
longing that informs so much of the music. You get the idea that
most of these characters will indeed spend all their Saturday
nights at home in Brooklyn. No matter what the script intends, this
does not register as a gladdening thought.
</P>
<P>
   But the composer of ``Saturday Night'' is already aware that
``happy endings can spring a leak,'' as a Sondheim lyric from a
later show observes. It's the tug between the conventional
all-American hominess of the script and the suggestions of
ambivalence in its score that make ``Saturday Night'' more than a
dismissible piece of juvenalia. The show has dreary stretches, but
it leaves a sweetly haunting afterglow.
</P>
<P>
   As orchestrated by the extraordinary Jonathan Tunick, a longtime
collaborator of Sondheim's, the score seems forever balanced
between wise-guy jauntiness and lyric gravity. It's an appealing
combination that gives us, on the one hand, several truly exquisite
ballads (``So Many People,'' ``What More Do I Need?'') and, on the
other, comic treats like the ensemble number ``That Kind of a
Neighborhood,'' a paean to life in Brooklyn that anticipates the
satiric lyrics of ``West Side Story.''
</P>
<P>
   You can see glimmers of the hungry words to ``Some People'' from
``Gypsy'' in ``Class,'' Gene's hymn to upward mobility, a song
notable for underpinning brassy affirmation with minor-key doubts.
And the pastiche master that Sondheim would prove himself to be in
``Follies'' is prefigured here in the piano rag of the overture and
the wonderfully droll crooner piece ``Love's a Bond,'' which
translates the language of romance into that of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim's celebrated verbal dexterity comes through slyly in
the sustained financial metaphors of that song, performed in wry
period style by Donald Corren, with simple language in deft
combinations. (``This bond if you get it/is stable and yet it/will
grow if you let it/mature.'') Not every set of lyrics is that
smooth. But who else would manage to find an internal rhyme for sex
in the middle initial of Francis X. Bushman, the silent movie star?
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night'' has been given full productions only twice
previously, at the Bridewell Theater in London (1997) and by the
Pegasus Players in Chicago (1999). In introducing the show to New
York, Marshall doesn't make the mistake of deconstructing something
that most people haven't seen in any form. There's neither
retrospective winking nor heavy-handed dragging of dark emotions to
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the approach is largely to let the score set the tone
for everything else in the show, starting with the soft-pedaled
whimsy of Marshall's choreography. There's a delightful sequence in
which Gene's pals float through a Park Avenue apartment on roller
skates brandishing the accouterments of high-society life and a
winningly graceful and unsalacious interpretation of ``Exhibit A,''
a lesson in the art of seducing a girl, adroitly performed by
Christopher Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In vocal terms, it's hard to imagine a better cast. Michael
Benjamin Washington, Kirk McDonald, Greg Zola and Joey Sorge bring
just the right sharpness and restraint to the intricacies of the
twice-reprised title song. Clarke Thorell and Andrea Burns, as the
show's token married couple, generate a spontaneous feeling of
speech in singing a duet about their first date.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, the image of the Arrow Shirt man come to life, looks
perfect for a magnetic leader of a fledgling white-collar pack, and
as expected, he sings with clear and appealing tunefulness. What he
fails to convey, crucially, is his character's explosive, unstable
side; this Gene is too easy to domesticate.
</P>
<P>
   Ward isn't entirely comfortable with the comic Southern accent
of her first song, which has to be exaggerated for the number to
work. Once that's out of the way, she inhabits her sketchily
written character with a thoroughness that makes her the focal
point of every scene she's in. And she brings a fine emotional
elegance to her love songs.
</P>
<P>
   There is also one heart-stopping scene in which the faces of
Campbell and Ward betray almost too much. ``Saturday Night'' ends,
as musicals of its period usually did, with a finale promising
domestic bliss for its leading lovers. But it's the number that
concludes the first act that you're more likely to remember.
</P>
<P>
   It happens just after Gene has announced to his friends his
intention of marrying Helen, a declaration that takes everyone,
including Helen, by surprise. As the ensemble rousingly sings of
the pros and cons of marriage, it hoists the lovers onto its
shoulders. Gene and Helen exchange a glance just then, and it is
filled with naked terror. Relationships are scary things. Sondheim
has spent much of his subsequent career exploring this basic truth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SATURDAY NIGHT'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Book by Julius J. Epstein; music and lyrics by Stephen Sondheim;
based on the play ``Front Porch in Flatbush'' by Julius J. Epstein
and Philip G. Epstein. Directed and choreographed by Kathleen
Marshall; orchestrations by Jonathan Tunick; musical direction by
Rob Fisher; sets by Derek McLane; costumes by Catherine Zuber;
lighting by Donald Holder; sound by Scott Lehrer; music
coordinator, Seymour Red Press; production stage manager, Karen
Moore; associate director, Rob Ashford; stage manager, Karen
Evanouskas; musical continuity, Sean Patrick Flahaven. Presented by
Second Stage Theater, Carole Rothman, artistic director; Carol
Fishman, managing director; Alexander Fraser, executive director.
At 307 W. 43rd St. in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: David Campbell (Gene), Lauren Ward (Helen), Christopher
Fitzgerald (Bobby), Andrea Burns (Celeste), Clarke Thorell (Hank),
Frank Vlastnik (Pinhead), Michael Benjamin Washington (Ted), Kirk
McDonald (Artie), Greg Zola (Ray) and Joey Sorge (Dino). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
