<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-DANNY-GLOVER-IN-FREEDOM-SONG-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANNY GLOVER: AN OBLIGATION TO HEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Danny Glover in
a scene from ``Freedom Song.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Danny Glover has always been a magnetic performer, but lately
he's taken it to a new level.
 &HT;    The actor recently had screws removed from his foot and ankle
following surgery, and he's promoting the healing process by
resting his bare feet and ankles in a round, metal tray that
generates a magnetic field around them.
 &HT;    It's a strange contrast to the rest of the luxurious suite at
The Ritz-Carlton in Pasadena, Calif., where Glover is promoting
``Freedom Song,'' a Turner Network Television movie about the
civil-rights movement set to air on Feb. 27.
 &HT;    The saga of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee's
efforts to integrate Southern towns and enfranchise
African-Americans in the early 1960s isn't actually as far removed
from turn-of-the-millennium Pasadena as one might think, Glover
believes.
 &HT;    ``I lived this history,'' he says, ``because the other
revolutionary thing that happened at that time in the '50s and '60s
was television.
 &HT;    ``I saw this stuff on television every night,'' he recalls. ``I
saw the Montgomery boycott _ I was 8 years old, but I knew about
those things. My parents were postal workersand talked about those
things and joined organizations. As a child it became part of my
cultural reality, even though I grew up in a city that was
considered very progressive, San Francisco.''
 &HT;    Glover plays Will, a solid, hard-working citizen of the
fictional town of Quinlan, Miss. The civil-rights movement has
arrived in the person of an SNCC organizer, and Will's teen-age son
_ played by Vicellous Reon Shannon, who co-starred in ``The
Hurricane'' (1999) _ joins the campaign, even though in doing so he
jeopardizes his relationship with his father.
 &HT;    ``Will is in the middle of a typical father-son relationship _
one in which the father wants to nurture and protect the boy and
doesn't want him to get hurt,'' Glover says. ``He knows his son
will have to fight his own battles, as every generation does, but
he's also aware that his son might become a casualty in those
struggles, so he's very worried.''
 &HT;    Will's experience is much like that of many African-American men
in the postwar years, the actor adds.
 &HT;    ``African-American soldiers came back from World War II and
said, `In France I was treated as a human being, in England I was
treated as a human being _ and when I came back, black men still
wearing their uniforms and medals were being burned and lynched and
castrated,''' Glover says. ``Will knows he's entitled to more, but
at the same time, because of having to protect his family, he loses
that sense of entitlement in the face of intense fear.''
 &HT;    Glover, who achieved the kind of fame and fortune accorded very
few black actors when he teamed with good friend Mel Gibson for
four ``Lethal Weapon'' movies beginning in 1987, says his own
political activism began at San Francisco State University.
 &HT;    ``I was a student activist before I was an actor,'' Glover says,
his words tumbling over one another in recollected excitement.
``Thirty years ago I was involved in issues like ending apartheid,
developing an ethnic-studies department, fighting for the
liberation of the African colonies. I was always involved, whether
it was with the McGovern campaign, the radicalization of the
civil-rights movement, the Vietnam War or the Black Panther Party _
all of that was part of my culture. The first acting I did was in
radical agitprop theater.''
 &HT;    Now a star, Glover hasn't strayed far from those roots, acting
in and often producing several films and television movies aimed at
educating African-Americans about their history.
 &HT;    He's also an outspoken critic of the lack of minority faces in
network-television shows, but decades in the entertainment business
have left him a cold-eyed realist as well.
 &HT;    ``The networks deal primarily in making money,'' he says. ``If
the demographics show that the people watching my show may be 30 to
40 percent black, and only 10 percent of them are going to go out
and buy the products advertised on the show, why would they waste
their time with them?
 &HT;    ``Network people are not mean-spirited,'' Glover adds, ``but
they have a cultural framework in which they work, and that
cultural framework is that African-Americans are still second
bananas. We may have African-Americans elected to high office and
African-American millionaires, but 51 percent of the incarcerated
population are still African-Americans, and African-American
unemployment is still double digits.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Glover says he isn't an angry man. The father of a
22-year-old daughter, he considers himself a constructive
pragmatist, interested in change instead of conflict for its own
sake.
 &HT;    Not long ago the actor stood helplessly on a New York street as
taxicab after taxicab passed him by _ because, he was sure, they
are reluctant to pick up black passengers. Instead of launching
legal action or holding a protest rally, he filed a complaint with
the city's Taxi and Limousine Commission and began a much-needed
dialogue with the drivers _ most of whom are themselves minority
members.
 &HT;    ``It was not my intention to instigate any punitive action
against the cab drivers,'' he says. ``I said from Day 1 I wanted to
begin a discourse between the drivers, the taxicab owners and those
people who are the victims of this kind of racial profiling.
 &HT;    ``It's about more than me,'' Glover adds. ``It happens thousands
of times a day to people who are not as conspicuous as I am. And I
felt only through a discourse could we put all of our feelings on
the table.
 &HT;    ``My intention was to do something we don't get to do very often
in a very polarized society _ talk to each other and understand and
have compassion for each other.''
 &HT;    Next up for Glover is ``Boesman and Lena,'' co-starring Angela
Bassett and due out later this year. Based on the Athol Fugard
play, it was shot in South Africa.
 &HT;    Some people point to stars such as himself and Bassett as proof
that there's no systemic discrimination against blacks in today's
Hollywood, but Glover begs to differ.
 &HT;    ``Every actor has a difficult time at the beginning,'' he says.
``The only difference between me and a white actor is that I had to
create a space for me to even be in the industry. The white actor
has a space _ whether he gets in or not depends on certain
variables, but they're not the same variables I had to deal with.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, we've done well, the handful of us who've made it,'' he
concludes, ``but that doesn't absolve us of the responsibility. We
are the exception, not the rule.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Freedom Song,'' consult the
Turner Website at www.turner.com. And don't forget to visit The New
York Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate
for information on Hollywood Stars and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
