<HEADER>
A0084 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT &LR;      02-17 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., England, Israel)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Richard Charlton-Jones was cataloging some old master
paintings at Benacre Hall, a Palladian villa near Lowestoft in
Suffolk, England, he spotted a small wood panel painted with a
Madonna and Child flanked by a pair of angels. It was small,
measuring only 8 by 10 inches, and was painted on gold ground.
</P>
<P>
   Charlton-Jones, a director of the old master paintings
department at Sotheby's in London, said he found the work a bit
perplexing. ``It was obviously very old and rare,'' he said. ``I
took it back to London and began researching it.''
</P>
<P>
   After putting the work to sophisticated tests to determine the
age of the wood and the pigments, he discovered that the panel
dated from the late 13th century and that the pigments were
Italian.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many parallels to Cimabue,'' he said, referring to
the Italian painter and mosaicist who predated both Giotto and
Duccio. ``I got nervous and took it to Dillian Gordon, the curator
of early Italian paintings at the National Gallery in London, who
had just acquired two early pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   The two experts studied the work together and concluded that it
was by Cimabue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Madonna and Child Enthroned With Angels'' will be
auctioned at Sotheby's in London on July 6. It is expected to fetch
$3.2 million. This will be the first time a Cimabue has been
offered at auction.
</P>
<P>
   The work, Charlton-Jones said, is part of a small tabernacle, a
portion of which is in the Frick Collection. Even though the
similarities were striking from photographs, he and Gordon took the
panel to New York to study alongside the one in the Frick. They
asked curators from the Metropolitan Museum of Art to examine the
two panels with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two were virtually the same size,'' said Charlton-Jones.
While the Frick panel has been the subject of scholarly debate and
is only labeled ``Tuscan school,'' Charlton-Jones said he was now
certain the two were part of the same tabernacle.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's portion probably formed the top left, which depicted
scenes from the life of Jesus, and the Frick's is thought to have
been from the bottom right.
</P>
<P>
   The angels, the Virgin Mary's throne and the drapery are all
identical in style to another Madonna and Child by Cimabue that is
in the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   ``This painting is one of only seven or eight independent panel
paintings by Cimabue that survive,'' Charlton-Jones said. ``And
this is the only one in private hands.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Owned to Loaned
</P>
<P>
   In what it described as a ``sensitive solution,'' the Israel
Museum announced this week that it had transferred one of its
prized paintings, Pissarro's ``Boulevard Montmartre: Spring''
(1897), to Gerta Silberberg, the daughter-in-law of Max Silberberg,
a Jewish industrialist and collector from Breslau, Germany, who was
killed in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Silberberg is now considered the legal owner of the painting,
but she has agreed to let the museum keep it on its walls as a
long-term loan.
</P>
<P>
   Records that were opened after the Silberberg estate made a
claim to the painting in 1998 showed that it had been sold at
auction in Berlin in 1935 and passed through several owners until
1960, when the Manhattan gallery Knoedler &AMP; Co. sold it to John and
Frances L. Loeb, New York philanthropists.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we got the claim in July, we began investigating
it,'' said James Snyder, the Israel Museum's director. The museum
even brought in Joachim and Lionel Pissarro, great-grandsons of the
artist who are authorities on his work, to help.
</P>
<P>
   The Loebs had promised the painting to the museum in 1985 to
honor Teddy Kollek, the former mayor of Jerusalem who is the
museum's founder and honorary president, on the institution's
20th-anniversary. It entered the museum's collection after Loeb's
death in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Silberberg recovered a van Gogh drawing, ``Olive Trees
With the Alpilles Range in the Background,'' that had been hanging
in the National Gallery in Berlin. In December she sold it at
Sotheby's in London.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer was Ronald Lauder, who donated it to the Museum of
Modern Art, of which he is chairman. He paid $8.5 million, a record
for a van Gogh drawing. Silberberg said she planned to use some of
the proceeds to finance a search for other missing works. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Prize for Pixels
</P>
<P>
   The Tate Gallery in London has the Turner Prize, and the Solomon
R. Guggenheim Museum in New York has the Hugo Boss Prize. Now the
San Francisco Museum of Modern Art has come up with the Webby Prize
for Excellence in Online Art, a $50,000 award to be given annually
for a body of work that is primarily experienced online.
</P>
<P>
   The international competition is open to anyone who wants to
enter. Entries will be accepted from Tuesday to March 14.
Guidelines are available on three Web sites: www.webbyawards.com,
www.sfmoma.org and www.iadas.net.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will be chosen by a panel that includes Gary Hill,
the Seattle video artist; John Maeda, a professor of media arts and
sciences at the MIT Media Lab; Machiko Kusahara, a media art
curator and assistant professor in the Graduate School of Science
and Technology at Kobe University in Japan; and Femke Wolting, the
curator of the Exploding Cinema, the experimental film division of
the International Film Festival in Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will be announced on May 11 and will be featured on
the museum's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pushing online art to the forefront,'' said Benjamin
Weil, the museum's curator of media arts. ``It's hard to tell, but
we'll probably get about 1,000 applications. We're hoping to
discover work we haven't been aware of. This is a new form of being
informed.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getty's Choice
</P>
<P>
   The J. Paul Getty Trust has named Thomas Crow director of the
Getty Research Institute. Crow, who has been the chairman of the
Yale University art history department for four years, will replace
Salvatore Settis, who resigned last year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
