   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Talks on a possible settlement of the
federal antitrust suit against Microsoft are intensifying ahead of
a scheduled new round of court arguments next week. Chairman Bill
Gates said Thursday that top Microsoft officals are deeply engaged
in the Chicago discussions, in which the two sides are now meeting
face to face. Some believe progress in the talks could lead in the
next few days to a settlement or a decision to postpone the court
session. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE _ WASHINGTON _ Studies linking homocysteine, a damaging
enzyme found in all humans, to heart disease and stroke are
becoming so convincing that they could revolutionize public health
policy and the practice of medicine, scientists who have been
studying the substance said Thursday. The enzyme can be controlled
with a daily tablet of vitamins and folic acid. From the annual
meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-HISPANICS _ WASHINGTON _ The percentage of Hispanics
without health insurance has doubled since 1987 to nearly 40
percent, the Commonwealth Fund reported Thursday. (Schultz, Cox
News Service). 18.
</P>
<P>
   DEPORTATION _ WASHINGTON _ The United States should deport
people responsible for commiting torture and genocide in their home
countries, a congressional panel was told Thursday. (Lipman, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   US-AFRICA _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton opens the National
Summit on Africa with a speech Thursday. (Turay, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
