<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     02-17 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BEAUTY,' starring Kevin Spacey, Annette Bening, Chris
Cooper, Wes Bentley and Thora Birch. Written by Alan Ball. Directed
by Sam Mendes (R, 116 minutes). With heavenly finesse Spacey plays
a buttoned-down 42-year-old suburbanite who flips his lid for a
teen-age cheerleader. And he never gets it back on. The midlife
crisis motif is familiar, but the stage director Sam Mendes brings
terrific visual flair and dry humor to this barbecuing of the
bourgeoisie. All the actors display coolly expert timing,
especially Bening as the antihero's grasping wife. Although the
story spreads itself thin among many characters, the film coalesces
for a devastating finale (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE BEACH,' starring Leonardo DiCaprio, Tilda Swinton and
Robert Carlyle. Directed by Danny Boyle (R, 120 minutes). DiCaprio
plays Richard, a young American vacationing in Thailand who is
given a map that leads him to an island paradise. All of DiCaprio's
charisma and the director's savvy are used to divert us from the
fact that there's not much going on here. While DiCaprio shows some
talent, the movie is simply a Colors by Benetton take on ``Lord of
the Flies,'' with the imperious paradise ruler (Swinton) holding
court as the Promised Land crashes around her. Richard finds
himself living the aphorism that has ruined the life of so many
film protagonists: paradise breeds callousness, a marginal
rethinking of beware of the things you want, for you shall have
them (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS DON'T CRY,' starring Hilary Swank and Chloe Sevigny.
Directed by Kimberly Peirce (R, 114 minutes). This stunning debut
feature tells the strange and resonant story of Brandon Teena, who
despite being born Teena Brandon went on to create a charismatic
identity as a young man. Brandon's ultimately wrenching tale may
sound tabloid-ready, but on screen it turns into Theodore Dreiser's
idea of American tragedy. The film makes it hauntingly real and
even tenderly romantic, with the astonishing acting needed to make
it work. One of last year's best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE CIDER HOUSE RULES,' starring Tobey Maguire, Charlize Theron
and Delroy Lindo. Directed by Lasse Hallstrom (PG-13, 125 minutes).
Radically downsized in scope, and its examination of the issue of
abortion greatly softened, John Irving's sixth novel (with a
Dickensian screenplay by the author) has been turned into a lovely
World War II-era fable about a young man venturing out into the
world. Maguire is Homer Wells, a doleful innocent raised in an
orphanage by Dr. Wilbur Larch (Michael Caine), who performs
abortions. Fleeing the institution with a golden young couple
(Theron and Paul Rudd), he becomes an apple picker. Sentimental but
smart, the movie has the sweetness and narrative drive of a 1940s
``David Copperfield'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `EYE OF THE BEHOLDER,' starring Ewan McGregor and Ashley Judd.
Directed by Stephan Elliott (R, 105 minutes). McGregor is a British
surveillance expert and Judd the serial-killing femme fatale he
falls in love with (while observing her kill a boyfriend) in this
ludicrous psycho-thriller. As McGregor's character, known only as
the Eye, follows the object of his obsession from city to city, the
movie tries futilely to capture some of the mystique of
``Vertigo.'' But the film, by the director best known for ``The
Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert,'' is so garish,
disjointed and incoherent that it feels like an extended music
video posing as a movie (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `GIRL, INTERRUPTED,' starring Winona Ryder and Angelina Jolie.
Directed by James Mangold (R, 120 minutes). Except for being
several years too old for the role, Winona Ryder, an actress who
oozes high-strung intelligence, is ideally cast as Susanna Kaysen,
a college-age girl who lands in a Massachusetts mental institution
in 1967 after a halfhearted suicide attempt. (The movie is based on
Kaysen's memoir.) The period details are perfect, and Ryder has the
courage to make her character a pain in the neck. But the small,
introspective movie is nearly stolen by Jolie as a charismatic,
brutally truth-telling sociopath who becomes Susanna's best friend
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE GREEN MILE,' starring Tom Hanks, Michael Clarke Duncan,
David Morse, Doug Hutchison, Sam Rockwell and Bonnie Hunt. Written
and directed by Frank Darabont (R, 180 minutes). In adapting the
death row drama that Stephen King wrote in multiple installments,
the director of ``The Shawshank Redemption'' could have managed
more economy and fewer talky bits of business around the cellblock.
Still, this long film is vivid and well played. Smooth ensemble
acting builds up to the discovery that a gigantic condemned man
(Duncan) is a prisoner with very special abilities, which gives the
film its mixture of religious overtones and mild horror. Hanks, as
a wry Southern prison guard, is so unaffectedly good that it's
redundant to say so (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `GUN SHY,' starring Liam Neeson, Oliver Platt, Jose Zuniga and
Sandra Bullock. Written and directed by Eric Blakeney (R, 102
minutes). Last spring saw both a film comedy (``Analyze This'') and
a cable series (``The Sopranos'') about gangsters forcing
themselves to unload to a shrink. This year, in ``Gun Shy,'' we get
a shaken undercover fed, Charlie Mayo (Neeson), seeing a
psychiatrist on the down-low. Charlie, a wreck who has lost his
nerve after he was exposed during an undercover operation, is
assigned to a job that involves his acting as an organized-crime
envoy. He moves between the preening Fidel (Zuniga), a yuppie
Colombian thug, and Fulvio (Platt), whose vulgar pride in his
violent streak is perverse. Blakeney has come up with one of the
subtlest and most inspired comedies you'll see this year in his
feature-film writing and directing debut (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `HOLY SMOKE,' starring Kate Winslet and Harvey Keitel. Directed
by Jane Campion (R, 95 minutes). Having roamed so gorgeously
through North Africa as a young hippie mother in ``Hideous Kinky,''
Winslet this time appears in India as Ruth Barron, a headstrong
young Australian seeking enlightenment. Eventually Ruth's mother
coaxes her home, where a ``cult exiter'' named P.J. (Keitel) is
waiting to wean Ruth from her Indian guru. But as the film moves
from its early mix of rapture and humor into this more serious,
confrontational stage, it runs into trouble. It doesn't help that
Winslet's obvious strength and beauty leave Keitel's P.J. looking
overmatched (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE HURRICANE,' starring Denzel Washington. Directed by Norman
Jewison (R, 120 minutes). The life story of Hurricane Carter, a
middleweight contender who spent nearly 20 years in prison for a
triple murder he didn't commit, is a big, schmaltzy ballad of a
movie redeemed by Washington's moving, bone-deep portrayal of the
boxer from Paterson, N.J. But the movie plays fast and loose with
the facts, giving far too much credit to the members of a Canadian
commune who took up Carter's cause and all but eliminating his
heroic co-defendant, John Artis, from the story. And the minor
characters are either saints or monsters. Yet the story of a man
heroically fighting his demons and winning his freedom is still
inspiring (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SCREAM 3,' starring David Arquette, Neve Campbell and Courteney
Cox Arquette. Directed by Wes Craven (R, 116 minutes). At this
point it goes without saying that the ``Scream'' movies are like
episodes of ``Scooby Doo.'' Like the others, ``Scream 3'' belongs
on the Cartoon Network. This time for a better reason: the film is
funny and brisk, with enough good lines to make the comedy more
satisfying than the somewhat routine but still unsettling jolts to
the spine. Craven and his group recognize that the franchise's real
competition is not the recent hit films ``The Blair Witch Project''
or ``The Sixth Sense'' but rather ``Scream'' itself. ``Scream 3''
doesn't skimp on jacked-up scares, but it's as much a personality
show as it is a slasher film (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `THE TALENTED MR. RIPLEY,' starring Matt Damon, Jude Law,
Gwyneth Paltrow, Cate Blanchett and Philip Seymour Hoffman. Written
and directed by Anthony Minghella (R, 135 minutes). There are
diabolically smart surprises wherever you care to look in this
glittering thriller. Proving that the brilliance of ``The English
Patient'' was no fluke, Minghella shapes a hypnotic, sensually
charged adaptation of Patricia Highsmith's fascinatingly reptilian
murder story. The traffic-stopping cast includes Damon as the
dangerous chameleon of the title and, in a star-making role, the
English actor Jude Law as a rich dilettante who exerts a homoerotic
magnetism. Paltrow plays the odd woman out with the shrewdness of a
fine character actress, while Blanchett makes the delirious most of
her role as a needy American post-debutante. As the story's odious
playboy-snob, Hoffman is scene-stealingly wonderful. Gorgeously
photographed in Italy by John Seale (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TITUS,' starring Anthony Hopkins, Jessica Lange, Alan Cumming,
Harry Lennix and Jonathan Rhys Meyers. Directed by Julie Taymor (R,
160 minutes). Taymor, the theater director and puppeteer who
created transfixing stage pictures in ``The Lion King'' and ``Juan
Darien,'' has turned Shakespeare's goriest tragedy, ``Titus
Andronicus,'' into a powerful contemplation of murderous revenge
enacted throughout history. Hopkins is ghoulishly funny and tragic
as the title character, whose political stupidity sets in motion a
devastating chain reaction of killing, torture and retaliation.
Lange is Tamora, the captured Goth empress who strikes back.
Although the movie's British theatrical and American film acting
styles don't mesh, Taymor's vision is realized with a shattering
force in time-traveling imagery that blends ancient Rome with
Mussolini's Italy and contemporary cyberpunk flash (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TOPSY-TURVY,' starring Allan Corduner and Jim Broadbent.
Directed by Mike Leigh (R, 161 minutes). Leigh's grandly
entertaining ``Topsy-Turvy'' is one of those films that create a
mix of erudition, pageantry and delectable acting opportunities,
much as ``Shakespeare in Love'' did last year. Instead of a
love-struck young playwright, it presents the curiously matched
personalities of the librettist William Schwenk Gilbert and the
composer Arthur Sullivan in the midst of a robust, knowing,
frequently hilarious look at the musical theater over which they
held sway (Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
