<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      02-17 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Well, Miramax is doing it again. Can no one stop
this?
</P>
<P>
   The little-independent-that-could, now an independent-minded cog
in the Disney empire, has dominated the Academy Awards for a
half-dozen years or so, with best-picture Oscars in 1997 for ``The
English Patient'' and in 1999 for ``Shakespeare in Love.'' In this
year's tight race, with no film dominating the proceedings and no
clear favorite in any major category, it was always assumed that
one or two dark horses could emerge in the nominations, announced
on Tuesday. But very few expected that Miramax's ``Cider House
Rules'' would not only get a best-picture nomination but would also
be tied for second (with Michael Mann's ``Insider'') in total
nominations, seven. ``Cider House,'' playing on only about 800
screens at the moment and just beginning its wide theatrical run,
now stands to capitalize on the momentum of the nominations and
could suddenly become a serious contender for best picture as well
(although the top nomination-getter, ``American Beauty,'' with
eight, remains the narrow betting favorite in Hollywood).
</P>
<P>
   Miramax has drawn criticism in previous years for its aggressive
Oscar tactics, with some studio executives grousing that it was
buying gold statuettes with expensive ad campaigns and plentiful
screenings for academy voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miramax, I think everyone agrees, has taken the lead in how to
market a film to the academy,'' said John Ketcham, a producer of
``The Hurricane,'' which many expected to do very well in this
week's nominations but came away with only one, for Denzel
Washington's lead performance.
</P>
<P>
   But Miramax executives contend that the film, not their
campaign, carried the day. And the creative forces behind ``The
Cider House Rules,'' almost giddy with delight over the unexpected
shower of nominations, were also eager to connect the strong
showing to the way the film has played to audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen people watch the movie, and I've seen people get
emotional about it, and that's all anyone could wish for,'' said
Richard N. Gladstein, the film's producer. ``Actually, this is more
than anyone could wish for.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did ``Cider House'' do so well, while ``The Hurricane''
didn't? Many in Hollywood were attributing the latter film's poor
showing to charges that the movie had misrepresented crucial facts
in telling what is billed as a true story, a charge that the
director, Norman Jewison (an academy favorite who was not nominated
on Tuesday, as many had expected), and the producers vehemently
deny. ``I think the academy is a fickle group,'' Ketcham said.
``They picked films they thought were better. I'm not going to say
they made wrong choices or blame it on the controversy. It may have
hurt us, it may not have. Everybody is welcome to their opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time ``Hurricane'' was embroiled in controversy,
``Cider House'' was ducking one. The film, which on one level is an
argument for abortion rights, has somehow managed to escape being
dragged into the presidential race. John Irving, who wrote the
novel on which it is based as well as the screenplay, half-jokingly
said he wouldn't mind a little controversy if it meant drawing more
people into theaters to see the film. ``Now that Gary Bauer is out
of a job,'' Irving said, referring to the conservative candidate's
withdrawal from the Republican presidential race, ``I think it
would be great if he saw the film and attacked it.'' Something
Different
</P>
<P>
   Richard Farnsworth admits it: he was up at the crack of dawn on
his 60-acre ranch in Billy the Kid country, up along Bonita Creek
at the foot of the Mescalero Apache reservation in New Mexico. ``We
were watching the Oscar nominations on the TV,'' he said. ``Heard
the whole thing, then somebody called right after.''
</P>
<P>
   Farnsworth, a veteran stunt man who says he's semiretired from a
belated acting career, was nominated for best actor for his
performance in ``The Straight Story,'' David Lynch's subtle saga of
an elderly man who drives a lawnmower across two states to visit
his estranged brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm 80 years old in a couple of months,'' Farnsworth
said. ``So I'm quite excited about all of this.'' Extraordinarily
soft-spoken, with liquid blue eyes and a sprawl of white hair,
Farnsworth said he had seen only one David Lynch movie before
accepting the role (``It was `Elephant Man,' way back when, many
years ago'') and was aware that the director was known for darker,
more disturbing fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were about four days into shooting it, and I think we knew
we had something really different,'' the actor said. ``We didn't
know what, exactly, but the crew was getting really excited. When
you've been at this as long as I have, you know that when the crew
gets excited, you must have something.''
</P>
<P>
   Farnsworth said he would attend the Oscar ceremonies on March
26. He's looking forward to it. But even more, he's looking forward
to a hip replacement operation in a few weeks. ``I'm on one cane at
the moment, unlike the fellow in the movie, who was on two,'' he
said. ``But after the operation, then I'll be able to go out riding
horses again.''
</P>
<P>
   Reconciliation
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Friedman said the most intense moment for him this week
came at the end of the first Berlin Film Festival screening of
``Paragraph 175,'' the documentary he made with Rob Epstein about
Nazi persecution of homosexuals. An elderly Alsatian man, Pierre
Seel, who bitterly describes his concentration camp experiences in
the film, walked onto the stage. It was a particularly emotional
moment because in the film Seel had said he would never forgive the
German people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made this great, long speech, and there was so much
applause, it was a real moment of reconciliation,'' Friedman said.
``The place erupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman and Epstein, who also made the ``The Celluloid
Closet,'' a documentary about homosexuals and the movies, have
already struck a deal for ``Paragraph 175'' _ named for the portion
of the German legal code that allowed persecution of gays _ to be
released at the Film Forum in Manhattan in September. And they say
they are still working, with the full cooperation of HBO, which
financed the film, to secure theatrical showings.
</P>
<P>
   They had made ``Paragraph 175'' without German financing. So
they were a little worried about the reception they might get in
Berlin. (The film had already been screened, to much acclaim, at
the recent Sundance Film Festival in Utah). The reaction was
generally positive, they said, although some complained that
Americans, not Germans, had made the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our response is that there are many films to be made; this one
was ours,'' Epstein said. ``It did feel like we'd struck a nerve,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
