<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0096 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCIENCE18-COX     02-17 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE 'OTHER CHOLESTEROL' LINKED TO HEART DISEASE
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Within a few years, scientists say they will know
whether a naturally occurring human protein they could not even
measure a decade ago is causing as many as 50,000 heart disease
deaths every year among Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The substance is homocysteine, and studies indicate that between
30 and 40 percent of heart disease victims have elevated levels of
it in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, hundreds of researchers in the United States and
other countries are scrambling to determine whether homocysteine is
responsible for those cases of the disease or is simply a
``marker'' that coincides with the disease but does not cause it.
</P>
<P>
   If homocysteine, also linked to stroke and even Alzheimer's
disease, is found to be responsible for the diseases, there is a
simple and inexpensive treatment: folic acid and other B vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will know in three to five years,'' pioneer homocysteine
researcher Rene Malinow said Thursday at the annual meeting of the
American Association for the Advancement of Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two important questions that need answers,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   _ Should blood tests be performed on everyone to see if they
have elevated levels of the substance?
</P>
<P>
   _ If a person has an elevated level, should that person be
treated with vitamins?
</P>
<P>
   Malinow said between 15 and 20 clinical trials, involving more
than 200,000 patients, are under way to determine whether the
incidence of coronary heart disease goes down after vitamin
treatments lower homocysteine levels.
</P>
<P>
   Malinow, Cleveland Clinic cell biologist Donald W. Jacobsen and
Aleksandar Rajkovic of Baylor College of Medicine will lead a
symposium Friday on whether a growing understanding of homocysteine
will fundamentally change public health policy and medical
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration requires certain
food manufacturers, especially bakers and millers, to supplement
their products with folic acid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 260 million people in the United States involved in a
huge experiment,'' Malinow said. ``We may already have started
having a significant impact on these diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen said a Harvard University researcher studying a rare
genetic condition that leaves some people unable to rid their
bloodstreams of homocysteine noted in the 1960s that these people
had an increased risk of coronary heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   However, the researcher's suggestion that the protein might be
responsible could not tested until the 1980s, when the Cleveland
Clinic and other research centers developed ways of testing for it.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen said homocysteine may cause deterioration of veins and
arteries because it is toxic to other substances in the cells.
</P>
<P>
   It also leads to the development of hydrogen peroxide in cells,
he said, and hydrogen peroxide breaks down into superoxide and
hydroxyl, two highly reactive free radicals.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
