<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-REFORM-HNS &LR;      02-17 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-REFORM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN BATTLING TO WHIP GOP INTO LINE 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ John McCain's ``national crusade,'' as he
grandly styles his campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination, is a multifront battle that seeks more than just
capturing the White House.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is fighting not only George W. Bush but also the regular
order within their party. The Arizona senator sometimes spells it
out plainly for audiences: ``There's no doubt what we're trying to
do is bring about a new Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign represents the clearest threat to the
Republican establishment, including the party hierarchy and GOP
leadership in Congress, in a quarter century. Not since Ronald
Reagan challenged President Ford for the Republican nomination in
1976 has the party's institutional power structure come under such
a sustained attack from within.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts see McCain making a virtue of a necessity as he
assumes a war footing against his party's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no choice,'' said Stephen Wayne of Georgetown
University in Washington. ``All of the establishment is with
Bush.'' A majority of Republican governors, senators and members of
the U.S. House have endorsed the Texas governor. But McCain's
message is still alluring for nascent reformers who have joined his
effort, such as Knox White, mayor of Greenville, S.C. In endorsing
the senator, White called for a house-cleaning after eight years of
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this means shaking up the political establishment, then so
be it,'' White said. ``I think it needs a shaking up.''
</P>
<P>
   In almost every campaign speech, McCain calls for breaking ``the
iron triangle'' of Washington, which he identifies as lobbyists,
money and legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Congress is in the grip of the special interests,'' McCain
says. His campaign, the senator contends, is ``all about getting
the government out of the hand of the special interests and back to
you'' through overhaul of campaign-finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   McCain would ban the unlimited and unregulated contributions
that individuals and political action committees, usually
representing corporations or unions, can pour into the parties _
so-called ``soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush contends McCain's major campaign-finance proposal,
co-sponsored with Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wisc., would leave
Republicans vulnerable because it would still allow labor
organizations to use dues in political campaigns without explicit
permission from union members. McCain says he could back such a
plan if corporations also had to get permission from individual
stockholders before making ``soft money'' contributions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's proposal puts him on a collision course, should he be
elected president, with virtually every element of the party and
its funding base.
</P>
<P>
   The senator relishes the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, I'm proud, I'm proud, I'm proud that anyone would
flock to our banner because our banner really is all about the
future of America,'' McCain said Thursday at a VFW hall in
Spartanburg, S.C. ``And it's about the future of my Republican
Party because my Republican Party, to some degree, has lost its
way. I want it to be a reform party. I want to be a party that's an
inclusive party.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown's Wayne said the Republican establishment has ``every
reason to be worried'' by the prospect of a McCain presidency.
``He's unpredictable. He doesn't take orders. He gives orders.''
</P>
<P>
   In long bus rides across the South Carolina countryside between
campaign stops, the senator has held forth on what a McCain
presidency would mean for GOP powerbrokers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though McCain claims to have ``very cordial'' relations
with Republican leaders, such as House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, he said they would have to change their method of
operation if he is elected and his reforms enacted.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked if McCain expected DeLay to give up his
close relationship with business lobbyists, who then direct big
campaign donations to Republican campaign committees, the senator
was unambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can have a lot to do with them, but he can't have the kind
of money that's the mother's milk of his whole operation,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that McCain can run the moneychangers out of the
political temple amuses some analysts. Merle Black, a political
scientist at Emory University in Atlanta, said the notion is ``so
ludicrous it's just unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain has been in Congress almost 17 years and is
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, he likes to picture
himself as a maverick outsider, a classic pose for a national
candidate who lacks much establishment backing.
</P>
<P>
   The insider-outsider split is nothing new in a contest for the
Republican presidential nomination, most recently in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan insurgency failed that year but triumphed four years
later as the former movie actor and California governor won the
nomination and the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The split is not unknown in the Democratic Party, when John
Kennedy, an outsider in the Senate, took the 1960 nomination from
consummate insider Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had these tensions for quite a while,'' Wayne said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his fight against money in politics, McCain
lashes out against other standard operating procedures in
Washington, including what he sees as the venality of some
congressional chairmen and leaders.
</P>
<P>
   McCain regularly rails against military weapons systems, which
the Pentagon says it does not need but which are products of
congressmen's home states. A favorite target is a helicopter
carrier ship built near the Mississippi home of Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's critics contend that's pretty rich from a man who has
prospered under the system and is chairman of a committee that has
jurisdiction over virtually every industrial enterprise in the
nation. McCain regularly taps many of those interests for Senate
campaign contributions, some of which he rolled over into his
presidential campaign account.
</P>
<P>
   The senator is undaunted, arguing ``everybody but the old bulls
... would say, `Thank God''' if the system is reformed.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is regularly disdainful of congressional intentions. When
telling a meeting of the American Association of Retired Persons to
be wary of promises that Social Security revenues will be
safeguarded, he sounded this alarm: ``Lock boxes get picked by
master thieves, and Congress is full of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Were McCain to make it to the White House, he would undoubtedly
have his strong partisans out in the country. But whether the
nation would have the same feeling for _ and would politicians have
the same fear of _ McCain as they did regarding Reagan in the early
1980s remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his supporters have formed an intense bond with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But whether that could translate into whipping Congress _ or
even the party _ into line is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing he can do about the Republicans'' already in
Congress ``anymore than Clinton could do anything about the
Democrats,'' Wayne said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sees it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elections have a powerful effect on politicians,'' he said.
``We wouldn't have a big problem controlling Republicans on Capitol
Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   But it likely would be, as McCain calls his campaign, ``a wild
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
