<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0098 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GOP-ISSUES-COX     02-17 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ISSUES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush, McCain similar on issues
 &HT;    By Jena Heath and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _They don't walk alike. They don't talk alike.
But get past the style to the substance and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain think a lot alike, at least more
so than their TV ads suggest.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of some key issues and a look at their respective
tenures in office show that their biggest difference is in style _
and that may matter most as the two battle for victory in
Saturday's key South Carolina primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not huge differences,'' said John Zogby, a
nonpartisan pollster who said his surveys show that voters are
going on gut when it comes to evaluating the two candidates. ``Both
are pro-life. Both are in favor of a tax cut. Both represent maybe
different rungs on the ladder of Republican orthodoxy. ...The
biggest issues are the images and biographies of the two
candidates. ... The real issues come down to style, image.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain hold similar or identical positions on key
issues. They both oppose abortion except in cases of rape, incest
or danger to the woman's life. Neither would make opposition to
abortion a litmus test for Supreme Court nominees. Both support the
North American Free Trade Agreement and want to see China admitted
to the World Trade Organization. Neither has put forth environment
or health care proposals as detailed as those advanced by Vice
President Al Gore or U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Both men say the citizens of South Carolina should decide
whether to keep flying the Confederate flag over the Statehouse _
not a national issue but an explosive one in the Palmetto State.
</P>
<P>
   Their similarities have left the two Republicans scrambling to
prove how different they are from each other. In tax-averse New
Hampshire, the battle was over tax cuts, with Bush pushing a
five-year, $483 billion plan. McCain, meanwhile, pitched a tax cut
half that size, arguing that it would do more to preserve Social
Security and shore up Medicare. McCain beat Bush by double digits.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, Bush is marrying his new, reformer image with
the kind of anti-abortion, pro-God rhetoric that appeals to the
conservative GOP voters he will need on election day. Earlier this
week, he unveiled a campaign funding reform plan, much of it around
since last summer, that resembles McCain's with a key exception _
it would not limit soft money contributions from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   William Connelly, a political scientist at Washington &AMP; Lee
University, said the candidates' differences on campaign finance
reform are a powerful symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``In-kind contributions, soft money, these things make the
American people's eyes glaze over,'' Connelly said. ``I don't think
the arcana of campaign finance reform is really the issue. ...
McCain is the unClinton, the authentic, clean man of principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Georgia, backs Vice President Al Gore for
the White House, but he, too, admires McCain as a person and
politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain is a Republican conservative, but he is a reformer when
it comes to making the government work and when it comes to
campaign finance reform and tobacco,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tennessee, said McCain and Bush have
similar beliefs on issues. Where they differ is in style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think personal characteristics are more important than ever
before,'' Thompson said. ``After the last seven years people
</P>
<P>
   are looking for someone they can admire, look up to. People look
at John and see him as a chance to do something _ that is the core
</P>
<P>
   of his appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, Bush's point-man on Capitol Hill, said that
it is not just McCain's temper and personality that disturb him
about McCain _ it's the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a number of large issues, he simply is not in step with his
own party,'' Coverdell said. Specifically, he said McCain looks
more like Democratic Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts on
campaign finance reform and like Sen. John Kerrey, also a Democrat
from Massachusetts, in his quest to regulate tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Senate supporters solidly back their man despite his
similarity with Bush on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it interesting that the Republican Party establishment
that chose Bush as the knighted one has ignored the experience of
John McCain,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel, a Nebraska Republican. ``On
basic Republican issues, I see no difference between the two.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are fault lines, and they are showing in not-so-subtle
ways. Bush is getting help from tobacco and anti-abortion groups,
which are running radio ads against McCain in South Carolina.
McCain drew the ire of the tobacco industry when, in 1998, he tried
to usher a tobacco bill through the Senate that would have raised
taxes by more than $1 a pack. Groups opposed to abortion have
attacked him for reversing his opposition to fetal tissue research
in 1992 after a friend died of Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that neither man cleaves to the far right wing of
the Republican party, said Bruce Buchanan, a political scientist at
the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think either one of them is a classic idealogue like
Jesse Helms is, like Gary Bauer is, like Alan Keyes is,'' he said.
``They both ... take standard party positions ... but I don't
believe that this stuff burns near their heart in the same fervent
way it does standard ideologues. The big differences between them
have to do with iconoclasm versus conventionality.''
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be reached at jenah(at)coxnews.com. Rebecca Carr
can be reached at rebeccac(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
