<HEADER>
A0100 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-IRAN-ELECT-2TAKES-(TR     02-17 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ELECT-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMERS AND OLD GUARD VIE IN IRAN'S PARLIAMENTARY ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ At the age of 19, Abdi Manoumshah found himself
at the epicenter of revolution. An Iranian army officer, he was on
guard duty outside the U.S. Embassy in the fall of 1979 when
student firebrands seized what they called the ``nest of spies''
and took U.S. diplomats hostage. Loyal to the new Islamic Republic,
he stepped aside.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, he has fought in the war with Iraq,
abandoned a law practice because it could not provide for his
family, and tried to sustain the hopes kindled in those heady days
when the powerful were humbled by the powerless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the revolution would change things, but in a
different direction, not where we have ended up,'' said Manoumshah,
a pensive man of 40 who runs a tiny three-table restaurant shop
near Tehran's central bazaar. ``We wanted freedom to think and act
as we liked. That is very much what people are asking for now.''
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary elections on Friday have emerged as a
referendum to define just whose ideals were at the heart of the
Iranian revolution 21 years ago. The vote has become, as well, a
popularity poll for President Mohammad Khatami, the reformist
theologian who was swept into office in 1997 but has yet to realize
much of his liberal social agenda or achieve his stated goal of
improved relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For Iranians like Manoumshah, who is a Khatami supporter, the
election for the parliament, or Majlis, is a way to release the
religious monopoly's brakes on everything from a free-market
economy to a free press. ``If the president has the Majlis behind
him, nothing can stop him,'' he said. ``And if he can achieve just
50 percent of what he has talked about, he will be a great
success.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Old Guard that has resisted all reconciliation with the
West and Western culture remains a powerful force. It lost the
presidential election two and a half years ago, but has not lost
power _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami's promises to open Iranian society have already alarmed
those right-wing forces, which include elements in the security
forces blamed for killing several reformers last year, the
state-sponsored vigilante groups that attacked student
demonstrators last summer and the conservative clerics who have
closed down a succession of independent newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election of President Khatami opened a vista, and from
that time on, people started to criticize the system more
objectively,'' said Hermezans Vavand, a professor of international
relations at Tehran University. ``The conservative movement then
hardened its positions and reacted with violence toward anyone who
was critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a great number of them are time-servers and
opportunistic,'' he added. ``They might end up getting on the
bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever ideological faction wins control of parliament, it
will face the same mundane problems that have dogged Iran for
years. Its economy has not grown fast enough to keep up with its
ballooning population growth, with unemployment and poverty on the
rise. Nearly 38 percent of its population is 15 or younger, a group
that will also strain the job market. Much of Iran's production,
meanwhile, is in the hands of secretive religious foundations that
pay minimal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami has proposed widespread privatization of industries that
were nationalized after the revolution, and he has had some success
in pushing his economic plans through parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the Majlis has been fairly cooperative with him,''
said Ardavazd Baghoomian, who has served in parliament for 16 years
in one of two guaranteed seats allotted to the country's 200,000
ethnic Armenians. ``But if Khatami had a majority, he might have
been able to push through more fundamental changes.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the political factions vying for seats in parliament
have talked about an economic plan, either for or against
Khatami's. But the reformers have said they want to open the way
for a frank, even impertinent public debate on all matters of
public policy.
</P>
<P>
   They have talked of reforming the court system, encouraging the
formation of a range of political parties, and openly permitting
satellite dishes and other elements of foreign culture that are
officially prohibited but widely embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the powers of parliament are limited, although in many
ways untested. It approves and can also impeach ministers. It
approves the budget and economic policy. But no law is enacted
unless it is also affirmed by the 12-member Council of Guardians,
experts in Islamic law who have acted as a reactionary damper on
change.
</P>
<P>
   But a victory for the reformers in parliament could upset even
this venerable institution of the religious right wing. While half
of the council's members are appointed by the supreme leader, the
other six are selected by parliament itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reforms will be done slowly, step by step,'' said Mohammad
Reza Khatami, the brother of the president and one of the reform
candidates for the parliament in Tehran. ``It's hard to say now in
what order they would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The one-week election campaign has skirted some of the more
volatile issues that many Iranians avidly discuss in private,
particularly the constitution designed by the revolutionary leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini that assigns ultimate authority over
religious matters, foreign policy, security and much of the
judiciary to a nonelected supreme leader. The current leader is
Ayatollah Ali Khameini, who has condemned liberals, although not
the president, as the agents of evil foreign powers.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns of all factions have dealt with generalities:
helping young people, improving the economy, upholding Islam. Many
candidates have also tried to capitalize on Khatami's image as an
intellectual and a good-natured man, unlike the stern ayatollahs of
the revolution whose pictures adorn buildings all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian news agency IRNA reported this week that 12
candidates in the northern Iranian city of Meshed were arrested on
charges of election fraud because their campaign materials
understated their true ages.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, a former president and parliament
speaker, has also tried to present a kinder face. He sent flyers to
more than 2 million households in Tehran that show him bareheaded,
without his black clerical turban, lounging in a garden with a
little boy. ``I will stay with you in winter and deliver you to the
spring,'' the leaflet said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even the conservatives have flung around the word ``freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problems with the idea of freedom,'' said Mohammad
Reza Bahonar, a member of the current Parliament and a key
strategist for the conservative faction. ``Our main slogans during
the revolution were independence, freedom and an Islamic republic.
After all, God created people as free beings.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rafsanjani has become a pivotal figure in the campaign because
he has been endorsed by several conservative factions even as the
reformers vilify him as a man with no ideals. To many ordinary
Iranians, however, he represents stability and a familiar face for
a transitional time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of this right-left fight, which is really
among the clergy and not relevant to the general public,'' said
Sohrab Alizadeh, who is running a lonely and underfinanced race as
an independent environmentalist in Tehran. ``But Rafsanjani has
been in power since the revolution, so in a way people feel like he
has to be kept in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 38 million Iranians are eligible to vote, and
strategists in several parties have said a high turnout will favor
the reform candidates, as it did Khatami in his presidential race.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The government first announced that the ballots from 36,000
polling stations across the country would be counted by computer,
but the clerical body that oversees the elections said late this
week that they would be counted by hand. Strategists for several
parties said the final count may not be known for at least a week.
</P>
<P>
   Some 6,000 people are running for the 290 seats, although the
exact number was not known Thursday because hundreds of candidates
dropped out during the campaign week. And the day before the
campaign began, a council of clerics dropped 777 candidates from
the ballot, citing their views on the relationship between religion
and government. Still, with so many candidates _ up to 100 for each
seat in some districts _ pinpointing their positions based on their
backgrounds has been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Those running as pro-Khatami candidates or making speeches in
their support include former government officials forced out of
office for espousing a free press; a film director who hopes that
economic reform will revitalize the struggling Iranian cinema; a
cleric whose job is to safeguard Khomeini's writings; a
post-revolution intelligence chief; a writer who led the student
hostage-takers in 1979; and a number of high-ranking religious
figures.
</P>
<P>
   No one exemplifies this jumble of pedigrees better than Zahra
Eshraghi, a 37-year-old employee of the Ministry of Interior. She
is married to the president's brother and has campaigned with him.
She is also the granddaughter of Khomeini, known as the Imam and
the virulently anti-Western hero of the revolution and founder of
the Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is that if the reformers win, there will be
a good balance between the Majlis and the government,'' Eshraghi
said. ``We have had a Majlis that was very monotone, with all the
same kind of people. We should have a Majlis that is in keeping
with the times.''
</P>
<P>
   She has campaigned for her husband and the reform list of
candidates and said her grandfather would approve of her husband's
bid, just as he had encouraged her to marry into the Khatami
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government of President Khatami,'' she said, ``is the same
as the governments of the period of the Imam. The Imam himself had
a high degree of trust for Khatami.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
