<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOBACCO-NORRIS-COLUMN     02-17 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORRIS COLUMN: WHAT ARE THOSE BOND BUYERS SMOKING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market is worried that Philip Morris _ under attack
from all sides _ is going to die. The bond market is quite
unconcerned. Somebody is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   So the question for today is: Will Big Tobacco go bankrupt? Will
those who despise it _ a crowd that includes a growing number of
lawyers and politicians, not to mention some former customers who
are dying of cancer _ manage to drive the companies into the
ground?
</P>
<P>
   The stock market clearly is worried. You have to go back decades
to find big stocks that are as cheap as Philip Morris and R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco are now. Both trade for around five times profits.
The dividend yield on Reynolds stock is over 15 percent, while that
on Morris is about 10 percent. If Philip Morris' very profitable
tobacco business somehow vanished overnight, leaving it with only
the profits from its other operations, including Miller beer and
Kraft foods, the stock would no doubt rally significantly.
</P>
<P>
   The big risk is not the latest crop of suits, from tobacco
farmers and cigarette wholesalers claiming price fixing, but from a
pending Florida class action filed by smokers. There is talk of a
punitive damage award of $100 billion or more within a couple of
months.
</P>
<P>
   And yet over on the bond market, a Philip Morris bond that
matures in 2027 is trading at a yield of 8.5 percent. That's a
couple of percentage points more than the yield on similar Treasury
bonds, but it's far below the rate you'd expect if default was
deemed likely.
</P>
<P>
   That split opinion reflects the differing realities of the
cigarette business. Cash flows remain strong, in part because
addicted customers are loyal customers. But the class action
lawyers are circling, and the stocks keep falling.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to measure just how much investors fear bankruptcy
is the way the two Nabisco stocks trade. One, Nabisco Holdings, is
a pure play on Nabisco, maker of Oreos and Ritz Crackers. The
other, Nabisco Group Holdings, is the same thing. But it may have
some residual liability if R.J. Reynolds is driven into bankruptcy,
because it is a former parent of Reynolds. Nabisco Group now sells
at a 50 percent discount _ up from 21 percent last summer _
reflecting nothing but the fear of a Reynolds bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   In the cloud of litigation, it is easy to forget that cigarettes
are here to stay. Largely because of payments under the industry's
settlement with the states, cigarette prices rose 32 percent last
year, but the number of cigarettes sold fell just 8 percent.
Prohibition wouldn't work, and while education about the risks has
cut smoking _ per capita consumption is half what it was 40 years
ago _ those who smoke now do so despite both scorn from others and
a knowledge of the risks. If Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds were
driven into bankruptcy, their shareholders and bondholders might be
wiped out, but the companies would be reorganized and keep selling
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   If you accept that, there is no particular public interest to be
served by bankrupting the companies. To the contrary, it is in the
interests of the states to keep the companies in business and able
to make settlement payments.
</P>
<P>
   Those buying tobacco stocks now are placing a reasonable bet
that the companies will survive, and that the legal cloud will
eventually dissipate. It is a risky _ but probably very profitable
_ investment. Those buying Philip Morris bonds, on the other hand,
are taking virtually the same risk, but with a far smaller reward
if they are right.
</P>
<P>
   It sort of makes you wonder what the bond buyers are smoking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1814EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
