<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0105 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BACKSTREETBOYS18-COX     02-17 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKSTREETBOYS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Backstreet Boys come back for more
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine if the St. Louis Rams were so pumped about their Super
Bowl victory that they decided to put their uniforms back on,
return to the Georgia Dome and sell tickets. That's essentially
what's happening Saturday as the nation's hottest concert act, the
stylishly syncopated Backstreet Boys, bring their record-breaking
tour back to Atlanta for yet another sold-out night of pyrotechnics
and pop hits.
</P>
<P>
   Although billed as the ``Into the Millennium Tour,'' the show is
basically the same one the Boys staged at Philips Arena in
November, except with twice as many fans to squeal through the
20-song set. The original allotment of tickets sold out almost
immediately, but additional seats have been put on sale.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who missed the Boys on their last visit, here's
a preview of what's likely to happen when 65,000-plus fans
experience them in the Dome:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The crowd: The seats will be filled mostly by elementary
school children and teenage girls holding teddy bears and green
glow sticks. (A lot of their 30-ish parents will be along, too _
and they secretly know the words to all the hits.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The setup: The concert is ``in the round,'' which means the
stage will be set up in the center of the Dome, allowing the Boys
to point and wink at all four corners. Binoculars are recommended.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Intermission: Comes after a short opening act, about 20
minutes _ plenty of time to purchase items such as a BSB ``Comin'
Atcha'' T-shirt ($19.99), fingernail tattoos ($3.99) or a
millennium pencil ($5.99).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start looking for the BSB when: The lights dim and the theme
from ``Star Wars'' booms through the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  First sighting: After a parade of dancers arrives carrying
lighted poles, look up. The Boys materialize high above the crowd,
suspended near the ceiling. On boogie boards. Really.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Boys: A.J. McLean (22), Nick Carter (20), Brian Littrell
(24), Kevin Richardson (27) and Howie Dorough (26).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Also onstage: Ten dancers and a six-piece band.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most screams: The group's blond cherub, Carter, gets them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most sentimental moment: During a tune called ``The Perfect
Fan,'' the Boys haul five mothers and daughters onstage, dance with
the girls and present a rose to each of the moms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Words most frequently used in BSB lyrics: ``Body,''
``everybody,'' ``backstreet,'' ``back,'' ``backstreet's back'' and
``sex-yoo-aahll.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The reviews say: The show is Disney meets Motown, with The New
York Times, Newsweek and others giving the Boys high marks for
their professionalism and ability to entertain. In short, they're
winning almost everybody over. Even cynical critics.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0108 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SKUBE20-COX     02-17 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Casting an eye on the purposes of `Principle'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 20.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gadflies get around, and no one circulates like Stanley Fish. An
index to any of his books _ but especially ``The Trouble With
Principle'' _ tells you how widely the former chairman of Duke
University's once-notorious English department ranges when he's on
a roll. From a literary critic you expect Jacques Derrida and
Michel Foucault to make their obligatory appearances. But Fish
casts his net wide, and no one acquainted with him is surprised to
find Sam Peckinpah turn up in a disquisition whose serious purposes
extend well beyond ``The Wild Bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports, film, TV and radio, politics and journalism _ Fish is
fluent wherever he goes. Had he waited a few months before
publishing ``The Trouble With Principle,'' you could be dead
certain that the place in the index between the names Steven
Rockefeller and Ellen Rooney would be occupied by one John Rocker.
The title of his most recent book was ``There Is No Such Thing as
Free Speech, and It's a Good Thing Too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fish, who first made a name for himself as a Milton scholar,
escaped the ghetto of academic literary criticism several years
ago, turning up in respected law reviews, on the op-ed page of The
New York Times and, now, in the rarefied realm of political theory.
He is where he had been headed all along.
</P>
<P>
   Politics was always at the heart of Fish's criticism _ not party
politics but the subtler politics that underpins the principles we
profess to uphold. His rhetorical style is surgically precise, and
in ``The Trouble With Principle'' it is his best friends who are
put under the knife _ liberals comfortable with beliefs whose
rightness they take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Agile in the art of arguing
</P>
<P>
   Full disclosure: Fish and I once sparred in print a few years
ago _ enjoyably, I thought _ and he subsequently went on to stiffer
competition, debating Dinesh D'Souza on affirmative action and
campus speech codes before college audiences. That he would be
invited to D'Souza's wedding says something about his civility but
also his intellectual penchant for getting about.
</P>
<P>
   In the art of argument, he is formidably skilled if, sometimes,
given to the sophist's sleight of hand. He will unravel your every
position, reducing it to words of reversible meanings, while
resisting a firm stand of his own _ except that free speech is a
hollow concept. As a legal matter, he is of course right, the point
having been made long ago by Supreme Court Justice Hugo Black.
</P>
<P>
   Free speech advocates pay homage to Milton's ``Areopagitica,''
but tolerance had its limits for Milton, too. ``Everyone,'' he
wrote, ``should be allowed to speak and publish, except of course
Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   As statehouse politicians are fond of saying, ``It depends on
whose ox is being gored,'' and Fish understands why all is
relative. He offers, as an example, the shocked reaction of
Westerners to the death sentence conferred on Salman Rushdie for
``The Satanic Verses'':
</P>
<P>
   ``When the novelist Paul Theroux encounters a Pakistani with an
advanced degree in science who nevertheless declares `Rushdie must
die,' Theroux responds in true boutique multiculturalist fashion by
setting him `straight' and informing him (as if he were a child)
that his are `ignorant and barbarous sentiments.' (I bet that
really convinced him.)''
</P>
<P>
   The argument Fish proceeds to make is not that Rushdie deserves
to lose his head, but that multiculturalism _ like free speech, or
abortion rights, or democratic elections _ is a two-way street: We
respect other cultures so long as they do not offend our own. And
the flip side: Freedom of speech is fine when it serves our
purposes, but it cannot be absolute. It is defensible, he might
have said, provided it does not offend. But offend whom?
</P>
<P>
   A critique of liberalism
</P>
<P>
   ``The Trouble With Principle'' is a shrewd, unsparing critique
of liberalism by a man most people assume to be one of them. Where,
Fish asks, ``do I stand on the substantive matters ... abortion,
the death penalty, welfare reform, affirmative action, the line
between church and state, environmental regulation, and so on?
Stephen Macedo (a political scientist) once ventured a guess ...
when he said that Fish is in favor of affirmative action, abortion
rights, and equal treatment of gays and lesbians and he generally
opposes university speech codes. Well, as the great singer Meatloaf
might put it, two out of four ain't so good. I am in favor of
affirmative action and gay and lesbian rights; but I do not support
abortion rights (although what I would support in this vexed area
is not clear to me), and I disfavor speech codes only in those
contexts where the good they do (by my lights) will be outweighed
by the trouble and litigation they produce. ...''
</P>
<P>
   He stands, he means to say, not on principles for their own sake
but for the larger purposes they serve. The problem, in politics,
is that there is no guarantee of agreement on those purposes. To
fall back on the principles that underpin them is to take up
residence in magnificent sand castles.
</P>
<P>
   THE READING ROOM, the AJC's guide for book clubs that appears
the fourth Sunday of every month in Arts &AMP; Books, is available
online, along with a growing list of reading groups throughout
metro Atlanta that are looking for members. Go to ajc.com, click on
X-site, then click on reading club ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Questions or suggestions? E-mail: readingroom(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Trouble With Principle. By Stanley Fish. Harvard
University Press. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
