<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0109 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-UPDIKE20-COX     02-17 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-UPDIKE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Hamlet' prequel a daring exercise from playful master
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 20.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, you can't say that John Updike is getting crotchety on us.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, he's as unpredictable and venturesome at
age 67 _ in ``Gertrude and Claudius,'' his slim new novel _ as he
was at 27, when his ``Rabbit, Run'' heralded a great literary
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gertrude and Claudius'' is very clever and elegantly crafted,
but sometimes seems more like a daring academic exercise than a
full-bodied, satisfying read. It's a prequel to ``Hamlet'' in
narrative prose. Peppered with the well-researched sights and
sounds of medieval Denmark _ right down to the feast menu of
brine-injected ham and goose-in-honey _ it tells a fanciful back
story of the forbidden romance between the melancholy prince's
mother and uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare cast them as fleshy sensualists who married hastily
after Claudius murdered Hamlet's father with an earful of poison.
Updike's take, though, is in many ways sympathetic. Perhaps because
of his own guilt (achingly obvious in the Maples stories, for a
start) over leaving his family for the woman who became his second
wife, Updike sees the lusty Danes as much sinned against as
sinning. Thwarted at every turn by a domineering
king-husband-brother, King Hamlet, they stoically fulfilled their
duties and denied their desires as long as they could, and then
fell into a middle-aged affair all the more torrid for its delay.
</P>
<P>
   The peaceful close of the tale is shot through with irony: our
knowledge that Shakespeare's drama _ and its bloody comeuppance for
the lovers _ waits just around the dark bend of the forest trail.
</P>
<P>
   There are interesting, subtle undercurrents here. In the
tradition of Tom Stoppard's play ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are
Dead,'' Updike salutes Shakespeare with one hand _ treating his
fictive world as a real, solid launch pad for his own story. With
the other hand he rips open that classic with new perspectives on
its events, using the recurring image of the hooded falcon to
remind us that each storyteller can only give us his one special
frame.
</P>
<P>
   The book is divided into three sections, each assigning
characters with different names, some from the original Hamlet
story of Norse myth (where Gertrude was called Gerutha, for
example), some from Renaissance versions in German and French. At
first the device seems like a gimmick: showoffy bookishness. But as
the tale goes on, hearing the ever-changing names takes on a
mysterious, dreamlike air, as if we're watching the morphing of
mythic heroes with a thousand faces, in Joseph Campbell's phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, adultery is Updike's rut. He's written
brilliantly on it many, many times, and it feels too narrow a
subject for the breadth of his mind. Needled by critics for this
repetitiveness, Updike responded powerfully with ``In the Beauty of
the Lilies,'' his multigenerational epic of 1996, and, to a lesser
extent, with 1997's ``Toward the End of Time,'' which at least set
its suburban hanky-panky in the eerie aftermath of a nuclear war.
But let's face it, some breathless passages of ``Gertrude'' (``She
would have lain down in warm mud for him, even the mud of the
pigsty, to enter the exaltation she found in his brute love'')
sound like a parody of pulp romance.
</P>
<P>
   Such lapses are outnumbered by flights of ravishing beauty. Here
is Updike on the northern lights: ``Their evasive faint peacock
colors, violet and turquoise, a far-off music of phosphorescence.
They undulated along their vertical folds with a kind of beckoning
motion, fading and returning.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the last third of a passage that no one _ no one
_ could have written in precisely that way except John Updike.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't be put off too much by the still-youthful
experiments of this rascally old master. He still writes like an
angel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude and Claudius. By John Updike. Knopf. $23. 212 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Even in this eccentric prequel to ``Hamlet,''
Updike's dazzling style is intact.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST LOOK
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt from ``Gertrude and Claudius'':
</P>
<P>
   She broke the silence his own had pointedly suggested. ``My
lord?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, my queen? It is late. A king needs to greet the sun as an
equal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you feel guilty?''
</P>
<P>
   She felt his body stiffen, his breathing skip a breath. ``Guilty
concerning what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, what else? _ guilty concerning our, our coming together
while ... Hamlet was my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudius snorted and hugged tighter his accumulating nugget of
fatigue, making their bed of goose down emphatically heave. ``The
old Norse rule is, what you cannot hold is not yours. I took from
him a property he didn't know he owned _ territory he had never
plowed. You were a virgin to unbridled love.''
</P>
<P>
   And, though she felt this was not entirely true, it was true
enough to rest on, and they fell asleep in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert, a staff writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, profiled John Updike in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
