<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0110 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-FILMTRILOGY-SOUTHERNL     02-17 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMTRILOGY-SOUTHERNLIT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From blues poets to book authors, three films trace region's
literature
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 20.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If H.L. Mencken were alive to see Ross Spears' documentary film
trilogy on Southern literature, the acerbic journalist surely would
change his mind about the region he described in 1917 as ``the
Sahara of the Bozart.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambasting the South as a ``gargantuan paradise of the
fourth-rate,'' Mencken observed: ``Once you have counted James
Branch Cabell you will not find a single Southern prose writer who
can actually write.''
</P>
<P>
   Those comments were mostly true in 1917, Spears says, but
shortly after World War I the South underwent an amazing literary
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Spears' three 80-minute films trace this resurgence and bring to
life William Faulkner's famous line, ``The past is never dead, it
isn't even past,'' through an effective use of narration, author
interviews, archival photographs, dramatic re-creations, and the
writers' own words. Former U.S. poet laureate Rita Dove's narration
connects the accounts of individual writers.
</P>
<P>
   The first film in the ``Tell About the South'' series covers
1915 to 1940 and includes segments on Jean Toomer, the Vanderbilt
poets, the Mississippi Delta blues poets/singers, Zora Neale
</P>
<P>
   Hurston, Thomas Wolfe, Margaret Mitchell, Erskine Caldwell and
others. Blues composers such as Robert Johnson were included
because, as novelist Shelby Foote says in the film, the blues is
``real poetry. It has terrific emotion to it.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparing the blues poets to the Fugitive poets of
Vanderbilt, Spears emphasizes his point that Southern literature
was a partnership of blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Fugitive poets epitomized the cutting edge of high art,
the blues poets raised African-American folklife to the level of
genius,'' Dove notes in the film. ``Two rich cultures on parallel
tracks, often hidden from one another, but never completely out of
view.''
</P>
<P>
   The second film, ``Prophets and Poets,'' tells the stories of
Richard Wright, Eudora Welty, Robert Penn Warren, Flannery
O'Connor, Ralph Ellison and other writers in the 1941-1962 period.
And the third film, ``Let Freedom Ring,'' covers 1963 to the
present and includes interviews with Alice Walker, William Styron,
Ernest Gaines, Reynolds Price, Pat Conroy, Lee Smith and others.
</P>
<P>
   Recently completed, ``Let Freedom Ring'' will have its world
premiere Saturday at a screening of the trilogy at the Rialto
Center for the Performing Arts. Plans are to air all three parts of
the series on PBS stations late this year or early in 2001, Spears
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite an undertaking,'' says Spears, whose 1980
documentary on author James Agee is the only film biography of an
American writer nominated for an Academy Award.
</P>
<P>
   Spears and company began working on the project, funded
primarily by the National Endowment for the Humanities, in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things we did,'' Spears says, ``was assemble
a fine group of consultants, including Louis Rubin, Robert Coles
and Henry Louis Gates.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was a matter of convincing some of the more
reclusive writers to agree to on-camera interviews. Cormac McCarthy
turned them down, as did John Grisham. Alice Walker consented only
after two years of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people we interviewed have died,'' Spears says,
``including Cleanth Brooks, Margaret Walker, Willie Morris and
Andrew Lytle. We were fortunate to be able to talk with them when
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge was creating a visually interesting film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to use a lot of their own words, of course, and I
tried to find the right voice to speak those words by listening to
people audition. These were relatively unknown readers, but their
voices combined with the words of the writer to evoke the
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears also used dramatizations from some of the works to create
matching images. ``We did that with Zora Neale Hurston and Jean
Toomer. And with Flannery O'Connor, we used stills that looked like
her characters.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Spears' goals was to show how Southern literature was
really an African-American and European-American creation. ``I
tried to stress that in each of the three parts by pairing a black
writer and a white writer. Each presented a portrait of the
20th-century South from somewhat different angles.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to comparing the Fugitive poets and the blues poets
in Part 1, Spears pairs Thomas Wolfe and Zora Neale Hurston because
they had much in common. Both were larger-than-life characters,
they were born around the same time, both moved to New York, and
both went back to their roots in order to create their work.
</P>
<P>
   If there was ever a genius, Alice Walker says in the film,
Hurston was it. ``She came out of Florida with one dress and one
pair of shoes, and created this whole world, which is not there
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Prophets and Poets,'' Spears compares Robert Penn Warren
and Ralph Ellison ``because both were Southerners who moved to the
North and became friends. Both were highly intellectual, well-read,
extremely ambitious men of letters. Each is known for one big, big
novel.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Let Freedom Ring,'' William Styron is juxtaposed with
Ernest Gaines to highlight the differences and similarities in
their lives and the way their careers evolved. Styron's father was
a slave owner, and Gaines' father was a slave.
</P>
<P>
   The first two films have garnered a number of positive reviews.
Lewis Simpson, emeritus editor of the prestigious Southern Review,
praised ``Tell About the South'' as ``a great story about a
remarkable group of storytellers told by another remarkable
storyteller.''
</P>
<P>
   And, at Georgia State University, Faulkner scholar Thomas L.
McHaney lauded the film as a ``unique history of the great
literature of the South not only because it makes so many voices
visible, but it lets us see and hear the writers and then the
writers who talk about the writers. It's unique because it presents
together, better than any book I know, more of the great Southern
voices, black and white, that made and remade the literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was reluctant to tackle such a complex project at
first, Spears acknowledges that it was an ideal project for him. A
native of Tennessee, Spears has maintained an interest in Southern
literature ever since his days as a student of Reynolds Price's at
Duke University. After graduating from film schools in North
Carolina and California, Spears produced a documentary in 1979 on
the life and work of his favorite writer, James Agee. Other films
followed on the Civil War, the Tennessee Valley Authority, and one
family living in poverty in America.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hollywood directors, documentary filmmakers don't make a
lot of money, Spears says. ``I operate on grants and I pay myself a
salary, but mostly it's a labor of love.''
</P>
<P>
   This project should have a larger audience than his other films,
Spears says, because he is marketing the films, along with study
guides, to colleges. ``We've never done this before, but it looks
like they're really going to be useful.''
</P>
<P>
   His main purpose, he adds, is spreading the word about the South
and its writers. And, despite the increased homogenization of the
region, Spears and the scholars he interviewed predict a bright
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus is that the South is still a very distinctive
region and there are many great Southern writers out there. I'm not
sure there's anybody on the level of Faulkner, but maybe there is.
Time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FILMMAKER: ROSS SPEARS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AGE: 52.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BIRTHPLACE: Johnson City, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FAMILY: Divorced, one son.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  EDUCATION: Duke University (pre-med, literature), University
of North Carolina film school, California Institute of the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FILMS: ``James Agee: A Life,'' a documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Electric Valley,'' a feature on the Tennessee Valley
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Shadows,'' an exploration of the effects of the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Render a Life,'' a dramatization of Agee and Walker Evans'
book ``Let Us Now Praise Famous Men,'' and a study of one family
living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell About the South: Voices in Black and White,'' a
three-film series on Southern literature.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AWARDS: Blue ribbons from the American Film Festival for
``James Agee'' and ``To Render a Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
