<HEADER>
A0111 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-JSO-ANNIVERSARY20-COX     02-17 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JSO-ANNIVERSARY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jacksonville Symphony sets big anniversary fest
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb.20
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the Jacksonville Symphony Orchestra, a golden anniversary
means a golden opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   A regional orchestra that serves North Florida and the ``First
Coast'' _ so called because it's where Juan Ponce de Leon landed in
1513 _ the JSO is serving up a 50th-anniversary festival that
outshines what a lot of major musical ensembles do for significant
dates.
</P>
<P>
   Between Tuesday and March 5, travelers to the city can partake
of a banquet of concerts by the JSO and visiting ensembles,
including the Minnesota Orchestra (Thursday-Friday) in a first-ever
visit to the area by a major symphony. Those same days, on street
corners and in workplaces and schools throughout the city, JSO
musicians in small ensembles will offer a series of informal
chamber concerts dubbed ``Art Attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The JSO has an acclaimed American composer, 1998 Pulitzer Prize
winner Aaron Jay Kernis, in residence during the festival, and his
work will be featured in two programs. Kernis is also the judge of
a Florida composers' competition called ``Fresh Ink,'' and those
who wonder how he'll come to terms with untried music can watch the
process at open rehearsals of the orchestra Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The capstone of the first week will be a reunion concert Sunday
of JSO music directors and musicians. The new music director,
Brazilian conductor Fabio Mechetti, who took over the podium in
time for the golden-anniversary year, will play host to
predecessors Roger Nierenberg and Willis Page, and some 30 former
players are expected to return.
</P>
<P>
   The second week offers the lively show ``Swingtime!'' (March 3).
The JSO's showcase concert is March 4, a performance of Beethoven's
Ninth Symphony. And the festival ends with show biz on March 5: a
concert of ``50 Great Years of Music and Movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Above and beyond the music, another reason to check out the
festival is the chance to experience music in the 2-year-old,
1,800-seat, $33 million Robert E. Jacoby Symphony Hall in the
Times-Union Center for the Performing Arts. One of the few U.S.
performance spaces dedicated to orchestra music, Jacoby Hall was
acoustically designed by R. Lawrence Kirkegaard of Chicago. He's
the acoustical consultant who advised the ASO on its plan last
summer to build a new concert hall, which ultimately failed because
of fund-raising problems.
</P>
<P>
   Many at the reunion concert may regard it as something of a
miracle, for in its 20th year the JSO was all but dead. The New
York Times wrote its obituary in 1970, using it as a case study in
regional orchestra economics. After a year without music, the city
got its act together and resurrected the orchestra, which in 1972
went to New York and Washington, playing concerts that proved that
reports of its death had been greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Today it has an annual operating budget of $6.6 million, 52
full-time musicians, its own hall and a vigorous season of about
100 concerts a year, reaching audiences of 175,000 (including
schoolchildren) annually.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Atlanta, where sports is king and any of what
economists call ``multiplier factors'' (dollars returned to the
community through taxes, tourism and recreation associated with
sports activities) are incidental, Jacksonville's sports boom
helped fund its arts boom.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the city passed a $230 million bond issue _
to be repaid out of sales tax revenues _ to bring the Gator Bowl up
to pro football standards, and in 1995 it acquired the Jacksonville
Jaguars. But $22 million of the bond issue went to build Jacoby
Hall and refurbish the existing theaters in the Times-Union Center.
And bond issue money is also being fed into libraries, hospitals
and neighborhood projects.
</P>
<P>
   So all is well _ or getting better _ in the city surrounded by
paper mills. And, for a little orchestra with a near-death
experience in its not too distant past, the JSO is putting on a
great big show to celebrate half a century _ minus the year 1971 _
of music.
</P>
<P>
   SCHEDULE OF EVENTS
</P>
<P>
   All events in Jacoby Hall unless otherwise noted.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fresh Ink opens rehearsals. 10 a.m. Tuesday and 7:30 p.m.
Wednesday. JSO, Darryl One, conductor. New works to be heard:
``Diffusions'' (Miami native Jason Freeman); Symphony No. 1 (A.
Paul Johnson); ``Aquillae'' (Scott McAllister, Florida Southern
College, Lakeland); ``Short Symphony in Four Movements'' (Paul
Richards, University of Florida); ``In the Midst of the Mountain''
(Mark Schubert, who has been an administrator with the Palm Beach
Orchestras and South Florida Symphony); ``Fanfares Overture'' (Gary
Smart, University of North Florida, South Jacksonville); ``The
Signs of the Zodiac,'' Parts 1 and 2 (Charles Threatte, University
of Central Florida, Orlando). Conductor One (pronounced OH-nay) is
former assistant conductor of the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, and
Threatte, an Atlanta native, was composer-in-residence with the
Atlanta public schools in a project called YEOW (Youth Experimental
Opera Workshop). Free.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Art Attacks.'' Thursday-Friday. Surprise appearances by JSO
ensembles at schools, workplaces and public spaces around the city.
Free.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Minnesota Orchestra. 8 p.m. Thursday-Friday. Eiji Oue,
conductor; Pinchas Zukerman, violin. ``Musica Celestis'' (Aaron Jay
Kernis); Violin Concerto No. 5 (Mozart); Symphony No. 5
(Shostakovich). $15-$60.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fresh Ink concert and
</P>
<P>
   MUSEART Project. 8 p.m. Saturday. JSO, One conducting. ``Too Hot
Toccata'' (Kernis), ``Celebration'' (Ellen Taaffe Zwilich), works
by Florida composers. MUSEART Project comprises commissioned
chamber works based on pieces in the Jacksonville Museum of Modern
Art collection that are on display in the Times-Union Center.
``Night Bloom'' for clarinet and string trio (Stella Sung), based
on ``Night Bloom'' by Memphis Wood; Tuba Trio for tuba and
percussion (James Stephenson III), based on ``Dusk and Dawn'' by
Alexander Calder; ``Seeing Frankenthaler'' for harp, flute and
bassoon (Dennis Kam), based on ``Gateway'' by Helen Frankenthaler.
This half of the concert will take place in the Terry Theater, the
second half in Jacoby Hall. $15.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reunion Concert. 3 p.m. Sunday. With JSO Youth Orchestra.
Three overtures and the Triple Concerto (Beethoven) with Aaron
Krosnick, Joel Krosnick and Mary Lou Wesley Krosnick, violin, cello
and piano. Joel Krosnick is cellist of the Juilliard Quartet. $10.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Swingtime!'' 8 p.m. March 3. Warren Vache and the New York
City All-Star Big Band; Jivin' Lindy Hoppers from Britain. Jim and
Jan Moran Theater. $20-$60.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ninth Symphony (Beethoven). 7 p.m. March 4. JSO, Mechetti
conducting, with Jacksonville Symphony Chorus and Gainesville Civic
Chorus, soloists. $20-$60. Also 7 p.m. March 3, Center for the
Performing Arts, Gainesville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``50 Great Years of Music and Movies.'' 8 p.m. March 5. JSO,
with film clips and narration by John Goberman, host of PBS' ``Live
From Lincoln Center.'' Moran Theater. $20-$60.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Fly from Atlanta to Jacksonville for $53 each
way on Delta or AirTran with a 14-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ticket information: 904-354-5547 or www.jaxsymphony.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging and tourism information: Jacksonville and the Beaches
Convention and Visitors Bureau, 904-798-9100 or www.jaxcvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
