<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pseudonym, new heroine let Trocheck stretch
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the biggest-selling books of the last decade was about an
antiques dealer and a murder in Savannah. New York agent Stuart
Krichevsky is not saying that ``Savannah Blues'' will be another
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' but the debut novel by
Mary Kay Andrews has all of the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for publication in spring 2001, the novel features
Eloise Foley (Weezie to her friends), an antiques ``picker'' who
finds damaged or unrecognized treasures at junk shops, estate
sales, or even in the trash, and sells them for their true value.
As the novel opens, Foley, who is going through the divorce from
hell, takes an unauthorized ``sneak preview'' at an upcoming estate
sale and gets more than she bargains for when she discovers the
bloody corpse of her ex-husband's fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Susan Isaacs for the `Ya-Ya's' set,'' says Krichevsky,
who sold ``Savannah Blues'' and a second book to HarperCollins for
what he describes as ``a substantial six-figure advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews is a pseudonym for Atlanta mystery writer Kathy Hogan
Trocheck, who began her career as a crime reporter for The Savannah
News-Times, and covered the Jim Williams murder trial for The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. That case became the basis for John
Berendt's best seller.
</P>
<P>
   And it was in Savannah that she bought her first antique, the
beginning of a 20-year habit as an amateur picker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go on book tour, I'm always out junking,'' says
Trocheck, whose new Callahan Garrity mystery, ``Irish Eyes,'' hits
the stores next week.
</P>
<P>
   Trocheck says she'll continue to write her Atlanta-based mystery
series under her own name. ``But writing as Mary Kay Andrews will
allow me to write bigger books with broader themes, always with a
strong Southern protagonist,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Kay Andrews is a combination of my children's names. And,
this way, with a surname starting with `A' I'll be at the top of
the shelf in bookstores, instead of down on the floor with the
`T's. My readers don't like to squat to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Trocheck will sign copies of ``Irish Eyes'' at 7 p.m. Feb. 25 at
Final Touch Gallery &AMP; Books, 133 E. Court Square, Decatur,
404-378-5300.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Readers' choices: Saul Bellow is not known as a populist
writer, but the novelist garnered the most votes for the New Yorker
magazine's lifetime achievement award this week. More than 25,000
readers cast ballots for the new awards, established to honor the
magazine's 75th anniversary. Other winners include Edward Said for
``Out of Place,'' his memoir of his Palestinian childhood, Annie
Proulx won in fiction for ``Close Range'' and first-time novelist
Jhumpa Lahiri won the best debut award for ``Interpreter of
Maladies.'' Winners received $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Politics and prose: Jeffrey Archer (``Kane and Abel''), whose
novels have not met expectations recently, is being pressured by
HarperCollins to publish his controversial memoirs as a means of
recouping some of the multimillion-dollar advance the publisher
paid the British author in 1995. If Archer tells all in his
autobiography, some expect the truth to be more sensational than
his fiction. Archer, a former member of Parliament and a close
friend of former Prime Minister John Major, was expelled this month
from the Conservative party for five years after it was revealed
that he asked a friend to lie in court during a libel trial 12
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail:dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
