</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Savannah, Ga. _ The Savannah Irish Festival Friday through
Sunday at the National Guard Armory is a celebration of the best in
Irish music, culture, crafts, food and drink. The Prodigals, who
fuse rock with a strong traditional Irish music element, will be in
concert on Saturday night. 1-800-436-3746 or www.savannahirish.org
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hilton Head Island, S.C. _ Native Islander Gullah Celebration,
through Feb. 28, is a showcase of the arts, crafts history, music
and food of the Gullah region. 1-800-721-7120.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richmond _ The Maymont Flower and Garden Show Thursday through
Sunday at Richmond Centre invites participants to view garden
landscapes, shop the Garden Marketplace and get tips from the
experts. 804-358-7166.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pigeon Forge, Tenn. _ The Smoky Mountains Storytelling
Festival Friday and Saturday features local and international
artists. 1-800-934-7669, www.pigeon-forge.tn.us
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kissimmee, Fla. _ The 104th edition of the Silver Spurs Rodeo
is Friday through Sunday. At the largest rodeo east of the
Mississippi, 400-plus cowboys compete for more than $100,000 in
saddle bronc riding, steer wrestling and bull riding. 407-847-4052.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Miami _ The 17th Miami Film Festival opens Friday and
continues through Feb. 27. Features newly released international
feature films, movie shorts, animated films and documentaries.
305-662-6960.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando _ Mardi Gras at Universal Studios Florida is Friday
through April 1. Universal's back-lot streets become a moving
street party with entertainment, float-filled parades and food.
407-363-8000 or www.uescape.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anniston, Ala. _ The 20th Annual Black Heritage Festival
Saturday at the Anniston Museum features puppetry, singers,
lectures on folk culture, poetry and prose. 256-237-6766.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ The 18th Annual Southeastern Wildlife
Exposition, the largest wildlife art event in the country, is
Friday through Sunday at sites throughout downtown including the
Ansonborough Soccer Field, Gaillard Auditorium, the College of
Charleston, the Gibbes Museum of Art and Charleston Place. In
addition to wildlife and nature art, the expo features lectures,
live animal and conservations exhibits, the Sporting Village and a
garden area. 843-723-1748 or www.sewe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biloxi, Miss. _ The Mississippi Gulf Coast Mardi Gras
celebrations Saturday through March 7 include family-oriented ``Fat
Tuesday'' parades; past royalty's costumes at the Mardi Gras
Museum; and the Gulf Coast Carnival Association's Coronation Ball.
228-432-8806.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis _ The Kroger St. Jude Tennis Championships, one of
only seven championship-level tournaments in North America,
continues through Sunday. 901-765-4400 or www.krogerstjude.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Augusta, Ga. _ The Morris Museum of Art presents collages,
assemblages and sculptures celebrating the career of William Halsey
(1915-1999) through March 26. A pioneer of abstract painting in the
South, Halsey drew inspiration from Charleston, S.C., where he
lived most of his life. 706-724-7612.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Daytona Beach, Fla. _ The Daytona 500 on Sunday caps the
annual Speedweeks festivities. 1-800-854-1234; www.daytonausa.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
