u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     02-17 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STORY TWICE TOLD ;  NEW LEAD IN `THE DEAD' ;  CURTAINS FOR
BECKETT ;  TAKING TITLE(S) ;  ALONG THE WAY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With one production of ``The Wild Party'' under way
and the second beginning to strut its stuff, speculation was rife
this week that both shows might soon be playing on Broadway
simultaneously. If everything fell into place, this could set up
the tantalizing possibility that two shows with the same name and
source material would vie for best musical at the Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The source is Joseph Moncure March's poem ``The Wild Party''
(1928), which tells the story of jazz-era bohemians on the prowl
during a debauched soiree.
</P>
<P>
   The early word from those who have seen Andrew Lippa's ``Wild
Party'' at the Manhattan Theater Club, where it began performances
in late January, has been predominantly positive. This buzz
apparently has not escaped Theater Club officials and Jeffrey
Seller and Kevin McCollum, the commercial producers who have
shepherded the work since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   While the future of the Lippa version depends on reviews _
opening night is Thursday _ plans are in place for the off-Broadway
show to move to a Broadway stage, most likely the Richard Rodgers.
While the show is scheduled to run until April 2 at the Manhattan
Theater Club, an official there said discussions were under way to
bring it to the Rodgers in early May, just before the Tony
deadline. He added that some members of the technical staff had
already examined the Rodgers with an eye toward adapting the
current set to a larger stage.
</P>
<P>
   This would require the Rodgers' tenant, ``Footloose,'' to close
or move to another theater (with some sort of incentive likely).
Michael David, a producer of that show, said through a spokesman
that neither option had been discussed, and added that the show, in
its 16th month, was profitable week to week. Another consideration
for ``Wild Party'' producers is that any run at the Rodgers would
be limited, for ``Seussical'' is to take up residence there in
October.
</P>
<P>
   The tentativeness of a prospective move seemed to make most of
those involved media shy. The Nederlander Organization, which owns
the Rodgers, offered no comment. Barry Grove, the Theater Club's
executive producer, said only that he was ``investigating the usual
options for life after this production,'' a statement corroborated
by McCollum.
</P>
<P>
   Producers were less coy at the Papp Public Theater, in the East
Village, where ``The Wild Party,'' by Michael John LaChiusa and
George C. Wolfe, entered its sixth week of rehearsals. Plans there
are clear: the show opens on Broadway on April 13 at the Virginia
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday rehearsals were opened to the media, and while the
newly minted Oscar nominee Toni Collette was on display, the
reigning diva was Eartha Kitt. Kitt, looking closer to 30 than 70,
seemed to sum up the mood of both ``Wild Party'' camps as she
purred through the song ``Moving Uptown'':
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear you're moving uptown/ I'll move with you.''
</P>
<P>
   New Lead in `The Dead'
</P>
<P>
   It is a plum role in a surprising hit: Gretta Conroy, the female
lead and wife of Gabriel Conroy in ``James Joyce's `The Dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   And if she weren't hopping to another Broadway show, Blair Brown
would probably be content to play it till the end.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown has another role waiting: Margrethe Bohr, wife of the
physicist Neils Bohr in Michael Frayn's World War II moral drama
``Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   So a search started for a new Gretta, spurring one of the
hottest guessing games on Broadway, with names like Stockard
Channing, Betty Buckley and Patti LuPone tossed about.
</P>
<P>
   But the search is over. (Wasn't that quick?) Beginning on March
13, Faith Prince will step into Blair's role, opposite Christopher
Walken. Prince won't have much time to breathe; she's currently in
Drama Dept.'s production of ``The Torchbearers,'' and will be there
through March 4.
</P>
<P>
   Curtains for Beckett
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that an ambitious plan to renovate Theater Row is
moving forward, Ludovica Villar-Hauser, the producer of the play
``The Countess,'' said Thursday that her show had been asked to
vacate its theater, the Samuel Beckett, by March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Papert, president of the 42nd Street Development Corp.,
which owns Theater Row, on 42nd Street west of Ninth Avenue,
confirmed her report Thursday. The Beckett will be gutted and
several other theaters demolished to make way for a 499-seat
theater, jointly sponsored with the Shubert Organization and housed
in a new residential apartment tower. Also on the drawing boards
are four 99-seat theaters and a 199-seat theater.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``The Countess,'' Villar-Hauser said it was close to
getting a new home. The show's 300th performance was last week.
</P>
<P>
   Taking Title(s)
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Fiennes has a thing for title roles. On film, he's been
Onegin in ``Onegin'' and the English patient in ``The English
Patient.'' Onstage he's taken title roles as a suicidal Ivanov and
a homicidal Hamlet, for which he won a Tony in 1995. Now comes word
that he will take on two more titles, playing the protagonists of
the Almeida Theater Co.'s productions of Shakespeare's ``Richard
II'' and ``Coriolanus,'' coming in the fall to the Brooklyn Academy
of Music.
</P>
<P>
   The plays, directed by Jonathan Kent, will be presented in
repertory from Sept. 6 to Oct. 1. Tickets go on sale on April 1.
Speaking from London, Kent said the plays continued the company's
work begun with ``Hamlet,'' which he directed. ``Both plays are
about power and both about men who, because of a quirk of
character, are unable to exercise that power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ The Roundabout Theater Co. will present the New York premiere
of ``Hotel Suite,'' a play made up of scenes from three Neil Simon
suite plays. John Tillinger directs; performances begin on May 19
at the Gramercy Arts Theater.
</P>
<P>
   _ And downtown, another suite story: casting is complete for
``Noel Coward Suite in Two Keys.'' Judith Ivey has joined Hayley
Mills and Paxton Whitehead. The play opens on April 10 at the
Lucille Lortel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
