<HEADLINE>
WATER RATIONING ORDERED IN GALVESTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ Emergency water rationing was ordered
Thursday after three valves in the city's antiquated water system
broke, reducing water pressure in Galveston Island's most populous
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory rationing _ including a ban on watering lawns, washing
cars and filling swimming pools _ could be in effect through the
weekend or beyond, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of emergency is expected to last several days,''
Mayor Roger Quiroga said.
</P>
<P>
   Voluntary rationing had been instituted on the tourist center
after a pair of decades-old valves on the mainland end of the
city's water supply line broke late Wednesday. Quiroga declared an
emergency after another valve at a pump station near the island's
airport broke Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Galveston, a city of 64,000, is about 45 miles southeast of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Water pressure to the sprawling University of Texas Medical
Branch campus in the city's east end dropped to about 25 percent
below normal for this time of year, but not lower than on some days
at the height of the summer tourist season, said Dennis Bailey,
UTMB maintenance and utilities manager.
</P>
<P>
   Booster pumps in campus buildings struggled to maintain normal
service to upper floors but water continued flowing, Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some pumps that have dropped out because of dips in
pressure and we've had to go start the pumps back up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guests attending a conference at the city's tallest hotel, the
16-story San Luis Resort and Conference Center, experienced no
discomfort from the situation, general manager Paul Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a full house, and we've got plenty of pressure to
our guest rooms,'' he said. ``Really, everything's normal here. I
haven't had one guest complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Like UTMB, the San Luis and all other businesses were ordered to
cease landscape watering.
</P>
<P>
   Rationing violators are to be issued warnings for first offenses
but will face citations and possible fines for repeat offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's two valve failures occurred while crews were
preparing to connect a new water pipeline, already laid across the
bay, into a mainland feeder line that runs to Virginia Point, an
area adjacent to the north end of the I-45 causeway that connects
Galveston Island to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the valve failures had not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Water continued to flow to the island through a 100-year old,
30-inch clay pipe that is known to have leaks. Water pressure on
the west end of the island, from Jamaica Beach to San Luis Pass,
remained stable.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency situation was declared after an old valve at a
pumping station near the airport broke early Thursday, officials
said. That break widened the area that was experiencing
water-pressure problems but was unrelated to work on the new bay
pipeline, city spokesman Wes Swift said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just old valves,'' he said. ``It just reflects our
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   While the malfunction near the airport was not expected, Swift
said, ``The two on Virginia Point are near where we were connecting
the old water line to the new water line.''
</P>
<P>
   The new 36-inch line across the bay is complete, he said, but
the process of attaching it to the current water system is not
finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping that as long as people stick to the emergency
measures, we'll be OK until we get the water line and the system
back to normal,'' Swift said. ``It will probably be two or three
days at the minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
