<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS HOPE DEFENSE CONTINUES TO SHOW THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hallelujah! Hallelujah! Oh, sure, they're all
preaching the defense gospel now.
</P>
<P>
   Win one hotly-contested road game and they're all PhDs in
Preventology. Meanwhile, the coach can only hope and pray that what
he saw Tuesday night in Salt Lake City will be on display both
Friday night against the Golden State Warriors and also in the
remaining four games of this tough road trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics scored 68 points in the second half against the Jazz
in that 101-99 victory, but everyone was saying that it wasn't
about the offense, that the Celtics' offense can normally take care
of itself, that what really got the job done was some outstanding
defensive sequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play good defense, it shows what can happen,'' said
Paul Pierce. ``If everybody gives a concentrated effort on defense,
we can be a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they know what has to be done,'' added coach Rick
Pitino. ``Defense is 50 percent hard work, but the rest is talent
and athleticism. It's being able to move your feet quickly, and we
don't have that much athleticism in that department. So we have to
do it as a team, using energy, smarts and knowing the other team's
plays. That's what we did the other night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pierce injury situation, which was somewhat cloudy the day
before, was much clearer Thursday. After sitting out the Wednesday
practice at the Golden State facility in downtown Oakland, he
underwent an MRI on his right knee. He was back in action when the
team worked out at the University of San Francisco's Memorial
Gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a mild right MCL (medial collateral ligament) sprain,''
reported trainer Ed Lacerte.
</P>
<P>
   Not to suggest that Pierce has a disproportionate significance
to this fragile team or anything, but the Celtics have only
triumphed in one game this season without him. ``With a healthy
Pierce, we'd have won three or four more games,'' Pitino confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say three. That would make them 25-25 and put them at
either the eighth or ninth spot in the East, depending on which
games they were. Make it four, and they'd be in the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of the Pierce story is to avoid becoming the lunch
meat in-between two rather large slices of bread named Olden
Polynice and Vitaly Potapenko, whose combined weight is somewhere
in the vicinity of 550 pounds. ``I got caught between them sometime
in the second half,'' Pierce explained. ``I can't remember exactly
when. It was sore in the morning. But later in the day it felt
different.''
</P>
<P>
   The MRI, according to Lacerte, was ``to rule out anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics will become the first team to see the new-look
Warriors, who have been bolstered by the addition of Larry Hughes
and Billy Owens, the former a second-year player of great promise,
and the latter, who, five teams and a reasonably tarnished
professional reputation later, returns whence he cometh nine years
ago. The pleasant cost to Golden State was erratic and hyperkinetic
malcontent John Starks. You want to talk about smiles all around .
. .
</P>
<P>
   Pitino figured he already had enough to worry about after
watching the Warriors take mighty Portland to the wire for the
second night in a row. The Warriors lost, 92-83, at home on
Tuesday, and then hung in until the final nine seconds before
losing a 99-95 rematch the following night up in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a very physical basketball team,'' Pitino analyzed,
alluding to the likes of Jason Caffey and Erick Dampier. ``They
battled Portland on equal terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Before overnighting a crying towel to the mentor, however,
consider that the Celtics will have the good fortune of playing
this 12-37 team without its best player. Antawn Jamison has a bad
knee, and unless he is planning a quick trip to Lourdes, is not
scheduled to play.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison or no Jamison, Hughes or no Hughes, Rick Barry or no
Rick Barry, the Warriors can be had, but the Celtics must apply the
lesson they learned in Salt Lake City. ``It's obvious that what we
need is defense,'' reminded Pierce. ``We are last in the league (in
opponents' field goal percentage), but we know we have the
potential to play good defense. We've got to be consistent every
night. Guys have got to get it into their heads that it's not going
to be the offense pulling us through. We've got to play the defense
_ every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen, brother.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How appropriate that the Celtics should spend Thursday and
Friday practicing in a building unofficially known as ``The House
That Russell Built.'' When Bill Russell was busy leading the San
Francisco Dons to the 1955 and 1956 NCAA championships, the school
had no true home court, schlepping around the Bay Area in such
venues as the venerable Cow Palace. This gym was built in 1958, and
there is a picture in the lobby trophy case of a smiling Russell,
shovel in hand, helping to break ground. That said, wouldn't it be
nice if the USF officials would rectify the egregious mispelling of
No. 6's middle name on two separate plaques inside the building?
They've got it as ``Fenton'' when it's ``Felton.'' C'mon, guys.
Jesuits are supposed to be more precise than that . . . Sorry,
Pervis watchers. Rick practically promised an Ellison sighting
against the Jazz, but Mr. Dreadlocks instead racked up DNP No. 25 .
. . If you're going to be in the neighborhood, plenty of good seats
will be available. This is an ultra mortal lock . . . Cheer up. At
least one station put here is selling its highest grade of gas at
$1.99 a gallon, and some are in the high $1.80s.
</P>
</TEXT>
