<HEADER>
A0129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-SPEECH-HNS &LR;      02-17 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SPEECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH'S STUMP SPEECH: PARTLY PERSONAL, PARTLY POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: DATELINE subs for Myrtle Beach, S.C.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By Dan Freedman  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONWAY, S.C. _ Start with a joke about a woman who voted for
someone else, add dollops of ``what's in my heart'' and views on
education, taxes and national security, and you get the standard
stump speech by Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The speech, repeated over and over at rallies all week across
South Carolina, is a variety-pack of soft humor, applause lines and
attempts to define differences between him and Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The speech is not written down and never has been, according to
Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes. It is an amalgam of past speeches
from his days on the Texas gubernatorial campaign trail in 1994 and
1998, and new lines calculated to fight off McCain's strong
challenge to his position as the Republican presidential
frontrunner ever since the Arizona senator swamped him in the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing the two neck-and-neck just 24 hours before
South Carolina's Republican primary, Bush is pulling out all the
stops.
</P>
<P>
   He has ratcheted up his Texas-southern accent several degrees.
`Heah me out, now,'' he tells crowds when he's discussing what he
views as a crucial point.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes spontaneity creeps into the boilerplate. Speaking
at an upscale shopping center in Hilton Head Island against a
backdrop of pricey power boats moored nearby, Bush recalled his own
upbringing in Midland, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have scenes like this'' on the West Texas plains,
Bush says. ``We only saw (such luxury) in National Geographic.''
There is no hint of irony in his voice over the fact of his own
well-to-do upbringing as the scion of the wealthy Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the time, the Bush script follows a much-practiced
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   He always starts with a tale from his unsuccessful 1978 bid for
Congress from Midland. After his defeat, a woman came up to him and
told him she voted for his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't she vote for him? Bush inquired. ``Because you didn't
ask me,'' she replies. ``So I'm here asking for your vote,'' Bush
says, exuding full warmth.
</P>
<P>
   He segues to the story about how he proposed to his wife Laura,
on bended knee, and how she made him promise that she would never
have to give speeches. ``That's the only political promise I've
ever broken,'' he confesses. This line elicits anything from a
barely audible chuckle to a loud guffaw.
</P>
<P>
   Then he gets down to the business at hand, talking about his
qualifications to be president based largely on his five years as
governor of Texas. ``I'm a uniter, not a divider somebody coming
from outside (Washington).''
</P>
<P>
   The implication is that McCain is a Washington insider, having
served in Congress 18 years. Sometimes Bush is not subtle: He calls
his rival ``Chairman,'' a reference to McCain's chairing the
powerful Senate Commerce Committee, which oversees regulation of
much of American industry.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the outcome of the South Carolina primary Saturday,
it marks ``the beginning of the end of the Clinton era in
Washington D.C.,'' Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   The serious part of his speech is always a discussion of
``what's in my heart'': the importance of family and parenting and
of how he would honor the office of the president _ a line
delivered with an unspoken, but clearly understood, reference to
Bill Clinton and his personal peccadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   Children and education are always high in the Bush stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters should not be placed in school according to age but
how much they know, and students should get the help they need in
order to achieve. ``There are no second-rate children in America,''
Bush says. ``There are no second-rate dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly adds he is not running for ``national
superintendent of schools.'' The answer to educational
under-achievement is local and state school officials raising
academic standards and being held accountable for making sure
students don't lag.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's on to taxes and the budget. Bush has taken some hits
from McCain, who accused him of pursuing reckless tax cuts instead
of salting the budget surplus away for Social Security and debt
repayment. Bush denies the charge and touts his tax-cut plan,
saying, ``It's not Washington's money; it's the people's money,'' a
line that is generally a crowd-pleaser with conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Next is national security and foreign policy. Bush sees the
post-Cold-War world as a place of uncertainty, a place where ``even
though the evil empire has passed, there's still evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding the U.S. military is a top priority. He favors
deploying an anti-missile defense system as well as raising pay and
improving conditions for men and women in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   This area is a steep climb for Bush. McCain, a Navy flier and
former prisoner of war in Vietnam, is a heavy hitter in foreign and
military affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush reminds the crowd of his days as an F-102 fighter pilot
in the Texas Air National Guard, saying `I'm not conceding the
veterans' vote to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he winds up his speeches by thanking the people who are
undecided _ those he calls the ``tire-kickers'' _ for coming and
for letting him tell them ``what's in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
