<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-IRAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday's parliamentary elections in Iran cast light on the
unique predicament of a country struggling to survive the misrule
of a clerical theocracy.
</P>
<P>
   If the so-called reformers backing President Mohammad Khatami
gain a majority of seats in Parliament, as they are expected to,
they will diminish somewhat the hardliners' dominance and do so in
accordance with the will of a voting majority. But decisive power
will still remain in the hands of the supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, and his fellow conservatives who control the judiciary,
the police, the secret services, the army, and everything having to
do with foreign and security policy.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's uniqueness, on display in these elections, is of a
religious dictatorship allowing itself to be changed from within by
democratic means.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, who was elected president in 1997 with 70 percent of
the vote, has been laboring to instill a form of ``glasnost''
within the Islamic revolution. He speaks of creating space for the
flourishing of civil society, of constructing the rule of law, and
of permitting young people and Iranian women to breathe free of the
totalitarian controls imposed by zealous mullahs and their
vigilantes.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Gorbachev, in the Soviet Union, discovered that there
could be no halfway house between democracy and the power system
built by Lenin. Khatami and his supporters are launched upon a
similar voyage. If they are to eliminate the corruption and
incompetence of the mullahs who are strangling a statist economy,
if they are to attract foreign investment and integrate Iran into
the international community, sooner or later the reformers will
have to remove the hardliners from their commanding positions in
the economy and the government.
</P>
<P>
   This will not be easy. It is hard to imagine such a
transformation being accomplished peaceably, through democratic
means alone. Indeed, the current system allows no such change in
the principle of rule by the supreme Islamic jurisprudent,
Khamenei. As long as that principle holds, electoral exercises such
as Friday's balloting serve as a safety valve to let off some of
the steam of popular discontent, while preserving the power system
built by Ayatollah Khomeini.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
