<HEADER>
A0134 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      02-17 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL IN GERMANY IS OPPORTUNITY FOR AMBITIOUS BAVARIAN LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The ambitions of Edmond Stoiber, the conservative
premier of Bavaria, to lead Germany have never been much of a
secret. But with the Christian Democratic Union in turmoil, he has
abruptly emerged as a formidable national force.
</P>
<P>
   Stoiber, whose politics stand at the right edge of mainstream
German conservatism, heads a sister party of the Christian
Democrats called the Christian Social Union. Up to now, his party
has managed to avoid the financial scandal ravaging the party of
former Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   With these credentials, Stoiber has been much in evidence of
late, castigating the Social Democratic chancellor, Gerhard
Schroeder, for isolating Austria for including Joerg Haider's
anti-immigrant Freedom Party in a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have insulted the people of Austria,'' Stoiber said this
week. At the time of the Austrian election last year in which the
Freedom Party took 27 percent of the vote, Stoiber was the only
prominent German politician to congratulate Haider and suggest his
party was now eligible for government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Stoiber does not want to be a candidate for chancellor,''
the leading economic daily, Handelsblatt, said Thursday. ``He wants
to be chancellor.''
</P>
<P>
   This evident ambition alarms the governing German coalition of
Social Democrats and Greens, especially at a time when Haider's
success has illustrated the appeal of a nationalist right. This
week, Joschka Fischer, the foreign minister, accused Stoiber of
``playing a role in giving birth'' to the Austrian coalition.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that Stoiber saw Haider's electoral success as a
legitimate basis for entering the government, but the Bavarian
leader has at the same time been at pains to say that he ``does not
want anything to do with Mr. Haider politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoiber's domestic position has been considerably strengthened
by the crisis of the Christian Democrats and by the abrupt
resignation on Wednesday of their leader, Wolfgang Schauble, who
had been tainted by accepting illegal party financing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the candidates to succeed Schauble are in their 40s and
relatively inexperienced, giving added authority to the 59-year-old
Stoiber, who has been successful in making Bavaria one of Germany's
most prosperous states.
</P>
<P>
   Combining a conservative social message that is highly cautious
about immigration with a go-ahead approach to new technologies,
Stoiber has stretched his appeal from young Bavarian professionals
to the state's reactionary traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   He was much in evidence Thursday, doling out advice on how to
choose a successor to Schauble. ``We need to take our time,''
Stoiber declared. ``Quality is more important than speed right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``The new party leader must have great powers to
integrate the regions, north and south, east and west, young and
old. And he must above all be able to integrate the liberal center
and the conservative side of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   It was notable that Stoiber used the masculine pronoun ``he'' in
his description of the ideal candidate. He is known to be fiercely
opposed to Angela Merkel, the progressive general-secretary of the
Christian Democrats and one of the favorites to succeed Schauble.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the Christian Social Union has played a background
role behind its much larger, more centrist partner, the Christian
Democrats. But in 1980, the two allied parties did field a CSU
candidate in the race for chancellor _ Franz Josef Strauss. He lost
to Helmut Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Stoiber has his mind on this precedent at a time when
his partners have never been so weak. ``The chaos among the
Christian Democrats has made the Christian Social Union much
stronger than ever before,'' the Suddeutsche Zeitung newspaper
commented Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But several potential problems may hurt Stoiber. One is the
traditional uneasiness in the rest of Germany over electing a
chancellor from Bavaria, a very large and overwhelmingly Catholic
state. Another is his recent support for Haider's inclusion in
government.
</P>
<P>
   A third is the fact that Karlehinz Schreiber, the fugitive arms
dealer who gave cash to Schauble, is known to have had close links
to the Christian Social Union. He has said he has other secrets to
reveal and has given money to ``other parties'' apart from the
Christian Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
