<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Feb. 18 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   FED-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, said Thursday that the powerhouse economy shows few signs
of slowing despite four interest rate increases over the last eight
months, and he warned that the central bank will probably raise
rates further to avert a buildup of inflation pressures. In
testimony to the House Banking Committee, Greenspan said the
current combination of strong growth, low inflation, declining
unemployment and improving efficiency among businesses and workers
was unprecedented in the half century he has spent monitoring the
economy. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT11.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANK (Moscow) _ A look at the Kremlin connections of
Russian banks named in the guilty plea in the Bank of New York
case. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ELECT (Tehran, Iran) _ Iran's parliamentary elections on
Friday have emerged as a referendum to define the ideals at the
heart of the Iranian revolution 21 years ago. The vote has become,
as well, a popularity poll for President Mohammad Khatami, the
reformist theologian who was swept into office in 1997 but has yet
to realize much of his liberal social agenda or achieve his stated
goal of improved relations with the United States. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   SC-VOICES _ South Carolina voters speak ahead of Saturday's
vote. A ledeall by R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Plus these separates, at 750 words each:
</P>
<P>
   _ SC-VOICES-CONSERVATIVES _ Conservative Republicans. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   _ SC-VOICES-LOWCOUNTRY _ Low Country Republicans. By Gustav
Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   _ SC-VOICES-SUBURBS _ Suburban Democrats. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   _ SC-VOICES-BLACKS _ Black Democrats. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   _ SC-VOICES-RETIREES _ Retirees. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-SC _ A ledeall on the John McCain and George W. Bush
campaigns. By Alison Mitchell and Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, the story combines previously budgeted MCCAIN-SC and
BUSH-SC, which are now scratched.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-CHAIRMAN (Greenville, S.C.) _ In their spirited primary
battle, George W. Bush uses the sobriquet ``The Chairman'' to tar
John McCain as a Washington insider. But a close examination of
McCain's record as chairman of the powerful Senate Commerce
Committee shows that he defies easy labelling. He has angered and
perplexed many of the Washington agencies and special interests
that he oversees from his perch as chairman. His leadership of the
commerce panel and style as chairman are also interesting
indicators of how he might lead if he ever makes it to the White
House. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIVER-DISEASE (Undated) _ A new possible approach to
treating cirrhosis of the liver, the seventh leading cause of death
in the world, has emerged from studies of telomerase, a recently
discovered agent that indefinitely prolongs the life of human cells
grown in the laboratory. So far the treatment has worked only in
mice that have been artificially given cirrhosis. If it works in
people too, it would offer a new way of tackling a major and so far
intractable disease, as well as of averting liver cancer, the
leading cause of cancer cases worldwide, 80 percent of which derive
from liver cirrhosis. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1852EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
