<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-AFRICA-0218-COX     02-17 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-AFRICA-0218-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON URGES U.S. AID, INVESTMENT IN AFRICA
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ AIDS will soon double child mortality and reduce
life expectancy by 20 years in Africa unless America takes the lead
in helping Africa find a cure, President Clinton told a group of
advocates for the continent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst burden in life that any adult can bear is to see a
child die before you,'' said Clinton, who was joined by Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright and Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater at the first National Summit on Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The president, speaking before some 2,500 business and
government leaders from the United States and Africa, also said
America must take the lead in ending Africa's bloody conflicts and
get involved with the continent because ``Africa does matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, breaking away from prepared text, said the worst
problem in Africa now is that many children have lost their parents
to to HIV, the virus that causes AIDS. He said last year, a
staggering 10 times as many people died of AIDS in Africa than was
killed in all of the continent's wars combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do something about this,'' said Clinton, who was
commended by former U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations Andrew
Young for doing more for Africa than any American president since
Jimmy Carter. ``I know there are cultural and religious factors
that make it very difficult to tackle this issue from a preventive
point of view. ... But the real answer is to stop people from
getting the HIV virus in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Health officials battling the dread disease have blamed
promiscuity in some African societies, as well as sexual practices
that can make it easier for infection to enter a woman's
bloodstream, for the rapid spread of the disease. And many people,
especially women, engage in unprotected sex because they can't
afford condoms or can't get their partners to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton: ``We shouldn't pretend that we can give injections
and work our way out of this. We have to change behavior,
attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the five five-day national summit here hope to
draft a plan that will guide U.S. foreign policymakers in helping
Africa solve its problems with more than just the AIDS epidemic,
but such as encouraging open trade, democracy and peace.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, most of the world's conflicts pale in complexity
before the situation in the Congo where at least seven nations and
countless armed groups are fighting in a ``desperate struggle that
seems to bring no one victory and everyone misery, especially the
innocent people'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They deserve a better chance,'' he said of the people of
Congo, whose conflict has been dubbed as Africa's first world war.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary Albright, who also addressed the conference, said she
recalled visiting African countries and holding a little boy whose
arm had been cut off by rebels and wondering who did he hurt.
</P>
<P>
   She criticized Sudan's human rights record, urged adversaries in
Congo and Sierra Leone to live up to peace agreements they signed
and noted the world's failure to stop the 1994 genocide of more
than 500,000 mostly ethnic Tutsis in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of Africa's problems, she said, ``We should roll up
our sleeves, not throw up our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Albright and the president said it is time that Americans
stop ignoring the African nations because ``Africa is a cradle of
humanity..... but it is also a cradle of humanity's future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this world we can be indifferent or we can make a
difference,'' Clinton said. ``Americans must choose when it comes
to Africa to make a difference, because we want to live in a world
... of people who live on the cutting edge of a new economy, and
others who live on the very edge of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Americans know about African nations' conflicts,
famine and poverty, but little about the progress that is being
made. He said they don't know about thousands of African soldiers
who are trying to end the conflicts as peacekeepers, and that
Nigeria alone, despite all its difficulties, has spent $10 billion
in the peacekeeping efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they have asked is that we support their own efforts to
build peace and to make it last. We in the United States should be
willing to do this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has stopped short of recommending a
full-fledged peacekeeping force and instead proposed a protection
force for 500 unarmed military observers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked Congress to pay about $42 million of the
estimated $160 million cost of the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to continue working on these things as long as I am
president,'' Clinton said. ``The United States will be a friend for
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
