<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-ART-2T     02-17 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE SKY IS NOT THE LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A 200-word note appears at end of story with tour
information.) (ART ADV: Photos, NYT14,15 and 16 have been sent.
Non-subscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five years in the making, the Rose Center for Earth
and Space _ a $210 million successor to the old Hayden Planetarium
_ will open Saturday, offering visitors a virtual journey through
time, space and the mysteries of the cosmos. It promises to be a
fantastic voyage, but as with any trip, expect a few rough spots.
</P>
<P>
   The domed Space Theater, which is the centerpiece of the Rose
Center, the latest branch of the American Museum of Natural
History, offers synthetic views of the cosmos far more detailed
than the most elaborate Hollywood productions. With the help of a
supercomputer, a state-of-the-art Zeiss star projector, an advanced
laser system, a gigantic data base (in which the motions and
distances of thousands of stars are cataloged) and the hemispheric
Space Theater itself, the builders have created a marvelous
celestial playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   For the extra $9 adults pay to see an 18-minute-20-second Space
Theater show, they take a spectacular virtual ride through the
universe. The audience seated under the dome whizzes past Mars,
Jupiter and Saturn and on into interstellar space toward the
constellation Orion. The recorded voice of Tom Hanks calls
attention to points of interest along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the stellar nursery below Orion's belt, where newborn
stars are seen condensing from vast clouds, the Space Theater
travelers pass through wispy images of green-tinted gas and surge
onward toward the distant reaches of the Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling at many times the speed of light (in violation of the
laws of relativity), the audience then hurtles past clusters and
superclusters of galaxies, finally reaching the outermost precincts
of the known universe, where bright filaments trace a web of
billions of galaxies woven in complex patterns.
</P>
<P>
   For the homeward journey, a fanciful black hole providentially
appears overhead, sweeping the audience into its maw and providing
a psychedelic light show and a thunderous roar along the way.
(Never mind that sound cannot exist in the vacuum of space, or that
a real human being entering a real black hole would be ripped to
shreds by the hole's gravitational field; after all, this is
theater, not astronomy.)
</P>
<P>
   The sky show occupies the upper half of the center's 87-foot
diameter sphere; the lower half is devoted to a very brief light
and sound show depicting the Big Bang _ which, for this visitor,
turned out to be a bit of a bust. It is big on pyrotechnics but not
on explanations, creating more dazzle than enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a rim inside the darkened lower hemisphere, the
audience looks down and hears the voice of Jodie Foster say that
the universe began with a gigantic explosion. As a prelude to this
great event, spectators are shown bright little rosettes flashing
on and off at the bottom of the bowl. These little blips are
puzzling. Perhaps they are intended to suggest virtual particles in
the quantum ``foam'' of empty space, spontaneously popping into and
out of existence, perhaps they have some other meaning, but they
are not explained.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes an ear-splitting crash, a bright flash, some colored
streamers, and some more garish lights. That's about it. There's no
attempt to address the obvious (although unanswerable) questions
posed by the Big Bang theory: What, if anything, preceded the
genesis explosion, and what, if anything, made it happen? For that
matter, why did the Big Bang theory gain the almost universal
support of astronomers?
</P>
<P>
   Between the upper and lower levels of the Rose Center is a
spiral walkway (reminiscent of the Guggenheim Museum) with a
splendid gallery of 220 astronomical photographs arrayed in order
of their distances in time and space from the Big Bang to the
present.
</P>
<P>
   The spiral ramp itself is one of many devices incorporated in
the Rose Center to impart a sense of scale _ in particular, an
appreciation of the staggering dimensions of the universe. The
length of the walkway, nearly 100 yards, represents a span of
around 13 billion years, at the end of which is a single hair, the
thickness of which represents the duration of human history.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most interesting photographs along the walkway show
the results of gravitational lensing, an effect not explained until
we reach a little enclosure called the Black Hole Theater on the
lowest level of the center. Modest in size, this presentation is
nevertheless richer in content than most of the rest of the Rose
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Using very effective animation, the film explains not only how
black holes are created and what they do but also gives viewers the
flavor of relativity theory, of the genius of Einstein and of the
bizarre distortions enormous masses cause in nearby space-time.
</P>
<P>
   The brief show demonstrates how a massive foreground object like
a large black hole or a galaxy can warp rays of light from a very
distant object in the background, in somewhat the way a telescope's
glass lens collects light and focuses it. Gravitational lensing,
sometimes manifested as bright arcs of light appearing in telescope
images, has revealed exceedingly distant galaxies and quasars that
would otherwise have remained undetected. Some are shown in the
center's picture gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Center also contains curiosities, including a sealed
ecosphere in which little crustaceans and various plants live
isolated from the outer world, thriving on each other and the light
that shines on their transparent globe.
</P>
<P>
   As fearsome as ever, the 15-and-a-half-ton Willamette Meteorite
salvaged from the old Hayden Planetarium rests on a new stand on
the ground floor of the Rose Center, reminding visitors of the
destruction wrought from time to time when such monster projectiles
hit the earth. Interactive television monitors are everywhere, and
a remote-controlled robot entertains young visitors.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   All this is dazzling, but for visitors who knew and loved the
Hayden Planetarium built in 1935, a certain human touch seems to be
missing from its successor.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing the new planetarium lacks the big orrery that was
a feature of the old planetarium. Operated by clockwork and
old-fashioned ceiling tracks, models of the planets and some of
their moons slowly circled a golden sun around the base of the old
planetarium, giving viewers a general idea of the solar system's
layout, relative distances and orbital speeds. Alas, the old
planetarium's orrery broke down several years before the building
was demolished in 1995, and it was not recreated for the new Rose
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the special effects used at the old planetarium came to
seem crude and creaky; as the planetarium went into its terminal
decline, its black-light murals of astronomical subjects seemed as
dated as the fading 20th century itself. But there was something
appealing about the star shows that bridged the chasm between puny
humanity and the awesome immensity of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the rim of the old dome were silhouettes of
Manhattan's skyline, reminding audiences that what they were about
to see would mirror the real sky overhead. Little lighted signs
around the dome's rim marked the points of the compass, making it
easier for spectators to find familiar constellations. Narrating
the sky show was not a recorded movie star but a real astronomer at
the controls of the star projector, wielding a flashlight pointer
to call attention to objects under discussion, clearing his throat
from time to time, and sometimes even cracking a joke.
</P>
<P>
   The old planetarium mostly depicted things that anyone standing
under a dark sky could see with the naked eye or a small telescope.
In the old planetarium, volunteers instructed classes in mirror
grinding and the construction of telescopes, and experts told
stargazers planning to look up at a real sky where they should look
for Mars, the Pleiades and the galaxy we used to call the Great
Nebula in Andromeda; it wasn't glitzy NASA-style animation, but it
was participatory astronomy for the common man.
</P>
<P>
   As the theater lights went down and the stars came out, the
planetarium's low-fidelity speakers used to play a bit of Brahms' E
minor Symphony, a wonderful musical setting for things vast and
mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   Well, times change. Don't let that stop you from visiting the
Rose Center and enjoying a great show.
</P>
<P>
   ADDITIONAL INFORMATION FOR A &UR;  &LR; BLASTOFF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Center for Earth and Space, at Central Park West at
81st Street, opens Saturday. The 333,500-square-foot, seven-floor,
120-foot-high exhibition and research site includes the new Hayden
Planetarium, the Cullman Hall of the Universe and the Gottesman
Hall of Planet Earth. The Hayden Planetarium contains the Space
Theater, presenting ``Passport to the Universe,'' and the Big Bang
Theater, featuring narrated visual and audio effects simulating how
the universe began.
</P>
<P>
   The Cullman Hall of the Universe is a 7,000-square-foot
permanent exhibition hall on the bottom level of the Rose Center
divided into four zones that illustrate the processes that led to
the creation of the planets, stars, galaxies and universe.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: Sundays through Thursdays, 10 a.m. to 5:45 p.m.; Fridays
and Saturdays until 8:45 p.m. Space shows run throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Admission (suggested donation), for the American Museum of
Natural History, which includes the Rose Center: $10; for students
and the elderly, $7.50; children 12 and under, $6; under 2 free.
Admission to the museum, the Rose Center and the new Hayden
Planetarium Space Show: $19; for students and the elderly, $14;
children 12 and under, $11.50. Information: (212) 769-5100.
Reservations: (212) 769-5200.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
