<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-SELES-COMEBACK-AR     02-17 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SELES-COMEBACK-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA SELES READY TO PLAY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MIC HUBER   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ It's a new year and Monica Seles has a new
coach, a new racket ... and the same old frustrating problem.
</P>
<P>
   The next tournament Seles plays will be her first of the year.
Injury has once again interrupted her drive back to the top of
women's tennis. It's been that way, it seems, for part of every
year since her career was disrupted in the spring of 1993 when she
was stabbed by a crazed fan at a tournament in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   This time she has been kept off the court by a stress fracture
in her right foot, which has been slow to heal. The injury was
costly. It kept Seles out of the Australian Open, the first Grand
Slam event of the year and a tournament she has dominated over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of wondering whether to go or not go,'' Seles,
26, said. ``At the end we decided that I have taken this much time
off and, that for one tournament, it was not the worth the risk.
Especially to go that far.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Sarasota resident believes she is ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played for so long, I am really itching to go
back.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears her 2000 debut will come either at Scottsdale, Ariz.,
the week of Feb. 28 to March 4, or at Indian Wells, Calif., March 6
to 19. She then would play at the Ericsson Open on Key Biscayne,
March 20 to April 2.
</P>
<P>
   Seles has been through this enough not to expect to step in and
cruise to titles. She knows she will have to play her way back into
tournament-level shape. She will do that with a focus on being
ready for the French Open, the next of the four Grand Slam events,
the last week of May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it will be tough to go back the first two weeks,'' she
said. ``I'm looking forward to playing, but realistically I will be
getting ready for the Grand Slam tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   How far she must go to be a threat to win her 10th Grand Slam
title remains to be seen. Seles says her game is ``OK'' at the
moment. But she really doesn't know for certain at what level it is
because she has not been able to practice much because of her foot
problem.
</P>
<P>
   When she is able to get on the court to practice, she has a
couple of new things working for her. She now has Bobby Banck as
her main coach. She is also using a smaller racket in an effort to
get more power on her serve.
</P>
<P>
   Banck is a popular guy. He had been working with Mary Joe
Fernandez, one of Seles' best friends on the tour. Tennis is
currently on the back burner for Fernandez as she plans her April
wedding to Tony Godsick, who works for the International Management
Group and has represented Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Banck began working with Seles after the U.S. Open and the
partnership is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is great to have someone that understands the game,'' said
Seles, who also hits with Jimmy Arias. ``Bobby brings a lot of
consistency to my game and we are trying a few new things in terms
of when to hit certain shots. We are also trying to get a little
more power and placement on my serve.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Seles has given up her favorite racket, one that
she took a lot of good-natured abuse for using the past several
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things where you picked up a racket and
loved it,'' Seles said. ``People always gave me a hard time but, to
this day, I love that racket.''
</P>
<P>
   But, at 130 square inches, it was far too big and Seles was
having difficulty controlling points against the big hitters. The
new Yonex is 110 square inches. And one benefit of the time off was
that it gave Seles time to adjust to the new racket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little time I have been able to play with it, I can
already feel a huge difference,'' Seles said.
</P>
<P>
   The time off also gave Seles a chance to travel to Washington
last week to speak in front of congressional leaders while
accepting the annual Flo Hyman Award, presented during National
Girls and Women in Sports Day on Capitol Hill. The award was
presented for her ability to overcome adversity and return to her
sport.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, though, she would rather stay busy
playing tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was tendinitis in her left forearm that disrupted
her schedule, during a year in which she had some success but just
one title. She also had a couple of firsts she would rather forget.
She suffered her first-ever loss at the Australian Open, an event
she won four times. She had become the first player, male or
female, to win as many as 33 matches at a Grand Slam tournament
before losing. She also suffered her first loss in Federation Cup
play after 10 straight wins.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
