<P>
   The New York Times plans three pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the presidential campaign:
</P>
<P>
   SC-VOICES (Columbia, S.C.) _ No one who has spent much time
talking to South Carolina voters the last couple of days would
hazard a guess as to the likely winner of Saturday's pivotal
Republican primary here. That's because it's so hard to judge
exactly who will vote. All the polls show that Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas is the heavy favorite of the Republicans, but Sen. John
McCain of Arizona is preferred by most independents and Democrats,
who are free to vote in the Republican contest, the only one
scheduled on Saturday. But who will turn out? In detailed
conversations with voters in five locations across the state, from
the wealthy enclave of retirees at Hilton Head to the conservative
heartland of Greenville and the upstate region surrounding it, no
clear pattern emerged _ except this: it is an agonizingly close
race, one that often divides best buddies and married couples. By
R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
