<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0151 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MEDICAL-MISTAKES-HNS &LR;      02-17 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-MISTAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BILL AIMS TO REDUCE MEDICAL ERRORS THAT KILL THOUSANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying she was ``shocked'' to learn that up to
98,000 Americans die each year from mistakes made by hospitals and
doctors, Rep. Constance Morella, R-Md., on Thursday introduced a
bill aimed at encouraging hospitals to share information about
their errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at these numbers, I see that more people die from
avoidable medical mistakes each year than from highway accidents,
breast cancer or AIDS,'' she said at a news conference announcing
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Morella said that virtually every other industry collects,
analyzes and distributes data on accidents occurring at different
companies to prevent other firms from making the same mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the available technology to stop putting patients at
risk as mistakes are repeated,'' she said. Noting that often
doctors are unable to learn from the mistakes of others because of
the current failure to share information, she said, ``I was simply
shocked to discover that this was happening'' and that so many were
dying as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Morella said her legislation would give hospitals and health
care professionals the incentive to voluntarily report mistakes and
problems encountered on the job by protecting the confidentiality
of data collected on medical errors.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, this information would not be subject to
subpoena or discovery in any administrative or civil proceeding
unless it becomes a matter of public knowledge through other
channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the protection afforded by this simple but important
legislation, hospitals and health care professionals fear that
information reported might ultimately by subpoenaed and used in
lawsuits against them, which would lead to very little information
sharing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Morella emphasized, however, that ``if a hospital does something
wrong and a patient starts asking the hospital itself for
information, my bill won't help the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals nationwide have been trying to implement new patient
protections after a study last November by the Institute of
Medicine reported that between 44,000 and 98,000 hospitalized
Americans die each year because of medical errors.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine is part of the National Academy of
Sciences, a private organization chartered by Congress to advise
the government on scientific matters.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, medical errors include such events as
botched surgeries, doctors prescribing the wrong drugs and nurses
causing infections because of poor hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   Many errors, the report said, could be prevented if only
hospitals analyzed patterns of problems and put in safety nets.
Unfortunately, health workers often refuse to disclose errors for
fear they'll be sued or fired, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Cousins, vice president of U.S. Pharmacopeia, a Rockville,
Md., group that has developed a national anonymous database on the
Internet for hospitals to share information on medical errors, said
Morella's legislation is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials ``have told us time and again that they would
be willing to participate, but only if they can be sure the
information they provide will remain anonymous,'' said Cousins,
whose not-for-profit group is composed of about 500 members
representing health care professionals, hospitals and government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins said nearly 100 hospital throughout the country take
part in her group's database, called MedMARx, but that the number
likely would increase dramatically if Morella's legislation were
passed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its report, the Institute of Medicine recommended the
following measures: _ Congress should establish a federal Center
for Patient Safety that would cost $35 million to start and would
eventually spend $100 million a year in safety research. That
represents just a fraction of anestimated $8.8 billion spent
yearly as a result of medical mistakes, the report calculated.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government should require that hospitals, and eventually
other health organizations, report all serious mistakes to state
agencies so experts can detect patterns of problems and take
action. About 20 states now require error reporting, but the
penalties they impose vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   _ State licensing boards and medical accreditors should
periodically re-examine health practitioners for competence,
stressing safety practices. Standardized guidelines for medical
equipment and treatment can help doctors keep up. _ Medical
professionals should change the ``culture of secrecy'' that
surrounds medical mistakes, encouraging doctors to discuss errors
as well as near-misses so problems are fixed.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
