r a BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     02-17 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY THE SUN SOMETIMES RISES ON THE EMPIRE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   British filmmakers and performers _  &UR; Michael Caine &LR; ,  &UR; Jude &LR; 
 &UR; Law &LR; ,  &UR; Janet McTeer &LR;  and  &UR; Samantha Morton  &LR; _ were big winners in
Oscar nominations this week.  &UR; Mike Leigh &LR; 's ``Topsy-Turvy'' got
four nominations; the director of the much-nominated ``American
Beauty'' is  &UR; Sam Mendes &LR; , who is English, as is  &UR; Phil Collins &LR; ,
whose song for ``Tarzan'' was nominated.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, comedian and director  &UR; Eric Idle  &LR; wrote about
the number of probable British nominations in a somewhat tart
letter to the editor of the Los Angeles Times. The first reason
British actors get hired in Hollywood, he wrote, is because they
are cheaper. ``They seem to be happy to be working for almost
nothing plus, they are extremely keen on piling into costumes and
pretending to be Victorians. The second reason is, of course, they
are usually extremely grateful to be nominated and happy to be
dragged out and interviewed, whereas back in England they are used
to being ignored or asked to leave restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   As to winning, Idle described the  &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow &LR;  rule:
``Being British will help you get nominated, but it will not help
you win unless you are pretending to be British.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAKING IT WORK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michael Douglas &LR;  talks about his engagement to  &UR; Catherine &LR; 
 &UR; Zeta-Jones &LR; , 30, in Us magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially,'' says the 55-year-old Douglas, ``I was worried
about the differences in our ages, but since the first three weeks,
it hasn't come up. Early on, any doubts I had were because I
realized that I've had it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the great advantage of that is nothing would make me more
excited, prouder than to watch Catherine explode, something a lot
of guys couldn't handle unless they've had their own success.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he loves her because she's beautiful and witty and has
``a good work ethic. As a young kid in Wales she was in tap-dancing
competitions. She's an unbelievable tapper.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RED FLAG WORDS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Almost a third of American companies peek at e-mails sent on
company computers to fellow workers, and new software allows
employers to sift through the mail looking for objectionable words.
Wired magazine describes Cameo, which works with Microsoft Exchange
and goes through 50,000 e-mails an hour. When it finds
objectionable words, the entire messages that the words are in are
sent to a manager.
</P>
<P>
   This sampling of words is typical of what employers look for,
Cameo's manufacturer told Wired:
</P>
<P>
   Bimbo, David Duke, resume, fondle, ATF, job offer, ammonium
nitrate, reefer, I'll show him/her, fertilizer, anarchy, signing
bonus, bacteriological, meth, copyright, Puerto Rican, stress, pipe
bombs, unfair, Aryan and performance review.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gerry Costanzo &LR;  of the barbershop quartet Dusty Rhythm turned
down an offer from ``a very large high-tech company'' that was
introducing a product at Moscone Center. The company wanted the
quartet to dress in bumblebee costumes and sing ``bug songs'' _ to
make fun of publicity surrounding the new product's bugs _ as
people arrived at introductory ceremonies. The quartet turned down
the offer. ``We don't know any bug songs,'' said member  &UR; Don &LR; 
 &UR; Kington &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chicago Sun Times says that if  &UR; John Travolta  &LR; and  &UR; Kelly &LR; 
 &UR; Preston &LR; 's forthcoming baby is a girl, they will name her Diana,
after  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Unveiled this week at the International Toy Fair in New York
is Jewel Girl Barbie, who has wider hips and _ for the first time
in Barbie history _ a belly button.
</P>
<P>
   _ In response to Rama Lama's proposal for making eyes out of the
last two digits of 2000,  &UR; Hank Chapot  &LR; suggests writing the year as
``2K,'' as a reminder ``that we just dodged a bullet on January
1.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lovely city and the people are lovely, but I don't like
the foreign money. I don't care! It's foreign money. It's not
American. It doesn't feel like I'm in another country. It's a very
strange experience because you fly from Los Angeles in two hours
and you're in Vancouver and everyone speaks the same language, but
if you want to buy a Coke, you can't because you don't have the
right money, so don't tell me that isn't strange.''
</P>
<P>
   _ International sophisticate and actress Charlize Theron, in the
Ottawa Citizen, describing her sufferings during the shooting of
``Reindeer Games'' in Vancouver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
