<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0163 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-IRAQ-INSPECTORS-NUKES     02-17 1767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-INSPECTORS-NUKES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DANGERS OF A SHAM IN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By DANIEL BYMAN  
 c.2000 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The return of U.N. arms inspectors to Iraq would do more harm
than good.
</P>
<P>
   This is true no matter how robust is the successor to the U.N.
team that originally worked to disarm Iraq _ that is, the new group
led by Hans Blix, former head of the International Atomic Energy
Agency and chairman of the new U.N. Monitoring, Verification and
Inspection Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Simply discovering and destroying Iraq's biological, chemical
and nuclear capabilities is not enough to stop Iraq over the long
term if Iraq is able to simply rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   If inspectors return to Iraq, President Saddam Hussein is again
likely to refuse to cooperate, leaving the United States almost
alone in seeking punishment including military strikes.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, besides gaining the complicity of officials at
the United Nations, Iraq has also gained the tacit _ and at times
overt _ support of several major powers: notably Russia, China and
France.
</P>
<P>
   Even more dangerous, however, is the possibility that Saddam
WILL cooperate with the new inspectors. This would spell not only
an end to inspections but also an end of sanctions. And then Iraq
would be free to reconstitute its arms programs _ a clear and
present danger to the entire Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising as it sounds, an impasse will better position the
United States to hamper Saddam's quest for weapons of mass
destruction _ and to avoid being a part of the deliberate flouting
of U.N. resolutions and arms-control agreements.
</P>
<P>
   In the final years of the U.N. Special Commission, or UNSCOM,
which was dispatched to disarm Iraq after the Persian Gulf war,
Saddam chose his provocations according to his own lights,
disrupting inspections or otherwise egregiously violating
agreements when he felt global support for his cause was strong or
when domestic concerns led him to pick a fight abroad.
</P>
<P>
   If the inspections resume, and Saddam picks a particularly
sensitive moment _ say, a setback in the Arab-Israeli peace process
or a burst of internal discontent in Saudi Arabia _ to be defiant,
the necessary diplomatic support for U.S.-led strikes to ensure
compliance may not be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Today's politicians and pundits who champion a resumption of
inspections say that, first, it will lead to the end of Iraq's
clandestine arms projects. Some inspections, they say, are better
than none and besides, it is impossible for Iraq to sustain an
impasse for very long. All three assumptions are false.
</P>
<P>
   The nominal success of inspections today would give Saddam a
free hand to develop bombs tomorrow. A new round of work would
probably not unearth much. U.N. workers would likely discover only
what Saddam wanted them to, or at best marginally improve our
knowledge of what is going on, leaving Iraq's existing lethal
capabilities untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is likely to again find itself in a nasty dilemma
comparable to what it faced on the eve of the Desert Fox airstrikes
in December 1998, when UNSCOM was finally withdrawn. The options:
Either ignore Saddam's deception and pave the way for declaring
Iraq free of weapons of mass destruction, or use force to demand
access.
</P>
<P>
   Past shows of force against Iraq, however, have brought at best
limited progress on disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   A more fundamental concern is that if Iraq were allowed to
forbid the conduct of ``any time, any place'' searches and instead
to control their timing and location, it could eventually get a
passing grade for disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam could then push to have Iraq certified as free of
nonconventional arms, which would end the sanctions that keep
Saddam in his box. Better an impasse than a sham.
</P>
<P>
   Before the invasion of Kuwait in 1990, the world knew little of
Iraq's efforts beyond the fact that it had a chemical-weapons
program _ used with gruesome effectiveness against its own Kurdish
population and against Iran during the eight-year war. Information
discovered after the Persian Gulf conflict indicated that Iraq was
close to producing a nuclear weapon and had vast stores of chemical
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the United States and its allies mistakenly believed
that Operation Desert Storm had destroyed much of Iraq's
threatening capability. As Defense Secretary Richard Cheney
testified in the immediate aftermath of Desert Storm, ``Saddam
Hussein is out of the nuclear business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Iraq's arsenal proved far more extensive than Western
leaders initially suspected _ and the job for inspectors more
onerous too.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Saddam blocked the inspectors' access, lied to
them about the existence of his deadly weapons programs and
otherwise made a mockery of the whole system. Iraqis repeatedly
stopped the U.N. team at the door and simply moved any sensitive
documents out the rear exit.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's interference was hardly subtle, and its pretexts for
noncompliance were often pathetic. But except for the United States
and Britain, the major powers would not back up the beleaguered
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the work was going full-bore, its effectiveness was
limited. Finding hidden weapons in a vast area is exceptionally
difficult, particularly biological weapons, which require
relatively limited infrastructure and can be easily concealed as
legitimate medical or research facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the U.N. inspectors were never led to a real
success: a complete accounting of Iraq's secret programs and the
destruction of all its proscribed weaponry. Baghdad revealed almost
none of its activities willingly and often lied about destroying
parts of its arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The full extent of Iraq's biological weapons effort became clear
only after the August 1995 defection of Hussein Kamel al-Majid, a
former general and son-in-law of Saddam who had headed the
clandestine weapons projects. Likewise, the defection of Wafiq
al-Samarrai, the former chief of military intelligence, led to the
revelation that Iraq had manufactured and loaded onto delivery
systems the lethal chemical agent VX _ a surprise to UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq almost certainly still has a small stockpile of chemical
weapons and limited quantities of biological agents and seed stock.
Yet Iraq implausibly insists that its nonconventional weapons
programs have been terminated and therefore demands that sanctions
be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Although assessments vary, Iraq would probably need only a few
years to build a nuclear weapon after sanctions were lifted. Its
biological programs could be resumed in a matter of days. Producing
chemical agents such as mustard gas and sarin would take only a few
months.
</P>
<P>
   So not only sanctions but also strict controls over Iraqi
imports are still crucial to stop proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions have cut Iraqi state revenues by $10 billion to $15
billion a year, slashing the regime's assets. Equally important,
sanctions have sharply restricted what Iraq can buy. If Iraq cannot
acquire dual-use items that can be used for both weapons and
legitimate civilian purposes, developing weapons of mass
destruction will be far harder. An Iraq that can trade as a
``normal'' nation is an unnerving prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Russia is an aggressive advocate of Iraq's cause and a
full-throated critic of inspections and sanctions. France and China
also oppose U.S. policy and _ except for a handful of traumatized
gulf emirates, especially Kuwait _ the Arab states often hesitate
to support U.S. strikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatically, it would be difficult and, indeed, foolish for
Washington to openly oppose renewed inspections. But U.S.
policy-makers should recognize that compromises, which offer the
false promise of progress, will in fact lay the groundwork for Iraq
to go its own way.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam has spent what limited money he controls on the tools of
war and on lavish rewards for his loyal followers, not on the
well-being of the Iraqi people. Money earmarked for humanitarian
purposes often goes unspent. The regime smuggles humanitarian goods
out of Iraq to sell on the black market. And Iraqis living in the
parts of northern Iraq under U.N. control fare far better than
those under Saddam's political thumb.
</P>
<P>
   If sanctions were lifted, there is little reason to expect that
Saddam would start spending revenue generously on the Iraqi people
and every reason to believe he would blow it on Iraq's lethal toys.
</P>
<P>
   To counter legitimate humanitarian concerns about the harm done
by halting the transfer of some dual-use items _ such as chlorine,
which can be used for both chemical weapons and water purification
_ Washington should push for more international supervision of
Iraqi imports. If the world community can confidently purchase,
transfer and install water-treatment facilities without worrying
that Iraq will divert them for military uses, it could send the
requisite dual-use items.
</P>
<P>
   Such humanitarian acts, however, require that control remain in
international hands lest Saddam's goons swipe the technology. Iraq,
not the United States, is the main barrier to such a shift.
</P>
<P>
   In a wider sense, however, the stumbling blocks in this
diplomatic dance lie not with Iraq but with the U.S. allies and
other major powers who are so anxious to resume trade with Baghdad.
Indeed, America's greatest obstacles are the efforts by France,
Russia and other defenders to readmit Iraq into the community of
nations without requiring it to adhere to international norms.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, standing alone may be self-defeating, despite its
moral attractiveness. But the perfect should not become the enemy
of the good. Renewed inspections would, however unwittingly, help
Saddam develop his weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing inspections may require Washington to stake out some
unpopular diplomatic positions, but given the stakes involved, the
danger of offending Saddam's defenders is easily worth the risk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Daniel Byman is a policy analyst at the Rand Corp. This is
adapted from a longer version in Foreign Affairs.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
