<SLUG> BC-RUNNING-MECCA-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINESVILLE IS A MECCA FOR WORLD-CLASS RUNNERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BOB ARNDORFER   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ You may see them as a blur in the woods,
spinning nonstop around a high school track, or ascending en masse
one of Gainesville's steep hills.
</P>
<P>
   They're the runners, shod in high-tech sneakers, who set a fast
pace in Gainesville and its outskirts. Many run just for fitness
and fun, but among the vast community of hobbyist runners is a
sizable enclave of people who make their living running. They're
some of the fastest people in the world, and for part of the year
they call Gainesville home.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Ukraine is very cold and a lot of snow,'' said Tatyana
Pozdnyakova, 44, who for the last four years has been ranked No. 1
in the world among distance runners in her age division. ``I like
the Gainesville area because it is nice place for running.''
</P>
<P>
   Pozdnyakova is among an estimated 40 international distance
runners who winter here to train for races throughout the United
States and Europe. With its mild winter climate, relatively flat
terrain and countless miles of jogging routes, Gainesville long has
been a mecca for runners. It ranks with Boulder, Colo., and Eugene,
Ore., as prime destinations for world class runners.
</P>
<P>
   But weather and landscape are only part of the reason for the
community's 30-year-long popularity among professional runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition is a big factor,'' said Doug Brown, head coach of
the University of Florida's track and cross country teams. ``Since
the early 1970s Gainesville has remained on the map as a place for
world-class distance runners. It started with Jimmy Carnes, who
found support for runners and encouraged athletes to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnes was a former University of Florida track coach who helped
found the Florida Track Club, which began as an organization for
elite runners but today has 700 members in several states who run
mostly for fun. Among the Olympians and other track luminaries
Carnes enticed here were Barry Brown, Jack Bacheler, Marty Liquori
and Frank Shorter, the 1972 Olympic marathon gold medal winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time in the early 1970s there were 40 world-class
people running at 6:15 every morning around Gainesville,'' said
Liquori, 50, who came here in 1972 and liked it so much he stayed.
``Then Shorter won the gold medal in '72, and things really grew
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, it was primarily American runners who trained
in Gainesville's runner-friendly atmosphere. Today, there's a boom
in international athletes who have discovered the area,
particularly Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bumped into a Russian coach at a race somewhere who was
looking for a place to train,'' said Liquori, a founder of the
Athletic Attic sporting goods chain who co-produces the monthly
``Running &AMP; Racing'' program for ESPN. ``I encouraged him to come
here and he brought three people with him. That was in 1988. The
next thing you know there were about 12 Russians here. Since then a
lot of Russians have come here to train.''
</P>
<P>
   Pozdnyakova, who lives in nearby Newberry with her husband/coach
and their 13-year-old son, first came here in 1996. Before then,
she said, she trained at an indoor track in the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very hard for me,'' she said. ``It's a lot better to
be able to run outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Pozdnyakova runs twice a day, every day, usually on the track at
Newberry High, racking up 110 miles a week. In the summer she lives
and trains in New York, where the climate is less oppressive.
</P>
<P>
   Other distance runners favor the soft trails and natural beauty
at San Felasco Hammock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love the scenery out there,'' said Donna Cohen, executive
director of the Florida Track Club. ``It's a very popular place to
run.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Pozdnyakova plans to compete for the $4,000 purse
in the 5K Great Gainesville Road Race, the showcase event among the
20 local races the Florida Track Club puts on each year. Also
scheduled to race Saturday is Andrey Kuznetsov, a 42-year-old
Russian who won the last two Boston Marathons in the Masters
Division for runners 40 and older. He now trains in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Liquori said Boulder's altitude and hilly terrain makes it an
important summer training ground for a lot of runners, but Boulder
has become expensive. Although good distance runners can earn from
$500 to $7,000 in a weekend, lucrative races aren't held every
weekend, and winning is never guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a lot of these people expense is a factor, and the cost
of living down here is so much cheaper than Boulder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Waitz, husband of retired marathoner Grete Waitz, said
Gainesville is the most convenient training ground for European
distance runners. He and his wife, who won the New York Marathon
nine times before retiring in 1990, moved here in 1988 so she could
train. They bought a home here and divide their time between
Gainesville and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Waitz said the East Coast location is attractive to
Europeans and so is the excellent medical community.
</P>
<P>
   Grete Waitz, who promotes races and is under contract with
Adidas, left this week for Norway to coordinate the Grete Waitz
Run. It's the world's largest women-only race, Jack Waitz said, and
in 1997 attracted 47,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   That's an indication of the popularity of running in Europe.
Sometimes that popularity has driven competitors to places like
Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are huge stars in their countries,'' Liquori
said. ``They can't go out of the house without getting mobbed. In
Gainesville they're totally anonymous, and can get on with their
training in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
