   REGIONAL-JETS (Undated) _ The battle to attract more air
passengers from smaller markets has become so intense that airlines
are now scrambling to replace their turboprop planes with jets,
giving passengers in smaller markets more flight choices than ever.
Although the average regional jet costs $20 million, nearly double
the price of a comparable turboprop, the airlines feel that the
switch is well worth it. ``Turboprop planes are not an attractive
product,'' said Leo F. Mullin, chief executive of Delta Airlines.
``Passengers view them as second-rate service.'' By David J.
Morrow.
