<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-STOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY DELAYS TAX PLAN TO END CROSS-SHAREHOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ A tax proposal aimed at dismantling the
cross-shareholdings of corporate Germany will become effective one
year later than originally planned, the government said Thursday, a
move that sent down stock prices of German banks and insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But economists and political experts predicted that the
proposal, which lifted the German stock market when it was
announced just before Christmas, does not appear to be in any
fundamental danger.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would allow companies to sell their holdings in other
companies without having to pay taxes on the capital gains. Though
seemingly somewhat esoteric, the measure is expected to reshape the
corporate landscape here because it will allow Germany's biggest
banks and insurance companies to sell their huge stakes in each
other and in the country's biggest manufacturers. They will then
presumably be able to make more profitable use of the money that
had been tied up in these long-term investments.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank AG and insurers like Allianz AG and Munich Re have
more than $100 billion in such holdings, and the cross-holdings
have slowed corporate takeovers and other forms of restructuring.
But the banks and insurers have been loath to sell the holdings,
which were accumulated over many decades, because they would face
tens of billions of marks in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, officials at the German finance ministry confirmed
that the law would become effective in 2002 rather than 2001.
Shares of major financial institutions declined on the news,
because it will delay their ability to cash in many of their
long-held profits. Allianz fell 4 percent, to 354 euros, and shares
of Deutsche Bank were down 1.2 percent, to 80.4 euros.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Becker, an economist at Deutsche Bank Research, said the
delay reflected compromises between the government of Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder and skeptics in his Social Democratic Party. But,
he added that ``these are small problems'' and that support for the
measure seems to remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   Holger Schmieding, an economist at Merrill Lynch, agreed. ``This
is a technical matter rather than a political action,'' he said.
``The government wants a significant tax reform and it wants to
encourage the restructuring of the German economy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
