<HEADLINE>
2000 MAY BE A VINTAGE YEAR FOR NASCAR ROOKIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JODY ROYCE   Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Rookies are not supposed to have an impact
on the Winston Cup series. That perception changed after Tony
Stewart finished fourth in the series' point standings last season.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 rookie class may be the best group since NASCAR was
formed in 1949. Only the 1994 class could be compared.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton won the rookie award that year, beating out older
brother Ward and several others. Other drivers who were rookies in
1994 and are still on the circuit include John Andretti, Joe
Nemechek and Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony proved himself and I'm sure he's going to be one to
contend this year,'' said Dale Earnhardt, the 1979 rookie of the
year and seven-time Winston Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   Other top rookies are Rusty Wallace in 1984 and Jeff Gordon in
1993. Six have gone on to win Winston Cup titles. Earnhardt is the
only driver to win a series title after winning top rookie honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anybody is going to top what Tony Stewart did
last year,'' Gordon said. ``That was pretty amazing. If anybody can
do it, it's this rookie class.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven drivers are contending for the 2000 honor. The three most
notable are Dale Earnhardt Jr., Matt Kenseth and Scott Pruett.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt and Kenseth finished first and third, respectively, in
the 1999 NASCAR Busch Grand National Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of the attention is on Dale Jr.,'' Gordon said,
adding that Matt Kenseth is also talented with the advantage of
having Jack Roush behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Those two are likely to swap paint for that title. Both drivers
ran in five Winston Cup races in 1999 and each garnered a top-10
finish in September.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. was 10th in the Exide 400 at Richmond, Va., the
one where Stewart picked up his first Cup win. Kenseth had a fourth
in the MBNA Gold 400, won by Roush Racing teammate Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they come into the sport they're a lot more in tune and
smarter with what's going on with Winston Cup racing and the
cars,'' the elder Earnhardt said. ``It's really not like being in
the dark when they hop in a Winston Cup car.''
</P>
<P>
   Pruett, 39, who drives for Cal Wells, has the most diverse
background of the rookies. He's a veteran road racer with a victory
in the Daytona 24-hour, has driven and won in the IROC series and
had two wins and four poles in 125 starts in the CART-FedEx series.
</P>
<P>
   But this battle is more than just a three-man race. Jeff Fuller
and Dave Blaney also make the jump to the Cup cars from the BGN
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Blaney will join Ward Burton and make Bill Davis Racing a
two-car operation. The 1995 World of Outlaws champion improved from
29th in the 1998 BGN points standings to sixth in BGN last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rate them pretty high because I'll probably be going to
those guys for advice,'' Stewart said. ``What our team did last
year, there's a good possibility that it could be overshadowed
pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller spent five seasons in the Busch Series, but saw his
chances take a step backward this week. In a two-car crash Monday
morning with Greg Sacks, the front of Fuller's Pontiac burst into
flames.
</P>
<P>
   The last three Rookie of the Year winners have benefited from
being part of multi-car operations. Stewart hooked up with Joe
Gibbs Racing and Bobby Labonte last year. In 1998, Kenny Irwin
joined Dale Jarrett for Robert Yates. Mike Skinner became a
teammate of the elder Earnhardt in 1997 for Richard Childress. Two
drivers are coming from the Craftsman Truck Series, which runs its
season opener, the Daytona 250, Friday at Daytona International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Compton will try to revive Harry Melling's career as a
Winston Cup owner. Melling prospered in the 1980s with Bill Elliott
behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar No. 14, synonymous with four-time Indianapolis 500
champion A.J. Foyt, now exists on the Cup circuit with Mike Bliss
at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss has competed in the Truck series since its inception in
1995 and has finished in the top 10 in the points standings all
five seasons. He was runner-up to Jack Sprague for the championship
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 and 1988, Pruett won IMSA's GTO drivers' championship.
He captured the Trans-Am series title in 1982 and 1994. In his
first appearance at Daytona International, he won the IROC opener
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 he co-drove the winning Nissan 300ZX at the Rolex 24
Hours of Daytona, sharing the cockpit with Paul Gentilozzi, Butch
Leitzinger and Steve Millen.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to the CART champ-car series in 1989, when he was
co-rookie of the year at the Indianapolis 500. His career almost
ended in 1990 when he shattered both legs in a crash in the
preseason test of an Indy car at West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Pruett was chairman of the Championship Drivers
Association, which represents CART and IRL drivers on safety issues
and manages a benevolent fund that supports injured drivers and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   (Jody Royce writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla. The
Herald-Tribune is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
