<SLUG> BC-U.N.-TUVALU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SECURITY COUNCIL CLEARS WAY FOR U.N.'S 189th MEMBER  
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Over the objections of China (population 1.2
billion), the Security Council cleared the way Thursday for the
Pacific island nation of Tuvalu (population 10,000) to become the
189th member of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly is expected to admit the new country
formally later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly spokeswoman, Shirley Brownell, said that the
organization was trying to place a call to Tuvalu through Fiji on
Thursday to tell the Tuvaluans the good news. Tuvalu, which
occupies nine coral atolls halfway between Hawaii and Australia, is
the fourth small Pacific nation to apply to join the organization
recently. Last year Nauru, Tonga and Kiribati became members.
</P>
<P>
   Tuvalu, with no point of land higher than about 15 feet, is one
of the countries most threatened by rising seas caused by global
warming. A diplomat from another small island nation suggested that
Tuvalu may have decided that now was a good time to join the United
Nations, which took up the problems of small island states at a
special assembly session last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly a British colony known as the Ellice Islands, Tuvalu
became independent in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council vote Thursday was 14-0 with one abstention
_ China's. Tuvalu, with a total land area only one-tenth the size
of Washington, D.C., has diplomatic relations with Taiwan, which
China considers a breakaway province. China said Tuvalu was in
violation of the U.N. resolution recognizing Beijing as China's
sole representative.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has now grown from 51 members at its founding
in 1945 to nearly four times that number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
