<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-YATES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YATES HAS THE CARS TO BEAT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PAT ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Robert Yates sat on the steps at the back
of Dale Jarrett's hauler, totally unconcerned with the fact that he
is a marked man. For a long time, Robert Yates Racing has been one
of the most respected names in NASCAR, although the battle to stay
on top hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   It began in 1989 when Yates bought the team from Harry Ranier,
urged on by Davey Allison. Yates and Allison were competitive
almost from the start, and they continued their upward surge when
Larry McReynolds signed on as crew chief in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the dark days. In rapid succession, Allison was killed
in a helicopter accident at Talladega, Ala., in 1993 and then his
replacement, Ernie Irvan, almost lost his life in a wreck at
Michigan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Yates brought in Jarrett, but with all the strife the team had
been through, it didn't take right away. The team was not able to
run at the level to which Yates was accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   When Irvan returned fulltime in 1996, Yates expanded to two
cars, pairing Jarrett with young Todd Parrott and putting Irvan
back in his primary car. Immediately Jarrett rocketed to the front
while Irvan's team struggled, although he was able to win a race, a
source of pride for Yates.
</P>
<P>
   While Irvan's 1996 victory brought closure, in some sense, to
the dark days that had enveloped the team in tragedy, it didn't
completely end them. It was a constant source of frustration for
Yates as he watched Jarrett and Parrott flex their muscles while
his other car scrambled.
</P>
<P>
   But here this week, seven drivers and about as many crew chiefs
after Allison, it looks like Yates, who won the Winston Cup
championship with Jarrett in 1999, now has a one-two punch to
contend with.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Yates brought in respected veteran Ricky Rudd and
another bright young crew chief, Michael McSwain, to take over
Allison's former entry.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, things have clicked. Come Sunday, Jarrett and Rudd will
start one-two in the Daytona 500 and if they finished that way, it
wouldn't surprise a lot of people in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   The close-knit, family atmosphere that drew Jarrett's team
together is now also evident in Rudd's operation, and that's why
Yates is a marked man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets down to what gets the job done, and you have to bring
the right stuff and then hope you can come down here and know what
you're doing,'' Yates said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the time the 1999 season ended, maybe earlier, Yates
pointed his team at this objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the cars had a little less drag this year, and we
really worked on building quality pieces,'' Yates said. ``We worked
hard on the aero package, and Ford's been good to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd never took a vacation. He worked every day on the cars.
We knew we had a chance to do something special this year, to get
both cars on the front row, and that's a coveted objective.''
</P>
<P>
   So Yates now looks to have not one, but two cars to beat, and
the word is out. Catch them if you can.
</P>
<P>
   (Pat Zier writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. The Ledger is
part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
