<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLING-CASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGKOK BUSINESSMAN HELD IN ALLEGED SMUGGLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Bangkok businessman accused of plotting to smuggle
night vision goggles and blueprints of a US military aircraft to
the Pakistani Army was ordered held without bail Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Reynolds, 33, a British citizen now living in Thailand,
was arrested Feb. 5 by US Customs agents who lured him to Boston
for a meeting at an undercover export company they had set up to
stop the illegal shipment of defense items.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has banned military exports to Pakistan since
1990 because of the country's failure to restrict nuclear testing
and development. Tension between Pakistan and neighboring India has
continued to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries tested nuclear devices in 1998 and declared
themselves nuclear powers. Earlier this month, Pakistan test-fired
a new missile that officials said improves accuracy and can hit
targets 60 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who is charged in a federal complaint with conspiring
since September 1998 to export defense items to Pakistan, was
ordered detained Thursday by US Magistrate Judge Robert Collings.
</P>
<P>
   The court appointed public defender Owen Walker to represent
Reynolds. Reynolds described himself as the owner of a company that
sells aircraft parts, but said he cannot afford to hire a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Walker declined to comment Thursday on the charges against
Reynolds and did not argue against Reynolds's etention.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant US Attorney Despena Billings told the judge that the
charges against Reynolds could carry a lengthy prison term, and
that prosecutors believe he may flee if released.
</P>
<P>
   US Customs agents in Boston set up an undercover company in June
1998, according to an affidavit by Special Agent Richard C.
Krueger, after a witness told them that he had been contacted over
the Internet by Hassan Ahmed, of the Sun &AMP; Star Co. in Pakistan,
who wanted to buy night vision goggles for the Pakistani Army.
</P>
<P>
   Agents purporting to work for the undercover company
corresponded by e-mail, fax, and telephone with Ahmed, who said his
company specialized in supplying spare parts for military
aircrafts, weapon systems, and ground support equipment, the
affidavit says. .
</P>
<P>
   After acknowledging that he knew it was illegal to export the
goggles to Pakistan, Ahmed told the undercover agents that he
wanted to ``proceed cautiously'' and asked them to negotiate with
Reynolds, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   During recorded conversations, Reynolds said that he was a
purchasing agent for Pakistan concerns and boasted that he knew top
officials in the United Kingdom's Department of Trade and
Industries who could help him.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Reynolds sent $10,980 to the undercover company
for one pair of night vision goggles and asked it to send them to
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds also used the undercover company to purchase drawings
of Lockheed's C-130 aircraft from an unnamed US company for $18,000
last October, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit says an undercover agent asked an employee of the
company whether the boss knew where the blueprints were going and
was told, ``Absolutely . . . He knows about Jonathan (Reynolds),
trust me. I'd be . . . dead . . . if he didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
