<HEADLINE>
BANGKOK BUSINESSMAN HELD IN ALLEGED SMUGGLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Bangkok businessman accused of plotting to smuggle
night vision goggles and blueprints of a US military aircraft to
the Pakistani Army was ordered held without bail Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Reynolds, 33, a British citizen now living in Thailand,
was arrested Feb. 5 by US Customs agents who lured him to Boston
for a meeting at an undercover export company they had set up to
stop the illegal shipment of defense items.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has banned military exports to Pakistan since
1990 because of the country's failure to restrict nuclear testing
and development. Tension between Pakistan and neighboring India has
continued to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries tested nuclear devices in 1998 and declared
themselves nuclear powers. Earlier this month, Pakistan test-fired
a new missile that officials said improves accuracy and can hit
targets 60 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who is charged in a federal complaint with conspiring
since September 1998 to export defense items to Pakistan, was
ordered detained Thursday by US Magistrate Judge Robert Collings.
</P>
<P>
   The court appointed public defender Owen Walker to represent
Reynolds. Reynolds described himself as the owner of a company that
sells aircraft parts, but said he cannot afford to hire a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Walker declined to comment Thursday on the charges against
Reynolds and did not argue against Reynolds's etention.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant US Attorney Despena Billings told the judge that the
charges against Reynolds could carry a lengthy prison term, and
that prosecutors believe he may flee if released.
</P>
<P>
   US Customs agents in Boston set up an undercover company in June
1998, according to an affidavit by Special Agent Richard C.
Krueger, after a witness told them that he had been contacted over
the Internet by Hassan Ahmed, of the Sun &AMP; Star Co. in Pakistan,
who wanted to buy night vision goggles for the Pakistani Army.
</P>
<P>
   Agents purporting to work for the undercover company
corresponded by e-mail, fax, and telephone with Ahmed, who said his
company specialized in supplying spare parts for military
aircrafts, weapon systems, and ground support equipment, the
affidavit says. .
</P>
<P>
   After acknowledging that he knew it was illegal to export the
goggles to Pakistan, Ahmed told the undercover agents that he
wanted to ``proceed cautiously'' and asked them to negotiate with
Reynolds, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   During recorded conversations, Reynolds said that he was a
purchasing agent for Pakistan concerns and boasted that he knew top
officials in the United Kingdom's Department of Trade and
Industries who could help him.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Reynolds sent $10,980 to the undercover company
for one pair of night vision goggles and asked it to send them to
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds also used the undercover company to purchase drawings
of Lockheed's C-130 aircraft from an unnamed US company for $18,000
last October, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit says an undercover agent asked an employee of the
company whether the boss knew where the blueprints were going and
was told, ``Absolutely . . . He knows about Jonathan (Reynolds),
trust me. I'd be . . . dead . . . if he didn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1939EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER18-COX     02-17 2547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Wider area, wilder leads
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Front-runners Al Gore and George W. Bush are finding the
national polls friendlier these days than the polls in the primary
states in which they're battling right now. Bush retains a healthy
lead over John McCain in the Republican presidential race, say two
national polls. Bush leads McCain 58 percent to 31 percent in a
CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll and leads by 20 points in a CBS-New York
Times poll. Gore led Bill Bradley by about 40 points in both polls,
a strong position he has had in many polls since winning in Iowa
and New Hampshire. Both polls have a margin of error of 3
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH HORSES AND LOW ROADS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush accused John McCain on Thursday of running as a
``high horse'' candidate while using ``low road'' campaign tactics.
``This is a man who says he's going to do one thing and does
another,'' Bush said, referring to McCain's vow last week to end
negative advertising. ``You can't have it both ways in the
political process. You can't take the high horse and then claim the
low road.''
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN'S `SEMINAL EVENT'
</P>
<P>
   John McCain said his campaign would prove ``a seminal event'' in
American politics, promising to attract independents and Democrats
for a general election coalition. ``If we win here, I don't see how
we can be stopped,'' McCain said Thursday at a Veterans of Foreign
Wars post in Spartanburg, S.C. Two new national polls Thursday _
CNN-USA Today-Gallup and CBS-New York Times _ show McCain faring
better than George W. Bush in a matchup with likely Democratic
nominee Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   FIRING AWAY ON GUN CONTROL
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley promoted gun control today in a Boston neighborhood
plagued by shootings. As he toured the Codman Square Health Center,
Bradley heard from a woman who lost two stepsons to gunfire.
Bradley called for licensing all handguns and dismissed as
ineffective Al Gore's plan to register only new gun purchases.
Bradley also stepped up his criticism of Gore's mixed record on
abortion with a new ad suggesting the vice president played both
sides of the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   CHEERS FROM GAY ACTIVISTS
</P>
<P>
   In a rousing finale to two days of barnstorming New York state,
gay activists cheered Bill Bradley as the candidate most
sympathetic to their concerns. Ethan Geto, who introduced Bradley
at the Lesbian and Gay Community Services Center in Manhattan,
cited Bradley's early opposition to President Clinton's ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy on gays in the military, his call for
adoption rights for gay couples and his proposal to expand
protections of the 1964 Civil Rights Act to include sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY SHIFT AT THE SHIPYARD
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO leaders took Al Gore to shake hands with workers during
an early morning shift change at the Avondale shipyard in New
Orleans on Thursday morning, introducing some of the voters they
hope will back their endorsement of Gore for president. Gore was
welcomed with a cheer when he arrived outside the shipyard gates at
7 a.m., accompanied by AFL-CIO President John Sweeney. Last fall,
the Avondale shipyard workers won a six-year campaign to unionize _
a victory the labor movement has highlighted as proof of union
tenacity and power.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GET AROUND CAMPAIGN FUNDING LIMITS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, his once-massive campaign war chest down to $20
million, has some extra millions set aside from his top political
donors that could give him a boost if he manages to survive the
challenge from John McCain. Bush's financiers have built a separate
$5.2 million ``soft money'' fund that Bush could use in the general
election. Here's how it works, according to Knight Ridder
Newspapers: Bush operators created a fund-raising organization last
year that enabled donors to contribute up to $25,000 a year to
state Republican parties, much more than the $1,000 maximum each
donor could legally contribute to the Bush for President Committee.
If Bush gets the GOP nomination, the money could be used in his
fall campaign. If he loses, of course, he'd be giving McCain a nice
little gift.
</P>
<P>
   WINTER CAMPAIGN OF HIS DISCONTENT
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by what he called a ``pattern of pandering'' by
George W. Bush, one New York Republican congressman says he is
``seriously reconsidering'' his support for Bush. Moreover, Rep.
Peter King said, a ``significant'' number of other Republicans in
the state also are quietly questioning Bush's viability in the
presidential race. ``I'm hearing discontent,'' King said, but
added, ``How far they're going to go, I don't know.'' King said he
was troubled by several recent Bush comments and appearances _ most
notably his visit to Bob Jones University in Greenville, S.C.,
which bars interracial dating and has harshly criticized the Roman
Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   IS HE OR ISN'T HE A CONSERVATIVE?
</P>
<P>
   There have been increasing attacks on John McCain by some
Republicans for being a GOP moderate who compromises frequently
with Democrats, or even a ``closet liberal.'' But, says the Chicago
Tribune, those charges are not supported by the votes he cast
during his career in the House and Senate. A Tribune examination of
hundreds of McCain's votes during the past 17 years leaves little
doubt that he does belong in the conservative camp. In the words of
Sen. Sam Brownback (R-Kan.), McCain's record follows ``a
conservative line with a populist bent to it.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW ADS FOR CLOSING DAYS
</P>
<P>
   Closing out the South Carolina race, John McCain returned in a
new TV commercial to the themes that launched his campaign. In the
ad, the announcer says McCain has ``the character to do what's
right'' and ``the courage to fight for it.'' The announcer declares
McCain is ``a Republican like Ronald Reagan who can win.'' George
W. Bush also has a new ad that continues to hammer McCain for
negative campaigning, even though McCain stopped running such ads
last week. It also accuses McCain of bashing Bush in a television
interview.
</P>
<P>
   A STRUGGLE TO CATCH ON
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley is voicing disappointment with his inability to
capture public attention and, in particular, to connect with black
voters. Responding to questions while campaigning in upstate New
York, Bradley acknowledged that time is running out before the
decisive primaries March 7 in 15 states. He conceded that he has
had little success in reaching voters since the New Hampshire
primary Feb. 1, when he came within 4 points of Al Gore. If Bradley
is to gain ground, he needs to break through to black voters, a
core Democratic constituency. To date, Gore has enjoyed
overwhelming support among African-Americans. ``I feel a little
disheartened by those numbers,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST-LAID PRIMARY PLANS
</P>
<P>
   After considerable calculation last year, Michigan Gov. John
Engler and GOP lawmakers moved up the state's Republican primary by
a month, to Feb. 22. The reasons were twofold: Elevate Michigan's
standing in the selection process and deliver a big, early victory
for George W. Bush. But Engler may have misjudged the impact of
Michigan's open-primary status, and now is conceding that Bush
could lose if large numbers of independent voters and Democrats
flock to the polls to support John McCain. ``I think it will be
close,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   WOULD THIRD TIME BE A CHARM?
</P>
<P>
   Just days after followers of Ross Perot ousted Jack Gargan, the
Reform Party chairman who was loyal to a Perot rival, Minnesota
Gov. Jesse Ventura, party leaders launched a petition drive to
draft the Texas billionaire for a third presidential try. ``There's
beginning to be an upswell among the grass roots in the party,''
said national secretary Jim Mangia. Perot finished with 19 percent
of the vote in 1992 and 8.5 percent in 1996. He would face former
GOP candidate Pat Buchanan for the party's nomination and the $12.6
million in federal matching funds that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY MEN MUSTER UP
</P>
<P>
   Battling the advantages George W. Bush has with money,
Republican leaders and the regular party organizations, John McCain
has been making up for it by building a nationwide campaign
organization using established veterans' groups. He calls it his
``Patriots Network,'' and if he beats Bush in South Carolina, the
former Navy pilot and POW will have a lot of veterans to thank.
There are 400,000 veterans in the state, the same number of people
expected to vote Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ALL FIRED UP UPSTATE
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley accused Al Gore of ignoring western New York and
other places left out of the economic boom while courting votes
elsewhere for the big March 7 primary. Going all out in New York,
Bradley spoke in Rochester, where he portrayed Gore as a latecomer
to an area that has not shared deeply in the past decade's economic
good times.
</P>
<P>
   WITH HATCH AND BAUER GONE, THERE'S ROOM FOR MORE CANDIDATES
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader plans to announce his candidacy
for president on Monday, CNN reports. Nader, 65, will campaign for
nomination of the Green Party, a small party best known in
California where it has elected more than a dozen local officials.
It would be Nader's third campaign for the White House. He ran as a
write-in 1992 and as the 1996 Green Party nominee, getting 684,902
votes nationally and 2 percent of the vote in California.
</P>
<P>
   SHOW OPEC WHO'S THE BOSS?
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani blasted President Clinton, his
Senate opponent's husband, for not releasing the nation's oil
reserves to reduce heating oil prices. ``What's happening right now
to our home heating oil prices is outrageous,'' Giuliani said at a
Plattsburgh restaurant as snow fell outside and the temperature
hovered in the 20s. ``He could stand up to OPEC and he's refusing
to do that,'' Giuliani said of the president. Meanwhile, Clinton on
Wednesday released $125 million in emergency aid to help the poor
pay their heating bills.
</P>
<P>
   YEAH, THEY KNOW WHAT SHE MEANS
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, meanwhile, was on Rudy Giuliani's turf, laying
out her goals during a ``60 Minutes II'' interview in front of a
Manhattan audience. Journalist Charlie Rose asked what she would do
if she lost to Giuliani. ``Well, I am going to win,'' she said
without hesitation. She also said she did not plan to use the
Senate as a springboard to return to the White House as president.
``I want to serve my full six-year term, and I have learned that
senators have a whole lot more privacy than presidents,'' she
added, getting a laugh from the mostly friendly audience of about
900 people.
</P>
<P>
   NOW SHE'LL HAVE TO REPORT ALL THOSE TIPS TO THE IRS
</P>
<P>
   That upstate New York waitress who didn't get a tip from Hillary
Clinton last week when the Senate candidate's breakfast was comped
by the restaurant, has been flooded with cash from sympathizers.
Trish Trupo, 31, has gotten nearly $1,000 in gratuities from
strangers as far away as California who read about the first lady's
faux pas in newspapers and on the Internet. ``I'm a little blown
away,'' said Trupo, a single mother who works for $2.90 an hour
plus tips at the Village House Restaurant in Albion, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   JUMPING ABOARD THE MCCAIN TRAIN
</P>
<P>
   Rumors abound in California, according to the Christian Science
Monitor, that Secretary of State Bill Jones, who dumped George W.
Bush and endorsed John McCain, made the switch because he saw how
many Democrats reregistered as Republicans, indicating swelling
interest in McCain. Those numbers will be released next week.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK ON THE HOME FRONT
</P>
<P>
   A group critical of social conservatives says George W. Bush,
who bills himself as the ``compassionate conservative,'' has
ignored child poverty issues at home. Samantha Smoot, executive
director of the Texas Freedom Network, a social-issues watchdog
group, said Texas' poor ranking on a variety of issues, coupled
with Bush's recruiting of social conservatives in South Carolina,
is hypocritical. Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor
has worked with the Legislature to make sure all Texas children
have access to quality education and health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS JUMPING THROUGH HOOPS
</P>
<P>
   If a preteen vote existed, Bill Bradley might have wrapped it up
with his new TV ad starring Michael Jordan. The other day in
Buffalo, N.Y., Jordan's name was invoked twice by Bradley
supporters introducing the candidate. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan
(D-N.Y.), told the crowd his grandson, Michael, 8, was not
interested in politics until the basketball great endorsed Bradley.
Same thing with City Councilman Byron Brown's son, Byron III, 9.
``My only wish,'' Bradley said, ``is that 8- and 9-year-olds could
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   TIME OUT TO PLAY VICE PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore took a vice presidential detour Wednesday to view
tornado-ravaged Camilla, Ga. His campaign paid for his trip to
Georgia, but taxpayers paid to take him from Macon to Albany and
then for a helicopter to Camilla. Gore spokeswoman Laura Quinn said
Gore did not want to go so near the destruction ``and not have the
administration give it its full attention.''
</P>
<P>
   HE'S HER SON, AND SHE LOVES HIM
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush, mother of the candidate, took a swipe at John
McCain and the media in an interview with the Arizona Republic. The
former first lady said McCain's campaign has ``been boosted by
reporters looking to generate excitement'' in the race. Barbara
Bush: ``Without sounding like I'm whining, I feel (McCain) had
enormous help from the press, because he's become sort of a star
figure with them.''
</P>
<P>
   IT'S HIS MEDIA, AND HE DOESN'T LOVE IT
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes traveled to New York to receive endorsements from the
Congress of Racial Equality and Jews for Morality. While there, CNN
reported, Keyes couldn't resist a swipe at reporters, categorizing
the New York press as ``basically Communist-style media.''
</P>
<P>
   IN A STRONG ECONOMY, TAXES AREN'T AS BIG AN ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, polls have found that although tax cuts
were the top priority for Republican voters, they were far less
popular among ticket splitters, whose votes are critical for party
success. Taking care of Social Security ranked first with them. The
dilemma is now at work to the detriment of George W. Bush and to
the benefit of John McCain. In other words, a candidate can't just
say ``My tax cut is bigger than your tax cut'' and expect results.
``There's no doubt that the whole issue of tax cutting does not
resonate like it did in the 1980s,'' said Bush spokesman Ari
Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   SORRY AL, BILL SLIPPED UP
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton still has time to register to vote for wife
Hillary in the Nov. 7 Senate election in New York, but he can't
vote for Al Gore in the state's important March 7 presidential
primary. Jenny Palazola of the Westchester County voter
registration office told the Washington Times that Clinton did not
register to vote in New York by the Feb. 11 deadline for the
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
