<HEADLINE>
GORE REASSURES UNIONS ON TRADE PACTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ With organized labor expected to flex its muscle
on his behalf in the upcoming presidential primaries, Al Gore
reassured union leaders Thursday he would fight for them on such
thorny topics as trade pacts with China.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO leaders emerged from a meeting with the vice president
convinced that Gore would place more safeguards for labor and the
environment in trade pacts than President Clinton has.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has committed himself to being stronger on
core labor standards in future trade agreements when he is
president,'' said John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, after the
executive council meeting with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's opponent, Bill Bradley, campaigned Thursday at a
community center in Dorchester, Mass., one of Boston's poorer
neighborhoods, where crime remains a presence and adolescents can
get a gun more cheaply than a pair of sneakers, and he reiterated
his gun-control proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is now lobbying Congress to approve
normalizing trade relations with China, a move opposed by unions
who claim they would have to compete with an exploited work force.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said he will not defy his boss on the pact; however, if
it is not approved by Congress this year and he is elected
president, he will rework the agreement to include provisions that
meet union approval.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders say Gore will help them if he wins the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference between being Number One and Number
Two,'' said Sweeney, who also accompanied Gore early Thursday to
greet shipyard workers as they changed shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's assurance to the unions that he will help them next year
could undermine the Clinton's administration's ability to sell the
China trade deal this spring to wavering members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor is expected to mount a lobbying effort to defeat
the measure and may use Gore's pledges as an argument to members of
Congress to delay consideration until after next November's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to give the Gore administration an opportunity
to deal with this,'' said George Beck, president of the United
Steel Workers union, who attended the meeting with the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   While the vice president did not address the media after the
labor meeting, his spokesman Chris Lehane said Gore had promised
unions that he would integrate their demands into future trade
pacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore supports China's ascension into'' the World Trade
Organization, Lehane said. ``But he has also said as president in
terms of future trade agreements he would look at labor
environmental and human rights agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO, which endorsed Gore last fall, has marshaled its
troops to help the vice president beat Bill Bradley in key states
in the upcoming March 7 primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rosenthal, political director of the AFL-CIO, said union
members comprised as much as a third of Democratic primary voters
in California, 28 percent in New York, and 39 percent in Ohio. Each
of those states holds its primary March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders said Bradley and Gore had similar pro-labor voting
records when they were in the Senate. But Sweeney said that it was
much tougher for Gore to take such stands because he represented
Tennessee, a more conservative state than Bradley, who retired as
senator from New Jersey in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
