<HEADER>
A0193 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-OIL-RESERVE-KENNEDY-B     02-17 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-RESERVE-KENNEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. KENNEDY TO SEEK HEATING OIL RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as the Clinton administration said Thursday
that oil prices will soon stabilize, Congress is preparing to
consider measures designed to curb future spikes in the price of
home heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   Early next week, Senator Edward M. Kennedy will introduce a bill
requiring wholesalers to keep a reserve of heating oil on hand as a
cushion against shortages and price run-ups. And a bill filed last
fall by senators from New York and Maine would make it easier for
the president to ease prices under certain circumstances by
releasing oil from the government's Strategic Petroleum Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   News of Kennedy's bill comes as US Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson said the oil market ``is starting to stabilize.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe . . . that prices will stabilize. Heating oil
prices are already going down,'' Richardson said on the ABC
television program ``Good Morning America.'' His comments came one
day after Richardson attended a ``heating oil summit'' in Boston,
where he told consumers, truckers, and political leaders that the
administration was ``caught napping'' as heating oil prices nearly
tripled in the Northeast the past month.
</P>
<P>
   Oil heats a far larger percentage of homes in the Northeast than
elsewhere in the country. Analysts say prices have spiked because
of a slowdown in production by members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, and because suppliers were caught
short-handed as a relatively warm winter turned suddenly colder.
Moreover, tankers had a hard time moving heating oil to ports
because of frozen rivers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has already said he will release $125 million
in emergency funds to help low- and middle-income people pay
heating oil bills, and he plans to ask Congress for $600 million in
additional funds.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Kennedy will introduce a bill giving the US energy
secretary new powers to require that heating oil wholesalers keep
reserves at a certain level. Those reserves would be built in the
summer months, when prices are low and supplies plentiful, and
could be drawn down during the winter if supples become low.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would affect only large wholesalers, including the 20
or so operating in Massachusetts, and not small distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The energy secretary already has authority to require petroleum
producers nationwide to maintain reserves, a Kennedy aide said. The
bill would augment those powers so that the secretary could also
focus on heating oil supplies in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Producers oppose the bill, saying that the government should not
meddle in the market.
</P>
<P>
   If required to hold reserves, said Michael Shanahan of the
American Petroleum Institute, a trade group, a wholesaler might be
caught with a big supply during a collapse in price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market falls out. You're sitting there holding oil that
you bought at one price, and now it's worth less. You have to take
a loss,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Shanahan said, it costs money to store oil, and so the
Kennedy bill would raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   A Kennedy aide said the bill was written so that the cost of
holding oil in reserve would add no more than a penny per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy aides also argued that people who heat their homes with
natural gas and electricity already have certain protections under
federal law. Electric utilities are required to keep a reserve on
hand in case of plant malfunctions, they said, and natural gas
suppliers must meet pipeline capacity requirements so that
bottlenecks do not develop, which would raise prices. Kennedy's
office said the bill extends similar protections to users of home
heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Senators Charles E. Schumer, Democrat of New York,
and Susan Collins, Republican of Maine, have filed a bill that
would ease the rules regarding the release of oil from the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton so far has resisted releasing oil from the reserve as a
way to lower prices, despite growing political pressure. Kennedy
and Schumer have called for him to do so, and New York Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani has begun airing television ads on the issue as
campaigns against Hillary Rodham Clinton for a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   The Schumer-Collins bill would allow the president to release
oil from the government reserve when US oil and gas prices rise
sharply because of ``anticompetitive practices'' by foreign
producers.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan of the petroleum trade group said the reserve ``was not
created to be used to affect the market directly, and to affect
supply and demand.'' Rather, the government created the reserve so
the nation could continue essential functions in case of a Mideast
war or political disruption, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law states that the reserve is ``only for national
supply emergencies,'' Richardson said. ``This is a price problem. .
. . The United States doesn't try to manipulate markets. . . . We
don't try to manipulate the price of oil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
