<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTA-TRAVEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fed asked to block airline Web site
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's leading travel agent group is asking the government
to block the creation of a new travel Web site co-owned by numerous
airlines, including Atlanta-based Delta.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Travel Agents asked the U.S. Justice
Department to halt formation of what it termed the ``monster
airline Web site.'' ASTA said the site would lead to price-fixing
and violate antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This joint site is a clear attempt on the part of the airlines
to lure consumers onto the Web with lower prices and drive all
their competitors out of business, resulting in complete and total
domination of the public airways,'' ASTA President Joe Galloway
said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, United, Continental and Northwest announced plans in
November to create a jointly-owned, independently-managed travel
Web site to compete with sites such as Travelocity and Expedia.
Delta and other airlines would maintain their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 other airlines have since joined the project. The
still-unnamed site is expected to be running later this year. The
participating carriers say the site will be airline-neutral,
offering unbiased comparative fare information. It also will offer
cruise, hotel and rental car information.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman had no immediate comment on the ASTA
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents have long viewed airline moves onto the Internet
as designed to pull travelers away from agents and control the flow
of comparative price information. ASTA, which is primarily composed
of midsize and smaller agencies, has also bitterly protested cuts
in the commissions airlines pay to agents.
</P>
<P>
   In its complaint to the Justice Department, ASTA said the
airlines involved in the Web site are ``acting in unison and the
Web site has no apparent purpose but to destroy competition once
and for all and restrict the availability of independent sources of
information for the traveling public.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
