<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BOARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke board moves Daft, Stahl into top spots
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Doug Ivester passed the Big Red baton Thursday to Doug
Daft.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Ivester retired as chairman and chief executive
officer of Coca-Cola two months earlier than originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   Daft had actually been running the company since becoming
president and chief operating officer in early December after
Ivester stunned the world of Coke by announcing he would be
prematurely retiring at the April 19 shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Doug Daft clearly running the company, it must have been
uncomfortable and unrealistic for Doug Ivester still to have the
CEO title,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage
Digest. ``This move makes everything clean as a whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's board of directors finalized the transition at a
meeting Thursday. With Daft rising to the top spot, the board also
elected Jack Stahl president and chief operating officer two months
earlier than planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board of directors had asked me to stay on through April
to ensure a smooth management transition,'' Ivester said in a
statement. ``That transition is complete, and I am very confident
that the Coca-Cola Co. is in very good hands under the leadership
of Doug Daft and Jack Stahl.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester's retirement compensation package will be revealed in
the company's proxy statement, scheduled for release in early
March. Ivester, 52, will be a consultant to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, 56, has thoroughly reorganized the company since December,
decentralizing operations and announcing 6,000 job cuts, including
2,500 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to all employees Thursday, Daft said he wants the
company to develop ``qualities that will make us winners in the
marketplace. Nimble, agile, innovative, creative, responsive and
trusted _ these are the qualities that will drive our success in
the markets of today and tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But, so far, Daft's moves have not helped the company on Wall
Street. The stock has fallen nearly 24 percent since the December
announcement of the leadership change. On Thursday, it fell XXX to
close at XXX.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Bill Pecoriello of Sanford Bernstein believes the stock
will start making significant advances in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are completely focused right now on the
restructuring itself and not on the long-term benefits of the
restructuring,'' Pecoriello said. That mentality will change, he
predicted, once the market starts to concentrate on the likelihood
of strong earnings growth in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the board also increased the quarterly dividend to
17 cents a share, from 16 cents. The dividend is payable April 1 to
shareholders of record as of March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
