<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0197 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SUVS-GASPRICES-COX     02-17 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUVS-GASPRICES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUV owner to feel it at the pump
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    and Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ David Mullin just pumped $49 worth of gasoline into
his Chevrolet Suburban at the local Texaco station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am upset about these increases, but I realize I can't do
anything about them,'' said the salesman who fills the tank about
every five days. But he has no plans to trade the big sport-utility
vehicle in on something smaller and more fuel-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this car. It gives a good ride. It is safe. There is
room enough to haul things. I would keep it even if gas went up to
$3 a gallon _ but it does cut into my spendable income.''
</P>
<P>
   As the price of gasoline has climbed to record levels in the
past week, and up 40 cents a gallon overall since last year, owners
of big sport-utility vehicles don't plan to change vehicles. But
they might join other drivers in changing some driving habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will change the way they drive, not change their car.
It's smarter economically,'' said Jim Hall, vice president for
industry analysis with AutoPacific Group in Detroit. Those steps
might include making fewer or shorter trips and slowing down on the
interstate.
</P>
<P>
   In the current economic boom, people just don't care that much
about gasoline prices, said Mark Bowen, general manager for
Hyundai, Subaru and Oldsmobile for the Ed Voyles automotive group
of dealerships in Smyrna. ``The increase in gas prices hasn't hurt
big car sales, and it hasn't helped small cars either,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, gasoline prices have risen at a time when dealers have
high inventories of sport-utilities. Analyst Matt Darnell with J.D.
Power and Associates in Detroit doesn't blame gas, though. ``The
market is maturing, and the rate of sales growth is slower,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As more competitors enter the segment, as they have over the
past year, there will be fewer sales per model.
</P>
<P>
   People love the size, style and image of sport-utilities in
spite of what it costs to fill them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing eats gas, but I love it,'' declared Phyllis Crews
of Dunwoody, who spent $28.90 Wednesday topping off her 1999 Land
Rover. She paid $46,000 for the four-wheel-drive model with a V-8
engine. ``It is my favorite thing I have ever driven.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're driving vehicles that have sticker prices
approaching $50,000, an extra $10 to $20 a week for gas may not
seem like that much. Even at current prices, Hall noted, gasoline
is cheaper than Perrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers need to perceive constant high (gasoline) prices for
a long time'' before it influences their car-buying decisions, said
Darnell.
</P>
<P>
   He and other experts don't see prices staying at higher levels
for a long period.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that fuel prices will come down again, and they
will,'' said Hall. ``The (OPEC oil) cartel can't hold the prices up
for very long; some guy will break it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tori Young, whose family has run a service station at Mount
Vernon and Chamblee-Dunwoody roads since 1975, thinks the situation
will get worse before it gets better. ``People ask me every day
when prices are going back down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who drives a big sport-utility herself, said Amoco told
her to raise her price by 3 cents a gallon at midnight Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Young said, people still have to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
