<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0199 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DOW18-COX     02-17 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greenspan sees rate increases
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan removed any doubt
Thursday that interest rates on business and consumer loans are
headed higher.
</P>
<P>
   In his semiannual Humphrey-Hawkins testimony to Congress,
Greenspan said the U.S. economy is still growing too fast despite
four short-term interest rate increases since June.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little evidence that the American economy, which grew
more than 4 percent in 1999 and surged forward at an even faster
rate in the second half of the year, is slowing appreciably,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Fed will stick to a policy of ``incremental
interest-rate increases'' this year to avert inflation _ even
though, at the moment, ``inflation has remained largely
contained.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no `irrational exuberance' speech, but the message was
the same: there will be more rate hikes on the horizon,'' said
Prudential Securities analyst Bryan Piskorowski. He was alluding to
Greenspan's famous 1996 charge that speculation in stocks was a
threat to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of higher interest rates sent financial and other
interest-sensitive stocks lower, depressing the Dow Jones
industrial average. But the Nasdaq composite surged 2.7 percent to
its first finish over 4,500 as technology stocks continued to
advance on strong profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on the 30-year Treasury bond fell, benefiting, analysts
said, from the current low inflation environment and the prospect
of Fed protection against renewed inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's statements overshadowed another piece of good news:
the government's report that wholesale prices were unchanged in
January after rising 0.1 percent in December. The core rate _ minus
food and energy costs _ fell 0.2 percent vs. a rise of 0.1 percent
in December.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's testimony contained his strongest statements yet
that something more than a 1 percentage point increase in
short-term rates will be needed to restrain the economy and head
off an outbreak of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised the target rate for its overnight federal
funds to 5.75 percent in four quarter-percentage-point steps since
June. But the economy, measured by gross domestic product, rose
from a 3.7 percent annual rate in the first quarter to an estimated
5.8 percent in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has maintained all along that the economy must slow to
an annual growth of 2 percent to 2.5 percent to maintain job growth
without causing inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Fed was in this situation was 1994-1995, when
it raised the federal funds rate 3 percentage points to 6 percent.
Annualized GDP growth dropped in that same period to 0.8 percent
from 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the economy rallied briskly from the 1995 low and produced
four straight years of 4 percent annual growth through 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan reiterated his earlier explanation that the economy
expanded without serious inflation thanks to strong productivity
gains.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, corporate profit growth encouraged investment
in the stock market, where the wealth effect of the long-running
rise in share prices buoyed the economy by encouraging consumers to
spend beyond their annual incomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historical evidence suggests that perhaps 3 to 4 cents out of
every additional dollar of stock market wealth eventually is
reflected in increased consumer purchases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said it isn't necessary for stock prices to come down,
as long as the market grows ``no faster than household incomes.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest inflation threat, according to Greenspan, lies in
the tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point in the continuous reduction in the number of
available workers willing to take jobs . . . wage increases must
rise above even impressive gains in productivity,'' he said. ``This
would intensify inflationary pressures, or squeeze profit margins,
with either outcome capable of bringing our growing prosperity to
an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also warned that some of the other forces that held
consumer prices down in recent years are disappearing, including
foreign economic weakness that resulted in a flood of cheap
products into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong growth in foreign economic activity is expected to
continue this year, and, other things equal, the effect of the
previous appreciation of the dollar should wane, augmenting demand
on U.S. resources and lessening one source of downward pressure on
our prices,'' Greenspan explained.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
