u i BC-CLINTON-AFRICA-BOS &LR;      02-17 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AFRICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CITES AFRICA'S UNHERALDED ACHIEVEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After being greeted by the banging of ``talking
drums'' from Ghana and Gambia traditionally used to herald the
arrival of a great leader, President Clinton Thursday told 2,300
delegates attending the National Summit on Africa that Americans
``must choose, when it comes to Africa, to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly the plan of the delegates, including 50 from
Massachusetts, who will be spending the next three days here
working out a national agenda to advance African economic, health
and security interests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was warmly received in a large convention hall,
said Africa may suffer from a great number of crises, but it also
has achieved great accomplishments _ most of them overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen thousands of triumphs, large and small,'' he
said. ``I wish every American knew last year the world's fastest
growing economy was Mozambique. Botswana was second, Angola fourth.
. . . People know all about Africa's conflicts, but how many know
that thousands of African soldiers are trying to end those
conflicts as peacekeepers?''
</P>
<P>
   The conference is the result of five years of planning and
hundreds of community meetings around the country in hopes of
building an African lobby that would give the continent something
it has always lacked: clout in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts delegation, like those from the other 49
states, came carrying a plan of action promoting three strategies,
including campaigns aimed at defeating the AIDS pandemic; elevating
women's groups as key players on issues of peace and security; and
developing business relationships between Africa and the US East
Coast using models from US-Asian partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to start building the internal capacity nationally . .
. to move forward and implement our agenda,'' said Jemadai Kamara,
a University of Massachusetts professor heading the state
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Herman J. Cohen, former assistant secretary of state for African
affairs in the Bush administration, said in an interview that he
remembered when, in 1977, then-US Ambassador to the UN Andrew Young
told him that the US lobby for Africa ``needed to be able to get
5,000 faxes on the desks of every member of Congress whenever they
had an urgent issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never gotten to that point,'' said Cohen, who was
attending the conference. ``Will this summit bring it together? I
hope so. I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, delegates heard several stirring speeches, including one
by the chairman of WorldSpace Corp., Noah A. Samara, an Ethiopian
native who talked about the power of individuals and small groups
to ``change the state of affairs in our world.''
</P>
<P>
   Samara put up a satellite over Africa that gives direct audio
and multimedia broadcasting to hand-held receivers. He and a few
others raised over $1 billion in private capital toward a goal of
``an information-affluent African society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no fear to stand alone in my conviction that Africa
will overcome its problems,'' he said. ``The question for us is not
whether the inevitable will happen; but whether our fingerprint
will be among that small group of thoughtful, committed people who
actually changed the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The audience stood and cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clinton arrived, to strains of ``Hail to the Chief,''
followed by the banging of the drums.
</P>
<P>
   He called for more open markets to Africa, including passage of
an African trade bill now mired in a conference committee in
Congress; more debt relief atop a US $500 million commitment, which
will make only a small dent in the billions of dollars in debts
carried by African nations; spending more money on education;
fighting killer diseases of AIDS, tuberculosis and maleria; and
pushing African leaders to end the wars that currently afflict 11
of the continent's 54 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke at length on the AIDS crisis. He said, slowly,
``AIDS is going to reduce the life expectancy in Africa by 20
years. . . . In Africa, there are companies that are hiring two
employees for every job on the assumption that one of them will
die.''
</P>
<P>
   He said even if an AIDS vaccine were developed, that wouldn't
solve the problem. He said African leaders must emphasize
prevention to a far greater extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how hard or delicate or difficult this is,'' he
said. ``This is your children's lives we're talking about. . . . We
shouldn't pretend that we can give injections and work our way out
of this. We have to change behavior, attitudes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-CHILD-SOLDIERS-3     02-17 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CHILD-SOLDIERS-395&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. POSTS FULL-TIME ADVOCATES FOR CHILDREN AT LOCATIONS ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ For the first time in the history of its
international peacekeeping missions, the United Nations has begun
assigning full-time advocates of children to operations centers
abroad, the secretary-general's special representative on children
and conflict said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows increasingly horrific reports from a range of
U.N. agencies and private relief organization of the plight of
children in an era of brutal civil wars, and two years of lobbying
the Security Council by the secretary-general's representative,
Olara A. Otunnu, a former diplomat and ex-president of the
International Peace Academy in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, the first advocate for children was assigned to
Sierra Leone, where children as well as their parents have been
mutilated by a vicious rebel army that has also dragooned young
people into service as soldiers or virtual slaves. Two other child
advocates will take part in a peacekeeping operation in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   All three are officials from UNICEF, the U.N. children's fund.
Future appointments are to be drawn from a larger pool of eligible
child advocates from within and outside the United Nations,
including from private relief organizations, Otunnu said. All
peacekeeping operations will have one or more advisers on children.
</P>
<P>
   Otunnu, whose formal title is special representative of the
secretary-general for children and armed conflict, has insisted
that his child advocates be part of a regular peacekeeping staff
with a seat at the table of the leader, civilian or military, of
the mission in any country.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the protection and welfare of children to be taken
seriously, and not be marginalized, we must have within the central
political structure a representative, an advocate, whose charge is
making sure that the head of mission will have to coordinate these
issues,'' said Otunnu, a former foreign minister of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   He described the roles of the child protection officer as
adviser to the head of a mission, coordinator of all
child-assistance groups and strong advocate for whatever programs
are necessary to aid children, including education and relief
projects to deal with not only physical problems but also mental
trauma. Child advocates have the power to report violations against
children by U.N. troops and other officials.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Sierra Leone, the first child advocate, Bituin Gonzales of
the Philippines, has begun to look at ways to help traumatized and
toughened former child soldiers get special educational attention.
She has also explored the use of local radio to announce and
promote her work, she said in messages to Otunnu.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Otunnu is also using electronic media to spread the
word about his projects. He has arranged videoconferencing with
schools in the metropolitan area to tell American children about
the hardships and suffering of children abroad. He said that he
hopes to set up a network of children, parents and teachers here
and abroad to keep the issue alive.
</P>
<P>
   Otunnu said that in a world of satellite television, public
opinion matters to even the roughest rebel armies, who are
circumspect in admitting to what they do to children when he meets
their leaders on his frequent trips to war zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a changing normative mood worldwide, he said. ``Some
things are unacceptable. Some things are beyond the pale. None of
these actors, whether they are insurgencies or the state, are
outside the orbit of international influence. They are all touched
in a major way by international public opinion; they feel it.
Tomorrow they know that if they want to be Mr. President or Mr.
Prime Minister at some level international acceptance and
legitimacy matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Otunnu, who has met government officials and rebel leaders
involved in wars in Sri Lanka, Somalia, Sudan, Congo, Sierra Leone
and Colombia, is struck by the dissonance between their lofty
statements of their aims and the brutality around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have a vision of a better society,'' he said. ``I
tell them, I take you at your word. But if this is you vision of
your society, how could you achieve this by what you're doing now,
by destroying the children?''
</P>
<P>
   Otunnu, who grew up in Uganda but is now a citizen of the Ivory
Coast, said that it doesn't go very far to wave international
conventions at combatants in a civil war, however important
treaties are. Those, he said, are only one of two ``pillars of
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other pillar, which we must never, ever forget, speaks
directly with a resonance to most people around the world, and that
is what is grown on the local soil,'' he said. ``We must reach out
and recognize and strengthen the traditional norms that provided
for the protection of children and women - the taboos, the
injunctions. For many of these people that grabs them, that calls
them to order.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in the society in which I grew up, not in any of the
societies I have been visiting, which have been torn asunder by
war, was war traditionally a free for all,'' he said. Chiefs,
elders and religious leaders know this, he added, and they need
support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
