<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-BUSH (Greenville, S.C.) _ John McCain appeals to
Democrats and independents to join Republicans to propel him to
victory in Saturday's GOP primary. Meanwhile, George W. Bush
accuses McCain of riding a ``high horse on a low road'' by
continuing to distribute a brochure that says Bush's tax cut plan
would harm Social Security. The latest polls show the two in a
statistical dead heat with turnout the likely determining factor.
By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-REFORM (Columbia, S.C.) _ John McCain's ``national
crusade,'' as he grandly styles his campaign for the Republican
presidential nomination, is a multifront battle that seeks more
than just capturing the White House. McCain is fighting not only
George W. Bush but also the whole Republican establishment,
including the party hierarchy and GOP leadership in Congress. By
CRAGG HINES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SPEECH (Conway, S.C.) _ Start with a joke about a woman who
voted for someone else, add dollops of ``what's in my heart'' and
views on education, taxes and national security, and you get the
standard stump speech by Texas Gov. George W. Bush. The speech,
repeated over and over at rallies all week across South Carolina,
is a variety-pack of soft humor, applause lines and attempts to
define differences between him and Republican rival John McCain. By
DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-VIETNAM (Greenville, S.C.) _ John McCain once said of his
wartime captors in Vietnam: ``I hate those gooks and I always
will.'' The Republican presidential hopeful says he was only
referring to those individuals who held him captive and tortured
him _ not the Vietnamese people. Also, McCain says he is
``unstoppable'' if he wins South Carolina. By CLAY ROBISON and R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-UNIONS (New Orleans) _ With organized labor expected to
flex its muscle on his behalf in the upcoming presidential
primaries, Al Gore reassures union leaders he will fight for them
on such thorny topics as trade pacts with China. AFL-CIO leaders
emerged from a meeting with the vice president convinced that Gore
would place more safeguards for labor and the environment in trade
pacts than President Clinton has. By BENNET ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
