   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FED-GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan signals the likelihood of more interest rate hikes ahead
as the central bank tries to cool down a super-charged U.S.
economy. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MISTAKES (Washington) _ Saying she was ``shocked'' to
learn that as many 98,000 Americans die each year from mistakes
made by hospitals and doctors, Rep. Constance Morella, R-Md.,
introduces legislation aimed at encouraging hospitals to share
information about their errors. She says the aim is to help prevent
other institutions from making the same mistakes. By MARK HELM.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WATER-RATIONING (Galveston, Texas) _ Emergency water rationing
was ordered after three valves in the city's antiquated water
system broke, reducing water pressure to Galveston Island's most
populous areas. Mandatory rationing, including a ban on watering
lawns, washing cars and filling swimming pools, could be in effect
through the weekend or beyond, officials said. By KEVIN MORAN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WATER-MEXICO (McAllen, Texas) _ A regional water district on the
Texas border claims Mexico has been withholding water it is
required to release into the Rio Grande. Under a 1992 treaty
related to the building of two new dams, the United States and
Mexico are required to release a certain amount of water. Texas
officials claim Mexico has been cheating, even as Texas has been
suffering through a drought. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-EROS (Undated) _ Scientists say Eros, the Valentine's Day
asteroid, appears to be a fragment from a planet. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
