<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ HITS RECORD BUT `OLD ECONOMY' STOCKS GO NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FED-GREENSPAN, FED-GREENSPAN-REACT) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shrugging off the ever more likely prospect of
additional interest rate increases this spring, technology stocks
powered the Nasdaq market to a record Thursday as turnover surged
past 2 billion shares for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index jumped 121.27 points, or 2.74
percent, to 4,548.92.
</P>
<P>
   However, other stocks, particularly those of the so-called Old
Economy, languished once again, with the Dow Jones industrial
average losing 46.84 points, or 0.44 percent, to 10,514.57, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index barely managing to stay in
positive territory, rising 0.59, or 0.04 percent, to 1,388.26.
</P>
<P>
   The latest government report of minimal inflation spurred a
general early rally but Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, soon dampened sentiment with an unusually direct warning
that higher rates would be needed to slow an overheated economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once, I thought I understood what he was saying _ that he
will continue to increase interest rates until job creation slows
down,'' said Robert Bloom, president of Friends, Ivory &AMP; Sime, an
investment management company. As a result, Bloom added, stocks are
now on the defensive and 2000 is ``a year to try to preserve
gains.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip index, which had been up more than 110 points,
swung to a loss of nearly 107 points at midday and then clawed back
part way in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart and other retailers were once again prominent
casualties; the giant discounter dropping 4 3/8, to 48 3/8, 31
percent below its Dec. 31 peak. Gap lost 6 7/8, to 42 1/8, and
American Eagle Outfitters 4 15/16, to 20 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks were also weak, especially American Express,
which sank 5 29/32, to 147 15/16, and was the biggest factor in the
Dow's decline. Bank of New York, at the center of a
money-laundering case, fell 2 7/16, to 35 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   But technology, both in the Nasdaq and the small-cap Russell
2000 _ the latter up 1.95 percent, to a second consecutive record _
was largely untouched by concern over how hard rising rates, when
they kick in, will brake the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, introducing Windows 2000, climbed 2, to 99 5/8;
Intel, 2 13/16, to 110; Qualcomm, 8 1/8, to 130; Cisco Systems, 3
21/64, to 130 1/2; Juniper Networks, 20 3/4, to 241 1/4; and eBay 4
9/16, to 145 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick, though, skidded a second day as the online
advertising company faced a federal investigation into its
collection of data on Internet users. The shares fell 15 3/4, to 90
3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision Systems, the top operator in the New York City area,
fell 2 5/8, to 68 3/8, after reporting a widened fourth-quarter
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Rite Aid, facing a fraud investigation, fell 1/2, to 6 5/8, down
from more than 45 a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
