<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-EARNHARDT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVROLETS `FIGHTING A LOSING BATTLE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ In a shocking development, Dale Earnhardt
ended the Twin 125 qualifying races whining instead of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's streak of 10 consecutive qualifying victories came
to an unceremonious end as he finished 11th in his heat yesterday.
The seven-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion claims he never had a
chance, because of Chevrolet's alleged disadvantage that is
compounded by NASCAR's new shock rule.
</P>
<P>
   Ford drivers Bill Elliott and Ricky Rudd won yesterday's races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't worried about the streak,'' Earnhardt said. ``That's
the worst racing I've seen at Daytona in a long, long time. They
took NASCAR Winston Cup racing and made it some of the sorriest
racing. They took the racing out of the drivers' and the crews'
hands. We can't adjust. We can't make our cars drive like we want.
They just killed the racing at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   ``[NASCAR founder] Mr. Bill France Sr. probably rolled over in
his grave if he seen that. This is a joke to have to race like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt started ninth and moved up as high as sixth before
dropping back to 11th. He had the second-best finish among
Chevrolets in his 28-car qualifier, but in the second qualifier,
Earnhardt's teammate, Mike Skinner, finished second in a Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt will start 21st Sunday, his worst starting position in
the Daytona 500 since 1984. After NASCAR chief operating officer
Mike Helton announced that the ruling body will not implement rules
changes between now and then, Earnhardt's GM Goodwrench team
counted itself out of Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to win the Daytona 500,'' team owner Richard
Childress said, ``and we absolutely don't have a chance. No chance.
It'd be like putting my grandson in there fighting Muhammad Ali in
Ali's young days. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just disappointed they let this thing get this far out of
hand. We spend millions of dollars trying to race, and they've let
this thing get so far out of hand that the competition isn't good.
The show isn't good.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's new shock and spring rules were intended to smooth the
ride for drivers and slow the cars by eliminating custom-made
shocks at the series' restrictor-plate races. At Daytona and
Talladega, teams are required to use NASCAR-issued shocks and a
specific spring rate.
</P>
<P>
   Crew chiefs complain that the new shocks package affects their
ability to adjust their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt said he had a push in his car, because the new shocks
create an air lift in the front end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've basically got what we're dealt, and it's pretty hard to
get around it,'' said Kevin Hamlin, Earnhardt's crew chief. ``Their
cars [Fords] don't push as bad, because they have a little more
downforce in the nose it seems like. ... We're just kind of
fighting a losing battle right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt lost twice yesterday. His streak ended, and he failed
to convince NASCAR officials that rules changes are necessary for a
competitive race Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dale Earnhardt is driving the car, we've got a chance to
win anytime,'' Hamlin said. ``But he can't do but so much. We have
to give him something he can drive in. We are kind of at the end of
our barrel of tricks right now.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
