<HEADER>
A0212 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-17 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHO WANTS TO BE A VOTER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Station WTAT-TV scored a big coup on the
evening news this week when its resident psychic announced the
winner of the upcoming presidential primary. Somewhere between a
story about a fire and a report on child molestation, Lou Wright
(``Elvis' personal psychic'') took viewer calls and delivered
predictions about financial windfalls and the imminent arrival of
curly-haired suitors before raising her thumbs and revealing that
``it's McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an excellent example of the Fox Network approach to news
gathering _ low-cost, to the point and celebrity-related. After
all, if you want people to pay attention to public affairs, you
need creative packaging. This is the same theory that persuaded a
TV station in Russia to have its newscaster do a striptease while
she read the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But in South Carolina, we are once again discovering that what
American voters actually want is real elections, with decent
candidates and competition and a chance to influence the outcome.
People here are so stunned and excited about their primary, you'd
think it involved the Nasdaq, or women vying for the right to marry
a total stranger on network television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics isn't usually a hot-button issue in this market,''
said Don Feldman, the WTAT news director, between attempts to
explain that Wright is not a central feature in his operation.
``I've never seen this much interest.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is the hot ticket of the moment, but he's relatively
unchanged by his celebrity. For better or worse, he's set in his
ways, with three basic notes _ ironic humor, intense sincerity and
a fumbling, testy evasion that comes up whenever he's feeling
cornered. When he started running for president, McCain had a stump
speech he delivered so badly the staff couldn't find any good
moments to put in the TV ads. But now he basically gives a
collection of his answers to the questions he heard in New
Hampshire, and it works pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, however, is adaptive as all get-out, and since
his New Hampshire debacle he's taken on McCain's coloration. He now
promises audiences never to tell a lie, talks about campaign
finance reform and portrays himself as the anti-establishment
outsider, an especially tricky move for a candidate seen so
frequently in the company of Strom Thurmond. ``I just want to
remind you I'm a person who's coming in with a record of reform,''
he told a crowd in Beaufort, in case they had not noticed the huge
``REFORMER WITH RESULTS'' banner hanging behind him. He even
casually mentions that he once flew jets for the Air Force,
although failing to add that said flying occurred in the Texas
National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken up McCain's town-meeting format with a vengeance,
and is actually very good at it, sounding more human and
unprogrammed. ``I don't know about the South Carolina lynching
law,'' he told a woman who asked a rather incoherent question about
racial issues. ``But I can't imagine it's a good law, so I don't
support it if it is a law.''
</P>
<P>
   After all this mutation, the one clear distinction that voters
can still grab hold of is taxes, where Bush favors a huge,
Reaganesque cut that gives big breaks to the wealthy. But the
voters seem to prefer McCain's more modest program targeted toward
the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Bush is painting himself as a profile in courage, a
man driven by principle to force a huge tax break down the
electorate's throat. ``They say the polls don't show people want a
tax cut,'' he told a well-heeled crowd in Hilton Head. ``I don't
care about the polls. I care about what's right.'' Since Bush never
refers to the wealthy as the wealthy (think ``entrepreneur'') he
can describe his tax break for rich people in terms that make him
sound like Pitchfork Ben Tillman. ``Cut taxes for everyone! Not the
favored few!'' he cried to a blue-collar crowd at a Beaufort youth
center. The audience responded enthusiastically, possibly unaware
they were the ``favored few'' in question.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush doesn't win on Saturday, I foresee him campaigning in
the Michigan primary with a comb-over of thinning gray hair. He
will take questions for seven or eight hours every night, and then
invite voters to watch him flog the Republican congressional
leadership at a pillar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
