<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-CONSUL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH CONSUL ISSUE FANS AUSTRIA DEBATE IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BENJAMIN WALLACE-WELLS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The lushly appointed downtown offices of the Austrian
consulate are open from 11-1 three days a week, but the consul
general can't see many visitors then because he is praying. And in
the reception area there is a neat array of black kippahs so
visitors can cover their heads before meeting the consul.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange twist that has drawn outrage from some local Jewish
leaders, Austria's honorary consul to New England happens to be a
rabbi and publisher of the region's leading Jewish newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Yitzchok A. Korff, a Hasidic with a congregation in Newton
who has a reputation for unorthodox political views, is the local
representative of a country whose new government has been condemned
by the United States, the European Union, Israel, and a host of
Jewish organizations worldwide for the anti-immigrant views and
past pro-Nazi comments made by one of its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Some local Jewish leaders say they can not understand how a
learned Jewish cleric could associate with a nation they believe
has not come to grips with its own Nazi past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germany has gone through 55 years of very deep acknowledgement
of its history,'' said Martin Kaplan, a Boston attorney and a
nationally-known Jewish leader. ``Austria hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Korff, who also is an attorney and holds a doctorate degree
in international relations, believes it would be foolish to cut off
ties with Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``One does not educate, sensitize others to issues, or resolve
differences by removing oneself, building walls, or cutting off
communication,'' Korff said in written responses to questions
submitted by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Korff was asked by Austria's ambassador to the United States to
become honorary consul in 1987. His predecessor, Edward
Masterman,had resigned in protest when Kurt Waldheim, who served in
the Nazi party, was elected President.
</P>
<P>
   Several local Jewish leaders believe the participation of the
far-right Freedom Party in Austria's governing coalition shows the
country tolerates prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austria pretends to be the first victim of Nazi Germany when
perhaps it would be more accurate to call Austria Nazi Germany's
first collaborator,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Lawrence Lowenthal, Executive Director of the American
Jewish Committee's Boston chapter: ``To this day I don't understand
why Rabbi Korff agreed to be the Austrian consul to Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But Korff says Austria's recent behavior towards Jews,
particularly its welcoming of Jewish refugees from the former
Soviet Union, ought to weigh heavier in public opinion than events
of half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Post-war Austria has consistently and repeatedly been of
assistance and support to Jews and the Jewish community in Austria
and internationally,'' Korff said, ``from nurturing and aid to the
Austrian Jewish Community and its institutions to serving as a
welcome respite and refuge for thousands upon thousands of Jews
from the former Eastern Bloc and the Soviet Union on their way to
settling in Israel, the United States, and other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Sarna, chair of the Near Eastern and Judaic Studies
departments at Brandeis University, says there has been a
historically close relationship between Jews and Austria that
predates the Nazi era and which might help explain Korff's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly true that in the Austro-Hungarian empire under
(Emperor) Franz Joseph, Hasidim thrived,'' Sarna said. ``Franz
Joseph, unlike Tsar Nicholas of Russia, was seen as highly
benevolent. Long after his death, there were still Austrian Jews in
America who celebrated his birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   That Korff would be caught up in part of what has become a major
international firestorm is not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   He hails from a long line of locally controversial Hasidic
rabbis. His grandfather Jacob I. Korff, worked on a proposal to
``buy'' Jews from the Nazis during the Holocaust by getting
American organizations to give money to Nazi Germany in exchange
for the safe return of Jewish concentration camp prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   His uncle, Baruch Korff, made headlines during the Watergate
crisis for defending President Nixon against calls for his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Y.A. Korff was a prominent Boston attorney who was married to
the daughter of Sumner Redstone, the chief executive of Viacom. But
in 1992 he divorced, reconnected with his religious roots and
became a full-time Hasidic rabbi. The Hasidim are among the most
Orthodox of Jewish denominations.
</P>
<P>
   Korff maintains that his decision to stay on as Austria's
diplomatic liaison to Boston is consistent with his own religious
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Representing Austria) is consistent with our primary calling
as rabbi and with the philosophy of open communication and outreach
that is a hallmark of our Jewish heritage,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
