<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE </SLUG>
 HORSE RACING REPORT-TEX 
Derby bets starting to come earlier 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe some people will argue that horse racing isn't a sport _
or not much of one compared to football, basketball or baseball _
but anyone who has handicapped a race knows there aren't many games
as great as this one.
</P>
<P>
   We know this to be true because it's a lot easier to regain your
temper while tearing up a losing mutuel ticket than it is after you
tried to wrap a 5-iron around a tree trunk. And there's a remote
chance that you can outsmart your 8 year old at the track but never
at his home computer game.
</P>
<P>
   The horse racing game is great, and it gets better at this time
of year. Believe it or not, there are a few imaginative types
involved in horse racing. They are the ones who presented the
Kentucky Derby Future Wager last year.
</P>
<P>
   Another round of investing in largely unproven 3 year olds
started when this year's Future Wager started yesterday at Lone
Star Park at Grand Prairie and racetracks in more than 20 other
states.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're spending any amount of time in the Cincinnati
area, you can play the ``Road to the Derby Challenge'' at Turfway
Park. It really took a lot of imagination to figure this one out:
Guess the winners of 23 key Kentucky Derby prep races and the
winner gets $5,000, second place a trip to the Belmont Stakes and
third place a trip to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Someone ought to do some skull work on this one and figure out a
way to put it on the Internet, or at the hometown racetrack at
least, so everyone can play.
</P>
<P>
   These games add to the interest in the Triple Crown series.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waiting for the major prep races to find the
contenders and waiting for the Derby to talk about them,
handicappers are searching out maiden races and allowance events to
find live horses even before the prep races start.
</P>
<P>
   Those imaginative guys with the Derby Future Wager ought to do
the same thing. There are at least three horses that will be a drag
to this wagering pool.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Chief Seattle ought not to worry if he can make it
to the Derby: He has to make it out of Dubai first. Mull Of Kintyre
only has raced in the United States once. Scottish Halo is trying
to stay sound and still hasn't raced this year.
</P>
<P>
   Horses such as Country Only (winner of the Whirlaway at
Aqueduct), Un Fino Vino (an honest, if unsensational type who's an
allowance winner at Gulfstream) and either Rupert Herd or
Grundlefoot (they race at Gulfstream tomorrow) would be more
compelling betting interests at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe people thought that the person who paid for the $10,000
bet on the field in the opening moments of the Future Wager last
year was a knucklehead, beating down his odds before things got
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   But the only knuckleheads turned out to be the rest of us who
could not figure out the math and see that a group of more than 300
horses in the field was a big overlay against 23
moderately-talented horses listed as individual betting interests
in each of the pools.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on the field being overlooked again this year.
LONE STAR RECRUITS
</P>
<P>
   Applications for stalls at the Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie
thoroughbred season are not due until March 1, but it looks if
there is plenty of interest despite competition from the re-opening
of Arlington International Racecourse. Jeanette Hughes, Lone Star's
assistant racing secretary, said she expects requests for a full
allotment from trainers Steve Asmussen (defending champion trainer
at Lone Star), Mike Stidham (current leader at Fair Grounds) and
Cole Norman (defending champ at Louisiana Downs).
</P>
<P>
   Hughes also said Mike Pegram, owner of Real Quiet,
Silverbulletday and Captain Steve, could have at least 10
``second-string'' horses stabled at Lone Star in the name of
trainer Mike Puhich. Hughes said she has not been contacted by Hall
of Fame trainer Jack Van Berg, who indicated interest last year in
coming to Lone Star. RISEN STAR PROBABLES
</P>
<P>
   Fair Grounds stakes coordinator Brent Seward said the field for
Sunday's $125,000 Risen Star Stakes could include Exchange Rate,
Snuck In, Proper Man, Ifitstobeitsuptome, Doctor Mike and Peninsula
in addition to LeComte Stakes 1-2 finishers Noble Ruler and Mighty.
</P>
<P>
   Chilukki, last year's champion 2-year-old filly for owner Bob
and Janice McNair of Houston, is expected to make her debut as a 3
year old tomorrow in the Grade III Davona Dale Stakes at Fair
Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The $500,000 New Orleans Handicap on March 5 could attract
either Behrens or Pleasant Breeze, Elaborate, Ecton Park,
Temperance Time and Allen's Oop. $51K BET THIS TIME
</P>
<P>
   The publicity office at Churchill Downs said that the same
person who paid for a $10,000 bet on the field on opening day of
the Kentucky Derby Future Wager last year at Lone Star Park at
Grand Prairie made a $51,000 bet on the Derby Future field
yesterday at Churchill's Sports Spectrum in Louisville, Ky. An
independent source confirmed it was the same person.
</P>
<P>
   The gambler told track officials he did not wish to be
identified. If it's the same person _ sources identify him as a
professional horseplayer based in Las Vegas _ he took all his
winnings and let it ride. His $10,000 investment last year and
winnings totaled $51,000. DUBAI OBSTACLE MOVED REAL QUIET TO THE
FARM
</P>
<P>
   The decision this week to retire 1998 Kentucky Derby champion
Real Quiet is not because he's injured and can't race again. It's
simply another situation which made more economic sense for his
owners to send him to the breeding shed rather than keep him at the
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet recovered from a leg injury he suffered last year,
and he exercised the past month over the track in Southern
California. He was sound, but he wasn't progressing in his fitness
quickly enough to make the trip overseas for the Dubai World Cup on
March 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``That softened me up right there,'' owner Mike Pegram said.
``You're missing out on a $6 million race.''
</P>
<P>
   So rather than chase after smaller races and have no cinch of
winning substantial purse money, Pegram agreed to the retirement in
which Real Quiet can generate more than $2 million guaranteed this
year through breeding rights. Real Quiet is at the new Vinery Farm
located outside of Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   As for one of his other high-profile horses, Pegram said he
would entertain the thought of one day breeding Silverbulletday
(she's by the Deputy Minister stallion Silver Deputy and out of a
Tom Rolfe mare) to Real Quiet (by the Fappiano horse Quiet American
and out of a Believe It mare).
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I can get another couple of years of enjoyment out
of Silverbulletday at the races before she's retired,'' Pegram
said, adding that there's a remote chance she will return to the
races in the $500,000 Apple Blossom Handicap on April 9 at Oaklawn
Park before running in the $250,000 Louisville Breeders' Cup
Handicap on Kentucky Oaks Day at Churchill Downs. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
