<HEADLINE>
BRITISH ENVOY TO ULSTER STYMIED OVER STALEMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Peter Mandelson, the secretary of state for Northern
Ireland, is praised as brilliant, panned as vainglorious, and
regarded by admirers and critics alike as one of Britain's most
effective politicians, but even he seemed at a loss Thursday as he
pondered how to break the latest stalemate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he proposed to rescue a process that has ground to a
halt, yet again, over the vexing question of what to do with the
Irish Republican Army's hidden arsenal, Mandelson shook his head
and replied candidly, ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his office here, above the River Thames,
Mandelson admitted he had no plan to persuade the IRA to make a
firm commitment to disarm or persuade the Ulster Unionists to drop
their insistence on it. But he said that unless a way was found
around the impasse in the next two or three weeks, the political
vacuum could be filled by extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people need to draw a breath. But if we allow this
stalemate to drift on, it will deteriorate,'' he said.
``Hard-liners on both sides will be emboldened.''
</P>
<P>
   While some have suggested ditching Sinn Fein, the political wing
of the IRA, and trying to move the process forward without the
republican movement, Mandelson dismissed that idea outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's realistic,'' he said when asked if Sinn
Fein could be excluded if there is no progress on IRA disarmament.
``The great thing about the (Northern Ireland) assembly is that
it's inclusive. That's the only way this is going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has he considered asking the White House to bar Sinn Fein
officials from traveling to the United States, as some have called
for, a sanction that could damage Sinn Fein's fundraising and its
newfound status as a mainstream political party.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a matter for the US administration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate British political operative, Mandelson has met his
match in trying to keep the peace process on the rails. While both
loved and loathed, he is universally respected for his political
skills, which some have described as visionary, others as
Machiavellian.
</P>
<P>
   He may be Prime Minister Tony Blair's most valued cabinet
member, having orchestrated the British Labor Party's landslide
victory in 1997 by marginalizing the party's socialist left wing
and compromising on longheld principles to gain power. So
indispensable is he considered by Blair that Mandelson spent less
than a year in the wilderness after he was forced to resign as the
cabinet's trade secretary in December 1998 for taking a personal
loan from a man whose business his office was supposed to monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Mandelson took over the Northern Ireland portfolio
from Mo Mowlam, the most popular member of Blair's cabinet. While
some say Mowlam was dumped for refusing to take a transfer a few
months before, and because unionists in Northern Ireland had no
faith in her, Blair's aides say Mandelson was brought in because
his considerable political skills were needed to get the Good
Friday Agreement of 1998 fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   But last Friday, in what was the biggest and most scrutinized
decision of his political career, Mandelson pulled the plug on the
power-sharing assembly that was the cornerstone of the new
political institutions that are supposed to transform Northern
Ireland into an equitable, stable, peaceful democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish government said it believed a last-minute pledge from
the IRA to eventually put its weapons ``beyond use'' was enough of
a concession to avert a suspension. Mandelson, however, said the
IRA's pledge was too vague to prevent the Ulster Unionists, who
represent most Protestants, from walking out, collapsing the
assembly. He said Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble's position
was untenable. For Mandelson, suspension was the least worst
option.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had not done as I did, we would not have institutions
worth reviving,'' he said. ``The cross-community support would have
collapsed. Trimble would have resigned, or he would have been
sacked. What the IRA said was a significant change, but it was not
a sea change.''
</P>
<P>
   His decision led the IRA to break off contact with the
international commission overseeing the disarming of paramilitary
groups, and led to charges that he was taking the unionist side,
abandoning Britain's role as honest broker in Northern Ireland,
where it insists it has no economic, military, or strategic
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Even the liberal British press has accused Mandelson of adopting
the unionist line. Mandelson denies he is biased toward unionists,
and privately, British officials insist the Irish position is
closer to Mandelson's, but that they understand the Irish have to
play to a constituency that does not want to see its government
unquestioningly following the British line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish share the same analysis,'' said a senior British
official. ``We created the breathing space so the Irish government
could work with Sinn Fein to get a change of heart on the IRA's
part. Because of the Irish government's work, the IRA did move, but
they did not move enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said he has resigned himself to the attacks that have
followed his decision to suspend the power-sharing assembly..
</P>
<P>
   ``As secretary of state, I know that I earn my salary by
spending half my time as a punch bag and the other half as a
scapegoat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is also resigned to how much he can do to bridge the yawning
gap of mistrust between unionists and republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can encourage, cajole, facilitate, and occasionally punish,
but I can't force them to do anything. I can't force the unionists
to stay in the assembly, as some have suggested,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As they try to find a way out of the impasse, some have urged
the British government to negotiate directly with the IRA. But a
senior British official said that London officials were told by
Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator, that the IRA would
not discuss disarming with the British ``in a million years.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the IRA would ever disarm, Mandelson said,
``I don't know. And that is the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
