<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MY KINDA TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Replace double parentheses (()) with brackets.) 
(jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boy, I feel better now. The leading Internet execs met with the
president at the White House Tuesday and they all agreed that
despite the recent hacker attacks that disrupted major Web sites,
there was no need for any government regulation or taxation of
cyberspace. When George W. Bush and John McCain were asked about
this they both said: Hands off the Net _ we've got to nurture this
new baby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I agree. In fact I think this hands-off approach is such a good
idea I and my neighbors are trying it in our town. Why should
cyberspace have all the fun? We formed ``the Bethesda
Government-Free and Tax-Free Zone.'' It includes everyone who lives
in a very distinct space _ the 20817 ZIP code _ and here's what
happened: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, we got our congresswoman to arrange a three-year
moratorium on any taxation, police or government regulation in the
20817 area. This has already paid enormous dividends. Because
Montgomery Mall shopping center, the main mall in Bethesda, doesn't
have to charge sales tax anymore, we now have people coming from
Virginia, Baltimore, even Philadelphia, just to shop there.
</P>
<P>
   All the e-commerce retailers, like Buy.com, are complaining to
the federal government about the fact that neither Montgomery Mall
nor any of the stores in Bethesda have to charge sales tax so
people can just shop there tax-free _ while the e-commerce
retailers have to pay UPS and FedEx to deliver their goods to your
door. But our mayor, who gets paid in stock options instead of from
tax revenues, told the dot-coms: ``Too bad. We've got an experiment
going in Bethesda and we're gonna nurture it. So keep your hands
off.`` &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing we Bethesdans have had to get used to is the
fact that when we declared our government-free zone, window shades
were banned. So now all kinds of people passing by your house can
peer in and see your eating habits, shopping habits, sexual
predilections, and then sell that information to marketing
companies, unimpeded. When people asked why they couldn't have
window shades in Bethesda, the companies, who benefit most from
this, said, ``That's just how it is and that's how it always must
be. No one created Bethesda. It just happened. So get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But we tell everyone who wants to move here: Don't worry. We're
a self-regulating community. Your private information is safe with
us. You don't need any government here. Our motto is:
``Suburbanites Just Wanna Be Free.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We also tell them that although companies dominate here, we
never have to worry about being overwhelmed by advertisers.
Precisely because firms can peer into our houses unimpeded, and
they know exactly what all our personal habits are, we only receive
advertising tailored exactly to our desires. There's no more junk
mail. Our companies know from examining our credit-card slips
exactly which car we are likely to buy next and where we are most
likely to vacation, and they get exactly the right marketer to our
doors.
</P>
<P>
   You can't imagine the creative new businesses our little
government-free zone has nurtured. Some guy even wrote about one of
our start-ups in The New York Times: It sells $1 bills for 90
cents. It's called IOU. It hasn't made money yet, but you should
see its market cap! You need a special place to nurture innovative
firms like that.
</P>
<P>
   Now people do ask whether it isn't sort of scary living in a
distinct place with no government, but we tell them that rules and
regulations will just emerge in Bethesda spontaneously from among
the citizens. We're all good people here. Pioneers, actually. No
one wears a suit or tie. Sure, occasionally someone abuses your
freedom _ reading your mail, libeling you or spreading scurrilous
rumors like McDonald's uses mad-cow beef for its burgers. But
that's life on the frontier. If you don't like it, move to Chevy
Chase. Because if you regulate us, or tax us, you'll kill us. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even Commerce Secretary William Daley agrees. Tuesday he said,
``It is not about the government regulating this or taking steps or
actions that would at all impede ((Bethesda)), because, of course,
((Bethesda)) is the dynamic engine that is driving our economy
today and we must keep that open.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, we've been so successful, we've thought of changing our
name. Got to get away from the name Bethesda. Sounds too old. Comes
from the Bible. I've thought of something more exotic. Maybe
``Amazon'' or ``Yahoo.'' But my wife says we should go for
something big and techie-sounding, something like ``The Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
