<SLUG> BC-BUSH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survey: Bushs' place in polls uncertain
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN, Mich. _ Former President George Bush campaigned in
Michigan on Thursday for his son George W. Bush as a new poll
showed the Texas governor leading Arizona Sen. John McCain among
Republican voters, but trailing when Democrats and independents are
included.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, released by WDIV-TV of Detroit, showed Bush leading 53
percent to 35 percent when only likely Republican voters were
counted.
</P>
<P>
   However, among all likely voters in next Tuesday's Republican
presidential primary, McCain held a 46 percent to 38 percent lead.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and independents can vote in Michigan's primary, as
they can Saturday in South Carolina and as they did earlier in New
Hampshire, where McCain defeated Bush by 18 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The survey included 500 people statewide and has a margin of
error of 4.5 percent, WDIV officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush received a hero's welcome here at the
Ukrainian Cultural Center in Warren, just northeast of Detroit,
where a crowd of 200 turned out.
</P>
<P>
   He also made campaign stops in Wayne, another Detroit suburb,
and in Flint, 60 miles north of here, the city where General Motors
was born. Today, he is to campaign in Midland.
</P>
<P>
   While not directly knocking McCain, the former president said it
is his son who, as governor of Texas, has been the real reformer in
a wide array of areas including juvenile justice, education, taxes
and tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush told the crowd the Michigan primary is
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our son is involved against a good man in a very close race,
but I believe if he can come in, with your support, into Michigan
next Tuesday and win, I would think that that would guarantee that
George W. Bush would be the next Republican nominee for
president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is in the center of Macomb County, a primary location of
the so-called ``Reagan Democrats'' who helped Republican Ronald
Reagan win two terms as president and Bush win in 1988 before he
lost to Democrat Bill Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
