A0222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-BOYS18-COX     02-17 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOYS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riveting performances transcend painful story of `Boys'
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Hilary Swank and Chloe Sevigny both earned
well-deserved Academy Award nominations this week for their
performances in Kimberly Peirce's riveting true-life drama, ``Boys
Don't Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Swank is considered the favorite for the best actress Oscar,
having won the lion's share of critics prizes and a Golden Globe
Award for her convincing turn as Brandon Teena, a woman who lived
her brief life as a man.
</P>
<P>
   Peirce's feature debut was passed over for best picture and
director nominations, presumably because the heavy drama was too
tough for Academy voters. Granted, the brutal climax is difficult
to endure, but ``Boys Don't Cry'' is one of the year's most
powerful and unforgettable films.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``In Cold Blood,'' ``Badlands'' and ``The Executioner's
Song,'' from which Peirce drew inspiration, it's a fact-based tale
of murder involving young drifters in the rural Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Teena was born Teena Brandon in Lincoln, Neb. She does
not consider herself a lesbian, although her sexual desire is
directed at other women. Saving her money for a sex-change
operation, Teena cuts her hair short, stuffs a sock down her jeans
and effectively passes herself off as a handsome, charismatic young
man named Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   Exposed in Lincoln, where he awaits a court date for forgery and
theft, Brandon makes his way to the small town of Falls City. There
he finds the love and acceptance he seeks, albeit unwitting, from a
rough but endearing group of new friends.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-partying crew includes ex-cons John Lotter (Peter
Sarsgaard) and Thomas Nissen (Brendan Sexton III) and blue-collar
beauty Lana Tisdel (Sevigny).
</P>
<P>
   Peirce warmly depicts Brandon's bonding with the group, which
includes drunken ``bumper skiing'' on the back of a speeding pickup
truck, as well as his tender courtship of Lana. A rivalry for
Lana's affection develops between Brandon and John _ who is
gradually revealed to be crazy and dangerous, as is his sidekick
Tom.
</P>
<P>
   We come to care deeply for these authentically drawn characters,
which makes the tragic and inevitable unraveling of Brandon's
double life all the more heart-rending.
</P>
<P>
   Peirce spent five years investigating the story, which was also
the subject of an award-winning 1998 documentary, ``The Brandon
Teena Story.'' Her emotionally complex drama explores the nature of
identity, as well as her subject's confused and fascinating life.
</P>
<P>
   The film is sharply photographed and makes strong use of its
soundtrack, which includes the Cure song that inspired its title.
</P>
<P>
   Swank, who starred in ``The Next Karate Kid'' and did a stint on
``Beverly Hills, 90210,'' gives an astonishing performance _ often
making you forget that her character is really a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Sevigny (``The Last Days of Disco'') is outstanding in the
difficult role of Brandon's devoted girlfriend. Sarsgaard (``The
Man in the Iron Mask'') and Sexton (``Welcome to the Dollhouse'')
are frighteningly accurate in their portrayal of the brutish
rednecks.
</P>
<P>
   Gripping, poignant and sometimes painful to watch, ``Boys Don't
Cry'' is a great film.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
