r e BC-FILM-DIAMONDS-SPI &LR;      02-17 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DIAMONDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIRK DOUGLAS FILM `DIAMONDS' HAS THE SPARKLE OF CHEAP ZIRCONIA  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's impossible not to admire Kirk Douglas _ both for a career
that includes ``Paths of Glory,'' ``Spartacus'' and a dozen other
classics over a 50-year span, and for the gutsy determination with
which he's refused to let his 1996 stroke push him into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he's fought back like a tiger, making TV appearances,
writing new novels and a new volume of his autobiography. Now, in
``Diamonds,'' he once again stars in a feature film _ sharing
billing with Lauren Bacall, with whom he burned up the screen in
the 1950 film ``Young Man With a Horn.''
</P>
<P>
   But, sad to say, the movie is not very good. Douglas makes a
noble effort, and manages to overcome the handicap of slurred
speech to marginally win us over. But the script is poorly
conceived and written, the direction is clumsy and amateurish, and
the film is surprisingly vulgar in a way that leaves a bad taste in
the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas plays Harry Agensky, an 80-something former welterweight
boxing champion (so scenes from ``Champion'' can be used as
flashbacks) and recent stroke victim who embarks on a personal
quest in the company of his estranged newspaper-columnist son (Dan
Aykroyd) and 18-year-old grandson (Corbin Allred).
</P>
<P>
   It seems that a half-century earlier, Harry hid a packet of
diamonds _ a payoff received from a gangster for throwing an
important fight _ in the wall of a house somewhere in Reno, Nev.
Now he wants to fetch the gems so he can sell them and use the
money to keep himself out of the old folks home.
</P>
<P>
   As the three generations of Agensky men journey from British
Columbia to Reno _ bickering with each other and engaging in one
highly improbably experience after another _ the movie gradually
becomes just what we know it will be from the gushy music of the
title sequence: an exercise in family forgiveness and male bonding.
</P>
<P>
   It's a movie in which almost nothing works. The situations seem
contrived, the humor is forced, the characters and their
relationships ring false, and the performances don't click _
Douglas can't muster that lion-in-winter radiance that his old
buddy, Burt Lancaster, found in ``Atlantic City.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the filmmakers have opted to set a good 40 or so minutes
of their film in a Reno brothel, with heaps of ribald humor as
Grandpa tries to take on four hookers at once, the son shows
himself to be an unlikely sexual dynamo, and the grandson has a
series of premature ejaculations with the star attraction (Jenny
McCarthy).
</P>
<P>
   It's an undignified spectacle that's a slap at Douglas' legacy
of quality filmmaking. Think of what it would have been like if the
last act of ``On Golden Pond'' had taken place in a swinger's club,
with Fonda and Hepburn playing it for cheap laughs. It's something
you just don't want to see.
</P>
<P>
   Diamonds. Directed by John Asher. Screenplay by Allan Aaron
Katz. Cast: Kirk Douglas, Dan Aykroyd, Lauren Bacall, Corbin
Allred, Jenny McCarthy. Miramax. 90 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sex
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-DOME-NYT &LR;      02-17 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-DOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO GLEE AND CHAGRIN, BRITAIN'S MILLENNIUM DOME FALLS FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, England _ It is hard to pinpoint when the Millennium
Dome, the Labor government's $1.3 billion celebration of national
pride, clearly became a colossal national joke.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was when Prince Charles reportedly ridiculed it as a
``monstrous blancmange,'' in a reference to the unattractive milky
gelatin dessert. Or perhaps it was when thousands of people were
forced to wait for up to three hours in a cramped, unheated subway
station for its opening on New Year's Eve _ a group that,
unluckily, included a large proportion of Britain's national
newspaper editors, who retaliated by making sure the nation shared
the full horror of their inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   By the time The Guardian got around to printing an article
titled ``101 Uses for a Dead Dome'' (No. 12: ``Convert it into a
home for very large Teletubbies''), even the government had to
admit that things were going slightly off message.
</P>
<P>
   And 10 days ago, the company that manages the dome admitted it,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about sluggish ticket sales and a media image about as
positive as that of a suburban nuclear power station, it fired the
dome's chief executive and hired as a replacement Pierre-Yves
Gerbeau, a young, energetic former executive from Disneyland Paris,
giving him a simple order: Fix it, now.
</P>
<P>
   At a lunch at the dome Thursday in which he presented himself to
the wolfish British news pack for the first time, Gerbeau, who is
34, speaks English with a French-American accent, and likes to be
called ``P.Y.,'' with the letters pronounced the English way,
outlined his vision for the dome.
</P>
<P>
   Dominating the east London landscape, the dome is an awesome
Richard Rogers-designed structure that looks like an upside-down
wok and has enormous spines that protrude like ships' masts.
Inside, there are 15 zones devoted to themes like work, play, and
the body; a music-and-dance extravaganza that runs throughout the
day in a center arena; restaurants and cafes; and roving bands of
musicians and performers.
</P>
<P>
   To meet its budget in the next year, the dome has to attract 10
million visitors and make a total of $320 million in revenues from
tickets, merchandise and the like. So far, it is way off schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to make sure things are happening,'' Gerbeau said.
``We sat down and said: `Let's not do philosophy here. Let's do
action.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dome's problems, he said, are relatively minor and
easily fixable. Some of the merchandise is prohibitively expensive,
for instance, and the signs are so high that it is hard to see
where you are going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's my problem,'' he said. ``Being small it's, like, I
don't see the signage.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, he said, he is considering introducing
longer hours and more flexible ticket prices; more aggressively
marketing the dome overseas; serving better food; and making sure
that visitors are encouraged to explore the whole thing, not just
one or two exhibits, so that some areas do not become oppressively
crowded while others remain empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am tremendously impressed by the structure and the soul and
the content of this place,'' Gerbeau said. ``This is a team effort,
and we're going to make this happen, no matter that the little ugly
French guy is here,'' referring to himself.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters were surprisingly benign to Gerbeau, even if some
of their questions belied their biases. One repeatedly tried to
make Gerbeau admit that he planned to fill the dome with ``adults
dressed in costume, walking around,'' presumably so that he could
then write that Gerbeau was secretly creating a
Disneyland-on-the-Thames. And when Gerbeau said he was considering
hiring some new managers, another reporter asked, ``French
people?''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the reporters have roughed up Gerbeau in their
newspapers in the last week or so. They have ridiculed him because
he is French and because his duties at Disneyland Paris, originally
known as Euro Disneyland, included overseeing customer parking.
They have reported, incorrectly, that he wrote the thesis for his
master's degree on Club Med. They have repeatedly called him
``Mickey the Gerbil.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerbeau was determined not to let any of that bother him,
gesturing down to the floor of the dome, noting the thousands of
people swarming around the exhibits, and repeatedly saying, ``This
place is fun.'' And the people on the floor seemed to agree.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they said, they do not hate the French, even when the
French are hired to manage faltering British institutions. They do
not hate having to spend $35 a ticket to take a long subway ride
out to the dome. They do not hate having to wait half an hour to
get into the Body Zone, where, as part of the exhibit, there are
lice in the pubic region.
</P>
<P>
   What they hate, they said, are the news media, which seem
largely responsible for the dome's dismal beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's typical British cynicism,'' said Anthony Bains, 29,
referring to the bad publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Bains' companion, Ross Spicer, also 29, observed that ``as a
nation, we always knock everything we do,'' and said he had
particularly liked the body zone, in which visitors walk through a
giant human body and learn how it works. He didn't mention the
lice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart was very realistic,'' Spicer said. ``It hangs above
you and pulsates.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Newband, who has worked in the dome since its opening,
selling soup at a kiosk called Soup, could barely contain himself
on the subject of the British newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's terrible that our national press is so
negative,'' he said. ``I'm sure half the people who wrote those
things didn't even come here.''
</P>
<P>
   He handed out some tomato soup. ``As far as we're concerned,
things are really picking up. This is going to be a success.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
