r e BC-TV-2GETHER-REVIEW-LAD     02-17 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-2GETHER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS DEFINITELY NOT SPINAL TAP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: EMBARGOED until Monday, Feb. 21. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in time for the Grammy Awards _ where such utterly
manufactured entities as the Backstreet Boys and Britney Spears
have legitimate chances of actually being feted for ``excellence''
_ comes ``2gether,'' MTV's first TV movie, a documentary-style
parody of the boy-band craze that has emptied the wallets of
parents of pre- and early-teen girls everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the quest of a longtime show-biz grime-bucket
manager (Alan Blumenfeld) to assemble a five-singer ensemble in one
brief week's time, ``2gether'' gets the formula for these acts down
cold. There's the heartthrob lead _ in this case, Jerry O'Keefe,
played by Evan Farmer _ and the ``rebel'' _ an attitudinal but
ultimately wimpy Mickey Park, who frets over what his mom might
think, played by Alex Solowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the ``shy'' one _ Chad Linus (Noah Bastian), discovered
experiencing stage fright at a Mr. New York pageant, and the
reassuring big brother, Chad's middle-age sibling Doug (Kevin
Farley, a dead-ringer for his late brother Chris), who isn't
recruited for his looks but because he can help with all the heavy
lifting. And don't forget the diminutive ``cute'' one, whom the
manager moonily eulogizes as ``my Ewok'' _ Jason ``QT'' McKnight
(Michael Cuccione), who is discovered singing ``The Battle Hymn of
the Republic'' at a karaoke bar and has a terminal illness that
ensures the band reams of publicity.
</P>
<P>
   After the guys are wrangled, the rest of the movie is given over
to shaping them into a semi-competent stage act, with all of a
whopping two songs to perform _ which is OK, since that seems to be
their audience's attention span. One number's lyrics: ``Say it,
don't spray it/I want the news/Not the weather.'' Of course, the
usual complications set in, and of course, by the film's close,
they're all resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``2gether'' has a lot of cute touches _ each pop-up graphic
introducing individual characters comes with its own Universal
Price Code symbol, a wry acknowledgement that everything on display
here is simply ``product.'' At one point, the guys blanch (rightly)
at having to wear patriotic, star-spangled jumpsuits. Overall,
though, the satire is so attenuated that fans of the genre won't
likely even realize they're being played for dupes _ in fact, the
video culled from the film has already been highly requested on MTV
_ and the wane comedy is outpaced by the pallid narrative logic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film speeds along with an agreeable energy; the
editing and general look of the film looks more like a music video
than a documentary. Though ``This Is Spinal Tap'' homages have
abounded in the wake of that classic film, here you wonder if the
filmmakers have even seen the movie they're ripping off.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers, of course, are encouraged to hope that these genial
hacks exploiting the dimwitted masses will make it to the top of
the show-biz heap. It's a little like hoping that Tom Ripley or
Hannibal Lechter get away with their murders, except here,
obviously, we're not encouraged to consider the moral quandary.
Unless Tom or Hannibal the Cannibal were to turn their attentions
to boys' bands, in which two wrongs really would make a right. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``2gether.'' &QL; 
What: Mockumentary about the creation of a boys' band. &QL; 
The stars: Alan Blumenfeld, Evan Farmer, Alex Solowitz, Kevin
Farley, Noah Sebastian, Michael Cuccione. &QL; 
Where: MTV. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Monday. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
