<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-OSCAR-INVENTIVE18-COX     02-17 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-INVENTIVE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witherspoon, 'Three Kings' didn't deserve Academy shutout
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There was much blather and bluster about 1999
being an unconventional year for film, pocked as it was with
crunchy perversities like ``Being John Malkovich,'' ``Magnolia,''
``The Blair Witch Project,'' ``Go'' and ``Three Kings.'' But you
wouldn't know it looking at Tuesday's Oscar nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The best picture derby, despite inclusion of the slightly
off-center ``American Beauty'' and the spooky but deeply
conventional ``The Sixth Sense,'' wears the mantle of moldy
traditionalism, constituting a company of inoffensive titles that
exert the qualities the Academy falls for every time. True, the
Dreamworks-produced ``Beauty'' scratched itches we forgot we had
(and made them bleed), but the Academy is known on occasion to
salute films that have the power to ruffle (see the X-rated
``Midnight Cowboy''), as long as they don't ruffle too much (see
``Blue Velvet'').
</P>
<P>
   Academy voters, a musty, easily befuddled bunch, like sweep and
broad strokes, snack-size narratives that don't squiggle and that
possess a literary tang, wanton sentimentality and soul-swelling
do-goodism. This year's roster, rounded out by the tough-minded
``The Insider'' and major eye-rollers ``The Cider House Rules'' and
``The Green Mile,'' fulfills all of the requisites.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the genuinely unusual movies of '99 had to settle for
consolation nods _ meaning perfunctory nominations they likely
won't win _ which, frankly, were all some of them deserved.
</P>
<P>
   I for one am relieved the overestimated ``Malkovich'' didn't
yield a best picture nomination. Yet I am appalled that the twinkly
racist fantasy ``The Green Mile'' did. And I don't think anybody
knows what to say about the surprise bounty of nods for the
little-seen ``Cider House Rules.'' The movie's like a boomerang
Hollywood forgot it threw last year that has shwinged back to bonk
it on the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair Witch,'' of course, got nothing (there is no best
scriptless, director-less, improvised, sea sick-inducing picture
category), nor did the snappy teen caper ``Go.'' I stand unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Payne and Jim Taylor's fanged high school satire
``Election'' duly earned a best adapted screenplay nod, but where
oh where was Reese Witherspoon, whose Machiavellian goldilocks ran
for student body president with Nixonian fervor? That best actress
slot was wasted on Meryl Streep's mindless nomination for ``Music
of the Heart,'' Wes Craven's latest nightmare about violins and
kids or something. Streep's name, I suspect, is preprinted on
nomination ballots _ a concept, come to think of it, Witherspoon's
perfidious pol might relish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Kings'' _ what happened? David O. Russell's seething
action dramedy was flagrantly, baldly, disgracefully overlooked.
How to ignore Russell's screenplay, which mingled the avant and the
pat to strike a happy, galvanizing medium? It was mildly
challenging, and that tends to make the Academy's collective head
go ouchy.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-for-shot, idea-for-idea, Russell out-directed Spike Jonze,
whose ``Malkovich'' only merited its script and supporting actress
nominations, not the one for Jonze. Same goes for Paul
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Anderson's hyperventilating opus ``Magnolia,'' which,
sanely, was only tapped for its grandiose screenplay, Aimee Mann's
song and Tom Cruise's sweaty display of thespian purging.
</P>
<P>
   Several Oscar omissions make me a happy critic: Matt Damon and
Gwyneth Paltrow, vanilla and ice, passed over for the arid
``Talented Mr. Ripley,'' which itself was dissed for best picture
(yes!); Tom Hanks overlooked for his rote cardboard turn in ``The
Green Mile''; Jim Carrey and everyone involved in the lackluster
``Man on the Moon'' snubbed big time.
</P>
<P>
   Several omissions rankle. The swiftly dismissed ``Snow Falling
on Cedars,'' which I quite liked, had to settle on a cinematography
nod because it was pretty. But much of its beauty was shaped by
some of the most exquisite editing in recent film. The Academy
missed this. (And I know voters can do right in this category. When
I saw 1994's ``Speed'' the first thing out of my brain was, ``This
better be nominated for an editing Oscar.'' It was.)
</P>
<P>
   At least Richard Farnsworth earned David Lynch's sorely
underrated ``The Straight Story'' an acting nomination, though the
film, a spare document of gossamer beauty, also deserved
recognition in the best picture, director and cinematography
categories.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not about to wade into the morass of how foreign-language
films are nominated _ it's tricky _ but that doesn't mean I don't
wonder why art-house hit ``Run Lola Run,'' unalloyed adrenaline
from Germany, didn't register on Oscar's fickle radar. There's no
shock or umbrage (just a yawn) in the nomination of Pedro
Almodovar's praise-showered melodrama ``All About My Mother'' from
Spain. Yet I must ask, what is ``Solomon and Gaenor''? It hails
from the United Kingdom, where I thought English was spoken. (The
movie is mostly in English, with parts in Welsh and Yiddish.)
</P>
<P>
   The documentary department continued its checkered tradition of
suspiciously lame nominees. (Recall that three of the best docs of
recent years _ ``Brother's Keeper,'' ``The Thin Blue Line'' and
``Hoop Dreams'' _ were shut out in favor of soft, inspirational
portraits like ``Maya Lin: A Strong, Clear Vision.'')
</P>
<P>
   This year boasts three music-related nonfiction films _ two too
many: critical darlings ``Genghis Blues'' and ``Buena Vista Social
Club,'' and ``Speaking in Strings,'' which was so tepidly reviewed
that it never made it as far as Austin. Also tapped were ``On the
Ropes,'' an earnest but flawed look at an inner-city boxing club,
and ``One Day in September.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, we know ``American Movie'' _ Chris Smith's hilarious
chronicle of a young filmmaker's almost existential struggle to get
his no-budget horror movie made _ wasn't exactly politically
correct or welling with explicit social redemption. But it was good
_ a witty, colorful portrait of a real live American, swaggering
nerd Mark Borchardt, whose crazy triumph of the will elicited more
inspirational pathos and naked humanity than perhaps any film last
year.
</P>
<P>
   A beer-swigging, job-hopping, debt-ridden romantic with a tragic
mullet haircut, Borchardt emerged as a Midwestern Sisyphus, sad,
comic and deluded. In one scene in the film, our anti-hero watches
the Academy Awards ceremony on TV. You can see in his besotted,
bespectacled eyes how much he wishes he was there, basking in a
little glory.
</P>
<P>
   If only.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
