<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0245 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-CHAIRMAN-ART-2     02-17 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CHAIRMAN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN, AS COMMERCE COMMITTEE CHAIRMAN, DEFIES LABELING  
(ART ADV: Photo _ NYT10 _ is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ In their spirited primary battle, George W.
Bush uses the sobriquet ``the Chairman'' to tar John McCain as a
Washington insider.
</P>
<P>
   But a close examination of McCain's record as chairman of the
powerful Senate Commerce Committee shows that he defies easy
labeling.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator has angered and perplexed many of the
Washington agencies and special interests that he oversees as
chairman. His leadership of the Commerce Committee and his style as
chairman are also interesting indicators of how he might lead if he
ever makes it to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, for example, McCain denounced a measure adopted
by Congress that made it easier for the satellite television
industry to compete head to head with cable television and
broadcasters, calling the legislation a sop to special interests.
</P>
<P>
   What made the senator's remarks so striking was that he had
sponsored an earlier version with great fanfare and had long
promoted efforts to help satellite television, in part because vast
stretches of his home state, Arizona, rely on satellite signals as
the only way to get television reception.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the legislation had been completed, McCain had
been unwilling to strike compromises with broadcasters who were
competing with the satellite companies, and the measure spun out of
his control and wound up being shaped by other senators on the
Commerce and Judiciary Committees.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's failure to get support for his bill and his frustration
with the final legislation signed by President Clinton was hardly
an unusual experience for him as a lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   In his three years as chairman, he has helped pass a number of
laws, most notably one limiting the liability of companies for
computer problems linked to the year 2000 changeover, another that
puts a three-year-moratorium on Internet sales tax, and others on
automobile and truck safety.
</P>
<P>
   But having alienated the Senate leadership and many of his
Republican colleagues because of the highly visible positions he
has staked out in criticizing his colleagues over campaign finance
and pork-barrel legislation, McCain has been unable to garner
enough support for many other measures. And even though he is a
member of their club, a majority of his fellow Republicans in the
Senate have forsaken his presidential candidacy and endorsed his
chief rival, Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that I did not win Miss Congeniality,''
McCain said here earlier this week in a debate in South Carolina.
``I've taken on the iron triangle: special interests, campaign
finance and lobbying. I did not make a lot of friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Likening himself to a cross between Presidents Theodore
Roosevelt and Ronald Reagan, McCain has tried to convey both
populist and traditional conservative Republican themes, at times
yielding positions that his critics say are not always consistent.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he has sponsored legislation to block the
government from regulating the Internet, saying politicians and
bureaucrats from Washington have no business trying to place their
stamp on the free-flowing medium. But he has also introduced bills
requiring the use of filters to protect children from Internet
pornography and imposing limits on companies from using private
information they get about consumers.
</P>
<P>
   He has consistently criticized large corporate mergers in the
telecommunications industry as a bad byproduct of the 1996 law
deregulating the industry, which he was the only Republican to
oppose. But he has also proposed legislation that would make it
significantly easier for the largest companies to merge by raising
the current concentration caps that limit acquisitions. And he has
repeatedly tried to strip the Federal Communications Commission of
authority to review and impose conditions on mergers of telephone
companies or broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation on his campaign bus, McCain acknowledged that
he walked a fine line between criticizing industry practices while
at the same time advancing broad deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do sometimes feel conflicted,'' he said. ``As a conservative
Republican, I have more faith in the marketplace then the
bureaucrats, and the measures I have put forward are basically
deregulatory in nature. But I have studied the speeches of Teddy
Roosevelt and I understand the importance of these issues for the
common man, who can get shafted by these big companies.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said, for instance, that he did not know what to make of
the government's antitrust case against Microsoft, or what he would
do about the case if he were president.
</P>
<P>
   ``His is a dual personality,'' said Ralph Nader, the consumer
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Nader has sought campaign finance legislation and was
praiseworthy of the work McCain has done on auto and truck safety
and reducing corporate welfare. But Nader has opposed the senator's
efforts to change the tort-law system and limit liability for
computer problems related to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows what people want to hear and he tells it to them,''
Nader said of the senator, ``but he also knows what corporations
pay to get, and he gives that to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has ruffled many of his Senate colleagues, McCain
enjoys a considerable base of power at Commerce, Science and
Transportation Committee. The committee, among the most important
in Congress for Corporate America, regulates almost everything that
is bought or sold, or moves over the nation's roads, rails, rivers
or airways.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Republicans in the Senate, McCain enjoys an unusually
good relationship with a small group of consumer advocates who
historically are much closer to liberals and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   One member is Joan Claybrook, president of Public Citizen and
administrator of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
under President Jimmy Carter. Claybrook worked closely with McCain
and his staff on air bag and truck safety legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Another member is Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the Washington
office of Consumers Union, who is also highly critical of federal
regulators. Kimmelman said McCain was always willing to listen to
Consumer Union's positions and, at congressional hearings, was one
of the few who gave the group an equal platform with many senior
corporate executives and lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   McCain says he has ignored repeated pleas by corporate
executives not to include the voice of Consumers Union, or to
include it later in the day after the executives have testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``These executives don't realize that the consumer groups
represent the little guy and need to be heard,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman said that while McCain often identified industry
problems in telecommunications and other areas, he had little faith
in regulators to solve them. Still, it is one of the unusual
aspects of McCain's chairmanship that he often seeks advice from
regulators on all kinds of issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very effective on the issues he raises,'' Claybrook
said. ``He gets people's attention. In large measure he doesn't
always win because he takes on some pretty knotty issues. He
doesn't always win, but he plants the seeds. And he doesn't mind
combat. He doesn't mind the adversary process. He is comfortable
with it and won't walk away, and that's critical.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's detractors say it shows that he has been unable to cut
the pragmatic political compromises.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Windhausen Jr., president of the Association for Local
Telecommunications Services, an organization that represents the
newer telephone services trying to challenge the older ones, said
that despite McCain's pronounced views the senator had often acted
more in the interests of larger, more established companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say he's being intellectually honest or you can say
he's pushing an agenda that will never be accomplished,'' said
Windhausen, who previously worked as a top aide for Sen. Ernest F.
Hollings of South Carolina, the ranking Democrat on the Commerce
Committee. ``He's using consumer complaints about the
Telecommunications Act to take positions that would be even worse
for consumers and better for big business.''
</P>
<P>
   A lobbyist for the regional Bell companies whose agenda of
getting into long-distance and high-speed Internet service has so
far been unsuccessfully championed by McCain also questioned the
senator's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would call him tenacious, almost ideological,'' said the
lobbyist, who spoke only on the condition that he not be identified
because of issues still before the committee. ``But I would not
call him an effective legislator. After doing work on tobacco and
campaign finance, it makes it hard for him to work together with
others in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, McCain co-sponsored a ``bill of rights''
measure for airline passengers who have consistently complained
about deteriorating service. But in the face of pressure from the
airline industry he changed course, abandoned the legislation and
instead asked the Department of Transportation to monitor several
less severe voluntary measures that other supporters of the
proposed legislation said the industry was already doing anyway.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has repeatedly taken hard-line conservative views on
other issues, trying to kill or substantially reduce government
financing of public television and opposing gun-control legislation
and bills that seek to end discrimination against gays.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, part of McCain's difficulty in collaborating with
other Republicans in the Senate stems from his attacks on their pet
projects, often exposing what he calls wasteful spending.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., and a number of Republicans who
have been criticized by McCain said he had also advanced his own
wasteful projects in Arizona, including a $56 million authorization
for an environmental and habitat restoration project along the Salt
River, $4.2 million to create a national mediation center in
Tucson, and $3 million for the Turquoise Trail, a joint effort of
the Navajo and Hopi tribes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his aides said those projects were not pork barrel
because hearings were held over their merits, in contrast to
spending programs that are inconspicuously tucked into legislation
without ever being exposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' McCain said, ``I cut $90 million out of a planned
courthouse in Arizona. There were plenty of people back home who
weren't too happy about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
