<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      02-17 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION-YEAR CONGRESS TORN BY CONFLICTING IMPULSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Calif., Mo., S.D., Ill.)  (mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A month into this campaign-compressed legislative
year, it is still hard to tell which Republican-controlled Congress
will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be the cautiously bipartisan one that is working with
the White House to pass a China trade bill, repeal earnings limits
for Social Security recipients and increase military spending? Or
will it be the deadlocked one that is riven over the choice of a
new House chaplain and is fighting with President Clinton over
taxes, debt relief and new spending programs?
</P>
<P>
   These same doubts were raised last month before Congress
returned to work. Now there are more certain signs that both sides
may have to settle mostly for issues to campaign on, rather than
produce bills Clinton can sign into law.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting impulses between comity and gridlock reflect the
intensity of this election year. Not only is control of the White
House and Congress at stake, but so is Clinton's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in tight re-election races, like Sen. William V. Roth
Jr., R-Del., are holding out olive branches while being careful not
to sacrifice their core principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question common ground exists between us,'' Roth
said of Clinton's proposed budget. ``But debt reduction is too
slim. Real tax cuts are too few.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, in particular, are eager for accomplishments
to run on this fall to protect their narrow six-seat margin. Top
aides to Speaker J. Dennis Hastert recently drew up a list of 10
``items of agreement'' between Republicans and Clinton, including
eliminating the public debt and bringing China into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats see no advantage in meeting Republicans
halfway on traditional Democratic issues like health care and
education. Campaigning on their party differences, rather than on
their compromises, Democrats say, will propel them into the
majority again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd caution Democrats not to compromise on issues that will
only produce incremental changes that will help Republicans,'' said
Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   At least in principle, Democrats and Republicans sound closer
than they did six weeks ago on many issues, including tighter
regulation of managed care, eliminating the tax code provision that
forces many married couples to pay more than if they were single,
adding a prescription drug benefit to Medicare and increasing the
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   But discourse has dissolved into discord when the two sides talk
specifics. Republicans want to limit patients' ability to sue their
health providers. Democrats do not. Republicans want to couple
large tax breaks for employers to a $1 hike in the minimum wage.
Democrats do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going nowhere fast,'' Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri,
the Democratic leader, said in an interview. ``The Republicans are
trying to create an illusion they're for something but they
aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and some Democrats disagree, saying there is room
for compromise on health care issues, though not on, say, tighter
gun control laws, which stand little chance of passing this year.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Republicans want to head home early this
year, both to campaign and to avoid being trapped in a yearend
budget negotiation with Clinton that many Republicans fear they
would lose.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert scrapped last year's push for a $792 billion, 10-year
tax cut in favor of piecemeal, specific measures, like a
Republican-sponsored bill that would cut taxes for married couples
by $182 billion over the next decade. The House passed the bill
last week, 268-158, with 48 Democrats voting for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The administration supports a smaller version of the tax cut _
Clinton proposed $45 billion over 10 years that would be restricted
to couples penalized by the current tax code _ but only after the
nation's fiscal house is put in order. Sen. Thomas Daschle of South
Dakota, the Democratic leader, says there is ``a real good
possibility'' lawmakers will approve a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   While both parties agree that the projected budget surpluses, if
they materialize, offer the country a rare opportunity to pay down
the public debt and shore up Social Security and Medicare,
Democrats and Republicans differ over how to divide the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The start of any session is typically marked by such fits and
starts, and this year is no different. Each of the four major bills
approved by the House or Senate faces hurdles in the opposite
chamber or White House opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the marriage tax bill, the House approved legislation to
strengthen ties between the U.S. military and Taiwan. But even
Senate Republicans warn that could unnecessarily provoke China.
</P>
<P>
   Senators approved a bill to make it harder for people to declare
bankruptcy, but tacked on the contentious minimum-wage package. The
Senate also approved a bill to store tons of radioactive waste in
Nevada, but failed to muster enough votes to override Clinton's
promised veto.
</P>
<P>
   When lawmakers return from back-to-back recesses in two weeks,
the budget process will dominate lawmakers' attention. But perhaps
the hottest issue with voters is prescription drug coverage for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has assured his rank-and-file that they will vote on a
prescription drug plan and has ordered key lawmakers to draft one
within 60 days. House Democratic leaders this week said they would
use a parliamentary tactic to try to force a vote on drug coverage
for all Medicare recipients. But some centrist Democrats are
rebelling, arguing that the strategy could hamper efforts to reach
a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the oddest spectacle is the clash between House
Republicans and Democrats over the selection of a Presbyterian
minister instead of a Catholic priest to be the next House
chaplain. ``It's a disgrace,'' said Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., ``that
we have to argue about something as simple as appointing a
chaplain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
