<HEADER>
A0256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-VIETNAM-HNS &LR;      02-17 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-VIETNAM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
FORMER POW McCAIN UNAPOLOGETIC FOR CALLING CAPTORS `GOOKS' 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ John McCain, whose experience as a prisoner
of war has helped boost his presidential race, was unapologetic
Thursday for using the word ``gook'' to describe his North
Vietnamese captors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated the gooks. I will hate them as long as I live,'' the
Arizona senator told reporters on his campaign bus, two days before
South Carolina's crucial Republican primary, where McCain is
fighting to boost his insurgent campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a Navy flier who endured torture for nearly six years in
a North Vietnamese POW camp, was questioned about a recent report
in The Nation magazine that he had used the term ``gook'' in a
conversation on his bus in October.
</P>
<P>
   The article, the topic of e-mail messages now reportedly
circulating in California, questioned why the media hadn't
challenged McCain on the ethnic slur.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, who engages in an almost nonstop, on-the-record
dialogue with reporters while traveling between campaign stops,
didn't deny using the word. But he said he didn't intend it as an
insult of all Vietnamese or Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will call right now my interrogator that tortured me and my
friends a gook,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was referring to my prison guards, and I will continue to
refer to them in probably language that might offend some people
here because of their beating and torture of some of my friends.
</P>
<P>
   He said some of the guards were ``cruel and sadistic people''
and had been called much worse.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, McCain rarely speaks about his captors, much less
by using ethnically disparaging terms. But last Saturday, in a
rally at Fort Mill, S.C., McCain turned one of his regular campaign
stories into a questionable reference to Asians.
</P>
<P>
   The comment came as McCain was discussing the fund-raising
abuses of the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996. He often refers to
Vice President Al Gore's visit to the Hsi Lai Temple in suburban
Los Angeles in April 1996, which turned into a fund-raising event.
McCain, massaging the facts, says Gore claims not to know where he
was, and usually remarks that the incense and people in
saffron-colored robes should have given him a clue.
</P>
<P>
   But in Fort Mill, McCain, apparently mixing up his words, said
``all those funny looking people in robes'' should have reminded
Gore where he was. At subsequent stops, McCain reverted to his
former version of the story.
</P>
<P>
   As the pivotal South Carolina primary campaign entered its final
48 hours, both candidates expressed confidence.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush acknowledged Thursday that South Carolina has a
history of voting for the eventual GOP presidential nominee since
1980, but Bush said he feels confident that he will be the nominee
even if he loses Saturday's primary to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina has had the ability to pick the Republican
nominee,'' Bush said. ``I'd put it in the important category. I'm
continuing one way or another. You'll find me in Michigan,
Washington, North Dakota.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's primary is Feb. 22, along with Arizona. Washington,
North Dakota and Virginia hold primaries Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   McCain predicted his campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination may be unstoppable if he wins the South Carolina
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can lose here and go on. This campaign is not over `til
March 7,'' McCain told veterans at a rally in Spartanburg,
referring to the day when California, New York and 11 other states
hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll tell you what, my friends. If we win here, I don't
see how we can really be stopped.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has been reaching out to Democratic and independent
voters, predicted the South Carolina race will be ``very, very
close. I think it's going to come down to voter turnout.``
</P>
<P>
   A number of veterans have been campaigning for McCain in South
Carolina, which has more veterans per capita than any other state.
One is Mike Thornton, a Medal of Honor recipient from the Vietnam
War who grew up in South Carolina but now lives near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in what John McCain is doing for our veterans. (He)
is much more qualified to be president of the United States,''
Thornton said. ``It's not about Republicans and Democrats here.
It's about the American people. That's who I fought for.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush proudly touted a Virginia poll showing him leading McCain
54 percent to 31 percent. But he also has lost the endorsements of
Secretary of State Bill Jones in California and former Gov. Dan
Evans of Washington. Evans said he was upset with the negative tone
of Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the Detroit News reported Thursday that McCain and Bush are
running television commercials in Michigan attacking one another.
</P>
<P>
   Bush complained about efforts in Michigan, as there have been in
South Carolina, to encourage Democrats to vote in the primary to
teach Gov. John Engler, a Bush backer, ``a lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know how that's going to affect the outcome of the
election,'' Bush said. ``Other than that, I think I've got a good
organization in Michigan. I've been up there a lot and laid the
groundwork for a good campaign. A lot of party leaders have united
behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those endorsements, McCain has closed rapidly on Bush in
Michigan after his upset victory over the GOP front-runner in the
New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
