<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0257 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-SPRING-HNS     02-17 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-SPRING-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ There are few general managers throughout the
majors who are not at least a little concerned when pitchers and
catchers report for spring training.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The talent pool has been diluted at both positions _
particularly pitching _ and, quite frankly, there's not enough to
go around for 30 big-league teams.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Astros GM Gerry Hunsicker won't be alone today when
he welcomes the 29 pitchers who will compete for 11 spots on the
Astros' 25-man roster over the next six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 29 pitchers, about 10 have virtually no chance of
making the opening-day roster. And barring anything unforeseen, 10
of the 11 spots already are locked up.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima, Shane Reynolds, Octavio Dotel, Chris Holt, Dwight
Gooden, Billy Wagner, Jay Powell, Doug Henry, Jose Cabrera and
Trever Miller seem assured of spots if they stay healthy and _ in a
few cases _ show some semblance of effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The total would rise from 10 to 11 if Scott Elarton, who is
recovering from offseason shoulder surgery, can get up to speed by
opening day. There is some concern he might miss the first month of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the Astros' best-case scenario, the aforementioned 11
pitchers would be on the opening-day roster, eliminating the
thought of having to choose from seemingly lesser alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the starting rotation is concerned, spring training
will be business as usual for Lima and Reynolds, who are the only
locks. Dotel is the next-best thing to a certainty. Holt and Gooden
likely will round out the rotation unless Elarton is able to start
the season on time, in which case Holt or Gooden would go to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   In the bullpen, Wagner, Powell, Henry, Cabrera and Miller are
set, barring injury. Assuming Holt and Gooden are in the rotation,
veterans Mike Maddux and Kip Gross are the leading candidates to
fill the final relief spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have a little less depth in the starting rotation than
we've had in previous years, but we're not lacking for candidates
in the bullpen,'' Hunsicker said. ``You might argue about the
quality, but we have quantity.
</P>
<P>
   ``By definition, bullpens are suspect because _ outside of the
closer and possibly a setup man _ most of the candidates are
usually guys with checkered careers, guys who couldn't make it as a
starter or a closer and they end up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most bullpens look like question marks to begin the season.
That's one area where a lot of teams can have upside surprises.
Every year, the bullpen looks suspect on paper, but we always find
a way to put together a quality bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring shouldn't be much different, especially if Elarton
is healthy and the Astros avoid any other serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elarton will be the key,'' Hunsicker said. ``If he's out for a
long time, that might leave us a little vulnerable, but we have a
multitude of candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros would like to give righthanded prospect Wade Miller
at least another half-season at Class AAA New Orleans, but he is
being prepared as an option in the event the Astros need another
starter at the beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is Trever Miller, who was a starter
throughout his minor-league career.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the pitchers and catchers who will report to the
Osceola Sports Complex today, the Astros also extended early
invitations to outfielders Moises Alou and Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   It is unknown whether either player will arrive early or choose
to report Wednesday with the rest of the position players. Alou and
Hidalgo were given early invitations because both are coming off
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In a related matter, Hunsicker addressed a report that Alou
would be willing to waive his no-trade clause to play for the
Braves, Rockies or Cubs by saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading Moises Alou is not an issue. It's not something the
player desires or something the team desires. To comment any
further than that would be inappropriate because it's just not an
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
