<SLUG> BC-FED-GREENSPAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN HINTS OF MORE INTEREST RATE HIKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan on Thursday
signaled the likelihood of more interest rate hikes ahead as the
central bank tries to cool down a supercharged U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   And while Greenspan voiced particular concern about high oil
prices, he urged the administration not to dip into the Strategic
Petroleum Reserve in an effort to force down prices.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing Thursday on Capitol Hill for his semiannual report to
Congress on the state of the economy, Greenspan told members of the
House Banking Committee: ``There is little evidence that the
American economy ... is slowing appreciably.''
</P>
<P>
   While calling the economy's performance ``unprecedented in my
half-century of observing,'' Greenspan argued ``those profoundly
beneficial forces driving the American economy to competitive
excellence are also engendering a set of imbalances that, unless
contained, threaten our continuing prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan warned the Fed ``will have to stay alert for signs
that real interest rates have not yet risen enough to bring the
growth of demand into line with that of potential supply, even
should the acceleration of productivity continue.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he has talked of such dangers in the past, Greenspan
argued that proper alignment ``seems more pressing today than it
did earlier, before the effects of imbalances began to cumulate,
lessening the depth of our various buffers against inflationary
pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed watchers interpreted Greenspan's comments to mean the
central bank will almost surely raise interest rates a quarter of a
percentage point at its next meeting, scheduled for March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Following that possible hike, many economists look for yet
another quarter point rate hike down the road, either at the Fed's
meeting in May or at a subsequent session in June.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's comments were enough to squelch a 100-point rally on
Wall Street. The Dow Jones industrial average plunged after
Greenspan's prepared remarks were released, ending the day down
46.84 points to close at 10,514.57.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market responded to the news by boosting the 30-year
Treasury 1/2 point, or $5 per $1,000 in face value. The yield,
which moves in the opposite direction of price, fell to 6.22
percent from 6.26 percent late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does nothing if not contribute to volatility,'' said Bryan
Jordan, economist for Banc One Investment Advisors in Columbus,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan argued investors should not have been surprised by
his message.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been giving the same speech for the last couple of
years,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hilber, an economist with Wells Fargo in Minneapolis, agreed
Greenspan's testimony was not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it obviously confirmed to everyone that, yeah, the Fed is
going to be in a raising rates mode, and maybe for some time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed already has nudged up short-term interest rates four
times since last June, raising the Federal Funds rate a full 1
percentage point to the current 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those rate hikes, the U.S. economy grew at a robust 4
percent in 1999, surging at an even faster pace in the second half
of the year, Greenspan said. Most Fed economists expect the
economy's growth rate to moderate somewhat this year, to 3.5
percent to 3.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit like an engine running so hot you have to
dab it with water every once in a while so it doesn't flame out on
its own,'' said David Lapin, president of Houston-based Lapin &AMP;
Wigginton Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   While Greenspan and other Fed officials remain concerned about
the spectre of inflation, the economy is showing few signs of
inflation to date.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale prices remained unchanged in January, the U.S. Labor
Department reported Thursday. And if volatile food and energy
prices are factored out, the core Producer Price Index actually
fell 0.2 percent that month.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, crude oil prices climbed above $30 a barrel
to reach the highest levels seen since the Persian Gulf War,
although it dropped back to $29.46 a barrel Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned about what's happening to oil prices,''
Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan noted that inventory levels for both crude and
petroleum products are far below normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, some are joking that we need to measure the fumes to
get any measurable inventory at all these days,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   Those tight inventories make the market vulnerable to price
spikes when even minor supply disruptions occur. And this is the
time of year when the industry begins gearing up for the busy
summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan opposes a plan to pull oil out of the Strategic
Petroleum Reserve in an effort to manipulate prices downward.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from the Northeast and Mid-Atlantic states have been
trying to prod the administration into adopting a plan to allow
energy companies to swap crude from the reserve in exchange for a
promise to replenish the stockpile at a later date when prices are
lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always viewed the Strategic Petroleum Reserve as a
reserve in the event of a serious crisis,'' Greenspan said. ``I
mean by that a shut-down in Middle East oil, or something of that
nature, because of some catastrophe of some form. I think it would
be a mistake to try to move market prices by small additions or
subtractions from the (reserve).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with an overall world market which is huge,
relative to our Strategic Petroleum Reserve,'' Greenspan said.
``And it's foolishness to believe that we can have any significant
impact short of a very major liquidation short-term of that
reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, a member of the Banking Committee,
challenged the notion oil prices are so out of line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm a little less startled about oil prices today then
I was a year ago when they were around $10 or $12 a barrel,''
Bentsen told Greenspan. ``And $30 a barrel, at least in my neck of
the woods, is close to a fair price.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, Greenspan believes the market, not government, will
best resolve energy price issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through innumerable synthetic fuels discussions,
programs and endeavors to counter previous oil shocks. I think our
experience suggests that we ought to leave it to the marketplace to
make these judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
