<HEADER>
A0263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-17 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESTIGE AND MONEY RIDING ON OUTCOME OF AMERICA'S CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HERB McCORMICK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The source of all the hubbub rests in a
shatterproof-glass case in a still room on the second floor of the
Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron. Wide windows offer a picturesque
view of the Auckland Harbor Bridge. Each evening, one of the
security guards entrusted with its care packs it into a specially
made suitcase and tucks it into the club's vault.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the daily grind of the America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday (Friday night Eastern Time), the five-of-nine-race
finals to determine the cup's future address will commence between
the current defender, Team New Zealand, and the hopeful usurper,
Italy's Prada Challenge. Much is riding on the outcome of this
waterborne duel.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Italian yacht, Luna Rossa, win, the reasoning goes,
the cup will be swept away to the glorious shores of the
Mediterranean Sea, where a host of new European suitors _ England,
Germany, Norway, Sweden _ would join the ranks of established
challengers like France, Switzerland and Spain to create a
continental maritime extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   In this warm and fuzzy scenario, the United States would renew
its efforts to regain the cup on the largesse of the many flush
corporate sponsors who would clamor onto the bandwagon, their
interests piqued by the chance to woo new markets far from the
tiny, remote antipodes.
</P>
<P>
   For this to happen, of course, New Zealand must relinquish the
cup in its inaugural defense. And for most Kiwis, this is a destiny
far too awful to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of optimism out there,'' said Jonathon Denver,
the assistant manager of Euro, perhaps the trendiest of the many
new Auckland restaurants to open along the wharves bordering the
downtown syndicate camps at Viaduct Harbor. ``Our national identity
is aligned with our sporting figures. If we lose, the whole country
will go into mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the Viaduct was a nasty, fetid example of urban
neglect. Today, it is the showcase of a waterfront renaissance
ignited by New Zealand's winning cup effort in San Diego in 1995.
Tens of millions of dollars have been invested not only on the
yachting facilities _ easily the most impressive ever assembled for
any regatta _ but also on the hundreds of new apartments and dozens
of fledgling cafes and pubs, as well as the walkways and parks that
interconnect them.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, the cup will have left an amazing legacy here. Of
course, to truly reap the benefits of this miraculous
transformation, New Zealand must retain it for at least one
defense. Otherwise, said Denver, contemplating the image of closed
doors on the very establishments that fronted big money to open,
``Six months from now there could be a lot of sad stories around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is sympathetic. Take Mick Cookson, the legendary
Kiwi boat builder who fashioned both of Team New Zealand's new
boats _ NZL 60 and its backup, NZL 45. ``Well, some of those
downtown developers might see things go flat if we fail,'' said
Cookson, who believes all this talk of losing is an interesting
academic exercise, but impossible. ``But if someone risked
everything on keeping the cup, that's their problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In the here and now, however, the party is on and the boom-town
mentality rages. This was evident last Monday, when the speakers at
a 500-person dinner following a technology information conference
included the Silicon Graphics and Netscape founder, Jim Clark, and
the renowned venture capitalist Tom Perkins. Both entrepreneurs are
in town aboard their respective superyachts, an international fleet
of which line the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win this thing again,'' Clark said, to cheers, ``I
might have to come back with my own cup campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark would be welcomed with open arms. Many Kiwi businessmen
were disheartened when challenging syndicates representing the New
York Yacht Club and San Francisco's St. Francis Yacht Club were
eliminated. So, too, went the logic, did their chances of wooing
deep-pocketed members with Down Under proposals.
</P>
<P>
   So it was big news this week when the American investor Jay
Snider, whose family has had interests in a number of professional
sports teams in Philadelphia, ponied up $5 million to back the
Kiwi-based Internet cup broadcaster Virtual Spectator.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not all big deals and bigger boats. At the Loaded Hog,
a waterfront pub with original tank-test models of the winning 1995
New Zealand boats dangling from the ceiling, the beer is cold and
the taps are open. ``Whatever happens, we'll be fine,'' said the
manager, Sara Tucker. ``We get everybody in here _ overseas
tourists, yachties hangers-on, out-of-town Kiwis. They're all
thirsty.''
</P>
<P>
   And Win West, a native Aucklander who drives one of the
ubiquitous water taxis zipping along the harbor, shares a similar
philosophical outlook. ``Auckland's lifeblood is the water, and the
cup has brought this waterfront alive,'' he said. ``Even if we
lose, it will be good for the cup. The Italians have been great
sportsmen, and it would be wonderful for Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   His countrymen may not share his magnanimous view but, for now,
it doesn't matter. For the next two weeks, at least, the America's
Cup is a Kiwi icon, and its harbor view from the yacht squadron's
second floor is just fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
