<HEADLINE>
`WHOLE NINE YARDS' FAILS TO MEASURE UP AS A CAPER COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After his success as a serious psychologist in ``The Sixth
Sense,'' Bruce Willis has reverted to his smug and smilin' ways.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Whole Nine Yards'' _ which refers to a cool $10 million
_ he plays a recently released-from-prison hit man named Jimmy
``The Tulip'' Tudeski. He's gone into hiding in Montreal because a
Chicago syndicate boss, Janni Gogolak (Kevin Pollak), is out to
silence him permanently. It seems Jimmy ratted out Janni's father
to the feds, sending the old don down the river for the rest of his
natural days and giving Jimmy a short sentence.
</P>
<P>
   So the smooth, unflappable assassin has settled for upward
mobility in a nice neighborhood next door to dentist Nicholas
Oseransky, or ``Oz,'' played by ``Friends'' star Matthew Perry, and
his evil-spirited French wife, Sophie (Rosanna Arquette), who would
love to see her bumbling husband dead.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Oz's perky assistant Jill (Amanda Peet), Janni's
right-hand man Frankie ``Figs'' Figueroa (Oscar nominee Michael
Clarke Duncan) and Jimmy's beautiful ex-wife Cynthia (Natasha
Henstridge).
</P>
<P>
   All are itching to pull the trigger on someone because there is
$10 million moldering in a bank vault and only three people know
how to retrieve the dough.
</P>
<P>
   Before long everyone has a price on his or her head, and who
will whack whom becomes the question.
</P>
<P>
   There are some clever twists and the film is an initially
promising caper comedy. But the script refuses to let the
cleverness develop and, once each character's alter-identity or
real motive is evident, it becomes a pedestrian movie with a
predictable romance at its heart.
</P>
<P>
   Another big problem is the casting of Willis and Perry. When
he's subdued, Willis can be an effective actor. But here he appears
to be slumming, overwhelming a role that demands subtlety. Perry
has yet to prove himself on the big screen. His last film, ``Three
to Tango,'' was awful, and while he's pretty good at physical
comedy and has a nice sense of timing, he always looks rigid and
uncomfortable. While the mix of Willis' languor and Perry's uptight
demeanor could make good comedy, it's done in by a script that
settles into mediocrity and opts for a hasty exit.
</P>
<P>
   The Whole Nine Yards. Directed by Jonathan Lynn. Written by
Mitchell Kapner. Cast: Bruce Willis, Matthew Perry, Rosanna
Arquette, Michael Clarke Duncan. Warner Bros. 103 minutes. Rated R
for language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
