<SLUG> BC-SCI-VACCINE-FDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA APPROVES VACCINE AGAINST BACTERIA THAT CAUSES MENINGITIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, N.M., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first vaccine to prevent a leading cause of
meningitis in infants and toddlers was approved Thursday by the
Food and Drug Administration, one day after a panel of scientific
experts recommended against giving it to all children under age 5
in part because of its high cost.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine, Prevnar, manufactured by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories,
protects youngsters against the pneumococcus bacteria, which each
year causes an estimated 1,400 cases of meningitis and 16,000 cases
of blood poisoning in children under 5, as well as 40 percent of
all childhood ear infections.
</P>
<P>
   The approval is important because meningitis, while not very
common, kills several hundred children each year and leaves others
with brain damage and other neurological problems. But prevention
will come at a price; a four-dose course of Prevnar will cost $232,
roughly the same as all other childhood immunizations combined.
</P>
<P>
   With that high cost in mind, a panel of expert advisors to the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommended on Wednesday
that the vaccine become part of the routine immunization schedule
for the roughly 3.8 million babies born each year, but given
immediately on a catch-up basis only to children under age 2.
</P>
<P>
   Among 2-to-5 year olds, the panel called for vaccinating only
those children at high risk, specifically blacks, Native Americans,
Alaskan natives and youngsters with HIV, sickle-cell anemia or
other disorders that weaken the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was unusual for two reasons: it marked the first
time that the panel had given special consideration to black
children, and only the second time it had taken cost into account.
Taking into account lost time at work for parents, the panel
conducted a cost-benefit analysis for Prevnar. It concluded that
the vaccine would be cost-effective at $46 a dose, $12 less than
the $58 the company has set.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Dr. Peter Paradiso, vice president of
scientific affairs and research strategy for Wyeth-Ayerst, defended
the price, and said the company was pleased with the committee's
decision. He said the company spent 14 years developing the vaccine
and tested it in more than 50,000 children, which drove up the
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal for this vaccine was for it to become part of the
routine immunization schedule for all kids, and it will,'' Paradiso
said, adding that ``the amount of disease you are preventing and
will prevent for years to come justifies the price.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's advice is not binding, but the disease control
centers is likely to follow it, and doctors, health insurance
companies and government funded health programs, will use the
guidelines to determine how to put Prevnar into medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   While some doctors say it troubles them to offer vaccines to
some children and not others, Dr. Gary Overturf, an infectious
disease expert at the University of New Mexico, said a committee of
the American Academy of Pediatrics has reached the same conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are uncomfortable making decisions strictly on cost, but I
don't think this was strictly on cost,'' he said. ``We had to set a
priority to put those children at highest risk first.'' He said it
would be logistically impossible to vaccinate all children under
age 5. And in any event, over the next five years, once all
newborns have gotten the vaccine, the issue will become moot.
</P>
<P>
   For Wyeth-Ayerst, a division of American Home Products in
Philadelphia, the FDA approval is good news; its last childhood
vaccine, to prevent rotavirus, was approved in 1998 but withdrawn
from the market last year amid concerns that it could cause a
painful and potentially fatal bowel obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration said Prevnar is extremely
effective in preventing cases of pneumococcal meningitis, a
dangerous infection of the spinal cord and central nervous system
that often leaves children with neurological damage, including
deafness and learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In clinical trials, the vaccine, which is targeted against seven
of the most common strains of pneumococcus, proved 100 percent
effective in preventing infection with those strains, and 90
percent effective in preventing infection with all strains, the FDA
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first vaccine that can seem to have a great impact
on severe diseases'' caused by pneumococcus, said Dr. Jesse
Goodman, deputy director of the Center for Biologics Evaluation and
Research at the food and drug agency. ``For the most serious
infections, it really appears to be excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency said infants can receive the vaccine at 2, 4, 6 and
12-15 months of age. For children under age 2 who have already
missed the initial doses, the vaccination schedule will be
determined by health care providers.
</P>
</TEXT>
