<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-TWIN125S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS QUESTION RULES AFTER `BORING' TWIN 125S AT DAYTONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ There will be a pass made for the lead of
the 42nd[ annual] Daytona 500 on Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Won't there? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As absurd as that might sound when talking about a NASCAR
Winston Cup race, it was a valid inquiry following the annual Twin
125 qualifying races at the Daytona International Speedway. A
combined 100 laps of caution-free racing around the high-banked,
2.5-mile trioval produced not one pass for the lead yesterday, as
Bill Elliott and Ricky Rudd paced their respective sprints
flag-to-flag.
</P>
<P>
   The outcomes provided a sentimental return to Victory Lane here
for Elliott, a dominating Daytona 500 champion in 1985 and 1987 _
in the days before introduction of the carburetor restrictor plate.
Rudd, meanwhile, made his first visit to Daytona's winner's circle
four days after crashing and landing on his roof during the Bud
Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   But the feel-good stories surrounding the 40-something winners
were overshadowed by a burgeoning quality-of-racing issue that
could be spelled B-O-R-I-N-G.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly not going to tell any of these drivers, who are
running 192 mph with their front ends pushing, that it's boring,''
said NASCAR official Mike Helton, addressing an already touchy
issue at DIS.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,400-pound Fords, Chevrolets and Pontiacs compete here with
restrictor plates that reduce an engine's ability to crank out
horsepower from 750 to 450, creating racing in single-file packs
and a heightened possibility of multi-car wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   That situation has been compounded by NASCAR's recently
standardized shock/spring-rate package. Introduced in January to
make the racing safer and more cost-effective, the new rules were
warmly received by most teams during off-season testing. Yesterday,
however, the race results left many drivers complaining that their
cars will not handle through the track's 31-degree banked turns.
Instead of turning left, the cars are pushing up toward the wall,
forcing drivers to lift off the accelerator and lose time and
ground.
</P>
<P>
   It is a condition known as ``aero push,'' and it prompted Mike
Skinner to lobby NASCAR for a rules change immediately after
driving his new No. 31 Lowe's Chevy Monte Carlo to a second-place
finish to Rudd in Twin No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``They [NASCAR] might consider something with the shocks,'' said
Skinner, who spent his race staring into the rear-end ``TV panel''
of Rudd's No. 28 Texaco/Havoline Ford Taurus. ``Everybody in the
first race complained about push. We tried the best we could, and
we just never could get the car to turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when you see Dale Earnhardt finish out of the top five at
Daytona, you know his car wasn't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, a seven-time Cup champion and Skinner's teammate at
Richard Childress Racing, saw his 10-year winning streak in Twin
125-mile races end with an 11th-place finish in the opener.
Earnhardt thoroughly trashed the current rules after watching
Elliott, reigning Cup champion Dale Jarrett and Rusty Wallace lead
a Ford sweep in Twin No. 1. But Rudd, Skinner and Ward Burton made
it a Ford/Chevy/Pontiac Grand Prix top three in Twin No. 2, with
rookie Dale Earnhardt Jr. piloting his aerodynamically challenged
Monte Carlo to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   That apparently was enough evidence for NASCAR officials to
dismiss thoughts of any quick aero fixes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to change anything for the Daytona 500,'' said
Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief executive officer.
``One of the things we're concerned about is not creating a moving
target after six days of Daytona 500 practice. And we're not
convinced any change is necessary. We're going to press on.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, the pole-sitter for the season-opener, said teams in
every camp need to massage their cars today and tomorrow _ and
during the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is about handling now,'' said Jarrett, driver of the
No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit Taurus. ``You do that by
changing the things they allow you to change _ swaybars, trackbars,
spring rubbers and things like that. They have the same opportunity
that we do.''
</P>
<P>
   And the same opportunity to change the complexion of NASCAR's
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Daytona 500, and I think you'll see an exciting
race,'' Rudd said. ``I hope so. I mean, the fans didn't pay a lot
of money to come and see us run single-file, I think.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
