s f BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV20-N     02-17 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a New Look At Some Easy Targets &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Harold S. Geneen _ the architect behind the ITT Corp.'s
foray into, well, just about everything _ was right, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Conglomerates have long gotten a bad rap because they are
perceived as inefficient dinosaurs. Corporate raiders and analysts
plot how to break them up in order to ``unlock'' value. And
shareholders complain about their low price-to-earnings multiples.
</P>
<P>
   But a December study by Larry Shulman, senior vice president of
the Boston Consulting Group, throws a fair amount of cold water on
those preconceptions. Shulman first looked at the performance of
the Value Line Diversified Companies Index, a proxy for
conglomerates, and compared it with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index for the 10 years through 1997. Surprise! The conglomerate
index was the winner in average annualized return, 18.6 percent to
17.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that from 1989 to 1996, conglomerates that
``de-merged'' _ consultant-speak for being broken up _ were just as
likely to underperform the market as to outperform it.
</P>
<P>
   Shulman's explanation for all this is straightforward: there are
good conglomerates and bad conglomerates. Pick the right ones _
premiums, as he calls them _ and investors will reap the rewards.
</P>
<P>
   While the premium conglomerates vary in the types of businesses
they run, they share four key characteristics, the study said. They
shrink or abandon their low-return businesses and invest in their
high-return ones.
</P>
<P>
   They emphasize performance and accountability in management.
Their portfolios of businesses have what he described as a
``distinctive'' logic to them. And their earnings are consistent
and predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Shulman found that for the 10 years through 1997, his 50 premium
conglomerates returned 27 percent annually, on average, versus 18
percent for the S&AMP;P 500 and a negative 1 percent for the 50
underperformers he identified.
</P>
<P>
   The five top-performing premium conglomerates, ranked by total
returns to shareholders over that period, were Gillette, Safeguard
Scientifics, Pfizer, Berkshire Hathaway and Crompton &AMP; Knowles.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Consulting did not disclose the underperformers. Perhaps
they will make for good future clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Site for Diminutive Offerings &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The biggest funds and fund families get lots of attention. But
research has shown that it is often the smallest offerings that
achieve the best results, although they often warrant nary a
mention in business publications.
</P>
<P>
   Enter MAXfunds.com, a mutual fund Web site devoted to covering
new and small funds with assets under $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   The site, free to use, began operations last Tuesday and has
listings for funds without Nasdaq symbols. It includes daily
prices, as well as analysis and tools for researching funds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
