s f BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$A     02-17 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Generally, the Coasts Still Pay the Most &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where you live continues to dictate how much you are paid, with
salaries on the West and East Coasts again outpacing the national
average, according to a new survey by William M. Mercer Inc., a
compensation consulting company based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer's 2000 Geographic Salary Differentials Report, released
this month, found that private employers in San Jose, Calif., in
the heart of Silicon Valley, generally paid the highest salaries.
Second was New York City, followed by San Francisco, Los Angeles
and Stamford, Conn. (Newark was No. 6.)
</P>
<P>
   The lowest pay was in Brownsville, Texas. Others at the bottom
of the list were Albuquerque; Little Rock, Ark.; Birmingham, Ala.;
and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The survey covered more than 200 American cities. It found that
a job with an average salary, nationwide, of $60,000 would pay 17.4
percent more, or $70,440, in San Jose, and 15.4 percent more, or
$69,240, in New York. That same job in Brownsville, however, would
average about 16.1 percent less, or $50,340.
</P>
<P>
   The cities conforming most closely to the average were
Charlotte, N.C., and Richmond, with salaries paying $60,120 and
$59,940, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The survey highlights the challenge faced by large employers
with employees in various parts of the country, said Joyce Cain, a
Mercer consultant in Louisville, Ky., who helped analyze the
report. ``This will help employers set a salary range when
relocating workers, since the cost of labor varies so much by
region,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the survey focused on cities' costs of labor
rather than on general cost-of-living expenses but that one often
reflected the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Silicon Valley, with its high-paying technology jobs, has
led the salary list for the last decade. New York has also ranked
high.
</P>
<P>
   _Vivian Marino
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
