<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKCLUBS20-COX     02-17 1566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKCLUBS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, Feb. 20
 &HT;    Popularity of book clubs growing
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ There was Guiness and Budweiser, and
soda for those who wanted it. And microwave popcorn, bags of it
poured into wooden bowls, enough Jiffy Pop for a January evening.
</P>
<P>
   There were six men dressed comfortably, seated in a circle in
Earl Reid's family room, and one book _ ``Les Miserables.''
Unabridged. War and love and prison and a revolution of ideas in
1,000-plus pages by Victor Hugo.
</P>
<P>
   And there was discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Jean Valjean is his strength, just his
physical strength ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``... this guy was like an all-star wrestler type ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``... when he picked the wagon up off the guy ...''
</P>
<P>
   They talked about Valjean's moral dilemmas, asked each other
whether they, in the same situation, would have been as strong.
Reid began reading a favorite passage, his glasses low on his nose,
words about memory and beauty and love.
</P>
<P>
   ```The supreme happiness of life is the conviction that we are
loved,''' he read. The other men were silent for one breath, then
two and three, looking at their hands or the carpet or the big bowl
of popcorn. Then someone joked he'd seen that on a Hallmark card
and everyone laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said, ``I would just like to commend us for being brilliant
on choosing this book.''
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the Grand Book Club nodded in agreement: It
was a good choice, and some commented that if it hadn't been for
the book club they never would have read ``Les Miserables,''
unabridged or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Book clubs are interesting that way, inspiring people to read
things they normally wouldn't, bringing together diverse
assortments of individuals with an interest in reading and learning
and meeting others who share that interest.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of book clubs is growing. In Mesa County, Colo.,
there are at least 40 book clubs meeting weekly or monthly. There
are about 500,000 book clubs in the United States, said Rachel
Jacobsohn, author of ``The Reading Group Handbook'' and founder of
the Chicago-based Association of Book Group Readers and Leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Book groups have been around for hundreds of years,'' she
said. ``In America, they've had a wellspring of attention for well
over a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed at what I've seen happen in just the last year,''
said Janie VanWinkle, manager of the Grand Junction Barnes &AMP; Noble.
``The book clubs that we've become aware of in the store have
doubled in the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, some credit talk-show host Oprah Winfrey with
leading the renaissance in book reading. In 1996 she founded
Oprah's Book Club in which she picks one book and its author to
profile on her show each month. Each of her book picks has shot
into the best-seller stratosphere after being featured. Winfrey is
credited with helping pump millions of dollars into a recently
revitalized publishing industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's raising the social issues of what authors are
putting into their novels and that's her purpose,'' Jacobsohn said.
``Once readers are lead by Oprah to the pool, to the blessings of
reading a book, now they want to talk about the book and that's
another very positive thing that she's done for the people of this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Winfrey can take credit for inspiring people to read,
the fact that the conservative estimate is 500,000 book clubs
nationally means people are reading and getting together to talk
about what they read.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the phenomenon, publishers of many trade books have
begun printing a reader's guide at the end of books, with questions
and topics for discussion that cater to book clubs. Some people,
such as Carol Benet of Belvedere, Calif., have become freelance
book group facilitators, traveling around the country to host
seminars on how to establish book groups and visiting book groups
to teach members how to prompt discussion, resolve conflicts and
choose books that will educate and enlighten.
</P>
<P>
   With the increase in number of book clubs, the purpose of them
has diversified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one way people can get together and still
maintain the community-type atmosphere on a more intimate level,''
said Dana Weber, owner of Readmoor Books.
</P>
<P>
   At the Feb. 7 meeting of The Reviewers, the oldest book club in
Grand Junction, each member of the club donned a vintage hat
provided by Melba Schmidt, who hosted the meeting, as they listened
to Shirley Ela review ``Annals of the Former World'' by John
McPhee. The women tried on different hats before the meeting began,
laughing and admiring the feathers and flowers on each other's
hats, which provided a catalyst for conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The group formed in 1892 as the Isabella Ivy Tourist Club, a
group of Grand Valley women who wanted to broaden their education
as they prepared to travel to the World Exposition. It became The
Reviewers in 1904 and since then has established the Ottman Shelf
at the Mesa County Public Library for donations from group members,
and uses the membership dues to buy flowers for group members who
lose a loved one and wine for the spring party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Book groups are a source of social camaraderie and are a mode
of continuing education,'' Jacobsohn said. ``It's a way for people
to be face-to-face with each other in kind of an intimate setting
where they can exercise their hearts and their minds at the time
time. It provides a safe atmosphere for discussion, it's a way to
learn about others, learn about characters in a book, learn about
how others respond, learn about yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mesa County, there are groups in which one person reviews a
book for the other members _ such as The Reviewers _ and groups in
which everyone reads the book and discusses it. The Grand Book Club
consists of just men, and some groups, such as Seasoned Women and
Monumental Women, are just for women. Some meet in the morning,
others in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Friday Morning Book Group, which meets September through May
and is a branch of the local American Association of University
Women, has one person present the book, which group members read
before the meeting, with extensive background on the author and the
book. Sometimes the presenter has a guest speaker if the book's
topic facilitates it. At the Jan. 21 meeting, Anita Johnson
presented ``Midwives'' by Chris Bohjalian, about a midwife who is
accused of killing a woman on whom she performed an emergency
Caesarean delivery, and asked Janet Grant from Mesa Midwives to
speak to the group about midwifery.
</P>
<P>
   Grant spoke about Colorado regulations for midwives, a midwife's
role in pre-natal care and delivery and answered questions from
group members about a physician's role in midwifery, hard
deliveries and delivery protocols. They shared stories of their own
deliveries and discussed in quiet voices with the women sitting by
them whether they would have wanted a midwife to deliver their
children.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsohn said some book groups have a more social dynamic while
others are more literary and academic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking about a book can be social,'' she said. ``There are a
lot of book groups that say, 'Did you like the book? Who's going to
play the character in the movie?' and then eat and have
conversation. Then there are people who are highly academic, who do
intense literary criticism of the book.''
</P>
<P>
   She said it depends on the reading experience a person wants and
what a person wants from the book group, whether it's to meet
people with similar interests or to hash out the symbols and
metaphors and literary devices of a particular book.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding which book group to join, she said, it sometimes
helps to look at the group's previous reading selections. Sometimes
groups read just classics, or only prize winners, or science
fiction, or nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, the selections vary widely depending on what
sounds interesting and is picked by the group's selection committee
or because one member suggests a certain book that sounds
interesting. At the end of Grand Book Club's Jan. 17 meeting,
member Steve Watson suggested ``Epitaph of a Small Winner'' as
their next book and everyone agreed. In their more than 12 years of
book discussion, club members also have read ``Generation X,''
``Hamlet,'' ``Rendezvous with Rama,'' ``Tropic of Cancer,'' ``Iron
John,'' ``Othello,'' ``Texasville,'' ``The Firm,'' ``Walden'' and
``Death Comes for the Archbishop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just like getting together and talking about what we've
read,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   So on a January evening he had his shoes off and his feet
propped comfortably on a coffee table, a copy of ``Les Miserables''
open on his lap. ``This cat was a genius,'' he said, referring to
Hugo, and the discussion meandered from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took world history in high school,'' Dennis Kirtland
said, ``it was probably one of the dullest things I've ever done
because all we did was memorize dates of battles. This makes it
real.''
</P>
<P>
   ``... I think Hugo loved Napoleon ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``... My problem is I want to skip over some of the stuff like
Waterloo but I'm afraid I'll miss something ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``... When she had to sell her teeth that was so pitiful ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``... Isn't it fun to discover a book like this?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
