<HEADLINE>
ELLIOTT ENDS DROUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS AND JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ After riding around in circles for the
past five years, Bill Elliott finally found his way back to Victory
Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who had not won any race since Sept. 4, 1994, took the
checkered flag in yesterday's first Twin 125 qualifying race at
Daytona International Speedway. He will start third Sunday in the
Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this is more for the \Rcrew\S guys who worked to
put this car together than for me, because they made it easy for
Bill Elliott to sit in Victory Lane,'' said Elliott, who passed
Dale Jarrett on the first lap and led all 50 laps. ``All the guys
with the long hours and the hard work and the weekends they didn't
have off, it's a reward for those guys to be able to put it all
together and sit in Victory Lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's last victory, which came at Darlington, was the 40th
of his career. On Sunday, he will try to end his streak of 169
points races without a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we can win,'' said Elliott, who has two Daytona
500 victories. ``You've just got to have a little bit of luck on
your side.'' AROUND AND AROUND
</P>
<P>
   The second time around was not as sweet for Joe Nemechek.
Nemechek had the top speed in yesterday's second-round qualifying
for the NAPA Auto Parts 300, turning a 187.141 mph lap around the
2.5-mile trioval.
</P>
<P>
   But Nemechek will start only 26th tomorrow in the Busch Series
race.
</P>
<P>
   His speed of 189.225 mph, which was the fastest in Wednesday's
pole qualifying, was disallowed after the post-qualifying
inspection. Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's director of operations, said
the wheel weight distribution on the No. 87 Chevrolet was outside
the allowed parameters. FINE TIME
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials fined Jason Shapiro $2,000 for his part in the
fight between drivers Tony Stewart and Robby Gordon in the garage
area Wednesday. Shapiro, a crew member on Stewart's No. 20 team,
threw a punch at Gordon that was caught on video tape.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Gordon had to be separated after an angry exchange
precipitated by Gordon's complaints that Stewart had not given him
enough room during a Winston Cup practice session in which Stewart
sent Gordon's car spinning with a tap from behind. SCHEDULE
SPECULATION
</P>
<P>
   The green flag has not fallen on the start of the 2000 NASCAR
Winston Cup schedule, so naturally, speculation already is rampant
about the 2001 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   New speedways in Kansas City, Kan., and Joliet, Ill., outside
Chicago, are scheduled to be completed this year, and both are in
markets coveted by NASCAR. Asked where those racetracks might fit
into the 2001 schedule, NASCAR official Mike Helton hinted that the
tracks would be slotted into one of the open weekends remaining on
the 10-month tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already thinking about 2001,'' said Helton, NASCAR's
senior vice president and chief executive officer. ``And as we
start piecing that together, you could look at the 2000 schedule
and see there's only very few holes in it that you could plug races
in. But there are opportunities to plug races in. That's what we'll
be looking at _ how many we can \Radd\S and where they go.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the 2000 schedule as a guideline, there are five open Cup
weekends between Feb. 13 and Nov. 21. After eliminating the
traditional off weekends for Easter Sunday and Mother's Day, that
leaves two open dates in July and one in October. DODGE READIES
LINEUP
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler and Dodge officially will announce the
manufacturer's 2001 Winston Cup lineup during a news conference
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cup crew chief Ray Evernham, who is point man for Dodge's
return to NASCAR's premier series, already has announced that he
will field a two-car team. Speculation is that Petty Enterprises,
whose history with Mopar dates to the glory days of seven-time Cup
champion Richard Petty, will leave Pontiac for the Dodge camp with
Kyle Petty, son Adam, and John Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   The other team rumored to be heading to Dodge is Bill Davis
Racing, which is fielding Pontiacs for Ward Burton and rookie Dave
Blaney. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
