 STRONG TURNOUT IN SOUTH CAROLINA COULD BENEFIT McCAIN  
 (EDS: This is the precede of a six-part package. The other five
stories are SC-VOICES-CONSERVATIVES, SC-VOICES-LOWCOUNTRY,
SC-VOICES-SUBURBS, SC-VOICES-BLACKS and SC-VOICES-RETIREES.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT32-33 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ No one who has spent much time talking to South
Carolina voters the last couple of days would hazard a guess as to
the likely winner of Saturday's pivotal Republican primary here.
</P>
<P>
   That is because it is so hard to judge exactly who will vote.
All the polls show that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is the heavy
favorite of the Republicans, but Sen. John McCain of Arizona is
preferred by most independents and Democrats, who are free to vote
in the Republican contest, the only one scheduled on Saturday. But
who will turn out? Tough to say, because there is no precise
precedent for the primary.
</P>
<P>
   In detailed conversations with voters in five locations across
the state, from the wealthy enclave of retirees at Hilton Head to
the conservative heartland of Greenville and the upstate region
surrounding it, no clear pattern emerged _ except this: it is an
agonizingly close race, one that often divides best buddies and
married couples. Of 34 people interviewed in Greenville, for
example, where Bush is counted the favorite, 17 said they backed
McCain, 15 said they backed Bush and 2 were unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Among religious conservatives at a Baptist church supper in
Mount Pleasant, an affluent suburb of Charleston, there were solid
pockets of support not only for Bush and McCain but also the third
contender in the race, Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   Using much more scientific means, the latest Palmetto Poll,
conducted by Clemson University between Feb. 11 and 17, suggested a
Bush victory by 49 percent to 47 percent if 18.6 percent of
registered voters took part, as they did in the 1996 primary
elections. But if the turnout climbs much above 19 percent, the
poll indicated, the result might well be a McCain victory. The
survey involved 450 people who have been active in elections here
since 1984, and had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3.3
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key factor will be turnout,'' said Dave Woodard, a
professor of political science at Clemson. ``It's difficult to
predict turnout because previous elections have featured contests
in both political parties. The absence of a Democratic primary this
year could boost participation by crossover voters in the GOP
contest. That would favor McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, McCain appeals again and again to potential
crossover voters. Thursday, on his campaign bus, he said he wanted
to broaden the Republican Party _ he described it as ``an inclusive
party, the party of Abraham Lincoln and Teddy Roosevelt and Ronald
Reagan'' _ in the same way President Clinton had broadened the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In Forest Acres, a Columbia suburb, a significant number of
Reagan Democrats, independents and ticket-splitters said they would
vote for McCain, many despite disagreements with him on issues. In
Hilton Head, some retirees from the Northeast and Midwest spoke of
crossing over.
</P>
<P>
   But in Orangeburg, in the middle of the state, black Democrats _
a bulwark of the South Carolina Democratic party _ said they had no
intention of voting Saturday. Any temptation was eliminated,
several said, by McCain's and Bush's refusal to speak out
unequivocally against displaying the Confederate flag over the
state capitol here in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   All across the state, McCain voters spoke not so much of his
views but of his character. Walter Ferguson, 37, a pastry
distributor in Goose Creek, near Charleston, described McCain as an
anti-Clinton. A Republican, Ferguson commented: ``Clinton puts his
finger to the wind before he decides what to say. Not McCain. He's
not afraid of offending people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's counterattacks here on McCain, the decisive victor in the
New Hampshire primary, are bearing fruit. Elizabeth Thrash, 73, who
reported retiring recently for the third and last time, said she
decided this week to back Bush because she heard that ``McCain has
been married several times'' _ he has been married twice _ and
because she concluded that the senator was ``a bit too liberal for
an ultraconservative like me.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no broad agreement on whether Bush had been helped or
hurt by his parents. Some said his family was a key reason for
backing the governor, but others, like Bill Brent, 70, a Republican
retiree, disagreed. Brent said disdainfully, ``I don't want no
dynasty going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
