<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOILER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE OF MORAL DECAY RAPIDLY LOSES STEAM IN `BOILER ROOM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the opening moments of ``Boiler Room,'' its young
hero-narrator recites some choice examples of the
get-rich-quick-on-stock-options mythology that has created the
great gold-rush sensibility of our time (including the fact that
Microsoft has more ``millionaire secretaries'' than any company in
history).
</P>
<P>
   And for most of its first act, the film shrewdly chronicles the
subtle moral decay that inevitably goes hand in hand with such a
sensibility _ and does it with such enjoyably flamboyant characters
and a deliciously hard-boiled dialogue that the story constantly
verges on being special.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the film falls apart rather badly in its third
act, and ends up being empty, anti-climactic and overlong. Still,
before it fades into nothingness, the film powers along nicely and
proves to be a strong showcase for first-time writer-director Ben
Younger.
</P>
<P>
   It tells the story of Seth Davis (Giovanni Ribisi), a wayward
but highly enterprising _ he runs his own casino _ young man
recruited to work as a stockbroker in a disreputable Long Island
brokerage firm: a boiler room that always operates on the edge of
SEC laws, and sometimes on the other side of them.
</P>
<P>
   The film is essentially a morality tale that follows Seth from
apprenticeship to big success as a broker _ as he learns to
ruthlessly con his clients (and destroy the lives of some of them
in the process) and otherwise compromise himself so that he comes
into increasing conflict with his federal judge father (Ron
Rifkin).
</P>
<P>
   It's a blatant combination of ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' and ``Wall
Street'' (both are generously referenced throughout the film) _
with a slight dash of ``The Firm.'' But it also tries to be unique,
and to address the particular corruption of American society by the
crazed tech-stock boom of the late '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Younger crates a rich tapestry of distinctive
performances, not just from the jaded Ribisi and the almost
frighteningly sanctimonious Rifkin, but also from Ben Affleck (in
perhaps his career-best performance) as an oily company recruiter
and Vin Diesel, Nicky Katt and Tom Everett Scott as a trio of
splendidly sleazy salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Younger also uses a fast-paced, slightly disorienting visual
style (counterpointed by blasts of rap music) that seems just right
for the story; and the kind of witty and evocative dialogue that
manages to reveal character, sum up the milieu and entertain at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   What ``Boiler Room'' does not have is the kind of satisfying
script that can draw us into its train wreck of a story on an
emotional level, and leave us feeling fulfilled by its destination.
Like so many young directors trained on video, Younger could use
the services of a writing partner with the novelistic and
structural skills he so obviously has not yet acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Boiler Room. Directed and written by Ben Younger. Cast: Giovanni
Ribisi, Vin Diesel, Ben Affleck, Ron Rifkin, Nicky Katt, Nia Long.
New Line Cinema. 110 minutes. Rated R for language and some
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
