A0275 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-HANGING-SPI &LR;      02-17 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HANGING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANGING UP'S' APPEAL IS A MEG RYAN CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your reaction to ``Hanging Up,'' the latest domestic
comedy-drama from the pen of Nora Ephron, will depend largely on
how much you like Meg Ryan. Because, even though she shares the
marquee with four other stars, she's pretty much the whole show.
</P>
<P>
   If you find her distinctive persona to be too irritatingly cute
to bear, this mannered movie is likely to play like fingernails on
a blackboard and drive you straight up the wall.
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, you respond to her elfin charm (and I
guess I do), this fourth and probably least inspired Ryan-Ephron
collaboration (after ``When Harry Met Sally ... ,'' ``Sleepless in
Seattle'' and ``You've Got Mail'') gets by, barely.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel by Ephron's sister (and writing partner) Delia,
it's the story of three sisters who have to deal with the
incapacitation of their unpleasant and increasingly senile
screenwriter father (Walter Matthau).
</P>
<P>
   The oldest is Georgia (Diane Keaton), a 50ish, self-centered
magazine publisher; the middle sister is Eve (Ryan), a wife and
mother in her 30s with her own party-planning business; and the
youngest is Maddy (Lisa Kudrow), a shallow, Gen-X dilettante and
soap-opera actor.
</P>
<P>
   Eve has always been the closest to her father. The movie follows
her plight as he becomes so mentally unstable that he finally has
to be hospitalized and she has to struggle with the situation while
fighting with her unsupportive husband (Adam Arkin) and trying to
put together a big event at the Nixon Library.
</P>
<P>
   She spends the entire movie in a state of heightened
exasperation, frequently lapsing into painful flashbacks, and
constantly screaming into her cell phone at her two insensitive
sisters, who are more than happy to let her carry the entire burden
of their father's disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   In its lesser scenes, the Keaton and Kudrow characters seem too
contrived and broadly played to believe, and Keaton (who took over
directorial duties from Ephron) has trouble making some of that
very stylized Ephron dialogue work.
</P>
<P>
   In its better scenes, however, the film communicates the anguish
of a domestic trauma that many people face and it has a handful of
warm, tender and funny moments _ most notably Eve's unlikely
friendship with an Iranian doctor (Duke Moosekian) she meets cute
when she crashes into his Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   For Ryan fans, the movie also serves as a strong star vehicle.
Throughout, she's simply radiant _ Howard Atherton's camera is in
love with her _ and her pain and epic frustration in the face of an
overwhelming emotional crisis seems so real that it creates an
exquisite, if fleeting, sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging Up. Directed by Diane Keaton. Screenplay by Delia Ephron
and Nora Ephron. Cast: Meg Ryan, Diane Keaton, Lisa Kudrow, Walter
Matthau. Columbia. 92 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual references
and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
