<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0276 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-PITCH-SPI &LR;      02-17 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PITCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF `ROAD WARRIOR' MET `ALIEN,' `PITCH BLACK' WOULD BE THE
OFFSPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though it's riddled with some of the lamest, dumbest
dialogue imaginable, ``Pitch Black'' is a total guilty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   It benefits from its Australian outback location and a nice
blend of Aussie talent, including newcomer Radha Mitchell (``Love
and Other Catastrophes'') and seasoned veterans Lewis Fitz-Gerald
(``Breaker Morant'') and Simon Burke (``The Devil's Playground''),
which it mixes with such American actors as Vin Diesel (``Saving
Private Ryan'') and Cole Hauser (``Good Will Hunting'').
</P>
<P>
   And while it borrows heavily from the best in the sci-fi
thriller genre _ Ridley Scott's ``Alien'' _ it has just enough of
its own style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch Black'' follows that ``Alien's'' formula _ a crew
piloting a spacecraft crash-lands on, this time, a desolate and
arid planet that is warmed to the boiling point by three suns.
</P>
<P>
   Its surviving passengers include a docking pilot (Mitchell); a
cop (Hauser) transporting a dangerous prisoner (Diesel); a Muslim
cleric (Keith David) traveling with his three disciples; an
antiquities dealer (Fitz-Gerald) and a teenage runaway (Rhiana
Griffith).
</P>
<P>
   With limited water and a damaged craft, the group begins to
explore the unknown territory looking for anything to help repair
the ship. They discover a deserted mining camp scattered with
bleached out bones and no sign of life.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, they're about to discover that lack of water
isn't their only problem. Something else is out there; something
that hides from the sunlight and waits for the arrival of new
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Director David Twohy, who has had some luck in the sci-fi genre
_ he did a passable job on the 1996 film ``The Arrival'' _ goes all
out visually, fabricating a terrific look for ``Pitch Black.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the film's flair is culled more from ``The Road
Warrior'' than ``Alien'' and the movie defies categorization into
straight science fiction or action genres. It could be called a
post-apocalyptic thriller and it's desaturated look and ``Mad Max''
mentality make it a fun-to-watch picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch Black'' tweaks and twists convention just enough to have
an individual pulse. And in doing so it manages to keep our pulses
ats racing, providing enough of a taut, stylishly gripping
ride to separate it from all the other ``Alien'' ripoffs that
crashed to earth.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch Black. Directed by David Twohy. Written by Jim Wheat, Ken
Wheat, Twohy. Cast: Vin Diesel, Radha Mitchell, Cole Hauser, Keith
David. USA Films. 107 minutes. Rated R for violence, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
