<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-17 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CANDIDATES DENOUNCE WASHINGTON BUT SPEND MILLIONS TO GET
THERE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Feb. 20)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the current presidential campaign, this city has
come to resemble a glamorous woman of myriad charms and
questionable virtue who is denounced publicly by men gathering
funds to help them pay for her expensive favors.
</P>
<P>
   A major paradox of the quest for the presidency is that the
contenders are spending millions of dollars to win the White House
while, in their political demagoguery, they describe Washington as
a synonym for evil.
</P>
<P>
   When John McCain decided to stop running negative ads in the
South Carolina primary and challenged George W. Bush to do the
same, Bush rejected the idea, calling it an ``old Washington
trick.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't claim it to be an old Texas or Arizona or California
or New York trick although political chicanery and deceit are not
foreign to those states. He simply indulged in a bit of campaign
hyperbole regarding a city he can't wait to live in.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing for a massive tax cut, the governor, who has raised
some $70 million to pay his fare to Washington, claims the
reduction is needed because if the budget surplus is ``left in
Washington, it will be spent.'' Again, Washington is the symbolic
culprit.
</P>
<P>
   He would not let Washington determine his tax cut, Bush said in
his South Carolina debate last week with McCain and Alan Keyes,
because the ``Washington mentality'' is to base such action on
politics and polls rather than the needs of the people.
</P>
<P>
   In vowing to break the Washington ``gridlock'' Bush does not
mention the fact that half of that gridlock is a Congress run by
his own party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust Congress I trust the people,'' Bush proclaimed
in South Carolina, ignoring the fact that members of the House and
Senate are the elected representatives of the people.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, meanwhile, has vowed that, if elected, he would break
the ``Washington triangle of big money, lobbyists and
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Bill Bradley, the lanky basketball
legend who served 18 years in the Senate before retiring in 1997,
also has found it profitable, as part of his ``new politics''
campaign, to take some old-politics swats at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Only Al Gore, who as vice president is an integral of the
Washington establishment, has refrained from slamming the city,
although he did find it politically profitable to move his campaign
headquarters to Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's capital is far from an ideal community. It has its
share of crime, double-dealing, graft, sin, waste and lying. Its
most exalted residents have been known to indulge in adultery and
to use the money and power at their disposal to further their
political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   As in other cities _ such as Austin, Phoenix, Sacramento and
Albany _ where governors and legislators jockey for political gain,
partisanship often is the prevailing influence.
</P>
<P>
   Just about every major American business and many foreign
corporations have offices in the Washington area, which encompasses
large sections of Maryland and Virginia. Most of these firms hire
well-paid lobbyists to help them win favors from Congress and the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But, as bad as critics claim it is, Washington is visited by
thousands of eager tourists each year. They clamor to see the White
House, Congress and the fabulous network of museums, art galleries
and memorials that illuminate the city.
</P>
<P>
   When they climb to the top of the Washington Monument, they
thrill at the view below. At the Lincoln Memorial, tears may fill
their eyes as they read the compassionate message of Lincoln's
</P>
<P>
   second inaugural at the end of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jefferson Memorial, they are inspired by the immortal
words of the Declaration of Independence. At the Franklin D.
Roosevelt Memorial, older Americans relive the dramatic moments of
the Great Depression and World War II while younger ones get a
vital lesson in history.
</P>
<P>
   At the Vietnam Memorial people may find the name of a relative
or friend who perished in that horrible war. Across the river, in
Arlington National Cemetery, they may discover the grave of a loved
one who died at Belleau Wood, Anzio, Guadalcanal, the Battle of the
Bulge or in deadly combat in the mountains of Korea, the jungles of
Vietnam and the desert sands of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has decided that there is political gold to be mined in
bludgeoning the nation's capital with vitriolic rhetoric. He rarely
misses an opportunity to announce that his zip code is in Austin
and not Washington.
</P>
<P>
   That is supposed to separate the good guys from the bad guys.
And in Bush's campaign portfolio, Washington is the home of the bad
guys.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of Washington should not be whitewashed. They
should be confronted and solved. Schools and education are in bad
shape. Traffic is horrendous. Crime, though way down, is still
prevalent. Some government employees, like some members of
Congress, have adopted a cavalier attitude toward spending federal
funds.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted, however, that the vast majority of people
living in Washington and its suburbs are decent, hard-working
individuals who are the backbone of our government's operations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush might ponder the fact that his father spent 20 eventful
years in this city, serving two terms in the House and acting as
chairman of the Republican National Committee, director of the CIA,
Ronald Reagan's vice president and, for four years, as president.
</P>
<P>
   Had it been the evil city his son makes it out to be, the elder
Bush would not have sought a second term as president.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
