<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-VOICES-SUBURBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURBANITES PLAYING UP CHARACTER AND PLYING CROSSOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is part of a six-story package. The other five stories
are SC-VOICES, SC-VOICES-CONSERVATIVES, SC-VOICES-LOWCOUNTRY,
SC-VOICES-BLACKS and SC-VOICES-RETIREES.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT32 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOREST ACRES, S.C. _ When Sen. John McCain's campaign decided it
wanted to hold a rally in a Jewish community in South Carolina, it
asked to use the parking lot of the Beth Shalom Synagogue in this
suburb of Columbia. There were a only a few grumblings in the
congregation, said Rabbi Philip Silverstein _ the campaign had
chosen its neighborhood well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an honorable man,'' said Silverstein, who described
himself as a ``Scoop Jackson liberal'' who later became a fan of
Ronald Reagan and is now enthusiastically behind McCain. ``I don't
agree with everything of his _ the campaign finance plan is too
much government. But I was a 20-year military chaplain, and I like
his character. This year, that's the issue behind all issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In a state dominated by conservatives, it is telling that McCain
wanted to speak to this suburb at all. Few white neighborhoods in
the state can be called liberal, but Forest Acres is full of the
independents, ticket-splitters and Reagan Democrats that McCain
needs to turn out in force if he is to win Saturday's Republican
primary.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with about 30 neighborhood residents, nearly half
said they were non-Republicans who planned to vote in the primary
for McCain, with some voting in a Republican primary for the first
time, taking advantage of its open registration system. Almost
everyone who regularly votes Republican, however, planned to vote
for Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Almost without exception, crossover voters said they disagreed
with many of McCain's positions, particularly his opposition to
abortion. But they dismissed such differences as minor, saying they
admired his character and believed he was more trustworthy than
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want someone who isn't going to lie to me,'' said
Eunice Jacobs, a retiree who was browsing through the
Books-A-Million store in a shopping mall here. ``He seems like
someone who isn't going to mess up the country and make me feel
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Several McCain supporters made it clear they would not be voting
for him in November. David Waldman, program director of the
Columbia Jewish Community Center, said he would have voted in the
Democratic primary if it had not been canceled. But to exercise his
voting rights, he will choose McCain as the lesser of two
Republican evils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little worried that voters are making him what they want
him to be, in their own mind,'' said Waldman, a Democrat. ``After
all, he's a conservative politician. But at least he isn't the
vapid, empty-headed politician that Bush is.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, however, whether this incorporated suburb, which
voted for Bob Dole in 1996 but elected a Democrat to the state
House of Representatives two years later, has enough independents
and Democrats to counterbalance a large number of Republicans
supporting Bush. In today's unscientific survey here, there were
about an equal number of Bush and McCain voters, but those who plan
to support Bush were much firmer in their conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has the business experience, and that's important,'' said
David James, a pharmaceutical salesman. ``McCain is just a career
politician.
</P>
<P>
   Several people said they liked Bush's family, and admired him as
a ``regular guy'' who seemed to understand them. Only one person
who regularly votes Republican said he was supporting McCain, and
he was the most conservative person interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very pro-life, and he's a real straight talker,'' said
Thomas Davis, who works in the Family Christian Bookstore in the
Columbia Mall. ``If I could, I'd vote for Alan Keyes, but he can't
win, so I'm going with McCain.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
