u f BC-REGIONAL-JETS-ART-2TA     02-17 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REGIONAL-JETS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES ARE INCREASINGLY REPLACING TURBOPROPS WITH REGIONAL JETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT29 and a graphic are being sent. Non-subscribers
can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many other airline passengers, Michael Gallagher has gone
out of his way to avoid flying a turboprop plane. When he attended
an Orbital Sciences shareholder meeting a few years ago in
Washington, for example, he changed his schedule at the last minute
to fly on a jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been a nervous flyer,'' said Gallagher, who
lives in Cortland, N.Y. ``On a turboprop plane, you just get
bounced around too much.'' Gallagher and others may soon find an
easier path to a smoother flight. The battle to attract more
passengers from smaller markets has become so intense that airlines
are now scrambling to replace their turboprop planes with jets.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next three years, Continental Airlines will spend
around $2 billion to supplant all its turboprops with regional
jets: twin-engine planes that can carry up to 70 passengers. Delta
Air Lines will pay $4 billion for 200 regional jets and start
service to 100 cities.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every major airline is stocking its fleet with
regional jets. According to estimates by PaineWebber, American,
Continental, United and Northwest Airlines will more than double
the number of regional jets operated by their feeder airlines in
the next three years, giving passengers in smaller markets more
flight choices than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The orders are going primarily to the two big makers of regional
jets, Empresa Brasileira de Aeronautica, or Embraer, of Brazil and
Bombardier of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Though the average regional jet costs $20 million, nearly double
the price of a comparable turboprop, the airlines feel the switch
is well worth it. ``Turboprop planes are not an attractive
product,'' said Leo F. Mullin, chief executive of Delta.
``Passengers view them as second-rate service. With a regional jet,
passengers are more comfortable, and we can use them to serve more
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   An informal survey by Delta recently found that its passengers
hate turboprops so much that most are willing to drive two to five
hours to avoid flying in them. Most major carriers depend heavily
on their regional fleets for feeder traffic _ passengers from a
smaller market who connect to the major carrier at a hub airport.
American Airlines, a unit of AMR, and Delta, for example, each
receive about $1 billion in annual revenue from their regional
fleets.
</P>
<P>
   There will still be a place for turboprops, primarily on short
flights provided by independent regional carriers. At the end of
last year, in fact, there were about 1,350 turboprops in use
compared with about 410 regional jets, according to the Regional
Airline Association.
</P>
<P>
   The switch to regional jets _ R.J.'s in airline lingo _ should,
however, significantly increase the major airlines' sales in
smaller and midsize markets.
</P>
<P>
   Turboprops have a flight span of only 500 miles, about half that
of regional jets, which can serve markets that had been beyond a
turboprop's reach. They are also cheaper to operate on longer
routes. They are expected to attract passengers close to small
airports who have been reluctant to fly primarily because of a fear
of turboprops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing about regional jets is not that they are
more cost efficient than turboprops,'' said Samuel Buttrick, an
airlines analyst with PaineWebber. ``The airlines expect to get
more revenue from regional jets by selling more seats in what is a
preferred product.''
</P>
<P>
   The major carriers also hope to swap larger jets with regional
jets on flights that do not sell out. But that is not likely to
become a common practice anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Airline Pilots Association, which covers most major carriers
in the United States and Canada, is so fearful that regional jets
could take work away from its members that most labor contracts
with the airlines restrict how many such aircraft an airline can
own as well as the number of seats on each plane. After receiving
its shipments for 26 new regional jets next year, for instance,
United Airlines, a unit of UAL, will not be able to buy another
without permission from its pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the pilots' resistance and other barriers could be
overcome, the airlines would like to develop ``on-demand
dispatch,'' industry code for a last-minute equipment swap. If a
flight from La Guardia to Chicago on a Boeing 737 was, say, only a
quarter full, the airline could substitute a regional jet and avoid
losing money on unsold seats. Such a swap, of course, is likely to
irritate passengers who prefer the larger jets.
</P>
<P>
   Airline executives are confident, however, that regional jets
will become popular alternatives to their propellered predecessors,
though there is less consensus on exactly what constitutes a
regional jet. Most industry executives agree that its flight span
is 1,000 miles or less, but they are less clear on the number of
seats the plane can contain. Some said regional jets could have as
many as 100 seats, while others deferred to their pilots'
contracts, many of which dictate a total of no more than 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``The definition of a regional jet can get fuzzy,'' said Tom
Bacon, a senior vice president for marketing and planning at
American Eagle, the regional carrier of American Airlines. ``But
we're beginning to think of regional jets in terhe new
service with the cities that we can connect.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of passengers on regional jets has already begun to
surge, increasing 20 percent in the first nine months of 1999 over
the corresponding period a year earlier, according to the Regional
Airline Association. The number of seats available increased 18.2
percent, while the length of the average trip rose 9.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passengers have clearly decided that they do not want to fly
on turboprop planes,'' said Susan Donofrio, an airline analyst at
Deutsche Banc. Alex. Brown. ``But the regional jets offer other
advantages. The airlines can make sure that they have quality
feeder service. When passengers start a trip, they are more likely
to stay on that airline to make connections.''
</P>
<P>
   In the scramble to gain more passengers from smaller cities, the
regional jet is fast becoming the airlines' most effective weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Airline executives have known for decades that passengers
avoided turboprops like the flu, but used them anyway, in part
because second-tier cities were not important enough for the $20
million capital investment required to buy a new regional jet.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, however, markets that were once shunned as
too small have grown rapidly. And executives from these smaller
markets had the same turboprop complaints as their big-city
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the perception among some passengers that turboprops
are not safe,'' said Glen Hauenstein, the vice president for
scheduling at Continental. ``Turboprops vibrate and the passengers
can see the propellers. ''
</P>
<P>
   (The rate of accidents involving turboprops in 1996, the latest
year statistics are available, was small, only 3.62 for every
100,000 miles flown, but more than twice the accident rate of
turbojets, according to the National Transportation Safety Board.)
</P>
<P>
   Regional jets can also fly farther, faster and more smoothly
than turboprops. But even more important for attracting passengers
from smaller but growing cities is that the airlines can use them
to create more nonstop flights. Executives, who buy only 20 percent
of the airlines' tickets but account for about half of the industry
profits, avoid multistop flights as much as they shun turboprops.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw in some of our markets was that the flight was
just too long for a turboprop,'' Bacon of American Eagle said. ``A
turboprop could have made it from Boston to Norfolk, but it would
not have been competitive service. Some of our competitors would
have offered a nonstop flight.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
