<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-REGIONAL &LR; - &UR; JETS-ART-2     02-17 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REGIONAL </SLUG>
 - JETS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT 
UNDATED: nonstop flight.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An example of the scuffling over smaller markets has been
playing out in Greenville-Spartanburg, an area of two counties with
about 650,000 people in the South Carolina foothills. In the last
10 years, the area has become a manufacturing mecca, where
Michelin, the French tire maker, is planning a big expansion and
where roadsters are built for BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The area was served primarily by Delta, through its hub in
Atlanta, until Continental began nonstop Continental Express
service to Newark from Greenville a few years ago and then between
Greenville and Houston. The combination of more flights from the
Northeast and an opening to the West lured many passengers away
from Delta. Within a year, Delta's share of the
Greenville-Spartanburg market plunged from 84 percent to 23
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has not taken its massacre in Greenville-Spartanburg
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Through its regional fleet, Delta Connection, it has begun an
aggressive push to expand its presence in smaller markets. After
spending $2.6 billion last year to buy two of its regional carriers
_ Comair and Atlantic Southeast Airlines _ Delta recently replaced
American Eagle as the nation's largest regional carrier, according
to the Regional Airline Association.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year, Delta Connection will own more regional
jets than any other airline. And it is wasting no time deploying
them. The airline recently started service between Worcester,
Mass., and nine cities, including Denver, Atlanta and Myrtle Beach,
S.C. Within the next two months, it will start regional jet service
with daily flights from La Guardia to six cities, including
Richmond and Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens with a regional jet is that you can give some
smaller cities big-market access,'' said Frederick W. Reid, Delta's
chief marketing officer. ``The next step in our expansion will be
to start connecting some of the smaller cities with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The connections are some of the least expensive deals the
airlines have been able to make. Because they are very fuel
efficient once they reach cruising altitude, regional jets cost
only 10 cents an air mile on longer routes, those that are 500 to
1,000 miles long, compared with 19 cents for turboprops.
(Turboprops are, however, a lot less expensive to operate on
shorter hops.)
</P>
<P>
   When replacing larger jets, regional jets can also save money at
the gate. Delta said it could park three regional jets in the space
that it uses to park, say, a 737. Analysts estimate that could
reduce gate fees by some 10 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Delta recently made such a swap on its routes between Atlanta
and Grand Rapids, Mich., after too many seats on the 737s were left
unfilled. To draw more people, Delta added three daily flights.
</P>
<P>
   Given the advantages of regional jets, airline executives may
soon be more irked that they cannot deploy more. But they are not
likely to press the sensitive issue too hard, at least for now,
with the airline pilots unions.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the love affair with regional jets is not shared by
some passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fly turboprops or regional jets,'' said Paul Tauger, a
lawyer in Costa Mesa, Calif. ``I took a regional jet from Fort
Lauderdale to Dallas, and the luggage compartment was not big
enough for my carry-on bag. After that, with airplanes, I don't
downsize anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
