<HEADLINE>
COZYING UP TO LABOR, GORE VOWS TO SHIFT CHINA TRADE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ In seeking to please organized labor and inspire
it to work hard for his election, Vice President Al Gore could
become a potent weapon against his own administration.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders meeting here said that behind closed doors
Thursday, Gore had reiterated his pledge that if he is elected
president, he will negotiate a tougher trade agreement with China
than President Clinton has. He also said he would include labor and
environmental matters in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did say that he favored the admission of China to the World
Trade Organization and that he wanted Congress to give Clinton's
agreement the green light. And his spokesman said he would do
whatever Clinton asked him to do to prod Congress toward approving
normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   But the message that organized labor, which has endorsed Gore,
received was this: The vice president favors their view that any
agreement should include labor and environmental matters.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders emerged from their session with him with what
appeared a nod and wink: While they did not expect Gore to be
disloyal to his president, they said, they did expect that his
preference for a tougher agreement could help them defeat Clinton's
efforts to remove trade barriers against the Chinese. At the least,
they said, it could delay a vote, now set for this summer, until an
agreement could be renegotiated by a Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see that it's delayed, because we will be
better off,'' said George Becker, president of the United
Steelworkers Union, after the session between Gore and the nearly
50 members of the executive council of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to give a Gore administration the opportunity to
deal with this,'' he said. ``In any agreement that goes forward in
a Gore administration, we expect to have enforceable labor rights
and human rights into the core agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   As the showdown over the trade vote in Congress nears, Gore's
delicate balancing act _ as a presidential candidate in favor of
one kind of agreement, and the vice president of an administration
that is promoting another _ is coming into sharper focus.
</P>
<P>
   The situation prompted some delicately chosen wording Thursday
as both labor and the Gore campaign attempted to explain the vice
president's dual aims.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference between being No. 1 and No. 2 ,'' John
J. Sweeney, president of the federation, said jovially after the
private session.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has said that he supports the president and
the president's position,'' Sweeney said. ``But he did say, and he
said it in Los Angeles, that when he's president, he will support
core labor standards and environmental protections as part of our
trade agreements. Essentially, we know what he means, and he knows
what we support.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Harnage, president of the American Federation of
Government Employees, said: ``He's not going to say anything
against Clinton. He's a gentleman, and he's there to support
Clinton. But there's been times that he's disagreed with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not make himself available to reporters Thursday. But
Chris Lehane, his spokesman, put it this way: ``He's still vice
president and will do whatever he can to help the president. But
having said that, he also said that in future trade agreements, we
will make it more open for labor, environment and human-rights
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   George Becker, president of the United Steelworkers Union, had
another formulation: ``We're not putting any pressure on him, we're
not putting him under the gun at all. We've taken a position as a
labor movement in the United States that we're fighting permanent
most-favored nation agreement with China and we're going to see
that that's beaten. We expect different treatment from the Gore
administration, and we trust him, we believe him and we'll get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, labor does wield a big stick. The federation has
endorsed Gore and is putting its muscle behind his race for the
Democratic presidential nomination against former Senator Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is well aware that labor may have made the difference in
his early victories against Bradley. Labor officials said that the
union vote in the Democratic contests so far had been pivotal for
Gore _ accounting for about a third of the Democratic vote in Iowa
and a fourth in New Hampshire _ and that it would be crucial in the
March 7 primaries, particularly in New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Thursday's meeting, Gore thanked the labor leaders
profusely for their work on his behalf, and acknowledged their
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very firm in there that he is for the agreement, but
also extremely laudatory about what they had done for him,'' Lehane
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
