<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RICHARD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDTRACK'S GREAT BUT `LITTLE RICHARD' IS SADLY LACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the credits for ``Little Richard,'' the biographical film
airing Sunday night on NBC, Little Richard is listed as executive
producer. It must be a courtesy title, though, cuz, good golly, if
the ``architect of rock 'n' roll'' really had a hand in the
technical side of this biopic, he'd have made sure the extras could
walk and chew gum at the same time, no?
</P>
<P>
   As seems to be the case with so many of these rock-music
retrospectives passing as in-depth biographies, the adoring fans of
the rock stars apparently flunked out of the I've Got Rhythm School
of Remedial Finger-snapping. This is largely a flaw in film
editing, in synchronizing the actors' movements to the beat of the
soundtrack. But, really, how difficult is it to make the audience
keep time with the music? Or are we expected to believe Little
Richard's frantic approach to popular music was so far ahead of its
time that mere mortals in his entourage couldn't possibly tap their
toes that fast?
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Richard'' isn't the first such TV movie to suffer
out-of-sync-osis. But to be guilty of it in a film about someone
whose career was rooted in the raucous rhythms of deep-South gospel
music is a-wop-bop-a-loser move.
</P>
<P>
   Even stranger is the decision to end the story in 1962, when
Little Richard successfully returned to the concert stage after a
five-year hiatus during which he devoted his considerable energies
to religious studies and the ministry. True, his biggest hits were
behind him at that point, but to highlight only the first 30 years
suggests Little Richard may have had a little too much influence on
the conceptual side of this project.
</P>
<P>
   Leon, the artist formerly known as Leon Robinson, plays Little
Richard. Viewers may remember him as the free-spirited David Ruffin
in last year's NBC miniseries, ``The Temptations.'' (If Leon is
thinking of making this rock 'n' roll movie thing a career, I'd
like to put in my vote for Ben E. King and the Drifters as his next
project).
</P>
<P>
   Now, if ever there was a free spirit in rock 'n' roll, it was
Richard Wayne Penniman, the Macon, Ga., boy with a gift for music,
an abiding love of makeup and a flair for the theatrical. ``Little
Richard'' touches on all of that, but it touches ever so gently,
going only as deep as a light layer of pancake, leaving us with
something as ephemeral as a 2{-minute Top-40 single, as meaningful
as the lyrics to ``Tutti Frutti.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon is certainly energetic as Little Richard, but incapable of
providing much insight because of a script that is fearful of doing
anything more than providing the barest facts. The film hints at
the struggle behind the success, the pain behind the glory, but
every time the story gets interesting, the music starts.
</P>
<P>
   The music is good, too. But this makes ``Little Richard'' as
rewarding as a touring Broadway musical, which isn't bad if you're
looking for hummable tunes but deadly if you're looking for a
provocative story about an effeminate black singer trying to make
it in an industry dominated by white men comfortable with
eccentricity only if it makes them rich.
</P>
<P>
   Even Little Richard's struggle with his own conscience over
whether to serve God or devote his life to what his father (Carl
Lumbly) and his pastor (Garrett Morris) called the devil's music _
a pretty fair premise for a movie _ gets buried under the
``Bandstand''-like playlist.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. There's a good story lurking here. But the best we can
give ``Little Richard'' is a 70 because the melody is pretty but
the words leave something to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   Little Richard. Two-hour TV movie about the rock 'n' roll
legend. Starring Leon, Tamala Jones, Jennifer Lewis, Carl Lumbly
and Garrett Morris. Sunday night on NBC. Parental guideline rating:
TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-ART-2TAKES-NY     02-17 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLOWS HUMOR COMES TO THE BRADLEY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT21,22 _ are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Douglas Berman, the chairman of Bill
Bradley's presidential campaign, was strolling into a hotel bar
late one evening recently when he spotted three reporters assigned
to cover Bradley. Months ago, there might have been a dozen or more
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're the only ones left?'' Berman said with a glum laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Gallows humor has come to the campaign Bradley once described as
``a joyous journey.'' After losses to Vice President Al Gore in
Iowa and New Hampshire, and with Gore widening his double-digit
lead in almost every recent poll, there is a deepening sense of
gloom among some of Bradley's staunchest supporters. At times, even
Bradley seems to be grasping for answers as to why his campaign
seems stuck in neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what happens in these things,'' he said in an
interview this week. ``If you do a poll afterward and ask people
how they'd made up their minds, you could take the data and devise
five different explanations.''
</P>
<P>
   Though poker-faced and hard to read, Bradley has shown flashes
of frustration in recent days that suggest he is not pleased with
his position. In a recent news conference he expressed his dismay
with the news media's portrayal of his struggling campaign, saying,
``I don't have perfect communication with the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been particularly exasperating for Bradley and his aides
to watch Sen. John McCain swiftly close a once yawning gap with
Gov. George W. Bush in the Republican race. McCain's stunning
victory in New Hampshire, in fact, was attributable in part to his
growing support among independents and Democrats, whom Bradley had
courted aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   And that helped produce an avalanche of media attention that
Bradley's aides contend has relegated the Democratic race to a
sideshow, slowing Bradley at a crucial moment in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly McCain is getting the kind of press that Bradley
should be getting,'' said State Sen. Richard Codey of New Jersey, a
friend and supporter of Bradley. ``When we came within a few points
of beating a sitting vice president in New Hampshire, we should
have been on the cover of Time and Newsweek.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley clearly seems to share that sentiment. He argues that a
major reason McCain has taken off in the polls, while he has not,
is that Gov. George W. Bush had until recently not engaged in the
kind of negative campaigning that Gore has waged since last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an atmosphere where he wasn't getting attacked,''
Bradley said in the interview. ``George W. Bush didn't attack him.
And I think he had a free sail.''
</P>
<P>
   But did that mean that negative campaigning works? Bradley, who
has criticized ``the old politics of 1,000 attacks,'' paused,
briefly troubled by the question. ``I don't know,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better symbol of the difference between his campaign
and McCain's than the way they travel. McCain rides in a bus packed
with reporters. On Thursday, Bradley rode in a 54-seat bus with
only three aides, while reporters followed in a separate vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are no visible signs of panic within Bradley's
inner circle. Unlike Gore or Bush, who retreated to their
headquarters for urgent strategy sessions when their campaigns were
foundering, Bradley continues to trudge ahead, suggesting strongly
that he will make no radical changes to his game plan before March
7, when more than a dozen states hold primaries that will elect
about a third of the delegates needed for nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Gore seems to be widening his lead in polls, Bradley
said he considered it ``a bump from New Hampshire'' that would soon
dissipate. He asserted that most voters in states that hold March 7
primaries, including New York and California, are not paying
attention yet, giving him time to win them over.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the campaign has been opening new offices in key
cities each week and using its ample war chest to bombard select
states, including Ohio, New York, California and Missouri, with
television commercials. To build his name recognition, Bradley has
been doing a dozen or more interviews a day with local news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 18 points back in New Hampshire, and we lost by 4,''
he said. ``So I'm not prepared to say that things can't happen very
quickly. They can happen very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Having been occasionally criticized for not campaigning
energetically, Bradley has also begun packing his days with rallies
and media events, crisscrossing New York state by plane on Tuesday,
driving by bus through Massachusetts, Rhode Island and Connecticut
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But his events sometimes have a meandering feel to them. On
Thursday, for instance, Bradley spent two hours in a high school
gym in Providence, R.I., where he spoke to several hundred people
about the values he learned playing basketball and then shot hoops
with the girls' and boys' teams. (Bradley and two girls played a
shooting game against three boys. But his team lost, largely
because of Bradley who, despite his Hall of Fame skills, went 2 for
9.)
</P>
<P>
   The event provided Bradley an opportunity to campaign in a black
community _ a vital Democratic voting group _ and provided
energetic images of him in a sweat suit for local television. But
he did not mention Gore once, failing to draw the kinds of sharp
contrasts that could sway undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even some of his supporters seemed puzzled by the gentle tenor
of the event. ``Bradley's got to go negative on Gore,'' said
Wilfred LeHoullier, 72. ``But he just can't seem to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley insists, however, that he will be sharpening the
distinctions between him and Gore on issues of importance to
Democrats, particularly health care, education, gun control and
abortion. He also said he would step up his criticism of
fund-raising abuses by the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996, asserting
that Gore's involvement should disqualify him for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Democrats don't want to hear that, but it's true,''
he said in the interview. ``The message that you would communicate
is that this is the way politics has always been: take and get,
quid pro quo's, and money plays a role in everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Using some of his rawest language yet in describing his rival,
Bradley ridiculed Gore as ``the co-opt kid'' who stole his ideas
and oratory even as he criticized him. He also called Gore ``a
risk'' to the Democratic Party who would inevitably be rejected by
an electorate suffering from a sense of Clinton fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   And he accused the vice president of undermining the goal of
universal health care _ a core Democratic principle, he said _ by
relentlessly berating Bradley's own proposal to extend private
health insurance to almost all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he demeans universal health insurance, he's making it
less likely that we achieve universal health care as a country,''
Bradley said. ``It's not me or my candidacy, but what he does with
his divisiveness to injure the body politics, to injure the
prospects of anybody doing good things.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a rare moment, Bradley acknowledged that Gore's withering
attacks on him had probably weakened his support, saying the vice
president had ``clouded the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley plugs on gamely, many of his most loyal supporters
have been growing increasingly melancholy about his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends are becoming resigned to a Gore victory,''
said David Loebsack, a professor of political science at Cornell
College in Iowa, who was one of Bradley's grass-roots organizers in
that state. ``They are frustrated with the lack of movement on the
Bradley front.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in New York, once considered Bradley's strongest big state
_ he played basketball for the Knicks for 10 seasons _ some of
Bradley's friends are worrying about his chances of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the momentum the vice president's got certainly does
not bode well,'' said State Assemblyman Alexander P. Grannis, a
Manhattan Democrat who is helping Bradley. ``People still like
Bradley. But they wonder whether he has it in him to wage this kind
of fight. And now Gore looks stronger, so Bradley looks weaker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
