<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0293 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-2TAKES-$AD     02-17 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ONLINE MATCHMAKER OF ATHLETES AND SCHOOLS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.Y., Wash.)   (af)  
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When someone makes a big profit on Wall Street,
traders like to say, ``Don't confuse brains with a bull market.''
And when a corporate climber in most any field hits a home run,
business friends are apt to attribute it to being in the right
place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   But for Lisa Henderson, 37, founder of LevelEdge.com, an
Internet service that matches young athletes with colleges and
scholarships, it took nearly 20 years for her own lucky break on
the high school playing fields to germinate into a hot business
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   That business _ solidly financed and widely praised, though
still unproven _ demonstrates how well some entrepreneurs can reach
back into their pasts for the Big Idea. For all the material
rewards of success, venture capitalists say, it is business
founders with a profound motivation to change the world, or at
least a portion of it, who are the most successful. Henderson,
considering herself lucky, wants to create such kismet for others.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's break came in 1980, when she was a high school
senior of modest means in the small town of Pontoon, Ill., near St.
Louis. Two girlfriends invited her to watch their preseason soccer
tournament at Lindenwood University in St. Charles, Mo. When the
team suddenly ran short of players, someone tossed Lisa a jersey
and sent her onto the field. She scored two goals, prompting the
coach to offer her a $2,000 scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, was not enough money to send Henderson to
college. So the coach set up tryouts on the basketball and softball
teams, and she got offers of $4,000 more in sports scholarships.
After selling her car, Ms. Henderson had enough money to enroll. In
the next five years she earned a bachelor's degree in finance, an
MBA and the school's ``athlete of the year'' award.
</P>
<P>
   Recruited directly out of college by Ralston-Purina as a
marketing research analyst, she spent five years working her way up
to brand manager and introducing products from the company's
headquarters in St. Louis. In 1992, she moved to San Francisco to
run the Mexico operation of Del Monte; a year later, she became an
executive vice president at Specialty Brands, which sells spices
and food ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Ms. Henderson made the leap to technology, joining the
software developer Autodesk as head of its consumer products
division. Seeing firsthand how the Internet could break down
economic and geographic barriers, she began thinking about going
into business for herself.
</P>
<P>
   She often talked to friends and colleagues about young people
who were not able to fulfill their potential because of where or
how they had grown up. ``Kids like me are invisible,'' she said.
``And we're forced to rely on luck as a means of getting a good
education.''
</P>
<P>
   So in 1998, Henderson wrote a business plan for LevelEdge, a
start-up that would use computer technology to match promising high
school and junior college athletes with four-year colleges and
universities. The company is intended as an alternative to the
unseemly practices that Henderson and others feel are widely
prevalent in the college athlete recruiting process.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, LevelEdge is a clearinghouse, allowing its subscribers
to get a broad view of prospective graduates and promising athletes
without an intermediary who might take advantage of unsuspecting
families.
</P>
<P>
   Living in the shadow of Silicon Valley, Henderson didn't need
long to round up $2.7 million in seed capital and recruit such
high-visibility investors as the retired tennis champion Billie
Jean King, who has since become co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``LevelEdge shares my vision of providing equal opportunities
across the board for athletes,'' King said in an interview. ``I
came up through the public parks system, not the country club, and
it's much tougher if you're not part of a highly visible program.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The service has also attracted support from coaches. ``I will
subscribe to LevelEdge because it will allow me to find talent that
may have otherwise been unknown to me,'' said Scott Thompson, the
men's basketball coach at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henderson wants to raise the visibility of all student
athletes. ``Everyone knows the top 50 players for each position,''
she said. ``Only there are 21 million high school students, and 33
percent play sports.''
</P>
<P>
   While most students and parents know how to fill out college
applications, she added, not many understand the complicated sports
recruitment process. Students who participate in LevelEdge need
file only one profile of academic, athletic and personal
information for posting on the site. They can also request that it
be sent by e-mail to specific coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The matching service will be free to students and parents. The
plan calls for financing through subscription fees from schools
that use the site for recruiting, and through advertising from
companies offering athletic goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   The site's database of potential basketball recruits will be
unveiled next month at the National Collegiate Athletic Association
during the men's and women's Final Four basketball tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited about LevelEdge because it removes economic
and geographic barriers for athletes,'' said Beth Bass, executive
director of the Women's Basketball Coaches Association. ``A student
doesn't have to pay to travel to an elite camp in order to be seen
by coaches.'' After the basketball rollout, Henderson plans to
extend LevelEdge to 20 other sports.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Henderson was one of 27 chief executives of
start-ups chosen from 350 applicants to present business
propositions to several hundred potential investors at Springboard
2000, a venture capital forum for women entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   The fair, in Silicon Valley, was championed by Kay Koplovitch,
chairwoman of the National Women's Business Council, a government
advisory panel. There, Henderson lined up her next round of
capitalization _ $10 million from a group of backers. (The fair, by
the way, proved such a success that three more are scheduled this
year, for Washington, New York and Boston.)
</P>
<P>
   Aside from building a thriving business, Henderson has three
other goals. First, she hopes not to receive any more heartbreaking
phone calls from low-income parents who have handed over big
up-front fees to freelance ``recruiters'' of dubious reputation.
Second, she eagerly awaits the first e-mail message from a student
who has found a scholarship through LevelEdge, resulting in
opportunities like the ones Henderson had.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, she hopes not to be called a ``former athlete.''
In a match last week, she scored two of the three goals for her
local indoor soccer team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laura Pedersen-Pietersen is a Manhattan author and public
speaker. Her column profiling people whose work is their passion
appears the third Sunday of each month. E-mail:
yourmind(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
