<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-EROS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS SAY ASTEROID MAY BE FRAGMENT OF A PLANET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The distant asteroid 433 Eros, which received a Valentine's Day
visit from a robot NASA spacecraft, may be the fragment of a busted
planet, scientists reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's $224.1 million Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous probe
has been transmitting photographs of the peanut-shaped Eros back to
Earth since it began to orbot the asteroid Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even at an orbital altitude of 284 miles, the spacecraft's
cameras have detected a prominent layering in the structure of the
22 mile-long, 8-mile wide asteroid, the kind of structuring
geologists believe could occur only in response to gravitational
forces much greater than those present on Eros.
</P>
<P>
   ``This layering seems to extend globally throughout the body of
the asteroid, as if this asteroid were made up of layers like a
sheet of plywood,'' said Andrew Cheng, the chief NEAR mission
scientist from Johns Hopkins University.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of layering would come about if Eros was once part
of a much larger body,'' said Cheng. ``This would be an indication
that Eros is the type of asteroid that is the fragment of a
planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Most asteroids circle the sun in a beltlike formation between
the orbits of Mars and Jupiter. Astronomers have long wondered
whether they are remnants left over from the formation of the solar
system 4.5 billion years ago, or chunks of a rocky planet that was
shattered by an impact with another planet. The formation of the
planets was a chaotic but little understood process.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists estimated it would take a planet at least the size of
the Earth's moon, but possibly slightly smaller, to produce the
statification they witness on Eros. On the Earth, the gravitational
forces gradually pull the heaviest minerals toward the planet's
core, leaving the less dense material in the crust, or surface
layers, of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Eros is drab, heavily cratered and 160 million miles from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eros is not a boring object, and not just a rock floating out
in space,'' said Mark Robinson, a Northwestern University
scientist. ``There is a lot of neat geology going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The NEAR probe reached Eros after a four-year journey from
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists plan to spend a year chipping away at its secrets by
gradually steering the 1,800-pound spacecraft closer and closer to
the surface. They may even attempt to land briefly for a more
intimate look.
</P>
<P>
   Other features that have quickly piqued the curiosity of
scientists are a long saddlelike depression carved into the
exterior of the asteroid, dozens of mansion-sized boulders strewn
across the surface and at least one bright prominent feature.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Eros is heavily cratered, suggesting to experts that it
is old enough to have undergone hundreds of millions of years of
bombardment by meteorites. The surface of the saddle, however, is
much less disturbed and therefore possibly much younger terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective discrepancy in the ages in the terrain of such a
small celestial body is among its most puzzling qualities. Another
is a large bright spot. The gleaming feature is high on the list of
features that will be scrutinized as NEAR begins its gradual
descent in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us have felt like kids in a candy store,'' said James
Bell, a Cornell University scientist. ``But we get to stay in this
candy store for a full year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
