<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MINORITY-TV18-COX     02-17 1934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-TV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minorities on network TV still looking for their piece of the
pie
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Prime-time television is sickly pale these days,
no doubt about it. It's white in front of the cameras and even
whiter behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Ensemble dramas such as ``ER,'' ``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``NYPD Blue''
and ``The Practice'' are the exception. So are the ``ghettoized''
sitcoms on mini-networks WB and UPN, where a large group of black
writers work on black shows that air in separate blocks on the
schedule. And the lone network sitcom, ``The Hughleys,'' on ABC.
Not exactly a multi-cultural situation.
</P>
<P>
   Most shows on the major networks are unbelievably,
unrealistically white. It doesn't make sense for a group of young
``Friends'' in New York not to have a single African-American or
Latino pal. Then there's ``Frasier,'' which is set in Seattle, a
city with a sizable Asian population, with non-Asians as far as the
eye can see. And ``Walker, Texas Ranger,'' with no Latinos where
plenty should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV is not a mirror of society and never will be,'' says John
Ridley, an AfricanAmerican who is supervising producer and writer
on NBC's ``Third Watch.'' ``But you do need to see something that
looks like your world. When you don't, it gets to the point where
that seems OK. And it's really not.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees there's a lack of diversity in the dominant
medium of this diverse nation, but there's no agreement on what to
do about it. Should there be more minority faces on screen? Should
casting be colorblind or color conscious? Should networks focus
instead on filling writing and producing jobs to increase diversity
in a more organic manner?
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few months, a coalition of minority leaders
hammered out agreements with the four main networks. In January,
NBC and ABC agreed to add minority writers and training programs
geared toward minorities; earlier this month, CBS and Fox agreed to
add ``vice presidents of diversity'' to their corporate management
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements were hailed by some as a breakthrough. NAACP
President Kweisi Mfume called the CBS and Fox agreements ``a
constitution for real and meaningful change.'' Esteban Torres, head
of the Latino branch of the minority coalition, called the
nonbinding documents ``the Magna Charta of television.'' And Paris
Barclay, creator and co-executive producer with Steven Bochco of
the much-heralded ``City of Angels,'' a new CBS drama with a
predominantly minority cast, has said the network agreements could
``change the look and landscape of of TV very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But many minorities in the creative community have greeted the
news with a mixture of cautious optimism and skepticism. They've
heard promises before, and they've seen the diversity landscape
change in cycles. Up in the '70s, when Norman Lear's socially
conscious comedies were all the rage, down toward the end of the
decade when white-bread shows such as ``Happy Days'' and
``Charlie's Angels'' were all the rage. And then up again when
``The Cosby Show'' spawned a flurry of African-American comedies in
the '80s _ most of which were decidedly non-``Cosby'' in tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've failed to the point where you have to use these
(quota) programs, there's real trouble,'' says Ridley, whose fall
drama is chock full of diversity but was overlooked when Mfume
charged that no new series had minority characters. ``These are
very small steps _ maybe three of NBC's sophomore shows next season
will add minority writers. To me, that's tokenism. And what if it
doesn't work? That poisons the pot and makes people resentful. I'd
feel bad if I were hired just because I'm black.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley, who landed his first writing job after doing an
internship at Fox in '94, believes training programs are a better
way to identify minority talent. He's pessimistic about the
prospect of adding one minority writer to each returning series
next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that people are paying attention to the problem,
but I don't think it'll help much,'' Ridley says. ``The issue has
come up many times over the years, but there's such a turnover in
management that the people who make these agreements are gone
before they're carried out, and the new people don't remember the
agreements were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Carter, a Southwest Texas University graduate, has had
more success in television than most minority writer-producers, but
frustration has never been too far away. He started out as an actor
on ``The White Shadow,'' a drama series about a high school
basketball team, and began learning behind-the-camera skills there.
Not long after, he directed several episodes of ``Hill Street
Blues'' before selling his own legal drama, ``Equal Justice,'' to
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Praised by critics for its smart stories, cinematic style and
multiethnic cast, ``Equal Justice,'' starring Joe Morton, should
have had an easy time but didn't. Carter says he had to fight ABC
to have Morton, who is black, as the lead. And there were
scheduling problems. It debuted midseason in 1990 and disappeared
until midseason the following year, never making a fall lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never really had a chance,'' Carter says. ``It was an
uphill battle the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   But not nearly as difficult as ``Under One Roof,'' Carter's
superb family drama starring Morton, James Earl Jones and Vanessa
Bell Calloway. The CBS series was praised by critics and even held
up in Congress as an example of strong family values. It lasted
only a month in the spring of '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been so much talk about how people won't
accept black dramas that I think the people at CBS had already
decided it wouldn't work,'' Carter says. ``Although I've been very
successful on TV as a director, it's been frustrating trying to get
people to stand behind the good shows I've done as a producer.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter is cautiously optimistic about the networks' diversity
agreements and agrees that the focus should shift from casting to
writing and producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made great strides in the last 25 years in minority
casting, but we still have to work on inclusion of minorities in
the executive offices, writing staffs and those areas,'' Carter
says. ``It's difficult when you deal with creative areas to talk
about quotas. I'm not in favor of that. But when there's been a
historical exclusion of minorities in certain areas, you have to
take some kind of steps to encourage minorities to seek those
opportunities and to encourage people in power to open those
doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Latinos, the fastest-growing minority in the United States with
a population close to 30 million, have a disproportionately low
representation in television. Traditionally, diversity has been
almost exclusively represented by blacks. According to a study
released last month called ``Fall Colors: How Diverse Is the
1999-2000 TV Season's Prime Time Lineup?'' 80 percent of series
characters are white, 13 percent are black and other minorities
(Latino, Asian and American Indian) are less than 7 percent. (The
number of black characters is deceptive, since 13 percent is
actually more than the 12.2 percent of African-Americans who make
up the general population. The problem is that almost all of the
black characters on TV are congregated in the same shows, not
spread out across the prime-time landscape.)
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Latin culture is influencing music, food and just
about everything else, Latinos are practically nonexistent on
television. Since Jimmy Smits departed ``NYPD Blue'' and Benjamin
Bratt left ``Law &AMP; Order,'' Cheech Marin and Hector Elizondo are
just about the only Latino stars in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The stats tell the story: The Screen Actors Guild's membership
is only 4 percent Latino; of 839 writers of fall series, 11 are
Latino.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos who are visible on TV tend to be stereotyped as gang
members, prostitutes, illegal aliens and drug dealers. When the
National Council of La Raza meets to bestow its media awards every
year, often there aren't enough nominations to fill the categories.
While blacks may be ghettoized on the smaller networks on certain
nights of the week, Latinos have been shipped off to their own
networks _ Univision and Telemundo, which are increasingly popular
in Latino households.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see Latinos in technical positions (on the major networks)
but certainly not in a decision-making capacity,'' says Hector
Galan, an Austin-based filmmaker whose films (``Songs of the
Homeland,'' ``Chicano! The History of the Mexican-American Civil
Rights Movement'') frequently appear on PBS. ``We've made very few
inroads. When you talk about casting, a lot of that has to do with
the people who are writing. ... There hasn't been an effort to
bring in Latinos, and it's not one of those areas that Latinos
traditionally go into as a profession. That's why we need
mentors.''
</P>
<P>
   Galan is optimistic that the networks' agreements will chip away
at the stumbling blocks and open doors for Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   So, is television's segregation the result of blatant racism or
simple ignorance on the part of the networks? Or is it the result
of viewers choosing white programs and rejecting others?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's unenlightened racial attitudes rather than
racism,'' Carter says. ``What people do in TV is hire people who
are like themselves, so if you tend not to be in the group who went
to college with them or lived in their exclusive gated communities
or played golf at their country club, you tend not to have the same
access. While I do believe the industry responds to talent, it's
not exactly a level playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter concedes he fell into the same trap when he sold ``Equal
Justice'' to ABC. The first season the show was on, he hired
writers and producers who were approved by the network and thus
considered ``safe.'' And mostly white. But when he realized that
half of the ``safe'' hires weren't all that good, he decided he
would have been better off hiring talented minorities or women.
</P>
<P>
   Of course when a show such as ``Under One Roof'' or the much
ballyhooed but low-rated ``City of Angels'' doesn't turn into a
``Cosby''-like phenomenon, the network brass says white viewers
just won't watch serious black dramas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can blame this on the audience,'' Ridley
says. ``They'll watch what's entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   But even black viewers tend to turn to black sitcoms rather than
dramas. Audience surveys after the widely praised civil rights
drama ``I'll Fly Away'' failed revealed that black viewers had no
interest in reliving racial strife. They preferred comedies.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of a few mega-hits such as ``Cosby'' and
``ER,'' black and white viewers do not watch the same shows. Not
many blacks are fans of ``Friends,'' and few whites tune in for
``The Steve Harvey Show.'' That makes multicultural programming
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do like to watch themselves, but that's more true of
black people because we haven't see that much of ourselves, so
we're really hungry,'' Carter says.
</P>
<P>
   A fully integrated landscape on TV is unrealistic, but most
people agree that the networks must do better. For the diversity
agreements to have an impact, the networks need to hire more than a
couple of minority writers. They must add minorities to every level
of production and decision-making. They need to add black writers
to ``Will &AMP; Grace'' and white writers to ``Moesha.'' Otherwise,
prime time's pallor _ and segregation _ likely will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
