<HEADER>
A0300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SC-VOICES-RETIREES-NY     02-17 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-VOICES-RETIREES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG RETIREES, SPLIT LOYALTIES REVIVE LONG-LOST EXCITEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is part of a six-story package. The other five stories
are SC-VOICES, SC-VOICES-SUBURBS, SC-VOICES-LOWCOUNTRY,
SC-VOICES-BLACKS and SC-VOICES-CONSERVATIVES)  
(bl) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. _ ``In the beginning, I was neutral,''
John F. Carson said of the state's Republican primary. ``But as
I've watched and listened, I've even gotten a little excited now.
About McCain, I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson said he had come to regard Sen. John McCain as ``a
righteous individual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is what he is, it seems to me,'' Carson said.
</P>
<P>
   Carson, a retired steel executive, is one of this island's
30,000 or so permanent residents, mostly retired, mostly wealthy
and overwhelmingly Republican. Here, the rich Low Country accents
of the nearby mainland abruptly give way to voices from the
Northeast and the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Carson lived in Cleveland until he retired last year at age 62.
He has occasionally voted Democratic and said he longed for the
excitement he remembers feeling with John F. Kennedy's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was certainly open to Bush,'' he said after a tennis match
at one of the island's gated communities. ``But I found him a
little too willing to do whatever it takes to win. I thought he was
a bit slick, and I certainly didn't want that after this guy,'' he
said, referring to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain seems to stand a little taller,'' Carson said. ``I
think there is a line that he won't cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson's enthusiasm for McCain was not uniform among other
retirees interviewed here, many of whom said they would vote for
Gov. George W. Bush. But there was an across-the-board exasperation
with the rough style of the campaign. And all agreed that they had
not paid this much attention to a political race in a long while.
Many of those who said they preferred Bush also said they had been
lifelong Republicans. Many of McCain's supporters said they had
voted for Democrats at various times.
</P>
<P>
   Terry O'Donnell, who has lived for four years at Sea Pines
Plantation, as the largest development is called, said she
supported Bush as the best alternative to Steve Forbes, who
recently dropped out of the race and had been her favorite. When
her husband, Joe O'Donnell, said he liked McCain and would thus
cancel out his wife's vote, she said, ``He's really a Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, a retired manufacturing executive from Baltimore,
responded: ``No, no, I'm really a Republican. Really.'' He said he
liked McCain because he would attract more people to the Republican
Party. ``I think he's flexible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell shot back, ``Of course, he's flexible. He wants to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she said of her husband, ``See. He's a Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Soldan, a retired businessman and investor who had just
posted his day's golf score at the pro shop at Wexford Plantation,
one of the wealthiest enclaves, said he believed the news media had
built up McCain too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, you've got to take your hat off to him on the experience
he had as a prisoner of war,'' Soldan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's just too much,'' he added, complaining that both the
candidate and the news media had emphasized that issue too much.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Braxton, a retired military officer, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pulling for McCain all the way,'' Braxton said. ``I've
been talking him up to all my friends for a long time now. I think
he would restore some dignity there in Washington. But in the
beginning it seemed like there was no chance for him. Now, all of a
sudden, it seems he's taking off.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
