A0302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-VOTER-TURNOUT18-COX     02-17 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTER-TURNOUT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turnout may be critical in S.C. dead heat race
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ The frenetic South Carolina primary campaign
focused on voter turnout Thursday as the Republican candidates
launched a final round of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush continued to criticize John McCain, saying the
Arizona senator does one thing and says another. In particular,
Bush was referring to a campaign flier that attacks Bush on Social
Security after McCain promised to run a positive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take the high horse and then claim the low road,''
Bush said in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, meanwhile, predicted that a win in South Carolina's
primary Saturday would propel him to the Republican nomination, the
first time he has made such a bold prognostication.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win here, I don't see how we can really be stopped,''
McCain told supporters at a pancake breakfast at VFW Post 3539 in
Spartanburg.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns acknowledged that the race is a dead heat, with
turnout likely to be the deciding factor. A lower turnout, which
probably would consist of Republican faithful, would favor Bush.
McCain is hoping for a heavy turnout of independents and Democrats,
who are allowed to vote in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   A poll directed by Clemson University political scientist David
Woodard projects a turnout of 350,000 to 370,000, which would be a
record. In 1996, when former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole beat
conservative commentator Pat Buchanan, 276,000 ballots were cast.
</P>
<P>
   If turnout stays in the 350,000 range, Woodard said, ``Bush
should be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But if turnout exceeds 400,000, with a surge of independents and
Democrats, ``Bush could be in trouble,'' Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend line is moving the right way,'' John Weaver,
McCain's political director, said about recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is redoubling his get-out-the-vote efforts, which
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A glowing letter of endorsement from the commander of the
South Carolina National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   _ A mailing outlining Bush's positions and accusing McCain of
waffling, going to 300,000 Republican, Democratic and independent
voters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two telephone calls to every voter identified as a Bush
supporter, and an additional telephone call to identified social
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ A taped telephone message from Bush that will be delivered by
automatic dial to thousands of households. A message from his wife,
Laura, will be targeted at female voters. A message from Sen. Strom
Thurmond will be dialed in to rural households.
</P>
<P>
   _ A letter of support from former presidential candidate
Elizabeth Dole is being mailed to young women. The letter
criticizes McCain's tax-cutting package. Older women are getting a
letter from Bush's mother, Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ A mailing to social conservativesrevives inconsistent
statements McCain has made about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain chose to ignore Bush's comments Thursday, telling an
audience in Greenville, ``I wish Governor Bush the best.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also was forced to defend himself against charges of
ethnic insensitivity relating to the use of the slur ``gooks'' to
refer to his North Vietnamese captors. An e-mail message that is
circulating among Asian-Americans includes an article from The
Nation magazine that contends McCain uses the term ``casually.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who spent 5 1/2 years in a North Vietnamese prisoner of
war camp, told reporters aboard his campaign bus that he employs it
_ and will continue to use it _ only in reference to his captors,
whom he called cruel and sadistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated the gooks and I will hate them as long as I live,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
