<HEADER>
A0303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SC-VOICES-CONSERVATIV     02-17 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-VOICES-CONSERVATIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES SEEK CANDIDATE WITH A FIRM STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is part of a six-story package. The other five stories
are SC-VOICES, SC-VOICES-SUBURBS, SC-VOICES-LOWCOUNTRY,
SC-VOICES-BLACKS and SC-VOICES-RETIREES)  
(bl) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Doug Bray and Daryl Renshaw are two old
friends from nearby Bob Jones University who like a friendly
debate. So Thursday morning, as they often do, the two men shared a
pot of coffee at the International House of Pancakes and each tried
to convince the other of the error of his political thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Renshaw, 35, favors Gov. George W. Bush, while Bray, also 35,
likes Sen. John McCain. They even brought printouts of the
candidates' positions, jousting over different points. But no minds
were changed: One vote for McCain, one for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaning toward McCain,'' Bray said. ``I like the fact of
having a person in the White House who has strong leadership
qualities. What he was able to do during the war showed me has some
intestinal fortitude.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Renshaw countered, Bush is the right candidate.
Particularly, he said, since he has resisted denigrating Bob Jones
University, the conservative school that prohibits interracial
dating and refuses to allow gay alumni to return to the campus.
Renshaw said the school has been unfairly tainted in the national
media during the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I don't believe in interracial dating, I'm not a
bigot against colored people,'' Renshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a conservative state, Greenville and the surrounding
upstate region are considered ultraconservative. Bush is counting
on strong support here, and several people spoke approvingly of his
character, his anti-abortion stance and his record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in an informal survey of 34 people in Greenville, voters
were almost evenly divided, with 17 people favoring McCain, 15
favoring Bush and two undecided. Those who supported McCain cited
his character and integrity, his military record as a prisoner of
war and the belief that he would best bring change to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do believe in the guy,'' said Vicki Perfect, 48, a
hospital administrator. .
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat, Perfect said she is not interested in her party's
candidates and plans to delay a trip Saturday to vote for McCain in
the primary. ``I think McCain is going to stand for something.''
</P>
<P>
   A few booths away, Dean Powell, 67, the retired superintendent
of the local water system, echoed Perfect's endorsement of McCain,
particularly because of his war record. Powell said he served in
the Korean War. ``Bush is OK, but he's riding on his daddy and
mama's coattails,'' said Powell, an independent. ``I don't think he
has the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush and Barbara Bush are considered
extremely popular in South Carolina, but the family's history
seemed to be a mixed blessing for the Texas governor. Several
people cited his family as one of the reasons they found Bush
appealing. But Bill Brent, 70, a Republican retiree and McCain
supporter seemed irritated over a recent mailing he received from
Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want no dynasty going on,'' Brent said. ``I like what
McCain stands for. I want him to do something about the
lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   Several voters cited honesty and character as reasons to vote
for Bush. They also said they considered him the more conservative
candidate. ``I keep hearing John McCain caught in lies and that
bothers me,'' said Diane Jerina, 56, a Republican who was shopping
at a Publix grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   She said McCain seemed to be waffling on certain issues, noting
how he first decried the flying of the Confederate battle flag
above the state Capitol, then called it a symbol of heritage.
``He's changed his mind about the flag, and he's changed his mind
about this, that and the other.''
</P>
<P>
   A short drive away at Bob Jones University, campus officials
refused to allow a reporter to interview students and faculty until
first meeting with an administrator. James Pachter, 22, a senior
and campus security officer who stopped the reporter, did offer his
choice: Bush. Pachter said he appreciated that Bush spoke at the
school and has not criticized the university. Bush has said he
opposes any policy prohibiting interracial dating, but he has
defended his decision to speak at Bob Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more electable than Keyes,'' Pachter said, referring to
the third Republican contender, Alan Keyes. ``He's really standing
on his ground when we've become an issue,'' Pachter said. ``When he
was asked by the national media why he came here, it should be very
clear that a candidate can come to a school and speak and not
necessarily endorse every policy the school has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
