A0304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DRY-RIVER18-COX     02-17 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRY-RIVER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A low period for America's mightiest river
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The Mighty Mississippi, known for flooding entire
towns from Iowa to Louisiana, these days is a slow, slender shadow
of its former self.
</P>
<P>
   A drought that began last summer is persisting, causing the
Mississippi River to shrink to near-record low stages.
</P>
<P>
   The river is at minus 8 feet at Memphis, Tenn., about 20 feet
below normal, according to the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers. That
means it is 8 feet below a ``zero'' set point, or bench mark,
created a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The record, minus 10.7 feet, was set during the drought of 1988,
said corps spokesman Bob Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Rain this week will raise the river about 18 feet in the next 10
days, Anderson said, but then it is expected to dwindle again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a roller coaster,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The river is moving at 250,000 cubic feet of water per second.
On average in February, it moves as fast as 500,000 cubic feet per
second. During a flood, it can move 1.5 million cubic feet per
second.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the shallow depths have not caused major disruptions in
ship traffic, although there have been some delays. Along narrow
sections and at sharp bends, barges passing each other going up and
down river have to take turns, Anderson said. The Coast Guard has
been busy moving buoys to warn ships of dangerous sandbars and
sills. The corps dredges the shoals daily to prevent groundings.
</P>
<P>
   If the river gets any lower, it could impact the shipping
industry more significantly, Anderson said. Barges could be forced
to lighten their loads. In 1988, barge companies lost $1 million a
day because they could not move coal, petroleum and agricultural
products along the nation's midsection and out to the Gulf of
Mexico. The Mississippi carries 600 million tons of cargo annually.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, where the river is always deeper because
oceangoing ships sail through here, the river hasn't caused any
problems. But A.J. Gibbs, vice president of the Crescent River Port
Pilots Association, said he has never seen it so low.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs and other river pilots measure the river from sea level,
and it is less than 2 feet above sea level at downtown New Orleans.
Normally, it's about 8 feet above sea level in February.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, since the city itself is below sea level, the river
still looks high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen it stay low for this long,'' Gibbs said.
``It's either feast or famine with the Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   The drought is affecting smaller bodies of water as well. In
Mississippi, streams and rivers are at record lows. In Louisiana,
the Atchafalaya River Basin is so low it can't support the
reproduction cycle of crawfish. The result is the worst crawfish
season anyone can remember.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
