<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0305 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-STATES-TAXES-WYO-ART-     02-17 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-TAXES-WYO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE MOST STATES ARE FLUSH, A HANDFUL STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Tenn., Iowa, Kan.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 34 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEYENNE, Wyo. _ The nation's record economic expansion has left
most states so flush with tax revenues that lawmakers argue over
how to spend a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Not here.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Wyoming's elected officials are debating how large
the budget deficit could become and what services might be cut if
dramatic new measures _ including taxes _ are not passed to raise
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone say new taxes? That's almost incomprehensible to
people in Wyoming, who pay no personal income tax and, overall, a
lower percentage of their income in taxes than residents of any
other state. That's why many of them live here.
</P>
<P>
   But Wyomingites are not alone in confronting difficult choices.
While many Americans are growing wealthier and Congress debates how
much of the federal surplus should be returned to taxpayers, a
handful of states are facing choices that more commonly arise
during recessions. Their lawmakers are deciding whether to raise
taxes or cut spending because their state economies are not
diversified enough to reap the full benefits of the boom or their
tax base is too narrow.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, unstable oil prices and marginal increases in tax
revenues have left the state facing a potential deficit of $540
million for the fiscal year beginning in July, state officials
said. Mark Drennen, the state's commissioner of administration,
said that spending caps and cuts, including the dismissal of
recently hired state employees, could offset much of it.
</P>
<P>
   But a remaining deficit of $275 million, he said, would require
new revenue sources, including the possibility of a new business
tax, which is supported by Gov. Mike Foster, or a penny increase in
the 4 cent sales tax. Other possibilities are a reduction in the
state homestead exemption and an increase in the personal income
tax.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, Gov. Don Sundquist has been fighting for more than
a year for tax changes to help cover increased spending in
education and other areas. After the Legislature rejected his
proposals last year, he tried again this year with a package that
includes a flat-rate income tax. He challenged lawmakers to adopt
his plan, find other new revenue or cut spending by $342 million.
</P>
<P>
   A slow rate of economic growth in Iowa caused by depressed farm
prices, nearly full employment, a lack of new industries and an
aging population, forced Gov. Tom Vilsack to cut $30 million in
spending from the current fiscal year's budget of $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a lot of room for growth if you are not able to
add new jobs, and that affects the revenue base,'' said Randy
Bauer, the Iowa state budget director.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the same factors forced the Kansas Legislature to reduce
its current budget of $4.45 billion by $65 million. ``Actual
revenue collection came up short of revenue forecasts, and that is
what caused us to go back and reduce the level of spending,'' said
Duane Goossen, the state budget director.
</P>
<P>
   No state faces a more precarious economic situation than
Wyoming, the least populated state with just 479,000 people, about
the population of Denver. It is one of only seven states with no
personal income tax and one of four with no corporate taxes, major
sources of the windfall in other states.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, almost two-thirds of Wyoming is owned by the
federal government, which means only a small part of the state
budget comes from property taxes. The largest single source of tax
revenues is from mining, as much as 60 percent in some years,
followed by revenues from sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials say Wyoming has grown too reliant on global
markets for commodities that are found in vast abundance around
Wyoming, including natural gas, coal and minerals like trona, which
is used to make soda ash, and bentonite, an absorbent clay.
</P>
<P>
   When natural gas prices are booming, for example, Wyoming's
budget is stable. The only reason the state is not facing a deficit
for the fiscal year beginning July 1 _ after deficit projections of
$127 million a year ago and $183 million six months ago _ is a
recent surge in coal prices.
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of gyrations have forced state leaders to cut many
programs, like services for the elderly, from the state's $4.1
billion two-year budget. They have also prompted Gov. Jim Geringer,
a second-term Republican, to lead efforts to wean the state off the
uncertainties of volatile markets, arguing that economic growth and
full service delivery can come about only through predictable
revenue streams.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been out front on this, with the need to do something,''
said James King, a professor of political science at the University
of Wyoming in Laramie. ``He realizes you can't put a Band-Aid on
this. But whether he can truly get a long-term solution or another
Band-Aid remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of his campaign, Geringer has been traveling the state,
selling ``a sense of responsibility'' to people who have grown
accustomed to low taxes. As he said in his state of the state
address this week: ``In order to create a long-term solution, we
must make some difficult choices.''
</P>
<P>
   They may be on the way.
</P>
<P>
   After state lawmakers returned on Monday for the 20-day budget
session that is held every other year, House members approved one
major revenue-raising measure for introduction as legislation, an
extension of the state's 4 percent sales tax, which was scheduled
to expire in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Votes on another proposal, a new tax on services, were held back
until Friday to give lawmakers time to generate more support. But a
raft of other proposals failed, including ones that would have a
created a personal income tax and a tax on electricity production
and separate measures that would have increased taxes on fuel,
cigarettes and property.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in tax-loathing Wyoming, even one new tax is dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an optimist,'' said House Speaker Eli Bebout. ``I think
we're on the path toward long-term solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Geringer said the Legislature was ``a little bit gun shy'' about
adopting long-range solutions. But he held out hope that more
measures would be approved, saying it was just a matter of finding
mutually agreeable approaches.
</P>
<P>
   But even new taxes might not be enough to keep Wyoming stable in
the long run. Other than scenic beauty, recreation and the tax
base, Wyoming has few advantages for prospective residents and
businesses over neighboring western states. Its population has
dropped for four consecutive years though mid-1999. Only one
airport in the state, Jackson's, accommodates commercial jets. A
teacher shortage is looming in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a new state agency, the Wyoming Business Council,
was formed to attract businesses, but some lawmakers are trying to
eliminate its $21 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie A. Ball, a council board member, says that would be a
mistake. A former executive with Macy's who moved from New York to
Cheyenne six years ago to become chief executive of a western wear
company, Ball said the council has already landed eight new
companies, bringing in 800 new jobs, and has prospects for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of obstacles here, but the state is starting
to move a little bit,'' Ball said. ``For the first time in a long
time, all the economic categories are moving. I think the state has
a fairly positive future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
