<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0308 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-FED-GREENSPAN-1STLD-W     02-17 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GREENSPAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN WARNS OF HIGHER INTEREST RATES TO AVOID INFLATION
</HEADLINE>
  (Updates, revisions, additions thruout)  
(See also FED-GREENSPAN-REACT) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, said
Wednesday that the powerhouse economy shows few signs of slowing
despite four interest rate increases over the last eight months,
and he warned in unusually direct terms that the central bank would
probably raise rates further to avert a buildup of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony to the House Banking Committee, Greenspan was also
blunter than normal in suggesting that one of his primary targets
in raising interest rates was the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time he set out what amounted to a speed limit for
Wall Street, saying that wringing the risk of inflation out of the
economy would require that stock and other asset prices rise no
faster than household incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, household wealth _ a broad measure that captures the
persistent gains in most stock prices _ grew twice as fast as
income, according to figures often employed by economists at the
Fed to gauge the effects of the market on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan did not specify what his arcane equation meant for
popular measures of stock prices like the Dow Jones industrial
average or the Nasdaq, although he emphasized that it would ``not
necessarily imply a decline in asset values.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors in blue chip stocks seemed to mildly heed the Fed
chairman's warning, sending the Dow industrial average down 46.84
points, to 10,514.57. But investors in technology stocks _ as they
have done repeatedly over the last few years _ thumbed their noses
at Greenspan by driving the Nasdaq index up 121.27 points, to
4,548.92, another record.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed next meets to consider monetary policy on March 21, and
economists said the tone of Greenspan's testimony Thursday all but
ensured that the central bank would act then to raise its benchmark
federal funds target rate by another quarter of a point, to 6
percent. They said additional increases could follow through the
spring and into summer if the economy did not slow.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the good news the nation has enjoyed now for years,
Greenspan said the current combination of strong growth, low
inflation, declining unemployment and improving efficiency among
businesses and workers was unprecedented in the half century he has
spent monitoring the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But he stressed that the good times could fall victim to
gradually mounting inflation pressures if the Fed did not act to
take some steam out of the expansion, which this month became the
longest on record at eight years and 11 months. The previous record
period of economic growth without a recession lasted through much
of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance that touched on a wide array of topics,
Greenspan brushed aside concerns that the recent turmoil in the
bond market was making the Fed's job harder. Yes, he acknowledged,
investors had driven down the interest rate on 30-year government
bonds at a time when the Fed was trying to use higher interest
rates to slow the economy. But the important thing, he said, was
that rates paid by private sector borrowers, especially
corporations, had risen substantially. Mortgage rates, too, while
not yet significantly slowing home building, have now reached a 3
1/2 year high.
</P>
<P>
   But in the formal report on monetary policy that he submitted to
Congress Thursday, Greenspan acknowledged that aspects of the
economy were making the central bank's job more complicated. In
particular, the report said, the rise in the growth rate of
productivity _ the amount that each worker produces per hour _ made
the economy so resilient that the scale of interest rate increases
needed to bring inflationary growth under control ``may have
increased substantially.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan reiterated his position that the federal budget
surplus should be used to reduce the national debt rather than for
tax cuts or new spending. And he said he was somewhat worried by
the recent sharp rise in oil prices, but advised against selling
the government's oil reserves to try to bring the price down,
saying such a move would be ineffectual.
</P>
<P>
   But his focus was on the risk that the economy was simply too
strong for its own good.
</P>
<P>
   The strains on the economy might soon become evident in the
labor market, he said, where a rapidly declining pool of jobless
workers could force employers to begin raising wages at a pace that
could ignite a widespread and destabilizing rise in prices. The
nation is also bumping up against the limit of how much it can
afford to import from other countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he traced the underlying problem to the stock market.
Buoyant stock prices, he said, were fueling consumer spending and
business investment to such a degree that overall demand in the
economy was outstripping supply. The only way to resolve that
fundamental imbalance, he said, was to sharply curtail the
relentless rise in equity prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little evidence that the American economy, which grew
more than 4 percent in 1999 and surged forward at an even faster
pace in the second half of the year, is slowing appreciably,''
Greenspan said at the beginning of his twice-a-year testimony to
Congress on monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the very factors underpinning the nation's remarkable
economic performance _ falling joblessness, accelerating
productivity, an improved outlook for corporate earnings _ ``are
also engendering a set of imbalances that, unless contained,
threaten our continuing prosperity,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   The pressures on the economy have been eased so far by a surge
in imports, which have made up for the inability of domestic
producers to keep up with demand, and by the willingness of people
who had not previously been in the labor force to get a job.
</P>
<P>
   But those ``safety valves,'' he said, could not contain
inflationary pressures forever, especially since the rate increases
so far have done little to rein in growth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's policy-setting federal Open Market Committee ``will
have to stay alert for signs that real interest rates have not yet
risen enough to bring the growth of demand into line with that of
potential supply, even should the acceleration of productivity
continue,'' Greenspan said. ``Achieving that alignment seems more
pressing today than it did earlier, before the effects of
imbalances began to cumulate, lessening the depths of our various
buffers against inflationary pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of rebalancing the economy, he said, would be limiting or
ending the rise in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable run-up in stock prices over much of the last
decade has been tempered or even reversed by some measures over the
last six months, though it remains almost as breathtaking as ever
by others. Greenspan made clear that he was not predicting a
downturn in the market, emphasizing only that it would be difficult
to achieve the kind of moderation he wants to see in the economy
without a leveling off of stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not necessarily imply a decline in asset values,
although that, of course, can happen at any time for a number of
reasons,'' he said, ``but rather that these values will increase no
faster than household incomes.''
</P>
<P>
   G. David Orr, an economist at First Union Securities, said, ``If
that is not targeting the stock market, what is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has long worried aloud about what economists call the
``wealth effect,'' the idea that rising stock prices translate into
higher spending levels by consumers. In his testimony Thursday, he
said historical evidence suggests that 3 to 4 cents of every dollar
in additional stock market wealth is reflected in increased
purchases by consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman said he tracked the wealth effect by looking at
the ratio of household net worth, or wealth, to income. According
to data collected by the Fed, net worth was 4.88 times higher than
disposable income in 1988. By 1998, net worth was 5.95 times higher
than income.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has not yet released figures for 1999. But economists
said wealth last year grew at about 11.3 percent, while income grew
about 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed's interest rate increases so far do not appear to
have slowed demand, the inflation that Greenspan fears has also
been a no-show. Just Thursday, the government's report on prices at
the producer level showed that inflation remained tame.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Fed's own forecast, submitted to Congress Thursday
as part of the monetary policy report, concludes that consumer
prices this year will rise between 1.75 percent and 2 percent,
compared with 2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The report also forecasts that the economy will expand between
3.5 percent and 3.75 percent, down from 4.2 percent last year. That
implies that the Fed now believes that the economy has the capacity
to grow at better than 3.5 percent a year over the long run without
producing inflationary pressures, well above what economists
believed possible not that long ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
