<HEADER>
A0310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-FLA-WATERWARS18-CO     02-17 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-FLA-WATERWARS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Water usage plan may cause serious drought in Georgia, official
says
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The current plan to settle the bitter water war with
Alabama and Florida would leave metro Atlanta in ``perpetual
drought'' and lower Lake Lanier to ``dangerous levels,'' the head
of the metro area's planning agency warns.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the negotiations have the potential to create
great hardship for all of Metropolitan Atlanta, indeed all of North
Georgia,'' departing Atlanta Regional Commission Director Harry
West said in a letter to Georgia's negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking his public silence since negotiations began in the
10-year water feud, West warned that plans now under consideration
would be disastrous for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He said his staff's analysis showed current proposals to divide
up the waters of the Chattahoochee, the Flint and other rivers
flowing through the region would lower Lake Lanier to unacceptable
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perpetual drought will become the normal operating procedure
for Metropolitan Atlanta,'' West said in the letter last week to
chief negotiator Bob Kerr and to Harold Reheis, head of the state
Environmental Protection Division. ``Any agreement that does not
allow for the sound management of Lake Lanier will be bad for
Georgia and disastrous for Metropolitan Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr said Thursday he and fellow negotiators are studying West's
concerns. ``We will give full consideration to his comments,'' said
Kerr, who added that discussing the letter further could jeopardize
negotiations with the other states.
</P>
<P>
   West could not be reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The states are trying to work out water allocation formulas in
two negotiations. Georgia, Florida and Alabama are fighting over
the Apalachicola, Chattahoochee and Flint rivers, the so-called ACF
basin. In a separate negotiation, Georgia and Alabama are
squabbling over the Alabama, Coosa and Tallapoosa rivers, the ACT
basin.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia wants to be assured of enough water from the river
basins to fuel projected growth in metro Atlanta and North Georgia
through the next 30 to 50 years. Alabama wants adequate water to
support its own growth, and Florida wants to be assured of enough
water coming down the Apalachicola to protect its thriving oyster
industry in Apalachicola Bay at the tail end of the ACF basin.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, West said Georgia could not deliver to Florida
the amount of water called for under current proposals without
jeopardizing Lake Lanier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be mathematically impossible to manage the
Chattahoochee (through dams now on the river) to guarantee these
flows,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   The states have until May 1 to reach water allocation agreements
for both basins. If there is no settlement, the water war most
likely will be tossed to the U.S. Supreme Court, where it could
take years and millions of dollars to settle. The feud has cost
taxpayers more than $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Gov. Don Siegelman on Thursday hinted the squabble may
very well end up before the nation's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Alabama chief negotiator Jim Campbell, Siegelman
said Georgia ``has been absolutely unwilling to meet us halfway''
in agreeing on an allocation formula for the ACT. ``Alabama has
been fair and reasonable in this process, but if Georgia is
unwilling to consider our needs, we will see them in court,''
Siegelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials have expressed similar sentiments over the
ACF.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, ACT talks in Montgomery between Alabama and Georgia
negotiators verged on breaking down.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell characterized Georgia's latest proposal as ``We'll take
all the water we want, and if there's anything left, you can have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
