<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF KOMERCNI BANKA RESIGNS DURING FRAUD INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LADKA BAUEROVA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The chairman of the Czech Republic's
Komercni Banka has resigned during an investigation into suspected
fraud at the ailing state-controlled bank, the largest in Central
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Czech government called the departure of Jan
Kollert, 50, an important step in preparing the bank for
privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Kollert, who stepped down Wednesday after less than two years on
the job, is the first high-ranking executive of the bank to leave
since financial irregularities were uncovered there late last year.
A complete replacement of the bank's management is planned by the
government, said Prime Minister Pavel Mertlik.
</P>
<P>
   The bank is currently saddled with $1.77 billion of
nonperforming loans, about 30 percent of its loan portfolio. The
government is hoping to clean up the bank's financial problems and
sell it by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government welcomes Kollert's resignation,'' Mertlik said.
``It was a logical step in light of all the problems that have
surfaced recently.''
</P>
<P>
   He announced that the state would assume the bulk of the bank's
nonperforming loans by the end of April. The cost of the portfolio
cleanup will be borne by Czech taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heavy losses and a problem-riddled loan portfolio,
Komercni represents an attractive investment opportunity to foreign
financial institutions, banking analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can imagine big European banks, and maybe even overseas
banks, being interested in Komercni,'' said Martin Vojta, a
financial analyst with the Patria Finance brokerage firm in Prague.
``It could be especially attractive to large German banks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the bank's management shake-up was likely to have a
positive effect on its share value. Komercni shares already have
risen more than 70 percent this year in anticipation of a
government bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Kollert's leadership of the bank was called into question in
December when Komercni's auditor, Deloitte &AMP; Touche, pointed out
huge discrepancies in the bank's books.
</P>
<P>
   The audit indicated that Komercni had fallen victim to a
complicated fraudulent scheme involving an Austrian commodity
trading company, BCL Trading; the scheme cost the bank $22 million.
The case is currently under police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Komercni has accumulated some of its bad loans in the last two
years, a period that included a recession in which many local
companies fell behind with loan repayments. But a greater portion
of its bad portfolio dates back to the early and mid-1990s, when
the bank was lending heavily to recently privatized companies and
fledgling private businesses that emerged after the fall of
Communism.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Czech government has rid Komercni of
nonperforming loans worth $640 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mertlik said in a radio interview Thursday that he expected the
government to get more than $1.1 billion from the sale of Komercni
Banka.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised that the planned April bailout would be the
last before its privatization. ``Unless something goes terribly
wrong again, this is the last time we will assist Komercni Banka
with its problems,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
