<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-GEORGIA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NRA backs Barnes' gun control plan
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes unveiled a gun control
proposal Thursday that immediately drew praise from an unlikely
source: the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes asked the General Assembly to increase penalties for
adults furnishing firearms to minors and for carrying guns to
schools. He also wants to make it a crime for felons to even
attempt buying a gun _ for what he described, half-jokingly, as
``criminal stupidity.'' Current law prevents them only from
completing the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill helps keep guns out of the hands of convicted
criminals and away from our children and schools,'' Barnes said at
a news conference. ``And those are two of the most important things
we can do in law enforcement today.''
</P>
<P>
   But the governor's plan may have more symbolic value than actual
effect on gun availability and violence, a political analyst
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a safe way to crack down some on gun abuse,'' said
Charles Bullock, a political scientist at the University of
Georgia. ``But it doesn't plow any new ground. It certainly isn't
going to reduce the availability of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Bullock added: ``It is a step against gun abuse. Many a
person who had been supported by the NRA would not even do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has enjoyed support from the NRA, a powerful force in
Georgia _ and national _ politics. The organization, which counts
90,000 members in the state, endorsed him in the 1998 governor's
race. It donated $5,000 to his campaign that year and gave another
$1,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes returned the favor shortly after he took office. One of
the first major bills he signed last year was an NRA-backed measure
that sought to prevent Georgia cities from suing firearms
manufacturers to recover costs of dealing with gun violence. A
lawsuit is pending over whether the measure blocks a suit the city
of Atlanta had already filed.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Barnes has not taken a position on a bill that would
make it a misdemeanor for adults to leave a handgun within easy
reach of a child younger than 18. The NRA opposes the measure,
which it describes as ``feel-good legislation'' that would
``stigmatize'' gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   But the NRA offered unqualified support for Barnes' bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is putting resources where they belong in
fighting crime _ which is on armed criminals and criminals who are
seeking to illegally arm themselves,'' said Randy Kozuch, the NRA's
director of state and local affairs. ``We commend the governor for
showing the courage to face the heart of the problem, which is
armed criminals in our communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said that if the bill had already been law, charges could
have been filed against the 9,000 convicted felons who have tried
to buy firearms from Georgia gun dealers since 1996. All were
turned away after background checks. But the only possible
sanctions they could face would be federal perjury charges if they
lied on a gun purchase application.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they go out and try again,'' Barnes said, ``and they find a
seller that's willing to sell to them anyway. Get a gun on the
street. That's the loophole we're trying to close.''
</P>
<P>
   Felons who seek to buy firearms could be sentenced to one to
five years in prison. No other state punishes felons for simply
trying to buy a gun, Barnes' aides and NRA spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   They also said the bill would impose the nation's toughest
penalty for possessing a firearm at or near a school or on a school
bus. The penalty would double to 10 years in prison and would
continue to have a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to say to every child _ and to every adult who would
give a child a handgun _ that we as a society will not tolerate
it,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also increase the minimum sentence for providing
a handgun to a minor to five years, up from one year. A second
conviction for anyone under 18 possessing a handgun would be a
felony, punishable by at least three years in prison and a $5,000
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the bill would increase penalties for convicted felons
who receive, possess or transport firearms; for carrying a
concealed deadly weapon; and for possessing a sawed-off shotgun,
machine gun or silencer.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he did not consult with the NRA before drafting the
bill. NRA's Kozuch said his organization provided no suggestions on
the measure's content.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed us the package,'' Kozuch said, ``and we expressed
our support for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
