<SLUG> BC-LONGSHORE-WAGES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS SAY AVERAGE LONGSHOREMAN MAKES $100,000 A YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Want to make $100,000 a year?
</P>
<P>
   Write software.
</P>
<P>
   Be a law partner.
</P>
<P>
   Or get a job as a longshoreman.
</P>
<P>
   In each case you will have to work more than 40 hours a week.
But to stack shipping containers, you won't have to go to grad
school.
</P>
<P>
   The average West Coast longshoreman, journeyman class, working
full-time or better, earned $101,500 last year. So says the Pacific
Maritime Association, the San Francisco-based association of
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike pay for seamen, carpenters or even aerospace machinists,
the longshore workers' pay compares well with salaries for
white-collar professionals.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't count their stock options, its even above the
much touted pay of computer engineers. The state says computer
engineers average $63,350, plus options. Of course, their options
can be substantial. The American Electronics Association says
Washington software employees, for example, average $158,000
including options.
</P>
<P>
   Longshore workers have been highly paid for years. In the 1960s,
Harry Bridges of the International Longshore and Warehouse Union
negotiated a deal that allowed shipowners to containerize. In
return, he won higher pay. Bridges, a scrappy left-winger who
professed little use for bosses, had won his members great
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just sharp negotiating. It was bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the strongest trade unions in the United
States,'' said David Olson, a University of Washington professor of
political science who has studied waterfront workers. ``It battled
over decades to achieve the status it has, and those battles are
seared in the memories of all members of this union. It shows
extraordinary solidarity, and extraordinary strategic abilities at
its leaderhip level. And when they sit down at the bargaining
table, they are tough as nails.''
</P>
<P>
   The longshoremen have the power to shut down the docks. One
day's delay can cost ship owners thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The employer is not willing to take a strike,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   The ILWU headquarters in San Francisco declined to comment on
the $101,000 figure. Steve Perkins, business agent for ILWU Local
19 in Seattle, was skeptical of it. ``In this area, that is
absolutely wrong. It certainly doesn't apply in Seattle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I wish I made that much money. I've been here 33
years. I've never made that.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Johnson, manager in Seattle for the owners' organization,
agreed that a higher proportion of $100,000-plus workers is in Los
Angeles-Long Beach, the ports offering the steadiest work.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Robert Dockendorff, the maritime association's vice
president for research, there are longshoremen pulling down more
than $100,000 in Seattle and Tacoma. Some operate gantry cranes, a
delicate job in whcih mistakes can be fatal; others do simpler jobs
running lifting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   As for the derisive laughs PMA gets for its survey, he said,
``We do the payrolls. That's where we get the figures.''
</P>
<P>
   His $101,500 figure is for class ``A'' longshoremen. It does not
include less experienced class ``B'' workers or casual workers, who
earn less _ nor clerks or foremen, who earn more.
</P>
<P>
   His $101,500 figure includes straight time, overtime, vacation
and holidays but not pension contributions, medical and other
benefits. These added $32,000 per worker under the old contract,
according to the employers' survey. (A new 3-year contract was
reached last summer.)
</P>
<P>
   The $101,500 average is only for those with at least 2,000 hours
of paid time. Some 55 percent of the journeymen longshoremen worked
that much time; 45 percent didn't. Many stop after 1,300 hours, the
minimum to qualify for a year's work under the pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   The average income for all West Coast journeymen longshore
workers, including part-timers, was $79,767.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state has different figures. Unlike the employers'
averages, the state's are medians (half of examples are above, half
below). That lowers them. They are for 1998, not 1999, which also
lowers them.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the state says:
</P>
<P>
   Longshore equipment operator, $71,420.
</P>
<P>
   Stevedore, $67,600.
</P>
<P>
   Though lower, these are still the sort of pay reported for
pharmacists and chemical engineers and nearly double the pay of a
carpenter or able seaman.
</P>
<P>
   The state's figures do not include overtime, which is how the
longshore worker who gets $100,000 does it. His base rate is
$26.68, which works out to $55,000 per year. But in addition to
overtime, other rules increase pay. If a longshore worker operates
a machine, his rate is $29.35 to $34.68; on overtime, $44.03 to
$52.02.
</P>
<P>
   It's standard practice for some workers to book nine or 10 hours
per day. Longshore clerk William Wallace, who has worked on the
waterfront for 35 years, puts in 10-hour days. Still, he laughed at
the the employers' wage survey. ``Last year was the first I made
more than $100,000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He radioed to the driver of a top picker. ``How many hours did
you have last year?''
</P>
<P>
   ``2,236,'' the driver replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was your gross?''
</P>
<P>
   A pause. ``Just over 85.''
</P>
<P>
   That's $38 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace explained that a reporter was asking about the $100,000
worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to scramble pretty hard for that,'' the driver
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some do. Sometimes workers volunteer to do two shifts, called a
double out. ``We have guys here who make 10 shifts a week,''
Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   The employers' statistics show that 13 percent of longshoremen
clocked at least 2,800 hours last year.
</P>
<P>
   Do they work hard? That's more than four months of overtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
