<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SC-VOICES-LOWCOUNTRY-     02-17 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-VOICES-LOWCOUNTRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW COUNTRY SOLIDLY REPUBLICAN BUT SPLIT ON CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is part of a six-story package. The other five stories
are SC-VOICES, SC-VOICES-SUBURBS, SC-CONSERVATIVES,
SC-VOICES-BLACKS and SC-VOICES-RETIREES)  
(bl) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT PLEASANT, S.C. _ The white-collar professionals at a
mid-week buffet supper at East Cooper Baptist Church, a big
congregation in this growing, affluent suburb of Charleston, take
their politics seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of those interviewed said they had tuned into the
three Republican candidates' debate on CNN on Tuesday night, and
several said they had attended rallies to hear the candidates. But
while they share conservative beliefs, there is little consensus on
a favorite Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Among these white Southern Baptists in the state's Low Country,
Alan Keyes, a black Roman Catholic, has won surprising support.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes has ``got a terrific Christian worldview of the integrity
and value of life,'' said Dennis Allen, 43, a former Air Force
fighter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bret Lott, 41, a novelist, said he would vote for
Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to know he's not going to win,'' Lott said, though he
added, ``His convictions are not swayed by the demographics he's
speaking to. And that means he's a man of character, a man of
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Most East Cooper Baptist members, however, lean toward either
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas or Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mosteller, 43, who manages a tour boat company, backs
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain has a compelling persona, he is a leader,'' said
Mosteller, whose wife, Cyndi, is vice chairman of the Charleston
County Republican Party and serves on McCain's national steering
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mosteller, 43, took McCain, an Episcopalian, to visit East
Cooper Baptist last August. Asked about the differing opinions in
the church, she said in an interview, ``We don't have a bloc vote.
And I think that has happened to the Christian community in the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   People are assessing the candidates on their own, Mosteller
said, rather than following recommendations of conservative
organizations like the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Sharon Mills said they were leaning toward McCain.
Dr. Mills, 43, said he liked the senator's talk of using the budget
surplus to reduce the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Millses said they would be content if Bush won the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they both are very honest candidates,'' Dr. Mills
said.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Bates, 43, a real estate developer, said he would vote for
Bush, partly because of the governor's emphasis on education and
tax-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Reg Christopher, 34, an engineer, also cited Bush's tax plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an entrepreneur, a small-business owner, so tax reductions
in any form I'm for,'' said Christopher, who said he also liked
Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists are the largest single religious group in
South Carolina, nearly 750,000 people spread among more than 1,900
congregations. They form a natural constituency for Bush, a United
Methodist who, with his story of a personal religious conversion,
speaks a language familiar to evangelical Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican presidential primaries in the South in 1988,
surveys showed that Southern Baptist ministers voted by a 2-to-1
margin for Bush's father, Vice President George Bush, said James L.
Guth, a professor of political science at Furman University in
Greenville. S.C. And this year, Guth said, the younger Bush may do
well in South Carolina's northern counties, where Southern Baptists
are especially numerous.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy T. Ammerman, a sociologist of religion at Hartford
Seminary in Hartford, Conn., said McCain's image as a crusading
reformer, opposed to big money in politics, would also appeal to
Southern evangelicals, who traditionally see themselves as
outsiders critical of the secular establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Brunderman, 40, a teacher at East Cooper Baptist's school,
said she leaned toward McCain. Brunderman, whose husband is an Air
Force lieutenant colonel, said she liked McCain's knowledge of
military matters and was convinced that he was solidly against
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really is a conservative,'' Brunderman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
