<SLUG> BC-WATER-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH TEXAS OFFICIALS SAY MEXICO WITHHOLDING IRRIGATION WATER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Joe Joe White is cq) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   McALLEN, Texas _ Mexico is withholding billions of gallons of
irrigation water from the Rio Grande, pushing many South Texas
farmers to the brink of insolvency, Valley water officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of the Rio Grande Regional Water Planning Group
Thursday, angry farmers and some board members called for trade
sanctions and other reprisals against Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   And while Glenn Jarvis, the McAllen attorney who chairs the
water planning group, said Mexican officials have indicated they
will release more water in the near future, it was clear many
farmers and other water officials are not willing to wait any
longer. Mexico has been withholding water since 1992, they charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to go ahead and address the problem right now,
instead of putting it off,'' insisted Jimmy Steidinger, a Hidalgo
County citrus producer. ``We've only got one more watering (left)
on some of these citrus groves, it's going to be a total disaster
to the Valley. A lot of these water districts are out of water,
almost. They need to go ahead and talk to the head people in
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, the United States and Mexico signed a treaty to build
two dams on the Rio Grande, and Mexico agreed to release an average
of a hundred-billion gallons of water into the Rio Grande a year.
The only exceptions allowed were in cases of ``extraordinary
drought'' or accidents in Mexico's hydraulic system.
</P>
<P>
   But at Thursday's meeting, Austin consultant R.J. Brandes said
records obtained from the International Boundary and Water
Commission show that from 1992 to 1997, Mexico had plenty of
rainfall and river inflows to the Rio Grande watershed to allow it
meet the treaty requirements, but the country nevertheless fell far
short of the quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reservoirs on the Mexican tributaries are storing more
water, there is more demand for water in Mexico and more water is
being used,'' Brandes said. ``It simply isn't making it to the Rio
Grande.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Joe White, manager of the Valley's largest irrigation
district, said the water shortage in the two Rio Grande reservoirs
cost growers in three Valley counties $150 million in reduced crop
harvests during 1998. The figure climbs as high as $400 million
when lost salaries and other expenses and added to the equation,
White said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Hill, manager of the Bayview Irrigation District No. 11
in Los Fresnos, accused Mexico of withholding the water to serve
its own growing agri-businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some large American companies that have gone into
and are operating on the Conchos (the largest tributary to the Rio
Grande) and basically those are large operations that need the
water,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill claims to have seen documentation indicating Mexico's 1997
harvest was the largest in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they're in there producing as much as they can,
like we do in the Valley, but they're using our water, at our
expense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McAllen's public utilities system manager, Bart Hines, suggested
the United States retaliate by withholding some of the 32 billion
gallons of water released to Mexico each year from the Colorado
River. IBWC engineers said that is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   A number of officials accused the international water commission
of bungling talks with the Mexicans. They called on the Texas and
U.S. governments to get involved in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are in the year 2000 and nothing has been done,'' said
James Matz, a Cameron County commissioner. ``We're at the beginning
of another planting season, the agricultural community is just
about ready to go bankrupt. We need help now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Jarvis is optimistic the water dispute will be worked
out later this month during a Monterrey, Mexico, meeting of the
IBWC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is something that will be resolved, it will be a
matter of time possibly,'' Jarvis said. ``I think ultimately Mexico
will release some water.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
