<SLUG> BC-TORNADOES-MEMORIAL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memorial honors Georgia's tornado victims
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMILLA, Ga. _ The roof was gone, blown away by the tornado that
forced Harris Malcom, his wife and daughter to cower in the hallway
with only a thin mattress for protection.
</P>
<P>
   Pine trees punctured the wooden house. Windows exploded. The
wind, roaring like some unseen demon, whirled glass and books and
clothes and furniture around Malcom, wife Phyllis and 16-year-old
Katie.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was gone. The Malcoms survived.
</P>
<P>
   Their story is not too dissimilar from those of hundreds of
other South Georgia residents. Yet unlike the farmers, the
teachers, the chicken plant workers and others who experienced
God's fury up close, Harris Malcom is a preacher.
</P>
<P>
   He's the pastor of First Baptist Church in Camilla, where a
memorial service for tornado victims was held Thursday evening amid
much song and prayer and sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The shepherd of a flock numbering 1,000 parishioners, Malcom
clearly holds no special dispensation from above when it comes to
suffering. He expects none and unselfishly deflected any undue
attention paid to his plight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are questioning the love of God right now,'' said
Malcom, 46, outside his soon-to-be-bulldozed home off U.S. 19.
``But the love of God is what spared me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is not why it happened or how it happened,'' he
said. ``Regardless of what happened, at any moment in your life,
you have to be ready to meet God.''
</P>
<P>
   Another round of funerals took place Thursday in this rural
corner of Georgia. Emergency officials listed 18 dead and dozens
injured in the tornadoes and thunderstorms that raked Mitchell,
Colquitt, Tift and Grady counties late Sunday and early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 450 homes were damaged or destroyed. Forty
manufactured homes and travel trailers should arrive Monday to give
temporary housing for those most in need.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state officials kept an eye on possible stormy
weather moving eastward.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's potential for severe weather through this weekend,''
said Jeffrey Jellets, a spokesman for the Georgia Emergency
Management Agency. ``We certainly don't need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
