<SLUG> BC-BBN-DOWNING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Downing, 715 victim, joining Braves booth
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Al Downing forever will be remembered as the pitcher
who threw home run No. 715 to Hank Aaron. But that historic moment
will no longer be his only connection to baseball in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Downing was named as the analyst on Fox Sports Net
South's 30-game Braves package.
</P>
<P>
   Downing succeeds Ernie Johnson Sr. as Bob Rathbun's partner on
the network's schedule of 25 regular-season games and five spring
training telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never talked to Al about that (No. 715), and it had nothing
to do with our decision,'' said Fox Sports Net South executive
producer Steve Craddock. ``I've been aware of Al's work for CBS
Radio on the playoffs, and we wanted a guy with broadcasting
experience, and a guy who had been around the clubhouse as a
broadcaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Craddock said the former pitcher for the Yankees, Dodgers and
Angels also has worked in television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a traditional booth with Bob doing all the
play-by-play,'' Craddock said. ``When analyzing baseball games, the
drama between the pitcher and batter is the most intriguing, so we
needed someone who was a master with the pitch or a master with the
bat. And when we looked at who was available, Al was the logical
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Downing, who lives in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
