</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux ready as media pops the `big question'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ The scene was surreal.
</P>
<P>
   Straight off a red-eye flight from Las Vegas, Greg Maddux sat at
his locker in the Braves' clubhouse, wearing his usual golf shirt,
shorts and baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was the first and only pitcher on hand at 10 a.m.
Thursday, the day Braves pitchers and catchers were scheduled to
report to spring training.
</P>
<P>
   But he was far from alone. He was surrounded by a throng of
national media, both television and print, and he was speaking in
his usual quiet way about a very loud topic.
</P>
<P>
   And reliever John Rocker, still awaiting word on his appeal of
the suspension he received for his controversial comments in Sports
Illustrated, wasn't even there.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ken) Griffey's later, (and) playoffs in other sports don't
start yet,'' Maddux said, shrugging at the attention he was
drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Then he continued with the question about how Rocker will react
upon his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personal problems? On the field is usually the only time you
forget about it. Who knows? He was under the gun last year and we
were like, `Wow, go ahead, Rocker.' It'll be that times 100
wherever he goes. Maybe he throws 100 times better, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   In his own soft-spoken way, Maddux might have helped to defuse a
subject the Braves would very much like to forget. Getting ready
for the season officially begins today with workouts for pitchers
and catchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only going to be a distraction if you let it,'' Maddux
said. ``It's not going to distract me. I'll talk to you guys about
it, get on the treadmill, do my PFPs (pitcher's fielding practice),
talk about it again and then find another golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   After general manager John Schuerholz and manager Bobby Cox met
Thursday morning, Cox said the Braves would not issue a gag order
and that players would be asked to use common sense in commenting
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll treat it like it's someone with a sore arm,'' Cox said.
``You mention it, then that's it. It's going to be a dead issue
simply because we've got to get ready for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was a big day for several reasons. Andres Galarraga
arrived in camp ready to intensify his climb back from a yearlong
bout with lymphoma. Galarraga has been soft-tossing since December
but today plans to start swinging against pitching from coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I almost started crying when I came here,''
Galarraga said, referring to the day he spoke publicly for the
first time since his illness was revealed. ``Now I'm happy. I'm
excited. (I've had) no problems, no pain. Everything is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The concern is how his back will respond to the rigors of
swinging against major-league pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (back) is strong enough not to break it,'' Galarraga said.
``In my mind, I'm ready to go. . . . They want me to go easy. They
know me. They don't want me to push it too much now.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez was set to take his first swings in a batting cage
Thursday since he had surgery on his nonthrowing shoulder in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg, coming back from ligament surgery, last week
revved up his throwing to between 85 percent and 90 percent. On
Thursday, he described it this way: ``No pain, the ball was live,
good control, feels almost too good.''
</P>
<P>
   However, nothing close to a decision has been made about a
closer. But Maddux had his own funny contribution to that question,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see _ maybe Ligtenberg, maybe Rudy (Seanez), maybe
Smoltzie,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz, probably on a golf course, wasn't there to defend
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
