u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-TRUCKS18-C     02-17 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TRUCKS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newest event could be the raciest
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The newest event of Speedweeks at Daytona
International Speedway could be the most exciting.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's Craftsman Truck Series will stage a 250-mile race here
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to see more drafting than you'd even believe,''
said Bobby Hamilton, who is running Winston Cup and truck races
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Safety restrictions placed by NASCAR and the aerodynamic
disadvantage of the trucks' boxy shape, Hamilton said, will allow
drivers to race the way Winston Cup drivers could in the era before
restrictor plates changed strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have two people racing for the lead, and the guy
behind them can pass them both if he hits it right,'' said
Hamilton, who will start fifth. ``You don't need any help.''
</P>
<P>
   If the situation changes, help is nearby. Joe Ruttman,
Hamilton's teammate, starts on the pole.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grissom, a former Winston Cup regular, will start a Petty
Enterprises Dodge from the 10th starting spot. He said he agrees
with Hamilton that trucks give drivers more options.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the trucks, you can go ahead and make a move,'' Grissom
said. ``If it doesn't work out, the truck can pull itself back up
and you won't lose the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Speed will be governed by an air cleaner that has been changed
to limit air flow, thus hampering engine performance. The rear
spoiler also must be an inch taller, which slows the trucks and
makes them drive better.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said the restrictions should succeed in providing a
margin of safety for a group with little experience on a track such
as Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are doing well in practice. And they've got the
trucks driving so well that you're going to have to really put
yourself in a bad position for it to get out from under you,''
Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Truck drivers have run on 1.5-mile and 2-mile superspeedways
before, but this is the first time on a 2.5-mile track.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
