r s BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX     02-17 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO RELINQUISHES EXTRA RESPONSIBILITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The return of defenseman Derian Hatcher to the
Dallas Stars' lineup tonight means center Mike Modano will have to
return the ``C'' on his sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Modano has been captain since Hatcher was sidelined by a
lacerated calf muscle on Dec. 17. He usually fills in when
Hatcher's hurt, but this has been his longest stint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been fun having it,'' said Modano, who took the ``C''
pretty seriously. ``I think responsibility is the big thing,
knowing each and every night you have to come to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano isn't kidding when he said the responsibility came at
just the right time.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30 games before being selected captain, Modano had 11
goals and 11 assists. In the 23 games since, Modano had 13 goals
and 16 assists. NIEUWENDYK ON SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk is he's on
schedule to return from his separated shoulder in the eight-week
time frame first given by doctors. The bad news for him is that's
another three weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing pretty good,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``It's getting
better all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk said he has been able to feel the improvement while
lifting weights and stretching. He said he expects to begin skating
next week while the team is on a three-game road trip. MARSHALL
DISAPPOINTED
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated doesn't even begin to explain winger Grant Marshall's
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm frustrated,'' Marshall said. ``I've only got one
point in 24 games or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't exaggerating either. He has more torn groins (two) this
season than points (one). But Marshall said he has been trying not
to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting to the point now where I know I am working hard,''
Marshall said. ``If I get points, I get points. If I don't, I
don't.'' BUILDING A LEAD
</P>
<P>
   At times during the season, six points barely separated the
entire Pacific Division. Now, the Stars, winners of nine of 11,
have the opportunity to take a six-point lead over second-place
Phoenix with a victory tonight against the Coyotes at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars dominated the Coyotes, 2-0, in Phoenix before the
All-Star break to draw even in points, and despite all the problems
and distractions of this season, the Stars lead the season series,
2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it makes teams and players wonder how we're still
doing it,'' Mike Modano said. ``They're still asking themselves
that question, a lot of coaches are, I'm sure, surprised,
bewildered how we're still keeping track with everyone else and
still winning with all these new faces and changes.'' THIS AND THAT
</P>
<P>
   Surgery on winger Jere Lehtinen's ankle went well, coach Ken
Hitchcock said. Lehtinen is expected to miss six weeks, returning
on April 2 against Colorado. ... In their past 15 games at Reunion
Arena, the Stars have played in seven one-goal games. They are
undefeated in them. ... Ed Belfour will be in goal for the Stars
tonight. nn
</P>
