<SLUG> BC-CAR-TWIN-RACE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Twin upsets at Daytona
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Bill Elliott took the checkered flag in
Thursday's first Twin 125 and will start third in Sunday's Daytona
500, behind Dale Jarrett and Ricky Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia native, who hasn't won a Winston Cup race in nearly
six years, said the fast start at Daytona was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was very critical,'' Elliott said. ``For as hard as
our team has worked through the winter, to be able to come out and
qualify third and win the 125, it was a critical point for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, driving the No. 94 Ford, also ended the record streak
of a longtime rival.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Thursday's events, Dale Earnhardt had won a Twin 125
for the past 10 years, dating back to 1990. Earnhardt started third
but fell to 11th by the finish. It led to a disappointing No. 21
start in Sunday's Daytona 500 and a rare postrace outburst by the
Intimidator.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the worst racing I've seen at Daytona in a long time,''
Earnhardt said. ``They took NASCAR Winston Cup racing and made it
some of the sorriest racing. They took the racing out of the hands
of the drivers and the crews. They just killed racing at Daytona.
It's a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who rarely blasts the sport's governing body, says
NASCAR's new rules requiring all teams to run the same shocks,
along with equal distribution of the weight of the cars, is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Both races were boring, several Winston Cup drivers said. It was
mostly single-file racing, with no cautions or lead changes during
either of the 50-lap events. Elliott took the lead from Jarrett
just after the starting line. In the second race, Rudd started and
finished first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Daytona 500 and I think you'll see an exciting race.
. . . I hope so,'' Rudd said. ``I mean, the fans didn't pay a lot
of money to come and see us run single file, I think they want us
to run three-wide. I think a lot of (drivers) just wanted to get
these races . . . behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of surprises Thursday. In the first race,
Scott Pruett solidified his status as Daytona's top rookie by
finishing eighth, earning the No. 15 spot in the big event. In the
final race, Dale Earnhardt Jr. passed seven drivers to end up in
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers having to take provisionals were Bobby Hamilton,
Sterling Marlin, Kenny Wallace, Elliott Sadler, Kevin Lepage, Kyle
Petty and Darrell Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
