<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MOVES (SMART OR LUCKY?) PAY OFF
</HEADLINE>
 12-JONES COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of circumstance is sometimes genius born. And sometimes, stuff
just happens.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sharp eye that recognizes good fortune and so it is
that Texas coach Rick Barnes has discovered a method in his recent
madness.
</P>
<P>
   Recall that Barnes dropped both guard Will Clay and forward Gabe
Muoneke from the starting lineup recently for disciplinary reasons.
Clay missed an early flight to Massachusetts. Gabe? Well, Gabe in
his words, ``made coach Barnes mad'' at practice the day before the
Longhorns played Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The point now is that Barnes ``likes'' using both players off
the bench, not that he disciplined two seniors. And that's where
some people have missed the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain things happen and you have to do things,'' Barnes
said. ``But it's like with family, you don't hold it over someone's
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in practice with Gabe obviously made me do what
I did. But I actually liked it. I felt he was good coming off the
bench. He was great against Missouri and great \Ragainst Oklahoma
State\S. The thing that bothers me right now is, I don't want
people to think Gabe is being disciplined over something that is
over and done with. And the same thing with Will.''
</P>
<P>
   So, prying minds want to know, how does Gabe feel about it?
Truth be told, Gabe said this week he'd just as soon be in the
starting lineup because he's a senior and he has been introduced as
a starter for most of three seasons. But he could get that out of
his mind if people stopped asking him about it.
</P>
<P>
   The most misunderstood player I've known in 30 years, however,
has accepted his new role. He played 32 minutes and was the
difference-maker in Wednesday night's victory against No. 8 OSU
that sends Texas into Baylor tomorrow (12:45 p.m.) at 9-2, even
with the Cowboys and a game back of leader Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe also understands that Barnes' latest moves are part of an
evolving plan for March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Barnes has been doing this a long time,'' Gabe said.
``He knows what he's going to do in his head. Right now, he's
seeing how different things work. The most important thing is
winning. I believe that once March Madness starts, once the \RNCAA
Tournament\S seeding comes out, coach Barnes will say OK, this is
what I've done. This is what works best. And now we're going to get
after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes knows what he gets from Muoneke, Clay, Chris Mihm, Ivan
Wagner and lately Darren Kelly, who was just short of sensational
against both Missouri and OSU. Starting Chris Owens and Lawrence
Williams gives Barnes a chance to see what he might be getting from
two players who can be impressive in bursts. But that's their
problem, the time between bursts. Muoneke's all-around game and
Clay's defense change the game when they check in. And Gabe
relieves either Owens or Mihm _ or Williams or Kelly if Barnes
wants to go big as he did in the stretch Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing that amused, mad-scientist look he sometimes gets,
Barnes says the tinkering might continue. But if he doesn't put
Muoneke back into the starting lineup, Gabe won't bear a grudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love coach Barnes to death,'' Gabe said. ``Nothing that goes
on on the court is personal. I've never had any malicious feelings
for coach Barnes at all. What happened at practice that day wasn't
him. It was me. There were some other things bothering me that day
and I was in a bad mood. It was good that he busted my butt when he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   In ways then yet unknown. A&AMP;M'S KING DISCOVERS PRACTICE, SCORING
RELATED
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M freshman Bernard King has reappeared in the running
for Big 12 rookie of the year after a difficult January.
</P>
<P>
   During one stretch last month, King made only 16 of 55 shots
from the floor. In February, he has again found his stroke. In the
past four games, including a 3-for-20 game against Oklahoma State,
King is 28-for-56 and has hit 16 of 37 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started with last week's practice,'' A&AMP;M coach Melvin
Watkins said. ``We sat down and had a conversation with him about
how hard you have to practice every day. We ask a lot from him and
it's been tough on him. But still, we know his potential and after
a good week of practice, it's good to see him let it shine on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   King followed his Big 12 freshman record 34-point game against
Colorado with 21 points in a losing cause against Baylor on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   His 16.7-point average ranks fifth nationally among Division I
freshmen. He is on pace to break the Big 12 freshman scoring record
set by close friend and fellow north Louisiana product Marcus
Fizer, who averaged 14.7 points in his first season at Iowa State
three years ago. King is averaging 2.73 3-point shots per game,
which would eclipse Luke Axtell's freshman record of 2.43, also set
in the 1997-98 season. UT STUDENTS SPEAK
</P>
<P>
   In a recent story about upcoming changes involving the Erwin
Center, both Texas men's coach Rick Barnes and women's athletic
director and coach Jody Conradt urged some sort of immediate
reconfiguration to make students more a part of the games.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't musing idly. Except for a service group of about
two dozen guys who paint their faces, students aren't even remotely
a part of games. Part of that reason is the fact that their seats _
most above the band behind a basket at one end of the court _
stink. That was reflected by the fact that students returned for
public sale almost half of their 4,000-seat allotment for the
Longhorns' Wednesday night game against Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not coming and my question is why?'' Barnes said.
``One thing I will never buy into is the fact that they once had
\Rbetter seat locations\S and didn't use them \Rin the early 90s\S.
I'm not concerned with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we've got 1,000 students standing in each end zone,
it would have a tremendous effect on the game. I do believe there
is a way we can get 2,000 students on the floor where they can make
a lot of noise and make a lot of difference \Rin the atmosphere\S.
That's one of the things we've got to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   UT athletic director DeLoss Dodds says the announcement of the
Erwin Center coming under the auspices of the athletic department
is imminent, pending minor details. IT AIN'T OVER 'TILL ...
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looked like Iowa State was in a commanding position
for its first Big 12 women's title and the accompanying No. 1 seed
in the conference tournament, along comes tomorrow's pivotal game
involving Oklahoma and an old familiar face, Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   A victory in the nationally televised (ESPN2, 1 p.m.) affair in
Lubbock would thrust the No. 12 Lady Raiders (20-3, 9-3) into a tie
with No. 18 Oklahoma (20-5, 10-2) and could create a four-way jam
in the loss column with Kansas and Iowa State, which doesn't play
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Or, a loss could drop Tech to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a mess,'' Tech coach Marsha Sharp said. ``You can go from
first to fifth in about two hours' time these days. It's
unbelievable. We've talked a lot about the strength of our
conference all the way through and it's been proven out.''
</P>
<P>
   The OU game will be the first national exposure for Tech's new
arena since the Lady Raiders christened it in November with a
victory over Louisiana State on the Lifetime Network. ESPN2 gets
into a few more homes. Should be about 13,000 fans at United Spirit
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great thing for our conference,'' Sharp said. ``The
atmosphere, everything on the line with national exposure. Just
great for the Big 12.'' FREE THROWS
</P>
<P>
   -- A hint on when you know this is your season. Iowa State's
Marcus Fizer hit the winning shot in the Cyclones' 64-62 victory at
Kansas on what was described as an improbable 17-foot turnaround
jumper from the right corner with 6.2 seconds left, just before the
shot clock expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deflected the ball,'' KU center Eric Chenowith said.
``That's probably what made it go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer, who scored 12 of his 15 points in the second half, said
he was thinking bank shot off the glass when he shot. It swished
instead.
</P>
<P>
   -- So here is Kansas (17-6, 7-4), hanging on in sixth place and
playing for the fourth and final seed (based this year on 1-4 in
the conference standings).
</P>
<P>
   ``This one hurts,'' coach Roy Williams said after the Iowa State
loss. ``It's one I'm going to remember for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Been a couple of those this season.
</P>
<P>
   -- There had to be some question about the Texas women's chances
of returning to the NCAA Tournament after last season's surprising
invitation following a 16-11 season and a first-round loss in the
Big 12 tournament. But the Longhorns (17-8, 8-4) now look good for
an NCAA reprise if they can split down the regular-season stretch
(at Colorado, Texas Tech, at Texas A&AMP;M, Iowa State).
</P>
<P>
   Why? UT plays one of the top schedules nationally and now has
three victories over ranked opponents in nine Top 25 games after
Wednesday's improbable victory at No. 18 Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   -- The NCAA is investigating possible rules violations by the
Iowa State men's team, the Des Moines Register reported yesterday.
According to the newspaper, the investigation apparently focuses on
Ernest Brown, a 7-foot center playing at Indian Hills Community
College in Ottumwa, Iowa. Brown signed a letter of intent with Iowa
State last fall. ISU athletic director Gene Smith has acknowledged
the school received a preliminary letter of inquiry from the NCAA.
Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy said he is confident the NCAA will
find nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   -- Baylor's DeMarcus Minor is due for a rest. He's averaging
39.4 minutes a game in the Big 12. He could break the conference
record set by former Texas shooting star Reggie Freeman, who
averaged 38.5 minutes in 16 games in 1997. Following Minor in
minutes played this season are ISU guards Michael Nurse (37.6) and
Kantrail Horton (36.9).  &QL; 
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's victory over UT-Pan American this week was the last
nonconference game of the 2000 season for Big 12 men's teams,
giving the conference its most victories over non-league foes in
its four-year existence. A look back: Year W-L Pct. 1996-97 104-32
.765 1997-98 96-45 .681 1998-99 98-51 .658 1999-00 108-40 .729
