<HEADER>
A0340 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-RICHARD-REVIEW-515     02-17 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RICHARD-REVIEW-515&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE RICHARD SINGS AN ODE TO HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This just in: It's been a whopping 10 days since ``Who Wants to
Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' was taped in Las Vegas, and Rick and
Darva Rockwell remain married.
</P>
<P>
   In related news, the show was a hit on Tuesday night, and Fox
plans an hourlong encore version on Tuesday. It will replace the
previously scheduled ``Banned in America: The World's Sexiest
Television.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a moment to let that soak in _ OK, that's enough _ and
we'll move along to Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The early rock 'n' roll star Little Richard always seemed more
of a force of nature than a carbon-based package of humanity, so
maybe his story lends itself to the cartoonish treatment it gets
Sunday on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'd have expected something at least a little weightier
than the frothy and shamelessly self-serving ``Little Richard.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-serving because although the star of the movie is the
one-named Leon (``The Temptations,'' ``The Five Heartbeats''), the
executive producer is none other than Little Richard, who modestly
allows himself to be called ``the architect of rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   That accolade comes twice, actually. At another point, the Leon
version of Little Richard more accurately calls himself ``hotter
than fish grease in the summertime.''
</P>
<P>
   By way of biographical insight, the movie informs us that Little
Richard was from Macon, Ga., that his hard-nosed but loving father
(played by Carl Lumbly) was murdered, that Little Richard had a
girlfriend named Lucille (Tamala Jones) for a while, that he is
religious and that he adores pancake makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly these personal asides are like thin rye wrapped around
the movie's real innards _ the music. And around Leon's cutesy
performance as the eye-rolling, shoulder-shimmying purveyor of such
early rock classics as ``Tutti Frutti'' and ``Long Tall Sally.''
</P>
<P>
   I give director Robert Townsend (``The Five Heartbeats,''
``Hollywood Shuffle'') credit for putting a bright, brassy sheen on
the movie. It's lively and watchable, however empty. The music is
fun.
</P>
<P>
   The film's best few moments capture Leon and a Pat Boone
look-alike in separate recording sessions for ``Long Tall Sally.''
The scene, with Boone struggling through his cover version for his
well-scrubbed audience, could make a white man wince in
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Richard'' finds its epiphany in 1967 when the erstwhile
Richard Penniman is seen knocking an audience dead during an
Australian tour. Right in the middle of ``Long Tall Sally,'' he
spots a comet streaking across the sky and takes it as a sign from
God. He decides, right there, to chuck his brilliant singing career
to become a preacher.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked in this pivotal scene, which leads the movie and is
repeated later, is the fact that by 1967, Little Richard was a rock
'n' roll relic.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that the executive producer of this movie didn't
choose to see himself as outdated. It's also possible that a movie
that would fudge on one fact might fudge on others.
</P>
<P>
   But as a program form, these bios keep rocking along. We've had
Elvis, the Beatles, the Jackson Five and the Temptations, and a
week from Sunday the overly familiar story of the Beach Boys hits
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   How long before some network coughs up a Bob Dylan biopic? And
will it have the honesty to call it ``It Ain't Me, Babe''?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``All the King's Men,'' a one-part film on ``Masterpiece
Theatre,'' is a British World War I story, not a remake of the
Robert Penn Warren novel. It's about an incident that Winston
Churchill once called ``without a doubt the greatest unsolved
mystery of this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Churchill said that in 1919, so there were a few 20th century
mysteries to come. Such as: Why is ``Veronica's Closet'' still on
national television?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the mystery involves a company of volunteers raised from
the royal estate at Sandringham. In 1915, during the disastrous
Gallipoli campaign in Turkey, the company vanished on the
battlefield. There were reports that the soldiers had been swept up
into a strange mist.
</P>
<P>
   That seems a poor explanation, scientifically speaking, although
I have known a few people to disappear into strange clouds. This
BBC movie is based on a book by its co-producer, Nigel McCrery, and
purports to solve the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   I won't spoil the movie, but the answer isn't pretty. And it
doesn't take the movie where a casual viewer might expect it to go.
It seems as if we're just settling in with these guys and then,
(set ital)poof.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   David Jason, a popular comic actor in Britain, is utterly
convincing as the squat, middle-aged Capt. Frank Beck, who turned a
company of grooms and gardeners into soldiers and then led them
into battle.
</P>
<P>
   For American viewers, the more familiar co-star is Maggie Smith
as the compassionate Queen Alexandra, mother of the reigning King
George V (David Troughton). She encouraged and honored the dutiful
Beck and commissioned a quiet inquiry into what happened on the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the King's Men'' becomes a bit disjointed in its second
half, but it's still a smartly entertaining, and beautifully
photographed, trek to two worlds _ Sandringham and Gallipoli _ that
contrast with each other as idyllic and gruesomely terrible.
</P>
<P>
   A footnote at the end of the movie reminds viewers that of more
than a million men from the British Empire who were killed in World
War I, half have no known graves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
