<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0341 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BANK-2TAKES-NY     02-17 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKING INQUIRY'S TANGLED WEB REACHES LOFTY LEVELS IN MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: The 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 9:40 p.m. ET) 
(js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a city where banks sprout and die like mushrooms and
pseudo-banks are not uncommon, the money-moving network described
in a New York court on Wednesday in the fast-unfolding Bank of New
York case quickly branches into a tangled web of control and
ownership, some strands reaching to the highest levels of Russian
finance and government.
</P>
<P>
   For a start, neither Flamingo nor DKB _ the two Moscow banks
that figure prominently in the accounts of Lucy Edwards and Peter
Berlin, the banking couple whose guilty plea has opened a new
window on the case _ were really banks at all, according to Russian
bankers and U.S. investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they were front companies that allowed ingenious schemes
for funneling money out of Russia beneath the radar of customs and
tax officials, and into one of three accounts at the Bank of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Such specialty banks are a key element of the economic chaos
that resulted from the precipitous disintegration of the Soviet
system. The most rudimentary mechanisms and controls were absent as
Russians scrambled for the abandoned resources, the winners
emerging with huge holdings and fabulous fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these entities are called pocket banks, belonging to a
single company or industry that needs a special line of credit.
Others are political banks, born of the embrace between Russian
business and government that has given new meaning to crony
capitalism. And sorting out which is which and who owns what is an
accountant's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, according to documents filed Wednesday in New
York, both Flamingo and DKB (the Russian initials for Deposit
Clearing Bank) were the children of two Russian banks, MDM and
Sobinbank, both of which have enjoyed the backing of well-connected
patrons in Moscow, some with close ties to the Kremlin, others
linked to the Moscow City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Sobinbank was no phony institution. Founded in 1990, it had a
lobby and customers and had been put together by a collection of
larger, powerful Russian banks, including SBS Agro, a bank headed
by Alexander Smolensky, who had ties to Boris Berezovksy, Russia's
master political intriguer, financier and media mogul.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known whether those powerful patrons invented, used or
even knew of the elaborate money transfer schemes used to move $7
billion through the Bank of New York accounts controlled by Berlin
_ Benex, BECS and Lowland. Much of the money that moved through
them belonged to Russian importers looking for ways to pay foreign
suppliers without alerting Russian authorities to the real value of
their contracts. But there is also evidence that the same schemes
were used by criminals to launder money, and by rich Russians to
park their profits overseas, in off-shore banking havens.
</P>
<P>
   According to observers here, the more Edwards, the former Bank
of New York vice president, and her husband, Berlin, cooperate with
federal authorities, the more nervous many of Russia's top bankers
are likely to become.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am certain that if these two continue to talk, they will be
able to say a lot about illegal activities, the participants in
which would include well known financiers and public figures,''
said Yuri Skuratov, Russia's former prosecutor general, whose
ouster last winter by the Kremlin set off a successive wave of
financial scandals here that culminated last August when the
federal investigation of the Bank of New York became publicly
known.
</P>
<P>
   But sorting out the facts in the chaos of Soviet banking is a
formidable task, if not impossible. With lax reporting standards,
weak laws and a high mortality rate among banks _ if not bankers _
paper trails meander through tangles of shifting owners, and
sometimes disappear.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
