<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FED-GREENSPAN-REACT-N     02-17 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GREENSPAN-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GREENSPAN IS TUNED OUT BY TECHNOLOGY INVESTORS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also FED-GREENSPAN) 
(rk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Alan Greenspan speaks, the old economy trembles. But the
new one thinks it is impervious to higher interest rates, and
shrugs off warnings from the Fed chairman.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the pattern since the Fed began to raise interest
rates last summer, and it continued Thursday. Greenspan's stark
warnings that short-term interest rates will continue to rise had
only a brief impact on the Nasdaq composite index, which is
dominated by high-technology companies that are benefiting from the
digital revolution.
</P>
<P>
   That index then shot up 121.27 points, or 2.7 percent, to a new
high of 4,548.92, as the Nasdaq market traded 2 billion shares for
the first time. The index is up 69 percent since June 30, the date
of the first of the Fed's four rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   But the story was different for the Dow Jones industrial
average, which is far more dependent on stocks that are liable to
be hurt as higher interest rates slow the economy. It fell 100
points within minutes after the Fed chairman began testifying;
while it recovered some of that, it ended down 46.84 points, or
almost half a percentage point, at 10,514.57. It is down about 4
percent since June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus reaction on Wall Street seemed to be that little
was new in the chairman's testimony. ``Maybe he's raised his own
estimate'' of how high interest rates have to go to slow the
economy, said Robert DiClemente, an economist at Salomon Smith
Barney. ``But he didn't say we needed to get there faster.''
</P>
<P>
   For some time the fixed-income markets have been expecting at
least two more increases in short-term rates by the Fed, with the
first one, of at least a quarter percentage point, expected next
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chairman's comments did not trigger any massive
re-evaluation of where the Fed is going,'' said Louis Crandall, the
chief economist of Wrightson Associates, a bond market research
firm. ``If anything, it may have made people a little more
nervous'' that the next increase might be a half percentage point,
rather than the quarter-point raise seen in the previous increases.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term interest rates rose moderately Thursday, though it
was unclear how much of that was caused by Greenspan's remarks and
how much by other factors, including a report by the Federal
Reserve Bank of Philadelphia that indicated rising price pressures
for manufacturing companies.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Greenspan noted the willingness of many stock
investors to shrug off the risk of higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, rising business earnings expectations and declining
compensation for risk have more than offset'' the impact of higher
rates, he said. But he forecast that, at some point, rates would
rise enough to have an impact on the expectations of stock market
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenspan seems dead set on taking the punch bowl from the
party,'' said Thomas M. Galvin, chief equity strategist at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``The market is understanding that
interest rates will continue to head higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Barbera, the chief economist of Hoenig &AMP; Co., agreed.
Greenspan, he said, ``is committed to ending, for a time, outsized
gains for the equity market.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks, however, do not stop going up just because interest
rates rise. They stop going up because investors stop bidding them
up. So far, it appears, higher interest rates have alarmed
investors in many industries. General Electric, Coca-Cola and
Citigroup were among the Dow stocks that fell by at least a dollar
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But those losses were partly offset by gains in Microsoft, Intel
and IBM. Technology stock investors are not worried about higher
interest rates, and Wednesday's forceful testimony from Greenspan
did not change that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
