<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0346 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-WINDOWS-SPI     02-17 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-WINDOWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOCT LAUNCHES HIGH-STAKES WINDOWS 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Microsoft partied as it unveiled its new Windows 2000
operating system in San Francisco Thursday, accompanied by rock
stars and an actor, cheering fans and a 40-foot high mock laptop
with keys the size of stepping stones.
</P>
<P>
   But chairman Bill Gates only rarely cracked a smile as the
hoopla reached its pitch, a telling reminder that this is the
product upon which the company has risked its future.
</P>
<P>
   With $2 billion development costs and 35 million lines of code,
Windows 2000 is the product that Microsoft hopes will allow it to
continue its dominance in the worldwide software market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we unveil the future of computing,'' said Gates, flanked
by Star Trek actor Patrick Stewart and rock's Carlos Santana and
his band at a conference staged by the company to introduce the
software upgrade. ``We're so excited that this will become the
standard on the business desktops.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the product has drawn positive reviews from several
Seattle-area companies that have been previewing the
business-oriented operating system designed to replace Windows NT
4.0. It is a solid product that boosts performance and stability on
both desktop PCs and servers, they say.
</P>
<P>
   But others, leery of major new software because it is often
flawed, say they'll hold off for six months or more until problems
that may emerge have been cured. One of those is the city of
Medina, the wealthy community where Gates lives.
</P>
<P>
   Gates predicted that Windows 2000 would be on every desktop PC,
but didn't predict the same for servers, the souped-up PCs that run
many corporations' e-mail, accounting and personnel systems.
Microsoft chief executive Steve Ballmer admitted that delays in
Windows 2000 _ it was initially expected to debut in early to
mid-1999 _ have given Microsoft's competitors, including Novell's
NetWare and the grassroots Linux operating system, an opportunity
to gain converts in the server marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   But Windows 2000, he said, will bring customers back.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 2000 Professional Desktop version costs $319 for new
users, $219 for upgrades from Windows 95 and 98, and $149 for
upgrades from Windows NT. The Server version sells for $959 for
five users. Advanced Server, which supports larger, multi-processor
servers, lists for $3,999 for 25 users.
</P>
<P>
   By this summer, Microsoft is also slated to ship Data Center
Server, an as-yet unpriced version for sites that run the massive
databases needed by e-commerce Web sites and Internet service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers that have used the product have been incredibly
happy, so I'm feeling that we're doing what we hoped to do,''
Ballmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer gurus at three Seattle-area companies said they were
indeed happy with Windows 2000, though each also had some
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Husting, co-founder and chief technology officer of
online real estate company eHome, said upgrading will help the
18-month-old company list and sell homes over the Internet in three
new cities a month over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the national expansion effort that brought eHome into
Seattle earlier this month, eHome upgraded all 80 of its desktop
PCs from Windows 95 or 98 and all 21 of its servers from Windows
NT, including those in Bellevue that host its Web site. It has also
upgraded all 30 of its laptops to Windows 2000 from Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   Husting said the upgrades are worthwhile in large part because
the desktop and server versions contain built-in remote-management
software that had to be purchased and used separately under earlier
versions of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   With no such add-ins, Windows 2000 will allow him to easily add
antivirus updates to every company PC from a central location
automatically when each user logs onto the network. He expects
these capabilities will likely help cut back travel time and
expense as the company's PC count expands to 1,500 by the end of
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Plug and Play, which is built into Windows 95, 98 and Windows
2000 but was missing from Windows NT, saves Husting and his staff
``many hours of aggravation'' he said. Without it, every time a
CD-ROM drive, printer, or digital camera is added to a machine, it
must be rebooted. With it, no reboot is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Curry, local-area network manager for the Seattle Mariners,
upgraded the 15 Compaq Proliant servers that power the Mariners'
accounting system, e-mail, file- and print-sharing, and sales from
stores and kiosks in the stadium. He also upgraded about 150 PCs
from Windows 95, 98 or NT starting in December, completing the task
just last week.
</P>
<P>
   Built-in administrative tools and printer support have
eliminated the need to use some third-party software, like a
port-configuration utility formerly required for printing, Curry
said. He said he especially appreciates that in the Server edition,
a built-in terminal utility lets him call in from home to monitor
machines, add or delete users, and make other changes that had
required coming onsite.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone demonstrated the terminal services, I instantly
knew we had to upgrade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Sullivan, director of information services at InfoSpace in
Redmond, said he normally wouldn't use a product that's ``just out
the door like this, but a lot of the feedback is that it's
substantially better than any previous release, and we see our
ability to respond quickly as depending on keeping abreast of the
newest technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Windows 2000 is already up and running on the 150 servers that
make up the bulk of InfoSpace's mission-critical Web server farm,
Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Providing more than 500 million page views per month, the
company is heavily dependent on its servers to supply Yellow Pages,
White Pages, stock quotes, and other information to thousands of
other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade from Windows NT went smoothly, though some changes
to scripts and home-grown applications were required, Sullivan
said. Windows 2000 allows the possibility of expanding from dual-
and four-processor machines to eight-processor machines, which
Sullivan said might be required as the company grows.
</P>
<P>
   When the occasional failure does occur, or a server just needs
to be brought down for maintenance, Windows 2000 takes half the
time to reboot as did Windows NT, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   InfoSpace has also upgraded about half its pool of roughly 75
laptops and 150 desktops to Windows 2000. Windows NT was widely
acknowledged to be far less than ideal for laptops, and Sullivan
said Windows 2000 offers much better reliability and stability.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers greater security than Windows 98, which many
people put onto laptops to avoid NT's shortcomings there. Now, a
lost or stolen laptop is useless without a valid ID and password.
</P>
<P>
   But other Seattle-area technology experts said that for now,
they'll take a pass on Microsoft's newest software.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carney, senior vice president of information systems at
Costco wholesale, said, ``We're concerned at this point (with) any
debugging that might have to be done. Some bugs are normal with any
new product.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said there is no clear cost justification for upgrading
the company's 3,000 PCs and 200 Windows-based servers at this
point.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Medina city manager Doug Schulze said ``cost is part
of the reason we're not converting now.'' A recent hardware and
software upgrade program, he said, has stretched the information
systems department's financial resources.
</P>
<P>
   Don Eagon, whose Lynnwood-based Accunet Computer Services
provides network management services to Medina, added, ``Windows 98
is a great operating system, with all the glitches worked out. Why
spend money when you don't have to, especially when it's glitchy?''
</P>
<P>
   Though the launch of Windows 2000 was announced several months
ago, it caused Microsoft stock to climb $2, to $99.63. Shares
continued to trend up in after-hours trading, touching $100.75.
</P>
<P>
   Wire service material is included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
