 CHARLESTON, S.C.: a favor.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Bush, his surrogates and interest groups have also tried to
appeal to conservatives in the party. He has steadfastly refused to
nudge South Carolinians in any direction in their debate over the
Confederate battle flag at the state house. And two weeks ago, he
spoke to students at Bob Jones University, a conservative Christian
school that bans interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at the news conference whether voters might reach the
conclusion that he was not an ardent foe of racial intolerance, the
governor grew tense and visibly angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you judge my heart based upon giving a speech at a
university,'' he admonished reporters. Then noted that former
Presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush, his father, had also
visited the university.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was not sure whether he had been informed about the
dating policy before he spoke at the school, but insisted he did
not regret his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also aware of the power of religious conservatives,
and his aides tried to deflect accusations from Bush supporters
that McCain was not reliable on abortion and other social issues.
</P>
<P>
   But there was at least one sign on Wednesday night that Bauer's
support would not fully insulate McCain from the religious right.
James C. Dobson, a prominent Christian conservative who has been
close to Bauer over the years, released a statement that took issue
with the endorsement and expressed harsh criticism of McCain over
his votes to confirm what Dobson called ``pro-abortion'' Supreme
Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   Dobson, who has not endorsed anyone in the race, added: ``McCain
has accepted huge contributions from the gambling industry and
apparently is comfortable with the proliferation of gambling in
American society. He has also accepted large contributions from
producers of alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bauer seemed aware that his endorsement of
McCain would not be greeted with great enthusiasm by allies in the
religious right. At one point, he said in a phone call to his
friend William Kristol, the editor of The Weekly Standard, ``Did I
mention to you if this doesn't work out, my family and I will be
living in your house?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain hailed Bauer throughout the day as a man of courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, the best thing and smartest thing for Gary Bauer
to do in this campaign was stay out of it,'' he told the audience
in the outdoor Wyche Pavilion here. ``Now you tell me,'' Bauer
murmured.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Johnson, a senior official of the National Right to Life
Committee, said on Thursday he did not think the endorsement would
change the minds of many conservative voters. ``Gary Bauer was not
attracting many pro-life voters in his own right,'' Johnson said,
``and we don't think he's going to be able to rehabilitate John
McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain began his morning at a breakfast at a Spartanburg VFW
post and later attended two rallies with rock music and confetti
shot into the air.
</P>
<P>
   One of the events at times resembled a revival meeting, as an
announcer called out the names of voters who had become recent
converts to McCain. As music boomed, the senator's wife Cindy
danced on an outdoor stage. Voters thrust copies of McCain's
autobiography at him to sign.
</P>
<P>
   One of the voters gazing up at McCain from the front of the
crowd was Diane Underwood, a nurse who had welcomed him and other
prisoners of war home from Vietnam at Clark Air Force base in the
Phillipines in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   She said she remembered how the returning prisoners of war asked
for things they craved, like a favorite food. McCain, she recalled,
``wanted books and newspapers and magazines, so that he could see
what went on while he was in captivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator's time as a prisoner also came up on the bus
Thursday afternoon when reporters asked him about an article in The
Nation magazine reporting that he had referred to his Vietnamese
captors as ``gooks'' while on his campaign bus in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll call right now my interrogator that tortured me and my
friends a gook,'' said McCain who was a prisoner for
five-and-a-half years. ``You can quote me.''
</P>
<P>
   He called his guards ``cruel and sadistic people'' and said ``I
will continue to refer to them in language that might offend some
people here, because of their beating and killing and torture of my
friends. I hated the gooks and I will hate them as long as I
live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
