<SLUG> BC-AOL-STOCK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMAL RESEARCH PREPARED ON AOL-TIME WARNER DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts spend a lot of time talking about how
companies in industries from retailing to telecommunications had
better prepare for the changes the Internet will bring in the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   But they are having a hard time living up to their own rhetoric
when it comes to the pending merger of America Online with Time
Warner Inc. The $120 billion deal, which marks the biggest
combination ever of a major Internet company with a traditional
company, has gone largely uncovered by analysts at major securities
firms like Merrill Lynch and Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost six weeks after AOL and Time Warner announced their
combination, the major firms have failed to produce a comprehensive
look at the combined company's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the merger say the paucity of research is at least
part of the reason America Online's stock has lost nearly a third
of its value since the combination was announced on Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   While skeptical investors play down the usefulness of research
by industry analysts, strong research provides both support for a
company's stock and a set of benchmarks against its performance can
be judged. The issue is especially important for the combined AOL
Time Warner, which will have no obvious peers and which will be a
very complex company.
</P>
<P>
   Neither AOL nor Time Warner would discuss the issue publicly,
presumably for fear of alienating the analysts who follow them. But
privately, sources close to the companies said that the lack of
research is frustrating. ``Right now, Wall Street is not moving at
Internet speed,'' a person close to the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   John Schreiber, who follows Time Warner for Janus Capital, the
Denver-based mutual fund company that is Time Warner's largest
institutional shareholder, was less reticent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a situation where you have very established
traditional media analysts, and very established new media
analysts,'' he said. ``Now, all of a sudden, you put these two
companies together, and it becomes a contest to see who has the
most clout within the firm. It's unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   At Merrill Lynch, Jessica Reif said she plans to cover the
combined AOL Time Warner jointly with Henry Blodget, the Internet
analyst. She declined to comment on when she plans to release
research on the combination.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter said the firm could
not offer research on the deal because it had advised Time Warner
on the merger and was in a quiet period. Goldman, Sachs did not
return phone calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner and AOL have traditionally been valued very
differently. Analysts generally value Time Warner, like most other
entertainment companies, based on its cash flow. (Cash flow
includes earnings before taxes, interest charges and some noncash
expenses.)
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say they like the measure because it enables them to
compare the performance of companies with different levels of debt
and amortization charges. Cynics note that using cash flow makes
companies with weak earnings and relatively high prices look less
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, analysts who follow AOL, which is extremely expensive
by any traditional valuation, prefer to value it based on
``metrics'' such as subscriber growth. And while analysts can
compare the performance and valuation of Time Warner with that of
other entertainment companies relatively easily, AOL essentially
stands alone in its business model, making a valuation more an art
than a science.
</P>
<P>
   Meshing those world views has proved to be a slow process, said
Jeffrey Logsdon, managing director of the Seidler Companies, a
regional invesment bank in Los Angeles. ``Most of the media
analysts do not want to become Internet analysts,'' Logsdon said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolzien, a stock analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein who is one
of the few people to cover both companies, agreed. ``There's a real
difficult time with the Street by and large coming to grips with
the combination,'' Wolzien said. ``In a lot of the houses, you just
don't even know who's going to cover the combined company.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, neither AOL nor Time Warner is easy to
understand at first glance, Wolzien said. AOL gets revenue from
subscriptions, advertising and Internet commerce, and is rapidly
expanding internationally. Time Warner has five major divisions,
each with its own business cycle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
