<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-AVALANCHES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR OF THE AVALANCHE IN ALASKA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIRDWOOD, Alaska _ One moment all was quiet, and the Chugach
Range stood out in the snowcapped splendor of a timeless winter
scene. The next, recalled Keith Burton, a track-repair man for the
Alaska Railroad, ``it was like a huge billowy cloud just jumped
right off the mountains and started rolling straight down toward
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The few seconds that Burton had to grab his radio and shout
``Avalanche!'' were not enough for another worker, Kerry Brookman,
who was operating a bulldozer to clear snow from the tracks that
run south from Anchorage along the Turnagain Arm, a waterway that
flows toward the Kenai Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The moving wall of snow slammed straight into the 38,000-pound
bulldozer, sweeping man and machine nearly 200 yards, out onto the
frozen mud flats of the Arm. The crumpled dozer landed upside down,
its tracks in the air, and although his frantic co-workers managed
to find Brookman still conscious _ ``I'm OK, I'll be all right,''
he said _ he died of internal trauma soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of at least 33 major avalanches that have struck
south-central Alaska in recent weeks, a cycle of fury and danger
that, even by the standards of a state where awesome natural power
is continually on display, has been extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   The massive slides, two of which have been a mile wide, are a
product of an unusual weather pattern of thawing and freezing that
created virtual shelves of ice on mountaintops earlier this winter.
By late January, extremely heavy snowfalls were accumulating on
those glacial shelves, creating conditions for what one state
expert describes as ``hundred-year avalanches.''
</P>
<P>
   Two have proved deadly _ the one that killed Brookman, 53, on
Feb. 1 and one on Jan. 26 that struck just outside the town of
Cordova on Prince William Sound, flattening several homes and
warehouses and killing Martha Quales, 63.
</P>
<P>
   Several others have played havoc, blocking the Seward Highway,
the link between Anchorage and all the towns on the Kenai
Peninsula, for five days earlier this month and cutting off
electricity to thousands of the peninsula's residents.
</P>
<P>
   Still other slides, far from much human habitation, have simply
been spectacular to behold, in either their occurrence or their
aftermath, the power unleashed akin to that of a volcano.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like nothing I've ever seen, short of visiting Mount St.
Helens,'' Dan Amyot, a ranger at Chugach State Park, said of an
early February avalanche near Eklutna Lake, north of Anchorage,
that snapped thousands of two-foot-thick aspens and cottonwoods and
created a mile-long field of debris near the base of 7,500-foot
Bold Peak. ``It's a whole forest laid down like toothpicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tony Knowles has declared the region a disaster area and
sought federal help. Property damage caused by the avalanches has
been estimated at more than $16 million so far, said Phil Oates,
adjutant general of the Alaska National Guard. And nervous state
officials say that depending on the weather over the next several
weeks, the problem could actually get worse as spring approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that we're not done yet,'' said John Horn, regional
director of the Alaska Department of Transportation. ``There are a
lot of slopes that haven't released any snow yet, and when the warm
spring sun hits, we're concerned there could be more problems.
There's just a whole lot of snow up there in the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   While some avalanches are predictable _ conditions in any number
of locations are frequently just right for them _ many others
strike without warning, quickly reaching speeds of 125 miles an
hour or more and leaving debris fields 200 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone here recognizes the continuing danger, especially on
the Seward Highway. The road runs for miles just beneath the
3,000-foot-high faces of several mountains in the Chugach Range,
which are all building up huge piles of snow and can, without
warning, shed them down their steep slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Even in less perilous times, the Seward Highway is among the
most avalanche-prone travel routes anywhere in the nation. It is so
susceptible to slides that the state sometimes tries, as at a
number of other locations, to let them loose before nature does,
with howitzers and with explosives that crews drop from planes and
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called avalanche control, which is a little presumptuous,
of course,'' said Bill Glude, a consultant to the state who is
director of the Southeast Alaska Avalanche Center. ``It's really an
attempt at mitigation. The bombs, if you drop them in the right
spot, provide enough of a shock load to trigger an avalanche.''
</P>
<P>
   Glude has been crisscrossing south-central Alaska in recent
weeks, helping state officials figure out where and when to set off
the explosives. Highways and railroad tracks are closed to traffic
when such work is done. Then the resulting snow and debris are
cleared, and the transportation corridors reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such work can stave off more snowy turmoil remains to be
seen. There is clearly a huge amount of snow around here, both up
in the mountains and even down below. Here in Girdwood, the plowed
snow rises in some places to the level of the street signs, and
walking through town can feel a bit like threading through a maze.
</P>
<P>
   After rains and a thawing period followed by the freeze, huge
amounts of snow started falling in January. Nearby Anchorage, which
normally gets about 9 inches of snow in January, recorded 34
inches, according to the National Weather Service. And even more
fell here in Girdwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to snow, but this was just incredible,'' said Todd
Hiibner, manager of World Cup, a store here that sells skiing
equipment. ``Even before the avalanches came, they had to close
down the Alyeska Ski Resort for a while. There was literally just
too much snow. You couldn't ski in it; you'd just sink in it to
your waist if you tried.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was so much snow one morning that Bob Mucha, owner of
Chugach Express, which operates dog-sled tours here in town, had to
dig his 40 Alaskan huskies out of their doghouses.
</P>
<P>
   Climate experts here can trace the unusual cycle to storms in
the Pacific but cannot say at this point whether it is related to
larger climatic factors like global warming. There is wide
agreement, though, that in the words of Mike Maillet, a maintenance
foreman for the Alaska Railroad, ``It's just been a strange year,
the thaws, the cold, then lots of snow.''
</P>
<P>
   And while avalanches kill people who venture into remote areas
nearly every year _ there were 11 such deaths across Alaska last
year, most involving snowmobilers _ the slides this year are
unusual for killing people in inhabited areas. In Cordova, Mayor Ed
Zeine said recently that the city would consider rezoning the area
where Quales was killed, to prevent new building there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were houses completely blown to smithereens, cars tipped
over, mature trees ripped out and thrown out onto the lake,'' Glude
said of the Cordova slide. ``It was really quite amazing. It was a
very graphic demonstration of the power of nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
