u a BC-NY-HOSPITAL-DEATH-NYT     02-17 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSPITAL-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL IS TOLD NEUROSURGEON CAN'T OPERATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The death of a patient has prompted the state to
order Staten Island University Hospital to stop its chief of
neurosurgery from treating other patients, five years after the
same doctor was fired from another hospital for operating on the
wrong side of a patient's brain, a Health Department spokeswoman
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinarily strongly worded letter to the hospital's
chief executive, the deputy health commissioner, Dennis P. Whalen,
said the state had received information of a ``potentially grave
risk to patients.'' He said there was ``an immediate and serious
threat to the health of any person subjected to surgery'' performed
by the doctor, Ehud Arbit, and directed the hospital to force him
to stop practicing medicine there, pending the outcome of its
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials would not comment Thursday night. State
officials would not specify the nature or extent of the
investigation at the hospital. A state Health Department
spokeswoman, Kristine Smith, said a patient, whom she would not
identify, died following brain surgery performed by Arbit earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995 case, at Memorial-Sloan Kettering Cancer Center in
New York, Arbit's patient survived.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit did not return calls to his office about the state's new
action. A woman who answered the phone there said, ``This all has
nothing to do with Dr. Arbit.''
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Barbara Ryan, said that she could not comment on the
state's actions. ``The cases under review are subject to patient
confidentiality laws,'' Ryan said. ``There are not any allegations
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``There is no cause for concern for any of the care
or treatment that this doctor has rendered.''
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department last investigated Arbit beginning in 1995,
when he was chief of neurosurgery at Memorial-Sloan Kettering. He
mistakenly operated on the healthy right side of the brain of
Rajeswari Ayyappan, the mother of a famous Indian film star,
Sridevi Ayyappan, instead of the left side, where a cancerous tumor
was situated, health officials said. The error left the patient
with little memory and unable to recognize family members.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department rebuked the hospital and fined it $16,000,
the maximum amount permitted, for eight violations of regulations
on health care that it said contributed to the error. The state
decided that Arbit's actions warranted a one-year probation, which
allowed him to continue practicing medicine.
</P>
<P>
   It is common for doctors who have been dismissed from one
hospital, even when they have been disciplined by the state as
well, to gain work at other health care centers. Even in cases
where doctors lose their medical licenses, they often move to other
states and find work.
</P>
<P>
   After the Sloan Kettering case, Arbit became the chief of
neurosurgery at the Staten Island hospital. Contacted several times
this week, the hospital spokeswoman, Arleen Ryback, said she knew
of no inquiry into Arbit or the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The state's letter to Staten Island University Hospital, dated
Tuesday, is highly unusual both in its language and its action. It
is likely a precursor to further departmental measures against the
doctor and possibly the hospital. In rare cases, the department
seeks to suspend doctors' licenses temporarily or gets them to stop
practicing medicine while it completes its investigation, if its
officials believe that a doctor is a danger to patients.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, state officials moved quickly as a protective
measure, the department spokeswoman, Smith, said. ``We recently
received credible information that would lead us to believe that
patients undergoing surgery by Dr. Arbit face potential risk,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
