<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOYS-CEO-SUIT-NYT &LR;      02-17 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-CEO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.) 
</HEADLINE>
   F.A.O. SCHWARZ SUES CHIEF FOR MOVE TO TOYS `R' Us  
 (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what amounts to a grown-up toy war, F.A.O. Schwarz is suing
John Eyler, its former chairman and chief executive, for jumping to
the rival Toys ``R'' Us last month. The complaint says Eyler
violated the terms of his employment contract, which required him
to provide a year's notice before any departure and barred him from
working for a competitor for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed on Jan. 26 in state Supreme Court in Manhattan
by Schwarz and its parent company, Vendex KBB of the Netherlands,
also faults Eyler for walking away with $2.4 million that was paid,
in essence, to keep him around.
</P>
<P>
   Eyler, 52, who became the top executive of Schwarz in 1992, was
traveling Thursday and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz is seeking a preliminary injunction to prevent Eyler
from working at Toys ``R'' Us. A hearing has been scheduled on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A Toys ``R'' Us spokeswoman denied wrongdoing by the company and
on behalf of Eyler. ``We firmly believe the case has no merit
whatsoever, and we will, of course, vigorously defend the matter,''
the spokeswoman, Rebecca Caruso said. Janis Meyer, a lawyer with
Dewey Ballantine, which is representing Schwarz and Vendex, said
her clients declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the interesting details in the court papers is that Toys
``R'' Us and Schwarz held merger talks last year. The suit names
Toys ``R'' Us, of Paramus, N.J., as a co-defendant and says it
violated an agreement reached last June not to solicit or hire any
Schwarz officers or senior employees for two years.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Toys ``R'' Us was negotiating a possible purchase
of the chain or an Internet partnership. Though no deal resulted,
Toys ``R'' Us agreed not to court Schwarz employees for two years,
according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   While the toy sellers engage in their own wrestling over how far
an employment contract can go, companies of all types are using
``noncompete'' and other restrictive employment contracts. And
increasingly, in a vigorous economy and a tight labor market,
companies are taking a tough stance on these agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume there might be more impetus, as a practical matter,
to keep people on the reservation if they are harder to replace,''
said Don Collins, a New York University Law School professor. ``I
don't think that matters to the court much.''
</P>
<P>
   For some companies, the goal is to send a message to executives
considering jumping ship. Other employers are seeking to prevent
key executives' expertise benefiting a competitor as long as
possible. ``The theory of it is to starve you into submission,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   The enforcement of such contracts varies greatly by state, with
spurned companies finding their cases stronger if they can show
harm or the loss of confidential company information.
</P>
<P>
   In the toy case, Schwarz contends that Eyler's move gives Toys
``R'' Us an unfair competitive edge because he departed with
knowledge of trade secrets and other confidential information.
</P>
<P>
   The big payment that Eyler received in January was intended as a
``golden parachute,'' should he leave after a change of control at
Schwarz. Vendex merged with the toy seller's former owner in
November 1998. Under his contract, he was entitled to $2.4 million
if he left within 12 to 18 months of that change, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the potentially rich severance package, Eyler
expressed ``serious concern'' to Vendex that he would have no
choice but to leave to collect it, according to the court filing.
Eager to keep him, the company agreed to give him the money by the
end of 1999 to negotiate a new employment contract.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us hired Eyler to help revive its business after five
months without a chief executive. The company said at the time that
it had hired Eyler for his ``passion and energy for the toy
business'' as well as his experience in electronic commerce and
catalog businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
