<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GOODWILL-DOWNHILL18-C     02-17 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-DOWNHILL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    French 1st, U.S. 2nd in downhill
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Howling winds that whipped up the fresh snow
at the top of Whiteface Mountain delayed the first of two Winter
Goodwill Games downhill races for 4 1/2 hours Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When the winds died down, a Frenchman with a name as white as
snow surprised the favored Austrians _ as well as himself.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Blanc, whose best finish this World Cup season was a tie
for 17th, schussed out of 17th position to win the race with a time
of 1 minute, 49.84 seconds. Blanc, who grew up in the 1968 Olympic
city of Grenoble, won the $20,000 first prize, the most lucrative
in the Goodwill Games' $650,000 purse.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Puckett of Boulder, Colo., who started 20th among
the 23 racers, was second in 1:49.96, bumping Canadian Kevin Wert
(1:50.32) to third. The top Austrian, 1998 Olympic bronze medalist
Hannes Trinkl, was fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Another downhill _ with the same skiers, although some will try
different equipment and tactics _ is scheduled for this morning.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Thursday's race started, the temperature was about 5
degrees at the starthouse and shadows cast part of the course in
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never would have thought in 100 years we would have had a
race,'' said Canadian Ed Podivinsky, who placed sixth. ``You'd be
up on the chairlift and wouldn't be able to see the ground. The
people who worked on the course were incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake Placid organizers were eager to show off a course that has
changed since the 1980 Olympics, when Austrians went 1-2 in the
downhill. They hope to return the venue to the World Cup circuit,
which has no sites in eastern North America.
</P>
<P>
   The Whiteface Mountain run calls for very technical turning at
the top, but favors gliders at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a surprise to win on this course, as I am so light and
do not normally do well in the flats,'' said the 176-pounf Blanc.
``My speed in this race came at the top of the course where it was
steep.''
</P>
<P>
   Wert, who weighs in at a solid 230 pounds, had been the early
leader after gaining ground at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the law of gravity, bigger things fall faster, you
know?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wert's smile disappeared when Blanc's time flashed on the
scoreboard, and he left the finish area, whistling joylessly, after
Puckett cruised in.
</P>
<P>
   The top 15 ranked skiers get to pick their numbers, but Puckett,
who is 16th, had to take what was left. By the time it was his
turn, he had to deal with flat light and deep shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in the starting gate and it was dark all the way down,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Everything brightened when it was time to glide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how fast my skis were on the flat,'' said
Puckett. ``I couldn't believe it. I was lucky to hang on to them.
They really wanted to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Puckett won $12,500. ``It's spent already. I have school
loans,'' said the Dartmouth graduate.
</P>
<P>
   He was thrilled to get some payback against all five Austrians
who came. Hermann Maier, the most famous Austrian downhiller, chose
to stay in Europe and compete in a World Cup, but Werner Franz (who
was seventh) and Fritz Strobl (11th) tied for first in a Super G
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of them have won World Cups this year, so it feels
pretty good to beat them,'' said Puckett. ``At least it tells me I
just have to keep doing what I'm doing and I'll be there someday.''
</P>
<P>
   And he still has today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
