<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-HALFPIPE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inspired snowboarder
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Tricia Byrnes wouldn't be a snowboarder if
not for her brother Doug.
</P>
<P>
   ``All his friends were snowboarders and I wanted to be cool and
mingle with the dudes,'' the New Canaan, Conn., native said
Thursday after winning the Winter Goodwill Games women's halfpipe
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Doug died suddenly last summer at age 27 from a asthma attack,
sending Tricia's world into a backward slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm OK with it, then all of a sudden, I go, `I can't
get my head together,''' said Byrnes, 25, who was the 1999 FIS
World Cup champion, but has struggled this season. ``It's just
rough. You go through phases of healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrnes said she feels blessed that despite a busy travel
schedule, she was in town and visited Doug the evening before he
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just weird, you can't curse the ground or anything
because he only got 27 years,'' she said. ``I feel really lucky to
have had him around my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrnes won seven World Cups last winter and is now on her way to
Japan. She threw down some 540s in her two halfpipe runs Thursday,
totaling 41.80 points on her first attempt to defeat teammate Kelly
Clark, who scored 41.50 on her second.
</P>
<P>
   Byrnes, who won $5,400, doesn't consider herself an innovator.
She leaves that to the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our tricks are from skatebording,'' Byrnes said, ``and the
men are so much bigger. They can land on their head, and they're
like `Oh, OK.' Girls are like, `Ow, my pinkie!' But I try.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
