<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: IRA BLAMES BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   In a statement in the Dublin weekly paper Republican News, the
Irish Republican Army blamed Britain for the suspension of the new
Belfast government and said the act should be immediately
rescinded, saying it was up to British officials to ``repair the
damage they caused.'' The statement made no mention of the IRA's
refusal to start disarming, the reason cited for the shutdown of
the home-rule administration.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: MILOSEVIC CONGRESS
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic's governing Socialist Party opened
a party congress in Belgrade under the slogan of ``Reconstruction,
development, reforms.'' They heard Milosevic praise the party for
10 years of success ``in a struggle for survival, freedom and
independence.'' Other officials attacked opposition-party rule of
Belgrade and other cities, in preparation for local elections due
this year.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: WARNING ON ARMENIA
</P>
<P>
   The government urged the French Senate not to approve a bill
scheduled to be discussed on Tuesday that would recognize the
massacres of Armenians in the early 20th century as genocide.
Armenians say as many as 1.3 million of them were killed by Ottoman
forces. Turks say the figure was far smaller, and that many Turks
died in fighting as Russian-backed Armenians sought to seize part
of the collapsing Ottoman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: PRI KEEPS ITS COLORS
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that cannot be appealed, the highest elections
court ruled that the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party,
known as the PRI, can continue to use the colors of the Mexican
flag in its logo and on ballots. Opposition parties had sued to
force the PRI to give up the national red, green and white colors,
a practice left over from the decades when the PRI was the only
substantial party in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: MAHATHIR READY
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said he is ready, if ordered to
do so, to testify at the sexual misconduct trial of his former
deputy and chief antagonist, Anwar Ibrahim. The judge said he would
decide Friday whether to call the prime minister, as the defense
has demanded.
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: ANNAN VISITS
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional and symbolic gesture, Secretary-General Kofi
Annan of the United Nations visited East Timor, five and a half
months after the territory voted for independence from Indonesia in
a United Nations-sponsored referendum. The United Nations runs an
interim administration for the territory while it struggles to
recover from a wave of violence that devastated it after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF PROSECUTION ENDING
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution said it planned to finish its hijacking and
attempted murder case Friday against the deposed prime minister,
Nawaz Sharif, but Sharif's lawyers said they might ask the court
for a week's postponement to prepare their case, delaying the
hearing of statements from the seven accused in the case.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN: CANADA PRAISED
</P>
<P>
   Sudan praised Canada for not imposing sanctions on a Canadian
oil company with a major role in Sudan's fledgling petroleum
industry. A report found that the oil industry was making Sudan's
civil war worse by providing money for arms to the government. The
war with rebel groups from the south has split the nation for more
than 16 years. The government said the report proved ``Sudan is a
safe place for investment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
