<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0365 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-2NDTAKE-     02-17 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MOSCOW: sometimes disappear.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider this tangle of accounts and relationships. In the
documents filed in U.S. District Court Wednesday in Manhattan, both
MDM and Sobinbank were mentioned as participants in wire transfers
to the Benex and BECS accounts. And the same documents say that
funds transferred to Benex and BECS between February 1996 and the
fall of that year went through an account at the Bank of New York
held by MDM, the Russian initials for Moscow Business World bank.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, Edwards allegedly opened an account for
Sobinbank which was later substituted by an account for DKB, or in
English, Deposit Clearing Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Two year later, money from Flamingo went to yet another account
at the bank set up by Edwards and her husband, in the name of
Lowland, via Sobinbank of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, acting on a tip from federal investigators in the
Bank of New York scandal, Russian agents swooped down on Flamingo
and scooped up $430,000 and 3.3 million rubles in loose cash lying
around its offices, unaccounted for and otherwise undocumented.
Russia's prosecutors have since brought criminal charges against
Flamingo for ``illegal banking activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the raid on Flamingo, Moscow city police launched an
investigation at Sobinbank headquarters in October, during which
they opened up safety deposit boxes held in the bank vaults. In one
box, held by a deputy director of an institute connected to the
Russian space program, they found $1.6 million in cash, and 6 kilos
of gold ingots. No charges have been brought against Sobinbank.
</P>
<P>
   Audits of SBS-Agro, a bank that is now virtually bankrupt, by
Arthur Andersen in the late 1990s, described Sobinbank as a
``subsidiary'' of SBS-Agro, which the auditors found also owned 20
percent of the shares in Flamingo.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Sobinbank also became partly owned by Manezh,
developers of Manezhnaya Ploshchad, the vast and ambitious
underground shopping mall at the foot of the Kremlin that was a pet
project of Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, and one of his favorite
businessmen, Umar Dzhabrailov. Other shareholders include Lukoil, a
major Russian oil company; Energia, the company that builds space
craft; and two other smaller banks.
</P>
<P>
   Later, both MDM, which was regarded as a well run institution,
and Sobinbank were to share the same patron _ Alexander Mamut, a
soft spoken young lawyer and banker who is closely tied to the
Family, the nickname given to an inner circle of advisers that
surrounded former Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his daughter,
Tatyana Dyachenko.
</P>
<P>
   Mamut, who had his own bank known as KOPF, became a member of
the Sobinbank board of directors in 1997, where he remained until
he became chairman of the MDM board last year. In each case, he
appears to have helped bring significant clients, including
Sibneft; Almazy Rossii-Sakha, Russia's largest diamond company; and
Energia, the space program company.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that the scheme survived because it had the benefit
of powerful political patrons in Moscow. But the Russian banker
familiar with scheme said that the Benex accounts' good reputation
also came from the protection it seemed to enjoy at the Bank of New
York, which had a significant business in Moscow. ``They
established a niche,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed last fall, Sobinbank president Alexander Zanadvorov
insisted he had never met either Edwards or Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, Benex and BECS worked actively with
Russian banks and Russian companies,'' he said. ``If anyone wanted
to, they could drag in a lot of banks and companies into this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
