<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenspan Hints That Fed Will Increase Rates More
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, said the
economy showed few signs of slowing despite four interest rate
increases in eight months, and he warned in unusually direct terms
that the central bank would probably raise rates further to avert
inflation. In testimony to the House Banking Committee, he also set
what amounted to a speed limit for Wall Street, saying that
wringing the risk of inflation out of the economy would require
that stock and other asset prices rise no faster than household
incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Daft Heads Coke Ahead of Schedule
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Daft became chairman and chief executive of Coca-Cola as
M. Douglas Ivester moved up his retirement date. Ivester said in
December that he would retire after two years in the company's top
job, but agreed at the time to remain until April to smooth the
management transition. Daft quickly took charge, eliminating the
need for Ivester to remain.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Breaks Record as Dow Falls
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks powered the Nasdaq composite index to a new
record, as investors shrugged off the ever-more-likely prospect of
additional interest rate increases this spring. The Nasdaq jumped
121.27 points, or 2.74 percent, to 4,548.92. The Dow Jones
industrial average lost 46.84 points, to 10,514.57, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose fractionally, to 1,388.26.
</P>
<P>
   Accounting Firm to Separate Units
</P>
<P>
   The accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers, which audits and
advises many of the world's biggest corporations, announced that it
plans to separate its auditing and consulting businesses into at
least two free-standing organizations.
</P>
<P>
   GE Plans Energy Announcement
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department and General Electric will announce a
breakthrough in natural-gas-powered generating plants Friday that
will result in the production of electricity using 5 percent less
fuel than current technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for Research on AOL Deal
</P>
<P>
   Almost six weeks after America Online and Time Warner announced
their combination, the major securities firms have failed to
produce a comprehensive look at the combined company's prospects.
Supporters of the merger say the paucity of research is at least
part of the reason America Online's stock has lost nearly a third
of its value since the combination was announced on Jan. 10,
although it was up slightly yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Germany Delays a Tax Measure
</P>
<P>
   A tax proposal aimed at dismantling the cross-shareholdings of
corporate Germany will become effective one year later than
originally planned, the government said, a move that sent down
stock prices of German banks and insurance companies. But
economists and political experts said the proposal did not appear
to be in any fundamental danger.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman of a Czech Bank Resigns
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Czech Republic's Komercni Banka has resigned
during an investigation into a suspected fraud at the ailing
state-controlled bank.
</P>
<P>
   Sears to Drop Benetton Apparel
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck said it would stop sales of Benetton USA apparel
and remove the products from its stores because of objections to a
Benetton advertising campaign called ``We, on Death Row'' that
features interviews with convicted killers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
