<HEADER>
A0372 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN     02-17 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JOCKEY GREAT TO EMULATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Corey Nakatani says his fast start at Santa
Anita was inspired by Laffit Pincay's history-making performance at
Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (watching Pincay) kind of got the spark going for me
again,'' Nakatani said this week at Santa Anita, where he led the
jockeys with 45 victories through Wednesday's races.
</P>
<P>
   That's not only flattering to Pincay. It says good things about
Nakatani as well.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the younger jockey appeared to be inspired by
darker forces. In the decade since he was the nation's richest
apprentice rider in 1989, the former high school wrestler from
Covina earned a reputation as a hothead without the proper
reverence for his sport.
</P>
<P>
   He was fined for head-butting one rival jockey after a race,
suspended for shoving another off his mount on the gallop-out,
fined and suspended for whipping a horse in apparent frustration on
the gallop-back.
</P>
<P>
   He was battling pressures that went beyond a jockey's typical
year-round mental and physical strains. In a matter of months in
1996-97, he lost a cousin to cancer, a sister to murder and his
father to a heart attack. But whatever sympathy those tragedies won
him, Nakatani couldn't shake the image of an immature young man
whose athletic gifts came too easily. In a sport that demands
absolute dedication, he seemed too eager to get to the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Every rider needs an emotional boost now and then. For Nakatani,
who will turn 30 in October, it came in December, courtesy of the
amazing Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 10, Pincay, at age 52, rode his 8,834th winner to break
Bill Shoemaker's career record. Pincay went on to lead the
Hollywood Park jockeys and become the oldest rider to win a title
at a major North American track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so gratifying to see him reach a goal that a lot of
people said he wasn't going to reach,'' Nakatani, who shares agent
Bob Meldahl with Pincay, said in the Santa Anita jockeys' lunch
room.'' ``People like yourself wrote articles that he'd have to go
to Bay Meadows (to break the record).
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) he's not a quitter. He's got more desire and will than
anybody I've ever met. I've never seen anybody who does the things
he does just to ride races. I look at him every day and see how he
takes care of himself and how he presents himself. He's an
unbelievable person.''
</P>
<P>
   During Pincay's record run, Nakatani found out more about the
Panamanian's 35-year career than he'd learned by riding next to him
for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read all about his accomplishments and it got the fire in me
going again,'' Nakatani said. ``I've been out here (exercising
horses) every morning at 5:30, rain or shine. People say to me,
`What are you doing out here?' I just say, `I'm hungry. I want to
do it again. I want to be on top. I want to do the things that
Laffit accomplished.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nakatani said watching the dignified way Pincay carried himself
as he neared the record and interview and autograph requests
increased, and seeing how the other Hall of Famers on the Southern
California circuit behave, has been an inspiration too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the way people handle themselves, the (Chris)
McCarrons, the Pincays, and the respect they get,'' Nakatani said.
``I go to restaurants with them and see the desire they have just
by the way they eat.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't eat much.
</P>
<P>
   Now Nakatani has the old hunger back, too.
</P>
<P>
   At Hollywood Park, he won with a huge 26 percent of his mounts
but didn't ride enough races to contend for the title. He finished
third behind Pincay and Pat Valenzuela. At Santa Anita, his
percentage is again around 25 and he's among the busiest riders. He
has opened a 15-win lead over Kent Desormeaux as the meet nears its
midpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Nakatani holds an early lead in purses with more
than $2.1 million, nearly $900,000 more than second-place Alex
Solis.
</P>
<P>
   If he goes on to win the Santa Anita title, it will be his first
at any track since 1996. And it will complete a rebound from the
1998-99 Santa Anita meet, during which he finished seventh with
just 43 wins.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Nakatani was riding under contract to The
Thoroughbred Corp., giving him security but costing him mounts with
other barns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm focused, I'm back on track,'' he said this week. ``And I'm
looking forward to riding more horses for more people.''
</P>
<P>
   And in more places. Nakatani will be out of town this weekend to
ride 3-year-olds Greenwood Lake for trainer Nick Zito in Saturday's
Fountain of Youth at Gulfstream Park in Florida and Exchange Rate
for D. Wayne Lukas in Sunday's Risen Star at the Fair Grounds in
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be back at Santa Anita on the holiday Monday to ride The
Fly in the San Luis Obispo Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Future is here: Very early ``morning line'' odds for the May 6
Kentucky Derby show the balance of power is in California. D. Wayne
Lukas-trained filly Surfside and the Neil Drysdale-trained War
Chant are 8-1 co-favorites, with Captain Steve and The Deputy 10-1,
and 2-year-old champion Anees one of several horses at 15-1.
</P>
<P>
   These are the projected odds on Churchill Downs' first Derby
Future Wager pool, which opened Thursday and closes Sunday
afternoon. Later pools will be open March 9-12 and April 13-16.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't be able to place bets from California because
state law prohibits tracks here from taking bets on events more
than seven days in advance. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Santa Anita leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Corey Nakatani,
45 wins; Kent Desormeaux, 30; David Flores and Alex Solis, 27;
Laffit Pincay, 24; Victor Espinoza, 21. Trainers: Bob Baffert, 19;
Bobby Frankel, 18; Ron Ellis and Bill Spawr, 10; Richard Mandella
and Ron McAnally, 9.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay watch: Winning the $50,000 Glendale Handicap at Turf
Paradise aboard Perfectly Clear last Saturday gave Laffit Pincay a
victory on 10 straight racing days. The streak ended with an
0-for-3 performance Sunday at Santa Anita, but Pincay bounced back
with two wins Wednesday, raising his career-record total to 8,869.
</P>
<P>
   On the stakes schedule: At Santa Anita: Saturday, $100,000 Boo
La Boo Stakes, 3-year-old fillies bred in California, 6 furlongs,
and $75,000 San Marino Handicap, 4-year-olds and up, 1 miles on
turf; Sunday, $125,000 Las Flores Handicap, fillies and mares 4 and
up, 6 furlongs; Monday, $200,000 San Luis Obispo Handicap,
4-year-olds and up, 1 miles on turf. At Bay Meadows: Saturday,
$100,000 Ken Maddy Sprint, Cal-bred 4-year-olds and up, 6 furlongs.
At Gulfstream Park: Saturday, $200,000 Fountain of Youth,
3-year-olds, 1 1/16 miles; Sunday, $100,000 Davona Dale, 3-year-old
fillies, 1 mile 70 yards. At Fair Grounds: Sunday, $125,000 Risen
Star, 3-year-olds, 1 1/16 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Mileposts: Real Quiet, the 1998 Kentucky Derby and Preakness
winner, who hadn't raced since winning the 1999 Hollywood Gold Cup,
was officially retired this week. The 5-year-old will stand at the
Vinery in Kentucky for a stud fee of $25,000 a foal. Real Quiet
earned $3.2 million by recording six wins (five in Grade I stakes),
five seconds and six thirds in 20 starts.... Also retired, with a
minor injury: Soaring Softly, the 1999 female turf champion....
Genuine Risk, the second filly to win the Kentucky Derby (1980) but
a flop as a broodmare, has been pensioned to owners Bert and Diana
Firestone's Virginia farm. She's 23 and has been barren the past
three years. She didn't produced a foal until 1993 and none of her
offspring has made it to the racetrack.... Santa Maria Handicap
winner Manistique will aim for a repeat in the March 5 Santa
Margarita.... Del Mar has renamed the Chula Vista Handicap for
fillies and mares as the Clemente L. Hirsch Handicap for its Aug.
12 running to honor the track's 85-year-old vice president. Hirsch
is a founder of the Oak Tree Racing Association.... Worldly Manner,
starting for the first time since he was seventh in the Kentucky
Derby and 12th in the Preakness, finished second by a nose in a
stakes race last week in Dubai.
</P>
</TEXT>
