<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-HOME18-COX     02-17 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-HOME18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis warmly welcomed home
 &HT;    By Mike Fish and Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Ray Lewis proclaimed his innocence Thursday to a
hometown that rallied around the NFL superstar and mostly blamed
his troubles on _ of all things _ Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of this historic city greeted their gridiron great
more as a returning hero than an accused killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard it many times before. Now you get to hear it from
me: I am innocent,'' Lewis said at a televised news conference at
the Baltimore Ravens' training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some see Lewis as the victim of what they perceive as
the South's backward, backwoods approach to law and order. And
hearing him make the short speech in his defense, they were worried
for him _ not only for his football future but for his survival in
Atlanta's judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first heard about it, we were thinking, 'He's in the
middle of the South. If he's convicted, he's going to die''' in the
electric chair, said Jamie Stevens, 27, a clerk at a Mailboxes,
Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Marian Roop, 48, a legal secretary, said she's heard the South
is ``a little harsher on blacks,'' and wonders whether prejudice
led Atlanta police to arrest Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Lewis' 75-second statement _ his first public utterance
since being charged with murder Jan. 31 in Atlanta _ people could
be seen nodding their heads. Many said he sounded sincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping he didn't do it because he's an idol to a lot of
children here,'' said Toya Knight, a 22-year-old college student
who watched Lewis' statement in a sports bar near Baltimore's
famous Inner Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   But others were not so sure. To many here, it seems absurd even
to mention the words ``murder'' and ``Ray Lewis'' in the same
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The doubts about his guilt run so deep that a Web site hawks
T-shirts that say ``Free Ray Lewis.'' In many quarters, strident
support for Lewis mingles with confidence that he will be cleared _
and anger that Atlanta kept him in jail for 15 days with no bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to make a mockery out of the prosecution,''
Eddie Rafus, a 45-year-old retiree, said of Lewis' defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Many believed from the start that the star middle linebacker,
who led the NFL in tackles last season, was innocent. Hearing him
say it, though, bolstered their confidence and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very sorry about the tragedy that occurred in Atlanta,''
said Lewis, dressed in a gray sweater with white stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis refused to answer questions, emphasizing a gag order on
the case. ``All I can do is sit back and wait for justice to take
its course and everything else to take its natural course. But I'm
looking forward to the day all the facts come out, everything is
out in front and my name is cleared,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis appeared solemn at Thursday's news conference, accompanied
by his friend and Baltimore attorney Ron Cherry and several team
officials _ including Ravens owner Art Modell and head coach Brian
Billick. Lewis had just arrived from Atlanta on a private jet
chartered by Modell.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis expressed his condolences to the victims' families,
saying: ``My sympathy goes out to the family and the friends of
both men that died.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is free on $1 million bond. He is charged _ along with
Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeting _ in the stabbing death of two
young Decatur, Ga., men after a Super Bowl party in Buckhead,
Atlanta's entertainment district.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Byrne, a Ravens vice president, said Lewis' lead attorney
in Atlanta, Ed Garland, is seriously considering whether to file a
speedy-trial motion under Georgia law, which could mean a late
April or May trial date. Criminal defense attorneys said such a
motion is normally filed if an attorney is confident in his case or
senses a weakness in the prosecutor's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ravens understand that Ray wants a speedy trial so he can
prove his innocence and get on with his life,'' Byrne said. ``Ed
Garland will make the decision whether to ask (for an early start
to the trial) _ not the Ravens. But he is good about keeping us in
the loop.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the Atlanta-bashing Thursday, many of Lewis' supporters
dismissed race as an issue because all three suspects and both
victims _ as well as the mayor, police chief and district attorney
in Atlanta _ are black. Among those making that distinction was
Larry Young, who hosts a call-in radio show on WBOL-AM, a station
whose audience is predominantly black.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority of the callers ... believe in Ray
Lewis' innocence,'' Young said. ``It's very much the talk of the
barber shops and beauty salons and taxi cabs and coffee shops.''
</P>
<P>
   He summarized Lewis' predicament: ``Wrong place, wrong time,
wrong crowd, wrong state.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others in Baltimore assailed Georgia's felony murder
rule, which says that anyone who commits a felony that leads to a
death can be convicted of murder _ whether or not there is intent
to kill.
</P>
<P>
   While he awaits trial on the murder charge, Lewis' life in
Baltimore has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's corrections department will monitor compliance to the
conditions of his bond.
</P>
<P>
   LaMont Flanagan, commissioner of pretrial detention and services
for Maryland, said his department will conduct weekly tests for
drugs and alcohol. A caseworker will meet with Lewis weekly at the
pretrial services office in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis will not be required to wear a monitoring ankle bracelet
``at this time,'' Flanagan said.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the Baltimore sentiment, Billick expressed the
team's support of Lewis, going so far as to say he would have use
of Ravens' facilities to prepare for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   A team official said Modell has been in contact with NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue, but neither the team nor the league is
ready to impose any disciplinary action, opting instead to see how
the case develops over the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   The first mandatory team function for Lewis is an April 28-30
mini-camp for veterans, followed by the start of training camp in
late July.
</P>
<P>
   It could create a public relations nightmare, however, if the
NFL were to suit up a player awaiting trial on murder and assault
charges.
</P>
<P>
   At minimum, Lewis' attorneys would have to request terms of his
bond release be modified, specifically a 9 p.m. curfew and a
restriction that he travel only between his home in Baltimore and
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the pro football players union said Thursday one
scenario might be for the NFL to grant Lewis a leave-of-absence
with pay while awaiting an outcome of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   However, legal counsel for the NFL Players Association said it
would likely file an appeal with an arbitrator if the league
attempts to prevent Lewis from earning a living while he's free on
bail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly have been situations where criminal charges
have been pending against a player and he was allowed to play,''
said Richard Berthelsen, NFLPA general counsel. ``We'd have to see
the circumstances at the time, but if a player is merely charged
with a crime and there are no restrictions on his ability to work,
I would see no reason why he shouldn't be allowed to play and earn
a living for his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
