<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Feb. 17, 2000 -- BROOKLYN-JAPAN-PRINTS-2 --
``Plum Estate, Kameido,'' (1857) by the Japanese master Utagawa
Hiroshige. His prints, among the best that deal with popular
subject matter in the woodblock medium known as ukiyo-e (''the
floating world'') have had a lasting effect on Western art. Their
compositional innovations have reverberated in the works of
Impressionists and Post-Impressionists, notably Monet, van Gogh and
Whistler. (Brooklyn Museum of Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Feb. 17, 2000 -- BROOKLYN-JAPAN-PRINTS-1 --
``Asakusa Rice Fields and Torinomachi Festival,'' (1857) by the
Japanese master Utagawa Hiroshige. Not the world's most enchanting
city, Tokyo has never looked so good as in ``100 Famous Views of
Edo,'' a series of color woodblock prints made in the mid-19th
century by Hiroshige (1797-1858). (Brooklyn Museum of Art/The New
York Times)
