<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0387 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PG&AMP;E-PG&AMP;E_SFCHRON &LR;      02-17 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PG&AMP;E-PG&AMP;E </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PG&AMP;E Given Huge Rate Increase  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Pacific Gas and Electric Co. was handed one of its largest rate
increases ever yesterday when state regulators ended a year of
acrimonious debate by approving the most generous of three rival
funding proposals.
<P>
   The more than $450 million increase passed by the California
Public Utilities Commission was about half what PG&AMP;E had originally
requested but nearly twice the amount recommended by an
administrative law judge who had investigated the utility's budget
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates were shocked by the decision. They had
expected the PUC to adopt a roughly $350 million rate increase put
on the table this week by the commission's president, Richard
Bilas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is complete corporate welfare,'' said Nettie Hoge,
executive director of The Utility Reform Network, a San Francisco
consumer group. ``There is no rationale for this decision. It's an
insult to ratepayers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a bad decision,'' agreed Martin Lyons, a
spokesman for the Office of Ratepayer Advocates. ``PG&AMP;E does not
require this level of funding.''
</P>
<P>
   According to TURN, the increase, which takes effect immediately,
will ultimately result in average residential power bills rising by
approximately $70 a year.
</P>
<P>
   However, PG&AMP;E insists that bills may actually decline as a
result of cost savings in other parts of the company's operations.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC estimates that residential gas bills will rise by about
$20 a year. Electricity rates are expected to remain frozen until
early next year under legislation passed in 1996 to restructure the
state's power industry. Electricity rates will probably drop about
10 percent when the freeze is lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Finkelstein, staff attorney for TURN, said his group will
appeal yesterday's decision to the PUC within a month. If that
fails, he said, TURN may consider legal action.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC voted 3 to 2 to adopt the $453 million rate increase
proposed by Commissioner Carl Wood, who was appointed to the panel
only last June and is its newest member.
</P>
<P>
   He joined commissioners Josiah Neeper and Loretta Lynch in
supporting the rate increase, while Bilas and Henry Duque voted
against.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said the two other proposals on the table _ for $264
million and $357 million, respectively _ ``cut too deep into muscle
and bone.'' He termed his own rate increase ``tough but fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``PG&AMP;E asked for too much,'' Wood said. ``The amount it
requested exceeded the amount needed for reliable service.''
</P>
<P>
   The utility had requested an increase of $822 million and had
threatened that as many as 3,500 jobs could be lost if the amount
approved did not come close to that.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E also had warned that tree-trimming around power lines could
be scaled back as a result of insufficient funding.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, the utility was granted a rate increase of $824
million. Most other recent increases have been between $200 million
and $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement yesterday, the utility said the latest increase
``does not provide everything we asked for, but it does recognize
the need for additional support to maintain the high level of
service our customers expect and to invest in the energy
infrastructure for our fast-growing California economy.''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E has said it needs substantially more funding not only to
meet existing service requirements, but also to keep pace with the
state's explosive economic growth, especially in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The utility said yesterday it will support the PUC's decision,
including implementation of a ``quality assurance program''
mandated by the commissioners to improve PG&AMP;E's dealings with
customers, billing accuracy and response to power failures.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were clearly pleased with the outcome of the vote.
PG&AMP;E's stock gained $1.31 yesterday to close at $23.13. The
company's shares had plunged by 35 percent last year as the rate
case dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   A senior PG&AMP;E official, who requested anonymity, said it is not
yet clear whether the rate increase will result in any layoffs.
``This is putting us on a tight budget,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The official did say, however, that the increase will allow PG&AMP;E
to maintain its tree-trimming program. Last April, the utility
quietly agreed to pay about $29 million to settle charges that it
had endangered the public by not keeping tree branches away from
electrical lines.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the PUC accused PG&AMP;E of no fewer than 500,000 counts of
violating state tree-trimming laws from 1994 through 1998. Each
count could have resulted in a fine of as much as $20,000 or a
maximum penalty of $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The PG&AMP;E official emphasized that work will continue on
expanding the utility's resources to meet California's growing need
for energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing growth rates in our system that we've never seen
before,'' he said. ``We're replacing pipelines and investing in new
infrastructure in Silicon Valley. That's what this case is about.''
</P>
<P>
   But TURN's Hoge said the state's technology-driven economic
surge does not justify a more than $450 million rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a booming economy and low inflation,'' she said.
``What happened is that the utility exercised its political muscle
in Sacramento to get what it wanted. This is a total failure of
regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
