<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Wash., Mich., Calif.) (rk) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   MORE PLAN TO VOTE
</P>
<P>
   A Palmetto Poll released Thursday by Clemson University in
Clemson, S.C., found that the percentage of respondents who said
they would vote in the Republican primary in South Carolina on
Saturday had risen to 45 percent this week from 31 percent last
month. Much of the increase appears to have come from those who had
previously said they would vote in the Democratic caucuses next
month or were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   CONVERT FOR McCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Switching his endorsement to a candidate who, he said, ``doesn't
have to be managed, pulled or prodded'' by advisers, Dan Evans, a
former senator and governor of Washington, pulled out of the Bush
campaign on Wednesday and announced his backing for John McCain.
Evans, a moderate Republican, excelled in pulling in independents
and Democrats during his political career but often butted heads
with conservatives of his own party.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HELP FROM DAD
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush campaigned across Michigan
Thursday, saying his son Gov. George W. Bush had a record of reform
as governor of Texas and had the character to be president. ``Our
son, the governor of the second-biggest state in the nation, has a
proven record of doing what he said he'd do,'' Bush said. ``Most of
all, at a time I think the country is crying out for it, he has
character,'' he told several hundred at the Ukrainian Cultural
Center in Warren.
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN AIDE UNDER FIRE
</P>
<P>
   A liberal Washington lobbying group, People for the American
Way, called on Sen. John McCain Thursday to fire his chief South
Carolina strategist, Richard M. Quinn, for editing a magazine that
the group said published racially insensitive material. The group's
president, Ralph G. Neas, wrote that Quinn's magazine, Southern
Partisan, a leading journal of the neo-Confederate movement, has
repeatedly criticized the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., Nelson
Mandela and Abraham Lincoln and has depicted blacks in demeaning
ways. McCain and Quinn have repeatedly denied that Quinn holds
racist views, and the campaign said Thursday that he would remain
on staff.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   ADS ON ABORTION STANCE
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley's campaign began running a 30-second
television commercial Thursday that promotes his strong support for
abortion rights and, by implication, questions Vice President Al
Gore's. ``Of the five men running for president only one candidate
has been pro-choice for everyone,'' the narrator says, echoing
language that Gore's campaign has used to criticize Bradley.
Bradley then comes on camera and says, ``This is the kind of issue
that you can't straddle. You can't be on both sides.'' The spot was
released two days after the National Abortion Rights Action League
endorsed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER RATINGS FOR FEINSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein got some good news about her bid for
re-election. A Field Poll released on Wednesday found her approval
rating at 56 percent and found that only 26 percent of respondents
disapproved of the job she had done. Last year, her average
approval rating in the poll was 49 percent and her disapproval
rating was 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: New York City, Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Clinton, Anderson, Clemson and Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: St. Louis; Cleveland; and Springfield, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: Hilton Head, Sun City, Charleston, Litchfield Beach
and Greenville, S.C. &QL;
