<SLUG> BC-WIN2000-WIN2000 </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Corporate Bash for Windows  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Downplaying reports that its newest system may be infested with
bugs, Microsoft yesterday launched Windows 2000 _ the company's
most ambitious software project ever _ with a curious mix of
tech-speak and celebrity pomp.
<P>
   Windows 2000, the business operating system that the Seattle
software giant itself calls a ``bet the ranch'' product, officially
became available through about 2,000 retail channels yesterday,
though it's already on the desktops of some 150,000 users,
including Microsoft's own 75,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates, who last month handed over the
chief executive post to longtime friend Steve Ballmer to take on
the role of chief software architect, led the wide-ranging Windows
2000 kickoff kick-off  &LR; at San Francisco's cavernous Bill Graham
Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the usual stylized demos and corporate testimonials
from the likes of Continental Airlines and ESPN, the presentation
featured a moving-van-size laptop, appearances by guitar guru
Carlos Santana; actor John O'Hurley, who played eccentric
businessman J. Peterman on the sitcom ``Seinfeld''; and Patrick
Stewart of ``Star Trek'' fame.
</P>
<P>
   And though there were plenty of jokes around the words
``enterprise'' and ``next generation,'' two serious themes
dominated the 90-minute presentation: Microsoft's desire to make
inroads in the high-end server market and the increased reliability
of Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since '95 (when Microsoft introduced its popular Windows 95
consumer operating system), some big things happened,'' Gates said.
``The Internet arrived and achieved critical mass. It's now viewed
as the future of communication and the future of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is billing Windows 2000, successor to its Windows NT
product, as the platform on which businesses can run Web sites and
manage information technology, as well as give workers a desktop
machine.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the company has embarked on a broad _ critics say maybe
too broad _ marketing campaign including billboards and bus cards
to build awareness of Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the ads, as well as yesterday's glitzy
dog-and-pony show, are aimed at IT professionals, the intended
Windows 2000 market. However, ``There will also be some enthusiasts
who will be interested in this product at home,'' said Deborah
Willingham, vice president of Windows Marketing, at a news
conference just after Santana finished playing the hit single
``Smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   In a mantra that has become familiar in the weeks leading up the
Windows 2000 launch, Willingham and others stressed that Windows
2000 isn't for consumers _ they should wait for Windows Millennium
Edition, the successor to Windows 98, which will garner its own
splashy launch sometime this summer.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the emphasis is on Windows 2000, the operating system
that is expected to generate more than $5 billion revenue over its
four-year life span and lay the groundwork for a slew of new
Microsoft products including the Windows 2000 Datacenter Server and
SQL Server 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It's also Microsoft's most complex project.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 2000 represents about 35 million lines of code, almost
four years of work and about $2 billion in development costs.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off for that complexity could be compatibility
problems with customers' old software. Last week, the Gartner
Group, a Stamford, Conn., research organization, warned that up to
a quarter of Windows 2000 users might experience such glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gartenberg, Gartner Group's research director, said:
``The problem isn't whether Win 2000 is ready for the enterprise _
it probably is _ but whether the enterprise is ready for Windows
2000. A lot of companies still run a lot of old hardware and
software, including in-house applications that may not have been
updated in years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gartenberg expounded on a shadow that has hung over Microsoft
and the its stock over the past week. According to an internal memo
obtained by Smart Reseller Magazine, Microsoft said there were
63,000 glitches in the release version of Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But both Microsoft and Gartenberg minimized the bug report.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell much from that figure,'' Gartenberg said. ``It
probably includes results from (Microsoft's) automated testing
tools, which log anything they consider an anomaly _ even things as
trivial as an icon being 1 pixel out of place.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Enderle, an analyst at Giga Information Group, believes both
the compatibility and bug issues have been overplayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very impressed,'' he said. ``This is the kind of product
people have been expecting for five years. It has a reliability
that we haven't seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the giant laptop's screen unfolding to reveal
Santana, the crowd reacted most enthusiastically when Gates pulled
up a chart showing the results of a study by Ziff Davis Labs on the
number of times various Microsoft applications needed to be
rebooted after 90 days of continuous use. For Windows 95, a reboot
was needed every 2.1 days; Windows NT 4.0 users had to reboot every
5.2 days and Windows 2000 was still up after 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Other features that drew applause _ often led by two groups of
Microsoft staffers in vivid blue shirts seated on the mezzanine
level _ were the ability to transfer files between computers using
infrared technology and the ability to plug in a few new servers to
a Windows 2000-equipped network and have them handling their share
of a network's traffic with a few clicks.
</P>
<P>
   According to the nonprofit San Jose organization Transaction
Processing Performance Council, Windows 2000 running Microsoft's
SQL Server 2000 database program on Compaq hardware could handle
more than 152,000 transactions per minute, compared with the next
closest contender _ a Unix machine _ which could handle about
134,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fitted with four extra nodes, or processors, the Windows 2000
machines could field 227,000 transactions per minute, ``enough to
handle all of the e-commerce handled on the Web last year in two
days,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gartenberg, the Gartner Group analyst, said Windows 2000's
apparent performance gains don't necessarily make the system a
no-brainer for IT professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The performance they showed is not unimpressive,'' he said.
``But the implication is that (Windows 2000) solves all the issues
about the scalability (ability of a system to adapt to increased
demand) of NT, and the reality is, it doesn't. They were talking
about ... eight machines clustered together, and they were
comparing it with a single Unix machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the hoopla, Microsoft stock rose $2, closing at $99.63.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Staff writer Henry Norr contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
