<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MENTAL-HOSPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS ABUSIVE CONDITIONS IN MEXICO'S MENTAL HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By MICHAEL WINERIP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long-term patients at Mexico's mental hospitals live in filthy,
abusive and dangerous conditions, and as many as half are epileptic
or mentally retarded and do not even belong in a psychiatric
institution, according to a study released Thursday by an
international human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions in Mexican institutions are among the worst we
have seen in the world,'' said Dr. Robert Okin, a human rights
inspector for Mental Disability Rights International who is also
chief of psychiatry at San Francisco General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The group's study focuses on long-term psychiatric hospitals,
known as ``granjas.'' ``One-third to one-half of the individuals
within Mexico's granjas are identified as people with epilepsy or
mental retardation,'' the report said. ``Such individuals do not
need or benefit from psychiatric institutionalization.''
</P>
<P>
   The human rights investigators, who made three inspection tours
of Mexican hospitals from July 1996 to last November, found feces
and urine soiling the floors of several wards. On an inspection in
1998, the director at one hospital, Sayago, ``reported a number of
deaths from infectious disease (bronchitis),'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The rights group, based in Washington, repeatedly noted
deterioration in patients because of failure to provide basic care.
``Due to the lack of physical therapy'' at Sayago, the report said,
``40 people have lost the ability to walk and are confined to
wheelchairs.''
</P>
<P>
   While the report finds that most of the patients could live in
the outside community, ``the majority remain within the institution
for life.''
</P>
<P>
   After a report on conditions at the Mexican institutions in The
New York Times Magazine in January, Health Secretary Jose Antonio
Gonzalez Fernandez began a tour of mental hospitals, acknowledging
that there were a ``lot of aspects to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Mexico City Thursday, members of the
rights team said Gonzalez had pledged an additional $3.6 million
for three institutions. Gonzalez did not respond to requests for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, several directors have acknowledged that a large
number of their patients did not need hospitalization, but said
those people had been abandoned by their families and had no place
to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mentally retarded should not be here,'' the director of
the Guadalajara state hospital, Dr. Daniel Ojeda, said. ``But
there's no place for them. This hospital is doing something it is
not qualified to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Inter-American Commission on Human Rights has scheduled a
hearing on conditions at Mexican institutions for March 2.
</P>
<P>
   According to the mental disabilities group, which has done
similar work throughout Latin America, Eastern Europe and the
former Soviet Union, Mexican hospital directors have ``reported
shortages of food, clothes and blankets.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said that at Hidalgo ``people are brought straight
from this ward to the dining area without an opportunity to wash
their hands or clean themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those able to get to a bathroom do not have access to toilet
paper,'' the study said. ``People on the ward are given medications
with water from a common bucket, using one cup passed from one
person to another.''
</P>
<P>
   The rights group recommended that Mexico begin to finance a
system of community housing programs for patients who should be
released. At present, there is not a single government-financed
group home or apartment program in all Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
