u a BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-640(2     02-17 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-640(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COVER-UP TRIAL, EX-OFFICER DESCRIBES HIS ATTACK ON LOUIMA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former police officer sentenced to 30 years in
prison for torturing Abner Louima in the bathroom of a Brooklyn
station house took the witness stand Thursday and described in
detail a simmering rage that led to the attack and an anguish that
eventually caused him to come forward and confess.
</P>
<P>
   In more than two hours of searing testimony in U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn, the former officer, Justin A. Volpe, delivered
an emotional account of how he pinned Louima against the bathroom
wall and confronted him face to face. Then, he said, in a mire of
confusion and anger over what he said was a defiant tone by Louima,
he rammed a broken broomstick into the defenseless man's rectum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I held the stick in front of his face to say `look what
happened, look what happened,''' Volpe recalled, adding that he
repeated the phrase using an expletive, `` `look what you made me
do,' and he didn't respond, he didn't say anything. I threw the
stick down and I picked him up and escorted him out of the
bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe was testifying in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn at the
trial of three other officers accused of conspiring to cover up the
attack. He said that the one officer, Charles Schwarz, never took
part in the assault and stunned the gallery to the point of silence
by saying that another officer, Thomas Wiese, stood by and did
nothing as Louima was tortured.
</P>
<P>
   In previous statements, Wiese has said that he walked into the
bathroom moments after the attack and discovered Volpe standing
alone with a stick in his hand as Louima sobbed at his feet.
Volpe's testimony Thursday was the first time that anyone has said
under oath that Wiese was inside the bathroom throughout the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   But more mesmerizing to the jury and the packed courtroom
Thursday was Volpe's excruciating account of the brutal assault
that made him infamous. At its height, he asserted that Schwarz,
who was convicted of being his accomplice, was, in fact, an
innocent man. His motivation for coming forth, he said, was to
clear his conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two months ago, I was sentenced to 30 years in prison,'' Volpe
said, swallowing his words and offering his palms in contrition.
``Part of reclaiming my life is to tell the truth about what
happened that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Haltingly, he continued: ``I can't live with myself and do my
time in peace by knowing that another man is paying for the crimes
that I did. It has nothing to do with friendship. It just has to do
with doing what's right in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, the government has argued that Schwarz held
Louima down while he was attacked and that he then conspired with
Wiese and another officer on trial, Thomas Bruder, to get himself
off the hook. The defense maintains there was no conspiracy to hide
Schwarz's involvement because Schwarz was never involved.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Wiese now faces some degree of public ignominy because
of Volpe's testimony, it is unlikely to damage his chances in the
trial because the jury can only consider whether the three
defendants lied about Schwarz. Likewise, federal prosecutors are
unlikely to enter a new charge against Wiese because they consider
Volpe an untrustworthy witness who has previously lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Volpe's damning testimony, Wiese's lawyer, Joseph
Tacopina, decided not to conduct an cross-examination. ``The only
issue in this case is whether Charles Schwarz was in the bathroom
and the defendants lied about it,'' Tacopina said. ``In that
regard, I had nothing to ask Volpe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Fischetti, Schwarz's lawyer, said his client was happy
with Volpe's testimony. ``We have said in openings and maintained
throughout the trial that Chuck Schwarz was never in the
bathroom,'' he said. ``Justin Volpe was there, and now he has
testified to that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning earlier by Fischetti, Volpe offered his
dramatic account of the events on the night of Aug. 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe said that while responding to a call that night at Club
Rendezvous, a Haitian dance hall in Flatbush, Brooklyn, he was
punched in the head and knocked to the ground by a man he thought
was Louima. Louima was arrested and taken to the 70th Precinct
station house, Volpe said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the police station, Volpe said, he took off his
bulletproof vest, his gun belt and and other equipment and went
into an empty room to be alone. He wanted to unwind from the fracas
on the street, he said, but he could not put the scuffle out of his
mind. ``I was just collecting myself,'' he said, ``and I started to
become angry.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a broom in the empty room, he said, and he picked it
up and snapped the handle in half. ``I was going to take that stick
and threaten him with it or possibly even hit him with it,'' Volpe
testified. ``I took that stick and put it in the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Volpe returned to the front desk and took custody
of Louima, whose pants and underwear were down around his knees, he
said. (He later testified that he did not see who had pulled down
Louima's pants.) He led the prisoner into the bathroom, he said,
then pushed Louima up against the wall and stood in front of him
face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you curse at me on the street and why did you punch
me?''he said he asked Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Louima cursed in response, Volpe said. He threw a punch at
Louima's chest. Then, ``I grabbed him by his arms,'' Volpe said,
``and I threw him to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima was face down on the bathroom floor, his head near a
toilet, Volpe said. ``At this point, I had a lot of emotions that I
never, ever felt before in my life,'' he said. ``I felt frustrated,
very confused and I didn't know how to proceed with the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Volpe found the stick where he had left it in a
garbage can, he said. He placed the stick near Louima's buttocks,
thinking, as he described it, ``that that would scare him
somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice while they were standing, Volpe said, he had asked Louima
to apologize for striking him on the street. Both times, he added,
Louima did not apologize.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor, ``I asked him one more time, do you have anything
to say,'' Volpe testified, pausing now, releasing breath. Louima
mumbled something, something aggressive, Volpe said _ ``possibly a
curse.'' Then he went on, ``And I tensed up and I pushed the stick
into his rectum.''
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Lauren Resnick, an assistant U.S.
attorney, suggested that Volpe was lying about Schwarz and that he
was seeking to implicate Wiese out of revenge. Early in the
investigation, Wiese had approached the authorities to give a
statement about Volpe but was rebuffed when he failed a lie
detector test.
</P>
<P>
   But Volpe said he was hoping to put an end to the case once and
for all. ``I am telling the truth about what happened that night to
clear it up,'' he said, ``not just for me, but for the officers,
for Louima and his family, for the newspapers and for everyone so
that they can go with their lives and there would be some closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who better to do that than me. I'm the man that assaulted
Louima.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
