u f BC-MAGAZINE-AD-COLUMN-NY     02-17 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: TIME INC. PLANS MAGAZINE ABOUT SIMPLIFYING LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a frenetic era when most women feel more pressed
than ever, how can a publisher persuade them to squeeze another
magazine into their busy lives? With some help from a longtime
agency executive, Time Inc. believes it's really simple _ er, make
that Real Simple.
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple is the name of the publication that the People
Magazine Group of Time Inc. in New York, owned by Time Warner Inc.,
plans to introduce in late March. The goal of the magazine, which
is to appear 8 times this year and then 10 times a year starting in
2001, is to help its readers _ projected to be college-educated
working women and mothers with a median age of 36 _ simplify their
overextended lives.
</P>
<P>
   The role taken in the development of Real Simple by the agency
executive, Mary Lou Quinlan, who heads a year-old New York shop
named Just Ask a Woman, is emblematic of the rewriting of the rules
by which the advertising, marketing and media industries operate as
the major figures redefine the parts they play.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, J. Walter Thompson USA, part of the WPP Group, has
formed an alliance with Basic Entertainment, the powerful Hollywood
talent management company, focused on entertainment marketing.
Unilever, the consumer products giant, is starting an Internet
company with Ivillage Inc., a Web site operator, to provide online
information to women. And Tyler Brule, who founded Wallpaper
magazine, now owned by Time Inc., has started a consulting company,
Wink Media, to produce ads and customized magazines for marketers
and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired Just Ask a Woman as a strategic and creative
consultant, to develop advertising, help with research and
collaborate with'' the top editorial and design staff members of
Real Simple, said Andy Sareyan, publisher at the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so clear the concept of this magazine is playing right to
so much of America,'' he added. ``People see the ability to control
your life as a sign of success.''
</P>
<P>
   That is encapsulated in the theme of the consumer and trade
advertising and promotion campaign for Real Simple, which rewrites
the familiar assertion that ``Less is more'' to declare: ``Do less.
Have more.'' The campaign, now getting under way, is one of many
elements of Real Simple developed under the aegis of Just Ask a
Woman, a division of BDM Inc., the agency company recently formed
by the merger of the MacManus Group, the former parent of Just Ask
a Woman, and the Leo Group, parent of agencies like Leo Burnett Co.
</P>
<P>
   Quinlan is a model of sorts for Real Simple because, she said,
``I had an affinity for the idea of simplifying your life; I did it
myself.'' Her reference was to her career choice early last year,
leaving another BDM agency, N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners in New York, where
she had been chief executive since 1995, to take on the task of
opening what became Just Ask a Woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took five weeks off to think about what I wanted from life
and redesigned it,'' Quinlan said, adding, ``Everyone says `You
look younger now' and I say `I'm happy now, that's why.'''
</P>
<P>
   The work done by Just Ask a Woman included showing prototypes of
the magazine to potential readers in focus groups, asking them
about ad campaign ideas and seeking opinions on ``what simplicity
means today,'' Quinlan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they talked about was quality, not quantity,'' she added.
``The premise of doing less and still having more was powerful.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But isn't there an inherent contradiction in a magazine that
asks readers to pare their lives, clear the clutter and become
better organized while its ad pages encourage purchasing and
consuming still more goods and services?
</P>
<P>
   In other words, is Time Inc. a publishing house divided against
itself for introducing a glossy, ad-fat magazine devoted to
conspicuous inconsumption?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not heard one comment'' to that effect, said Robin
Domeniconi, associate publisher at Real Simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would walk into a room'' to describe the magazine to
agencies and advertisers, she added, ``and people would be nodding
their heads in a few minutes'' in agreement with the concept.
</P>
<P>
   The sales effort must have worked because Real Simple, which
will initially guarantee advertisers a circulation of 400,000, will
simply be packed with ad pages.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``the biggest launch in Time Inc. history,'' Sareyan said,
``sold out'' at 110 ad pages. Among the blue-chip advertisers are
Cadillac, Chanel, Citigroup, Liz Claiborne, Clinique, Crate and
Barrel, De Beers, Gap, Donna Karan, Calvin Klein, Ralph Lauren,
Nordstrom, Reebok, Ann Taylor and Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about consuming less,'' Quinlan said of Real Simple.
``It's about consuming more selectively, not buying for the sake of
buying.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, she added, an article in Real Simple about
decorating with flowers would say, ``It's not all that hard, just
get a few and stick them in a jar.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will run in the pages of sibling magazines like
Entertainment Weekly, In Style, Life, Parenting, People, Southern
Living, Sunset, Teen People and Travel and Leisure. The ad space is
being valued at $10 million to $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   That would buy a lot of flower jars _ or from the Real Simple
perspective, a few truly wonderful jars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
