<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, FEB. 18
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NY-NASDAQ-SIGN-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Feb. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Feb.
16, about the dominance of Nasdaq's video screen in Times Square
misspelled the surname of a prominent sign designer who compared
the square to a corporate theme park and misspelled the name of his
company. He is George N. Stonbely, not Stonebly; the company is
Spectacolor Communications, not Spectracolor.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CONSUMER-GOODS-NYT (moved on Thursday, Jan. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Jan. 27,
about the success of mass-market retailers in developing their own
brands misstated the owner of White Cloud toilet tissue. It is
Paper Partners L.L.C., not Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TREASURY-MARKETPLACE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Feb. 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Feb.
16, about reducing the nation's debt, misstated the number of times
the Federal Reserve has raised short-term interest rates since
June. It is four, not three.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ARMS-STRATEGY-NYT (moved on Friday, Feb. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Feb. 4,
about the threat of nuclear conflict since the end of the Cold War
misstated the size of the Russian and American nuclear arsenals.
Russia has about 6,000 long-range nuclear weapons and the United
States has about 7,000; they do not have 2,000 to 2,500 each. (The
smaller figure is the number each country has on alert and ready to
launch.)
</P>
</TEXT>
