<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BANK-ASSESS-90     02-17 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANK-ASSESS-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: CHARGES AGAINST BANK ARE POSSIBLE IN MONEY LAUNDERING
INQUIRY  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a week ago, the Bank of New York enjoyed a brief respite
from the money laundering investigation that has engulfed it for
the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state regulators imposed embarrassing sanctions on
the bank that took it to task for lax supervision and weak controls
on money laundering. But the actions fell short of stricter
penalties that could have been imposed, which Bank of New York
officials described as a relief.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, the two main suspects in the investigation _
one of whom was a bank officer _ pleaded guilty to a range of
criminal charges including helping to launder money that flowed out
of Russia. And those confessions have raised the possibility that
the bank itself could face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   The bank declined to comment Thursday on its potential liability
in the matter, and pinning down the bank's exposure is difficult
because prosecutors have wide discretion in deciding whether to
pursue charges against a company.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, corporations are legally liable for the actions of
their officers, and now that the two suspects _ a former bank vice
president, Lucy Edwards, and her husband, Peter Berlin _ are
cooperating with prosecutors, the stakes have suddenly risen for
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and Berlin told a federal judge on Wednesday in
Manhattan that they ran a money laundering network tied to a
company called Benex International that illegally channeled the
money from Russia through the Bank of New York and on to overseas
accounts. They are expected to provide more testimony about others
at the bank who knew of the scheme, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher up in the organization knowledge flows, the easier
it is for the prosecution to make a case against the entity,'' said
Michael Zeldin, a former Justice Department official and a partner
with PricewaterhouseCoopers in Washington. ``If the head of a
division knows about it, then it's much worse than if some
lower-level employee knew.''
</P>
<P>
   So sorting out who knew what _ and when they knew it _ at the
Bank of New York will ultimately decide the company's fate in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even before regulators took action last week, they were
deeply divided about how high in the organization knowledge of the
Benex scheme went.
</P>
<P>
   According to people involved in the investigation, the New York
branch of the Federal Reserve withheld information from Federal
Reserve officials in Washington about what was known about the
scheme inside the bank and who knew it _ information that the New
York officials only passed on to the U.S. attorney's office in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve officials in New York and Washington declined to
comment Thursday when asked about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has already implicated one Bank of New York employee.
She said she paid Svetlana Kudryavtsev, a former low-level bank
employee, to help oversee the Benex accounts. Kudryavtsev pleaded
innocent Thursday to federal charges that she lied to investigators
about having received money from Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors will have to implicate much more senior officials at
the bank than Kudryavtsev if they hope to bring a case against the
bank. Of course, the highest officer at the Bank of New York is its
chairman and chief executive, Thomas A. Renyi. No evidence has
surfaced indicating that Renyi had knowledge of the money
laundering scheme before federal investigators began their secret
inquiry in September 1998. In fact, bank officials did not alert
Renyi about the investigation until March 1999, according to a
person involved in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, red flags existed. Bank employees knew that Berlin and
Edwards were married, but this served only to shield the accounts
from scrutiny. In congressional testimony last fall, Renyi said the
fact that Berlin was married to ``a well-regarded bank officer''
had dissuaded bank auditors from looking closely at the Benex
accounts. He described that as ``a lapse on the part of the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Testimony from Edwards and Berlin about what was known of their
activities inside the bank is crucial to any possible criminal case
against the institution. One reason a federal money laundering
investigation of Citigroup has stalled is that investigators have
been unable to find enough witnesses at the bank with knowledge of
the alleged scheme, according to a federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors do not need to show that every higher-up at the Bank
of New York knew of the scheme there to bring a case against the
company. A federal money laundering case against the Bank of New
England in the late 1980s established the legal precedent that
knowledge among only a handful of employees implicates the entire
company.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of New York has been cooperating with the federal
investigation from the beginning, and that may offer some shield
from prosecutions _ as long as evidence provided by Edwards and
Berlin is not too damaging. So far, the bank has not been accused
of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   In heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange on Thursday, the
Bank of New York's shares plunged $2.4375, or 6.5 percent, to
$35.0626. Several other bank stocks slipped but not as much as Bank
of New York shares.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, the House Banking Committee chairman,
said Thursday that he would subpoena Edwards and Berlin to testify
at a second round of hearings he plans to hold on the Bank of New
York investigation. A date for the hearings has not been set.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The Bank of New York story is seminally significant because it
represents a verifiable incident where the financial system has
been corrupted,'' Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a criminal suit is filed against the Bank of New York,
the company might take comfort in statistics because successful
money laundering prosecutions are rare.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 to 1998, the only years for which figures are
available, only three individuals were convicted in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan in money laundering cases not related to drugs,
according to Justice Department data compiled by the Transactional
Records Access Clearinghouse, a nonprofit organization at Syracuse
University.
</P>
<P>
   And during the last decade, according to a newsletter, Money
Laundering Alert, only foreign banks have been indicted in the
United States on money laundering charges. No American banks have
been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   If the federal prosecutors in Manhattan decide to pursue money
laundering charges against the Bank of New York, the law
enforcement agency cannot proceed on its own. It will need
approvals from the Justice Department, which must authorize federal
indictments of financial institutions for money laundering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
