u a BC-TV-MARRY-MILLIONAIRE-     02-17 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARRY-MILLIONAIRE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Pa.)  
 TV's MILLIONAIRE BRIDEGROOM HAS A PAST IN ENTERTAINMENT  
 (af)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Days after marrying, on national television, a woman he had
never met before, Rick Rockwell, identified on the show as a
multimillionaire real estate developer, Thursday became the talk of
his hometown, San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It is a city where he is less well known for real estate than
for comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell was the central figure in a Fox television special,
``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' which drew spectacular
ratings Tuesday night. He appeared in shadows for much of the
telecast while 50 contestants offered themselves as prospective
brides. Rockwell selected Darva Conger, 34, an emergency room
nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Details about Rockwell began to emerge Thursday, painting him as
a longtime comic performer, known mainly for elaborate stunts, like
chartering a plane and performing 10-minute stand-up routines in
six cities in one night, telling jokes for 30 straight hours in an
effort to set a Guinness world record, and, most recently, riding
from Los Angeles to Las Vegas on a bicycle to promote a comedy
club.
</P>
<P>
   The last event took place two years ago, said the owner of the
comedy club The Improv, Bud Friedman, who hired him for that stunt.
Mike Fleiss, the show's producer, said Thursday that he thought
Rockwell had not been a performer since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives emphasized Thrsday that they were aware Rockwell
had a show-business background and had fully disclosed that on the
show. Indeed, Mike Darnell, the Fox executive who conceived the
idea for the special, said Rockwell's ability to carry himself well
on camera and in front of an audience was one big reason he was
chosen.
</P>
<P>
   But Darnell said Rockwell had been thoroughly checked out and
qualified as a multimillionaire. ``That means at least $2
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell, who was born Richard Balkey in Pittsburgh, listed
himself as a real estate developer and motivational speaker. He has
a Web site where he calls himself a ``corporate comedian.''
</P>
<P>
   On the site he includes a long list of corporations and groups
he has spoken before, including Johnson &AMP; Johnson and AT&AMP;T and the
Joint Chiefs of Staff. The resume also includes a claim that
Rockwell ``opened for Jay Leno in the main room of Caesar's
Tahoe.''
</P>
<P>
   A booking representative for Leno said Thursday that Rockwell
has never opened in Lake Tahoe for Leno.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell has successfully invested in beachfront real estate in
San Diego, with some backing by his father, said Larry Himmel, a
former comedy partner of his who is now a reporter for KFMB-TV in
San Diego. Five Realtor associations in San Diego had not heard of
him.
</P>
<P>
   KFMB broadcast an interview Thursday night with a woman named
Gina Ord, who identified herself as a former girlfriend. Ord told
the station that she broke off the relationship with Rockwell six
months ago, and that he wanted to get back together but she was
unsure. She also said Rockwell called her two days before the show
and told her he was only doing it to advance his career as a
comedian and motivational speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell was best known in San Diego for his portrayal of
Skippy, a dim-witted beach bum on a sketch comedy program on KFMB
in the 1980s described by station officials as a ``poor man's
`Saturday Night Live.''' He appeared in a regular sketch with
Himmel. The running theme, the station officials said, was ``two
surfer dudes who couldn't get dates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
