<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SC-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      02-17 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUND OF ACRIMONY FILLS CAROLINA AIRWAVES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ ``Winning ugly'' may be taking on new meaning
in the closing days of the South Carolina primary campaign, as the
airwaves fill with a new round of acrimonious commercials,
virtually all directed toward Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In one, Carroll Campbell Jr., the former governor of South
Carolina and a leading supporter of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
suggests that McCain is the tool of a Democratic plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send the Clinton-Gore Democrats a message Saturday,'' Campbell
says in the radio commercial. ``Vote for the man they're
desperately trying to stop: George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   In another advertisement, paid for by South Carolina and
national anti-abortion groups, McCain is portrayed as a closet
supporter of abortion rights. ``So if you want a strong pro-life
president, don't vote for John McCain,'' an announcer says.
</P>
<P>
   And in a new 30-second television commercial, the Bush campaign
paints McCain as a spendthrift in pushing one of the backbone
issues of his candidacy, campaign finance reform. ``Five times, he
voted to use your taxes to pay for political campaigns,'' a
narrator says. ``That's not real reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Never before in this campaign have the advertisements of both
major candidates for the Republican nomination become so obsessed
with a single subject: John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Although the look of their commercials differed in Iowa and New
Hampshire _ Bush's used more stylish film techniques _ they tended
to concentrate on themes and traits peculiar to each candidate. But
since McCain's renunciation of his own attack ads last week, and
especially in recent days, Bush's advertisements have become almost
unrelentingly aggressive. If anything, they are tougher now than
before McCain pulled back.
</P>
<P>
   The radio and television campaign, with a cost now estimated to
be approaching $6 million, includes everything from 30-second takes
to infomercial-length commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is running a half-hour program, a video of a recent meeting
with voters at the College of Charleston, once in each of the three
major media markets in South Carolina. McCain's 30-minute piece,
compiled from commercials and taped interviews, was broadcast once
this week on WIS in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   On the local news stations, the changes in the tone of the
advertising are being reported as if they were shifts in the
weather. As the anchors on WTMA, Charleston's leading talk radio
station, put it throughout the day: ``Texas Governor George W.
Bush's ad takes on Senator John McCain for negative campaigning.
McCain's final ad is positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the new advertisements McCain has introduced, his
campaign appears hopeful that voters will punish Bush for
attacking. In an upbeat commercial that the McCain forces began
broadcasting today, the senator is described as ``a Republican like
Ronald Reagan who can win,'' and reserves its combativeness for the
Democrats. ``I'm going to beat Al Gore like a drum,'' McCain
declares.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's radio commercials, running far less frequently here
than those of Bush and the special-interest groups that support the
governor, concentrate mostly on the tactics of the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some power brokers fear our conservative reforms,'' the
senator says. ``They're using every old political trick they can to
fool you about me. But you know the truth. I am a proud, pro-life
Reagan conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Another commercial features a number of voices expressing
support for withdrawing McCain's attack ads. ``His decision to run
a purely positive campaign shows he's a man of confidence,'' a
woman says. A man adds, ``John McCain is drawing people into this
election that have been completely jaded by politics.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a one-sided feel now to the
mean-spiritedness of the advertising, a lot of which can be traced
to the on-air contributions of special-interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is not the first primary state in which outside
groups have run advertisements; in New Hampshire, Bush was the
target of attack ads by both the Sierra Club and the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the commercials running here seem harsher, and the
nastiest may be one being broadcast by a group called the
Federation for American Immigration Reform, which is not aligned
with either candidate. ``Ask the candidates if they think one
million immigrants a year are too many,'' the announcer advises,
``because some imports are just too expensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
