<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAYES LEADS BUT WOODS IS LURKING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (rk) 
 By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFIC PALISADES, Calif. _ Rain-softened fairways at Riviera
Country Club gave players the opportunity to lift, clean and place
their balls Thursday. The only question was why Tiger Woods, the
world's hottest golfer, did not shoot lower than 3--under 68 during
the first round of the Nissan Open on a course that surrendered
birdies to anyone with enough patience to wipe the mud from their
irons.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Hayes set Thursday's early standard, carding a bogey-free
7-under 64, which put him one stroke ahead of Robin Freeman and two
shots ahead of four players who included Freeman's brother, Jeff, a
club pro. Ordinarily, the Freemans would have made for a sweet,
homespun story about their sibling rivalry back in St. Charles, Mo.
``I kept looking up at the leader board and saw him go 3-under,
4-under, 5-under,'' said Jeff, who shot 66 and was tied for third
with Neal Lancaster, Mark Brooks and Bob Tway, ``and I said, gosh,
I can't let him beat me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsworthy, perhaps, but these are extraordinary days on the PGA
Tour. And no matter which round is being played, leader board
watching centers on Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's putting golf in places it hasn't been,'' said the South
African Nick Price, who was among 10 players at 4-under. ``I think
the interest worldwide has been just what was hoped for. There's a
tremendous amount of interest in my part of the world. It's found
its niche thanks to what Tiger has done lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods found his comfort zone early, teeing off on No. 1 at 8:03
a.m., reaching the 503-yard par-5 with a 3-iron for his second shot
and two-putting for an easy birdie.
</P>
<P>
   On No. 2, he sank a 15-footer for another birdie, which
threatened to send Tigermania back toward critical mass. Woods'
only mistake was a three-putt bogey at No. 6, before he added a
25-foot birdie putt at No. 7 and dropped a 12-footer for his final
birdie at the par-3 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm only four back, but it really doesn't matter that
much,'' he said. ``It's just a matter that I shot under par, which
I'm very pleased about. Right now, I'm not really worried about the
weekend. I'm worried about getting myself into position to where if
the weather turns bad, that I don't have to go out there and play a
miracle round to try and catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm right in the ballgame. It's where I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods does not enjoy too many fond memories of this tournament.
Two years ago, he lost a one-hole playoff to Billy Mayfair at
Valencia Country Club north of Los Angeles. As a 16-year-old
amateur in 1992, Woods played his first pro tournament at Riviera.
Although he missed the cut that year, he gave a preview of the
excitement to come on No. 1 and No. 2, lipping out a long eagle
putt and saving par from deep in the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about some of that in the pro-am, but not today,''
Woods said of Wednesday's pro-am. ``I was out there focused on what
I had to do. I had a few key things I needed to think about with my
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   He then offered a list of what he planned to work on at the
practice range: his hip-turn, the flex of his right knee, the
position of the left arm at the top of his backswing, his left
wrist and making sure he stays behind the ball at impact.
</P>
<P>
   Perfection is clearly not as simple as Woods makes it look.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the whole package right now,'' Brooks offered. ``The
way he keeps improving, he could keep going until he gets bored of
beating us. Sure, he could get beat any week, but it's going to
take guys who are playing great, inspired golf.''
</P>
<P>
   There is hope, though. According to Lancaster, the two par-5s on
Riviera's back nine, No. 11 and No. 17, are not automatic birdies,
even for Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Par is 68 for him on every golf course,'' he said. ``But on a
course like this, we stand more of a chance because he can't reach
all the par-5s.''
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at Woods' scorecard revealed pars on both holes
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
