<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-17 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HOOP DREAMS AND REALITY, THE COLLISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a 1979 recruiting visit to Albany, Keith Glass, a former
assistant basketball coach at UCLA, was asked a favor by Sam
Perkins' guardian: Would Glass drive the blue-chip prep star across
town, to his home, in a vicious snowstorm?
</P>
<P>
   Glass knew his innocent and seemingly innocuous deed was against
National Collegiate Athletic Association rules, but he told Perkins
to hop in his rental car anyway. The ride was deemed a recruiting
infraction by the NCAA, the UCLA program was penalized, and Perkins
wound up at North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so ashamed of that violation; it's just going to haunt me
for the rest of my life,'' Glass said Thursday in a phone interview
from New Jersey, his voice thick with sarcasm. ``Honestly, if I had
to give Sam Perkins a ride home in that snowstorm again, I'd do it
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass is on the other side of the fence today. He is a sports
agent, competing for clients like Erick Barkley, the St. John's
sophomore who was grilled by NCAA investigators about his alleged
contact with agents _ and the favors and gifts that come from those
associations.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis, Barkley's coach, has belittled the NCAA as if it
were made up of beat cops more concerned with a double parker than
with a real menace to the neighborhood. Go ahead and include the
street agents posing as Amateur Athletic Union coaches, the people
who put their hooks into these kids during the summer and won't let
go until they turn pro. You can even take umbrage with
underclassmen like Barkley, who may be naive in some ways but
clearly understand how the agent game is played:
</P>
<P>
   Play well, and someone professing to know what you're about
comes around and earns your trust. Says you're better than you are.
Makes you feel good about yourself. Preys on your insecurities
about money and the care of your family.
</P>
<P>
   Until, finally, that young, impressionable kid says: ``Enough
already. I'm going to the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   And the cycle begins anew. Predominantly black young men viewed
as a commodity because they can play basketball, sucked into a
vortex by people claiming to represent their best interests. These
talented players sometimes emerge wealthy, but they rarely come out
of the cycle squeaky clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I called up Mike Jarvis and he agreed to have me sit down
with Erick Barkley after the season, Mike would be naive to believe
that meeting would give me an opportunity to represent him,'' Glass
said. ``That's how it works. There are street agents and regular
agents who will tell these kids whatever they want to hear right
now. Everybody is looking for the quick hit. That's the reality,
but no one wants to deal with that. They'd rather look at the last
person in the door and take them on.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass added: ``That's like saying Billy Hunter or the Dallas
Mavericks are morally responsible for Leon Smith,'' referring to
the rookie who tried to kill himself last November by swallowing
250 aspirin. ``Where were his parents and his educators? Aren't
they to blame?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association held a technology summit
last weekend in San Francisco. Before the All-Star Game, Internet
billionaires like Mark Cuban, the Mavericks' incoming owner,
Shaquille O'Neal and Commissioner David Stern discussed the
emerging cyberworld, employing language like broadband and other
terms that barely resonate with anyone outside the techie
community.
</P>
<P>
   It made you wonder if the league understood that its sport was
ailing. Has anyone given serious thought to a basketball summit, a
weekend think tank about how to fix this system? Bring in the angel
Mike Krzyzewski and the outlaw Jerry Tarkanian and put them on the
same panel. Bring in Sonny Vaccaro, who funnels young, talented
players to agents and universities while running Adidas' premier
national basketball camp. Ask Vaccaro why he insists on telling
teen-agers, emotionally and mentally unprepared for the NBA, that
they should be shown the money today?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had conversations with the NCAA and the NBA, trying to
get people to all come together and do what's best for the sport of
basketball,'' said Isiah Thomas, the owner of the Continental
Basketball Association. ``As opposed to talking about just business
opportunities, the goal would be to move it to a higher ground and
do what's best for these kids. No one seems interested right now.
They want to talk business, but not much else.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens at St. John's, Barkley is hardly the problem.
The problem is a corrupt system in desperate need of repair.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to upgrade your sport utility vehicle or give a
kid a ride home in a snowstorm to understand that. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
