<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTEROID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAILBLAZING CRAFT EXPOSES AN ASTEROID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md., Calif.)   (af)  
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The asteroid Eros, now under the constant gaze of a
satellite from Earth, appears to be both composed of dense material
and battered by many ancient collisions, scientists reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The spacecraft NEAR, which on Monday became the first to orbit
an asteroid, has revealed a rocky surface covered with craters,
ridges, long grooves, large boulders and some surprisingly bright
areas that appear to reflect an unusual amount of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work is just starting, but it's already clear that Eros is
much more exciting and geologically diverse than we had expected,''
said Dr. Andrew F. Cheng, the project's lead scientist at the Johns
Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory in Laurel, Md., which
manages the mission for NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng, speaking at a NASA briefing outlining initial results,
said that the asteroid, a peanut-shaped object measuring about 21
miles long and 9 miles wide at its fattest point, is a moonlike
gray color with a yellowish tint. He said the asteroid appeared to
have layered, stratified features, which could indicate that part
of it once melted while part of a larger body, something probably
the size of the moon or smaller that broke up during the early
formation of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are also tantalizing hints that it has a layered
structure, as if it were made up of layers like in plywood,'' Cheng
said of the early data from NEAR, which stands for Near Earth
Asteroid Rendezvous.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Bell of Cornell University said the spacecraft's
near-infrared spectrometer, which analyzes reflected light for
clues to chemical composition, indicated that most of the
asteroid's surface is covered with pyroxene and olivine, iron and
silicon-bearing minerals commonly found in meteorites and molten
rock.
</P>
<P>
   Better information on the chemical history will come later in
the one-year mission, he said, when the spacecraft moves to a
closer orbit and uses other instruments that can detect
below-surface components.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of the asteroid revealed several bright patches of
lighter colored, unidentified material on the surface. Scientists
said this material, which reflects almost a third more light than
surrounding areas, could be subsurface material ejected from impact
craters.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the spacecraft into orbit and keeping it there are not
simple, said Dr. Donald Yeomans of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory
in California. Eros, with a gravitational pull only one-1,700th as
much as that on Earth, is the smallest object ever orbited by a
spacecraft, requiring the satellite to operate at unusually slow
speeds to stay within the asteroid's gravitational grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Yeomans said the spacecraft approached the asteroid at only 22
miles per hour before breaking rockets placed the craft into a
280-by-200-mile orbit, where it travels at only 2 mph, the speed of
a walking man. By comparison, the space shuttle travels in
low-Earth orbit at 17,000 mph, and satellites in high orbits that
stay above one point on the planet move at 6,700 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Working with such a low-gravity object presents many challenges,
Yeomans said. ``If someone on Earth weighed 200 pounds, they would
weigh about 2 ounces on Eros,'' he said. ``If I could jump three
feet on Earth, I could jump a mile on Eros and almost go into
orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   The irregular shape of the asteroid and these low speeds mean
that engineers have to be very careful as they lower the spacecraft
closer to Eros in coming months for more detailed readings. The
satellite's orbit will go down to 30 miles or below only after the
spacecraft better defines the asteroid's mass and gravity
variations caused by the irregular distribution of this mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2245EST &QL; 
