<HEADLINE>
TWO ARE NOMINATED TO NEW YORK TIMES CO.'S BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The board of The New York Times Co. has nominated an
executive and a psychotherapist for election as directors at its
annual shareholders meeting April 27.
</P>
<P>
   Those nominated were Dr. David E. Liddle, a partner with U.S.
Venture Partners and a retired chairman of Interval Research Corp.,
and Jacqueline H. Dryfoos, a psychotherapist in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Judith P. Sulzberger, who is 76, is retiring from the board.
</P>
<P>
   Liddle, 55, retired from Interval Research in January and joined
U.S. Venture Partners, a Silicon Valley-based venture capital firm
that specializes in developing Internet and electronic commerce
businesses, digital communications and semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   Liddle, a consulting professor of computer science at Stanford
University, founded Interval Research in 1992 with Paul Allen, a
co-founder of Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a bachelor's degree in electrical engineering at the
University of Michigan and a Ph.D. in computer science at the
University of Toledo in Ohio. For his contributions to
human-computer interaction design, he was named a senior fellow of
the Royal College of Art in London.
</P>
<P>
   Dryfoos, 56, has been a psychotherapist in private practice
since 1980. Previously, she was a psychiatric social worker for the
Jewish Board of Family and Children's Services and a social studies
teacher and counselor.
</P>
<P>
   She is on the boards of the Council on the Environment of New
York City and the literary journal Kenyon Review.
</P>
<P>
   Dryfoos earned a bachelor of arts degree from Barnard College; a
master's of arts from Teacher's College, Columbia University; a
master's of science from Columbia University School of Social Work;
and a certificate of psychoanalysis and psychoanalytic
psychotherapy from the Institute of Contemporary Psychotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   She is a daughter of Marian S. Heiskell and Orvil E. Dryfoos,
who was publisher of The Times from 1961 until his death in 1963.
She is a cousin of Arthur Sulzberger Jr., chairman of The New York
Times Co., and Michael Golden, vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to The New York Times, the company publishes The
Boston Globe, 22 regional newspapers and 3 magazines; it operates
television and radio stations and news, photo and graphic services
as well as electronic publishing and new-media businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
