<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS DOES IT RIGHT WITH ITS PICK TO LEAD OLYMPIC BID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting over here on our end of Interstate 30, the smugness is
hard to hide. We know if we ever need anything from the city of
Dallas, it's an easy buy. Like a city councilman. They come cheap
over there.
</P>
<P>
   And with the burial this week of a true legend, have you noticed
who has currently ascended to the position of Dallas' most
high-profile sports citizen?
</P>
<P>
   It's a tall guy, speaking through lip rings and a tongue-stud,
telling the nation he wants to climb into the ring and do combat
with another man _ naked.
</P>
<P>
   It does make us all appreciate that 36 miles of separation.
</P>
<P>
   But there was an announcement this week which truly summed up
where the city of Dallas stands when it comes to sports leadership.
</P>
<P>
   It's this Dallas 2012 thing. The thing to bring the summer
Olympic games to North Texas. The thing that normally would cause a
personal yawn, because when it comes to getting anything done in
sports, Dallas is the Can't-Do-City.
</P>
<P>
   But this project, despite the name, is not just about Dallas.
Plus, it's well financed by many business interests across North
Texas. What had been lacking, however. was a true leader capable of
bringing it all together.
</P>
<P>
   Who you gonna call? Nobody in Can't-Do-Dallas, that's a given.
</P>
<P>
   That call, of course, went to Arlington. One of us has been
chosen to lead them. It figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have just a long-shot chance of the 2012
games coming to our region,'' Richard Greene said. ``My view is
`Why not make us the favorite?' But that's me being me.''
</P>
<P>
   Need something done from a civic standpoint, or otherwise? Then
you do want Greene being Greene.
</P>
<P>
   As the dynamo former mayor of Arlington, Greene finally left
office with an exemplary record of achievement. For one thing, The
Ballpark in Arlington would never have been built without him.
Today, that ballpark is a national model for how a public-private
partnership should work.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Dallas 2012 Committee launched a nationwide search
for the person to be president and CEO of the organization, some 50
to 60 names were compiled.
</P>
<P>
   Except the committee never got past the first interview. That
was Greene, who since leaving the mayor's office had served as the
vice president and associate publisher of the ``Arlington
Star-Telegram.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have asked what I missed most about not being
mayor,'' Greene said. ``My answer was not having the opportunity to
pursue those things which only come around once in life. Well,
that's what this job is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene didn't apply for the job. He even mistakenly thought the
first interview in December was to seek his opinion on top national
applicants. As it turned out, he was the only candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job is immense because the project is immense,'' Greene
said. ``But once it became clear the committee wanted me, my
excitement hasn't ended since.''
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who originally attempted to ignore the local
Olympic endeavor as frivolous, Greene's hiring was an eye-opener.
Particularly if you've witnessed Greene's persuasive powers.
</P>
<P>
   But even before this hire, Dallas 2012 was gaining strength as
one of eight candidates among U.S. cities/regions.
</P>
<P>
   For that, thank Tom Luce, who, yes, is a Dallasite (I didn't say
they were all worthless over there.)
</P>
<P>
   When the bribery scandal broke around Salt Lake City's winning
bid for the Winter Olympics, corporate sponsors started to yank
grass-root-level support for Olympic bids in many cities.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Olympic Committee saw that as a dreaded trend.
But instead, here came Luce, showing the USOC a long and impressive
roster of Fortune 500 companies from across North Texas _ all of
them were ready to go not only with financial support for Dallas
2012, but also by loaning employees to the project.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, this region has emerged as one of the favorites
for 2012.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the eight regions, none are odds-on to win this thing,''
Greene said. ``It's very wide-open, which is good for us. Like one
of our drawbacks is the heat, but the other seven all have their
flaws, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, the list of positives, Greene says, that can
give North Texas the advantage. ``Let's just say we stack up very
favorably with any other region,'' Greene added.
</P>
<P>
   It's not certain a U.S. city will receive the 2012 bid, but in
an unspoken rotation system by the IOC, that would be the time for
the Summer Games to return to this country.
</P>
<P>
   In some opinions, the early favorites in the process are
Tampa-Orlando in Florida, Washington-Baltimore and North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, none of this would have been happening locally if an
ordinary citizen from Arlington, Grady Hicks, hadn't submitted the
region's bid back in 1997, after first convincing city officials to
back him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Arlington's Grady Hicks, we have come a long way,''
said Greene.
</P>
<P>
   But that's typical. We lead. They follow. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
