<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE TO LET DIALLO JURY CONSIDER OPTIONS TO MURDER CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The state judge presiding over the trial of the
four police officers charged with murdering Amadou Diallo said
Thursday that he would accept a request by prosecutors and defense
lawyers to add lesser charges to the two counts of second-degree
murder each officer faces.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling means that the jurors will also be able to consider
the lesser charges of first- and second-degree manslaughter and
criminally negligent homicide during their deliberations. Should
the officers be convicted, the minimum penalties they could face
range from 15 years to life for second-degree murder to probation
for criminally negligent homicide.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing arguments from both the prosecutors and the
defense, Justice Joseph C. Teresi of state Supreme Court also
finalized the legal instruction he will give jurors when they begin
deliberating on the case next week. Defense lawyers won the
language they wanted on several crucial points, and said afterward
that they were pleased; Eric Warner, the lead prosecutor, did not
appear to be.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi said that he would present the jury with two statutes
from New York penal law on when the use of deadly force is
justified. All four officers have testified that they believed
Diallo had a gun and was firing on them or planning to when they
shot him. Nineteen of their 41 bullets struck him.
</P>
<P>
   One of the statutes, Section 35.30, says that a police officer
is justified in using deadly physical force to defend himself or a
third person if he is in the course of making an arrest or
preventing an escape from custody.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution had argued that the statute was not applicable
in this case because the officers had said they merely sought to
question Diallo, not arrest him, when they approached him outside
his apartment building in the Soundview section of the Bronx on
Feb. 4 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi will also instruct the jurors on another statute, Section
35.15, that permits the use of deadly force, and is applicable to
any citizen. The statute says that a citizen may use physical force
if he ``reasonably believes'' it is necessary to defend himself
from attack.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution had sought to bar parts of the statute that
allow the use of deadly physical force when a citizen believes
another person is in the process of committing a crime like as rape
or robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Sean Carroll testified that he believed Diallo was
either a push-in robber or a rapist when he and the other officers
_ Edward McMellon, Richard Murphy and Kenneth Boss _ tried to
question Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi, however, did say that the officers must be judged on the
standard of what the ``average reasonable person'' would do, rather
than on what a ``reasonable police officer'' would do.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling essentially gives jurors two different ways in which
they could find the officers' conduct justified. It also means that
the jurors will not be instructed that the officers had a duty to
retreat if they could do so safely, which most citizens must do.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi also acceded to a defense request to explain state law on
the authority police officers have to approach citizens and request
information. The lawyers for the officers hope that if the law
makes clear that the police have the broad authority to do so,
jurors will not be distracted by weighing whether the officers
should have approached Diallo in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had originally planned to ask the judge to instruct
jurors that they must find every act of deadly force _ meaning each
shot fired _ justified. But as testimony in the trial made clear,
it is virtually impossible to determine which officers fired which
shots, or when in the barrage the fatal shots occurred. In this
instance, then, the number of shots fired appears to have worked to
the officers' advantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2251EST &QL; 
