<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-ROSE-CENTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEW UNIVERSE IN MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, Feb. 18: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday is a day to celebrate the completion and opening of the
Frederick Phineas and Sandra Priest Rose Center for Earth and Space
at the American Museum of Natural History. The architecture of this
new installation is so invigorating, and the imaginative outreach
of the science it presents is so all-engulfing, that it reframes
our sense of the museum itself. The most eloquent summary of the
museum's achievement will be the look on the faces of children _ a
vast, continuous tide of children over the years to come _ as they
leave the new Hayden Planetarium, stunned by a virtual trek from
Earth to the edge of the observable universe, and begin their walk
down a spiraling Cosmic Pathway that leads them from the Big Bang
to the immediate now.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Center reasserts the role of the Museum of Natural
History as a place where primary education and advanced research
intersect. It has to be said again and again just how fresh the
image of the cosmos presented here really is. Thanks to a
remarkable array of tools, chief among them the Hubble telescope,
we now have an unprecedented sense of the universe's origin, its
rate of expansion, its structure. Our new sense of cosmological
dimension is graphically depicted at the Rose Center in a series of
size analogies using the Hayden Sphere as a point of reference.
</P>
<P>
   We are lucky to live in an era graced by such a wealth of new
astronomical and cosmological knowledge, a time when our conception
of the universe takes us to the limits of strangeness and yet
promises to surpass those limits again tomorrow and the day after.
Portraying the outlines of that knowledge is a daunting task. Doing
so in a way that will engage a scientifically illiterate general
public is enormously hard. The wonder of that glass-enclosed sphere
on West 81st Street is great indeed. But its real test is whether
it will be able to transpose ignorance into enlightenment, to turn
incredulity not into wonder or faith but into a collective sense of
the scientific enterprise, an activity that is completed only when
its results reach the minds and intuitions of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   The new Rose Center for Earth and Space reminds us that human
curiosity and inventiveness have driven us to this revolutionary
new understanding of our cosmos. But it also reminds us what a leap
is needed to step from the welter of our daily lives into a place
where the scale, in time and space, of everything we know about
everything can begin to impress us. There is so much knowledge, so
much beauty at the Rose Center, such a rendering of what was
unrenderable until only recently. And yet amid those striking
images of deep space, of galaxy clusters and newly forming stars,
it is a shock to realize, looking up into the dome of the new
planetarium, that they are no more beautiful than the sight of a
deep night sky seen just as humans have always seen it, until we
turned on the lights. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
