<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-GORDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON, ONCE TOP DOG, IS DAYTONA UNDERDOG
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ A Winston Cup Series overall champion at
age 24. Two more Winston Cup titles in the next three years. That
was the distinctive swath that Jeff Gordon was cutting through
NASCAR. Then suddenly he blew a tire on his fast track to
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon won seven Winston Cup races last year, more than anybody,
but there were two troubling developments. His valued crew chief,
Ray Evernham, bolted in late September to spearhead Dodge's entry
into NASCAR. And after two quick victories following that
departure, Gordon did not finish higher than 10th in his final five
races. He wound up sixth in points.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the first Winston Cup race of the new year on Sunday,
people here for the Daytona 500 are wondering if Gordon can
recapture the magic that he and Evernham produced: 47 victories in
five years, including the Daytona 500 in two of the last three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The new crew chief is Robbie Loomis, who left Richard Petty
Enterprises after nine years for the chance to work with Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure a lot of people doubt us,'' said Gordon, who, by his
own account, got stale last season after a spectacular 1998 that
saw him win 13 races. ``But we've got a team that really is
enjoying working together. I think Robbie is just the guy we
needed. I told him right off the bat: `Don't treat me like a
three-time Winston Cup champion. Treat me with some respect, of
course, but don't ever be reluctant to tell me what I need to
hear.'''
</P>
<P>
   Loomis said he must learn what Gordon is thinking during races.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can tell me what the car's doing and he can tell me what
he's feeling, and I can make changes based on that,'' Loomis said.
``But it's those things he's not saying is what a crew chief has to
figure out. You've got to be able to get inside a guy's head.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why some think it may take a year before the Gordon team
can challenge again for the Winston Cup. Loomis even believes it
might not necessarily be a bad thing for Gordon's No. 24 Chevrolet
to struggle some early this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to grow, you have to go through hard times,'' he said.
``A lot of times, what happens is when you start out, things go
pretty good, maybe not as good as they need to, and it's hard to
get to where you need to until you go through some hard times
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-ANALYSIS18-COX     02-17 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ANALYSIS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How Bush got out-Bushed
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONWAY, S.C. _ In so many ways, on so many days, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona has turned out to be the Republican presidential
candidate Gov. George W. Bush was supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was supposed to be a new kind of Republican, a
``compassionate conservative'' who could unite the GOP's
conservative and moderate wings, then appeal to a broad range of
voters in November. Then came McCain, campaigning as a Republican
populist who could rally independents and build new coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush faces a crucial election day Saturday in South Carolina,
he finds himself cast as the old guard, the party insider, the
right wing _ even though he and McCain are virtually identical on
the issues. And McCain has become many things Bush was supposed to
be, not only on policy and politics, but on personality and style.
</P>
<P>
   The preconceived Bush path to the White House led down the more
moderate center of the Republican Party, a strategy designed to put
Bush in the political middle where most of America lives. The goal
_ typified by positions such as refusing to promise to appoint
judges who share his opposition to abortion rights _ was to avoid
the wide-right veer some believe is necessary to win the GOP
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The centrist strategy worked well for a while. The right-wing
candidates faded away. Pat Buchanan, gone. Dan Quayle, gone. Gary
Bauer, gone. Steve Forbes, gone. With all the candidates who
painted themselves as the true conservative alternative to Bush out
of the race, a new candidate with the true conservative tag
emerged: Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to that position because McCain, pitching campaign
finance reform and building a coalition that includes
non-Republicans and takes advantage of open primaries in early
states, became what Bush was supposed to be: the atypical
Republican attracting new faces to the party. McCain drew them in
unpollable numbers in New Hampshire, which he won by a surprising
18 points, and is trying to rally them here.
</P>
<P>
   It has left Bush hoping for the kind of relatively small turnout
Saturday that would mean only real Republicans are voting in the
GOP primary. But because South Carolina Democrats are not holding a
primary _ they will choose delegates by caucus next month _ and
because South Carolinians do not register by party, the GOP primary
is open to all comers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats and Independents CAN vote in Saturday's primary!''
McCain's literature proclaims. Independents are flocking to his
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on the other hand, has used South Carolina to shore up
support from party loyalists. He picked up Quayle's endorsement and
spoke at Bob Jones University upon arrival, an appearance he was
still defending Thursday. The university, a Christian
fundamentalist school that prohibits interracial dating, is not the
best venue for a candidate who boasts about how well he ran among
Hispanics and African-Americans in the 1998 gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it was merely an exercise in talking to voters and had
nothing to do with endorsing the school's policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aware of the interracial dating policy before I
walked in there,'' Bush said Thursday, noting that he denounced the
policy when asked about it after the speech.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has not been invited to Bob Jones. But if he were, McCain
has said, he would say, ``Look, what you're doing in this ban on
interracial dating, is stupid, it's idiotic, and it is incredibly
cruel to many people.''
</P>
<P>
   The final certification of Bush as the conservative he was never
supposed to be came last Sunday when he was endorsed by Christian
Coalition founder Pat Robertson, who said he would never back
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's status as the candidate Bush was supposed to be also
shows up on personality. Bush, as affable a politician as there is,
was supposed to be the candidate with whom you'd most like to have
dinner. Even folks who think he is not the brightest bulb in the
fixture as well as those who don't agree with him issue by issue
acknowledge the affability factor.
</P>
<P>
   But it's McCain who seems more at ease with himself on the
stump, pops the irreverent one-liners on his campaign bus and has a
life story compelling enough for Hollywood, which has bought the
rights for his autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also has surpassed Bush as the perceived darling of the
media. For months, people complained that Bush was getting a free
ride from the press. By last week, McCain had become a cover boy
several times over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great sucking sound you hear is the media's lips coming
off of John McCain's (behind),'' Marvin Bush, the governor's
brother, said on a South Carolina campaign flight.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also has worked to steal Bush's thunder as a positive
campaigner. As he did in his two gubernatorial races, Bush entered
this battle promising to run a ``hopeful, positive'' campaign in
which he would not attack his opponent. Both had negative ads up
for awhile. McCain dropped his. Bush, accusing McCain of starting
the attacks, did not. Regardless of who started it, Bush now is the
only candidate with TV ads attacking his foe.
</P>
<P>
   In the end _ again somewhat improbably _ McCain is having some
success at portraying Bush as something he was never supposed to
be: a Washington insider. Though he's been in Washington for 18
years, McCain's trademark campaign finance reform issue, combined
with Bush's big money and big-name endorsements, have allowed the
Arizona senator to position himself as the outsider.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reminds people that he lives in Austin, not Washington. But
he is genetically challenged in trying to portray himself as an
outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are the son of a former president just once removed,
it's impossible to claim you're the outsider,'' said University of
Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato.
</P>
<P>
   As the primary season builds toward its crescendo, McCain also
has chipped deeply into something else that was supposed to be
Bush's franchise: November electability. A New York Times/CBS News
poll released Thursday shows that Bush, who soared in earlier
polls, is now disliked by as many people who like him. McCain's
favorable ratings are triple his unfavorables. The poll shows that
voters do not link Bush with any set of policies.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, as well as in the overall battle to be played
out in coming weeks, Bush may win and he may lose. But regardless
of how it comes out, he can no longer become the kind of candidate
he was supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
