<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000217.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0425 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-VOICES18-COX     02-17 2687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-VOICES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain at zero hour
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Traveling with a candidate often is the worst
place in the world to try to get perspective on him. Reporters are
taught to be wary of crowds, to take with a grain of salt the
enthusiastic response of a candidate's most fervent supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But when 1,500 Clemson University students turn out to listen to
a 63-year-old man tell a bunch of corny jokes on a Wednesday night,
something is going on.
</P>
<P>
   When a couple of Democrats who oppose John McCain on virtually
every social issue take their lunch hour to cheer him on in
Greenville, S.C., something is going on.
</P>
<P>
   When more than 1,000 Atlantans wait in line for hours on a cold
Sunday afternoon to get McCain's autograph, something is going on.
</P>
<P>
   And the polls reflect what the traveling press sees on the
ground. The one-time dark horse is now running with the leader, at
least in the early states.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, advisers to McCain and George W. Bush say
their polling shows the race is a dead heat and voter turnout in
Saturday's primary will make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   McCain leads Bush 43 percent to 34 percent in Michigan, which
has a primary three days after South Carolina. The Detroit News
poll conducted last week has an error margin of 4 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, which holds its primary the same day as Michigan,
the news is even better for McCain. An Arizona Republic telephone
poll conducted Saturday through Wednesday shows McCain with 52
percent and Bush 29 percent. The poll has a margin of error of plus
or minus 3.4 percentage points. In October, the newspaper's poll
showed Bush leading McCain 40 percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush still has a comfortable though shrinking lead in national
polls. But McCain's strategy was to concentrate on New Hampshire _
which he won convincingly _ and then on South Carolina, believing
victories in those early states would begin to undo the Bush
campaign and translate into support elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   McCain supporters point to Michigan, where McCain has campaigned
little, as evidence the strategy is working.
</P>
<P>
   And support for McCain is building outside the early-primary
states, partially fueled by something past insurgents like Gary
Hart did not did not have _ the Internet. Online, McCain has raised
more than $5 million and attracted 115,000 volunteers across the
country. Since New Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary, McCain has raised
$3.5 million via the Internet, campaign manager Rick Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   This achievement hardly compares to the massive organization and
resources of his front-running rival, but it is more than anyone
expected a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   How long this surge will continue is unknown. A defeat Saturday
in South Carolina could begin to turn the tide.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, McCain is involved in a Republican
nomination struggle the intensity of which has not been seen in 20
years, when Ronald Reagan challenged President Ford.
</P>
<P>
   For a look at what's fueling some of that intensity, here are
reports from Cox Newspaper listening posts across the country:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: AURA OVER ISSUES?
</P>
<P>
   It sometimes seems the McCain campaign is a case of aura over
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Suzi Bergsman was standing in the Peachtree Battle Shopping
Center parking lot Sunday, along with more than a thousand other
people who have come to have McCain sign copies of his book ``Faith
of My Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   She is more liberal than McCain on social issues, including
abortion. But she does not accept McCain is as opposed to abortion
rights as he says he is and his voting record indicates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came to his family, he said it's an individual's
choice. He said it would be a family decision,'' Bergsman recalled
McCain saying in January.
</P>
<P>
   Told that McCain supports a constitutional amendment to ban
abortion in most cases, Bergsman said, ``I'm pro-choice, but I'm
not a litmus-test voter.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bergsman offered again why she likes McCain: ``You know
where he stands,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people who file through the book store for an
autograph and a brief word with McCain are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   John Sours, McCain's Georgia chairman, is not surprised. He has
been inundated by telephone calls since his candidate won the New
Hampshire primary. About a third of the callers are Democrats, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy has excited more Democrats than anyone since Ronald
Reagan,'' Sours said.
</P>
<P>
   One of those former Reagan Democrats currently enamored of
McCain is Wayne Merisotis, an Atlanta attorney. ``He is the
strongest candidate the Republican party has offered since Dwight
David Eisenhower. He is a man of heroic proportions,'' Merisotis
said of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The staunchest Democrat in the line may be Lawton Bowling, a
retired psychiatrist from Marietta who has not voted Republican in
more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this Roosevelt Democrat is supporting McCain because he does
not think the Democrats will take on McCain's favorite bogeyman,
the ``special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fact is, I don't think they'll do anything to hurt them,''
Bowling said. ``And I want them hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Sherman
</P>
<P>
   OHIO: A SPECIAL TIE
</P>
<P>
   David Ford, volunteer chairman of McCain's presidential campaign
in Ohio, has a special link to the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   From 1967 to 1973, they were both prisoners of war in North
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has got 30 days longevity on me,'' Ford said. ``And I
told him he can keep every one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford and McCain met when the peace agreements were signed and
they were released from their cells in Hanoi. McCain was
characteristically irreverent.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we just slammed each other because we were both
Irish,'' Ford recalled. ``He calls me the shanty Irishman. I call
him the lace curtain Irishman.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford retired from the Air Force in 1984 as a lieutenant colonel.
He had never been involved in politics _ until McCain's campaign
called in November and asked him aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first comment was `I know nothing about politics.' They
said, `You know how to organize.' I can do that, absolutely,'' Ford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since November, Ford has been working full time, without pay, to
build a network of McCain supporters throughout the state. McCain's
national co-chairman, U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine, has provided
invaluable help, Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   And recently, those efforts have picked up. Ford says he's
gotten as many as 200 e-mails a day, and in one 36-hour period he
received 87 phone calls. He estimates McCain's team now has about
1,000 volunteers, organized in Ohio's 19 congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that activity translates into votes remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   State party leaders and election officials said they have not
seen much evidence of a significant crossover effort in advance of
the March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Clark County Republican Party Chairman Dan Harkins said party
leaders are more focused on local races, ``but from what I'm
hearing they're pulling for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But longtime McCain supporter George M. McCann, a 77-year-old
retired pharmacist and World War II veteran in Springfield, said,
``I don't know anybody sending contribution checks at this point,
but the people that I talk with are just amazed at what has
happened. I think that a lot of people are having their minds
changed that probably last March would have thought that McCain was
a voice crying in the wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   _ William Hershey, Anthony Gottschlich
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: DESPITE LONG ODDS ...
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who won 68 percent of the vote in his 1998 bid for a
second term as Texas governor, isn't in any danger of losing the
March 14 primary in his home state. But McCain backers in the Lone
State State, like those across the country, say their candidate has
gotten a large boost from his victory in New Hampshire and the
closeness of the South Carolina race.
</P>
<P>
   ``My e-mail and my phone mail are just filled up _ it's amazing
what this is doing,'' said Hylan Lyon, an executive at Marlow
Industries, a high-tech company in Dallas. Lyon, who was a
classmate of McCain's at the Naval Academy and a pilot during the
Vietnam War, is heading the McCain effort in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Republican party of Texas should be glad this is
happening because it's bringing people in who haven't been involved
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice-weekly meetings in Dallas that used to draw from 10 to 20
people now draw 40 to 50, according to Lyon. He traces the
increased interest to ``a basic human desire to not be cynical
about the government.''
</P>
<P>
   There are groups of McCain supporters in every major Texas city,
he said, but he couldn't say exactly how many of them there are.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Binder, a former Austin City Council member who is
organizing McCain supporters in the capital, said many of them are
former Bush backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them don't like the tactics he's using, the way he's
changed since he left Texas,'' Binder said, referring to Bush's
attacks on McCain in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Binder said Texans supporting McCain are Republicans, Democrats
and independents who are attracted by the senator's war record and
his interest in reducing the influence of money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's the only one who is across the board trying to stop
big money from controlling the decisions in Washington,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long odds, Binder wouldn't discount the possibility
of a McCain victory in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got a good chance. I talk to more people who say
they're for McCain but they don't want to say it here in Bush
country,'' Binder said. ``There are a lot of people who are talking
Bush but are going to be voting for McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   If the McCain surge seems to have reached Dallas and Austin, it
is not registering in some other Texas locales.
</P>
<P>
   In Waco, M.A. Taylor, McLennan County's GOP chairman, said he
hasn't heard many people talk about the sudden jump in media
attention to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   He's not sure at this point what to believe and what not to
believe. ``I don't have any real good feel for what's happening,''
he said. ``Talking like a poker game, McCain was pretty much on his
last spade and he gambled and laid it all on the line in New
Hampshire, and it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he wasn't aware of any local increase in
contributions to McCain's campaign. A Waco retiree says he can't
understand why the outcome of one state's primary should affect the
way another state votes, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along I don't care how the people in South
Carolina vote, I'm gonna vote for Bush,'' Walter Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   But about 60 miles from Waco, Helen Dozier, GOP chairwoman of
Bosque County, said she believes the Republican establishment is
getting antsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people are taking it a little bit like, 'Let's
see what happens in South Carolina.' I don't think a loss there
would kill Bush, but it would certainly make his work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Marshall, in East Texas, seem to be either
unfamiliar with McCain or in favor of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Bush person,'' said Guinlyn Nash, owner of a local book
store. She said she chooses not to listen to the media's claim that
McCain is a threat to Bush's nomination. ``I'm just not swayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Antiques store owner Frank Shumaker, a registered Democrat, said
that as an ex-veteran he has respect for McCain as a prisoner of
war, but the negative campaigning has turned him off.
</P>
<P>
   And he said Democrats and independents registering as
Republicans to try to secure the nomination for McCain isn't fair.
``It seems to me to go against the whole theory of politics,''
Shumaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Will Hagle, a senior at East Texas Baptist University and a
native of Hallsville, said he doesn't like McCain, ``mainly because
he's running against Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   He often watches the candidate debates, along with his roommate
and college friends, and at this point he's not too worried about
McCain's victory in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think New Hampshire's messed up anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Greenberger, Rebecca Wyatt, Pat Walker
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON: THE `REAL FEAR'
</P>
<P>
   Ed Henry, a co-editor of Roll Call, a Washington newspaper that
covers Capitol Hill, was holding court in one corner of the
bleached wood bar at the swanky George Hotel, playing the McCain
``what-if'' game, a favorite pastime in a company town where
politics often takes on the manner of a parlor game.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time the ``what-if'' question was not whether George
W. Bush would choose John McCain as a vice presidential running
mate, but whether McCain would choose Bush as his.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if it flips and even though they hate each other, Bush
has to accept the VP nod for the party?'' asked Henry of the
Washington politicos gathered to celebrate the launch a new
political Web site. After all, LBJ and Kennedy hated each other, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Or what if McCain has to select a governor because 44 of the 55
Republicans in the Senate have snubbed him in favor of Bush?
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture. The buzz is high on McCain, mainly because
reporters admire him for standing up to the Republican leadership
on issues such as tobacco and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's real fear, real fear that the Republican
machine is going to beat him,'' said Arianna Huffington, a
Republican columnist and commentator. ``Their determination to beat
him is the final proof that our system is really broken. McCain is
about removing the corruption and that is why the people love him
and the senators don't.''
</P>
<P>
   John Sununu, a former governor of New Hampshire who is backing
Bush, seemed less concerned about McCain's prospects for the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans are saying it's a shame that he's not
espousing Republican principles,'' Sununu said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get Sununu wrong. By his book, McCain runs a good
campaign, having captured the primary in the state Sununu once
governed. But as Sununu sees it, McCain simply rewrote the play
book of ``See me, touch me, feel me'' politicking, which was
drafted by others.
</P>
<P>
   What about McCain's chances?
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's volatile vote market, anyone can beat anyone
else,'' Sununu said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate and House aides mingling at the get-together said the
word is out on the Hill to let the media know about McCain's famous
temper and reasons why he shouldn't be president. In other words,
spin as many anti-McCain tales as they can. All anonymously, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a genuine hatred on the Republican side of McCain,''
said Tony Blankley, Newt Gingrich's former press secretary. ``Among
the reasons why they don't like him is the media likes him. And
that goes to the old saying: The friend of my enemy is my enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rebecca Carr
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: A MORAL DILEMMA
</P>
<P>
   McCain poses a moral dilemma for Pete Hautzinger, a deputy chief
district attorney and chairman of the Mesa County Democratic Party
in Western Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Hautzinger hopes the Arizona senator loses the
presidential primary because he thinks Bush is more beatable in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   But, like unaffiliated voters and even some Democrats across the
county, Hautzinger is intrigued by McCain's upstart campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me would like them to nominate someone who I think
would be a pretty darn good president, and that's what McCain's
starting to look like to me,'' Hautzinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Mesa County residents haven't quite decided which
Republican they will support in Colorado's March 10 primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure respect (McCain) but I'm not sure if I'd vote for
him,'' said John Pritchard, a Steve Forbes supporter who has also
contributed money to McCain and Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,200 volunteers are working for McCain in Colorado,
said Barbara Masonheimer, state coordinator for the McCain
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying that they don't like that Bush was anointed,''
Masonheimer said. ``They don't like being told what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Barker
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
