clients of
the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Feb. 18. If you have any
questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602) 444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BAPTIST (Phoenix) - Investors in the Baptist Foundation of Arizona
could expect to receive about 40 cents on the dollar under a
liquidation plan being filed today in U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
</P>
<P>
   That amount could increase considerably _ possibly by enough to
repay the entire $590 million owed to investors _ if a major
lawsuit against former BFA officials and their lawyers and
accountants is successful. By HAL MATTERN. Story will move in the
`A' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GAMBLE (Phoenix) _John McCain's recent opposition to gambling in
South Carolina belies strong financial support from the gaming
industry and McCain's personal affinity for playing the tables.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has received $69,312 in campaign contributions from the
gaming industry, according to data provided by the Center for
Responsive Politics, a non-profit research group in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   According to the CRP, Texas Gov. George W. Bush received the
most from casino and gambling interests: $95,450. Of the Democrats,
Vice President Al Gore received $25,250 and former New Jersey
Senator Bill Bradley received $8,500. By KRIS MAYES and BILL
MULLER. Story will move in the `A` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AZPOLL (Phoenix) _ John McCain and Al Gore can expect to win their
Arizona presidential primary contests handily, and if the general
election were held now, McCain would crush either of his possible
Democratic opponents in the state, the Arizona Republic Poll showed
Thursday. By JON KAMMAN. Story will move in the `A` category. &QL;
</P>
