<SLUG> BC-RAC-FOUNTAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERBY HOPEFULS MEET FOR FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ It is still nearly three months and many
adventures away, but the Kentucky Derby cast its spell across the
country's leading 3-year-old horses Thursday when 11 candidates
were entered in the $200,000 Fountain of Youth Stakes, the first
Grade I race for Derby hopefuls in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The race will be run on Saturday at Gulfstream Park with D.Wayne
Lukas returning to the stage with the 3-1 early favorite, High
Yield, followed by Nick Zito and Greenwood Lake (4-1) and Shug
McGaughey with Polish Miner (5-1). They will run a mile and a
sixteenth, but beyond that, they will be aiming for the Florida
Derby and other landmarks on the road to the Kentucky Derby on May
6.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 colts who entered the Fountain of Youth did not include
several superstars, notably More Than Ready, the speedball whose
career began with five straight victories last fall and whose first
race of the year ended in a grinding dead heat with Summer Note in
the Hutcheson three weeks ago. The strain of the race removed
Summer Note from racing for three months with a stretched tendon,
and More Than Ready was removed from the Fountain of Youth Thursday
for a softer spot.
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone. Also absent from the Fountain of Youth will
be half a dozen of the leading candidates in the West, led by
Anees, winner of the Breeders' Cup Juvenile last fall and the
Eclipse Award as the top 2-year-old colt, who has just returned to
training after sustaining a foot injury; War Chant, who has raced
only twice and is being aimed toward the San Rafael at Santa Anita
on March 4, and Captain Steve, the Bob Baffert-trained colt who is
headed for the Louisiana Derby on March 12.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Red Bullet, the prodigy of Frank Stronach's barn
at Gulfstream Park, who will try to become the first horse in a
century to win the Derby without racing at the age of 2. And one of
the strongest fillies in years, Surfside, a daughter of Seattle
Slew trained by Lukas on the West Coast, will try to become the
fourth filly to win the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   She had a close call but won the Las Virgenes last Saturday, but
Lukas said he was committed to her for the Santa Anita Oaks on
March 12, the Santa Anita Derby four weeks later and the Kentucky
Derby four weeks after that. Surfside has won six of her eight
starts and does not seem to be the type who will be intimidated by
colts.
</P>
<P>
   The Fountain of Youth may be the stepping stone to the classics,
but Thunder Gulch was the only horse in the '90s who won both the
Fountain of Youth and the Kentucky Derby. But Lukas flew into
Florida Thursday brimming with confidence about the chances of High
Yield, who flew in from California three days ago with Cash Run,
the likely favorite in Sunday's Davona Dale Stakes for fillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both shipped here for the Breeders' Cup last fall and
handled it well,'' Lukas said. ``So far, they've shipped here and
handled it well this winter. They're both ready, and I'm looking
for both of them to run well,''
</P>
<P>
   High Yield ran third in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile at Gulfstream
Park last November, and Cash Run won the Juvenile Fillies,
outrunning the undefeated Chilukki. So, neither was a stranger to
the track or the climate.
</P>
<P>
   This year's class of 3-year-olds has not yet produced a dominant
horse, or even a leader. And Gulfstream Park was taking no chances
on losing any of the contenders to other tracks, so it raised the
purse of an allowance race Saturday to $75,000 and listed it at a
mile and a sixteenth, the same distance as the Fountain of Youth.
The maneuver drew five colts, four of whom won or placed in stakes
last year.
</P>
<P>
   McGaughey, facing the option of running Polish Miner in the
Fountain or the allowance, elected Thursday morning to run in the
Fountain. His colt won a tough allowance at Gulfstream in his last
start, on Jan. 29, and ran second in the Nashua and third in the
Remsen at Aqueduct in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just galloped him a mile and a half,'' McGaughey said, ``and
I think that's where he belongs. He's ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood Lake was keeping a low profile, with redemption on his
agenda. The colt won the Champagne and the Remsen in New York, but
in his debut this year, he ran a dull sixth in the Holy Bull at
Gulfstream Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
