<SLUG> BC-SC-BUSH-QUESTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LEFT IN WANT OF A WAND AS QUESTIONERS LOOK FOR HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. _ For a few seconds, Gov. George W. Bush
sounded less like a presidential candidate than a charity
auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I hear a bidder?'' he asked an audience at Coastal Carolina
University here Thursday afternoon after a partially blind biology
student complained that neither she nor the school could afford
$400 for a device that would enable her to use a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   Someone raised his hand, and the matter was settled. But Bush
had not addressed the student's questions about people with
disabilities, and what lingered was a sense that he and his
compassionate conservatism had been caught short.
</P>
<P>
   It had happened earlier in the day as well, at a campaign event
in Florence. A woman stood to say that her medical insurance did
not cover all the needs of her son, who had a chronic,
life-threatening illness. What would Bush do?
</P>
<P>
   The candidate, who has yet to articulate a comprehensive health
plan, seemed stumped. He sang the praises of medical savings
accounts, then acknowledged that it was too late for the woman to
start one and that he really had no specific remedy for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' he said. ``I wish I could wave a wand.''
</P>
<P>
   The student in Myrtle Beach, Christine Green, 26, was not asking
Bush for charity. Her description of her frustration with not
having certain equipment came in the context of a broader concern
about the government's assistance to disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, whose philosophy often stresses private solutions over
public ones, bypassed the big picture to bore in on this one
detail. He asked her how much the device cost.
</P>
<P>
   She said $400.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet somebody right here in this audience may stand up and
help you,'' Bush predicted. Correctly, it turned out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
