A0562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-KIMES-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      02-17 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KIMES-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS SAYS TENANT WORRIED MISSING WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A caretaker for an Upper East Side woman testified
Thursday that his employer was worried from the day she rented an
apartment to the man now accused, with his mother, of murdering her
in a plot to steal her $10 million mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, Mengistu Melesse, who worked for Irene Silverman
for six years until her disappearance in 1998, described the man,
Kenneth Kimes, as a difficult and suspicious tenant throughout the
22 days he rented an apartment in Silverman's town house under an
assumed name, Manny Guerin. Kimes and his mother, Sante, are on
trial in state Supreme Court in Manhattan, accused of a complicated
plot against Silverman, whose body has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   Melesse said that when he came to work on Monday, June 15, 1998,
Silverman told him to watch the new tenant. ``She said, `Mengi,
there is a young man who moved in yesterday,''' Melesse testified.
```His name is Manny and he looked like he just stepped out of
jail.'''
</P>
<P>
   Melesse testified that Kimes initially refused to allow him into
his apartment to water the houseplants and began entering the town
house in a strange manner. Melesse said Kimes came in and out of
the apartment by slinking along the wall, hiding his face from the
security camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the monitor and said, `Mrs. Silverman, look how he
comes in,' and she said, `Low-class jerk,''' Melesse testified.
</P>
<P>
   On the witness stand, Melesse described his last conversations
with Silverman in detail, sprinkling his testimony with asides
about her ``beloved houseplants'' and her ``beautiful boxer,''
Georgie.
</P>
<P>
   Melesse portrayed Kimes as a nervous man who rubbed his hands
together compulsively and lurked by the peephole in his apartment.
He said Kimes peppered him with questions about the staff's work
schedule, tried to get him to slack off and urged him to quit his
job. Melesse added that Kimes referred to Silverman with a
derogatory term.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, which will cross-examine Melesse on Friday,
prevented some of his warnings about Kimes from being shared with
the jury and had the judge strike the caretaker's testimony that
Silverman would sell the house only ``over her dead body.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were allowed to question Melesse about many of his
conversations with Silverman about Kimes. Ann Donnelly, one of the
prosecutors, argued that Melesse's testimony was critical to
disproving the defense's potential argument that the Kimeses were
friends with Silverman and that she wanted to give her house to
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shows she would not willingly transfer her home to them,
they knew it and there was only one way to get rid of her,''
Donnelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Melesse said that the relationship between Kimes and the staff
grew more tense on June 25, the day before the caretaker was due to
leave for what was supposed to be a two-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman confronted Kimes about his true identity and asked why
he had failed to turn in an application that she had given him for
the apartment. Kimes responded first that he had given it to his
lawyer to review, and then said he had given it to another
employee, Melesse said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `That's a lie,''' Melesse testified. ``I saw his
face change, and his ears flushing.''
</P>
<P>
   As Melesse spoke, a few feet away at the defense table, Kimes'
face turned red.
</P>
<P>
   The caretaker testified that after another brief exchange, Kimes
walked off, and Silverman turned to Melesse and called her tenant a
thief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Shhh, he'll listen.' She said, `I don't care, this is
my house, I'll stay in my house, and he'll have to go,''' Melesse
said.
</P>
<P>
   On June 26, Melesse said, he left for his first-ever vacation
and did not speak to Silverman again until he called the house on
July 4 from Atlanta. Silverman told him she was concerned about
Kimes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `I am worried, I want you to come home, I want you
to come tomorrow,''' Melesse testified. ``I said, `I will come back
and protect you.''' But when he called the house the next day, he
said, a police detective answered the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever talk to her again?'' asked Connie Fernandez, a
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Frowning, Melesse answered, ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
