<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-HISTORICAL-SOCIETY     02-17 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-HISTORICAL-SOCIETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE UNEARTHED INSIDE STAMFORD HISTORICAL SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ It has been the kind of civil trial normally
associated with huge corporations: five weeks of mind-numbing
testimony on bylaws and parliamentary procedure, reams of meeting
minutes and financial statements, and long discourses on dates of
record and proxy votes.
</P>
<P>
   But the proceedings that drew to a close in state Superior Court
here this week did not involve a high-stakes hostile takeover or a
class action by shareholders. Rather, they were the outgrowth of a
fight for control of the all-volunteer board of directors of the
Stamford Historical Society, a 99-year-old organization with at
best 360 members in a corporate mecca hardly known for its
reverence for history.
</P>
<P>
   What was expected to be a three-day trial has turned into a
five-week ordeal, all over an organization whose best-attended
exhibits hang in a local shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the meager prize, passions have only grown on both
sides and are likely to continue simmering in anticipation of the
court's ruling sometime next month. Each side has a team of lawyers
who are preparing their final written arguments, now that the
courtroom theater is over.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of his closing argument Wednesday afternoon, Glenn
A. Gazin, a lawyer for the defendants, seemed to embrace the
absurdity of it all by conceding a central allegation: that the
insurgent group he represents had conspired to take control of the
society by drawing up a list of potential board members to nominate
and approve in a suprise move last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say they did put together a list of 19 people who they think
would be good directors, so what?'' shouted Gazin, a former
magician whose animated features give him a cartoonish quality.
``So what?'' he shouted, throwing his hands in the air and raising
the eyebrows of the judge, William F. Hickey. ``I have been waiting
to say this for five weeks: `So what?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gazin's point was that his clients did nothing illegal. But more
telling about his remark is that no one said ``so what'' sooner,
underscoring that there are real issues at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are valid legal questions about the governance of
nonprofit organizations like the historical society, nonstock
corporations that rarely if ever come to the attention of state
regulators and whose meetings are often little more than a
kaffeeklatsch of old neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the heart of the struggle is a debate over what the
primary mission of a historical society should be.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is Walter Wheeler III, the president of the society,
who sued the insurgents after they tried to oust him. Wheeler, 75,
who has often worn a sweater and bow tie to court, conceded that he
represented the society's old guard, but said they take a modern
view. Recent exhibits have included artwork by public school
students and a display on the history of blacks in baseball in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made this more than a nice old house of antiquities,''
Wheeler said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side is a group led by Patricia Kane, 56, a
Stamford lawyer who is on the board of directors. A mix of
dissatisfied old members and new members hoping to clean house,
Kane's group say some of the contemporary exhibits have been a
waste of money and that the public rarely gets to see the society's
most prized holdings, including the Hoyt-Barnum House, an
18th-century residence that is seldom open, and a collection of
Federal-period furniture that is mostly locked away in the
society's stone headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Kane and her supporters say Wheeler has depleted the society's
investment fund, which they say should be an endowment and should
not go toward operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it about? Mismanagement,'' Kane said. She has produced
a report showing that historical societies in surrounding smaller
towns have larger memberships and healthier finances.
</P>
<P>
   But the issues in court have been far less philosophical,
focusing on whether Kane's group had the right under the bylaws and
state law to nominate new board members from the floor of the
annual meeting then vote them in even after Wheeler adjourned the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In the sort of loud exchange that has been typical in this
trial, Hickey shouted angrily at the lawyers, ``I will not listen
to foolishness,'' then allowed three more hours of incomprehensible
testimony from an expert parliamentarian on Robert's Rules of
Order.
</P>
<P>
   When a witness became tongue-tied, Edward V. O'Hanlan, the
lawyer representing Wheeler, asked her: ``Did you say hysterical
society?'' At another point, O'Hanlan, gripping a copy of Robert's
Rules, shouted, ``This is snake oil!''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping that the judge rules on a strict legal grounds, O'Hanlan
in his summation laid out a careful argument, tied to Connecticut
law on nonstock corporations, that most of the insurgents were not
eligible to vote. Even if Judge Hickey agrees, he could still order
a new vote.
</P>
<P>
   While many have warned that the dispute could kill the society,
some believe there is a silver lining.
</P>
<P>
   ``That it's gone on so long is bizarre,'' said Linda Baulsir,
the society's executive director and one of its three full-time
paid staff members. ``The interesting thing is that the historical
society means something in this town. Whatever the outcome is, it's
proof there is a passion for history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
