<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-17 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BUDDHIST-LAMA-ART-575     02-17 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDDHIST-LAMA-ART-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODSTOCK BUDDHIST MONASTERY PREPARES FOR HOLY YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, N.Y. _ The Buddhists on Overlook Mountain are
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   In late December, one of Tibetan Buddhism's highest-ranking
lamas, a 14-year-old monk known as the 17th Karmapa, made a
spectacular flight from his Chinese keepers in Tibet. Ever since,
the monastery here that was designed to be his home in the West has
been filled with joy and anticipation. Its 30 members are expecting
him to visit within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a hope, that's a definite,'' said Bardor Tulku
Rinpoche, one of two high Tibetan lamas at Woodstock. The site of
the monastery, on a wooded slope above the town, in terrain
remarkably similar to the Himalayan foothills that have nurtured
Tibetan Buddhism for centuries, was chosen by the 16th Karmapa
before he died while visiting the United States in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   While the shrine was being built, a boy was born in Tibet in
1985 whom Buddhists later accepted as the Karmapa's reincarnation.
The child, Ugyen Trinley Dorje, was officially recognized in 1992
as the 17th Karmapa, the leader of the Karma Kagyu lineage, not
only by a majority of that school but also by the Dalai Lama, the
leader of all Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
   After fleeing from the Tsurphu monastery near Lhasa, the Tibetan
capital, on Dec. 28, the boy arrived unannounced eight days later
at the exile headquarters of the Dalai Lama in Dharmsala, India. He
said that he fled in part because he had been barred from traveling
outside Tibet to study with older lamas in exile. He has requested
asylum from the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
   No one can be sure how long that will take, but at the Woodstock
monastery, the Karma Triyana Dharmachakra Center, expectations run
high that within a year the young leader will be coming to the
United States as his predecessor did, believing that there is
fertile ground here for Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   The main exile seat of the Karma Kagyu Buddhists is still at
Rumtek, in Sikkim, a Buddhist kingdom annexed by India in 1975. But
the community at Woodstock is prepared to offer the Karmapa an
alternative home, and there are hopes that he will become the first
major Asian religious figure to be based largely in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 16th Karmapa established his main seat in America because
of his vision of the future,'' said Bardor Tulku Rinpoche, a
Tibetan exile who was sent to the United States by the 16th Karmapa
two decades ago. The Woodstock center plans to break ground next
year on a $5 million monastic compound around the existing central
temple, completing the establishment of a major Tibetan Buddhist
center that will be one of the largest outside Asia.
</P>
<P>
   There are some problems to be solved as preparations begin. The
Asian-style couch-bed reserved for His Holiness has been judged too
small already for the strapping 14-year-old youth, whose flight
from Tibet included by most reports a grueling horseback dash
across some of the wildest reaches of Nepal. A new bed will have to
be found.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be crowds. Tibetan Buddhist Web sites are humming
as fascination grows around a vigorous young Buddhist leader who
may serve as a symbol for a younger generation of followers
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a hit record, really,'' said Thomas C.
Schmidt, a jazz musician who has mastered classical Tibetan
religious instruments and now, as a Buddhist, directs music and
recording activities for the monastery. ``He is going to spend a
lot of time here in future years.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bardor Tulku Rinpoche, who also teaches at the Woodstock
center's 40 affiliates around the United States, said that many
Americans seem to have ``good karmic connections'' developed
through past lives and deeds. This leads them inevitably to seek
Buddhist teaching in this life, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we strongly feel is in the West many of the Westerners
have a very strong karma in the past, and the time has come to
connect,'' he said. They seek a teacher to tap into that past and
release the spiritual store, he added, ``and whatever karma they
have, naturally it comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Westerners are attracted to the meditative practices and
individualistic style of learning through a personal teacher,
hallmarks of Tibetan Buddhism, known as Vajrayana, which set it
apart from two other major divisions of the religion practiced
elsewhere in Asia, Theravada and Mahayana, from which Vajrayana
grew centuries ago. For many, Buddhist teachers say, the reward of
Buddhism is inner peace and better relationships with other people
and all living things.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there is life, there is pain and suffering,''
Bardor Tulku Rinpoche said. ``Eventually people find in the
Buddha's teaching there is a lot of remedy for how to get rid of
pain and suffering, and how to apply happiness to their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inner peace is very important,'' he continued. ``If your mind
has all kind of negative thought, than there is not much peace to
you. There is not much peace you can give to others.''
</P>
<P>
   The center holds classes on weekends that attract dozens of
Buddhists and students of Buddhism. School groups also make trips
to Woodstock to hear classical Tibetan Buddhist musical instruments
and learn something of the religion.
</P>
<P>
   The layout follows a plan traditional to nearly all Tibetan
Buddhist monasteries and could be mistaken for a Himalayan retreat.
Financial support has flowed in from followers around the world.
The Karma Kagyu is thought to be the wealthiest of Tibetan Buddhist
branches or lineages, a factor that many Buddhists say contributes
to a challenge to the Karmapa's legitimacy from a Tibetan lama in
India, Trinley Thaye Dorge. He also has followers in the United
States and Europe but is not recognized by the Dalai Lama or most
major Buddhist figures.
</P>
<P>
   The dazzling central shrine at Woodstock, with its 11-foot tall
golden Buddha image and walls hung with religious paintings known
as thangkas (pronounced TONG-kas) mounted on fine brocades, was
finished first, about 15 years ago. Its brilliantly colored and
meticulously authentic decorative artwork was done by a Tibetan
master, Trinley Chojor, who is 67 and still in residence.
</P>
<P>
   The shrine, with its central heating and windows open to the
sun, seems a very bright and quiet place, far removed from the dark
dinginess of the Tibetan and Himalayan originals, with their sweet
fog of butter-lamp smoke and the shrieks of scrappy novices
racketing through monastic courtyards in flip-flop sandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tranquil and relaxing around here, which is nice,''
said Trinley Chojor, the seventh generation in a family of artists,
who has painted his way through monasteries across Tibet, Nepal and
India, and who spoke in Tibetan through an interpreter. ``It's
actually a great relief to be here in the tranquillity and freedom
that this country provides, compared with living in Tibet under
Chinese domination. It was anything but peaceful and tranquil in
Tibet.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael A. Doran, a former student of Eastern religions who is
now a Buddhist and secretary of the monastery, said that the young
Karmapa had recently written a millennium prayer for peace for his
followers that included ``a kind of strange line'' that has been
interpreted here as a message that he was coming.
</P>
<P>
   It said: ``May auspicious excellence, prosperity and goodness
flourish, especially throughout the land of America. May the
youthful lotus of teaching and practice bloom.''
</P>
<P>
   Doran said that when the Woodstock community discovered that the
Karmapa had fled Tibet virtually while they were reading his
prayer, followers began to interpret the ``youthful lotus'' that
could bloom here as the Karmapa himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's announcing that he's going to be here,'' Doran
said. ``As Bardor Tulku Rinpoche has said, `This is not an
accident: the karma is right in American for his presence.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
