<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDALS AND RISK SHOW THAT LUGE IS NO JOKE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ill.)  (rk) 
 By JIM GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ Despite their deepest wishes, Gordy Sheer
and Chris Thorpe know that the two-man luge is the Rodney
Dangerfield of winter Olympic sports. Luge, the odd Nordic sliding
sport, seems even more peculiar when done by a two-man team, both
on their backs, one atop the other, wearing lycra suits and
helmets.
</P>
<P>
   The sport is one of several that will be contested in the 2000
Winter Goodwill Games, the first cold-season version of the Ted
Turner made-for-television sports event, which began with an
opening ceremony Wednesday night and competition here Thursday. An
elite field of more than 250 athletes from 20 countries will
compete over five days in figure skating, snowboarding, ski
jumping, speedskating, bobsledding, and Alpine and Nordic skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Past Olympic and World Cup standouts include the figure skaters
Oksana Baiul, Nancy Kerrigan, Katarina Witt, Victor Petrenko, Brian
Orser and Brian Boitano; the freestyle skiers Ann Batelle and Eric
Bergoust; the snowboarder Tricia Byrnes; and the cross-country
skiers Justin Wadsworth and Marcus Nash.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation-only competition has even lured back into
competition the figure skater Dorothy Hamill, the 1976 gold
medalist. Household names aside, Turner Broadcasting is hoping to
cash in on some of the more obscure winter sports at the Goodwill
Games, the first world-class multisport event to be staged in Lake
Placid since the 1980 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   While luge is becoming less obscure, the lack of respect for
two-man luge occasionally finds its way into Jay Leno's nightly
monologue. Grin and bear it, the veteran sliders say. Of course,
winning helps, as the Americans Mark Grimmette and Brian Martin
could surely attest after winning Thursday''s doubles final. And it
does not hurt being the first U.S. lugers to win an Olympic medal,
say Sheer and Thorpe, who finished fourth Thursday but own the
silver medal from the 1998 Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to laugh,'' Sheer said of the negative asides about
his sport.
</P>
<P>
   As any eyewitness knows, luge is a sport for the skilled and
truly fearless. Lugers ride a small metal and fiberglass sled,
sliding feet-first down a banked ice track at speeds approaching 90
mph.
</P>
<P>
   The taller athlete in this case, Thorpe, who at 6 feet 2 inches
and 186 pounds has 4 inches and 30 pounds on Sheer, is called the
top driver, and he lies on top and a little forward of the bottom
driver for aerodynamic reasons. A race is comprised of two heats
and the winner is determined by the lowest cumulative time, which
is measured in the thousandths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   How significant are the leg, hip, and upper body movements
sliders use to steer their sled down the course while experiencing
five times the force of gravity in some curves? This significant:
Sheer and Thorpe missed a gold in Nagano by 22 thousandths of a
second on a course more than a mile long.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in Lake Placid, where Eric Heiden won five gold medals in
speedskating, and where the U.S. hockey team pulled off its miracle
on ice, Sheer and Thorpe were challenged by more than history.
Beside the American pair, they finished behind Steffen Skel and
Steffan Woeller of Germany, and Christian Oberstolz and Patrick
Gruber of Italy on the state-of-the-art course.
</P>
<P>
   The new $20 million bobsled and luge facility _ only one of
three in North America _ replaced the aging and, according to many
athletes, dangerous former Olympic ice track. It was constructed
just in time for the Goodwill Games: the new ice is only two weeks
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no home team here,'' Thorpe said. ``We're all
learning. The ice is a little bumpy, so it's anyone's race.
Frequent and heavy snowfall has also played havoc with track
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheer's and Thorpe's silver at Nagano was no fluke. They won the
overall World Cup title the year before Nagano, the first
non-European sledders to take that title.
</P>
<P>
   Lugers like Sheer and Thorpe are often described as adrenaline
junkies, but there is apparently a limit to sustaining that need.
With the Salt Lake Winter Olympics quickly approaching in February,
2002, they do not know if they will be able to muster the energy
and will to train for two more years. They have already been at it
for 12 years, by their count.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know now what it will take to go fast and win another medal
in Salt Lake,'' Sheer said. ``We just don't want to do it
halfheartedly.''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that after years of living out of duffel bags, both
men crave some normality in their lives. Sheer, 28, of
Croton-on-Hudson, N.Y., recently earned a bachelor's degree in
communications from Ohio State that took eight years to complete.
He will marry next month and relocate permanently to Lake Placid.
Thorpe, 29, originally from Waukegan, Ill., is still a few years
away from finishing his college degree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
