<SLUG> BC-AZPOLL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN OPENS UP BIG LEAD IN ARIZ. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JON KAMMAN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain and Al Gore hold commanding leads in their Arizona
presidential primary contests, and McCain would be the overwhelming
favorite if the general election were held now, the Arizona
Republic Poll indicated Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing George W. Bush by 4 points in late October,
Arizona's senior senator is sprinting to the finish line in his
home state with a 23-point lead, 52 percent to 29 percent, over the
Texas governor, according to the poll conducted for ``The
Republic'' over the previous five days.
</P>
<P>
   Former Ambassador Alan Keyes was the choice of 3 percent of
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week before the Republican primary, McCain is now
supported by about half the state's registered Republicans. Last
fall, he posted a 36 percent showing against Bush's 40 percent in
the newspaper-sponsored poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 808 registered voters, conducted by telephone
Saturday through Wednesday by Precision Research, had an overall
margin of error of plus or minus 3.4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   But given the margin of error of 4.7 points for the sampling of
423 Republicans alone, Bush would have a chance of winning
Tuesday's primary only if virtually all 16 percent of undecided
Republicans tilted to his side.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, meanwhile, leads former New Jersey Sen.
Bill Bradley 55 percent to 25 percent, or more than 2-1, in
Arizona's Democratic race, to be decided March 11. The margin of
error for the sampling of 266 Democrats was 6.3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Gore's support would evaporate, however, if he faced off
against McCain for the presidency right now, according to the poll
of all 808 registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   In that hypothetical race, McCain holds a lead of 45 percentage
points, 67-22, with 11 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley would fare even worse against McCain, a 71-15 percent
defeat, with 14 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush headed the Republican ticket, he, too, would beat either
of the Democrats right now, the poll said. He would have a 47-36
advantage over Gore and a 50-32 lead against Bradley, with other
voters undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen percent of poll respondents were registered as
independents or in other parties.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign did not respond to requests for comment on the
poll. &QL; 
SPINNING THE RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Brenda Burns, R-Glendale, a McCain supporter,
said she has always felt sure he would win Arizona and now sees a
win Tuesday as ``the launching pad for his victory on March 7,''
the so-called Super Tuesday primaries in 11 states.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of Arizona's primary will have the backing of all 30
of the state's delegates to the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spokesman in Arizona, Jay Heiler, said he was not
surprised to see McCain with a strong lead in his home state after
being ``cradled like a newborn babe in the arms of the media for
the past two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is cause for concern to the McCain campaign that
his support continues to hover around 50 percent in his own
state,'' Heiler said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the outcome of Saturday's primary in South Carolina,
where Bush and McCain are reported in a dead heat, will influence
voters in Arizona, and ``the race remains fluid here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull, a strong Bush supporter who has said that McCain
would have to win Arizona by 30 or more points for it to be
meaningful, ``still doesn't expect McCain to win by a landslide on
Tuesday,'' spokeswoman Francie Noyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half the poll's respondents described themselves as
having a middle-of-the-road political orientation, with 38 percent
conservative and 14 percent liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Another finding was that Arizonans are more inclined to vote
Republican in November than they were last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three percent of all respondents said they intend to vote
for the GOP presidential candidate, compared with 41 percent last
October. The Democratic candidate has the support of 29 percent
now, with the remainder undecided or divided among other parties. &QL; 
WHAT THEY THINK
</P>
<P>
   Poll respondents willing to elaborate on their views displayed a
healthy awareness of issues as diverse as gun control, education,
federal budget surpluses and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in our family is for McCain,'' said 30-year
Scottsdale resident Babette Wood, 49, ``mainly because of his
honesty and forthrightness.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said she agrees with McCain's stance on using budget
surpluses largely to pay down the national debt. And she favors
McCain for his military background.
</P>
<P>
   Values are at the core of Dianne Kazenski's support for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the economy is good, but the values of our country I
don't believe are good at all, and are slipping quickly,'' said
Kazenski, 51, a biblical counselor in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Citing McCain's war record, she added, ``I think from that we
see that he's a very strong man, a very persevering man and someone
who would stick by his guns and stand up for what he believes.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps typical of the many Democrats who might abandon their
party's nominee in the fall is Tom Bruner, 65, a Sun City resident
since retiring in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bruner said he likes Gore in the primary ``mainly for his
experience,'' but also because Bradley ``doesn't move me at all,
unfortunately.'' But in November, he probably would vote for Bush,
though not for McCain, Bruner said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Barbara Nelson of Tucson said her strong
abortion-rights stance, along with the feeling that ``things might
go a little bit better with somebody who isn't completely
establishment,'' leads her to pick Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like McCain, but I'm very definitely pro-choice. That's the
only thing I have against him,'' said Nelson, 70.
</P>
<P>
   An undecided voter, 35-year-old homemaker Mary Dunn of Chandler,
said that ``education and getting rid of abortion'' are the two
largest issues for her, and she considers both McCain and Bush
``strong candidates.'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Jon.Kamman &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-4816. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-00 2339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
