<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BADLY NEED MORE ARM-AMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can almost hear it now.
</P>
<P>
   It's opening night. Angels vs. the New York Yankees at Edison
Field, and the public address announcer gets his cue:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls, welcome to Edison Field!
Tonight, your Anaheim Angels take on the World Series champion New
York Yankees! And by the way, the Angels are currently taking
applications for those interested in becoming tonight's starting
pitcher! See the usher at Gate 3!''
</P>
<P>
   It might not be that bad, it only seems like it. Pitchers and
catchers reported to the Angels' spring training camp in Arizona
Thursday, but a familiar face was missing. The Angels lost starting
pitcher Chuck Finley to the Indians via free agency, leaving the
team severely lacking in their rotation.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the goal of new general manager Bill Stoneman to
trade an excess outfielder for a quality starter, but his efforts
so far have gone unrewarded. Jim Edmonds has drawn the most
attention, but is a free agent after the 2000 season and continues
to say through his agent that he is looking forward to exercising
that option.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a number of offers that Stoneman has deemed
unworthy of an All-Star-caliber outfielder. And thus, there have
been no deals. Not unless you count the free agent signing of Kent
Mercker as a noteworthy addition.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman's response to those offers is to insist the team will
be competitive if it must go to Ken Hill (arthritic right elbow),
Mercker, Jason Dickson (coming off shoulder surgery), Tom Candiotti
(age 42) and a group of talented but unproven pitchers including
Ramon Ortiz, Jarrod Washburn and Brian Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied to have them compete for spots, if that's what
it comes to,'' Stoneman said of Ortiz, Washburn and Cooper. ``If
you have talent and I know people have a hard time understanding
the concept but if you have talent I have no problem giving those
types of players an opportunity to compete for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, based on our reports, we have talented
players who lack experience. They've got to get over the hump, and
the only way to get them over the hump is to give them the
opportunity to get experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman is quick to point out that there is no trading
deadline. He can make a deal during spring training, which begins
with full-squad workouts on Tuesday, or even after the season
begins.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, rookie manager Mike Scioscia must run camp with the
players he has, whoever they are. Publicly Scioscia has remained
optimistic in the face of so many question marks. He says he
believes better health will be the biggest difference in this
year's team, noting the significant injuries to Mo Vaughn, Edmonds,
Tim Salmon and Gary DiSarcina in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of determining who his starting pitchers will be,
Scioscia will keep a close eye on the second base competition.
There are plenty of candidates for the job, but none stands out as
a clear-cut favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Spiezio, who played for the A's last season, was the only
one signed to a major league contract. Justin Baughman has been
deemed fit to play after having recovered from a badly broken leg,
but it is doubtful he'll have the same speed. Pat Kelly, Jason
Bates, Carlos Garcia and Benji Gil also are in the running.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher is another possible problem area. Benjie Molina will be
given every chance to win the job. He has potential but lacks
experience. Todd Greene's shoulder problems have prevented him from
catching for almost two years, but he may be healthy enough to
serve as a backup, along with Matt Walbeck.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Scioscia's focus will be on the bullpen and
bench, knowing that the other positions are basically set, barring
a trade. Troy Percival, Mark Petkovsek and Shigetoshi Hasegawa are
solid in the 'pen, but inconsistent Mike Holtz and journeyman Greg
Caderet are the lefties.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is no trade of an outfielder, one of Scioscia's
tasks during the spring will be to learn how to rotate one of the
four or Vaughn through the DH spot and keep everyone happy.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia will be a busy man for the next six weeks. Angel fans
hope Stoneman will be too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
